<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For FRIDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Friday, March 19.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ With the Kosovo talks at a dead end
and Yugoslavia's Slobodan Milosevic more recalcitrant than ever,
the Clinton administration is faced with pushing forward on a
policy _ the NATO bombing of a sovereign country _ that its
officials have repeatedly said they really don't want to carry out.
By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-GOETHE (Berlin) _ In 1970, scientists in East Germany
exhumed the corpse of Goethe in a secret operation to preserve his
skeleton for all time, according to a report published on Thursday.
Acting under cover of darkness in 1970, a team of pathologists and
archeologists removed the remains from their coffin in the Prince's
Crypt in the historic eastern city of Weimar. The skeleton was
stripped of remaining flesh fragments and treated with a preserving
agent before being replaced three weeks later. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MRSCLINTON-SENATE (New York) _ A month after announcing her
interest in a United States Senate seat from New York, Hillary
Rodham Clinton has discussed her potential candidacy with 60
influential Democrats, including the major party chairmen from the
suburban and upstate counties crucial to winning a race. Many
officials describe their conversations with the first lady as
lengthy and extraordinarily detailed about local issues. By
Elisabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARIJUANA-PATIENTS (Undated) _ A small number of patients
are now smoking marijuana with the approval of the FDA. We talk to
them and to people in similar situations who have been arrested for
doing the same thing, in a look at the controversy over medical
marijuana. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-SAFETY (Undated) _ When a semiautomatic's magazine is
removed, a round can remain in the chamber, ready to be fired, and
scores of people have died or been seriously hurt in recent years
as a result. Gun producers have long known of the danger, and some
responded by building into their guns an inexpensive mechanism
known as a magazine safety. But the fact that many gun makers have
chosen not to use simple devices like magazine safeties and gun
locks is now a focus of a growing wave of lawsuits in which cities
are accusing the firearms industry of making guns needlessly
dangerous. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANTIDEPRESSANTS (Undated) _ The new generation of antidepressant
drugs, of which Prozac was the first, is not any less _ or any more
_ efficacious in treating major depression as are older
antidepressants, a government report released Thursday concluded.
The report puts to rest lingering doubts about the relative
effectiveness of the new drugs, but it also notes that there is
insufficient research to conclude that the new drugs effectively
treat mild depression, a condition for which they are widely
prescribed. By Erica Goode.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIALLO-PROTESTS (New York) _ Protesters of the shooting here
by police of an unarmed West African immigrant have adopted an
event-a-day strategy. They have also put an emphasis on celebrity
rather than just numbers, as in the recent arrests and handcuffing
of Rep. Charles B. Rangel and former Mayor David Dinkins. By Dan
Barry.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MADCOW (Undated) _ A British medical journal reports what
may be more cases of new-variant CJD, also known as mad cow disease
in people. Meanwhile, a few more hunters in the Colorado/Wymoming
area have come down with something similar. By Sandra Blakeslee.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MARS-LIFE (Undated) _ The same researchers who caused a
sensation by claiming that a meteorite from Mars contained fossil
and chemical traces or microbial life are announcing that they have
found another meteorite with similar features. Experts who were
unconvinced by the announcement three years ago remain skeptical.
By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MOOD _ More and more, the president looks and sounds
like yesterday's man, spending large measures of his precious final
days in office revisiting the scenes of yesterday's glories and
trying to forget the pain of the humiliating impeachment battle he
survived. He is clinging to his last hours on stage, as the
spotlight shifts to the rising careers of First Lady Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   DUAL-PURPOSE-DRUGS (Undated) _ The possibility of lucrative
second and third uses is driving pharmaceutical companies to try to
find new, approved uses for existing drugs. While the trend is not
new, there has been a recent upsurge in such activity as drug
companies labor to maintain their strong earnings growth. By David
J. Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SONY-PLAYSTATION-II (San Jose, Calif.) _ Sony's Playstation II,
still more than a year away from commercial release, is creating a
stir among Silicon Valley's digerati because it delivers
supercomputer-class graphics at prices that will put it under
Christmas trees in 2000. It was shown Thursday for the first time
in this country to 1,000 software game developers. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-MARKETPLACE (Tokyo) _ Since DaimlerChrysler stopped
talking with Nissan last week about purchasing a stake in the
heavily indebted Japanese automaker, Renault of France has stepped
forward with an offer. But investors seem more interested in why
DaimlerChrysler walked away. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   OSCARS-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ The broadcast of the Academy Awards
will be sponsored by about 15 blue-chip advertisers paying an
average of $1 million for each 30-second spot, a historic high for
the show.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FRIEDMAN-COLUMN (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Thomas L. Friedman
assesses Thailand's economic recovery.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENTHAL-COLUMN (New Delhi) _ A.M. Rosenthal writes about the
politics of India.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN (Knoxville, Tenn.) _ Sports of The Times
column on the St. John's-Maryland game. By William C. Rhoden.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WEEKEND (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DOLOROSA-THEATER-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Via Dolorosa,'' at the
Booth Theater. Reviewed by Ben Brantley.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   ASSISI-EXHIBIT (New York) _ To draw attention to the the
post-earthquake situation in Assisi, as well as to showcase a
remarkable body of art temporarily out of pubic view elsewhere, the
Metropolitan Museum collaborated with various Italian cultural
agencies and the Vatican to organize ``The Treasury of St. Francis
of Assisi,'' an exhibition of some 70 objects from the church's
holdings, supplemented by 30 related works from other collections.
By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo has been sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   APPLES-TAMPA-BAY (Tampa, Fla.) _ Once upon a time, when there
were more orange groves than golf courses in Florida, Tampa Bay was
surrounded by a series of distinct communities: industrial,
ethnically mixed Tampa, white-bread St. Petersburg and its retirees
from the Midwest, laid-back Bradenton and Clearwater and, down the
coast a bit, artsy, cosmopolitan Sarasota, where the circus spent
the winter. Now, in fact if not law, it's one big metropolitan
area, laced together with bridges and freeways. On the road maps,
this entity of 2.5 million people doesn't exist. Only the old place
names are there. But everyone calls it Tampa Bay, and it is a
prototypical example of the Sun Belt's explosive growth. By R.W.
Apple Jr.
</P>
<P>
   NATURE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Forces of Nature'': Bronwen
Hughes, director; with Ben Affleck, Sandra Bullock, Maura Tierney,
Steve Zahn. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   KING-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The King And I'': Richard Rich,
director; animated with the voices of Miranda Richardson, Martin
Vidnovic. Reviewed by Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   RAVENOUS-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Ravenous'': Antonia Bird,
director; with Bobby Carlyle, Guy Pearce, David Arquette, Jeremy
Davies. Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   ROOK-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Rook'': Eran Palatnik,
director; with Martin Donovan. Reviewed by Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   SPARKLER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Sparkler'': Darren Stein,
writer and director; with Park Overall. Reviewed by Stephen Holden.
</P>
<P>
   TRUE-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``True Crime'': Clint Eastwood,
director and star; with James Woods, Diane Venora. Reviewed by
Janet Maslin.
</P>
