<HEADER>
A6180 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAIL-PROBE-AZR &LR;      03-19 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-PROBE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTY ATTORNEY QUITS JAILHOUSE DEATH INVESTIGATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 and RICHARD RUELAS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley on Thursday
removed himself from the investigation of the jailhouse death of
Scott Norberg, saying he faced a conflict of interest because of
reports that he was targeted by a Sheriff's Office surveillance
operation.
</P>
<P>
   Romley also claimed that misconduct by a former aide who now
works for the sheriff had compromised his work on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Sheriff Joe Arpaio, who long has called for his bitter political
rival to withdraw from the Norberg case, welcomed the news.
</P>
<P>
   ``My employees and I are thrilled that the county attorney will
not oversee this investigation,'' Arpaio said. ``Finally, we will
be treated fairly by a professional and impartial investigative
agency.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jack McIntyre, the former deputy county attorney
cited by Romley, denied Romley's claim that he had acted improperly
by advising the Sheriff's Office in the aftermath of Norberg's
death.
</P>
<P>
   In a hastily called news conference, Romley added fuel to
published reports that Arpaio had a squad of investigators conduct
surveillance on important figures in the Norberg probe, including
Romley.
</P>
<P>
   Romley noted that those reports in ``The Arizona Republic''
``have put me in the position of being the victim of potentially
criminal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that in recent days, ``A significant amount of
information has been provided to my office possibly corroborating
these allegations.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley refused to elaborate, turning aside reporters' questions
and saying he would turn the information over to the federal
investigators who have agreed to take over the Norberg
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' reported March 6 that federal investigators are
probing whether Arpaio ordered surveillance on foes in the Norberg
case, including Romley.
</P>
<P>
   The story was based on information from Steve Barnes, president
of the Deputy Law Enforcement Association, who said several
sheriff's deputies told him they were assigned to investigate
Arpaio enemies.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio initially called the report ``a product of a vile and
bizarre imagination.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of Thursday's developments, federal
investigators now will have complete responsibility for the
investigation into allegations that the Sheriff's Office and the
county medical examiner cov ered up jailers' brutality in Norberg's
1996 death.
</P>
<P>
   Norberg died in a restraint chair after battling with detention
officers.
</P>
<P>
   One officer, Kimberly Walsh, said under oath that two officers
ignored her warnings that Norberg could not breathe and continued
to force his chin into his chest until he turned blue, kicked
spasmodically and died.
</P>
<P>
   The medical examiner determined that the death was the
accidental result of ``positional asphyxia.'' An internal
investigation by the Sheriff's Office exonerated the officers.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio has consistently defended his detention officers, even in
the face of January's $8.25 million settlement of the Norberg
family's federal lawsuit against the county, Arpaio and the
detention officers.
</P>
<P>
   Romley said many questions about Norberg's death remain
unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Common sense would tell you that when the county pays out
$8.25 million dollars in a wrongful-death suit, there must have
been some problems surrounding the death of Scott Norberg,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the $8.25 million was paid by the insurer for the
county. Taxpayers, however, picked up a $1 million lawyers' tab in
the case.
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, Romley had resisted Arpaio's demands that he
withdraw from the investigation. Arpaio claimed that because the
county attorney has represented the Sheriff's Office in more than
150 lawsuits, personnel matters and business dealings, Romley
should declare a conflict of interest in the Norberg case.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio on Thursday bitterly complained that Romley had ``held my
detention officers hostage for three years'' after Norberg's death.
</P>
<P>
   Romley said a major factor in his decision to withdraw was
information he received last week about the conduct of MacIntyre,
the former deputy county attorney, in the aftermath of Norberg's
death in June 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Romley said that shortly after Norberg died, he directed that
his office would not represent Arpaio in the civil suit they were
expecting in the case. But MacIntyre disobeyed that order and
``continued to communicate with representatives of the Sheriff's
Office about the Norberg case.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. MacIntyre's conduct has created an appearance of conflict
of interest which has the potential of undermining public
confidence in the investigation,'' Romley said.
</P>
<P>
   At a rebuttal news conference late Thursday, McIntyre said he
did give broad legal advice to deputies, who came to him terrified
about the prospect of criminal charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the extent they would ask how the trial would progress,
what was possible, what was feasible, they had no other place to
turn,'' McIntyre said. ``Rick Romley was fully aware of that.''
</P>
<P>
   McIntyre said senior staffers knew that he was still being
peppered with questions from deputies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was recognized . . . that members of the county Sheriff's
Office were being left out to dry and needed some legal advice in
this arena,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Norberg death must be investigated,'' said Romley, whose
personal feud with Arpaio has been sharpened by the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``No investigation can be effective, however, if it is conducted
under a cloud of doubt and suspicion. Personalities and animosities
must not be permitted to interfere with the only appropriate
objective _ a fair and thorough investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Romley's withdrawal from the investigation makes it unlikely
that it will be wrapped up by the end-of-May deadline he
established two months ago. But Romley complained Arpaio had
continuously sought to frustrate his his investigators with
``obstacles and roadblocks.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the U.S. Attorney's Office said Thursday that
they would not respond to questions about the resources that would
be dedicated to the investigation and a possible timetable for its
completion.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, U.S. Attorney Jose de Jesus Rivera issued a prepared
statement that had more sentiment than substance:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the long-standing tradition of cooperative law enforcement
in this district, and in order to serve the best interests of the
public, the U.S. Attorney's Office has agreed to assume full
responsibility for the civil rights investigation into the death of
Scott Norberg.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
