<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 00:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6183 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-GONZAGA-FLORIDA-N     03-19 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GONZAGA-FLORIDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA NIPS FLORIDA, 73-72 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ To make the final eight of the National Collegiate
Athletic Association tournament, a team's origin matters little.
And it certainly isn't in the name.
</P>
<P>
   What is required is size in the low post and quickness on the
perimeter. A hot hand helps, and multiple defenses will have an
impact. Riding the wave of emotion is crucial, and seizing the
moment matters. And then there is luck. A nice, game-ending dose
will do.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga has got it.
</P>
<P>
   The team zigged and zagged its way into the final eight on
Thursday night at America West Arena, combining an array of
ingredients into a 73-72 victory over Florida. Gonzaga (28-6) will
play Saturday against the Connecticut-Iowa winner to determine the
West Regional champion and entrant into the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   A spectacular finish won it for Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs took a 69-69 game with 1 minute 12 seconds
remaining and rode the wave. Guard Matt Santangelo had made 1 of 2
free throws to tie the score.
</P>
<P>
   Then Greg Stolt of Florida made a searing 3-pointer with 45.7
seconds left to give Florida a 72-69 lead. With 42.5 seconds left,
Gonzaga called a timeout. The Bulldogs tried to run a play, were
trapped, and called another timeout. There were 27.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga center Jeremy Eaton made a layup out of that timeout,
cutting Florida's lead to 72-71. As Florida inbounded the ball to
center Ben Wright, there was luck for Gonzaga, a nice, game-ending
dose. Wright traveled, and the ball went back to Gonzaga with 15.4
seconds left. Gonzaga guard Quentin Hall drove toward the basket
and missed a shot from inside the lane. The sophomore forward Casey
Calvary leapt into the air, stretching and tapping and scoring a
putback basket. Gonzaga, 73-72.
</P>
<P>
   In the final, frantic four seconds, Florida tried a desperation
shot, but no luck there. This game was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga has got it.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unbelievable,'' Calvary said. ``We've dreamed about
this since we were little, and now that we're there, we have to
take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Calvary finished with 12 points. Forward Richie Frahm scored 17,
14 in a second-half shooting spree. Stolt scored 16 for Florida and
Wright 15 as the Gators' season ended with a 22-9 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just hurts inside that I let the team down,'' Wright said,
referring to his travel. ``It's just real sad. I thought the ref
gave me a timeout, but it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga shot 45.4 percent in the game and Florida shot 43.3
percent. Gonzaga scored 12 3-pointers, doubling Florida's total.
The second half ended in a 38-38 tie. Gonzaga squeaked by in points
in the first half and that helped provide the winning margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has great character and they are great kids,'' Coach
Dan Monson of Gonzaga said. ``There are a lot of teams at home with
better basketball ability, but we get through that with chemistry
and character.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga opened hot and Florida began cold.
</P>
<P>
   But by the end of the half, the roles were reversed. Little
wonder that Gonzaga led by only 35-34 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   From the opening tip, it was apparent that Gonzaga possessed the
bigger front line. Gonzaga built leads of 11-8, 21-13 and 26-13.
Gonzaga missed a few layups and short jumpers along the way that
could have pushed its lead further. The team compensated, however,
by exhibiting crisp, sure passing (10 assists) and by cutting,
slicing and passing its way for enough shots that found their way
into the basket.
</P>
<P>
   It was a 26-13 game with 6:46 left in the half. Gonzaga made it
that score when center Jeremy Eaton grabbed a blocked shot and
scored on a put-back. A second center, Axel Dench (7 points), and
Santangelo (6 points) led Gonzaga in scoring in the first half.
Santagelo, along with guard Quentin Hall, despite his five
turnovers, kept pushing the ball up the floor for the Bulldogs and
running the offense, assuring their team open looks.
</P>
<P>
   Florida appeared in trouble, down by 13 and reeling in floor
shooting. The team had scored its 13th point with 9:07 remaining in
the half and did not score again until 5:13 remained on a Eddie
Shannon layup. From that point, Florida changed the game in two
ways: it opted for a zone defense and forced Gonzaga to miss a
flurry of jumpers, and then the Gators began, finally, to sink a
few of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Stolt scorched a 16-footer. A steal, a layup, more misses from
Gonzaga against the zone and more Florida scores. A string of
baskets for Florida. More misses for Gonzaga. The roles were
reversing.
</P>
<P>
   There was 3:52 left in the half when center Ben Wright broke
free on a fast break, pulled up inside the free-throw line and
tossed in a jump shot. That quickly, Florida was within 26-22.
There was 3:11 left when Wright made two free throws. That tied it
at 27-27. Florida had climbed back, with Wright leading all scorers
in the half with 9 points. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
