<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 00:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6185 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-WEST-LADN     03-19 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-WEST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA CONTINUES MAGICAL RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ They have no McDonald's All-Americans. They have one
player taller than 6-foot-8. They come from a small conference,
play in a small arena and, before last week, had never won an NCAA
Tournament game.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no more doubts about the Gonzaga Bulldogs, not
anymore, because Thursday night they moved one step from the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Casey Calvary's last-second tip-in gave the Bulldogs a
73-72 Sweet 16 victory over Florida in front of 17,975 at America
West Arena, the largest crowd ever to watch a college basketball
game in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who play Connecticut on Saturday for the West
Regional title, could join No. 11 Louisiana State (1986) as the
only double-digit seed to make the Final Four. Win or lose,
however, they've accomplished their year-long mission to prove the
NCAA selection committee wrong for rejecting their at-large bid
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been calling us a Cinderella team,'' Calvary said.
``And to the media and the rest of the nation, it looks that way.
But in our eyes, it doesn't mean a thing. We just won another game.
That's the way we look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   After easily dispatching No. 7 Minnesota, stunning No. 2
Stanford and rallying to beat No. 6 Florida, the Bulldogs have left
no doubt about their qualifications as an Elite Eight entry. They
are skilled, unselfish, quietly confident and immaculately coached
by Dan Monson, whose father, Don, guided Idaho to the West Regional
semifinals 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   No surviving team, including Duke, runs its offense with more
patience and precision than the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of teams at home with better basketball
ability,'' Monson said. ``We got through with great chemistry and
character. All of these kids have two parents in their homes.
They're all stable. They're good kids with great character.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida took a 72-69 lead with 46 seconds left on Greg Stolt's
3-pointer from the right wing. The Bulldogs countered with Jeremy
Eaton's layup with 15 seconds left, setting up the decisive
sequence.
</P>
<P>
   It began when Gonzaga guard Quentin Hall's harassing defense
forced Florida center Brent Wright into a backcourt traveling
violation. After a timeout, Hall missed a 14-foot leaner from the
right side. Calvary charged from the foul line, jumped over Wright
and converted a two-handed tip with 4.4 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was nervous to get that shot off, but the ball just came my
way,'' Calvary said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida guard Eddie Shannon dribbled downcourt and launched a
23-footer as the buzzer sounded. It hit the rim and bounced away as
the Bulldogs swarmed Calvary near midcourt.
</P>
<P>
   A tournament with myriad upsets but few close finishes finally
had a game to hang its buzzer on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what March Madness is all about,'' Monson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
