<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6189 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASKETBALL-FEVER-2TAK     03-19 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASKETBALL-FEVER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL SIGNS POINT TO SOUTHWEST MISSOURI-DUKE MATCH-UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BLAIR KERKHOFF  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mo. _ There's this guy, Marty Prather. Everybody in
town knows him. He's the pizza guy because he co-owns the Domino's
franchises in town. And he's Southwest Missouri State University's
biggest fan because he doesn't miss an event.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly, he's the sign guy.
</P>
<P>
   Every game at the Hammons Student Center, Prather is there with
his signs. He has a quip for every player and usually a jab at the
opponent. One of his favorite moments this season was when coach
Billy Tubbs brought Texas Christian to town just before Christmas.
Prather broke out a ``Tele-Tubby'' sign, with a Tubbs photograph
over Tinky Winky's face. The TCU players broke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was before all the Falwell stuff,'' Prather said of
the denouncement of the children's TV show character in a
publication of the Rev. Jerry Falwell. ``That might have made
SportsCenter.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a strange week in Springfield. A foot of snow dropped
on Sunday and by Tuesday it was 70 degrees. The women's basketball
team is out of the tournament and the men live on.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears are playing in the NCAA tournament regional
semifinals, better known as the Sweet 16, against Duke today. A
Southwest Missouri State victory against the Blue Devils is almost
out of the question. Duke is the tournament's prohibitive favorite.
</P>
<P>
   But getting this far was just as improbable for the Bears,
according to the men on the selection committee. As a No. 12 seed,
Southwest Missouri was one of the final teams invited, and from
their position on the bracket the Bears were given little chance to
defeat first-round opponent Wisconsin, the fifth seed.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears won 43-32 in one of the great defensive performances
in tournament history. Next up was fourth-seeded Tennessee.
Southwest Missouri won in a romp, 81-51.
</P>
<P>
   Next up, Duke.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can say that the winner of this game has to be
favored to win it all,'' said Prather, who is planning a sign to
that effect. XXX
</P>
<P>
   Jenny Russo and her husband, Nick, own Ebbets Field, a
restaurant not far from campus. Russo, a Southwest Missouri State
grad who attended Park Hill High School in Kansas City, never much
liked sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really, not until this week,'' Russo said. ``Now I am.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bears have that kind of appeal. Their coach is Steve Alford,
34, one of the youngest coaches in the game. He doesn't look much
older than he did as an Indiana University senior in 1987, when he
led the Hoosiers to the national championship. And, by the way,
those tournament highlights are playing on the television sets at
Ebbets Field. Not a tape. It just worked out that way. Amazing how
little Alford has changed in 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   In his fourth season, Alford has guided the Bears to their most
successful season as a Division I program. Southwest Missouri
didn't win the Missouri Valley Conference or the league tournament.
But success these days is measured in the NCAA tournament, and the
Sweet 16 is a first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to do something no other Bears team had done,''
Alford said.
</P>
<P>
   They did. It made Jenny Russo a basketball fan. XXX
</P>
<P>
   Prather is on his cell phone. Turns out, he saw the perfect
cardboard cutout at a place in Charlotte, N.C., where Southwest
Missouri State played last weekend. It's the Statue of Liberty
spinning a basketball instead of holding the torch. Prather is
having it shipped from Charlotte to Newark, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gonna paint an SMS on the basketball,'' Prather said.
</P>
<P>
   Other planned signs for the Meadowlands, site of the game with
Duke: scores of the some of the great NCAA tournament upsets like
North Carolina State over Houston and Villanova over Georgetown.
He'll take the ``Bring on Duke'' sign, but he probably won't get
much local publicity for that one. Prather and the sign made the
front sports page of Monday's New York Times. In color. XXX
</P>
<P>
   Lunchgoers Chuck Clark and Ken Kabonic are federal probation
officers and Jeff Maloney is a psychology professor at Southwest
Missouri. They're big fans and were about as sure as anybody else
in Springfield that the Bears would get this far in the tournament.
Which is to say, not sure at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all gravy,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Southwest Missouri State followers, Maloney wasn't
even counting on an invitation, not after the Bears got knocked out
in the semifinals of the Missouri Valley Conference tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I didn't think they had lived up to
expectations,'' Maloney said.
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Until the Bears received the tournament invitation
and pulled off the upsets in Charlotte, the season was falling
short of Alford's hopes. The Bears had lost many close games and a
couple of baskets had cost them the conference title.
</P>
<P>
   Alford sensed the pressure his team was feeling. So he told
players that after they beat Wisconsin and their next opponent,
they would spend the first day preparing for Duke by leaving the
basketballs on the rack.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Bears spent their first day of Duke week playing
Wiffle ball. XXX
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri students are gone for spring break, so
there's no extra help in the sports information office. Manager
Mark Stillwell has a cold. Nobody's slept for two days.
</P>
<P>
   And nearly 50 reporters and radio shows from around the country
have to talk to Alford.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the reporters are assembled on a conference call.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hectic, but it's a great hectic,'' Alford said as he
breaks from a coaches meeting into his office.
</P>
<P>
   He grabs a homemade chocolate chip cookie and an iced tea and
settles in for nearly 45 minutes worth of chatting about Southwest
Missouri State, Duke, Bob Knight, Mike Krzyzewski, Missouri Valley
pride and his future, which is looking pretty bright these days.
There may be a bigger job in Alford's immediate future. MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
