<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-AUBURN-OHIOST19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buckeyes eliminate Auburn
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The sweetest ride in Auburn basketball
history is finally over. And Ohio State's turnaround, one of the
most remarkable in NCAA history, is one win away from the Final
Four.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing by a point with less than three minutes left, Ohio
State scored 10 straight to upset the top-seeded Tigers 72-64
Thursday night in the NCAA South Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   With point guard Scoonie Penn overcoming foul trouble to score
19 of his 26 points in the second half, and Michael Redd adding 15,
the Buckeyes (26-8) advanced to Saturday night's regional final
against St. John's.
</P>
<P>
   In becoming the first top-seeded team in the tournament to fall,
Auburn (29-4) got 15 points from forward Chris Porter. But when he
fouled out with 1:57 left and Auburn down 62-61, Ohio State scored
eight more unanswered points.
</P>
<P>
   When the night began, the top four seeds in this region were
still alive and Cliff Ellis had likened the South Regional to a
Final Four. In the real thing, the Auburn coach knows, two
ingredients essential for success are good guard play and even
better rebounding. At least Ellis got one of those in the first
half.
</P>
<P>
   En route to becoming the SEC Player of the Year, Porter had
terrorized the conference on the boards, particularly the offensive
glass. But he'd had just two offensive rebounds in the SEC
semifinal loss to Kentucky, none in an NCAA opening-round rout of
Winthrop. Although Porter grabbed 10 rebounds last Saturday in an
81-74 win over Oklahoma State, he had just nine points.
</P>
<P>
   Ellis knew he needed more production from Porter if Auburn was
to survive this mini-Final Four and reach the real one.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half, Porter pounded the glass for eight boards
(three offensive) and six points. Bryant Smith added six points,
too. But while Ohio State was getting outrebounded 26-17, the
Buckeyes were clearly winning the battle of the backcourts. Any
team might if it had Penn and Redd.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed Redd stuck a 3-pointer to open the game, then
scored seven of Ohio State's first nine points as the Buckeyes took
an early 9-5 lead. But Auburn got nicely balanced scoring,
including seven points off the bench by Daymeon Fishback, to grab a
24-21 lead. But then Ohio State, and Penn, closed with a rush.
</P>
<P>
   After sitting out last season upon transferring from Boston
College when coach Jim O'Brien left BC for Ohio State, Penn led a
remarkable Buckeye turnaround and became the Big Ten Player of the
Year. How, and why, were evident Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State closed with a 10-3 rush to take a 31-26 halftime
lead. Ken Johnson started it with a tip-in. After Brian Brown
drilled a 3-pointer, Penn stuck a jumper from the right side. Then
he beat the buzzer with a 3-ball from the left of the key to make
it 31-26.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since landing on his butt late in the regular season,
Penn's shooting had suffered. He was just 7-for-27 in Ohio State's
first two NCAA games. But Thursday he was on, especially after
Redd's follow put the Buckeyes up 35-32. Penn stuck a jumper from
the top of the key, then a pull-up 3-pointer off a pick for a 40-35
advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
