A6191 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASKETBALL-FEVER-2NDT     03-19 0440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASKETBALL-FEVER-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mo. _ Alford's immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Rowe, the school's athletic director since 1982, said
Southwest Missouri State had never ridden a publicity wave like
this. Not when the women's team went to the 1992 Final Four or the
men won their first NCAA tournament game in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember as a youngster when the Bears won back-to-back NAIA
titles (in Kansas City) and that was a monumental occasion,'' Rowe
said. ``We went to the Division II championship game four times.
Then we make the move to Division I (in 1982), and we play in the
NIT in 1986. All those were very special teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is another step up, a first time in the Sweet 16. It's a
luster we hadn't experienced. We're getting calls from all over the
country from people who want to be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   As an ESPN reporter sticks her head in the sports information
department looking for, what else, more information, an advanced
copy of this week's Sports Illustrated story on the tournament
rolls off the fax. There's a big picture of Bears forward Ken
Stringer blocking a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Staffers gather around, nod their approval, and somebody wonders
aloud if the Bears will make the cover after they win twice this
weekend. XXX
</P>
<P>
   Prather's signs date back to the 1985 World Series. An avid
Cardinals fan, he loaded up with ``Fat Lady singing'' signs for
game five. When the Royals won, he drove to Kansas City and will
never forget his meeting with one particular fan during the seventh
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fat lady came up to me and said, `I'm here to sing,' &UR; ''
Prather said.
</P>
<P>
   The series also inspired a favorite that he pulls out when an
official's call goes against the Bears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denkinger Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the signs have kept coming. Hockey and baseball
games in St. Louis _ he's also chairman of a Mark McGwire fan club
that raised funds for abused children _ and basketball games in
Springfield.
</P>
<P>
   Prather took time out from his signs to fill out his bracket and
had the Bears winning two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``In any other regional, if they were going against Auburn or
Michigan State, I'd have them winning at least one more,'' Prather
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Prather's packing for two games worth of signs. Then there's
that Statue of Liberty waiting for him. NCAA rules prohibit fans
from bringing signs into arenas, but the security folks at
Charlotte allowed it. Prather's taking no chances at the
Meadowlands. He won't be walking in with them, but he has a plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll see them,'' he said. ``I promise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
