<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6192 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-GOODYKOONTZ-     03-19 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-GOODYKOONTZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY CALL IT MARCH MADNESS FOR GOOD REASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - America West Arena has seen its share of ``big''
games. &QL; 
Suns playoff games (including the '93 NBA Finals), Coyotes playoff
games _ the joint hasn't exactly lacked for drama.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday night was different.
</P>
<P>
   This was the NCAA West Regional. Gonzaga's nail-biting 73-72
tip-in win over Florida. Connecticut's hard-fought 78-68 victory
over Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   This was madness, of the March variety.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, television has worked that phrase to death, but there is a
reason: because it fits. Sitting in an arena chopped up into
quarters _ one for each school _ you could feel it. Pep bands
blared school fight songs. Entire sections roared back and forth at
each other, seeming to live and die on every shot.
</P>
<P>
   You want proof? Look no further than Florida's Eddie Shannon,
sprawled on the floor after missing a shot that would have won the
first game. He was despondent.
</P>
<P>
   So were the Gator fans. Amy Howard, who attended Florida,
claimed not to be too down after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Her moist eyes said otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset for them,'' she said of the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``The college fever is at a higher pitch,'' said Eric Afrons, a
Florida native (and alumnus) who recently moved to Phoenix.
``There's just more emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly. College basketball breathes a passion that doesn't
exist in the professional game. Pro basketball isn't on a
respirator (though the lockout knocked the wind out of it), but to
real fans, the NCAA Tournament is a blast of fresh air.
</P>
<P>
   And the Gonzaga fans were like an air-conditioner on a hot
August day. They stood and screamed the entire first game. They
cheered their team's introduction and faithfully ignored Florida's.
When the Gators' pep band came out onto the court, they booed
lustily. And when Casey Calvary tipped in the game-winner, they
exploded.
</P>
<P>
   They were, in a word, nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Or, in another word, perfect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just drove 23 hours to come to this game,'' said Mike
Wenrick, a Gonzaga junior. ``I'm stoked!''
</P>
<P>
   Wenrick and the others in Section 115 were part of the portable
Kennel Club (Gonzaga's nickname is the Bulldogs).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're infamous,'' Wenrick said with considerable pride. He's
been to professional basketball games in Seattle, and felt the
difference in the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't care if you make a fool of yourself'' at a
tournament game, he said. ``Everyone else is.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, his fellow Kennel Clubbers painted their faces,
their foreheads and their hair red and blue, the school's colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can paint a big Z on your chest and rip off your shirt in
the middle of the game and nobody cares,'' Wenrick continued. ``At
a pro game, they might look at you funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, his chest was Z-less.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't have the paint,'' he sighed, then went looking for some.
</P>
<P>
   Might as well pull out all the stops. Phil Gilberto, a
Connecticut fan, knew the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you think we're here?'' he asked. ``You think we'd
travel 3,000 miles for nothing? I wouldn't travel 120 miles to
watch the Mets play.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro sports offer plenty of excitement, Gilberto's view of the
Mets notwithstanding. But the NCAA Tournament offers no seven-game
series, no chances to learn a team's weakness over a few games and
exploit it a day later.
</P>
<P>
   You lose and you're gone.
</P>
<P>
   John Bruntz, an Iowa law school graduate who lives in West Des
Moines, noted another difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not the professional aspect of getting paid to play,''
he said, then chuckled. At least there's not ``supposed'' to be,
his laugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Something else you probably won't see in the pros: Before the
Gonzaga-Florida game, Stuart Evey and his wife, Mary, yelled down
to Richie Frahm, a Bulldogs player who was warming up. Frahm sought
out the source of the voices, spotted the Eveys, grinned and waved.
</P>
<P>
   Evey, the former chairman of ESPN, didn't go to Gonzaga. But he
retired to Spokane, Wash., and he and his wife take a few players
under their wing every season, he said. You don't see many Phoenix
families adopting homesick Suns players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lose with 'em, and we win with 'em,'' Evey said. ``It's
unconditional.''
</P>
<P>
   Spread that around the arena in four different directions, and
you'll have the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a part of the team,'' Wenrick, the Kennel Club
resident, said. ``We ``are'' Gonzaga. We have something invested in
the school.''
</P>
<P>
   For the members of the Kennel Club, that investment paid off big
Thursday night. &QL; 
Bill Goodykoontz can be reached at 602-444-8828, or at
bill.goodykoontz(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0049EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
