<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-IOWA19-COX     03-19 0509
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-IOWA19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Connecticut dismisses Iowa
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Connecticut moved one step closer to its first-ever
Final Four berth Thursday by defeating Iowa 78-68 in the West
Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Huskies (31-2) will face surprising Gonzaga
Saturday for a trip to St. Petersburg and the Final Four. The loss
ended the Iowa coaching career of Tom Davis, who was forced to
resign early this season despite being the winningest coach in
school history.
</P>
<P>
   Khalid El-Amin had 21 points and five assists for Connecticut,
which advanced to the regional finals for the second time in the
last five years. In its previous appearance, also in the West
Regional, the Huskies lost to UCLA 102-96 in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having few athletes the caliber of those in the
Connecticut lineup, Iowa kept it close in the second half, taking
one lead and creating five ties in the first 10 minutes. Every time
UConn appeared to gain some breathing room, one of the Hawkeyes'
cadre of raw-boned inside players would bang in close for a hoop.
Iowa also played much better defense at the 3-point arc in the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup boiled down to UConn's blinding speed and Iowa's
undeniable spunk.
</P>
<P>
   That the Hawkeyes could even hang with UConn in the first half,
which ended with the Huskies leading 40-35, was a testament to
Iowa's muscle, moxie and manipulation. In the first seven minutes
alone, Davis used five different defenses: a box-and-one against
Connecticut star Richard Hamilton, a straight man-to-man, some 2-3
zone, a 1-3-1 zone and a halfcourt trap.
</P>
<P>
   While the Hawkeyes were able to control Hamilton most of the
half, they had no such success against UConn guard El-Amin, who
controlled the tempo the entire 20 minutes. The point guard scored
11 points and dished out five assists.
</P>
<P>
   When he wanted to get to the paint, El-Amin did so almost at
will. In the closing two minutes of the half, he twice exploded
past defenders to dump off to Hamilton for easy layups. Earlier in
the half, he took the ball nearly the length of the floor,
dribbling past three players to draw a foul off a drive.
</P>
<P>
   Looking to run at every opportunity, Connecticut hit 13 of its
first 17 shots, including all four 3-point attempts, and finished
the half with a 64.0 percentage. Iowa hit just 39.3 percent but
outmuscled Connecticut for second chances. That UConn managed 20
points in the paint was a result of penetration as Iowa stayed
tough inside and took advantage of some lapses by the Huskies to
stay close.
</P>
<P>
   If the Huskies have a weakness, it's that they simply don't live
up to their name on the boards, with little inside huskiness. Iowa
had a 15-13 rebounding edge at the half.
</P>
<P>
   The half ended with some ugliness, as Iowa center Jacob Jaacks
tossed a wicked elbow at UConn backup forward Souleymane Wane as
time expired. The two had to be pulled apart as the teams left the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
