<HEADLINE>
BOEING BETS FAITH AND MONEY ON JETLINER EXECUTIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAURENCE ZUCKERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many aerospace-industry analysts believe that the Boeing Co. is
banking its future on Alan R. Mulally, the newly appointed head of
its troubled commercial airplane division. And indeed it appears
that Boeing is willing to back up its faith with dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's latest proxy filing discloses that Mulally, who is 53,
received restricted stock and stock options last year worth between
$11.1 million and $19.6 million, depending on the future
performance of company stock. His salary and bonus for 1998 totaled
$778,601.
</P>
<P>
   The package was a significant jump from Mulally's 1997
compensation of $629,000 and makes him the third-highest-paid
executive at the company after Philip M. Condit, chairman and chief
executive, and Harry C. Stonecipher, the president.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally turned down an offer to become heir apparent at Raytheon
last year. A Boeing spokesman said the stock and options were given
to him as an incentive to stay at the company. ``Based on what Alan
was being offered by another company,'' he said, ``the board saw
this as an appropriate retention package and as an investment in
Boeing's future.''
</P>
<P>
   Mulally, who was not available for comment on Thursday, was
running Boeing's space and military businesses in September when he
was tapped to lead the commercial airplane division after Ronald B.
Woodard, the former president, was dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Production foul-ups and other delays at the passenger-jet unit
forced Boeing in 1997 to post its first annual loss in 50 years.
Last year, the unit sold a record 559 planes worth $36 billion, but
made a $63 million profit.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming leader of the division, Mulally, who made his
reputation at Boeing working with Condit to develop the 777
wide-body passenger jet, has begun straightening out some of the
production difficulties and meeting delivery deadlines. But he
still must put a plan in place that will lead the unit to sustained
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally's incentive package includes $5.2 million worth of
restricted stock that becomes available to him over 10 years and
200,000 stock options with an exercise price of $45.0625 a share
that become vested over three years. Boeing stock, which has
underperformed the market in recent years, closed on Thursday at
$35.125, down 62.5 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the proxy filing showed that two Boeing directors _
Donald E. Petersen, the retired chairman of the Ford Motor Company,
and George H. Weyerhaeuser, the forest-products industrialist _
will leave the board after reaching the mandatory retirement age of
72.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis E. Platt, chairman and chief executive of the
Hewlett-Packard Co., was nominated to fill one of the vacancies.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy filing also indicated, as previously reported, that
Condit and Stonecipher did not receive bonuses last year and that
Woodard received $1.35 million from Boeing as part of a separation
package.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
