<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO ERR IS HUMAN, TO SHOOT AIRBALLS IS STRICTLY NBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This week's sign that the apocalypse is NOT upon us:
</P>
<P>
   A partial exam of NBA attendance by Street &AMP; Smith's Sports
Business Journal shows that the no-show count at arenas is
estimated around 10 to 15 percent, even though the NBA refused to
provide any documentary help.
</P>
<P>
   The no-shows indicate at least some discerning fans understand
how inferior baggy-pants theater is this season. (The argument can
be made that these fans were silly to buy season tickets in the
first place, but they probably needed to hold their spots for next
season, should pro ball resume.)
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is smirking quietly to itself that overall attendance
(tickets sold) is down only slightly in the aftermath of the
lockout, indicating it guessed right in calculating the gullibility
of the American sports public.
</P>
<P>
   The increased number of no-shows means the clubs will be out
some money from concessions and parking, but the hit is minor
compared to how badly baseball wounded itself in its 1994 labor
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is remarkable how many people are showing up to watch
millionaire athletes airball free throws, creating statistical lows
unseen since Flintstone basketball was played with real rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, many fans made the same assumption as Sonics coach
Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a presumption that most of (the locked-out players)
were doing something,'' he said, barely smiling. ``The season's
more odd than I thought it would be. I thought after the lockout
was over it would be, `Oh, well, get a couple weeks of camp and
go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is apparent that too many players posted up at Royal
Fork's all-you-can-eat line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's hard enough to lose 10 pounds,'' Westphal said.
``If you're 40 pounds overweight, two months isn't much time to
lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's plain that the Ben &AMP; Jerry's poster children among the
Sonics are Vin Baker and Billy Owens, who packed enough extra
pounds between them to nearly have made the backup point guard for
which the Sonics have yearned.
</P>
<P>
   The recently improved play of Baker, whom the I-5 truck stations
gauged about 280 pounds at the start of the season, has a lot to do
with his slowly improving fitness. Only lately has Baker's
trademark quickness reappeared in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-9 Owens started out around 250, at least 15 over his best
weight, and since has been sidelined with a broken finger and a
sore knee, the latter a possible consequence of cheeseburger
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy is so much better than he's shown,'' Westphal said.
``But he was in almost the same boat as Vin. And he's been in and
out of good health.''
</P>
<P>
   The chubsters' lack of professionalism has been the primary
cause of the Sonics' worst start since the K.C. Jones era. But
since the problem is league-wide, the Sonics have not fallen off
the playoff map.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is physical sloppiness the only explanation for the
grimness. Hersey Hawkins (41.6 percent from the field), who might
be in the best shape of his career, has joined the rest of his
teammates in flirting with career lows in shotmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the benefit of summer league and exhibition season,
and with a new coach, new system and several new players, working
together has been a problem,'' said Sonics president Wally Walker.
``Normally, a new coach gets a chance in the offseason to get a
dialogue going with veteran players, and there's also a chance to
talk to free agents and see whether they will fit. We couldn't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Westphal put it, ``We have no ability to experiment without
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Two cases in point: The moves of longtime starters Hawkins and
Detlef Schrempf to the bench. Westphal wanted to talk to both about
the shift during the summer, but the lockout rules prohibited any
contact between management and union members. The moves were done
abruptly, with much resentment and little preparation, during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkins move was a bust, and reversed. Schrempf, after
lashing out, now seems accepting for the greater good.
</P>
<P>
   ``What brought the changes had nothing to do with Hersey or
Det,'' Westphal said. ``It had to do with no Sam Perkins, no Nate
McMillan, no Jerome Kersey, no Greg Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that made the Sonics so tough over the last several
years is the guys coming off the bench. How many games have those
guys won for the Sonics?''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his predecessor, George Karl, who wanted no part of
youngsters, Westphal finds himself with three rookies on his bench,
all with solid NBA potential. But they aren't ready this season.
Westphal figures if they must play, better to put them in the
starting lineup, as he did with Rashard Lewis, where the best
players can cover their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the years we would have loved to have a summer league
and a full preseason,'' Westphal said, ``this was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Westphal is getting a summer league. It's just that
fans are paying $250 courtside to watch it.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
