<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAQ TAKES HIS SHOTS AFTER LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Shaquille O'Neal had one of his vintage nights: 37
points, 19 rebounds and one thinly disguised flagrant foul on his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal slammed down a series of dunks on the Cleveland
Cavaliers, then slammed his Lakers for a shoddy defensive effort
that cost them a 100-93 loss at Gund Arena on Thursday, their
second loss in three games on this road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big man did his work, everybody else has to step up,''
O'Neal said. ``We've gotta be smart. I'm not gonna make excuses for
our loss, but we beat ourselves. And their guards just beat us
up.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, they shredded the Lakers, one open jumper at a time.
Wesley Person scored 18 points, Brevin Knight 20 and Derek Anderson
came of the bench for another 12 as the Cavaliers shot 49.3 percent
overall.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' guards, helpless to stop it, couldn't answer it
either. Kobe Bryant finished with 14 points but was 4 of 12 from
the field, and Derek Harper scored just two points, both on free
throws.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make a 325-pound center lose his cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their guards just dominated our guards the whole game,
rebounding and shooting jumpers,'' he said. ``When I get
double-teamed and I kick it out, guys have to be confident about
what they want to do, not (mess) around with all that dribbling,
all that (bleeping) monkey (bleep).''
</P>
<P>
   The big man also seemed to take a shot at Bryant, saying, ``You
can't let Wesley Person get open for a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the defensive breakdown is anything new. The Lakers'
defense has been nonexistent for large stretches of this road trip,
leading to losses in Sacramento and Cleveland and a near-loss at
Minnesota, where only a late scoring burst saved them from being
0-3.
</P>
<P>
   No one will pinpoint the cause, but there are plenty of
candidates: Dennis Rodman's absence, the numerous changes to the
starting lineup and rotation, the loss of their best defender
(Eddie Jones, traded for Glen Rice).
</P>
<P>
   For the season, the Lakers are 8-8 in games without Rodman, 9-0
with him. But they're also 1-2 since the trade of Jones, which
arguably downgraded their defense at both small forward (from
Bryant to Rice) and shooting guard (from Jones to Bryant).
</P>
<P>
   After letting Person score a quick eight points in the first
quarter _ all in a run that gave the Cavaliers an early 18-10 lead
_ Bryant said he was to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of that was my fault. Wesley Person came off and got
them started with jump shots coming off screens,'' said Bryant, who
is adjusting to playing guard after spending the first 20 games at
forward. ``I was just trying different (defensive) techniques; this
is my first time chasing somebody off screens like that. But I'm a
quick learner.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll have to be. The road and the matchups get no easier when
the Lakers try to rebound against Allen Iverson and the
Philadelphia 76ers tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Their offense could use a boost as well. They shot 43.9 percent
against Cleveland, with Rice hitting just 9 of 21, Bryant 4 of 12
and Rick Fox 3 of 8. The bench was outscored 27-12. And the Lakers
never regained the lead, or even a tie, past the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's taken a step backward for us,'' Harper said. ``We were
sort of pushing the fast-forward button for a while, then stopping
and hitting rewind. . . . I don't think our approach is serious
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said lineup changes probably played a role in the Lakers'
regression, but he also dismissed that as a poor excuse for a team
that expects to contend for a championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we decide to return to a defensive mindset as a unit,
helping each other and putting the onus on yourself to stop your
man one-on-one, teams are gonna score with us. Right now we're
trying to feel our way through some new additions, and we're not in
the greatest offensive sync that we will be in. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's not enough defensive pride. Teams in this
league will kick your butt if you don't come to play both ends of
the floor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
