<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY MAKES PITCH FOR STARTING ROTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. _ Beneath three large ice bags, accompanying
elastic bandages and a loosely draped warmup coat Thursday was a
likely Mariner starting pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd Bluford ``Butch'' Henry was nearly hidden from sight,
obscured by his many layers of postgame wrappings, as he stood in a
darkened hallway replaying his four-inning stint in an 8-7 loss to
the San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   But as far as Seattle's five-man rotation is concerned, the
30-year-old Texan is slowly coming into view. The lefty knows it.
Manager Lou Piniella knows it.
</P>
<P>
   Henry, who missed last season after incurring a spring training
knee injury for the Boston Red Sox, wasn't perfect against the
Giants. He gave up runs in the second and third innings. But he
never lost his cool. That rates big points with the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our veteran pitchers have stayed away from the big inning this
spring,'' Piniella said. ``What did he give up? A couple of
singletons? You win with that with our lineup. I was pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry, his left elbow and both knees under ice, has removed
enough rust to post consecutive solid outings. More importantly for
him, he was physically tested Thursday _ and he passed.
</P>
<P>
   With two runners on, the Giants' Bill Mueller bunted left of the
mound. Henry grabbed the ball, slipped as he planted his surgically
repaired left knee and threw Mueller out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember thinking about my knee, which was
incredible,'' the pitcher said. ``I slipped on the bunt but I
didn't flinch, which is good. It's not even an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Henry has started twice since reminding management, through a
Post-Intelligencer story, that his contract has a stipulation
allowing him to walk away as a free agent if he doesn't make the
starting rotation. Until then, he had been used only in relief.
</P>
<P>
   The free-spirited pitcher said he wasn't trying to create
problems, just protect himself. He did the same thing last year
with Boston. The Red Sox wanted him to pitch with his injury. Henry
said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't complaining and I wasn't bitching at anybody,'' he
said. ``I spoke up for the second time in my career. I'm getting
innings now.''
</P>
<P>
   MISSING IN ACTION: For their 15th spring outing, the Mariners
got on the bus without regulars Ken Griffey Jr., Jay Buhner, Edgar
Martinez and David Segui. Griffey took a day off. Buhner, coming
off elbow surgery, rested before he plays consecutive games Friday
and Saturday. Martinez and Segui both suffered from unexplained
neck spasms.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell is it?'' Piniella asked a trainer when told the
bleached-haired Segui was incapable of any activity. ``The (darn)
permanents he's been getting?''
</P>
<P>
   THE PLAN: Ken Cloude originally was scheduled to throw against
the Giants, but Piniella shuffled his pitchers to allow each to
start hitting the five-inning minimum he wants.
</P>
<P>
   Roster cuts will come before and after tomorrow's split-squad
games, paring the club from 42 to 36 players, and the mound staff
from 20 to 14 players.
</P>
<P>
   ``By (Monday), everyone in our rotation will have gone five
innings,'' Piniella said. ``Then we make up our minds. We can't
wait anymore. . . . The original plan was to get 27 innings from
our starters. We're going to do better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   The manager said he normally has had to give two pitching spots
away each spring, with the recipients not necessarily earning them.
That won't be the case this time.
</P>
<P>
   Rattling off reasons, Piniella explained the club has two solid
prospects in Freddie Garcia and John Halama from the Randy Johnson
trade to Houston; players with major league experience outside the
organization; and mostly players with previous big league time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sixteen of our 20 pitchers have major league experience,'' he
said. ``Last year, or the year before, we had eight or nine with
major league experience. . . . There is competition in earnest this
week.''
</P>
<P>
   SWIFT CURRENT: Among the pitching-staff candidates is
37-year-old Billy Swift, who is prepared for anything. He says his
arm feels great, but back problems have limited his mound time.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander is prepared to retire if the Mariners don't
keep him. He won't go elsewhere without a solid offer, and he won't
even consider starting the season in the minors. Idle time has been
a subject of converstion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to (retired Mariner first baseman) Alvin Davis the
other day and he said the first couple of years out of the game are
weird. You're retired, but you're still in your thirties,'' Swift
said. ``He said you're old for baseball, but young in real life,
and it's difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   BATTER CHATTER: In the Peoria clubhouse, reliever Jose Paniagua
pulled outfielder Charles Gipson's jersey out of a box, got into a
baserunner's stance and then stumbled into the cardboard container,
drawing this comment from Griffey: ``Stay off the basepaths.'' . .
. Piniella, sizing up Sammy Sosa's new home-run ritual of bowing
after hitting home runs and the resulting criticism that has
emerged from players such as pitcher Todd Stottlemyre: ``The next
hitter will have to do a lot of bowing himself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
