<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES END DAVIS' IOWA CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Like most Iowans who visit Arizona in the cool months,
Tom Davis was hoping to stay here as long as possible.
</P>
<P>
   But Connecticut cut Davis' visit, and coaching career at Iowa,
short Thursday night, beating the Hawkeyes, 78-68, in the NCAA West
Regional semifinal game at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   It was the last game at Iowa for Davis, who spent 13 years at
the school and was forced out when school officials decided not to
renew his contract after this season.
</P>
<P>
   The loss ended an heartwarming final run for the 60-year-old
Davis, who has already cleaned his office out back home, but has
yet to pack away his hopes for coaching elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   For Connecticut (31-2), it was another step closer to its goal
of reaching the Final Four for the first time in school history, a
fact that Coach Jim Calhoun has been reminded of only a few hundred
times since the tournament started.
</P>
<P>
   UConn, the region's No. 1 seed, was supposed to breeze through
the West Regional after the second through fourth seeds were
eliminated in the first two rounds. Iowa (20-10) proved to be much
tougher than expected. The Hawkeyes fought the Huskies, literally,
and UConn didn't pull away until the final minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies, led Thursday by forward Richard `Rip` Hamilton's 20
points, play another tournament darling Saturday afternoon in
10th-seed Gonzaga. The winner advances to the Final Four next week
in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa trailed UConn by five at halftime, but opened the second
half with an 8-2 to take a one point lead with 17:08 remaining.
UConn quickly countered, but the Hawkeyes run served notice that
the Huskies were not going to breeze through this regional.
</P>
<P>
   For awhile, Iowa had answers for everything. Khalid El-Amin hit
a three-pointer to put UConn ahead by 3 with 13:22 left. About a
minute later, Iowa guard Kent McCausland tied it with a three
pointer. Then Hamilton made a short jumper, which Range countered
with a little lay-in of his own to tie the score with 11:17 left.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut then threatened to pull away. The Huskies scored six
straight points, their longest run of the night at that point, to
take a six-point lead with 7:01 left. Iowa, however, refused to
wilt, even when they trailed by 7 with five minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   But a missed layup by guard Ryan Luehrsman a minute later, a
traveling ca ll on forward Jess Settles and a missed shot by
Settles effectively ended Iowa's glorious run in this tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were testy in the first half, and Iowa served notice
early that it wasn't going to be intimidated by the Huskies.
Calhoun argued several calls, and Davis was screaming at the
officials to call UConn for illegal screens.
</P>
<P>
   UConn led, 40-35, as the first half ended, but the excitement
wasn't over. As the teams started to leave the court, Iowa guard
Joey Range bopped El-Amin with a forearm. Iowa center Jacob Jaacks
stepped in to separate the two and became embroiled in the fracas
when he wrapped up El-Amin and pulled him away.
</P>
<P>
   But no punches were thrown, and after the officials spent a
couple of minutes looking at the replay, no one was penalized. The
incident did earn the team's captains a lecture from official Joe
Silvester.
</P>
<P>
   Neither team let up much in the second half. Connecticut center
Jake Voskuhl and Iowa forward Jess Settles traded bumps, and fouls,
underneath early in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa stayed in the game until the last five minutes by not
allowing UConn to make one of its trademark runs, which it has used
all season to bury teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies had no trouble breaking Iowa's fullcourt pressure,
but they did have problems scoring in the halfcourt. The Hawkeyes
used a 3-2 zone and a box-and-one in the first half, putting guard
Kent McCausland on forward Richard Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have struggled this season against zone defenses and
had difficulty finding any consistent offensive success Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   UConn was solid on defense, however, and Iowa had difficulty
finding open shots. Center J.R. Koch stepped out and hit a couple
three pointers in th first half as did McCausland.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa made just 11 of 28 shots in the first half, but the
Hawkeyes gathered seven offensive rebounds to make up for it. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
