<SLUG> BC-SOC-INTERNATIONAL-HELP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL SOCCER TRIO LIFTS TEXAS TEAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TROY PHILLIPS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ One is Bosnian, one is Brazilian and one
hails from Africa's Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Other than a love for soccer _ the world's game _ they have
little in common. They bring three distinct styles of play to a
soccer field _ European, South American and African.
</P>
<P>
   But Liman Becirovic, Jiuliano Teixeira and Ibrahim Doukoure are
all Arlington Heights High School Yellow Jackets, regardless of how
the paths of their lives led them here.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the Heights ``U.N. Coalition'' helped the 'Jackets
win their 13th district championship in 17 years and first playoff
game since 1994 against Carroll on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Heights (18-4-1) is scheduled to face Fossil Ridge (22-1-1) at 7
p.m. Friday in the Class 4A Region II quarterfinals at Fossil
Ridge.
</P>
<P>
   It's safe to say that Heights had plenty of domestic talent
before enlisting its three internationals. Senior goalkeeper Mike
Lahoud and his brother, freshman forward Chris Lahoud _ both
half-Lebanese _ are top select players in their age groups.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeper Charles Ivory, defender Phillip Lockwood and forward
Tino Castillo could have easily led Heights to another district
title and maybe postseason success.
</P>
<P>
   Adding three players from three soccer-rich regions could only
enhance a program that had gotten along fine on local talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We already knew about Jiuliano,'' Heights coach Jack Warren
said about the Brazilian exchange student who played on the
junior-varsity team in 1998. ``Liman and Ibrahim were surprises. I
saw their names on a list of 50 or so kids signed up for soccer and
didn't think much of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A week of running drills and scrimmages unveiled the mystery
players. Warren surmised that Becirovic, the Bosnian, and Doukoure,
the Ivory Coast native, would make the varsity.
</P>
<P>
   If only they had been as confident upon arriving in this
country.
</P>
<P>
   While senior midfielder Teixeira came as part of a
soccer-academy exchange program in January 1998, the stories of
Becirovic and Doukoure are more complicated. Teixeira, who has
lived with the Lahouds, played on last year's JV team because the
University Interscholastic League wouldn't grant him varsity
clearance.
</P>
<P>
   In his exchange program, top youth players from Brazil such as
Teixeira, a native of Sao Paulo, were brought to the United States
to help tutor American players. The UIL viewed the program as
``non-traditional,'' thus ruling Teixeira ineligible for varsity
competition for one season.
</P>
<P>
   Warren said Teixeira's skills compared with those of his
junior-varsity teammates were ``night and day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was definitely out of his element,'' Warren said.
</P>
<P>
   Teixeira played club soccer last year with Michael Lahoud for
Fort Worth United, and now both suit up for Dallas Inter. Knowing
he was ready for the high school varsity a year ago gnaws at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I thought, man, I lost all this time on the JV,''
Teixeira said. ``I missed the higher level. The soccer here is very
good. It's more physical than in Brazil. They use a lot of the
body, but they're getting better at picking up the skills.''
</P>
<P>
   Becirovic, a sophomore forward, has had only five months to size
up the American game. He arrived last fall with his parents from
Germany, where they lived for six years after leaving Bosnia and
Herzegovina in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Former Yugoslav republics Croatia and Bosnia and Herzegovina
declared independence in 1991 and touched off a four-year war
between Bosnian Serb Orthodox Christians, Catholic Croats and
Bosnian Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   A former professional player in Germany, Mirhat Becirovic moved
his family to Munich from their hometown of Zenica, a city outlying
the besieged Bosnian capital of Sarajevo.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, German immigration officials told the Bosnians to
return home or adopt another homeland. An international relocation
agency landed the Becirovic family in Fort Worth after it chose to
come to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Liman honed his soccer skills in Germany starting at age 10. In
five years, he made the junior team affiliated with 860 Munich, a
local professional club.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came here, I thought nobody could play soccer (in
the United States),'' Becirovic said. ``I saw them in the World
Cup, and I was worried. Then I saw that there was good soccer here,
and even that some are good enough to play professionally in
Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   Liman said Mirhat ``almost gets a heart attack'' while watching
his high school and club games, and that the elder Becirovic thinks
American soccer is too heavily influenced by its rougher cousin,
football.
</P>
<P>
   Doukoure's impression of the American game is the exact
opposite. Rough play, he said, is a trademark of Ivory Coast
soccer. There, referees who call matches too tightly get roughed up
themselves later on.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't even touch a player here,'' said Doukoure, a
freshman forward. ``You try to play physical, the referee stops
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Doukoure came to the United States in 1997 to live with his
father, who left Ivory Coast in 1986. Between those years, Doukoure
said he saw his father only once, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``His tenacity in going after the ball caught my eye,'' Warren
said. ``Even with a larger defender, he more often than not comes
up with it.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything toughened Doukoure, it was playing soccer barefoot
as a youth in the streets of his hometown, Abidjan.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the most determined Ivory Coast player we've ever had,''
Warren said jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Far from home and starting over, Doukoure, Becirovic and
Teixeira had little other choice.
</P>
<P>
   (Troy Phillips writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact him at (817) 390-7377. E-mail:
tphillips(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
