<SLUG> BC-SOC-NO.2-HIGH-SCHOOL-TEAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEYVILLE HERITAGE CONTINUES SUCCESS DESPITE INJURY SETBACKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEIDI PEDERSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEYVILLE, Texas _ It's surprising that members of the
Colleyville Heritage girls soccer team haven't grown tired of
repeating themselves.
</P>
<P>
   After all, haven't they already proved they aren't a one-player
show?
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers clearly survived the early February injury loss of
then-leading scorer Amy Van Zandt. Later in the month they got
along without Van Zandt's replacement at forward, Krystal Pfluger,
who went down to an ankle injury. Then they triumphed while playing
without yet another injured starter, Staci Everett, in the team's
last three district games.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Panthers are undefeated, with a 21-0-1 record
heading into Friday night's Class 4A Region II quarterfinals
matchup with Carroll. The Panthers survived a tough District 11-4A
race to win their first district title and now have their eye on
the state tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody else was saying our season was over when Amy got
hurt, but we didn't feel that way,'' starter Jessi Moore explained
patiently to yet another inquirer. ``I think it motivated us. If
one person hasn't had it, others have stepped up and done it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers, helped by the addition of Midlothian transfer Van
Zandt, have been stepping up all season. Ranked sixth among state
4A teams in one preseason poll, early on the Panthers knocked off
Richland, Lamar and defending Class 5A state champion Martin, and
earned a tie with Crowley.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been in 11-4A play, however, that Colleyville
Heritage proved what it was really made of. In the fourth district
game, against Grapevine, the Panthers were faced with potential
disaster when Van Zandt tore knee ligaments early in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   Grapevine scored shortly after to go up 2-1, but then the
Panthers tied the score on a Moore goal with about 12 minutes
remaining. They won, 3-2, when Pfluger, who had moved from
midfielder to forward to replace Van Zandt, scored in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adjustment is what this team is about,'' coach Angie Moss
said. ``In clutch games it would be so great to have Amy back, but
the girls know they can't rely on one person to do the work.
Everybody's had to take an extra step.''
</P>
<P>
   With the injury to Van Zandt, who at the time had scored 24
goals, Colleyville Heritage shuffled. Moore, like Van Zandt a
sophomore, now leads the team with 32 goals and 24 assists. Pfluger
has scored eight goals while playing her new position, and junior
Sarah Jensen replaced Pfluger at midfield.
</P>
<P>
   But Colleyville Heritage is hardly all offense. With a midfield
that includes senior Bethany Williams, defenders Kathy Nichols,
Julie Stevens and Kelly Christoffer, and goalkeeper Michele
Vaughan, the Panthers have 17 shutouts in 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   That play earned Colleyville Heritage the No. 2 spot among high
school girls teams in the latest National Soccer Coaches
Association of America poll. Martin is ranked fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our secret is just that we play so well together,''
Christoffer said. ``We just seem to know what each other is
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, after a 10-day layoff from competition, Colleyville
Heritage defeated Hewitt Midway, 5-0. With that victory, the
Panthers advanced further in the playoffs than they did last season
in their first postseason experience. The Panthers, who finished
second in District 9-4A last season, lost in the 1998 bi-district
round to Class 5A Richardson Berkner.
</P>
<P>
   This season, with separate Class 4A and 5A playoffs, Colleyville
Heritage players think they have what it takes to challenge for a
state title. But don't think they are taking anything for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The girls have kept everything in perspective. We're a new
program and we remember what it's like to be at the bottom,'' Moss
said. ``In the playoffs, you start each game from scratch.''
</P>
<P>
   (Heidi Pederson writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact her at (817) 685-3872. E-mail:
sportszone(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
