<HEADLINE>
GEOGRAPHIC REGIONS TAKE TURNS DOMINATING TEXAS BASKETBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STACY FEDUCIA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Six high school boys basketball teams from
the Fort Worth/Dallas area spent parts of last weekend in Austin. A
week before, Mansfield represented the area when it claimed the
girls Class 5A title against Dallas Lincoln.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that this area is a hotbed of basketball champions?
More likely, it is a hotbed of high schools. Having multiple
state-tournament participants from a geographic area is often,
alas, a function of the number of schools in that area and
University Interscholastic League realignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year there were quite a few teams from our area,'' said
Crowley coach Gary Surratt, whose Eagles defeated Port Arthur
Lincoln for the Class 4A boys title. ``I was looking at a Texas
basketball Web site and a lot of people were writing in saying it's
a D/FW thing; but really, it just kind of runs in cycles. For a
long time it was the Houston area, then I can remember when it was
deep Northeast Texas. It just so happens this was the year for the
D/FW area.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was at the boys state tournament: Representing Region
I, Duncanville defeated Region II Dallas Kimball for the Class 5A
title, and Crowley gave Region I the Class 4A title. Coppell
represented Region II in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Peaster, eight miles north of Weatherford, won the Class 2A
title. Ponder, near Denton, bowed out in the Class A semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the concentration of schools in this area, the UIL
almost always divides it in half, typically sending Tarrant County
west and Dallas County east for regional competitions. This season,
after years of playing the Plainviews and Canyons, Fort Worth
schools went east, while the Johnson County schools went west.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a tough region,'' Surratt said of Region I. ``We came
from a tough district and a tough region. We nearly didn't make it
out of regionals because of Plainview, and Peaster's in the same
region as Godley and Krum. That's pretty tough. You just can't ever
tell.''
</P>
<P>
   So before you start crowing about how Fort Worth/Dallas area
ball is better than San Antonio, Austin, Panhandle or even Houston
ball, consider these past geographically dominant state tournament
matchups:
</P>
<P>
   Bryan and Houston Memorial in the 1994 Class 5A final with Port
Arthur Lincoln in the 4A final and Sour Lake Hardin-Jefferson in
the 3A final; Houston Madison and Conroe in the 1985 Class 5A final
with Bay City in the 4A final and Sweeny in the 3A final; San
Antonio Jay in the 1991 5A final with San Antonio Alamo Heights in
the 4A final. Then there was the North Texas quinella in 1993 when
Dunbar won the 5A title, Dallas Lincoln won the 4A title, Carroll
won the 3A title and Brock lost in the Class A finals to Laneville.
</P>
<P>
   Championship city? Not really, simply a high cycle for North
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   (Stacy Feducia writes about high school sports for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can contact her at (817) 390-7407. E-mail:
feducia(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0102EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
