r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-GONAZGA-FLA-     03-19 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-GONAZGA-FLA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSTART GONZAGA KEEPS DREAM ALIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Let Gonzaga Coach Dan Monson speak for the rest of the
college basketball world after his Bulldogs beat Florida, 73-72, on
Thursday night in the West Regional semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow,'' Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   Say it, feel it, but don't dream it, because it's true: Gonzaga
is within one game of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Let the players express the universal reaction to that unlikely
piece of news.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unbelievable,'' said sophomore forward Casey Calvary,
whose tip-in of Quentin Hall's missed shot with 4.4 seconds
remaining was the winning basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is awesome,'' said junior guard Richie Frahm, who scored
17 points, making five three-point baskets in eight attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere, Bing Crosby is crooning a victory tune. John Stockton
might decide to play 10 more years for the Utah Jazz. Suddenly,
Gonzaga is known for more than its famous alumni. The Bulldogs,
representing a university whose enrollment weighs in at less than
5,000, who before last week never had won an NCAA Tournament game,
are the little team that did.
</P>
<P>
   The only ones not surprised at how this fabulous tale is turning
out are the ones who are writing it.
</P>
<P>
   But after leading for virtually the entire game, it looked as if
the Zags would be regarded as just another feisty bunch of
overachievers whose reach barely exceeded their grasp.
</P>
<P>
   Surviving deficits of 13 points in the first half and seven with
9:41 to go, and missing 16 of their first 17 three-point attempts,
Florida battled back to take a 72-69 lead on Greg Stolt's
three-pointer with 45.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   After three timeouts, two by Gonzaga, the Bulldogs passed up the
trey for a better shot, albeit a two-pointer. Frahm hit Jeremy
Eaton inside, and Eaton's layup made it 72-71, Florida, with 19.7
seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Florida inbounded to forward Brent Wright, who heretofore had a
nice game with 15 points and seven rebounds. Gonzaga's players were
yelling for Hall, a senior guard, to foul Wright. But Hall didn't
hear it. Instead of getting fouled, Wright traveled in the
backcourt with 15.4 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless his (Hall's) ears for not letting him hear us,''
senior guard Matt Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga (28-6) was down by one with one possession left to win,
and also down to one timeout, and Monson used it. After the Zags
in-bounded, Florida's Kenyan Weeks poked a pass out of bounds. With
10.6 seconds to go, Gonzaga brought it in again, Frahm to Calvary
to Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, the quickest of the Zags, drove to the basket from the top
of the key. He got into the lane, took off, seemed to hang for a
second or two, and let the ball go. The plan for Gonzaga at that
point was pretty simple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get a rebound or foul if we didn't score,'' Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall's shot bounced off the rim. Calvary, who stands 6-foot-8,
was blocked out by the 6-8 Wright. But the rebound bounced over
Wright and Calvary was there, going up with both hands.
</P>
<P>
   Or trying to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had both hands on the ball, and my right arm kind of got
pulled down a little bit, and I batted it off the glass with my
left hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove to the hoop, and I figured it would hit glass and go
in, or hit rim and go off. Coach told us to get the rebound or get
a foul doing it, and I like fouling. So I went in there figuring if
I didn't get it, I was gonna foul somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   Now trailing by a point, sixth-seeded Florida (22-9) had one
more chance. Senior guard Eddie Shannon raced upcourt with the ball
and launched a three-pointer from the right that bounced off the
rim at the buzzer. As Gonzaga's players mobbed each other, Shannon
lay face down for several seconds before being helped to his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, somebody had to lose,'' Shannon said later.
``And it was us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
