<SLUG> BC-BKC-AUBURN-OHIOSTATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OHIO STATE DEFEAT AUBURN, 72-64 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The only team standing between St. John's and
the Final Four is one that finished 8-22 last season and was dead
last in the Big 10 with just one victory in the conference.
</P>
<P>
   That team is Ohio State and that scenario unfolded on Thursday
night when the Buckeyes, led by Boston College's former coach Jim
O'Brien and former point guard Scoonie Penn, eliminated Auburn,
72-64, setting up a match with St. John's for the South Regional
title on Saturday at 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the continuation of a stunning resurgence for
the Buckeyes (26-8) in their second season under O'Brien. They were
second in the Big 10 this season, behind only Michigan State, the
top-seeded team in the Midwest Regional, and they were seeded
fourth in the South.
</P>
<P>
   Playing against top-seeded Auburn (29-4), Ohio State led at the
half by 31-26 behind 11 points from their other outstanding guard,
Michael Redd. But Ohio State's lead was just 62-61 with 1 minute 57
seconds left when Redd drew the fifth foul from Auburn's star
forward and leading scorer Chris Porter.
</P>
<P>
   Porter departed with 15 points and 11 rebounds and Redd hit both
free throws to extend the lead to 64-61. Then Penn, who transferred
to Ohio State to follow O'Brien, hit a 15-foot baseline jumper, 2
of his 24 points on 9-of-16 shooting.
</P>
<P>
   After a blocked shot by Ohio State forward Brian Brown on a
3-point attempt by Auburn, Brown led the fast break and sent a
behind-the-back bounce pass to a trailing Jason Singleton for a
dunk that gave Ohio State a 68-61 lead with 58.4 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that keeps hitting me between the eyes,'' said
O'Brien of his team, ``is how these guys have constantly come back
to accomplish a little bit more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just when I ask, `Are they capable of going on and doing
more?,' they somehow surprise me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0115EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCONN-IOWA-NYT &LR;      03-19 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-IOWA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT OUTLASTS IOWA 78-68 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Connecticut and Iowa decided from the start that their
Round of 16 matchup in the National Collegiate Athletic Association
tournament would boil down to this: One team was going down.
Literally. On the deck. With a push and a shove. No gentle nudge.
</P>
<P>
   This game got nasty.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut took its blows and made sure its shots lasted
longer.
</P>
<P>
   It was more than a game of survival and a game light on
artistry. There was a confrontational air to Connecticut and Iowa
on Thursday night, and the Huskies proved better at bump-and-grind
basketball, winning, 78-68, before 17,975 fans at America West
Arena. It was the largest crowd to watch a college basketball game
in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Was it basketball, or football? The crowd must have wondered at
times. But it was basketball, elbow-in-your-back style, and a
rugged tussle for the final eight. Include Connecticut (31-2) in
that group. The Huskies withstood the Hawkeyes (20-10), who were
inspired by the emotion surrounding the forced departure of Coach
Tom Davis after 13 seasons at the school. The Huskies advanced and
will meet Gonzaga (28-6), a 73-72 winner over Florida on Thursday,
here on Saturday for the West Regional title and a trip to the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Richard Hamilton led Connecticut with 24 points.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied at 44-44 with 15 minutes 29 seconds to play,
and Connecticut led by only 59-55 with 6:15 left. But Iowa wilted
in the stretch _ tired, bruised and unable to match the punch of
Connecticut. It was the Huskies' insistence on running every
fast-break chance and their interior defense that also frustrated
Iowa. Connecticut handled Iowa's full-court pressure, responded to
each Hawkeye rally and simply was the more talented team with
stronger staying power.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minutes, Connecticut broke the game open, making
its free throws while Iowa kept missing its shots and fouling.
Talent and composure. Connecticut offered a convincing display.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut won the first half, 40-35, and, obviously, it was a
bit much for Joey Range, Iowa's freshman guard. Range is big for a
guard, 6 feet 5 inches and 200 pounds, and on Thursday night he
liked throwing that weight around. As the teams walked off the
floor at the half, Range, in a casual yet calculating fashion,
lifted an arm and nearly clotheslined Khalid El-Amin. It looked
more like Big Ten football move than a basketball one.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin ran after Range, and the two were separated by
teammates. A cheap shot by Range, no doubt, but would it work?
Would El-Amin be flustered? Would Connecticut? Both teams were
pushing and shoving and jawing throughout the first half.
Connecticut hoped that kind of play would be kept in check. Iowa
hoped the sideshow could be an equalizer.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa, however, had no such luck in the first half. Iowa started
strong and shot the ball with vigor, displaying a nice touch. It
cooled as the half wore on, while Connecticut was steadier in
ball-handling, shot selection, defense and in its insistence on
playing the game at full speed.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut pushed.
</P>
<P>
   It took its rebounds and ran. It took its inbounds passes and
ran. It ran off Iowa's missed shots. It pushed and forced the
issue, forcing Iowa to keep up. The Hawkeyes could not, despite the
fact that that style is usually their game. In the half,
Connecticut led in fast-break points by 10-2. In order to fast
break, a team must rebound.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton scored 12 points in the first half and El-Amin scored
11. No Iowa player reached double figures. El-Amin added five
assists and Ricky Moore four. Iowa remained close in the half
despite shooting 39.3 percent compared with Connecticut's 64
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's biggest lead in the half was 7 points. Four times
in the final six minutes it produced that lead, and on three of
those occasions the margin was supplied by baskets by Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa is a team of size, shooters and determination. Those traits
helped it topple Alabama-Birmingham by 13 points and Arkansas by 10
points to reach this game. Tonight Iowa did not blink. Connecticut
is built the same way, inside and out.
</P>
<P>
   That is what made this game such a physical bout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
