u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT &LR;      03-19 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-MAGIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGIC DEFEAT KNICKS, 86-78 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Once it ended, the Knicks began to hand out tired
excuses like pamphlets on a street corner. To many of them,
particularly Coach Jeff Van Gundy, New York screeched to a halt
against the Orlando Magic with an 86-78 loss because of sluggish
pulses and blank looks on their faces.
</P>
<P>
   But confronted with a Magic team that had forced the Knicks into
disarray for the season opener, and chest-to-chest with an opponent
ahead of them in the Atlantic Division, it was hard to fathom how
the Knicks could have been anything but jazzed to play on Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   So it was hard to tell what was the bigger indictment of the
team: the thought that the Knicks were uninspired to play the
Magic, or the real possibility that, right now, they just aren't as
good as the top two teams in their division.
</P>
<P>
   The latter theory isn't popular in the Knicks' locker room. Only
a few entertain the idea. But the premise seems to be gaining
momentum after the Knicks ended their three-game winning streak
with the loss to the Magic as Allan Houston and Latrell Sprewell
vanished into the dull air of Madison Square Garden. The Knicks
(14-10), now 0-4 against Miami and Orlando, finished out the fourth
quarter hitting just 5 of 21 shots after opening it with a horrid
1-for-10 stretch. That span allowed the Magic to make up a 10-point
third-quarter deficit and pass the confused Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew this team was going to be tough,'' said Sprewell, who
was 0 for 7 in the second half after scoring 12 points to help give
the Knicks a 48-43 lead at halftime. ``It was a good challenge for
us to let us know where we're at. Obviously, we have some work to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   They are not on par with the Magic, yet. The undermanned Magic
(18-7), missing the injured Charles (Bo) Outlaw and a flu-bitten
Nick Anderson, scrambled and scurried to cover the tandem of
Houston and Sprewell, both so deadly in the first half. With Coach
Chuck Daly using everyone, including 39-year-old Dominique Wilkins,
the Magic began to shut down and frustrate Sprewell and Houston in
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Sprewell was able to find easy post-up opportunities against the
rookie Matt Harpring in the second quarter, scoring 10 consecutive
points. Those disappeared once the bigger Wilkins began guarding
him. Houston's troubles were more self-inflicted. One minute he was
aggressively shaking free of Anfernee Hardaway for 11 first-half
points, the next half he was aimless as he hit 3 of his last 8
shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got sucked into lazy basketball,'' Houston said. ``We just
couldn't pick up and get ourselves out of it. We just had no
energy, especially on offense. We just fell into a trap and never
got out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell Armstrong made sure of it. The Magic's bolt of lightning
off the bench hit a 3-pointer with 47 seconds left to give his team
an 80-72 lead. Armstrong, who had 10 assists, finished with 18
points and Hardaway had 19, while the Knicks were led by Houston
(18 points) and Kurt Thomas (17 points). Under the shadow of Horace
Grant, Larry Johnson scored 4 points on a 1-for-7 night. The Knicks
lost the rebounding, 39-33.
</P>
<P>
   Once Sprewell began to struggle, so did the Knicks. The Magic
closed on the Knicks' 10-point lead in the third quarter and went
ahead, 72-70, in the fourth on a jumper off a pick-and-roll play by
the rookie Michael Doleac with 4:02 left in the game. Doleac had 10
points in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the Magic personnel, the Knicks were no match. They
turned the ball over three consecutive times and buckled under the
talented Magic. But Van Gundy, trying to explain the defeat, leaned
more toward his team's own energy level, not the matchup problems
the Magic caused.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seemed like we were a step slow,'' Van Gundy said. ``We're
a team that right now, without Patrick Ewing, if we're going to
win, we're going to have to play at our highest energy level. I
don't think we had that energy level that was good enough through
the game. And it was only masked in the first half by great
shooting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
