<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NETS-BULLS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLS BEAT NETS, 104-95 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ _ Stephon Marbury, who shot 47 percent in his first
three games with the New Jersey Nets, could not find the rim in his
fourth. Missing 17 of 24 shots on Thursday night, Marbury fell into
that dark shooting hole that has engulfed the Nets all season. The
result was another embarrassing loss, 104-95, to the no-name
Chicago Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   After Chicago broke away for a 15-point lead in the third
quarter, the only suspense that remained was whether the Bulls
(7-16) would reach triple digits for the second time this season.
</P>
<P>
   To the delight of the United Center's sellout crowd, they did
when Toni Kukoc scored the final 2 of his 21 points on two free
throws with 1 minute 1 second remaining. Not since whipping the
Nets by 103-87 on March 9 had the Bulls' offense been so prolific.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the ball is too big and the rim is too small,'' said
Jayson Williams, who had 15 points and 10 rebounds. ``I think we
need to be playing with hard balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Kittles was the only Net to display any touch, making 8 of
14 shots in scoring 20 points. New Jersey was pleased to see its
third-year shooting guard find the range since he entered the game
shooting a career-low 33.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But unfortunately for the Nets, Kittles's teammates were not as
accurate. Keith Van Horn shot 6 for 17 in scoring 15 points.
Kendall Gill was 2 for 8 in scoring 7, and Marbury, his jump shot
having deserted him, was obviously just as bad. He still finished
with a deceiving stat line of 24 points and 10 assists, but anyone
who saw the game knows that his performance was poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put the ball in his hands a lot because we're groping,''
said Don Casey, now 1-2 as the interim coach. ``So statistically,
his numbers are a little misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Marbury said the inaccuracy was due to fatigue, since the Nets
were playing their third game in three nights. ``They all felt
good,'' he said. ``They all felt like they were going in. But I
don't think I had the lift that I usually have on my jump shot.''
</P>
<P>
   What was a close game at halftime got out of hand in the third
quarter, when Chicago outscored the Nets by 30-19 to go ahead,
80-65. Harper, who blitzed the Nets for a season-high 25 points
last week, scored 10 points in the period to lead the Bulls.
Looking almost Jordanesque, the 35-year-old guard flew through the
air and the Nets' defense for a couple of stylish slam dunks.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls, who made most of their third-quarter run with an
unsung lineup of Harper, Rusty LaRue, Kornel David, Mark Bryant and
Cory Carr, were not always so dominant.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets got off to a blistering start, making 7 of 13 shots to
take an 18-14 lead. Marbury, who averaged 24 points in his first
three games with the Nets, was more the playmaker in the early
going, assisting teammates on six of the team's seven baskets. But
the chemistry seemed to disappear over the next four minutes, as
Chicago ran off 16 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets missed eight consecutive shots during the Bulls' run,
but righted themselves with a 15-3 spurt that began in the last
minute of the first quarter and continued into the second. The run
was truly a team effort as five Nets contributed points to tie the
game at 33.
</P>
<P>
   The United Center, of course, was the site of the last three of
the six National Basketball Association championships the Bulls won
under Phil Jackson. With the coach having stepped down after last
season, speculation is rampant about where his next coaching stop
will be.
</P>
<P>
   Six clubs, including the Nets, have been in contact with
Jackson, who has been intrigued by New Jersey's tremendous young
talent pool, but interests outside of basketball might keep him
away from the game for another year.
</P>
<P>
   Already a speaker at fund-raisers and corporate gatherings for
the former Senator Bill Bradley's Presidential campaign, Jackson
might become more active in promoting the Presidential bid of his
former Knicks teammate, which would keep him out of coaching until
the 2000-2001 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
