<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS CINDERELLA HAS AN ATTITUDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
BICKLEY Bickley: Gonzaga an underdog, but not intimidated 
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They are a bunch of guys you'd find at the YMCA.
Calling their own fouls, arguing over shirts and skins, running
lunch-hour contenders off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Guys you'd expect to show up at a pizza parlor, order a few
pitchers of beer and plop their recreational league trophy on the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly the kind of outfit you expect to show up in March and
tug at your underdog loyalties.
</P>
<P>
   They are Gonzaga. They are hot. Off to the Elite Eight, destined
for a night with Letterman, representing a school experiencing a
mad rush in merchandise sales.
</P>
<P>
   The flavor of the month, if not a legitimate fad.
</P>
<P>
   But this is where you check yourselves. For starters, Gonzaga is
no fluke. They are 28-6, well-rounded and well-coached. They are
not the least bit warm or fuzzy. And they are not checking the
clock for midnight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying we have,'' forward Richie Frahm said. ``If we
get a glass slipper offered to us, we're going to crack it over
your head.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they have no shot Saturday against Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll need a lot of luck,'' Frahm conceded. ``They're a great
team.''
</P>
<P>
   True, and sentiment had no shot against the Huskies on Thursday.
Connecticut ended the run of Iowa and the cornfield career of Tom
Davis in workmanlike fashion, plowing through the emotion and a
plethora of cheap shots. And now Dr. Feel Good will walk off into
the sunset, pushed out of his job by a callous administration,
rumored to be replaced by Steve Alford.
</P>
<P>
   And the only thing separating Connecticut from the Final Four is
this quirky school from Spokane, Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 40 minutes against a great Gonzaga team,'' Connecticut
coach Jim Calhoun said. ``That stuff about Cinderella . . . the
slipper broke a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, sometimes the better team doesn't win, and there was
certainly a sense of destiny apparent on Thursday. As Gonzaga
stared at defeat, down by one with 19 seconds left against Florida,
the players were screaming at point guard Quentin Hall to foul
somebody. Hall heard the desperate pleas, but . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Something just held me back,'' Hall said, laughing
uncontrollably. ``I guess it was the man upstairs.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like that, the guy Hall was supposed to foul inexplicably
traveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you,'' Hall said. ``Something just blocked me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga is named for a Jesuit priest who died trying to comfort
the sick during a 16th-century plague in Rome. Divine intervention
for a basketball game?
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, it was hunger,'' said Father Tony Lehmann, a
man who has been behind the bench for every Gonzaga game since
1982. ``Just a decision they made not to let it slip through their
fingers.''
</P>
<P>
   Like the ending, a wild tip-in from Casey Calvary, which somehow
made sense.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of every Gonzaga practice, they run a drill. A coach
throws the ball off the basket and 15 guys fight for the rebound.
When you get three rebounds, you're excused from the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my favorite drill,'' Calvary said. ``I have an anger
management problem. Sometimes, I want to turn it into a boxing
match out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga is a smart team. They pass the ball wonderfully well,
and they pass with passion and trust. They know how to pick apart
defenses. They're content to play as a team. But more than
anything, they have nasty. And lots of it.
</P>
<P>
   No shortage of attitude with this group, a team that won't back
down from the Huskies, no matter what the spread says on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That just goes along with playing for a small school that
doesn't get a lot of notoriety or press,'' Santangelo said. ``So
we're always out to prove something. By all means, there's a chip
on our shoulder. There are people who can't pronounce our name, let
alone know where we're from. So, yeah, that adds to the
motivation.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough bunch, but no fluke.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people think of Gonzaga as an un-athletic team just because
we have a bunch of White guys, they're wrong,'' Calvary said.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they're wrong and Gonzaga is right. The perfect symbol for
a tournament that never lets you down. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
