<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-FLORIDA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATORS WILL RELIVE 1 THAT GOT AWAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD OBERT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Brent Wright sat on the floor Thursday night, his
jersey pulled over his head. In a matter of seconds, Gonzaga
snatched victory away from Florida, and the 6-foot-8 sophomore felt
at fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it got away,'' he said. ``It was right there.
We had it. Then, everything . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Went wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The final seconds ticking down, his team hanging on to a
one-point lead, Wright, under the Gonzaga basket, thought about
passing to Major Parker. Then he thought about calling a timeout
when he saw Parker covered and point guard Quentin Hall suddenly in
his face. Then he traveled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he gave me the timeout, but the ref said I
traveled,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen seconds remained, with the West Regional final at
America West Arena still in sight for the Gators.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators had the perimeter covered. Hall drove and pulled up
for a jumper. The Gators didn't block out Casey Calvary. Wright
said he felt Calvary come over his back for the tip with four
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to jump and he was already up in the air and he got
the ball,'' Wright said. ``We had a chance to win the game. All we
had to do was rebound. But we didn't block out.''
</P>
<P>
   Senior guard Eddie Shannon couldn't get his rushed shot from
behind the arc to fall at the end, and the Gators, who after
falling behind by 13, after making only 1 of 11 three-pointers in
the first half, were left with a sick feeling to take into next
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators never led until guard Kenyan Weaks' three-point play
gave them a 39-37 lead in the first minute of the second half. They
lost the lead on Gonzaga's next possession, a Richie Frahm
three-pointer, and the Gators, falling behind by eight, didn't lead
again until senior Greg Stolt's three-pointer gave them a 59-58
edge with 6:45 left.
</P>
<P>
   Stolt, ending his Florida career, nailed his third three-pointer
of the half with 45 seconds left for a 72-69 lead. But it was for
naught.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough way to lose,'' Weaks said. ``I'd rather lose by
50 than the way that game ended.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Billy Donovan called it frustrating, having the season end
``on a freak play.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon couldn't get up after missing as the buzzer sound. He
sat in agony, not far from where Wright was in tears, his face
covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was the last game I would ever play for Florida,''
said Shannon, who led the comeback with seven assists and two
steals. ``I knew it was over.''
</P>
<P>
   But not for most of the Gators. All but Shannon and Stolt
return.
</P>
<P>
   And they'll have a long off-season to recover, the surreal 73-72
ending playing endlessly in their minds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the game of basketball, but life has got to go on,''
Parker said. ``It would have been great to be on the other end of
the stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we've got to do is eliminate the taste we've got in our
mouths tonight, and, a week from now, get back into the gym and
work harder.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
