<HEADER>
A6229 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WEST-CASSTEVENS-A     03-19 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NCAA IS STRICTLY BY THE BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - It's as if someone hired an interior decorator.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA flounced into America West Arena, rolled its eyes at
the furnishings and immediately began changing everything.
</P>
<P>
   ````That's'' got to go.''
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   ``That ``laundry'' up there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns' Western Conference banners. The Rattlers' championship
banner. And the Suns' retired jersey numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beer sign, too. And get rid of that gaudy orange thing
painted on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The makeover began early Tuesday morning. Workers covered the
Suns' midcourt logo with a huge blue circle that reads ``NCAA.''
They erased the NBA three-point line. They blacked out all
advertising signs in the lower third of the arena.
</P>
<P>
   Then they hung blue drapes, acres of them, throughout the
building. Within 48 hours, the home of the Suns, Coyotes, Rattlers
and Mercury was so completely transformed that America West Arena
looked just like Continental Airlines Arena in East Rutherford,
N.J., and the Trans World Dome in St. Louis and Thompson-Boling
Arena in Knoxville, Tenn., the other regional sites of the NCAA
Division I men's basketball championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want every site to look exactly the same,'' said Bill
Hancock, who runs the Big Dance. ``We want it to be a ``college''
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to organization and a commitment to uniformity,
Hancock literally wrote the book. The NCAA's 2-inch-thick
tournament operations manual determined everything that happened
under the arena roof Thursday night except the outcome of the
semifinal games, won by 10th-seeded Gonzaga and top-seeded
Connecticut. The Bulldogs and Huskies will play Saturday, with the
champion advancing to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA's pledge is to treat every team in the tournament
equally. College athletics' governing body bends over backward not
to play favorites, and if you've tried bending over backward and
aren't a gymnast, you know how hard that is.
</P>
<P>
   Each tournament team may play its alma mater and fight song, but
NCAA rules limit the size of the pep band to 30 members. Big
schools with large bands have to make hard decisions. Do they cut a
flutist or the clarinet player? Gonzaga, a small school, has only
20 in its pep band. To reach the maximum number of musicians, the
NCAA allowed Gonzaga to recruit 10 trumpets and trombones from its
jazz program.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA has a 12-cheerleaders limit. According to the
tournament manual, a school may ``rent'' cheerleaders _ seriously _
but ``only'' if the school doesn't have any. Can you really rent
cheerleaders? If so, what's the deposit?
</P>
<P>
   According to NCAA rules, only one (1) costumed mascot may
represent the school during tournament games.
</P>
<P>
   The night Arizona won the national championship, Wilma Wildcat _
or was it Wilbur? _ stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   None of the four teams here was assigned to the Suns' locker
room, which is spacious and carpeted and has a whirlpool bath and
big-screen TV. Careful not to favor one school over another,
Connecticut was assigned the more modest NBA visitors' locker room,
Florida the NHL visitors' locker room. Gonzaga and Iowa dressed in
multipurpose rooms that have about the same square footage.
</P>
<P>
   While it tasted better, Gonzaga's post-game box dinner was the
same as Florida's last meal.
</P>
<P>
   One sandwich. One bag of chips. One orange. Two cookies.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA provided the media the same meal at all four regional
sites. Hot dogs and turkey sandwiches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to serve gumbo,'' Hancock said, and it was
difficult to tell by his straight face whether Bill, a longtime
friend, was serious. OK, so why didn't you? Hancock said, ``People
who got to New Orleans would have an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Hancock picked up his leather-bound manual and smiled at its
weight. The guidebook is not as big as the Valley Yellow Pages but
it's every bit as comprehensive. Every rule imaginable is written
there. Here's one, for example:
</P>
<P>
   ``Spirit squads may use megaphones for voice amplification but
not as a'' ``distraction''.``''
</P>
<P>
   The manual then defines what the NCAA considers a distraction.
Pounding them on the floor. Striking them with your hands or waving
them ``in any way''.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know the punishment for such a violation, or if a
cheerleader ever has been caught. But if the day should come when a
school is given a technical foul for improper use of a megaphone
and the other team ends up shooting a free throw to win the
national championship, it would be a crying shame, not to mention
the cause for a student riot, and probably one whiz-bang lawsuit. &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
b
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0153EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0032 </DOCNO>
