<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6231 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHRISTIE'S-AUCTION-NY     03-19 1289
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRISTIE'S-AUCTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAME, AND HIGH PRICE TAGS, CLING TO STARS' OSCAR GOWNS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES BARRON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ First there was the Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis
auction with the $574,500 humidor and the $442,500 rocking chair.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Diana auction with the $222,500 blue velvet
dress, and the Duke and Duchess of Windsor auction with the
$415,000 mahogany table.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, in the latest manifestation of celebrity
auction mania, the dress that Elizabeth Taylor wore to the Academy
Awards 30 years ago _ a periwinkle blue and violet gown with a
V-shaped front that plunged to approximately there _ went for
$150,000. It was bought by a toy maker that outbid a
cable-television network by $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-five thousand over budget,'' said the losing bidder,
Kate McEnroe, the head of American Movie Classics.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel Inc., the toy maker that is the couturier to millions of
Barbies and Chatty Cathys, did not send anyone to Christie's Park
Avenue auction room, where a standing-room crowd oohed and aahed as
the price climbed past five figures and into six. A Mattel
executive was at the other end of an open telephone line, matching
Ms. McEnroe bid for bid in $5,000 jumps.
</P>
<P>
   Listening in on another line was Miss Taylor, who has been
closely identified with raising money for AIDS charities. Proceeds
from the sale of 56 dresses worn to Academy Awards ceremonies over
four decades _ a total of $786,120, including buyers' premiums that
added 15 percent to the bids _ went to the American Foundation for
AIDS Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very pleased with the results,'' said Mathilde Krim,
chairwoman of the foundation's board. ``A lot of research can be
done with this kind of money.''
</P>
<P>
   The price for Miss Taylor's gown was the highest ever paid for a
dress at auction after the Diana dress, according to Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   The second-most-expensive dress sold on Thursday night went to
another cable network. The Home Shopping Network bid $70,000 for
the robe-like black outer garment and the dove-gray ball skirt that
Madonna wore to the 1997 Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   But while a handful of dresses sold in the $20,000 range, the
prices overall were less stratospheric than at the Onassis or Diana
sales. The crowd was younger and less moneyed than at the Onassis
auction, and the Oscar-night fashions lacked the historical
resonance of some of the Kennedy memorabilia. The dresses were not
even the costumes from the films that made the actresses famous,
just what they wore to a certain ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Some auctiongoers sounded almost like bargain-hunters. ``I think
that this auction was a good buy,'' said Troy Segal, who paid
$5,000 for Barbara Hershey's emerald-green evening dress from the
1996 Academy Awards, when she was nominated for best supporting
actress for ``Portrait of a Lady.'' ``In the grand scheme of
things, it's a Versace,'' said Ms. Segal. ``Of course, if I can't
wear it at all, it will turn out to be a horrible buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Diane Clehane, a freelance entertainment reporter from
Scarsdale, N.Y., sounded more certain. ``I got one of the best
dresses for three grand,'' she said after landing the aqua
silk-satin and cashmere dress that Claire Danes wore to the 1996
Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a long history of spending a lot on clothes, but not
that much this time _ and this was the first auction I'd ever been
to,'' Ms. Clehane said. ``It's amazing how your heart gets
racing.''
</P>
<P>
   Considering how much attention is paid to who wears what at the
Academy Awards, it was not surprising that the auction seemed to
draw more fashion followers than film fans. There were those with
crystal-clear memories of the dresses they were bidding on.
</P>
<P>
   Some bidders tried for a number of dresses, raising their hands
again and again and hoping the other bidders would drop out before
their budgets ran out. Others, like Jaime Rodriguez, a Bronx
restaurateur, waited for that one and only dress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jennifer dress, for me, that's excitement,'' said
Rodriguez, whose $5,500 bid got him the sleeveless, asymmetrical
Badgley Mischka dress that Jennifer Lopez wore to the 1996
ceremony. ``I figure, it's a great cause, bringing Jennifer back to
the Bronx.''
</P>
<P>
   Debbie Korb, who said she was Uma Thurman's real estate agent,
concentrated on the lavender silk chiffon evening dress that Ms.
Thurman wore to the 1994 Academy Awards, when she was nominated for
best supporting actress in ``Pulp Fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Korb started bidding when the dress was in the $1,000 range
and the bids were rising by $100 each time. She dropped out when
the price topped $3,000 and each jump was $500. It eventually sold
for $8,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``She came to see her dress the other night and was having sad
thoughts about it,'' Ms. Korb said. ``If I'd gotten it, I think
she'd have wanted me to give it back. I earned a big commission
when she bought her house, and if she buys a more expensive house,
I could do it next time.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Oscar get-ups got more down-to-earth bids. Mark Canno, a
real-estate developer whose wife bid $5,500 for the butterscotch
evening dress that Elizabeth Shue wore last year, said that he was
surprised that gowns that had belonged to better-known actresses
went for less money than some that had come from the closets of
younger, lesser-known stars. A Raquel Welch dress sold for $5,500,
while a black jersey evening dress that Rita Wilson wore to the
1994 ceremony went for $15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, spousal star power may have had something to do with
the price of Ms. Wilson's dress. As Canno noted, Ms. Wilson was
accompanied by her husband, Tom Hanks, when she wore the dress, and
it was the night he won the Oscar for best actor in ``Forrest
Gump.''
</P>
<P>
   Christie's officials said that Mattel made two other purchases
on Thursday night. One _ an all-black creation that combined a
velvet dressmaker's coat by Giorgio Armani, a skirt by Valentino
and a T-shirt from the Gap _ was the ensemble that Sharon Stone
wore in 1995, when she was nominated for best actress for
``Casino'' and was the presenter in the best dramatic score.
Mattel's winning bid was $8,500.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel also bid $10,000 for a Richard Tyler ivory gabardine
tuxedo that Diane Keaton wore to the 1992 Oscars, when she was a
presenter. For its bid, Mattel got a suit vest with silk-covered
buttons, a pair of matching trousers, a tuxedo jacket with
silk-satin peaked lapels and an ivory silk-satin tie.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McKendall said the company bought Miss Taylor's dress
``because we have a relationship with her'' _ the company created a
``one-of-a-kind Elizabeth Taylor doll'' for an AIDS charity in Los
Angeles whose founders include Mattel's chief executive, Jill
Barad, she said. The dress showed off Miss Taylor's tiny waist and
violet eyes, but was really designed to call attention to a
69.42-carat diamond necklace, a present from Richard Burton, her
husband at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Ms. McEnroe leave empty-handed. After a long round of
back-and-forth bidding, her $50,000 got the forest green ensemble
that Kate Winslet wore to the 1997 Academy Awards when she was
nominated for best supporting actress. She also bid $8,500 for the
Christian Lacroix dress that Kristin Scott-Thomas wore to the 1996
Academy Awards, when she was nominated for best actress for ``The
English Patient.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in her other role as the head of Romance Classics, Ms.
McEnroe spent $40,000 on the silver-beaded Edith Head evening dress
that Janet Leigh wore to the 1959 Oscars and $8,000 on a cocktail
dress that was designed for Marlene Dietrich and was worn to the
1983 Academy Awards by Jamie Lee Curtis, when she was escorted by
Dietrich's grandson, Michael Riva.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
