<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 02:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6241 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR     03-19 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIRED COYOTES TIE BLUES  
 DISALLOWED GOALS BRING OUT ST. LOUIS EMOTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The last game they played at the Kiel Center, the
visiting coach from Philadelphia got so mad he grabbed a stick from
behind the bench and chucked it onto the ice like a javelin.
</P>
<P>
   That decision Tuesday by Roger Nielson cost the Flyers' bench
boss a two-game suspension and a $10,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   During portions of Thursday's game here between the Coyotes and
the St. Louis Blues, both Jim Schoenfeld and Joel Quenneville had
moments when they probably wanted to do the same thing _ or worse.
</P>
<P>
   But when it was over, both coaches managed to find something
positive out of a series of negatives during a seesaw 2-2 draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a tired team,'' Schoenfeld said. ``We were on our third
game in four nights, and with the travel . . . So to have the
energy to mount a comeback I think again is a real good statement
from our men. I was pleased how they hung in there for each other
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of one St. Louis goal that was whistled dead
and another Blues' score disallowed due to a crease violation, the
Coyotes scored twice in the third period to take the lead, despite
being thoroughly outshot up to that point.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Adams redirected a slap shot from Jeremy Roenick for the
first one at the 8:05 mark, and Mike Stapleton found the net for
the third time in four games with nine minutes left on a skipping
shot he ripped from just inside the blue line.
</P>
<P>
   But Pavol Demitra sent it into overtime on his team-leading 32nd
goal with 7:42 remaining on a mad three-man dash into the Coyotes'
zone with defenseman Jeff Finley and Al MacInnis.
</P>
<P>
   Newly acquired goalie Mikhail Shtalenkov, making his second
start in as many days, came up with 29 saves to preserve the point
for Phoenix. The Coyotes put 22 on veteran Grant Fuhr, but only
eight in the first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The tie left the Coyotes (33-24-12) undefeated in their last
four games (2-0-2) after dropping 11 of their previous 13 to come
dangerously close to losing their grip on the fourth playoff seed
in the Western Conference. Thanks to their recent wake-up call,
however, home ice in the first round of the postseason now looks
reasonably safe.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was safe Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite outgunning the Coyotes with an aircraft-carrier amount
of sorties on Shtalenkov _ they outshot Phoenix, 16-3, in the first
period alone _ the Blues only had a 1-0 lead entering the third
period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Shtalenkov gave us a chance to win the hockey
game,'' Schoenfeld said. ``He made a couple point-blank saves
there.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the officials, according to the Blues. After former
Coyote Mike Eastwood scored on a breakaway due partly to a slow
Phoenix line change, Michel Picard had a goal turned down because
of a quick whistle by referee Richard Trottier.
</P>
<P>
   Then Demitra had one called back in the second period when
Picard was nailed for being in the crease before the puck arrived.
But what really made St. Louis feel like Arch Madness was a refuted
``no call'' by Trottier on Adams, whom Fuhr animatedly complained
had knocked him down as Stapleton's shot came in front the point.
</P>
<P>
   Did he?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Adams said, adding, ``I don't remember. I don't know
what he was upset about.''
</P>
<P>
   Quenneville said Adams had delivered an elbow toward the
goalie's head and screamed, along with Fuhr, for an interference
penalty, which would have nullified the score. Not so, according to
Trottier.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Adams) was already there, facing the shot. He's not in the
goal crease. He's allowed to stand there,'' the referee explained.
``Grant came out of the goal crease to stop the puck, and they ran
into each other. There was no intent to interfere with the
goaltender. That was my explanation to Grant.''
</P>
<P>
   Fuhr, still hopping mad, was not immediately available for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter anyway,'' quipped Blues enforcer Tony Twist.
``He was screaming so much, he lost his voice, and he can't talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes now have had four apparent goals against them
disallowed or waved off in the past three games. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0200EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
