<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 02:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6242 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LPGA-PING-1ST-AZR     03-19 0758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-PING-1ST-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COE-JONES CREATES BUZZ  
 TAKES LPGA LEAD DESPITE BEE SCARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - When it comes to the Standard Register PING, Dawn
Coe-Jones has a history of showing early speed. She led this
tournament after the first round in 1997 and was among the leaders
in Round 1 of the '96 and '93 tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   But Coe-Jones never ran faster than she did during Thursday's
opening round, when a swarm of bees flew into view as she
approached the 11th hole at Moon Valley Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I heard someone yell `Bees!' I turned around and
bolted for cover and started hiding in some lady's driveway,'' said
the Canadian, who is allergic to the insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Playing partner) Betsy (King) was tugging on the door of a
house, trying to get in there. She was as terrified as I was. Being
allergic to them, and having gone through all the shots to build up
all the immunities, well, I don't want to test that by getting
stung.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like they could make a movie out of all the bees,
but there was a lot of them. It was a brutal-looking group.
Scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Coe-Jones said she made a ``shaky'' 5-foot par at the 11th, then
went on to finish off her day with a bogey-free, 7-under 65 that
had the galleries buzzing. That left her 1 shot in front of Tracy
Hanson and Lori Kane, as scores were better than some had predicted
because of the substandard condition of the greens.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Coe-Jones said she benefited by Moon Valley's
problematic putting surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been struggling,'' said Coe-Jones, whose best finish in
five starts this season has been a tie for 31st. ``When the greens
are perfect and you don't make a birdie, you feel like the world
passed you by. But when they're not that good, it helps you because
you know it's not going to be a putting match.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the greens aren't that bad. You can make a putt on them.
Obviously, they're not what the superintendent would have liked.''
</P>
<P>
   That Coe-Jones led was not the biggest surprise of the day. She
has three top-10 finishes here, including a runner-up in '93 and a
tie for third in '92.
</P>
<P>
   No, the biggest shocker was defending champ Liselotte Neumann,
who was stung by an 82, which tied her for the high round of the
day. The Swede, who has a reputation as a rock-solid player,
suffered two double bogeys and closed out her day with four
straight bogeys. She was unavailable for comment, but her caddie,
Mark Scott, summed up the disaster well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad day at the office,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Several other players of note fared better. Last week's winner,
Juli Inkster, was in a star-studded group at 4 under. She was
joined by Karrie Webb, a two-time winner this year, and Laura
Davies, the four-time Standard Register PING champ.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not making any mistakes. When I miss, I'm not getting
hurt,'' said Inkster, who made just one bogey and closed with
back-to-back birdies.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, who is averaging an incredible 68.42 strokes per round
this season and is 41 under through her last nine rounds,
highlighted her day with a chip-in eagle at No. 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running on a lot of confidence,'' said the Australian, who
credits her improved play this year to a switch she made to
cross-handed putting.
</P>
<P>
   Davies also is feeling extremely good about her game and her
return to Moon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stood on the first tee, and I felt comfortable,'' said
Davies, who made a 15-foot eagle putt at the eighth hole. ``Last
week in Tucson, I stood on the first tee and thought, `God, I hope
I don't miss the cut.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Helen Alfredsson, who has five top-10 finishes in as many
events, also was among the red-numbered brigade, opening with a 69.
Scottsdale's Tina Barrett also carded that score.
</P>
<P>
   The shot of the day was recorded by Hanson, who holed out a
5-wood from 185 yards to eagle the par-4 sixth hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't particularly like the shot because it was fading,''
Hanson said. ``But two bounces and it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the pre-tournament favorites got out of the blocks on
a warm, sunny day. Annika Sorenstam, the two-time Player of the
Year, was at 72, along with Kelly Robbins and Scottsdale's Meg
Mallon. Hall of Famer Nancy Lopez also shot 72.
</P>
<P>
   There were others, such as LPGA Rookie of the Year Se Ri Pak,
who could no better than 74.
</P>
<P>
   And, obviously, the bees affected King much more than they did
Coe-Jones. The Hall of Famer from Scottsdale ended up with a 77.
Ouch!
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
