<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0041 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6247 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CACTUS-LOCKERROOM     03-19 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CACTUS-LOCKERROOM-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUMILIATION, HUMOR AT HEART OF ROOKIE-VET ERAN RELATION SHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX It drove Dante Powell to cross-dressing and Rod Beck to
singing Eddie Rabbitt hits.
</P>
<P>
   It's the rookie-veteran relationship, one of baseball's best
subplots because of the humor, drama and friendships that evolve.
The roots often can be traced to the spring training clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Seattle pitcher Ryan Anderson, who made the mistake
last season of feeling a little too confident after facing Mariners
veterans in batting practice for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dominated them,'' he told a reporter. ``I don't want to say
it, but I did.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the newspaper article was posted in the Peoria
Stadium clubhouse, with this note: ``I am the greatest. Just ask
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, outfielder Ken Griffey Jr. circulated a phony letter on
Mariners stationery and put it in Anderson's locker, along with a
case of baseballs. The letter read, ``From all the players. Would
you sign this case of baseballs? . . . We would be honored and
cherish it forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Gulp.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson should have sought advice from Chicago Cubs infielders
Mark Grace and Jeff Blauser.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old adage: Rookies are to be seen and not heard,''
said Grace, who broke in with the Cubs in 1988. ``I made sure I was
as quiet as a church mouse and minding my own business. I still got
my share of (expletive), but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Of his debut with Atlanta in 1987, Blauser said, ``My first
spring training, I had a corner locker in the clubhouse. And that's
where I stayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the changing face of the game has altered the
relationships between veterans and newcomers _ some rookies make
more money than their experienced peers _ it's still a given that
humiliation will be a part of a young player's career.
</P>
<P>
   For some, it comes at the team party. Beck was required to stand
up and sing Rabbitt's ``Driving My Life Away'' for his San
Francisco peers in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Was it difficult?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nah, after a few drinks, it's like karaoke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates made him sing again in '92, a season in which he
posted 17 saves and a 1.76 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I ain't singing. If I were a rookie this season, I'd
be Rookie of the Year.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His teammates didn't forget his bravado and, at the end of the
season, gave him ``this big . . . trophy to carry home on the
plane.''
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks rookie Powell, whose major league debut came with
San Francisco in 1997, returned to his clubhouse locker one day and
found that his suit had been replaced by a rather unattractive
dress. His Giants teammates insisted he wear it home, a journey
that included a stroll through San Francisco International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``People stared, but I tried to have fun with it,'' he said.
``It was this wool thing, with a big disco collar and happy faces
all over it. I tried to take it as a way of the team saying, `Yeah,
we like you.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, I haven't had it too bad. For the most part, you just
try to keep quiet and do your own thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace had the same philosophy, but it didn't keep him from being
the target of periodic verbal abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of it was good-natured, some wasn't,'' he said. ``A lot
of guys were rough. There were a few times I was like, `Man, if
this is the way it is in the big leagues, I'd like to go back to
Triple-A.' They berate you. You get absolutely no respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Blauser, ``You'd get treated like dirt. (The veterans) let
you know that you don't know very much about how to play the game
at this particular level. More than anything, they just let you
know that you're low man on the totem pole. The second you seem to
forget that, they're right there to put you back in your place.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all rookie-veteran relationships are based on humiliation.
Several rookies say they are benefiting from the experienced
players' guidance, from how to hit a changeup to how to conduct
yourself properly off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Most veterans recall players who took them under their wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dave Righetti and Jeff Brantley really took care of me and
showed me how things were supposed to be,'' Beck said. ``I really
appreciated that. I feel now like it's my turn to take care of the
younger guys. You pass it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Monetary benefits could be in store for rookies, especially when
it's time to go out to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't touch my wallet for four or five years,'' Beck said.
``I'd go to reach for it and get slapped.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Giants outfielder Stan Javier, ``When you're with a rookie,
you usually pay. It's not so much about salaries, though _ it's
about time spent in the league.''
</P>
<P>
   A rookie's first spring training and season is often memorable.
San Francisco pitcher Mark Gardner, who debuted with Montreal,
remembers the thrill of sharing space with players such as Hubie
Brooks, Bryn Smith and Tim Raines.
</P>
<P>
   ``These were guys I used to watch play, wanting to be in their
shoes, and now my locker is next to them,'' he said. ``It took a
while to get over the awe.''
</P>
<P>
   The awe factor seems less prominent these days. Maybe it's the
rookies' big signing bonuses, or a reflection of societal behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it is, veterans have noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed,'' Beck said. ``Some of the younger guys don't
necessarily respect the opinion of a player that's been around as
much.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Grace, ``Some of these first-round picks that come up for
the first time, they're being paid $2 million to sign and probably
make more money than half the veterans, so their attitude is, `Why
do I have to listen to these guys?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the reason is because they're older than you, and
they're wiser than you, and you can learn a lot from them, no
matter how much money you make. Unfortunately, everybody seems to
think that money is the status symbol. I've got news for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening, rookies?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
