<SLUG> BC-CAR-CYCLES-AMA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPERBIKE SCORING UNDER FIRE  
 WINNING NOT WORTH ENOUGH, RACERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Mat Mladin believes the American Motorcyclist
Association Superbike scoring system is a joke. He calls the format
antiquated and says it rewards consistency more than winning.
</P>
<P>
   Mladin isn't alone.
</P>
<P>
   Defending series champion Ben Bostrom, who greatly benefited
from the system Mladin is knocking, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mat's right,'' said Bostrom, who won the title on a Honda
without winning a single race. ``I was trying to win races last
year, but as soon as I saw the opportunity to win the championship,
I just sort of cruised.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Bostrom said he didn't think he deserved an asterisk
for capturing the crown without a trip into victory lane, he also
thought Mladin made a valid argument.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about who's winning each race,'' said Bostrom, who is
riding for Vance &AMP; Hines Ducati this season, which continues Sunday
with the AMA Cruise America Arizona Superbike Challenge at Phoenix
International Raceway. ``It's kind of who's winning the war in the
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``A great example is Doug Chandler. He's a three-time champion
because he's a smart rider. He's riding to finish every race. He
always tries to finish in the top five. That's why he's won so many
championships. You can't take anything away from the guy for that.
. . . But I also believe that the top three finishers should be
awarded a substantial amount of points because they rode hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Bostrom won't get any arguments from Mladin, who narrowly missed
winning the season-opening Daytona 200 two weeks ago, finishing
second to winner Miguel Duhamel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our system doesn't promote 100 percent hard racing,'' Mladin
said. ``And I don't think fans are getting everything they should
be getting. We want to put on good shows, but we also have to hold
back a little bit to try and win the championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see more of a point system where you win a bunch
of races, have a couple of bad races and still be there at the end,
rather than something that promotes finishing fourth and fifth.''
</P>
<P>
   At present, riders receive 35 points for a win and 32 for
runner-up. Third through 10th place awards 30, 28, 26, 25, 24, 23,
22 and 21 points respectively. Mladin and Bostrom think the point
differential is slight, meaning it's more difficult to make up a
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, however, disagrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the system is fine the way it is,'' Chandler said.
``Ben kind of did what I've done, which is just take the finishes
and go on to next week. He didn't win a thing, but he was there all
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not all the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bostrom's worst race last season was at PIR, where he finished
ninth and never mounted a threat against Ducati's Anthony Gobert.
</P>
<P>
   Bostrom and Gobert are teammates this season. Bostrom, however,
won't gain a huge advantage with Gobert sharing the same pit stall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our riding styles are so different, we can't even share
information,'' Bostrom said.
</P>
<P>
   Bostrom appears to be on a dominating bike. Although Ducati's
best finish at Daytona was Bostrom's fourth place, all four
previous winners at PIR have ridden Ducati's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a weird deal how I ended up at Ducati and not
with Honda this year,'' said Bostrom, 24, who lives in Granada
Hills, Calif. ``There were negotiating troubles with the (Honda)
management, and some people got upset. They ended up closing the
door on me there.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's no hard feelings. I like both bikes. And my
brother (Eric) ended up getting my Honda ride, which is beneficial
for him, and it makes me happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I ended up getting Thomas Stevens' (Ducati) ride because
he retired and there just happened to be an opening for me.
Everything worked out.'' &QL; 
Note &QL; 
Bostrom and Gobert will sign autographs tonight from 7 to 9 at
Cycle-Moto Ducati, at 330 E. Southern in Mesa. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
