<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S FLANNIGAN MAKES THE GRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the end, McDonald's didn't appeal to LaCresha
Flannigan.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the choice of dropping out of UCLA and possibly
taking a job at the fast-food outlet, Flannigan chose to stay. She
took her studies seriously, got out of academic probation and
improved on the basketball court.
</P>
<P>
   She won a starting position earlier this season and has helped
her team into the Sweet 16 for the first time since 1992. The
Bruins (25-7) meet Colorado State (33-2) in the West Regional at
the Sports Arena on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``There never has been a kid who's come so far as a sophomore _
athletically, academically, socially,'' UCLA associate head coach
Willette White said. ``She could've gone back to San Bernardino,
but she made the choice to stay here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``School was a big adjustment,'' Flannigan said. ``It was very
different from high school.''
</P>
<P>
   At San Bernardino, Flannigan was the star, both on and off the
court. Off the court, she was the oldest in her family of one
sister and five half-brothers.
</P>
<P>
   Since her father, Darryl Flannigan, raised her as a single
father, LaCresha took on the role of principal caregiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always there for their needs,'' Darryl said. ``If they
wanted time, she'd comfort them. 'Cresha's a real sweet person.
She's so nice. I work with a lot of teen-age kids. 'Cresha's
different. She lives life and doesn't let it affect her.''
</P>
<P>
   As for LaCresha's needs, Darryl took care of those. He taught
her basketball, listened to and held her when she needed
comforting, helped her with homework and choosing a college.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, she scored the points, led San Bernardino into the
playoffs and attracted UCLA's interest. This was a big deal to
Darryl, for no Flannigan had ever gone to a major university
before.
</P>
<P>
   But LaCresha had some academic problems. She needed to pass the
Scholastic Achievement Test and graduate with at least a 2.5 GPA.
With her dad's prodding, LaCresha accomplished it.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   Flannigan was the only freshman on the basketball team, so she
had no one going through the rough times with her. Plus, her family
wasn't there.
</P>
<P>
   People offered help. White, in particular, sent her to tutors,
academic coordinators and counselors. Nothing worked because
Flannigan didn't let them.
</P>
<P>
   On the court, she played about 10 minutes a game.
</P>
<P>
   At home, things were getting worse. One brother was seriously
injured in a car accident. Flannigan's father also had difficulty
adjusting to her absence. He wanted her to come home, but she
refused.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad was always there to fix things,'' she said. ``Now, he
couldn't. He was treating me like a kid. I needed to grow up. In
some ways, I shut him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Her grades slipped and she went onacademic probation.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were trying to help me, even though half the
time I didn't care,'' Flannigan said. ``In some ways, I'm going
through all this stuff for what? I love basketball, but I wasn't
playing. I wasn't working hard anyway. What was I here for?
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up on myself. I didn't want to deal with it. I didn't
know if I was willing to. I sat around and wasted a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, White came to her and told her if she didn't
improve academically, she would be kicked out of school. She went
home and saw some of her former teammates. They were working at
McDonald's. Some already were parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like everybody at UCLA, they put everything on the line
to get me here,'' Flannigan said, ``and they were doing everything
to keep me here. I should do the effort. I didn't want to end up
like that. It had to smack me in the face.''
</P>
<P>
   Since she already was on probation, Flannigan had to maintain a
B average in summer school, then have a strong fall quarter to get
off probation. She did it. Now, she happily bounds into practice,
telling White how excited she is at her latest A or B.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, I came with the attitude of taking care of
business,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Flannigan won a starting spot after Thanksgiving and has become
the second-leading scorer, averaging 14.1 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the highs and lows,'' White said. ``She is very
talented and very intelligent. Once you've seen her use (her
talents), you get a sense of joy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
