<SLUG> BC-HKN-SUNS-ROBINSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS' ROBINSON REWARDED FOR `D' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ He has guarded Houston center Hakeem Olajuwon, checked
Milwaukee small forward Glenn Robinson and defended a host of power
forwards from Denver's Antonio McDyess to Utah's Karl Malone.
</P>
<P>
   He's even taken a turn on the Los Angeles Lakers' 21-year-old
swingman, Kobe Bryant. Then there was the time Suns Coach Danny
Ainge assigned him to shut down Seattle point guard Gary Payton in
the fourth quarter of a game in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   That's an opponent for each of the five positions at least once
this season.
</P>
<P>
   So don't be surprised to see the Suns' 6-foot-10 forward,
Clifford Robinson, hounding anybody from playmaker Mookie Blaylock
to shooter Steve Smith to the towering Dikembe Mutombo tonight when
the Suns make their third stop on a four-game trip and play the
Atlanta Hawks at the Georgia Dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we'd be without him,'' Ainge said last
week.
</P>
<P>
   In deep trouble, that's where.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Robinson, who re-signed with the club this season for
a pro-rated portion of $3 million, the Suns are struggling at a
game above the .500 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge brought Robinson off the bench early in abbreviated season
because he wanted depth behind starting power forward Tom Gugliotta
and center Luc Longley.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first month of the season, Robinson emerged as one
of the top candidates for the annual Sixth Man Award, which goes to
the NBA's top reserve. Phoenix forward Danny Manning won it a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Robinson's candidacy may lose steam. Not because of his
play but because Ainge finally decided after the Suns had lost four
of six games that he could not afford to keep Robinson _ and the
athleticism and intensity he brings _ out of the starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 32, has started the last four games, scoring 20 points
or more in three.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixth Man Award requires that a player come off the bench in
the majority of his team's games, and so far Robinson would
qualify, with only eight starts in the first 23 games. But the more
effective is he starting, the less chance he'll have of going back
to the sixth-man role.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Robinson doesn't return to the bench, he might wind up
as a candidate for another top award _ Defensive Player of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the award goes to a player such as Mutombo who blocks a
lot of shots, or a small player such as Payton who racks up a lot
of steals. But a case can be made for Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't have overwhelming statistics in either category, but
his versatility as a defender is unmatched. Unfortunately, he can
only play one man at a time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had him on Kobe when we played the Lakers,'' Ainge said.
``He was doing a great job on him, and then I had to put him on
Shaq (O'Neal), and all of a sudden Kobe went off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cliff has guarded Gary Payton, Hakeem, Scottie (Pippen), he
held (Cleveland's) Shawn Kemp to two points in the second half.
Whoever needs to be guarded, he can guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's defense against Houston's Olajuwon was a key to a
Phoenix victory right before this trip started, limiting him to
5-of-14 shooting. In the first game on the road, he shut down
Milwaukee's Robinson, limiting him to 12 points on 4-of-11
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   In the Seattle victory, Ainge put Robinson on Payton to take
away one of Seattle's favorite ploys _ running its offense through
Payton on the low post.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defense is always going to be part of my game,'' Robinson
said.
</P>
<P>
   He is the Suns' top shot blocker with 21 in 23 games, and he's
second to Jason Kidd with 34 steals. But Robinson also has been a
key piece of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   He's averaging 14.7 points a game, behind only Gugliotta and
Kidd. His 50.8 field-goal percentage and 19-of-43 shooting from
three-point range rank him among the league's leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been huge for us,'' Ainge said. ``Without him, we'd have
no chance.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
