<HEADLINE>
BRIERE MOVED TO MINORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ The way things had been going,  &UR; Daniel Briere
figured it was simply a matter of time before the Coyotes benched
him. Coach  &UR; Jim
 &UR; Schoenfeld did the honors Thursday night, making the rookie center
a healthy scratch for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   Skating instead against the St. Louis Blue were wingers  &UR; Louie
 &UR; DeBrusk (a healthy scratch the previous night in Detroit),  &UR; Shane
Doan (returning from a forearm injury) and newly acquired  &UR; Brian
Noonan, who signed with the club Wednesday as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Briere? He was sent back to Springfield of the American Hockey
League after the game along with teammate Tavis Hanson. Apparently,
Briere grabbed his luggage off the team bus and did not accompany
the Coyotes back to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   His name has been linked to various trade rumors. One, in fact,
has him as Montreal's No. 1 choice in return for the Canadiens'
 &UR; Vincent Damphousse, whom the Coyotes reportedly have been coveting
for several days now leading up to Tuesday's NHL trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in Montreal, so I know how it works,'' Briere said
earlier Thursday. ``Ninety-five percent of the rumors aren't true
anyway, and a lot of them start there. It's the first time I've
heard them about me, but I'm sure it won't be the last time.'' &QL; 
Briere's ice time has melted in recent games. Wednesday against the
Red Wings, he had only six shifts totaling 4 minutes and 27
seconds. He saw the benching coming well before he got to St.
Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of room in the lineup right now, and some
other guys are playing well,'' Briere said. ``That's one of the
reasons why I lost my job on the second line earlier. But there's
nothing I can do about it. I can't change the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, I'll have another chance to get out there, and when
I do, I'll give the team a spark like I have before.''
</P>
<P>
   After the All-Star break, that's exactly what Briere did
following a reduction in ice time. He racked up two goals and eight
assists in a 13-game span, only to fall into a slump the past month
and lose more shifts. &QL; 
Thanks, no thanks
</P>
<P>
   In a surprise move making the rounds around the league Thursday,
the Chicago Blackhawks decided to waive a handful of veteran
players, including heavyweight  &UR; Bob Probert and defensemen  &UR; Doug
Zmolek and  &UR; Dave
 &UR; Manson, a former Coyote.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager  &UR; Bob Murray clearly is trying to send a message
to his underachieving club _ and to other teams as well, because he
wants to force a series of trades.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith said he wasn't particularly
interested, but he did say he'd been busy talking to several teams
about potential deals before Tuesday's 1 p.m. deadline. ``I've done
a lot of talking, but I don't know if we'll get anything out of
it,'' Smith said. &QL; 
JR staying put
</P>
<P>
   Responding to an ESPN report that star center  &UR; Jeremy Roenick
won't be back in a Coyotes uniform next season, Smith said he had
no plans whatsoever to move the talented and popular assistant
captain.
</P>
<P>
   He made it clear Roenick wasn't going anywhere ``before'' the
end of the season, but his answer was just a tad vague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not spoken to a single team about Jeremy Roenick,''
Smith said. ``Every year these rumors come up and start out East.
But whatever we do in the next four days, Jeremy Roenick won't be
involved.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
