A6258 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-A     03-19 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILKEY SHOWS AGILITY, SPEED IN RETURN FROM CALF INJURY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ So far, so good was  &UR; Bernard Gilkey's assessment of his
first day back in the Diamondbacks' outfield since March 7, when he
left a game because of a cramp in his left calf muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Gilkey started in right field, walked once and doubled in three
other plate appearances and scored twice in Arizona's 11-6 victory
over Oakland on Thursday at Tucson Electric Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went well,'' Gilkey said. ``I try not to focus on it (the
leg).''
</P>
<P>
   The leg was tested early when Gilkey walked with two outs and
then scored from first base on a double to right-center by  &UR; Dale
Sveum.
</P>
<P>
   He felt his agility was high as he pursued fly balls along the
foul line.
</P>
<P>
   And considering he had been sidelined for almost two weeks,
Gilkey was satisfied with his day at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about timing and rhythm and I'm getting there,
particularly on the change-ups,'' he said. ``I'm trying to take it
one day at a time.'' &QL; 
Benes wins second &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Andy Benes made his fourth start and said it was
his best, despite giving up a two-run homer to  &UR; Olmedo Saenz in the
first inning. After the home run, Benes, who won his second game,
retired seven men in a row and 10 of the last 11 he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had pretty good command after the first inning. I'm making
good progress, stretching it out,'' increasing the amount of
innings, Benes said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter: ``That's as sharp as he's been all
spring.'' &QL; 
There he goes again &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Versatility,  &UR; Andy Fox, was in top form, starting at
shortstop for the first time, moving to second base and finishing
the day at third.
</P>
<P>
   He started at six positions in 1998 but not at short, although
he did play briefly there on a couple of occasions late in games.
</P>
<P>
   While in the New York Yankees' organization, Fox played quite a
bit at short, and some of the Diamondbacks' officials believe that
it is his best position.
</P>
<P>
   He said it doesn't matter to him where he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot more things to worry about at short, but I feel
comfortable there. I've been working there off and on during
camp,'' Fox said. ``I just try to make it as simple as I can _
catch the ball and throw the ball.'' &QL; 
Olson returns &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Closer  &UR; Gregg Olson returned to game action for the first time
in about a week after battling tendinitis in his right wrist. He
pitched two-thirds of an inning, walking two, giving up a hit and a
run. He had thrown on the side on three occasions since receiving a
cortisone shot Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wrist was fine, but it was a bit of a struggle out
there,'' said Olson, who recorded 30 saves in 1998. ``I've never
been able to get into a decent game mode in the spring. I made a
few good pitches and I'm getting better. I still have 2{ weeks to
improve.'' &QL; 
Short stops &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Left-handed reliever  &UR; Brian Shouse was hit on the ear flap of
his batting helmet by a pitch from Oakland left-hander  &UR; Mark
Holzemer, but remained in the game. What helped Shouse was that the
pitch was a curveball and not a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander  &UR; Amaury Telemaco, sidelined because of tendinitis
in his right shoulder, will resume throwing on the side today, but
only long toss. If all goes well, he will graduate to a stint or
two in the bullpen, then a game.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander  &UR; Omar Daal will start this afternoon's (1:05)
split-squad game against the Chicago White Sox at TEP, and
left-hander  &UR; Brian Anderson will take the mound for the 7:05
nightcap against Colorado. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
