r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LPGA-ALFREDSSON-A     03-19 0765
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-ALFREDSSON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNAFRAID TO SPEAK HER MIND  
 ALFREDSSON OFTEN CRITICAL BUT LIKES U.S. GOLF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Frankness. Bald truth. Opinion. Sometimes, she even
talks about her round of golf. ``Golfweek's'' Brian Hewitt wrote
last year, ``She's fluent in four languages: Swedish, English, Body
and Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's Helen Alfredsson is anything but boring.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting a 3-under 69 in the opening round of the Standard
Register PING at Moon Valley Country Club on Thursday, she was
asked who should captain the European squad in the 2000 Solheim Cup
at Loch Lomond Golf Club in Scotland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, myself, of course,'' the 34-year-old from Goteborg said,
standing and throwing her hand behind her head in a pose. ``We'd be
rockin' and rollin'.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she was on the selection board, she said, ``No,
I'm never on boards. I just give opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Welch's Circle K Championship last week in Tucson,
she criticized former LPGA Commissioner Jim Ritts in a column for
``Golf'' ``World'' for passing through with misguided enthusiasm
and using the tour as a steppingstone.
</P>
<P>
   She also took issue with Ritts for calling the new tournament in
Naples, Fla., one of the tour's better events, when the
infrastructure encircling the course was a sea of construction and
not event-ready.
</P>
<P>
   A reader wrote that she's lucky to be allowed in the country.
</P>
<P>
   To which she said, ``I'm lucky Jim Ritts is not in the
immigration office.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she added, ``It may not have served any purpose to write
it. But I had had it. I love what I do. I see the LPGA as an
organization that does so many things for so many people. I'm not
vicious. I'm honest.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked to comment Thursday on hard greens filled with ``poa
annua'' and patchwork at Moon Valley, she threw another curve.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a little bumpy, but I don't know why people made out
they're terrible,'' she said. ``On four- to five-footers, I had a
couple high jump. But it's the case for everybody. There's no
reason to get upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``You become more spoiled when you come over here (from Europe).
Everything is so great. The courses are so much better. When we go
back home, we kind of laugh at the difference. I get tired of
complaining. You don't get a lot out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfredsson, fellow Swedes Anika Sorenstam and defending
tournament champion Lisolette Neumann, England's Laura Davies and
Australia's Karrie Webb have led a growing foreign invasion that
truly makes weekly LPGA events international.
</P>
<P>
   The European tour, which Alfredsson led in money earnings last
year while competing in just five events, is viewed as a poor
stepsister.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wish is we were more together,'' said Alfredsson, who won
two events and enjoyed her most productive LPGA season with
$471,859 in winnings. ``It's a great steppingstone for here. The
new LPGA Futures Tour, with the top three finishers getting tour
cards, is also a good steppingstone for European players. But it
also takes away from the ELPGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the good of women's golf, we need to nurture the European
tour. But we need to protect (tournament fields) here, too. It's a
dilemma. We need to find a way where everybody wins. This tour has
been great to us foreigners. And European events would love to have
more Americans come over.''
</P>
<P>
   She also holds opinions as to why the growth of the LPGA Tour
has outdistanced its European counterpart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love Europe. It's my home. But it hasn't had the same pace
as here. You have all the top players in the world here at any
given event. In Europe, you haven't had that,'' she said. ``Being
an athlete is a big thing here. In Europe, you played amateur golf
and then went home and had families. It's still that way more than
it is here.''
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line, she said, is that it's hard anywhere for female
athletes to be taken as seriously as men.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are too rough, you're wrong. If you're not, then you're
wishy-washy. Even for us _ and we're much bigger than Europe _
we're still fighting it. Hopefully, the perception will change
through you guys (the media). You'll see there is great golf being
played, and it's not just bumping it 200 yards out there and then
another shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hitting great shots out here. Last year's Solheim Cup
helped because we played at Muirfield Village, an established
course. We were hitting the shots necessary for the certain pin
placements. It surprised a lot of people, even some people who
follow us.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
