<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NOTEBOOK-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY NAMED CAPTAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Two major announcements concerning the 2000 Solheim
Cup were made Thursday at Moon Valley Country Club, just a wedge
shot away from the home owned by  &UR; Karsten Solheim, for whom the
biennial matches are named.
</P>
<P>
   The first involved  &UR; Pat Bradley, who was selected to succeed
 &UR; Judy
 &UR; Rankin as team captain when the Americans defend the Cup against
the Europeans on Oct. 6-8 at Loch Lomond Golf Club in Glasgow,
Scotland. Bradley had been reported as a strong candidate for
captain, as was another Hall of Famer,  &UR; Patty Sheehan.
</P>
<P>
   The second involved a change in format, which now will feature
eight foursome matches, six football matches and 12 singles.
Effectively, that change reduces the total points from 28 to 26.
The format change was developed to ensure that each day's
competition is concluded in available daylight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to continue the standard of excellence and winning
tradition set by Judy,  &UR; JoAnne (Carner) and  &UR; Kathy (Whitworth),''
Bradley said of her predecessors. ``I am looking forward to the
coming 19 months as we prepare for Scotland.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley played on three Solheim Cup teams, whereas Sheehan
competed on four. Bradley, however, has senior ranking, as she is
47. Sheehan is 42. Bradley's record in the Solheim Cup was 2-5-1,
although she played a pivotal role in the U.S victory in 1990,
going 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it came down to the two of us,'' Sheehan said. ``They
had to pick one of us gray hairs or the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't disappointed by the selection. It's time for Pat to
do it, and I know my time will come.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States leads the trans-Atlantic matches, 4-1. One
European praised the selection of Bradley, who is known as a fierce
competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She deserves it,'' said  &UR; Laura Davies, the four-time Standard
Register PING champ. ``She will be a great captain; she's still a
great player.'' &QL; 
How Swede she is &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Swedish Coach  &UR; Pia Nilsson, who once played golf for Arizona
State, was at Moon Valley meeting with her troops. Her visit will
last through next week's Dinah Shore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be here helping the team work on their games,'' Nilsson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Told the Swedes don't need any help, Nilsson laughed and said,
``Maybe they can teach me something.''
</P>
<P>
   Six of the 12 Swedes who have LPGA cards are among the top 30
money winners this season, including  &UR; Helen Alfredsson (No. 4),
 &UR; Catrin
 &UR; Nilsmark (No. 7),  &UR; Liselotte Neumann (No. 11),  &UR; Annika Sorenstam
(No. 12),  &UR; Maria Hjorth (No. 24) and  &UR; Charlotta Sorenstam (No.
30). &QL; 
Warding off disaster &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wendy Ward, the former ASU All-American, stumbled out of the
gate but made a fantastic finish for a 70 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was blocking everything right with my driver, but I finally
got it figured out and started hitting some good shots,'' Ward
said. ``But it was a tough start, being 3 over after five holes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who finished third in this tournament as an amateur in
1995, got on track for six birdies to offset one more bogey. She
was especially on target going down the stretch, with birdies at
Nos. 12, 13, 14 and 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``The little birdie run saved me,'' she said, sighing. &QL; 
All the way from Italy &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Silvia Cavalleri came all the way from Milano, Italy, to
attempt to qualify on Monday for the Standard Register PING. And as
it worked out, her 73 was good enough to get one of two spots in
the 144-player field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels so good to finally get in (an LPGA event),'' said
Cavalleri, who had competed unsuccessfully in three other Monday
qualifiers. ``It's been hard on me, to not have a card and come all
the way from Italy just to do all this traveling.''
</P>
<P>
   But she was feeling pretty good after shooting a 71 in the
opening round. Despite her failures in qualifying school, Cavalleri
can play. She won the U.S. Amateur in 1997, beating  &UR; Robin Burke _
 &UR; Jackie Burke's wife _ in the final. She has played in one other
LPGA tournament, the 1998 Australian Ladies Open, where she
finished 24th.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
