<SLUG> BC-BKC-WEST-IOWA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA GOES OUT SWINGING IN LOSS  
 EMOTION HIGH IN COACH'S LAST GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - His players went down fighting, at least at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Davis' team threw its best punch at Connecticut with no time
remaining in the first half, not the way he wants to remember his
last game as coach of the Iowa Hawkeyes.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut's 78-68 victory Thursday night in an NCAA Midwest
Regional semifinal game at America West Arena was the end of the
Davis era after 13 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   You have to feel for a guy who has been forced out after 269
victories and nine NCAA Tournament appearances, including reaching
the Sweet 16 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the game started, Iowa Athletic Director Bob Bowlsby
was again having to explain why he wasn't renewing the contract of
the winningest basketball coach in the school's history and why he
didn't congratulate the team after its 82-72 victory over Arkansas
in the second round of the regional.
</P>
<P>
   Bowlsby said he stayed away because he had been ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no intention of snubbing Tom or the team,'' Bowlsby
said. ``I couldn't be prouder. Tom and I communicated through the
season. Considering the circumstances, I thought we got along very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   They got along better than the Huskies and Hawkeyes did late in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   First, with seven seconds left, Iowa senior forward Jess Settles
threw down Edmund Saunders under the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after Jacob Jaacks hit two free throws with six seconds
left to pull the Hawkeyes within 40-35 at halftime, guard Joey
Range threw a forearm at Khalid El-Amin as the Connecticut point
guard ran off the court.
</P>
<P>
   Players from both teams had words at the center of the floor as
they were leaving the court. Then, Jaacks and El-Amin had to be
restrained.
</P>
<P>
   Referee Joe Silvester and his crew watched several replays of
the incident at the end of the half but decided not to take any
action.
</P>
<P>
   That had to upset Connecticut Coach Jim Calhoun, who didn't seem
to find a call against the Huskies he agreed with.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, it was obvious Iowa wasn't finished.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes rallied to tie the score at 53 on Guy Rucker's
5-foot jumper with 10:08 remaining. Then, they watched Connecticut
All-America forward Richard Hamilton show why Suns executives Jerry
Colangelo, Brian Colangelo and Dick Van Arsdale were glued to his
every move.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, a 6-6 junior, is expected to turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, meanwhile, would like to coach again, with the Marquette
job being his first choice.
</P>
<P>
   He better clean out his office in a hurry. Iowa fans think
Bowlsby has offered the job to Southwest Missouri State's Steve
Alford, who also has taken his team to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   He needs to do better than that at Iowa or might not have a
fighting chance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0213EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0053 </DOCNO>
