<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-IOWA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN DOWNS IOWA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ All season, critics of the University of Connecticut
basketball team said the one weakness the Huskies had was a
vulnerability against strong, physical teams that like to bang
bodies.
</P>
<P>
   In as tough a battle as they have had all season, the Huskies
needed all of their skill, all of their depth, and all of their
heart before pulling away in the final three minutes and recording
a 78-68 victory over Iowa Thursday &UR;  &LR; night in the West Regional
semifinals before a sellout crowd at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Although coach Jim Calhoun's team came into the tournament out
of the physical Big East, the No. 1-seeded Huskies had seldom seen
teams with the bulk and temperament of fifth-seeded Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (31-2) will now face 10th-seeded Gonzaga in
Saturday's regional final in an attempt to gain their first Final
Four appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The game was physical from the start with the Hawkeyes (20-10)
fighting to not only continue their season, but to extend the
coaching career of Tom Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the former Boston College and Stanford coach, was told at
the start of the season by Iowa officials that his contract would
not be extended.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with the passion of a team fighting for their coach, the
Hawkeyes did not flinch under the relentless pressure of UConn,
which was led by Richard Hamilton's 24 points and Khalid-El Amin's
21.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was as physical a game as we have had all year,'' said
Calhoun, now 40 minutes away from his first Final Four. ``Our
football team is going (Division) 1A, but I think we started
tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkeyes (20-10), coming into Thursday &UR;  &LR; night's game as
12-point underdogs, didn't back down.
</P>
<P>
   Not at the start when they began firing away from long range,
matching the Huskies shove for shove and basket for basket.
</P>
<P>
   Not at the end of the first half when Iowa's Joey Range let an
elbow fly at El-Amin's head that precipitated a shoving and staring
contest as the half ended, with the three game officials studying
tapes to see if any punches were thrown (which would have meant
automatic ejections).
</P>
<P>
   None were, but the tone of the game was set for the final 20
minutes. ``We were playing a little sporadic,'' said El-Amin, who
was the key factor in UConn forging a 40-35 halftime lead. ``We
weren't running the plays we should have been running, but they
forced us into doing some things.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun and the players also talked at halftime about keeping
their composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't going to do any talking,'' said Hamilton, who
scored 6 straight points in a two-minute stretch in the second half
that allowed the Huskies to break from a 53-53 tie to a 59-53 lead
they never relinquished. ``We said we would let the scoreboard do
the talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it wasn't until the final minute, with Iowa out of
timeouts and running out of time, that the Hawkeyes finally
conceded the end of their season and the end of Davis's career in
Iowa City.
</P>
<P>
   When the game ended, Hamilton, who had been physically punished
much of the evening, walked over and had a few words with Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him I admired the way he coached,'' said Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck in the tournament,'' Davis replied. ``Keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday &UR;  &LR; night, in a pressure-filled, physical confrontation,
the Huskies answered the question about their toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that takes care of that question,'' said Calhoun with
a laugh.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
