<HEADER>
A6266 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-OHIOSTATE-AUBURN-     03-19 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OHIO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENN AUTHORS OHIO ST. WIN 
</HEADLINE>
 STATE-AUBURN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Jim O'Brien didn't even need to look at the
scoreboard to know the gravity of the situation. He knew he had
just seen the first ripples of a large wave that had the capability
of turning into a patented Auburn tsunami.
</P>
<P>
   Scoonie Penn had four personal fouls and there was still more
than 10 minutes to play. Too bad. A man has to do what a man has to
do. Auburn had just scored 7 straight points to take a 52-46 lead.
It looked like the start of something very big.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could feel the game slipping away, and I wasn't going to
lose with Scoonie sitting on the bench,'' said O'Brien, whose
decision to reinsert the team's physical and spiritual leader will
probably go down in Ohio State hoop history as the smartest Buckeye
coaching decision since Fred Taylor decided to recruit Jerry Lucas
and John Havlicek more than 40 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   What Scoonie Penn did in those final 10 minutes was make sure
his team would not lose. He started off with an immediate three and
he kept making big play after big play, scoring 13 points after his
return as the Buckeyes advanced to a date in the Final Eight with a
72-64 victory over the No. 1-seeded Tigers Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 23,898 fans at Thompson-Boling Arena saw why the
5-foot-9-inch guard from Salem, Mass., and Boston College was the
media choice as the Big Ten Player of the Year. Penn scored 19 of
his game-high 26 points in the second half while playing 36
turnover-less minutes against a pressing team of magnificent
athletes. He was ably abetted by the slithery Michael Redd, who
scored 22 and who battled the rebounding maniacs of Auburn all
night, finishing with 10 very hard-earned boards, but there was
little doubt that the key man for the Buckeyes was Penn.
</P>
<P>
   He numbered four 3-pointers among his nine baskets. It was the
best he has shot since taking a scary fall against Penn State Feb.
27. He had only shot 7 for 27 last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've felt since the Penn State game,'' he
said. ``In the second half, I felt that when I put it up it was
going in.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the four personals, Penn said he didn't have time to
worry about that. ``I have a lot of faith in myself,'' he said. ``I
didn't think I'd do anything stupid. I thought I played pretty
loose out there.'
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State is living out a fairy tale that keeps adding new
chapters. This is a team that was 1-15 in the Big Ten last season
and which has had only one primary addition _ a certain 5-9 point
guard. ``I watched this team last year and I thought what they
needed most was leadership,'' Penn pointed out. A few more points
were a nice bonus.
</P>
<P>
   The fearsome Tigers are a renowned offensive rebounding team,
but the Buckeyes kept themselves from annihilation in that
category. This required a tremendous effort from all concerned, but
O'Brien has come to expect that kind of performance as a given.
Redd and Penn are the stars, but the others are not afraid to get
their hands dirty.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State led it by 5 (31-26) at the half in a fast-paced
opening 20 minutes. But when forward Jason Singleton joined center
Ken Johnson and Penn on the bench with 12:26 left, O'Brien was down
three starters and Auburn was ready to capitalize. When Doc
Robinson hit a jumper in the lane to make it 52-46, O'Brien made
his fateful decision to bring back Scoonie, four fouls or no four
fouls.
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied as late as 61-all on a Scott Pohlman
3-pointer, but a foul shot by Brian Brown and two by master slasher
Redd put the Buckeyes up by 3. When Robinson air-balled a three,
Scoonie made him pay with a 14-foot right baseline swisher. The
coup came when Brown came up with a steal and hit a streaking
Singleton with a behind-the-back pass and the forward jammed it
home for a 68-61 lead with 1:01 to go.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, of course, that no one really gets to celebrate.
The Final Eight is nice, but the Final Four is the real goal, and
so both O'Brien and St. John's mentor Mike Jarvis were planning
late-night tape sessions.
</P>
<P>
   The tape of this one can wait. But when O'Brien does look at it,
he will appreciate his point guard even more. Scoonie Penn put on
one amazing show here Thursday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
