<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 02:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6268 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-GONZAGA-FLORIDA-B     03-19 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-GONZAGA-FLORIDA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONZAGA SAGA CONTINUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ OK. So it's not quite midnight for Cinderella and
Gonzaga still has its magic slippers on in the Big Dance.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulldogs, who have made March Madness and the NCAA
Tournament their mission, took another step Thursday &UR;  &LR; night with a
pulsating 73-72 win over sixth-seeded Florida in a West Regional
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga is the first 10th-seeded team to reach the Regional
final since Providence lost to Arizona in the South Regional in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The hero for Gonzaga (28-6) was sophomore forward Casey Calvary,
whose tip-in of a missed shot by Quentin Hall with 4.4 seconds left
sent his team into Saturday's final against No. 1 seed UConn, a
78-68 winner Thursday &UR;  &LR; night over No. 5 seed Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had called the play for either Matt (Santangelo) or Richie
(Frahm),'' said Calvary, who scored 12 points and was one of three
Bulldogs in double figures. ``But when I saw Hall go to the basket
I just tried to get near to the boards. I just stuck my hand up. It
happened to hit it. I had no idea it was going in.''
</P>
<P>
   After a series of power surges for most of the evening, the
final minutes turned into an exchange of baskets _ and of leads.
</P>
<P>
   With Gonzaga ahead, 68-67, Florida freshman Mike Miller drove to
the basket to give the Gators a 69-68 lead with 1:38 left.
</P>
<P>
   Santangelo then countered with a drive, drawing the fifth foul
on Gators center Udonis Haslem with 1:12 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   After a timeout, Santangelo missed the first free throw and made
the second to again tie the score at 69.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Stolt then hit a 3-pointer from the top of the left key to
give the Gators a 72-69 lead with 45.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga then called a timeout to set up its strategy, and Jeremy
Eaton put in a layup with 19.7 seconds left to cut the Gators' lead
to 72-71.
</P>
<P>
   Then on the inbounds play, Florida's Brent Wright was called for
traveling as he attempted to call a timeout.
</P>
<P>
   With 15.4 seconds left, Gonzaga had its last chance to continue
its dream season.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of false starts, Hall, the Bulldogs' 5-foot-8
inch senior guard, drove the lane and threw up a shot that rolled
off the rim, but then Calvary tipped it in for the winner.
</P>
<P>
   For Florida (22-9) it was a bitter ending to a semisweet season
that had seen the young Gators and coach Billy Donovan advance to
the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of false starts in which they fell behind by as
many as 13 points in the first half and 10 in the second half, the
Gators cut into Gonzaga's lead with their speciality _ an onslaught
of 3-point shots.
</P>
<P>
   The Gators, who led the Southeastern Conference in 3-point
shots, seemed to make a final statement when Stolt, a 6-9 senior
forward (16 points, 4 for 7 on 3-pointers), popped in his trifecta
with 45.7 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   But destiny was not wearing a Gator uniform on this evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year when we beat Tulsa, Mississippi State, and Clemson
up in Alaska, I knew this was possible,'' said Gonzaga coach Dan
Monson, who earlier this week had said that while his team
appreciated its Cinderella tag, it was not ready to give up its
magic slippers and stop dancing. ``This far? I don't know. But
we're certainly good enough to be here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0222EST &QL; 
