<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 02:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6270 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-STJOHN'S-MARYLAND     03-19 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHN'S-MARYLAND-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST. JOHN'S RUNS OVER MARYLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ They've got to play these games and not
merely dissect and analyze them before they unfold. Exhibit A: St.
John's 76, Maryland 62 in the first game of an NCAA South Regional
doubleheader at massive Thompson-Boling Arena Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone but everyone said this was an even game. Might go three
OTs. Might last a week. What no one forecast was St. John's being
up by 26 (56-30) with 10:58 left. What no one forecast was St.
John's scoring the final 20 points of the first half, or a 21-2
Maryland second-half run getting them no closer than 9 (58-49).
</P>
<P>
   With dynamic freshman Erick Barkley (24 points, 9 assists) at
the controls, with the frontcourt of Ron Artest, Tyrone Grant, and
Lavor Postell controlling the inside and with Bootsy Thornton (17
points) doing a little bit of everything, the pride of Jamaica
(L.I.) took apart Maryland with a scintillating first half and did
what was necessary to preserve a victory that sends coach Mike
Jarvis into the Elite Eight for the first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not normally lost for words,'' said Jarvis, ``but this was
a great, great effort. The first half was just incredible,
especially on the defensive end. Until they told me coming off the
floor, I didn't know we had a 20-point run. I had no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   This is unlike any St. John's team you've ever seen. After a
half-century of treating the fast break like the bubonic plague,
Jarvis has a thoroughly entertaining transition-oriented team. It
wasn't an entertaining night for Maryland mentor Gary Williams,
however. He had to watch as his team, after a decent start, lost
complete control of the game in the final nine minutes of the half.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Maryland awoke from a stupor that had stretched to a
23-0 St. John run over the span of 10:42, it was too late. And when
things did threaten to get interesting, poised young Mr. Barkley
drilled his third 3-pointer to give the Red Storm a necessary blood
transfusion (63-51 at 4:55), and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   St. John's is now 28-8. Maryland finishes at 27-6 and Williams
is still looking for his own visit to the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   When Maryland's Laron Profit connected on a right-corner jumper
to give the Terps a 19-18 lead with 8:40 remaining in the half, no
one on either side got overly excited. After all, Mr. Profit has
scored nearly 1,500 points during his distinguished college career.
</P>
<P>
   What no one knew was that this would be the final 2 Maryland
points of the half.
</P>
<P>
   After starting off 7 for 13 and on equal terms with a very
aggressive St. John's team, Maryland then assumed the role of
Florida A&AMP;M to St. John's Duke. In as shocking a display as you
could expect to see in a tournament game of this magnitude, the Red
Storm maniacally destructed their opponent with a run of 20
unanswered points to take a startling 38-19 lead into the locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the tough St. John's defense that forced Maryland
into missing its last 10 shots. It wasn't just the
one-shot-and-one-shot-only control of the glass. It wasn't just the
fact that St. John's was thinking fast break with every Maryland
turnover (and there were 13 of them) and missed shot. It wasn't
just the fact that St. John's was combining transition expertise
with half-court prowess. It wasn't any one thing _ it was
everything. A 20-0 run sort of speaks for itself, doesn't it?
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a team deal, this was it. St. John's had no
men in double figures. But this is a team with five double-figure
scorers, so it really was just another evening at the office. If
anyone deserved to take a slight bow, it might have been Barkley,
who had seven assists and a pair of 3-pointers. But was he more
important than Artest, who had four rebounds and three blocks? Or
Postell, who had five rebounds? Or Thornton, who had 9 points? Nah.
</P>
<P>
   The first half was a particular nightmare for touted Maryland
star Steve Francis. The high-flying guard was limited to one field
goal, and he supplied the final exclamation point to the Terrapin
downfall by committing an offensive foul on his team's final
possession of the fiendish final 8:40.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
