<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 02:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6271 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-KAZA-LADN     03-19 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-KAZA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KAZAN AWARD REVIVES OLD HURTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MICHAEL COIT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. _ Bitter passions lingering from the Cold
War and McCarthyism flared anew Thursday when victims of
blacklisting denounced awarding a lifetime achievement Oscar to
film director Elia Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   Writers, actors and their families protested honoring a
filmmaking legend who identified eight people as communist
sympathizers during the 1952 congressional hearings, bolstering a
witch hunt that ruined hundreds of careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``No amount of film excellence can diminish that truth,'' said
actor John Randolph, 89, who was unable to find work for years
after being blacklisted for his political activities.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences of
``profound disrespect,'' Randolph said Kazan at the least should
apologize to the people whose careers he ruined. ``He named names
before. It would be courageous if he would name them again.''
</P>
<P>
   Kazan made such acclaimed movies as ``A Streetcar Named
Desire,'' ``East of Eden'' and ``On the Waterfront,'' but the
prospect of him receiving a lifetime achievement award at the
Oscars opened old wounds in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Displaying the passion for a period they fear the academy is
whitewashing, some 10 blacklisted men and women in their 70s and
80s said they plan to protest outside the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion
on Oscar night Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   A news conference Thursday in the lobby of the academy's office
building on Wilshire Boulevard was disrupted by a heckler shouting
``Communism is evil'' through a bullhorn outside.
</P>
<P>
   A counterdemonstration also planned Sunday by an institute named
in honor of anti-communist author Ayn Rand will add heat to the
controversy as the academy prepares to celebrate the film
industry's latest stars.
</P>
<P>
   That Kazan contributed greatness to Hollywood was not disputed
by the blacklisted. But they contend Kazan has won his Oscars _ for
``Gentleman's Agreement'' in 1947 and ``On the Waterfront'' in 1954
_ and his lifetime achievement is tainted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became a maitre d','' recalled Bob Lees, a writer who
couldn't find work in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't explain to my kids what McCarthyism was all about,
but they knew there were a lot of tensions,'' Lees explained. ``My
wife and I were married 39 years, but we nearly divorced.''
</P>
<P>
   At a separate news conference, academy President Robert Rehme
said the award was solely for Kazan's ``body of work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's a good side to the protest, it is that it has made
people aware of that terrible period of our history and the impact
of that,'' Rehme said. ``But we stand by our award to Mr. Kazan.''
</P>
<P>
   The academy's stand angers those who contend Kazan was in a
position, given his prestige and wealth, to stay silent in hearings
before the House Un-American Activities Committee prompted by
often-slanderous accusations made by Sen. Joseph McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   Kazan, a member of the Communist Party in the 1930s, was the
highest-profile liberal to name names. The eight he named were
colleagues in the Group Theater in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Those accused of having ever been members of the American
Communist Party could either name colleagues and friends who had
been party members or, by not informing, be blacklisted from future
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Writer Norma Barzman said the award celebrates a man who ``cares
more about himself and his career than human beings.''
</P>
<P>
   Barzman, 78, was blacklisted with her late husband and fellow
writer, Ben, while they worked on a film in England in 1949. The
couple moved to France and didn't return to the United States for
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The pain of that period poured back last week when she finally
received writing credit for the 1953 film ``Luxury Girls.'' It was
bittersweet because her husband couldn't share the satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish he were here,'' she said after Thursday's
demonstration. ``This morning, when I tried to rehearse my speech,
I broke into tears.''
</P>
<P>
   A book soon to be released includes Kazan's views on the
controversy. Kazan said he was disturbed to report on his
colleagues, but was concerned that communists threatened the
nation, according to The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   That Kazan's career continued while other talents were silenced
still angers many.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Oscar that my father never got to hold,'' Becca
Wilson said, holding the statuette her family received from the
academy in 1985, seven years after her father, Michael Wilson,
died.
</P>
<P>
   That Oscar _ for co-writing the screenplay for ``Bridge on the
River Kwai'' _ was Wilson's second. At the time, though, it was
given to French author Pierre Boule, who wrote the novel of the
same name.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was lucky because he won an Oscar when he was
blacklisted. For a lot of younger writers, your career was
virtually finished,'' his daughter recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson's first Oscar was for the 1951 film ``A Place in the
Sun.'' He was blacklisted for refusing to testify that year.
</P>
<P>
   Sustained by his initial success, Wilson provided for his family
living in Studio City. He was paid but didn't get credit for
writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was disgusted and angered by the hypocrisy,'' Becca Wilson
said. ``It caused an awful lot of strain in our family. My dad
drank an awful lot and died young.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The McCarthy period cannot be swept under the rug,'' Lees
said.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Ayn Rand Institute plan to demonstrate
support for Kazan outside the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as an issue of justice. People like Kazan took the
right stand in telling the public about what communism was all
about,'' said Chris Wolski, a spokesman. ``It would have been very
easy to sit on his hands and say, I don't know. He stood up and did
the just thing.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0227EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6273 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-19 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO ERR IS HUMAN, TO SHOOT AIRBALLS IS STRICTLY NBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ This week's sign that the apocalypse is NOT upon us:
</P>
<P>
   A partial exam of NBA attendance by Street &AMP; Smith's Sports
Business Journal shows that the no-show count at arenas is
estimated around 10 to 15 percent, even though the NBA refused to
provide any documentary help.
</P>
<P>
   The no-shows indicate at least some discerning fans understand
how inferior baggy-pants theater is this season. (The argument can
be made that these fans were silly to buy season tickets in the
first place, but they probably needed to hold their spots for next
season, should pro ball resume.)
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is smirking quietly to itself that overall attendance
(tickets sold) is down only slightly in the aftermath of the
lockout, indicating it guessed right in calculating the gullibility
of the American sports public.
</P>
<P>
   The increased number of no-shows means the clubs will be out
some money from concessions and parking, but the hit is minor
compared to how badly baseball wounded itself in its 1994 labor
debacle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it is remarkable how many people are showing up to watch
millionaire athletes airball free throws, creating statistical lows
unseen since Flintstone basketball was played with real rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, many fans made the same assumption as Sonics coach
Paul Westphal.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a presumption that most of (the locked-out players)
were doing something,'' he said, barely smiling. ``The season's
more odd than I thought it would be. I thought after the lockout
was over it would be, `Oh, well, get a couple weeks of camp and
go.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it is apparent that too many players posted up at Royal
Fork's all-you-can-eat line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's hard enough to lose 10 pounds,'' Westphal said.
``If you're 40 pounds overweight, two months isn't much time to
lose that.''
</P>
<P>
   It's plain that the Ben &AMP; Jerry's poster children among the
Sonics are Vin Baker and Billy Owens, who packed enough extra
pounds between them to nearly have made the backup point guard for
which the Sonics have yearned.
</P>
<P>
   The recently improved play of Baker, whom the I-5 truck stations
gauged about 280 pounds at the start of the season, has a lot to do
with his slowly improving fitness. Only lately has Baker's
trademark quickness reappeared in the low post.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-9 Owens started out around 250, at least 15 over his best
weight, and since has been sidelined with a broken finger and a
sore knee, the latter a possible consequence of cheeseburger
addiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy is so much better than he's shown,'' Westphal said.
``But he was in almost the same boat as Vin. And he's been in and
out of good health.''
</P>
<P>
   The chubsters' lack of professionalism has been the primary
cause of the Sonics' worst start since the K.C. Jones era. But
since the problem is league-wide, the Sonics have not fallen off
the playoff map.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is physical sloppiness the only explanation for the
grimness. Hersey Hawkins (41.6 percent from the field), who might
be in the best shape of his career, has joined the rest of his
teammates in flirting with career lows in shotmaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the benefit of summer league and exhibition season,
and with a new coach, new system and several new players, working
together has been a problem,'' said Sonics president Wally Walker.
``Normally, a new coach gets a chance in the offseason to get a
dialogue going with veteran players, and there's also a chance to
talk to free agents and see whether they will fit. We couldn't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   As Westphal put it, ``We have no ability to experiment without
consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   Two cases in point: The moves of longtime starters Hawkins and
Detlef Schrempf to the bench. Westphal wanted to talk to both about
the shift during the summer, but the lockout rules prohibited any
contact between management and union members. The moves were done
abruptly, with much resentment and little preparation, during the
season.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawkins move was a bust, and reversed. Schrempf, after
lashing out, now seems accepting for the greater good.
</P>
<P>
   ``What brought the changes had nothing to do with Hersey or
Det,'' Westphal said. ``It had to do with no Sam Perkins, no Nate
McMillan, no Jerome Kersey, no Greg Anthony.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing that made the Sonics so tough over the last several
years is the guys coming off the bench. How many games have those
guys won for the Sonics?''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his predecessor, George Karl, who wanted no part of
youngsters, Westphal finds himself with three rookies on his bench,
all with solid NBA potential. But they aren't ready this season.
Westphal figures if they must play, better to put them in the
starting lineup, as he did with Rashard Lewis, where the best
players can cover their mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the years we would have loved to have a summer league
and a full preseason,'' Westphal said, ``this was it.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Westphal is getting a summer league. It's just that
fans are paying $250 courtside to watch it.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 0228EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6274 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCARS-KAZA-LADN     03-19 0978
