<SLUG> BC-BKC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZAGS' THRILL OF VICTORY EQUAL TO STORY LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ From the bench, from all over the court, they were
yelling at Quentin Hall to commit the foul.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen seconds left in the game, Gonzaga down 72-71 to Florida,
the Zags' point guard was smothering the Gators' Brent Wright and
Hall's teammates were screaming at him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Foul him!'' guard Matt Santangelo shouted.
</P>
<P>
   This Sweet 16 game was ticking down to red-alert status. It
looked like Gonzaga's wild ride in the NCAA tournament might be
coming to an end too fast, too soon.
</P>
<P>
   All night, the Zags had looked like they were going to win this
thing, the way they shot their threes and beat the Florida press.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, it was time to stop the clock. It was time to put
Wright on the line because, even if he makes both free throws, the
bull's-eye-shooting Zags had confidence their 3-point shooters
could win this thing.
</P>
<P>
   But funny things happen in March, which is why this is the
maddest of months if you are college basketball hoopaholic.
</P>
<P>
   Hall never did foul Wright.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something just possessed my body and I just didn't do it,''
Hall would say later.
</P>
<P>
   ``God bless his ears that he didn't hear it,'' Santangelo said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Gonzaga's pressure got to Wright, which is funny since
it was the Gators whose pressure was supposed to finally wear down
the Zags and knock them out of this increasingly surreal NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But Wright was in trouble. The Zags had the passing lanes shut
down as tight as the state highway patrol. There was no pass he
could make, nowhere to turn.
</P>
<P>
   So, just as Wright tried to call a time out, he picked up his
pivot foot and the referee's whistle blew loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked terrified,'' Gonzaga's Casey Calvary said afterward
about the poor kid from Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags had pressured the Gators into a turnover with 15.4
seconds left. They had beat them at their own game. The door had
opened. And Gonzaga was more than happy to come marching through.
</P>
<P>
   On the inbounds play, Hall got the ball on the perimeter,
dribbled left and right and finally launched a shot toward the
basket.
</P>
<P>
   The ball skittered across the rim, no good, but just then, up
from behind, Calvary was there to push the ball back through the
hole and give Gonzaga a 73-72 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Four seconds later, after Florida's last-chance heave clanged
off the rim, the Zags were rolling on the America West Arena
hardwood at center court.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstacy.
</P>
<P>
   Exclamation point.
</P>
<P>
   Another public service announcement from the fellas from Gonzaga
U.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe people keep wanting to call us a Cinderella story, but
we feel we can win every game we play,'' said Richie Frahm, who
drilled three consecutive 3-pointers to keep Gonzaga a step ahead
of Florida through critical minutes late in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an ugly game but we'll take it. This is awesome. This
reflects our dream.''
</P>
<P>
   This wild NCAA ride also reflects the Zags' will, their
confidence, their chemistry and determination.
</P>
<P>
   And most importantly, at least from a basketball strategy point
of view, it also reflects Gonzaga's impressive ability to take its
opponent's best weapon and turn it against them _ with a vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   The Zags beat Minnesota in an uneven first-round game. They then
completely dominated the West's No. 2 seed, Stanford, in a
second-round victory.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, with Florida trying to trap Gonzaga with its
fullcourt pressure, the Zags just shrugged it off, using a pair of
point guards in Hall and Santangelo to beat the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just try and beat the press, you have to punish the
press,'' Santangelo said. ``We were able to do that. You blow by
people, you get into the seams. You have to punish the press and
punish it early and often.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga did, and in doing so the Zags find themselves in the
Elite 8. They believe they can play with anyone, anywhere, anytime.
</P>
<P>
   Did anyone say UConn?
</P>
<P>
   It is a tall order, but the Zags refuse to accept the idea they
are underdogs or Cinderellas to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   As his players were rolling on the court in a giant swarm of Zag
humanity, celebrating with the same abandon they have shown during
these past three victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I was thinking at the time? I was thinking we've
got to get up, get into the locker (room), we've got another game
on Saturday. We can celebrate on Saturday, not here,'' Monson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe that's the coach in you, but at that moment I'm like, we
need to get organized, we've got more work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   More work. More fun. The Zags are alive and the Zag-nuts are
growing ever faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
