<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS STOP KINGS AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ There is no such thing as a little mistake when Paul
Kariya and Teemu Selanne are on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they capitalize even when there was no mistake at
all.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, the play of Kariya and Selanne illustrated
repeatedly the difference between the Mighty Ducks and the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings had more good scoring opportunities than the Ducks,
but couldn't convert often enough.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Kariya and Selanne, the Ducks got more goals on less
chances, winning 4-2 before a Forum crowd of 12,037.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks also got plenty of help from the goal posts, the
crossbar and goalie Guy Hebert. But the story of the night was the
Ducks' explosive duo, which combined for seven points.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' Kings coach Larry Robinson said, ``is that you
can't make any mistakes when those two guys are on the ice.
Otherwise, it's in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem for the Kings (26-37-5) is that their three-game
winning streak ended, and that with 14 games left they remained
five points behind Calgary, which holds the eighth and final
Western Conference playoff berth. The problem for the Ducks
(31-27-11) is minor by comparison, a five-point deficit in their
race with Phoenix for fourth place.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks built a 3-0 lead on goals by Jason Marshall, Selanne
and Kariya before the Kings finally found some holes in Hebert, who
has stopped 166 of 171 shots while posting a 5-0 record this season
against his team's area rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the bounces,'' Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said, ``and
we got great goaltending.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings fired 39 shots at Hebert, and hit two posts (by Rob
Blake) and one crossbar (by Glen Murray). Blake's first post came
in the final minute of the first period when his 75-footer curved,
fooling Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like a center fielder on the play,'' Hebert said.
</P>
<P>
   With 8:23 left in the game, the Kings' drought ended when Donald
Audette drew them within two on a power play. Then, with 4:42 left,
Russ Courtnall cut the deficit to one with a rink-length rush on
which he beat Ducks defensemen Kevin Haller and Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes later, however, Selanne put the game away
when he scored on a 2-on-1 off a pass from Kariya, who had four
points in the game. Selanne's goals give him 39, tying him for the
NHL lead with Alexei Yashin of Ottawa.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were hitting (Kariya) all night,'' Hebert said. ``He took
what they gave him and showed what a great competitor he is. It's
incredible fortitude, not wanting to be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   About the only time Kariya was stopped all night was on a
penalty shot 12 seconds into the second period, after he was pulled
down by Blake.
</P>
<P>
   And Kariya and Selanne weren't the only Ducks the Kings had
trouble slowing down. During one shift midway through the second
period, the Kings were hemmed in their zone for a solid minute by
the line of Antti Aalto, Johan Davidsson and Jim McKenzie, until an
exhausted Blake finally took a holding penalty. Selanne scored on
the subsequent power play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shift may have won the game for us,'' Hartsburg said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will have to hope this loss didn't end the momentum
they'd recently gained.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the effort is there, the momentum will be there,''
Blake said. ``It's a disappointing loss, but not for lack of
effort. They've got two of the best players in the league. When
they get a chance, they score.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
