<HEADLINE>
SURPRISING PROFITS HEAT UP FOUR MEDIA SHARES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNary  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. -- Shares of post-production specialist Four
Media Co. shot up more than 14 percent Thursday after the company
posted profits that were well above Wall Street's expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Shares rose 87.5 cents to $7 for their highest close in more
than a month. Volume of 420,000 shares was more than 10 times the
30-day average.
</P>
<P>
   Four Media reported earnings of $2.3 million, 19 cents a share,
for its second quarter that ended Jan. 31, more than triple its
earnings of $693,000, 7 cents a share, in the 1998 period. The
profits were 4 cents higher than the consensus estimate of five
analysts surveyed by First Call.
</P>
<P>
   Four Media, which has been aggressively buying smaller rivals in
recent years, also reported that revenues increased 67.5 percent to
$47.5 million, highlighted by a gain of 138 percent in the
television division. Citing efficiencies from consolidating
acquisitions, Robert Waltson, chairman and chief executive officer,
noted that gross profit margins rose to 42.3 percent from 34.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Walston, whose strategy has been to make Four Media a one-stop
shop for all post-production services, remained bullish. ``We
continue to see favorable opportunities for growth, both
domestically and internationally, and look forward to expanding the
range of out-sourcing solutions and the creative and technical
services we provide,'' he said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   A previously announced three-part deal to give 51 percent
ownership to Wall Street investment firm Warburg Pincus, in
exchange for an $80 million investment worth about $7.85 a share,
was approved Thursday by shareholders in Four Media, which went
public in 1996 at $10 a share. A spokeswoman said the deal should
close by May 1, pending approval by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
