<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGKOR-HISTORY-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TIMELINE: HOW ANGKOR'S TEMPLES GREW
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With CAMBODIA-ANGKOR-$ADV20; CAMBODIA-BOX-$ADV20.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., March 20 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT and MARCIA KUNSTEL 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIEM REAP, Cambodia _ Here is the historical timeline of the
Angkor kingdom:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  800 AD. -1432 AD. -- The Angkor Kingdom emerges as the
dominant empire in Southeast Asia, ruled by a succession of
temple-building Khmer kings from their capital near present-day
Siem Reap. Each king tried to outdo his predecessor by building
bigger and more magnificent stone temples to the gods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1112-1152 AD. -- King Suryavarman II builds the Hindu temple
of Angkor Wat. Its central tower symbolizes the mythical Mount
Meru, supposedly located at the center of the universe. Its outer
walls stand for the mountains at the edge of the earth. Beyond the
walls is a surrounding moat representing the oceans beyond the
earth.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1177 AD. -- The Angkor capital is sacked by the Chams,
invading tribesmen from southern Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1181-1201 AD. -- The new Khmer king Jayavarman VII introduces
Buddhism and mobilizes the million inhabitants of his capital on a
crash program to build more than a dozen major new temples and
scores of schools and hospitals. Like his predecessors, he relies
on slave laborers to finish the building spree in his lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1220-1431 AD .-- Khmer Empire in decline. Angkor is sacked in
1351 and 1431 by Thai invaders.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1431 AD. -- Khmer kings abandon Angkor and move their capital
southward to Phnom Penh. The temples, increasingly engulfed by
jungle, remain inhabited by Buddhist monks.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1860 -- French explorer-naturalist Henri Mouhot stumbles onto
Angkor Wat, then all-but-forgotten. His detailed notes and
pen-and-ink drawings become a sensation in the West when they are
published in 1868, seven years after his death.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
