</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Saturday, March 20
and Sunday, March 21, 1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   Thursday for Friday: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP; garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD - This column is not available this week. It will
resume shortly. (Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA-NEWMOTOWN - Through the rose colored glasses sitting low
on his nose, Bunmi Junadi is looking out for the rich and fabulous.
That's his job. The bald-headed Nigerian was hired by musical
millionaires Sean ``Puffy'' Combs and Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid as VIP
coordinator for Justin's, their newly opened Buckhead restaurant.
The objects of his pampering are metro Atlanta's black glitterati,
a growing cast of African-American celebrities who are putting down
roots, hanging out their shingles, and searching for the perfect
place to see, and be seen. Long known as a magnet for
nine-to-fivers of all races who move to the metro area from
everywhere, Atlanta has quietly developed a distinctive celebrity
scene as African-American entertainers are decamping from
established glam capitols like Los Angeles and New York. (Harris,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 40. WITH PHOTOS. FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ARTS/ENTERTAINMENT
</P>
<P>
   The following stories are part of 4-part series on Lonnie
Holley, the Alabama folk artist who has endured nothing but trouble
since he was one of the stars of the Olympic Arts Festival in 1996.
Holley, one of the South's most important folk artists, has known a
world of trouble in his 49 years. But nothing has prepared him for
the random misfortunes that have bedeviled him like Job over the
past couple of years. This is a story about a man who has struggled
against great odds to make his art and to keep his family together.
</P>
<P>
   All stories MOVED Wednesday FOR SUNDAY. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEHOLLEY-PART1 - COLUMBIANA, Ala. - We start with Holley's
arrest, then back up and tell the story of how he got there.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 90.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEHOLLEY-PART2 - HARPERSVILLE, Va. - We look at Holley and
his family and their current troubles. Holley has raised five
children by himself, and by all accounts did a great job against
the odds. But in recent years, his kids have had all manner of
problems. And it could get worse. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 58.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEH0LLEY-PART3 - BIRMINGHAM, Ala. - We look at Holley's
career in the context of the world of folk art. The reasons for
folk artists' struggles are complicated but the results are the
same: renowned, respected artists who wouldn't qualify for an auto
loan. We also look at the efforts of various dealers and do-gooders
to help him and his family. (Auchmutey, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 50.
</P>
<P>
   LONNIEHOLLEY-PART4 - We sort out the endings, happy and
otherwise. The first good news, it seemed, Holley had gotten in
years was that juvenile authorities had been so impressed with
Holley's 16-year old son Kubra that they took it upon themselves to
nominate him for the Alabama School of Fine Arts, a magnet program
in Birmingham for gifted children from across the state. While
oldest son Ezekial appears headed for prison, and third son A.J.
for juvenile boot camp. And Holley? He'll probably plead guilty to
reduced charges and get probation, and he's finally painting again.
(Auchmutey, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 30.
</P>
<P>
   SXSW-CLUBS - AUSTIN - SXSW brings to showcase clubs 2 to 3 times
their usual monthly income, a huge difference considering the thin
operating margin of most local clubs. If only the clubs could pack
people in and sell as many drinks year round.... SXSW this year
should find big crowds at Liberty Lunch, likely the last time in
its present location, and the Electric Lounge, which is just trying
to keep its doors open through the festival after being hit with
rent increases. Austin Blues is an example of a new club trying to
get established during the festival. (McLeese, Austin
American-Statesman). 35. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Here is the budget for this week's Science-Medicine page:
</P>
<P>
   COXNET SCIHEALTH 0319 - A Brazilian doctor has created a new
procedure that involves an ``internal brassiere'' formed of mesh.
It's one of the hottest techniques in the plastic surgery business,
where breast reshaping, reduction and reconstruction take center
stage. (Lore, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BREAST LIST - A list of options for reshaping the breast. (Lore,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SLEEP DISORDERS - There may be more to that wheezing, snorting,
rattling rat-tat-tat deep-within-the-throat snoring that awakes
you, your loved ones (and possibly even the neighbors) each night.
A sleep evaluation could reveal the condition of sleep apnea.
(Mays, Waco Tribune-Herald)
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH NOTES - A quarter of the nation's nursing homes have
severe health and safety infractions that often go unpunished,
although the conditions jeopardize residents, federal auditors said
in a recent study. (Malone, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (EDS: This is the CoxNet SCIHEALTH page for the current week.
This layout is now available.)PHYSICISTS - ATLANTA - The American
Physical Society, the world's largest organization of physicists,
pulls into town today for a scientific session marking its 100th
anniversary. Among the sessions planned: presentations by Stephen
Hawking, and seminars on such topics as the physics of dance, toys,
magic, beer and baseball - many of them open to the public. A
bulleted roundup of what's happening, where and when. (Seabrook,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-HEALTH - What can those on-line health surveys really
tell you about your current health and whether your lifestyle
habits will lead to an early grave? (Kim, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-MUSICIANS - Many musicians don't have health insurance,
but they do have health problems related to their jobs - hearing
loss, carpal tunnel syndrome for guitarists and drummers. Talking
to musicians with these health problems and also to physicians who
work with musicians and seeing what solutions there are. What can
they do aside from not playing so much, which would hurt their
career. (Santos, Austin American-Statesman). 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   ASSISTED-LIVING-CENTERS - WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. - At the Palm
Beach Assisted Living Facility, there are younger people with
handicaps, and some former down-and-outers who qualify for state
aid to the elderly homeless. But most of the 165 residents are
``private pay'' retirees who don't need the constant care of a
nursing home but do need a watchful eye. It's a broad and forgiving
designation. The federal government considers them poor, but they
have some income: Social Security, veterans benefits. With luck,
they get a little help from family, and a little more from Joseph
Glucksman. (Kalajian, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOME &AMP; GARDEN
</P>
<P>
   HEIRLOOM-SEEDS - It's the first day of spring, and gardeners are
returning to their roots, experimenting with heirloom seeds to grow
vegetables. It's not just nostalgia but the growing tendency for
vegetable gardeners to want to save seeds from year to year. But
the hybrids do not necessarily produce the same fruit. So, with an
heirloom seed, if you have a really great tomato plant, you can
save the seeds and ensure one that is equally good the next year.
The drawback is that not all your plants from heirloom seeds will
be hearty. (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-ARRIVES - Spring officially arrives at 8:46 p.m. today.
On the first day of spring, also referred to as the vernal equinox,
the sun rises due east and sets due west; day and night are of
essentially equal length. This season, spring will last 92 days, 18
hours and 3 minutes until summer begins on June 21, say Fernbank
Science Center astronomers. A look at some of the signs. (Seabrook,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN - Lee on the importance of ``sitting places'' -
benches, chairs, rocks in the garden. ``Year-round sitting is as
important to me as year-round blooming. And with the shank of the
sitting season imminent, I pay as much attention to my seating as I
do to my pruning. Looking at plants when seated provides a valuable
perspective.'' (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GREIG-COLUMN - The Greig Files goes after Texas pests, from
armadillos to scorpions. We'll tell you where they lurk, why
they're there and how to get rid of them, including home remedies.
(Greig, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   WHITECLERIC-BLACKCHURCH - The Church of the Atlanta Lighthouse
once had a congregation of whites and blacks. That all changed as
white members began moving to the suburbs years ago. Now the
church, located near the Atlanta Federal Penitentiary, has only
African-American members, except for one key person - the pastor.
The Rev. Spiers, who is white, has remained. We try to find out why
and explore the daily challenges he faces as a white cleric
ministering to a black congregation. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-OSCAR - We continue a F&AMP;V tradition, inviting a group
of critics to offer their opinions regarding the spiritual content
of movies nominated this year for Best Film. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
