<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 10:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6494 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MINTER-COLUMN20-COX     03-19 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dream of a different kind across the great divide
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following is an excerpt from Jim Minter's book, ``Some
Things I Wish We Wouldn't Forget.''
</P>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ In the springtime, when the baseball
season is young and hope is fresh, I often think of my old friend
Junior Miles, and his great dream of seeing a major league baseball
game.
</P>
<P>
   On summer afternoons Junior and I, too young to be assigned a
mule and plowstock, worked together in the cotton fields, wielding
sharpened blades on long wood-handled hoes to chop and thin the
plants, always struggling to keep up with the women workers who
moved easily and rhythmically ahead.
</P>
<P>
   The work was tedious, made bearable by our talk of batting
averages and heroes whose pictures we had seen on the sports page
of the newspaper. On a flimsy excuse, we would slip away and catch
a few innings of the Game of the Day on radio. Fenway Park and
Yankee Stadium were magic places, far away in another world.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit was equally distant and magical, although Junior's older
brothers, Bo and James, had left the farm and gone there in search
of jobs becoming available in automobile plants gearing up for war
orders.
</P>
<P>
   Bo had not had much luck. He failed to find a job, and in the
cold Northern winter caught pneumonia. His mother, Miss Esther, got
on the train and went to nurse him. She was too late. Bo spent his
last lonely days in a spare room in a strange city.
</P>
<P>
   THE IMPOSSIBLE DREAM
</P>
<P>
   James eventually landed a job working for the Ford Motor Co.,
and in his prosperity wrote home that he had been to Briggs Stadium
and had actually seen the Detroit Tigers play the Boston Red Sox in
a major league baseball game. Hank Greenberg, of course, hit a home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Next summer, James wrote, he would send money for a train ticket
and Junior could visit him, and together they would go and see the
Detroit Tigers play in a major league baseball game. It was an
impossible dream, and neither Junior nor I really believed it would
happen.
</P>
<P>
   It did not happen the next summer, or one following, because
James encountered expenses he had not expected. It was late July,
after the cotton had been laid by, when the money arrived. In his
12th year, Junior Miles caught the train in Atlanta and set off to
fulfill his dream.
</P>
<P>
   He was gone two weeks. On the afternoon of his return, as we sat
under a gum tree, I was anxious to hear about his great adventure.
I expected him to be excited, and to say he had actually seen Hank
Greenberg or Ted Williams hit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   `NO BLACK, NO WHITE'
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he was strangely silent and preoccupied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you really see a major league baseball game?'' I asked. He
said he and James had done that. But he didn't seem to have
baseball on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Detroit,'' he told me instead, ``There ain't no black, and
there ain't no white.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange statement. I was puzzled. I had to ask him what
he meant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was riding up there on the train,'' he said, ``the
conductor came up to me and said: `Boy, get your things and move up
there to that other car.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `No sir, I can't do that. That's the white car.'
Then he asked me, `Boy, you remember when this train crossed that
big river? When you cross that river there ain't no black and there
ain't no white.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And sure enough,'' Junior Miles told me that afternoon under
the gum tree, ``there wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He said when he got to be 16 he was going to Detroit to live,
even if his brother Bo had died there with nobody to look after him
when he got sick. And he did. He became a preacher, eventually
pastoring a large church in Detroit before being called to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1996, Junior came back to Inman and preached
two nights in his old home church. He showed pictures of his big
church in Chicago, and of his expansive home.
</P>
<P>
   It was his last visit. Within a year, Rev. Son Jesus Miles, Jr.,
whose life was changed when he passed over the Ohio River, crossed
over the Jordan. His sons carry on his ministry at his church in
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
