<P>
   HEIRLOOM-SEEDS - It's the first day of spring, and gardeners are
returning to their roots, experimenting with heirloom seeds to grow
vegetables. It's not just nostalgia but the growing tendency for
vegetable gardeners to want to save seeds from year to year. But
the hybrids do not necessarily produce the same fruit. So, with an
heirloom seed, if you have a really great tomato plant, you can
save the seeds and ensure one that is equally good the next year.
The drawback is that not all your plants from heirloom seeds will
be hearty. (MLongino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SPRING-ARRIVES - Spring officially arrives at 8:46 p.m. today.
On the first day of spring, also referred to as the vernal equinox,
the sun rises due east and sets due west; day and night are of
essentially equal length. This season, spring will last 92 days, 18
hours and 3 minutes until summer begins on June 21, say Fernbank
Science Center astronomers. A look at some of the signs. (Seabrook,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LEEMAY-COLUMN - Lee on the importance of ``sitting places'' -
benches, chairs, rocks in the garden. ``Year-round sitting is as
important to me as year-round blooming. And with the shank of the
sitting season imminent, I pay as much attention to my seating as I
do to my pruning. Looking at plants when seated provides a valuable
perspective.'' (May, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GREIG-COLUMN - The Greig Files goes after Texas pests, from
armadillos to scorpions. We'll tell you where they lurk, why
they're there and how to get rid of them, including home remedies.
(Greig, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   WHITECLERIC-BLACKCHURCH - The Church of the Atlanta Lighthouse
once had a congregation of whites and blacks. That all changed as
white members began moving to the suburbs years ago. Now the
church, located near the Atlanta Federal Penitentiary, has only
African-American members, except for one key person - the pastor.
The Rev. Spiers, who is white, has remained. We try to find out why
and explore the daily challenges he faces as a white cleric
ministering to a black congregation. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-OSCAR - We continue a F&AMP;V tradition, inviting a group
of critics to offer their opinions regarding the spiritual content
of movies nominated this year for Best Film. (Blake, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
