<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Friday, March 19, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Saturday and Sunday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence
at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-UNIVERSITY (San Francisco) _ All of the state's high
schools will have a chance to send the top 4 percent of their
students to the University of California under a plan adopted by
the UC regents that aims to equalize opportunity. But the plan
would not significantly affect ethnic diversity at the nine
campuses. By KATHERINE SELIGMAN.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING (Sierra Village, Calif.) _ The FBI says the discovery of
the charred remains of a car used by three missing sightseers is
``incontrovertible evidence that the three were victims of a
violent crime.'' By RAY DELGADO, ERIC BRAZIL and MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-CALIF (San Francisco) _ California deserves a solid D when
it comes to treatment of women and girls, according to a new report
card issued by the Women's Foundation, a philanthropic
organization. The report card evaluates women's progress _ or lack
of it _ in five areas. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-MAYOR (Valatie, N.Y.) _ Mayor-elect Jason Nastke is not
your ordinary teen-ager. Two years after graduating from high
school, Nastke was elected the top official in this village of
1,500 and will take office April 1. By TIM O'BRIEN.
</P>
<P>
   CHAVEZ-AIRPORT (San Antonio) _ A majority of the City Council
members here have signed a memo to rename the San Antonio
International Airport next month after labor leader and activist
Cesar Chavez. By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   MURAD-RESEARCH (San Antonio) _ Dr. Ferid Murad, known for his
work in the development of the anti-impotence pill Viagra, says his
findings in the field of nitric oxide, which can relax the muscles
that control the body's blood vessels, have much broader
implications. By NICOLE FOY.
</P>
<P>
   ROCKET-BELT (Houston) _ This crime sounds as if it was ripped
from the pages of a comic book. The murder victim is Joseph White,
whose bludgeoned body was found in his home in July. He was
involved in a lawsuit over a rocket belt _ a recent model descended
from one first developed in the 1940s. Investigators believe the
killing is linked to a lawsuit surrounding the development of the
belt. By ERIC HANSON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Undated) _ Most companies have long hummed the
mantra of fairness. Treat everyone the same, the theory goes. But
University of Michigan business professor David Ulrich argues
that's a silly way to do business. It's much better to treat high
performers differently by giving them more flexibility and more
perks, he says. After all, that's what keeps these employees
humming. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ The Mac is back. In a more muscular
follow-up to the consumer iMac, Apple Computer has hit a home run
with its eye-catching new high-end line of Macintosh G3s. By DWIGHT
SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-HELPLINE (Undated) _ A reader who has 401 fonts wants
to know how he can safely delete some of these from his computer.
Assorted Q&AMP;As. By DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   STAR-WARS (San Francisco) _ Two months before the release of its
much-anticipated new ``Star Wars'' movie, Lucasfilm Ltd. sent a
message to companies and individuals who might be thinking of
pirating images from the flick: Don't. The San Rafael-based film
production company says it received about $1 million in a
settlement with unnamed companies who have sold such images. By
WENDY TANAKA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-COWBOY (Undated) _ Books where the authors spend a
day, a month or a year at someone else's job are usually dumb. But
in ``The Cowboy Way: Seasons of a Montana Ranch, '' David McCumber
brings the reader into the heart of his adventure on a Montana
ranch, morning to night. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-CASTRO (Undated) _ When he finished his novel,
``Castro's Curveball,'' Tim Wendel was probably thinking of Kevin
Costner. Costner would be perfect for the part of Billy Bryan, an
aging catcher making a last stab at baseball with the Havana Lions
in 1947, discovering Fidel Castro's curveball. By EDVINS BEITIKS.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-SINGLE (Undated) _ John Le Carre's new novel,
``Single &AMP; Single,'' will be a welcome sight in bookstores to his
many long-term fans. The basic promise of the book _ a father and
son who through betrayal and reversal of fortune find their way
back to redemption _ unfortunately does not materialize. It was
this promise that kept me reading. By GINGER BRISTOW.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-CRIME (Undated) _ In ``True Crime,'' Clint
Eastwood's success as an actor-director-producer is hampered by the
maddening suspicion that he'd rather be doing something else. He
seems distracted, bored out of his wits, bushed. By AMY BIANCOLLI.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-LENNYBRUCE (Undated) _ For a man whose agenda was
breaking the law, comedian Lenny Bruce spent a lot of time studying
it. He wanted to understand why and how it was forcibly entering
his art and shutting it down. That's the depressing revelation of
director Robert Weide's sneakily affecting documentary ``Lenny
Bruce: Swear to Tell the Truth.'' By WESLEY MORRIS.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TASTY-LEFTOVERS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Meatloaf, vegetable soup,
chili, or lasagna. These foods improve with age because the more
time allowed for the flavors to marry, the better the food tastes.
So prepare them on the weekend and enjoy them throughout the week.
By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOOT-SCULPTURE (San Francisco) _ The Foot, a proposed sculpture
for San Francisco Bay, took a big step when a key committee of the
Art Commission here gave it an enthusiastic hand. The work by
Seattle sculptor Buster Simpson is a hollow, 18-foot-high, striated
stainless-steel rendering of a foot with its big toe just touching
the water. By LARRY D. HATFIELD.
</P>
