<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 12:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6597 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCKET-BELT-HNS &LR;      03-19 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCKET-BELT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSOLVED MURDER FOLLOWS LAWSUIT OVER ROCKET BELT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: N.Y.) 
 
By ERIC HANSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In the movie ``The Rocketeer,'' Nazi spies, gangsters
and good guys fight over a rocket-powered backpack that allows a
man to soar like a bullet.
</P>
<P>
   A true story rivaling the movie's plot has unfolded here,
involving a real rocket-powered backpack, a nasty lawsuit and an
unsolved murder.
</P>
<P>
   First developed in the early 1960s, the backpack _ actually
called a rocket belt _ was last seen publicly in the summer of
1995, when pilot Bill Suitor flew it at a party celebrating the
Houston Rockets NBA championship series with the Orlando Magic.
</P>
<P>
   The murder victim is Joseph Wright, whose bludgeoned body was
found last July in his home in northwest Harris County. His head,
face and upper body had been beaten so badly that he had to be
identified through dental records.
</P>
<P>
   Wright, 37, and another man, Bradley W. Barker, 44, were being
sued by Thomas L. Stanley, 54, who claimed they had stolen the belt
from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a Harold Robbins novel,'' said Ronald Bass,
Wright's friend and attorney. ``This is an incredible story of a
bunch of very, very unusual people with a unique thing in the
middle of it, this rocket belt.''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators will not say what the motive was, but Harris
County Sheriff's Lt. Albert Diaz said Barker is the only suspect.
No charges have been filed.
</P>
<P>
   On July 19, when detectives arrived at Wright's patio home, Diaz
said, there were no signs of forced entry and nothing seemed to be
missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever came there was let in by the victim,'' he said. ``And
it appeared to us that whoever the suspect was, he had time to tidy
up the crime scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of that, Diaz said, there was little physical evidence.
He said detectives are still trying to track down documents and
financial records in a search for clues.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley filed the suit in 1995, claiming that Barker, his
partner, and Wright had taken the rocket belt from him unlawfully.
</P>
<P>
   Bass said he was trying to negotiate an agreement with Stanley's
attorney on Wright's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept telling them that Joe Wright did not know where the
rocket belt was, but that he could maybe help them, that he would
be a better ally than an enemy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bass said he participated in a meeting the night of July 15,
1998, with Stanley and his attorney, and that Wright agreed, by
speaker phone, to help Stanley recover the belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cut a deal and a couple of days later Joe was killed,''
Bass said. ``That's the sad aspect of this case. Joe was a nice
man, a nice sweet man. Everybody liked Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley's attorney, Michael P. Von Blon, was out of town and
unavailable for comment. Stanley did not return calls.
</P>
<P>
   Barker, who investigators say no longer lives in Houston, could
not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Bass said Stanley and Barker had formed a partnership, American
Rocket Belt Co., to market the belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it had ever been done right, it could have possibly made a
lot of money,'' he said. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But, he said, Barker and Stanley had a disagreement and the two
fought, with Stanley suffering head injuries that he claimed were
caused by Barker beating him with a ball-peen hammer.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents in the lawsuit, assault charges were
filed against both, but those against Stanley were dropped, while
Barker received probation.
</P>
<P>
   The rocket belt at the center of the lawsuit is an improved
version of a machine first developed in the early 1960s by Wendell
Moore, an engineer at Bell Aircraft in Buffalo, N.Y. Built for the
Department of Defense, its 20-second flight duration made it
impractical.
</P>
<P>
   California inventor Doug Malewicki said Barker contacted him
several years ago, after the original Bell patents had expired,
about building a new version.
</P>
<P>
   Malewicki said recent developments in space-age materials made
it possible to use lighter metals and thus carry more fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Malewicki said the principle is fairly simple. Two tanks are
filled with hydrogen peroxide and a third contains nitrogen under
high pressure. When the throttle is opened, the nitrogen pushes the
hydrogen peroxide into a catalyst pack, made up of tightly packed
samarium nitrate-coated silver screens.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to the catalyst, the propellant turns into
high-pressure superheated steam that blasts out two nozzles,
providing the lifting thrust.
</P>
<P>
   Malewicki said he helped Barker design the belt, but Barker
built it. He said the new device, dubbed the RB2000, could fly for
about 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   He said Barker has phoned him occasionally over the years to
chat, but will not discuss the rocket belt or Wright's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime I bring it up, he immediately changes the subject,''
Malewicki said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bell rocket belt, flown by Suitor, was featured in the 1965
James Bond movie, ``Thunderball.'' He made more than 1,200 flights
in it, including one over the Niagara Rapids.
</P>
<P>
   Suitor, who lives near Buffalo, was a neighbor of Moore and was
the test pilot for the first rocket belt at the age of 19. He later
test-flew the improved version developed by Barker and Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Contacted recently at his home, Suitor, now 54, declined to talk
about the rocket belt or Wright's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want anything to do with any of it,'' he said curtly.
</P>
<P>
   But in a recent interview with the Buffalo News, Suitor said he
was contacted in October 1994 by Barker and Stanley to do the test
flight.
</P>
<P>
   That was the first time he flew the device, which he calls
``Pretty Bird.'' The last was at the NBA party at the Houston Ship
Channel.
</P>
<P>
   He told the Buffalo News that he unstrapped the belt and handed
it to Barker, who put it in his trailer and drove off.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the last time I saw Barker or Pretty Bird,'' Suitor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Suitor said that he had hoped to make one more flight in the
RB2000 but that Wright's death changed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never be involved with any of those people again,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The personal fights between the partners, the ongoing
violence, and now murder. It's not worth the grief, let alone your
life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
