<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE MAKES A MAC FOR THE TRUE BELIEVER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apple computer is the high-tech industry's latest comeback kid,
yanking itself out of the abyss on the strength of Steve Jobs'
dogged vision and sales of the cheap little computer dubbed iMac.
</P>
<P>
   But one consumer model isn't enough to keep a ship the size of
Apple afloat. The company needed to follow the iMac with a worthy
overhaul of its entire line, including its mainstream Macintosh
computers.
</P>
<P>
   The result is the Power Macintosh G3 line, which, like the iMac,
sports an eye-catching external redesign marked by turquoise
accents. But in this case, beauty is much more than skin deep.
</P>
<P>
   The Power Macintosh G3 should restore the faith of the
professional Mac faithful, particularly those who need a
full-powered system for graphics applications. However, whether it
will win over the hearts and minds of Windows users remains to be
seen. It is an excellent computer, but it doesn't have enough
benefits over Windows 98 or NT 4.0 to inspire those with
established software libraries and usage habits to switch.
</P>
<P>
   The system I tried came with a 350-megahertz PowerPC G3
processor, 64 megabytes of memory, a six-gigabyte hard drive, a
DVD-ROM drive, a 16-megabyte ATI Technologies Rage 128 video card
and a 17-inch Apple Studio Display monitor.
</P>
<P>
   The computer sells on Apple's Web site in this configuration for
$1,999; the monitor, which has a beautiful Sony Trinitron display,
is another $499.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
WHAT'S MISSING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, it did not ship with a modem, though it does come
with a built-in Ethernet connection capable of either 10- or
100-megabit-per-second speeds. At first, I was peeved that it came
without a modem, but later I was pleased. More later.
</P>
<P>
   It also comes without a floppy disk drive, part of Jobs' ongoing
quest to rid the world of the 1.44-megabyte disk. While I still
think these Macs should have floppies of some kind included, it is
getting easier to find removable storage devices that will plug
into its Universal Serial Bus ports.
</P>
<P>
   The G3 systems come with two USB ports, two FireWire (or IEEE
1394) ports for use with personal electronics, a single Apple
Desktop Bus port and three open PCI slots inside. A fourth slot
holds the video card.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the colored plastic, Apple has come up with a unique and
intelligent design for the case. At each corner is a rugged handle
that makes moving the relatively heavy computer a snap. And the
case opens up simply by pulling open a latch on the side.
</P>
<P>
   When you pull the latch, the panel lays down flat, and the
motherboard sits on the inside of the panel. This makes working on
the Mac's guts a breeze.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to my experience with the lack of a modem for
the G3. At first, I was appalled that Apple would even consider
shipping a computer sans modem in this day and age, and I
remembered when Mac bigots would snicker at PC users because their
early machines didn't come with sound built-in.
</P>
<P>
   I called Apple and got the company to send a modem. It was
unconventional, to say the least: A square, tube-shaped device that
connected to the motherboard via two small screws and a ribbon
cable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MODEM GOES TO WORK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who's ever had to install a modem into a Windows-based
system _ even one of the newer Plug and Play models _ would have
stared in awe at what happened next. When I turned on the Mac, the
modem was ... simply there. No searching for drivers, no klunky
dialog boxes saying that the operating system was identifying the
hardware. The modem just worked.
</P>
<P>
   What a concept.
</P>
<P>
   And, the modem lacked a signature Apple trademark from the past
_ a high price. A 56K modem for the G3 only costs an extra $100 _
about what you'd expect to pay for a middling quality PC modem.
</P>
<P>
   The system was very fast, about what you'd expect from any
350-megahertz model. Apple has made lots of noise by bragging that
its PowerPC-based Macs are actually faster than Pentium systems at
the same speed, a claim that's been challenged by a series of tests
done by PC Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that, while some software may run faster on the Mac
than its Windows version will on a PC, there's more to a computer's
speed than just the processor. Hard drives, the motherboard's
speed, the graphics card, the speed of the memory chips _ all
affect system performance.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what you need to know about the zippiness of the G3s: If
you need or want to use a Macintosh, you are going to be very happy
with the speed of this system. Don't worry about whether it
outraces your Windows-using neighbor's machine, or whether hers
outdoes yours.
</P>
<P>
   While it is an excellent computer, no system is perfect, which
may come as a shock to Apple zealots who express outrage that
anyone may actually find fault with a Mac.
</P>
<P>
   Apple has made the big mistake of including the same lame,
one-button mouse that it introduced with the iMac. This mouse is
perfectly round and has no tactile cues to indicate its
orientation. After it is used awhile, the mouse has a tendency to
rotate under your hand, so the button is off to the left or right
instead of straight up.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto for the keyboard, which also is the same as that found on
the iMac. It's much less sturdy than the keyboards that shipped
with earlier Macs. Veteran Macintosh users will be appalled.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, both of these devices connect via the USB ports, so
they can be replaced. And if you buy one of these computers, you
should replace at least the mouse _ preferably with one that has at
least two buttons.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dwight Silverman can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address your comments and questions to
dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000 and enter
access code 1001. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
