<HEADLINE>
IT MAY BE EASIER TO KEEP 401 FONTS THAN TO FIGURE OUT WHICH ONES
GO 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DWIGHT SILVERMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: In a recent tip from CNet was the following: ``Delete any
unnecessary fonts, and you'll free up a bunch of disk space.'' From
``Windows 95 for Dummies'' comes a suggestion that one should not
remove any fonts that came with Windows. I have 401 fonts on my
machine, not any added intentionally by me, but rather added as I
installed programs. I will never use 401 fonts. How do I know which
ones I can safely remove?
</P>
<P>
   A: The problem here is your phrase, ``not any added
intentionally by me.''
</P>
<P>
   You didn't install any fonts, so that means the programs you use
_ possibly day to day _ installed them. And the fonts added may be
crucial to their operation, separate from any Windows requirements.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it difficult to figure out which ones you don't need.
If you remove something you know Windows didn't add, then some
program may have problems, or at the very least, it may look weird.
</P>
<P>
   Most fonts are relatively small files, averaging below 100
kilobytes. And in Windows 95/98, they don't all load with the
operating system, as they did with Windows 3.1 _ they are called
only as they are needed.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, you probably are better off leaving things as they are.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My son recently found a description of a file called
SmartDrive in a book about Microsoft MS-DOS 5.0. Apparently, if you
put it in your configuration files when they load, your system runs
faster. I have MS-DOS 5.0 on disk _ how can I get SmartDrive
installed on my Windows 95 system?
</P>
<P>
   A: As is the case with the first question, this is not something
you really want to do.
</P>
<P>
   SmartDrive is a disk cache program that provides a buffer for
loading data from the hard drive. SmartDrive tries to anticipate
what data the computer will need next, then pulls it off the hard
drive and stores it in random access memory. Since RAM is faster
than a hard disk, this can boost the speed of your computer.
</P>
<P>
   SmartDrive is not loaded as a separate file in Windows 95/98
because it's built into the operating system. You don't need
SmartDrive. In fact, if you install it, it could slow down your
Windows 95/98 system.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the definition of a ``hit'' vs. a ``visit'' when
talking about World Wide Web sites?
</P>
<P>
   A: A ``hit'' occurs any time that a component of a Web page is
accessed by a computer from across the Internet. A ``visit''
happens any time a unique user calls up a specific page.
</P>
<P>
   Let's say that you go to a Web site that has three graphics, a
block of text and perhaps a counter on it. That would constitute
five hits _ one for each component _ on that page.
</P>
<P>
   But your looking at that page in total is a visit. If you come
back to that page again, it should not be counted as a second
visit, because you are not considered unique for that day. You've
already been there and laid eyeballs on it.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of Web site operators justifying their traffic,
visitors are a better measure of a site's popularity than hits. If
a page has 100 components and one visitor sees it, that's 100 hits,
but only one visitor.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a PC I bought in early 1997 that has two USB ports on
it. I was excited about getting USB, but I have Windows 95 and all
the USB hardware that I want says it's for Windows 98. Do I really
have to upgrade to Windows 98 to use my USB?
</P>
<P>
   A: Only later versions of Windows 95 _ dubbed OSR2 _ support
USB, but it's dicey. USB support is much better in Windows 98, so
if you really want to use that feature, upgrading is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Got a question about your computer? Dwight Silverman can receive
electronic mail via the Internet. Address your comments and
questions to dwight.silverman(at)chron.com, or call (713) 220-2000
and enter access code 1001. &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
