<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES WIN BY REWARDING STARS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M.SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Most companies, especially the big ones, have long chanted the
mantra of fairness. Treat everyone the same, the theory goes, and
that will eliminate a lot of headaches.
</P>
<P>
   But David Ulrich, a University of Michigan business professor,
made an argument recently claiming that is a silly way to do
business.
</P>
<P>
   It's much better to treat high performers differently by giving
them more flexibility and more perks, said Ulrich, who recently had
a round-table discussion with human resource executives. After all,
that's what keeps them humming _ and makes them less likely to look
around at other companies that will provide the extras they're
missing.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his crazy antics, Dennis Rodman added a lot of value to
the Chicago Bulls as a great rebounder, Ulrich said. So during the
playoffs against the Utah Jazz, a time when most players practice,
what did the coach say when Rodman wanted to go to Las Vegas
between games?
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy yourself, Ulrich recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Offering that kind of flexibility is easier for smaller
companies because they're more informal, said Ulrich, who discussed
his ideas during the Houston Human Resource Management
Association's annual conference. But it also should become a matter
of course at bigger companies.
</P>
<P>
   He said a grocery store chain in Michigan lets its top
performers pick their own schedules, which include an option to
work three, 13-hour days. The new shift proved to be popular and
reduced the turnover of the stars.
</P>
<P>
   A bank that ran a 24-hour call center was having a hard time
staffing weird hours, especially 6 to 9 a.m. and 6 to 10 p.m., and
offered to set up at-home operations for its top performers.
</P>
<P>
   The standards were clear _ the operators must answer by the
third ring and 95 percent of the customers had to be satisfied, he
said. Other than that, they could fix breakfast or tuck their kids
into bed.
</P>
<P>
   The results were great, he said, adding that customers were
happier and the employees didn't quit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
IDEA LONG PUT IN PRACTICE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston human resource consultant Greg Nakanishi said many line
managers have long treated top performers differently, even though
that may have flown in the face of the policies set by their human
resource department.
</P>
<P>
   But it makes sense to show favoritism to stars, said Nakanishi,
who likened the idea to pay. You pay your top performers more, so
it's just logical to give them special flexibility too, said
Nakanishi, president of GN Resources in Kingwood, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   That makes perfect sense to Carol Nichols, manager of the
statewide corporate trust department for Chase Bank of Texas.
Nichols, a line manager, said she believes employers such as Chase
have become more conscious about taking better care of their top
performers.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't, someone else will give them what they want, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   She said one of her employees got married and was moving to
California to be with her new husband. Nichols said she worked out
an arrangement so the employee, a top performer, could work from
her home with a computer. She visits Houston about twice a month,
travel expenses that Chase is only too happy to pick up, Nichols
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another employee's husband was transferred to Laredo in South
Texas and Nichols set up a similar telecommuting arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said she is willing to make the concessions to keep her
top employees, the Dennis Rodmans of the bank.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DISSENSION IN THE GROUP &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While it may be great for the favored employee, a two-tiered
system can create a lot of dissension in a work group.
</P>
<P>
   A company would need an objective measure of value and
communicate that to employees, said Kathleen Fenninger, president
of the Houston Human Resource Management Association. The
performance measures can't be wishy-washy, touchy-feely concepts
that people can't get their arms around. And that's not easy: Many
companies have a hard enough time defining performance measures for
the annual review.
</P>
<P>
   Fairness is still important, she said. How do you communicate to
employees that one of them can take her sick children to the doctor
without using sick or vacation time because she is a ``good
performer,'' yet other employees have to use accrued leave? asked
Fenninger.
</P>
<P>
   Nichols said she isn't too worried about dissension. If an
employee feels she is being treated unfairly, Nichols said she
would be happy to explain what is necessary to bring up her skill
set.
</P>
<P>
   It's true that it's easier to explain to an employee in sales
who rings up just middling sales, she said. It's indeed more
difficult to explain when the performance measures aren't as
quantifiable _ such as professionalism and initiative.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
