almost everything.'' By 1985, Anderson had located a half dozen
similar patients in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson's colleague told Springer about him, the two
began working together. Studying blood samples from Anderson's
patients, they verified that the white blood cells would not clump
together, as normal white blood cells do, thus strongly suggesting
they were missing LFA-1. Further research showed that the protein
was indeed missing.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986 the team published the result: LFA-1's target was
ICAM-1. The discovery launched an entire field of biology dedicated
to the study of cellular adhesion in the immune system.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Richard Colonno, then a molecular biologist at Merck,
now a vice president of infectious-disease drug discovery at
Bristol-Myers Squibb, showed definitively that 90 percent of all
rhinoviruses used one receptor, and the other 10 percent used
another. It meant 90 percent of half of the common cold viruses
might be stopped with the same drug, which was a large enough
percentage to justify developing a treatment and putting it on the
market.
</P>
<P>
   During the mid-'80s, Colonno and his colleagues produced an
antibody that attacked the receptor and blocked the virus from
getting into the cell and replicating _ at least in a test tube.
But when they tried to come up with a cheap version of the
antibody, they failed.
</P>
<P>
   Colonno's work, however, had spawned competition from the work
of two molecular biologists, Jeffrey Greve and Alan McClelland who
worked for Molecular Therapeutics. McClelland and Greve tried to
nail down the receptor's identity, and succeeded in pinpointing the
gene that coded for the rhinovirus receptor as well as the receptor
itself.
</P>
<P>
   Greve's laboratory purified the protein and sequenced it,
creating a precise map of the string of amino acids that composed
the protein. When researchers in Greve's lab compared their
sequence with those in a computer database of proteins previously
sequenced by other researchers, ICAM-1 matched perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to the library ... to find out what ICAM-1 was, and
came up Springer's group,'' McClelland says. Springer's ``group''
now included a pair of former researchers _ Robert Rothlein and
Steven Marlin _ who were working at Boehringer Ingleheim.
</P>
<P>
   Once Greve and McClelland realized ICAM-1 was the rhinovirus
receptor, word began to spread. Marlin got a call asking him if
ICAM-1 could be the receptor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In very short order,'' Marlin says, ''we put together concrete
information that ICAM-1 was the receptor to a major group of
rhinoviruses.''
</P>
<P>
   During the next decade BI and Bayer, the company that owns
Molecular Therapeutics, raced to get a cold cure to market first.
Both teams hit on the same strategy. They produced a form of ICAM-1
that was not rooted in the cell walls but was soluble. They could
squirt it into noses in the hope that the rhinovirus would snatch
up the free-floating ICAM-1 and never get around to grabbing the
ICAM-1 receptors that let it into the cells. The strategy is a
''decoy effect,'' Marlin says.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of problems had to be solved first, however. For
instance, your nose produces mucus as a barrier to foreign
particles. Could soluble ICAM-1 survive, or would the mucus break
it down and wash it away before it had the chance to decoy any
rhinovirus?
</P>
<P>
   The researchers also had to prove that the soluble ICAM would
work on all or most of the 90-plus strains of rhinovirus.
Reassuringly, their experiments showed that the virus seemed to
remain susceptible to the ICAM decoys, at least in test tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Whether ICAM is good enough to make a marketable cold treatment
remains to be seen. McClelland, for one, calls it a good shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's the kind of approach that, even if it doesn't
work, will certainly have advanced our understanding quite a bit.
And _ who knows? _ maybe it will work. The common cold has caused
enough problems for us all. It would be nice to have something you
could just take and be done with it.''
</P>
<P>
   _______
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Taubes, a contributing editor at Discover magazine, won
the 1997 Pan American Health Organization award for excellence in
international health reporting.) &LR;  &QL; 
