<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCGRORY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAHEY LOSES ITS HEART DOCTOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was a wisp of a man, really, small in size but huge in
stature, his very presence able to fill a room, even an entire
life, which was precisely Dr. Warren Nugent's intent. In the
process of saving lives, he also filled them _ with hope, with
humor, and with dignity for those resigned to the dark possibility
that they may never grasp such feelings again.
</P>
<P>
   He combined the manner of a country doctor with the intellect of
one of the foremost specialists of his kind. He was in demand the
world over on the lecture circuit, the recipient of too many
medical honors to fit on any normal man's shelf. Back at home,
though, at the Lahey Clinic in Burlington, Mass., his patients knew
him best for his simple, unfailing kindness, his willingness to
talk them through the toughest of times and invest himself in their
needs.
</P>
<P>
   All along, he taught crucial lessons of character, not only in
the way he lived his life, but last week, in the way he died.
</P>
<P>
   Medical schools don't teach their students how to inform a
14-year-old girl that her colon must be removed and explain the
humiliating side effects that linger the rest of her life. But with
his silvery-white hair and his soothing voice, Dr. Nugent knew how,
with a grace uncommon in the halls of any hospital.
</P>
<P>
   His was the unalluring field of gastroenterology. His mission,
though, was the human heart. ``He thought it was important for
people not to get depressed by the disease,'' says his Lahey
colleague, Dr. Andrew Warner. ``He encouraged people to get out and
do something, to join a team or play an instrument, to be active in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the product of a time when the medical profession was
imperial, the individual doctors imperious. Decades later, he saw
the dawn of an age when doctors became known in bureaucratic
parlance as care providers, burdened with triplicate insurance
forms while taking instructions from an accountant on the other end
of the line. Yet Dr. Nugent always did it his own way. The diseases
he treated were chronic, his patients with him for life. He guided
the sick through graduations, marriages, and parenthood, creating
bonds, becoming a steady voice of calm.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Fran Wojnoski. Her prior doctors wanted to
remove her intestine, leaving her in the unpleasant need of a
colostomy bag. Dr. Nugent instead recommended an experimental
treatment involving an overnight intravenous feed that pumped
nutrients into her body in lieu of food.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't met him, they would have taken my insides out,''
says Wojnoski. ``If I hadn't met him, I'd probably be dead. He'd
take an hour on the phone with you if you needed him. If I called,
he'd see me immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   He was revered by doctors and nurses alike at the world-renowned
Lahey Clinic he called his home. He treasured them in return. He
arrived in 1954, learned gastroenterology at the knee of the
legendary doctor Sara Jordan, and never strayed anywhere else. He
became chairman of the department, was heralded from afar, and
received patients from every corner of the globe, especially from
his native Canada.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Joan, says he whistled every day as he left for work,
so happy with his lot. He was slightly shorter than the 5 feet, 7
inches that he often proclaimed, with curly, close-cut hair and a
frame kept trim on the ski slopes and his backyard tennis court in
Medfield _ an unusual indulgence in a modest life. He decorated his
office wall with fishing flies.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Nugent tried retiring in 1990, but it didn't quite take.
Truth is, he didn't know the business end of a hammer from the head
of a nail, so handy work was out, and you can play only so much
tennis over the course of a day. Two years later, he was back in
the office, seeing his patients and training his successor, Dr.
Warner, in the way to soothe a soul.
</P>
<P>
   ``You learn about diseases in medical school, and how to treat
patients in a hospital,'' says Warner. ``He taught me how to relate
to people in their whole lives.''
</P>
<P>
   He retired for good in 1995. Alzheimer's disease began setting
in shortly after. He fought it off in the best way he could, by
staying active and traveling. He continued an annual sojourn to a
fishing lodge in Canada with family and friends. He skiied as
recently as last year.
</P>
<P>
   Four months ago, the disease began to overcome. Three weeks ago,
his family checked him into Lahey. On Saturday afternoon (3/13),
with his wife, four sons, and daughter surrounding his bed, Dr.
Nugent died at the age of 75. It is less an irony than an act of
great intent that he took his last breath in the hospital he so
loved, a place where he not only saved lives, but filled them with
hope, humor, and dignity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Brian McGrory's e-mail address is mcgrory(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
