<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOTT'S EXCUSES FOR RACISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At a press conference last week, a reporter willing to pester
politicians on such trivial matters as bigotry, racism, and white
supremacy asked Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, ``Senator, can
you explain why you wouldn't support a resolution to censure the
Council of Conservative Citizens . . . ?
</P>
<P>
   Lott responded, ``I think if anybody wants to have a resolution
condemning any groups that advocate, you know, white supremacy or
racism, you know, we should support that. But when you start naming
one group over another group, or this group or that group, the list
is going to get to be pretty long, and that would be the wrong
approach.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a follow-up. ``But you all did that with the Khalid
Muhammad resolution several years ago and everybody supported that,
you know.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said, ``That was one individual. Are we going to start
doing that repeatedly, naming individuals and groups?''
</P>
<P>
   There was another follow-up. ``That doesn't seem hypocritical,
you supporting one and not the other?''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said, ``No. No, no, no. It doesn't seem hypocritical to
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott is the devilish dodger who has yet to break a sweat in the
three months that have passed since articles in The Washington Post
and The New York Times detailed Lott's cozy ties with the C of CC.
The 15,000-member group has a thick lineage to the racist white
citizens councils of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Its Web page is a current linkage to 1990s hate. Either its own
page or the pages of organizations that link back to the council
are engines of paranoia, desperately trying to prove black genetic
inferiority and the harm done to straight, white, Anglo-Saxon men
by Jews, homosexuals, and feminists.
</P>
<P>
   The C of CC's Web page has been praised by Web pages that also
support the Ku Klux Klan, Aryan Nations, and David Duke.
</P>
<P>
   The articles forced Lott to distance himself from the council.
``I have made my condemnation of the white supremacist and racist
view of this group, or any group, clear.''
</P>
<P>
   But he quickly muddied the water with the incredible claim that
he had ``no firsthand knowledge'' of it, despite having made
speeches before the group in the 1990s, despite the fact that an
uncle declared him an honorary member, despite the fact that he
never protested the use of his Senate column in the council's
newsletter, despite having had top officials of the group visit him
in Washington in 1997 and despite posing with a smile for a photo
with the officials.
</P>
<P>
   The condemnation became even more hollow when Democratic
congressmen Robert Wexler of Florida and James Clyburn of South
Carolina last month introduced a resolution to condemn the council.
As of early this week, the resolution has 132 signatures, including
10 Republicans. Wexler contacted Lott's office to invite him to
introduce a similar resolution in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, as you can see, is refusing. This is despite the fact that
Lott was one of the senators who voted, 97-0 in 1994 to condemn the
hate speech of Muhammad, a previously unknown aide to Louis
Farrakhan in the Nation of Islam.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it all comes down to,'' Wexler said last week, ``is when
it is a black person who is racist, it's OK to condemn that
invidividual and single him out, but when it is a white person or
white group, that it is not OK to single out that group.''
</P>
<P>
   That observation is shared by NAACP chairman Julian Bond. When
the African-American mayor of Washington, D.C., momentarily
accepted the resignation of a white aide who used the word
``niggardly,'' a word with no racial meaning, Bond said he received
50 telephone calls from the media, including one from Australian
public radio. As of Thursday, Bond said he has received only six or
seven calls from the media about Lott.
</P>
<P>
   ``I brought it up with Arlen Specter and Mitch McConnell,'' Bond
said. ``I said, `What are you going to do about Trent Lott?' They
said, `What about Trent Lott?' even though this had been in several
articles and columns in the Post.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Republican senators also voted to condemn Muhammad's
speech. Bond said, ``What this says is that white bigotry is so
ordinary, so everyday that it can pass without notice, even if you
cannot even begin to compare the proportionality between this
obscure figure of Muhammad and Lott, one of the most powerful men
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott should no longer be obscure and obtuse about the council.
If the United States Senate can stop to condemn Muhammad, a
crackpot with no influence, it must be used to condemn a council
powerful enough to have Lott, Representative Bob Barr, and
Mississippi Governor Kirk Fordice as keynote speakers.
</P>
<P>
   The battle to turn up the heat resumed Thursday, when Wexler
held a press conference with several civil rights organizations.
But Wexler needs help. Perhaps when Julian Bond gets 50 phone calls
on Trent Lott, we can begin to predict the day that Lott makes the
only condemnation that now matters, in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
