<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6709 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDDLEBURY-2     03-19 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-MIDDLEBURY-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 MIDDLEBURY, Vt.: ... the family.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If that seems simplistic, something has to explain why the
Panthers have prevailed in virtually every circumstance: as an
unknown commodity in 1995, the second year New England Small
College Athletic Conference members were allowed to compete in the
national tournament, ``and a lot of the kids didn't know the
difference between the ECACs and the NCAAs,'' says Beaney. In 1996,
when the pressure to repeat was tangible and the Final Four was in
hostile Wisconsin. In 1997, when many of the core players had
departed and the expectations were relatively modest. And in 1998,
when the seniors were seeking perfection, another generation of
contributors had been lost, the national record was at stake, ``and
it was almost a relief when we won,'' says Beaney.
</P>
<P>
   Something must explain why freshmen scored the winning goal in
the national final for three straight years before this year's
captain, Nickolai Bobrov of St. Petersburg, Russia, and Belmont
Hill, broke the string last year as a junior. ``Just when they
expect one thing, we throw something different at them,'' says
Giannacopoulos, who did the honors as a freshman in '97. ``Maybe
this year we'll have the goalie do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And something must explain why this year's team _ which rolled
the dice by bypassing the ECAC tourney (NESCAC teams can play in
only one postseason event), then sweated out an NCAA bid, which it
received only because the selection committee chose five Eastern
schools _ is back within hailing distance of the national summit.
</P>
<P>
   Bobrov thinks it's the Panther prototype, once suggested by
Beaney but in recent years demanded by the upperclassmen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unsaid rule,'' says Bobrov. ``We assume it together.
We try to get the young guys up to speed, teach them the tradition
on and off the ice. We want to uphold the Middlebury style, promote
the integrity of the game and the role of the hockey player as role
model.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes community outreach, again initially mandated by
Beaney and now standard operating procedure among the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the players place more demands on themselves than the
coaches do,'' says Beaney.
</P>
<P>
   They work on projects such as local blood drives, speak at high
schools, assist with various youth hockey programs, and go a bit
beyond. Tuesday's pre-practice skate included third-grader Jonathan
Grohs, at whose school McKee is a guidance counselor. The boy's
father died March 6, ``and this is so special for him,'' said his
aunt, Trudy Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   When a local sports psychologist was recovering from a heart
attack suffered at a recent game, Beaney suggested that it might be
nice for the team to send him a get-well card. ``Coach,'' he was
told, ``we already did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing stressed early on,'' says Sealfon, another of this
year's captains, ``is that the way the players act off the ice
reflects on the whole team.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it seems the Panthers have carried town-gown
relations to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, the first national title was achieved at arctic,
ancient Duke Nelson Arena, the Panthers' home until plush Kenyon
opened as part of a $17.5 million renovation this past January. The
players' first act as college kings was to scale the glass behind
their net _ right into the delirious embrace of the townspeople who
had been encamping there long before any titles were at stake.
``And it's not hero worship,'' says Beaney.
</P>
<P>
   What it seems to be is genuine affection. The locals who work at
Kenyon part-time find their way into the players' hearts each game
when they turn an unused locker room into an unofficial hospitality
suite for the Panthers, replete with a menu that on any given night
can include homemade chili, barbecued chicken wings, or similar
combustible delicacies.
</P>
<P>
   The support assumes more dramatic forms as well. The Panthers
finished this regular season at Williams, knowing they needed a win
to have even a remote shot at an NCAA invitation. When they arrived
in Williamstown, Mass., after a bus ride of more than two hours,
they were almost too shocked to disembark. Awaiting them was an
honor guard of Panther loyalists that stretched from the bus to the
arena entrance, through the lobby, and on to the visitors' locker
room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd heard a few people were coming,'' says Giannacopoulos.
``But I didn't believe this. The support here is unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it wasn't just students,'' says Beaney. ``Townspeople from
every walk of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Middlebury wound up winning, 5-2, then was kept in suspense for
15 days before getting an NCAA slot, albeit with an unwelcome trip
west.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew there was a chance we wouldn't make it,'' says Beaney.
``But you know what? That would have meant our last memories of
this season would have been the Williams game. And that's not such
a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And,'' says Giannacopoulos, ``we would have come out here to
finish the three-on-three, anyway, with or without the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now they can achieve both objectives, though winning the big
tournament is hardly a given. Despite their survival at St. Norbert
_ thanks to a deciding goal by, naturally, a freshman, Ryan
Constantine _ the Panthers won't be favored. Then again, they
weren't supposed to get this far.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was expected to be a rebuilding year,'' says junior
goalie Jon Marsh, a transfer who began his career at the Air Force
Academy and has compiled a 17-5-1 record while trying to keep this
drive for five alive. ``I think we've still got some playing left,
whether it's one or two more games.''
</P>
<P>
   If it's one game, that won't mean failure. ``The national
championship is the ultimate destination,'' says Giannacopoulos.
``But there's a lot of steps before that. We've got to walk
together.''
</P>
<P>
   If they ascend the mountaintop one more time, they'll add
another gold watch, courtesy of the NCAA, and another gold ring,
courtesy of the school, to their jewelry collection.
</P>
<P>
   With sundry choices, Beaney always wears his 1996 ring ``because
of where we won it and who we beat (RIT).''
</P>
<P>
   He has another reason for wearing it, but like the success of
his program, its significance is below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is kind of special,'' says Beaney. He takes off the ring
to reveal an inscription on the underside. ``Each year's team has a
slogan,'' he says. ``They engrave it on the ring. This one was,
`Find A Way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   What's the 1999 slogan?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' says Beaney, smiling. ``The players haven't
told me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's their slogan. Their team. Their dynasty.
</P>
</TEXT>
