<SLUG> BC-HKC-NCAA-UNH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNH AIIMING FOR ITS FIRST TOURNEY TITLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The University of New Hampshire, its first outright Hockey East
regular-season championship in the bank, starts its quest for
another first this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats clinched their first regular-season league title
with a weekend sweep of Maine two weeks ago. And now they will take
a run at their first Hockey East tournament title.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 1-seeded Wildcats take on No. 4 Providence in the first
semifinal at the FleetCenter at 5. No. 2 seed Maine and No. 3
Boston College play in the second game, scheduled for 8. The
winners play Satuday at 7 for the title.
</P>
<P>
   There are incentives aplenty this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Providence probably needs to win the event to get into the NCAA
Tournament, which begins next weekend in Worcester and Madison,
Wis.
</P>
<P>
   UNH has a spot in the NCAAs locked up with its regular-season
title, and Maine and BC will receive at-large berths if they don't
get the guaranteed spot for winning this tournament. But where the
teams will be seeded will depend on weekend results.
</P>
<P>
   Boston College is looking for a second-straight league
tournament title and to regain the form that took the Eagles to the
national championship game last year and had them ranked No. 1 in
the country in preseason.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's seniors are seeking their first league title and the
team's first since 1995. The Black Bears also want to tune up for
their first NCAA appearance since 1995. Maine, which was 17-15-4
last year, has lost in the league championship game two of the last
three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Black Bears hold a 2-1 edge over Boston College this year,
splitting their two games at Conte Forum and winning, 6-4, in their
last meeting, in Orono Feb. 13.
</P>
<P>
   UNH has a 2-1 edge on Providence as well. The teams split a pair
of games in early November and the Wildcats took a 4-2 decision in
Providence Jan. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, UNH was the No. 3 seed and was upset in the Hockey
East quarterfinals by Maine. This year, fueled by the sweep of
Maine and last weekend's sweep of Merrrimack, the Wildcats come to
the FleetCenter confident.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question the level of play goes up a notch each weekend
from here on in,'' said UNH defenseman and captain Steve O'Brien of
Braintree and Catholic Memorial. ``It will be tough, but if we play
our game, we can win those championships.''
</P>
<P>
   It starts with Providence against Friar guns such as Mike
Omicioli, Fernando Pisani, and Jerry Keefe. ``It's going to take
our team doing our systems in all three zones,'' O'Brien said.
``We've got to be physical like we were against Maine. We've got to
stay in other teams' faces. With guys like Omicioli and Keefe we've
got to put pressure on and not give them much space or time to do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   UNH has appeared in only two tournament championship games,
losing to Maine, 4-1, in 1992, and to Boston University, 4-2, in
1997. Providence won the tournament with a 3-2 win over Maine in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case for the last three years, the Wildcats will
be led by forward Jason Krog (30 goals, 45 assists in 36 games).
Last Saturday night he had a career-best four goals in a 5-4 win
over Merrimack that boosted the Wildcats into the semifinals.
Darren Haydar, his freshman linemate, had the other goal. And Mike
Souza, a junior from Wakefield who lines up with them, had three
assists.
</P>
<P>
   Krog led a UNH sweep of Hockey East's top awards. He was named
Player of the Year, Dick Umile was named Coach of the Year, and
Haydar Rookie of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Krog, Maine's Steve Kariya, and BC's Brian Gionta were named
Hockey East's first-team all-star forwards. Maine's David Cullen
and UNH's Jayme Filipowicz were the first-team defensemen, and BU's
Michel Larocque was the goalie.
</P>
<P>
   Krog, Kariya, Gionta, and Larocque were the Hockey East picks
among the 10 finalists for the Hobey Baker Award, given to the best
player in Division 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
