<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SNOW-SHOEING THE NATION'S FASTEST-GROWING WINTER SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
(poetry style) 
 
There's a patch of old snow in a corner 
That I could have guessed 
Was a blown-away paper the rain 
Had brought to rest. 
It is speckled with grime as if 
Small print overspread it, 
The news of a day I've forgotten _ 
If I ever read it. 
_ ROBERT FROST 
 
(end poetry style) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And so it is patch-of-old-snow season, except at ski areas,
where the building of depths is like saving money, with snowmakers
running through cold nights to give the depths their compounding
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Killington in years past has built up more than 20 feet of snow
to keep the Cascade trail skiing into June.
</P>
<P>
   But in the rest of the outdoor world, spring presents a bit of a
problem when, just before mud season, the going is soft and slushy.
Cross-country skiing is OK in some places, where the tracks have
been groomed firm, but in the mush, unless you know your klisters _
does anyone know klisters these days? _ the ski tends to collect
these huge globs of stuck snow on the scaled kick zone.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of step-glide, you clomp ahead as if you'd strapped your
feet into a pair of concrete blocks.
</P>
<P>
   But take heart, ye winter-weary, dying to get out and do . . .
something. Anything. One of the best back-country conveyances in
the most marginal, thin, rough, uneven cover remains what has
become the fastest growing winter sport in the US: snowshoeing.
</P>
<P>
   The appeal of the sport is pretty easy to fathom. In a word,
``minimalism.'' Snowshoeing requires no lifts, no lessons, no
infrastructure, no prepared trails of any kind. And shoeing, as one
aficionado friend is fond of saying, is the kind of discipline in
which one advances from beginner to intermediate in about 20
minutes, the initial lesson being how to wind the straps around
one's boots.
</P>
<P>
   Which, by the way, is also a piece of good news. Though some
entrepreneurial wise guys have marketed a boot designed for
snowshoeing, treat this with the same caveat emptor your might a
pet rock. Plain old hiking or outdoor boots will do fine.
</P>
<P>
   Just three years ago, in the 1995-96 snow season, the National
Sporting Goods Association reported that 400,000 people were
snowshoeing. The next season that figure leaped to 660,000, and
last season more than a million Americans were out busting through
woods and meadows with their now lightweight, thoroughly modern
equipment. Plastic and strong lightweight alloys have transformed
the sport from the old wood-frame days.
</P>
<P>
   Again, what separates snowshoeing from anything else done on
snow is its range and flexibility. And as early spring arrives with
its tremendous variety of conditions _ from rock hard mornings to
slushy afternoons _ snowshoeing is up to all of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people show up to ski and the conditions are marginal,
they might not want to get out there,'' says Brendan Sullivan, a
former US Ski Team racer who directs the cross-country center at
Bretton Woods. ``But then we have snowshoes for them, and that
takes the excuses away. They can still go out there and have a
winter wilderness experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Like others in the industry, Sullivan has seen snowshoeing take
off in the last few years. This is partly due to the product and
all its plusses, but another boost comes from the snowshoe
manufacturers who have given attractive discounts to cross-country
ski areas to buy and rent their products at a relatively low price.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a smart marketing move for them,'' says Sullivan, ``to
target the same market (as Nordic skiers) and give them the
option.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many skiers either carry a pair of snowshoes in the car
when they head north, or drop into rental shops to pick them up at
a cost of $10 to $12 a day. Snowshoe prices range from around $100
to $180, depending on quality, size, or weight-bearing capacity.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, proponents of cross-country skiing would say, ``If
you can walk, you can cross-country ski.'' This was an interesting
reversal of history, since cross-country was trying to market
itself as an alternative to Alpine skiing, a relative newcomer to
snow sports. The pitch line was not entirely true.
</P>
<P>
   It is for snowshoeing, however. ``Especially if people use
poles,'' says Sullivan, ``if they can walk, they can put on a pair
of snowshoes with those crampons and feel solid on anything they
walk on _ ice, groomed trails, or ungroomed.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter idea is discouraged for obvious reasons, he adds.
Straying from groomed trails in the forest around the base of Mt.
Washington, for instance, could result in getting lost.
</P>
<P>
   But the temptaiton when shoeing is always to get off the groomed
trail and hit the woods, where the deep snow is. And it's
particularly fun climbing up mountains through wilderness terrain.
</P>
<P>
   What also must be said for cross-country skiing is that
snow-shoeing has none of that smooth, exhilarating glide, speed, or
grace that make Nordic skiing so beautiful and satisfying.
</P>
<P>
   But when the melt is on, followed by those crusty old patches of
snow in the woods, the spring move is easy, say aficionados, who
have even established snowshoe race circuits and orienteering meets
on shoes. Strap on a pair, and just take off. Easy as that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
