<HEADLINE>
GO LIGHTLY WITH SOAP PADS ON OLD GALVY CREAM CAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have a nice old galvanized milk can, actually a smaller
sized cream can, that has my grandfather's name on it. I'd like to
clean it up some, but how? It is not rusting.
</P>
<P>
   LEONARD O'HARA, Plymouth, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Since the can is a family heirloom with a provenance
(significant background), and possibly worth more than you realize,
you may not want to do much to it at all. Too much cleaning and/or
refinishing antiques can reduce their value. I suggest washing it
with detergent and water, and scrubbing lightly with a bristle
scrub brush; rinse and let dry. Or, rub lightly with soap pads,
just to get surface dirt off, not to cut through the galvanizing;
rinse and let dry; be content with that. Rub very lightly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have clumps of moss in the ridge of my house in New
Hampshire. It is real moss, not algae. How can I remove it without
wrecking the asphalt shingles?
</P>
<P>
   BARRY BERKAL, Swampscott, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Moss has very shallow roots, so you should be able to scrape
it off carefully with a wide putty knife or, more safely, a wood
spatula or similar wide-bladed wood tool. After that, scrub off
residue with a bristle scrub brush. Then, apply a mix of one part
bleach and three parts water to kill any residue. Incidentally,
moss is great stuff _ in the right place: a shady corner of the
yard or similar area. It is maintenance free and will look good,
going dormant in winter and coming right back in spring. The
Japanese revere certain types (there are many kinds), and Americans
should learn to live with it. But not on the roof.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I plan to put up vinyl siding and replace windows. The walls
are covered with asphalt shingles, very thick and pretty ugly. The
siding people say they can put the vinyl right over the asphalt. Is
that a good way to do it?
</P>
<P>
   CONCERNED, in Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. No, it is not a good way to do it. If anything is uglier than
vinyl, it is asphalt siding, which pretended to be brick or wood or
other natural products, and never worked. Later, the cover-uppers
used asbestos cement shingles, which caused their own problems and
still didn't look like wood. Then there was aluminum, finally
vinyl, which the siding people like to say is final, but still
doesn't look like wood.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, I think the asphalt should come off, no matter how
expensive it is to remove and dispose of because it is a hazardous
waste.
</P>
<P>
   Vinyl or any other covering over the asphalt will not be even or
smooth because of the uneven surface of the asphalt, despite
putting an underlayment on first. Besides, you are adding another
layer, bringing the wall out even further, which may require new
molding around window and door casings.
</P>
<P>
   There are probably old wood clapboards or wood shingles under
the asphalt, and putting vinyl over this rather even surface would
result in a fairly decent-looking siding. Just hope that the wood
under the asphalt has not rotted out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My niece painted the baby's room recently, and spilled half a
gallon of latex paint on the wall-to-wall carpet, creating a stain
about two by two feet. With much gnashing of teeth and long, hard
scrubbing with water, the stain is gone and the carpet looks good.
The paint was pretty close to the color of the carpet. But it is
stiff as a board. How can we soften it?
</P>
<P>
   G.T.C., Burlington, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. It's the paint that was not removed that is stiffening the
carpet. What you have to do is knead the carpet to try to break up
the paint that is sticking to the fibers. Try vacuuming the spot,
really pushing the cleaner bar against it. If you have a beater
bar, use it. Repeat this as often as your energy holds up. Another
trick: Lift the carpet as you would lift a dog by the scruff of the
neck, and knead the carpet, rubbing it against itself.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes scraping a wood board over the spot will help break up
the paint. Don't try paint remover or anything to soften the paint
because anything like that will stain the carpet.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My mahogany coffee table has a leather top, which has a few
white stains on it. How can I remove them? Also, a black leather
pocketbook was left beside a white leather one, and some of the
white came off on the black. And how can I get that white off the
black?
</P>
<P>
   HELEN YOUNG, Weston, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. For the stains on the top, try rubbing them with a little
toothpaste. There's just enough abrasive to take off the very top
of the finished leather, enough to remove the stains without
spoiling the leather. You could try the same with the pocketbook.
</P>
<P>
   If you are leery about either of these techniques, you can use
an Apple Leather Care product made by Apple Polishers of Stow. The
company makes a number of products, including Leather Cleaner, an
aggressive cleaner designed to safely clean finished leather. Call
800-800-5803 or 978-562-4333.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader
questions. Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107. The
Handyman chats on line Thursdays, 1-2 p.m, at
http://www.boston.com, keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
