<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONEY MARKET MUTUAL FUND CAN IMPROVE SAVINGS EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am a 16-year-old girl who has saved about $5,000 through
baby-sitting jobs, etc. It is currently in a savings account
earning negligible interest. I would like to invest it so that when
I am in my mid-twenties I will be able to buy a car. What sorts of
stocks, bonds or mutual funds would you recommend?
</P>
<P>
   V.R., Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Basically, there are two courses you might take to improve
your returns. Most bank savings accounts do indeed provide a
negligible interest return. You can probably come close to doubling
the interest level if you went with a money market mutual fund _
getting perhaps 5 percent rather than the 2 1/2 to 3 percent you're
probably getting now. Such an account left alone for nine years
would grow to $7,757 over nine years _ not enough for a splashy new
car, but a nice start. With this investment, you would face, well .
. . a negligible level of risk.
</P>
<P>
   When you get into stocks and bonds and the mutual funds that
invest in them, the risk is no longer negligible. You might pick a
relatively low-risk fund that divides its investments between
stocks and bonds. One idea here is that the conservative
investments in bonds will reduce the risk inherent in the stock
markets. Another is that the bond and stock markets often move in
opposite directions, so if the stock portion of the portfolio is
heading south, at least in theory the bond portfolio will
strengthen and ease your losses.
</P>
<P>
   Balanced funds are good for what investors call
intermediate-term investments _ money that's being put away for a
period that might range from five to ten years.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity Puritan fund is an excellent example of such an
balanced fund. If you look at its record in detail for the past ten
years, it will give you a general sense of what to expect, both in
terms of general long-term results and how frustrating owning such
funds can be at times. During that decade, the fund produced
average total returns of 14.32 percent a year. But that average is
far from consistent. During those years, returns ranged from a high
of 24.46 percent (in 1991) to a low of minus 6.35 percent (in
1990). So you'll have to think a while about how you'd feel if you
put $5,000 in such a fund, only to find that it was worth $4,500,
or even less, a year hence. Still, if you are in for a nine- or
ten-year haul, the odds are excellent that the good years will far
outweigh the bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   But don't count on anything like that 14 percent figure I
mentioned above. Almost everybody who follows the stock markets
thinks the past ten years have been exceptional, and it's not
realistic to expect that such heady gains will continue.
</P>
<P>
   But I do think it's reasonable to hope for 8 percent average
returns, and if that happened your money (at least on paper) would
almost precisely double by the time you're 25 years old, growing
from your initial $5,000 to $9,996.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a civil service employee, 44, and I will be eligible for
retirement in 2011. I contribute the maximum allowed to the Thrift
Savings Plan and have the following assets: IRAs of $21,500 in
Vanguard Star, $12,000 in Janus, and $6,000 in Cisco Systems common
stock. I also have $15,000 in Franklin US Government Securities,
$9,000 in Washington Mutual Investors, and $40,000 in a credit
union's money market account. I want to be more aggressive. I'm
considering moving most of the Vanguard money to Vanguard Growth
and Income, with perhaps 10 percent of it going to Vanguard Health
Care. Would you recommend consolidating any of the accounts?
</P>
<P>
   M.P., La Mesa, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. I like your thinking, but I don't think you're proposing to
go far enough. And not only do I think you shouldn't consolidate
your fund positions _ I think you should diversify still further.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, when you liquidate the Vanguard Star position, I
suggest you divide the proceeds evenly between Vanguard Growth and
Income and Vanguard Specialized Health Care. Such a move would put
the Health Care position at roughly at 10 percent of the total
portfolio, and would add a lot more growth potential.
</P>
<P>
   If you indeed want to take a more aggressive stance, I'm sure
you've realized that the two positions that are most likely to drag
down portfolio are the government bond fund and your big money
market position. Why not divide the money now in Franklin US
Government Securities fund between Franklin Income, a balanced fund
with a relatively modest stock allocation, and Franklin Rising
Dividends, a mid-cap stock fund.
</P>
<P>
   As for the money market account, I suggest you begin by deciding
how much money you feel you would need as emergency savings to be
comfortable.Whatever the amount, I'd move it amount to a good
mutual fund money market account, which is likely to offer a
dramatically higher yield than what you're getting with the credit
union, and would provide similar liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a 31-year-old woman with no debts and the following
investments: I have a 401(k) plan at work now worth $13,000, with
20 percent invested in Fidelity Spartan U.S. Market Index fund, 30
percent in Baron Asset fund, and 25 percent each in Fidelity
Magellan and Fidelity Freedom 2020 funds; I add $480 a month to
this account. I also have a $10,000 account with Janus funds, with
the investments evenly divided among Janus fund, Janus 20, Janus
Worldwide Janus Global Technology, and its money market fund, and I
add $500 a month to these accounts. I also have 80 shares of Exxon
Corp. and add $150 a month to this investment through its dividend
reinvestment program. Finally, I have $10,000 in a money market
fund. I have no plans such as buying a house or a car in the near
future. Is the distribution of my money appropriate?
</P>
<P>
   E.S., Acton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You are doing a terrific job of developing your portfolio,
and if you can maintain the disciplines of diversification and
saving, you will have a mammoth nestegg by the time you're 65 --
nearly $4.4 million based on assumed 10 percent average annual
growth and contributions at the current level. (And that doesn't
factor in your $10,000 money market account, which I presume to be
emergency savings.) I probably would have looked for a health care
sector fund rather than going with Janus brand-new Global
Technology fund, but certainly you've moved into one of the two
sectors that are most likely to outperform over the long haul. I
think I also would have selected Janus Overseas rather than Janus
Worldwide, arguing that the 56 percent of the Worldwide portfolio
that's invested in U.S. equities duplicates the positions in your
traditional domestic growth funds; with Janus Overseas you would
get a pure international play. If I were you I would make that
switch right now, and at some point in the future I suggest you add
a health care sector fund to the mix. But that's all quibbling --
you're doing a great job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Send letters, including your name, address and telephone
number, to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
