<HEADLINE>
IRELAND'S CORRS FAMILY: SIBLING HARMONY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a busy St. Patrick's Day for the Corrs. The Irish
pop-rockers arose at 4 in the morning on Wednesday in Manhattan to
prepare for the ``Today Show,'' then caught their breath and headed
over to the ``Rosie O'Donnell Show.'' That was just the morning.
That afternoon, they had another steady diet of interviews, before
playing their evening gig at Roseland Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   The Corrs _ sisters Andrea, Sharon, and Caroline and their
brother, Jim _ are in heavy demand everywhere these days. They have
sold 4 million albums overseas, where their stardom has moved from
Ireland to the continent, and especially to England, where the
Corrs CD, ``Talk on Corners,'' has been No. 1 for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The next boundary to fall is the United States, where the Corrs
are determined to achieve similar recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes repeated returns to America to break through,'' says
guitarist Jim Corr. ``America is so huge _ it's like 50 countries
in one. But we feel we have laid the foundation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Corrs are not everyone's pint of Guinness _ they can sound
sticky-sweet at times _ but there is a growing depth that is hard
to deny. ``Talk on Corners'' has a tune cowritten with Alanis
Morissette producer Glen Ballard and another with the veteran
hitmaker Carole Bayer Sager. There are entrancing covers of Jimi
Hendrix's ``Little Wing'' and Fleetwood Mac's ``Dreams.'' Drummer
Mick Fleetwood even sat in on this song during the group's PBS
special, ``Live at Royal Albert Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very nice what Mick said about us. He said, `I love
this band. They play with passion,' '' notes Corr proudly during
our phone conversation.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a passion to rival that of fellow countrymen U2, but
it's a sincere enthusiasm as the group merges pop, rock, and the
traditional sounds of fiddle and pennywhistle. ``We go off in
directions that might not be predictable,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Corrs started playing music at their home north of Dublin,
where their parents sometimes played in a cover band. Singer
Andrea, the youngest at 24, is also an actress and appeared in the
Irish film ``The Commitments'' (``she played the sister of the
band's manager and got to speak a few rude lines,'' says Jim) and
in ``Evita,'' where she played Juan Peron's mistress.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Corrs, who are influenced by everyone from Irish
groups Horslips and Moving Hearts, to the Eagles and the Police,
kept working on their music and have improved to the point where
they were asked by the Rolling Stones to recently open five dates
of their American arena tour.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what it's like to be the only brother in a group with
three oft-described beautiful women, Jim offers this quick, nicely
diplomatic response: ``I don't see three beautiful women. I see my
sisters. This is complete normality for me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remains reunite: Barry &AMP; the Remains were the original hot
property of Boston's garage-rock scene. The group attended Boston
University, cut its teeth on gigs at the Rathskellar in Kenmore
Square, was the first local band to sign with a major label (Epic
Records). They achieved pop immortality by opening a Beatles tour
in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``We toured with the Beatles for three weeks and 14 cities. It
turned out to be their last tour and our last tour as well,'' says
Barry Tashian, who later played with Gram Parsons, Emmylou Harris,
and his wife Holly in the duo Barry and Holly Tashian.
</P>
<P>
   Spurred by the success of '60s garage-rock compilations (such as
the ``Nuggets'' series on Rhino Records, which has featured the
Remains' seminal ``Diddy Wah Diddy''), and by the success of a book
he wrote about the Beatles tour (``Ticket to Ride''), Tashian
reformed the Remains last year. They'll play their first,
welcome-back Boston gig Saturday, sharing a bill with the Lost,
another reunited '60s band that stars Willie Alexander, a Boston
rock legend. The show's emcee will be Peter Wolf of J. Geils Band
fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first (comeback) date was last year at a festival in Leon,
Spain,'' Tashian says from his home in Nashville. ``It was
fantastic. A couple thousand kids were there. The average age was
25 and they were going crazy for the band. We played all our stuff
and they knew all the words. We were later told there are 70 bands
in Spain covering Remains material. We knew nothing about that, so
it was overwhelming to us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Remains had more than their 15 minutes of fame in the '60s.
They were on ``The Ed Sullivan Show'' and ``Hullabaloo.'' They
played Boston Garden with the Dave Clark Five. They broke up only
after Tashian realized that they would never be as big as the
Beatles.
</P>
<P>
   But, responding to the ``magic'' of the '60s, Tashian says that
``we're rocking again and people are telling us that we're still
nailing it.'' The rest of the Remains are original members as well:
keyboardist Bill Briggs (who has been selling cars in Burlington),
bassist Vern Miller (a music teacher in New Jersey), and drummer
Chip Damiani (a contractor in New Haven).
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just taking things one day at a time,'' says Tashian.
``But it's amazing that the four of us are still here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------ &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coffeetable Stones: A lavishly beautiful, photo-oriented tome,
``The Rolling Stones: A Life on the Road,'' is now on sale.
Combining concert photos from the past 35 years, along with
interviews, it was compiled by Dora Lowenstein, daughter of
longtime Stones business manager Prince Rupert Lowenstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started talking about it in 1994,'' she says. ``I had the
idea of doing a program for the `Voodoo Lounge'' tour, but that
transformed into a book of the tour and then more.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein had access to the Stones archives and to the band
members, who consulted on the book. ``They had direct involvement
and looked at all the designs,'' she says of the Stones.
</P>
<P>
   Lowenstein, now 32, has seen more than 100 Stones shows. She
also has her own firm, Dora Lowenstein Associates, which organizes
all of the Stones's parties, from backstage affairs to the Prince
of Wales Heritage Fund Weekend. Not a bad job.
</P>
</TEXT>
