<HEADLINE>
LYCOS TEAMS WITH HSN TO SELL FINAL FOUR GOODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet portal Lycos Inc., struggling to preserve its merger
with assets of USA Networks Inc., is launching an important
business venture with one of USA Networks' best-known companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Home Shopping Network (HSN), one of the USA Networks firms
that is to merge with Lycos, will team up with Lycos this weekend
in a campaign to sell merchandise related to the NCAA Final Four
college basketball championship. Lycos will sell basketball
memorabilia on a special Internet site that will promote other
products for sale on HSN's TV channel. Meanwhile, the TV network
will flash advertisements for basketball merchandise for sale on
the Lycos Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be harnessing our on-line eyeballs to sell
product,'' said Jeff Bennett, vice president of electronic commerce
at Lycos. ``HSN is going to be our partner in on-air promotion and
fulfillment.''
</P>
<P>
   This is hardly an unusual campaign for Lycos. Earlier this year
the company worked with the National Football League to set up a
promotional Web site devoted to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But this Lycos-HSN alliance is different. The Lycos Super Bowl
site sent souvenir buyers to the NFL's on-line store. In this case,
Lycos itself will sell merchandise to visitors. And all the orders
Lycos receives will be shipped through HSN's order-fulfillment
system.
</P>
<P>
   HSN's ability to ship as many as 80,000 customer orders a day is
a key selling point for Lycos' controversial plan to merge with HSN
and several other companies now owned by USA Networks. Lycos
executives have argued that other on-line firms will have to spend
as much as $500 million to build an order-fulfillment
infrastructure like HSNs. The proposed merger, they said, would
instantly give the new USA/Lycos Interactive Networks Inc. a major
advantage over other Internet retailers.
</P>
<P>
   But terms of the deal have infuriated some Lycos shareholders,
who want more for their stock at a time when Internet companies are
selling for billions of dollars. David Wetherell, chairman of CMGI
Inc. of Andover, originally supported the deal, but resigned from
the Lycos board after the company's shares lost a third of their
value. Now Wetherell, whose company controls nearly 20 percent of
Lycos shares, is working to scuttle the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Ullas Naik, who tracks Lycos for First Albany Corp. in Boston,
says the outcome of the Lycos-HSN basketball promotion could either
help improve prospects for the merger or scuttle it altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they can demonstrate to the street that there are synergies
between Home Shopping Network and Lycos, there might be a
possibility that Lycos shareholders, those who are negatively
disposed to the deal, may reconsider,'' Naik said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ironically, a successful promotion could have the reverse
effect. Naik said shareholders may conclude that Lycos can gain all
the advantages of the merger without having to merge. That could
actually increase opposition to the Lycos-USA Networks deal.
</P>
<P>
   Lycos' headquarters are in Waltham, Mass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0115 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6723 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-19 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAILEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE `US' QUESTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Now that Terry Murray has agreed to pay $16 billion to
build the WalMart of New England banking, you think he wants to see
Home Depot move in? Think again.
</P>
<P>
   A Fleet-BankBoston merger was supposed to be the deal that would
never happen because the regulators would never allow it. Murray,
of course, was smarter than all of us. He has wanted this deal for
years, and he has done his homework in Washington; this merger is
going to be approved.
</P>
<P>
   The only real issue left is who will be Fleet's competition?
</P>
<P>
   As Ira &AMP; Anne &AMP; Ted &AMP; Alice inside the banks all wonder ``What
about me?', it's a good time to ask, ``What about us?'' You know,
as in us, the customers who now have a choice between Fleet service
and our friendly hometown bankers who are somehow supposed to keep
this behemoth honest.
</P>
<P>
   To get the deal past regulators, Fleet faces the biggest
divestiture in banking history. It has proposed selling $13 billion
in deposits and about 270 branches across New England. Who gets
what in those sales will determine Fleet's competition on the
ground.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line: Fleet is going to try and get away with the
weakest competition the regulators will allow. We, of course, want
just the opposite: the strongest possible competition.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet will argue, and quite correctly, that there is more
competition than ever. Citicorp is huge in the credit card business
here. G.E. Capital is a giant business lender. And there's that
thing called the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But wade through all the big-picture, future-of-banking stuff,
and you are still left with this: Fleet wants anyone in here as a
competitor as long as it's not a big national player. And if it
doesn't want BankAmerica or First Union here, maybe we should.
</P>
<P>
   Right now the world is going in just the opposite direction.
Thursday, the Massachusetts congressional delegation waded in,
saying it would ``oppose vigorously'' the sale of the branches to
one bidder and instead urging that the branches go to ``a diverse
group'' of local banks.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds great in the district, but Terry Murray couldn't
have written the letter better. Fleet would like nothing more than
to be competing against a bunch of pigmies. ``We were a little guy
once, too,'' one Fleet/BankBoston executive told me. He somehow
managed not to break out laughing.
</P>
<P>
   What Fleet fears most is giving a First Union a foothold here.
Even if First Union swooped up the entire $13 billion in deposits _
unlikely -- it would still be only a start. But it could then start
buying, snapping up USTrust (dial 1-800 Neal Finnegan) and maybe
even Citizens Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the little guys, a First Union would have the resources
to spend on technology. It could build market share by competing
aggressively on price, offering better deposit rates and lower
lending rates. It has a brand name.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet has a lot of latitude over who gets what. Under the rules,
Fleet will pick the buyer or buyers it favors. Regulators must
decide if the deal maintains competition, not which of the offers
is best for the region. The price the branches fetch is less
important to Fleet than the competitor.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy enough to construct an argument that Citizens, not a
First Union, could provide Fleet the toughest competition, at least
in the short-term. A winning bid could provide Citizens with bulk.
Plus it has a local headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet on it. Fleet has no interest in strengthening Larry
Fish's hand at Citizens. When Fleet bought Shawmut in 1995, Fish
bid on the Connecticut branches being divested. He lost.
</P>
<P>
   This game is almost over, but not quite. The activists know they
have some leverage during the approval process. Already, Bruce
Marks, the Jessie James of community activists, has popped up after
several years of robbing banks around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Marks wants a big national player here. He calls Fleet ``the
feudal landlord who wants to sell to the peasants you can crush any
time. The last thing it wants is to sell to its competitive feudal
landlords.'' We haven't had quotes like that since Fleet paid Marks
millions to go away in the old second-mortgage days.
</P>
<P>
   But Marks has a point. If someone doesn't squeeze the Justice
Department now, it will be Fleet squeezing us later.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
