<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6725 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-TRUE-BOS &LR;      03-19 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-TRUE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTWOOD WINS BIG AS A LOSER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
TRUE CRIME 
Directed by: Clint Eastwood 
Screenplay by: Larry Gross, Paul Brickman, Stephen Schiff (novel:
Andrew Klavan) 
Starring: Clint Eastwood, Isaiah Washington, Denis Leary, Lisa Gay
Hamilton, James Woods, Diane Venora 
Running time: 127 minutes 
Rated: R (language and some violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a lot of true grit, or at least convincing grit, in
``True Crime,'' and that's what makes the new Clint Eastwood movie
interesting. Eastwood not only looks his own age but uses it to
bolster his performance as a character who's pretty much a washout
as a man but has enough left to be a talented newspaper reporter.
Just enough, in fact, to go to bat at the last minute for a
death-row inmate he's convinced is innocent. He holds off the
race-against-time cliches (although not to the extent of omitting a
car chase) by nailing the details of the awfulness of death row and
focusing on the crumbling prospects of his Oakland Tribune
reporter, Steve Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood is too savvy to fashion an anti-capital-punishment
editorial, even if he were in favor of it, which I'm by no means
sure he is. He also knows enough to not try to get too cute with
what in many other hands would be the scapegrace charm of the
journalist. Rather, Eastwood plays the guy as the recovering
alcoholic we're told he is, barely keeping things together, given
focus by his job, which is the only thing he does right. As a
father and husband, he's blown it, we're convinced in a piercingly
sour little scene he has with his estranged wife, Diane Venora, and
the daughter he keeps disappointing. (She is played by his own
daughter, Francesca Fisher-Eastwood. A nice touch!).
</P>
<P>
   His late-night pass at a colleague sent her out into a rainy
night to die in a car crash. He inherits her assignment,
interviewing the condemned man the day before he's scheduled to be
executed by lethal injection. As the convicted man, Isaiah
Washington is given as pristine a character as credibility allows.
He's a born-again Christian whose dignity in the face of death and
sensitive fathering of his own young daughter heightens the
reporter's own conspicuous character failings. As his nose for news
starts to twitch to life, the suspense begins. Can he refute what
he feels is a faulty case in time to stay the execution?
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood knows Oakland, having grown up there, and his longtime
cinematographer, Jack Green, captures it with a grave clarity that
imparts to it a played-out look that deftly fits with the
protagonist and his self-diminished prospects. The shabby precincts
through which Everett moves parallel the shabby mess he has made of
his life _ which Eastwood nails wryly and unsparingly. As his
reopening of the case picks up speed, the question is whether he
can overturn the guilty verdict against a black man for shooting a
clerk in a convenience store. The more resistance Everett
encounters to reexamining the case, the more convinced he is that
the condemned man is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   It takes more subtlety than Eastwood has been credited with to
slide around the cliches implicit in the situation and work in some
comedy. But Eastwood brings it off with an enjoyable level of
detailing and finesse. As actor and director, he never allows heavy
moralizing to drag down the story, slyly finding humor in the
tension between Everett and his metro editor (Denis Leary), who's
furious because he knows the reporter is having an affair with his
wife. There's even more humor in the exchanges between Everett and
his boss, played by James Woods with an amusement and indulgence of
Everett's foibles to which he can't quite give voice. This is the
second smart script in as many weeks to have Stephen Schiff's name
on it, proving that there's not only life but commercial viability
after ``Lolita.''
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood's famed economy, the screenplay's emphasis on
character, and the film's allowance for atmosphere work on several
levels _ and lift ``True Crime'' beyond the crudely manipulative
nonsense that's cluttering up the genre. Clearly, Eastwood has
learned to enjoy playing weakness and could go on for years playing
damaged old pros with just enough left to keep going. His
confidence in his own musical ability is growing, too, and
deservedly so. He wrote a nice bluesy song for the finish, which
provides a moody but never self-pitying grace note. It's a shame to
have to roll the closing credits over the richly rueful atmosphere
in its all-but-deserted downtown pedestrian mall where, to steal a
line from the film, Santa rides alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
