<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-FORCES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFLECK, BULLOCK ARE OK, BUT `FORCES' FIZZLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
FORCES OF NATURE 
Directed by: Bronwen Hughes 
Screenplay by: Marc Lawrence 
Starring: Sandra Bullock, Ben Affleck, Maura Tierney, Steve Zahn,
Blythe Danner, Ronny Cox, David Strickland, Meredith Scott Lynn 
Running time: 102 minutes 
Rated: PG-13 (sensuality, language and a scene of drug use) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Forces of Nature'' is exactly what the new romantic comedy
starring Sandra Bullock and Ben Affleck is not. It wants to be a
neo-screwball comedy, with Bullock's free spirit upending Affleck's
buttoned-down blurb-writer. And it at least avoids formula
predictability. But it doesn't fly off the screen with the fizzy
energy of liberating disruption. It's a pleasant enough couple of
hours with two attractive leads, and it carries itself beyond
formula in tone as well as incident. But force, no. Nature, no. The
film just doesn't have that kind of spontaneity and impetuosity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Affleck does have his enjoyably squirmy moments as a very
straight guy headed from New York to Savannah to get married. All
it takes is one skid on a runway, and he's off the plane and into a
hired car, especially when he hears there are storms between him
and his wedding. So we're all set up for a road comedy, complete
with the sweet loose cannon sitting beside him, Bullock's character
named Sarah. She's also on her way to Savannah to sell her bagel
shop in the wake of a crumbling marriage to an exploitive flake.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock and Affleck throw themelves at the subsequent missed
connections and string of disasters that pull them way off course
from their intended destination and into a romance that he fights
and she doesn't. What's missing, though, is the screwball energy
that Sarah needs. Bullock is right to not want to get locked into
sweetheart roles, but you get the feeling, watching her here, that
she thinks she's being a lot wilder than she actually is. The
action is there in Sarah, but we don't feel the conviction and
abandon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet ``Forces of Nature'' isn't the ennui-producing dead weight
it could have been, considering how underwhelming it is. Affleck
does some nice things with his eyes when his character stares ahead
into the next disaster, not knowing how to stop it. Bullock is at
her best when she isn't trying to be zany, but slips into a more
realistic, serious mode and allows her character's vulnerabilities
and insecurities to show. The mood even turns bittersweet,
something unheard of in a studio comedy.
</P>
<P>
   There's a fundamental decency at work in ``Forces of Nature''
that works against the anarchy of screwball comedy, but makes the
characters more humanly appealing. To its credit, Marc Lawrence's
screenplay doesn't demonize or ridicule the fiancee waiting in
Savannah, either, a chance Maura Tierney makes the most of.
``Forces of Nature'' scores most of its points in its quieter
moments, when it isn't pushing the comedy too hard. Maybe they just
should have played it straight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1405EST &QL; 
