<HEADER>
A6728 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLEET-CONSUMERS-BOS &LR;      03-19 1227
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLEET-CONSUMERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSUMER GROUPS FEAR BIG MERGERS WILL LIMIT CONSUMER CHOICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The fee for taking cash out of an ATM machine might be
75 cents or a dollar. Or, it might be free of charge.
</P>
<P>
   A choice of ATM machines on the corner is one of the many ways _
some visible and some not _ in which fierce competition benefits
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The $16 billion acquisition of BankBoston Corp. by Fleet
Financial Group Inc. is being billed as a way to preserve a large
hometown institution by warding off buyers from outside the region.
</P>
<P>
   But the union _ before any branches are sold _ would lead to a
higher concentration of customer deposits in greater Boston than
has resulted from any other merger in recent banking history,
according to federal regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The danger, consumer and bank experts said, is that a merger in
which one of the two major banks in the region disappears could
crimp competition, leaving customers only one megabank and dozens
of smaller institutions. This could cause higher fees for consumers
and limit options available to small businesses that are most
likely to rely on banks for financial services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not aware of a merger with more anti-competitive consumer
effects than this one,'' said Stephen Brobeck, executive director
of the Consumer Federation of America, a Washington group that has
studied the impact of bank mergers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's good and healthy for banks isn't always healthy for
small business borrowers,'' said Julie Scofield, executive director
of the Smaller Business Association of New England.
</P>
<P>
   After the merger, Fleet Boston Corp. would have the lion's share
of deposits in New England's largest cities. According to the
Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., combined consumer and business
deposits would be 40 percent of total deposits in the Boston
metropolitan area, nearly half of Hartford's deposits, and 58
percent of deposits in the Providence-Fall River area.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet and BankBoston, in announcing the merger this week, said
they would sell bank branches and ATMs in order to obtain approval
from federal regulators and to avoid antitrust challenges. The
banks plan to divest 270 branches across New England _ including
most of Fleet's branches in Massachusetts _ and shrink assets by
$13 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Schepker, Fleet's spokesman, disputed speculation the merger
would hurt consumers. Banks, he said, are already under attack from
all sides of the financial industry.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, banks have lost billions in deposits since the mid-1980s
to mutual funds as investors have become enamored of investment
income earned by mutual funds .
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's Merrill Lynch in a cash management account or
Charles Schwab in a liquid mutual fund _ there are many options for
consumers,'' Schepker said. The popularity of transactions
performed on the Internet adds a new layer of competition, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Charles Biggio, a partner in the New York law firm of Akin,
Gump, Strauss, Hauer &AMP; Feld and a former deputy assistant in the US
Justice Department's merger division, suggested that the
Fleet-BankBoston merger may become a test of how much bank
dominance is acceptable for consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department, in reviewing bank mergers in the past
has traditionally focused on the impact on small business of
mergers between banks within a metropolitan area. Branch sales
resulting from Fleet's acquisition of Shawmut National Corp. in
1995 appeased regulators' concerns that small and mid-sized
businesses have enough banks with which to do business. When banks
sell off branches, customers are transferred to the buying
institutions, which then try to keep the customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, there hasn't been much activity'' at the Justice
Department in reviewing the impact on consumers since that market
is usually more competitive, Biggio said. Although unfamiliar with
details of the Fleet-Boston merger, Biggio said, that if there is
``significant concentration, this may be a case where the consumer
issues come into play.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Griffin, a financial specialist for the Consumers Union
said, ``lack of choice'' in the merger ``is a real concern that
needs to be looked at by the regulators.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department declined comment on the pending merger.
</P>
<P>
   If the merger is approved, Fleet Boston Corp. would be the
newest creature to emerge from 15 years of consolidation in
nationwide banking. Amid such rapid change, it would be difficult
to predict the landscape even five years from now.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy Vaill, chief executive of Boston Private Bank &AMP; Trust
Co., predicted that competition will be reduced immediately after
the merger. Loyal customers of both banks ``are going to have to
eat the food that's fed to them,'' he said. ``Over time, other
competitors will move into the market and provide choices.''
</P>
<P>
   A look back shows that consumers have often suffered as banks
increased their clout in a market through mergers. Although it's
difficult to blame mergers for higher fees, Federal Reserve studies
show that fees nationwide are up sharply as the industry has
consolidated into bigger and bigger banks.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, according to a July 1997 survey by MassPIRG,
the local affiliate of Ralph Nader's consumer group in Washington,
most fees charged by the six big banks were higher than those
charged by small banks eager to grab customers with lower fees.
</P>
<P>
   Banks ``use their size not to bring down the cost to the
consumer but they use a lack of competition in the market to set
higher fees,'' asserted Deidre Cummings, a consumer advocate at
MassPIRG.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, there could be less competitive pressure than in the
past, when Fleet and BankBoston kept a sharp eye on each other,
often setting prices to undercut the other bank.
</P>
<P>
   For example, when the state Legislature failed recently to pass
a bill that would have banned ATM surcharges charged by banks to
noncustomers that use their ATMs, BankBoston said it would charge
non-customers $1. Fleet set its fee at 75 cents. A Cambridge
Savings Bank customer facing only two choices _ Fleet or BankBoston
_ would tend to use Fleet's machine.
</P>
<P>
   There will only be one choice if the merger is approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big getting bigger. The small getting smaller,''
complained Francesco Ciailone, after walking out of a BankBoston
branch in Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   Bank fees have risen nationally as banks have become more
dependent on fees, which are a more stable source of revenue than
the loan business, bank analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   Often the big institution sets the tone after a bank merger. In
the San Francisco area, consumer groups are concerned that
NationsBank Corp., when it merges with BankAmerica Corp., would
eliminate BankAmerica's free checking accounts, said Ken
McEldowney, executive director of Consumer Action in the Bay area.
NationsBank does not have a comparable product, he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, San Francisco _ unlike Boston _ has an alternative, he
said. Washington Mutual, a big savings bank, also provides free
checking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In California, it's going to be very hard for NationsBank to
come in and set fees on these accounts if their major competitor is
not charging fees on the basic checking account,'' McEldowney said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
