<HEADER>
A6731 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     03-19 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
  
 (Eds.: Riskyman67 is cq)  
 RUN-UP REVEALS INTERNET'S POWER(For use by New York Times News
Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riskyman67 took the wild events of Thursday morning in stride
and offered this bit of reassuring advice: ``Just hang on to your
seats and enjoy the ride.''
</P>
<P>
   He was only one person in a crowd of investors writing on
Internet chat boards about the huge one-day gain and frenetic
trading activity in the stock of a previously obscure public
company, Netegrity Inc. of Waltham, Mass. Chances are, they were
responsible for much or even most of the activity that caught
everyone off guard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of got our coming-out party,'' said Netegrity
president Barry Bycoff, whose company sells Web security software
and services. ``As it turns out, it was a surprise party.''
</P>
<P>
   The Netegrity boom was another example of the power that now
rests in the hands of wired investors, who spend much of their day
scanning the Internet for news, corresponding on
investment-oriented electronic bulletin boards and actively trading
stock on line. They do not have the ability to affect big stocks
like Gillette Co. or Fleet Financial Group. But they can take small
stocks, particularly small technology shares, on a roller-coaster
ride.
</P>
<P>
   Netegrity stock shot up early Thursday and gained 90 percent in
value by day's end. The amount of stock traded, just under 10
million shares, made it the 14th most active issue anywhere, just
behind AT&AMP;T Corp. The volume roughly equaled the number of all
Netegrity shares swapped in the last 18 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the news: There was no news. Or not much to speak of.
</P>
<P>
   The Netegrity boom began when the Massachusetts Investor's
Digest, a free monthly newspaper with a ciculation of about 20,000,
issued a press release about the flattering profile of Netegrity in
its current issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look out Lycos! There is a new hot Waltham-based Internet
company, Netegrity, that is looking to grab mindshare and
marketshare in the e-commerce arena,'' the release began.
</P>
<P>
   The story and the rest of the issue had been available in a
newspaper box outside the Fidelity Investments investor center and
at other locations around downtown Boston or the city's suburbs
since Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was shot out into the electronic world and landed in
many places, including the part of Yahoo Finance dedicated to
information and chat about Netegrity.
</P>
<P>
   The stock roared ahead, from an opening price of just under 8,
and traded above 15 before noon. The price dipped a few dollars in
the afternoon, but finished strong to close at 15, up 7 1/8 for the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 8 million shares had traded hands by midafternoon, and
company officials said at that time they believed only about
160,000 involved bigger investors selling blocks of stock. The rest
were small trades, many executed by individuals, for 100, 500, or a
few thousand shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``A press release hits the on-line databases and goes into
(Internet) search engines. The power of the Internet to get news
disseminated is what sparked this,'' said Michael Stern, a former
Merrill Lynch broker who started Massacusetts Investor's Digest a
year ago. ``This is the first time it seems to have had a direct
effect on the stock, which is kind of scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Any third-party news about a stock like Netegrity can have an
outsized impact because it fills a void. The company is so small no
brokerage analysts follow it. Netegrity shares were worth just $141
million, even after their advance Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Riskyman67 and lots of other investors, writing under Web
pseudonyms, saw the release and stock reaction early. They
celebrated their good fortunes on Yahoo. So did investors writing
on a chat board at RagingBull.com, operated by a small company that
was the subject of another Massachusetts Investor's Digest profile
months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another piece of Netegrity news that hardly got as much
attention Thursday: A company filing with the US Securities and
Exchange Commission disclosed that Fidelity OTC Portfolio fund had
acquired 700,000 shares, a 5.15 percent interest in the company, in
a private placement earlier this year. Presumably, the fund made a
killing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Netegrity shares had slumped to as low as 1 3/16 in October and
traded with a price band of 1 to 4 for most of 1998. With it
seemingly stuck there, some investors had given up on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mouth is open,'' said an executive at one Boston brokerage
office that owned 350,000 Netegrity shares but sold them last year.
``I think of all the money I left on the table. We just didn't have
the patience and we regret it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other Internet-related firms, Netegrity remains more
promise than performance. The company lost money in each quarter
last year and reported revenues of only $4.9 million for all of
1998. Its SiteMinder product and services control user access to
e-commerce on Web sites. Big new customers include Delta Air Lines
and Radio Shack.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Bycoff about the most important event in his firm's recent
past and he points to a key reseller agreement signed in January
with Netscape Communications Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been focused on building our product and building our
market, not promoting the company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bycoff can worry less about that today. But he has a different
problem: What the Net gives in a flash, it can take away just as
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   Avinash Persaud, the man who agreed to take a job as the head of
currency at Putnam Investments and mysteriously bailed out two
weeks later, resurfaced Thursday at State Street Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Persaud was named managing director and global head of research
for State Street's financial markets business. He had taken the
Putnam job in January and then, without explanation, said the deal
was off. Persaud had been head of foreign exchange and currency
research at J.P. Morgan &AMP; Co. in London.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
