<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEARD ABOUT THE FIGHT IN THESTREET.COM? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I &UR;  &LR; wonder if the potential investors in TheStreet.com would be
interested in knowing that the cofounders, Cambridge's own Martin
Peretz and the odious James Cramer, are on the outs. How this will
affect the forthcoming public stock offering of the on-line
business-reporting site is anyone's guess. No one's allowed to talk
to the press during this enforced ``quiet period'' of stock
registration.
</P>
<P>
   Said silent time hasn't shut up the voluble Cramer, however.
He's raving in the current issue of Slate (www.slate.com) about his
``enemies'' who ``sincerely want to see me fail. They want to drive
a wedge between my partners and me.'' Hmmm. Maybe they've
succeeded.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know what's soured this once-sweet relationship. It
seems like only Thursday that Peretz was squiring Cramer around
Cambridge, trying to drum up clients for his protege's
money-management business. (That's separate from TheStreet.com.)
Peretz _ owner of the New Republic magazine and a savvy investor in
his own right _ and Cramer were quite successful. Many of Cramer's
clients hailed from Peretz's Harvard-New Republic coterie, e.g.,
Michael Kinsley, now editor of Slate magazine. In some cases,
Peretz even loaned friends money to invest with Cramer. The fund
performed well, at least until last year. Cramer turned in a
sub-par performance, lost clients, and bridled at critics who
suggested he was spending too much time promoting himself on
television, and too little time at his trading desk.
</P>
<P>
   With the new stock deal, Peretz and Cramer are aiming to get
rich _ again. TheStreet.com is one of the few successful Internet
publishing ventures. Sure, they're losing tons of dough. But they
have 37,000 paying subscribers, which is a lot for the Web. They
have a talented staff and savvy early-stage investors, including
the New York Times Co., which owns the Globe.
</P>
<P>
   So let's speculate. Peretz and Cramer each own about 2.5 million
shares. We can't know what the stock price will be, but like other
Internet stocks, it probably will be bid up quickly. A comparable
company, MarketWatch.com, went public in January at $17 and
recently traded in the low 60s. So Jim and Marty are each looking
at a $50 million payday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
My self-serving memoir
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Librarians will surely have the good sense to file Simon
Fireman's forthcoming ghostwritten memoir, ``No Justice,'' in the
category: Books That Should Never Have Been Written.
</P>
<P>
   Fireman, you may recall, is the moneybags chief of Aqua-Leisure
Inc. in Avon, Mass. who got nailed for making illegal campaign
donations in the waning days of the 1996 Bob Dole campaign. (He's
also the uncle of Reebok chairman Paul Fireman.) Fireman pleaded
guilty to charges that he forced employees to give a total of
$120,000 to candidates on his behalf between 1991 and 1995, and
received a harsh penalty, paying $1 million personally and $5
million through his company. He was also sentenced to six months of
arrest at his Marina Bay home in Quincy, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Fireman has been blabbing to anyone who will listen that he is a
victim of a Department of Justice scheme to score a big campaign
finance conviction against a Republican, given that embarrassing
revelations about illicit Indonesian and Chinese donations to the
Democrats were surfacing in the Clinton-Dole campaign. He may even
be right.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine provided me with a brief summary of his
manuscript, which Fireman declined to discuss, apparently because
he thinks that reporters will show up for a big pre-publication
press conference scheduled for the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Fireman's lawyer Morris Goldings says about the
forthcoming tome: 1. Yes, it repeats the malpractice charges that
Fireman recently leveled against his former defense attorney Thomas
Dwyer. 2. Yes, trial judge William Young is in the book. ``It's
critical of certain aspects of the case as handled by (Young),''
Goldings says, but the bombastic nonsense I had heard about will
not be published. 3. So, was Fireman unfairly targeted? Goldings:
``There's some speculation about how this case got out of the
Federal Election Commission so quickly.'' 4. Yes, there will be
much blather about the need for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
