A6736 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-EARTHLY-BOS &LR;      03-19 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-EARTHLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SARANDON'S NEW ROAD MOVIE IS AN UNEVEN TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
EARTHLY POSSESSIONS 
Starring: Susan Sarandon, Stephen Dorff, Elissabeth Moss, Jay O.
Sanders 
Directed by: James Lapine 
Written by: Steven Rogers, based on the novel by Anne Tyler 
On: HBO 
Time: Saturday at 8 p.m. 
Rating: TVMA 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In ``Thelma and Louise,'' Susan Sarandon was Louise, the more
worldly voyager on the road to empowerment and revelation. But in
``Earthy Possessions,'' Sarandon plays a variation on Thelma, the
scatterbrained member of the T-bird twosome. Putting on her best
flake bearing, she is Charlotte Emory, a small-town homemaker who
is taken hostage by a bank robber, forced to hit the road with him,
and, naturally, ultimately, freed up to be herself. She might as
well be living out the ad slogan for ``Thelma and Louise'':
Somebody said get a life . . . so she did.
</P>
<P>
   You've gotta love the road, that movie mecca that always seems
to lead to the Liberation Highway, with detours along Adventure
Avenue and Self-Esteem Street. Not long into the ``Earthly
Possessions'' trip from upstate New York to South Carolina, it
becomes obvious that our sheltered Charlotte isn't exactly a
hostage anymore. In fact, she is altogether digging the excitement
of being on the lam, as well as the gruff charms of her
gun-wielding kidnapper, a handsome hothead named Jake. And so goes
``Earthly Possessions,'' which premieres Saturday on HBO at 8 p.m.
The romantic comedy, based on the novel by Anne Tyler, is an overly
familiar tale of learning to take the wheel of life, with its roots
in every road movie from ``It Happened One Night'' to Jonathan
Demme's ``Something Wild.'' While it does contain a few mild
pleasures, most of them thanks to Sarandon, it suffers from too
much predictability and a distractingly cutesy tone.
</P>
<P>
   Partly, you wish Sarandon had stayed away from the project,
simply because of its similarities to the indelible ``Thelma and
Louise.'' But she wins you over with her earthy, rebellious, and
slightly clueless Charlotte. ``Ex-cuse me,'' she yells at Jake when
he grabs her pocketbook, not long after he has dragged her out of
the bank with his gun pressed against her. She manages to bring a
fresh spin to some of the more stock scenes, including when she and
Jake get drunk together, hit the dance floor, and then fight about
whether or not to make love. As Jake, Stephen Dorff is neither a
plus nor a minus, going through his usual boyish, explosive moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earthly Possessions'' has an uneven, lighthearted tone that
undermines the characters' emotional shifts. Mostly, the comedy is
quirky and quaint _ too much so _ but at times it veers into
satire, as Charlotte and Jake become increasingly notorious. Like a
mock newsmagazine, the movie flashes to deadpan interviews with
people who have crossed the couple's path. And then Charlotte's
vain husband and Jake's girlfriend are portrayed in much more
cartoonish terms than the others. Perhaps director James Lapine,
who hits just the right comic notes in ``Impromptu,'' is a little
too eager to jazz up the plain story. Halfway through the journey,
you may find yourself wishing he'd step on the gas a bit, and get
us to the finish line a little faster.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
