<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIE-RAVENOUS-BOS &LR;      03-19 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-RAVENOUS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAVENOUS SERVES UP HAM-HANDED CANNIBALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RAVENOUS 
Directed by: Antonia Bird 
Screenplay by: Ted Griffin 
Starring: Guy Pearce, Robert Carlyle, Jeremy Davies, Jeffrey Jones,
John Spencer, Stephen Spinella, Neal McDonough, David Arquette 
Running time: 100 minutes 
Rated: R (considerable gore and strong violence) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The trouble with ``Ravenous'' is not that it's a bad movie. Many
bad movies prosper. The trouble with ``Ravenous'' is that it can't
decide exactly what kind of bad movie it wants to be. This can be a
real problem with a cannibal movie, which is what ``Ravenous'' is.
Taking its cue from the Donner Pass episode, in which some
snowbound pioneers in the Sierra Nevadas ate others, it focuses on
a small Sierra Nevada fort in 1847, where a handful of soldiers
make bad jokes about serving their fellow men _ and do.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Griffin's script doesn't know if it wants to be a straight
horror movie, an exercise in black humor, or a metaphor for the
19th-century American doctrine of Manifest Destiny, a rationale for
gobbling up any land in its path. Having failed to resolve the
question of tone, the film compounds its shortfall by failing to
bring any faceting to the characters, leaving them two-dimensional
and uninvolving. The only one we care about is an American Indian
relegated to second-class-citizen status, pressed into service as a
maid. She's the one we hope will get away.
</P>
<P>
   She also supplies a visual reminder of the theory, articulated
by one of the flesh-eaters, that they may be possessed by an evil
spirit the Indians call a wendigo. According to the legend, those
who eat their enemies acquire their strength by consuming them.
Robert Carlyle, who first presents himself as a victim and later is
revealed to be one of the cannibals, is the busiest dispenser of
rationales. In an age before flu shots were invented, he points to
his own increased strength and immunity from disease and declares
human flesh a sort of health food.
</P>
<P>
   He and Jeffrey Jones, a more genial cannibal, are hugely
interested in bringing Guy Pearce's fluky military hero into the
fold. As Jones's officer says with a straight face (and I'm not
making this up), ``It's lonely being a cannibal.'' Pearce's
put-upon soldier could reply that it's not that great being a
vegetarian either, at least not in the company he's currently
keeping. But he's too busy clutching a big knife, trying not to
fall into too deep a sleep, lest he never wake up, and trying,
above all, not to examine too closely the contents of the simmering
stewpot in the rude log cabin they all share.
</P>
<P>
   Antonia Bird's direction does little to improve matters and it
isn't long before you're wondering what the actors _ including
dementos played by David Arquette and Jeremy Davies _ saw in this
confused and unfocused script. The mountain scenery in the Czech
Republic (standing in for the Sierra Nevada) is impressive, and
impressively contrasted with the dark, heavy, claustrophobic cabins
where most of the film takes place. Still, it's hard to work up
much appetite for ``Ravenous.'' Hannibal Lecter did this sort of
thing a lot better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
