</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKC-NCAA-MIDDLEBURY-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIDDLEBURY HOCKEY IS MORE FAMILY THAN DYNASTY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLEBURY, Vt. _ Arranged in chronological order, 1995-98, the
elegant walnut-and-gold NCAA Division 3 championship plaques
dominate a trophy case in the lobby of Middlebury College's
Fletcher Field House. They represent an era of excellence
unprecedented in college hockey; no other team at any level ever
has won four such prizes in a row.
</P>
<P>
   They might as well be stashed in a broom closet.
</P>
<P>
   Down below on this Wednesday afternoon, the pristine ice of
spanking new Chip Kenyon Arena is being carved up in a competition
that, for the moment at least, is of even greater consequence to
the Panthers than their latest foray into the national semifinals
two days from now.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Bill Beaney has been talking up this event all week, the
Final Four has been winnowed to two survivors, and the atmosphere
is understandably electric.
</P>
<P>
   Bodies, checks, elbows, and shots are flying from one side of
the rink to the other; rollicking cheers chart the ebb and flow of
the game until, finally, there is a champion.
</P>
<P>
   John Giannacopoulos, Curt Goldman, Ross Sealfon, and Grayson
Fertig exult. They have just won the season-long Panther intrasquad
three-on-three tournament, the glory that goes with it, and, most
cherished of all, the unique championship trophy. It's a crude
balsa rendering of a Middlebury goalie atop a knotty pine base,
carved by a bus driver from Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was our driver for the 1996 Final Four at Wisconsin-River
Falls,'' says Beaney, ``and after we got home, he sent this along
with a note saying how much he'd enjoyed driving such a nice group
of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of what it represents _ ``an appreciation for good
people who play exciting hockey and give honest effort'' _ Beaney
considers this folk art as precious as any of the handsome hardware
shimmering in the lobby upstairs. Because of what it represents _
``camaraderie, enjoying the moment'' _ Beaney considers this
three-on-three diversion as vital to his program as any national
recognition. Even now, on the verge of that other Final Four _ the
one in Northfield, where Middlebury (19-5-1) will continue its
quest for another page in the record book when it faces Rochester
Institute of Technology (26-1-2), followed by an semifinal between
Wisconsin-Superior (21-7-3) and host Norwich (26-1-2).
</P>
<P>
   When the Panthers, the upstarts in this year's NCAA field
despite their legacy of supremacy, returned to the rink Monday
after upsetting the top Western seed, St. Norbert, by coming back
from an opening loss _ their first ever in 19 NCAA games _ to win
the next night and the deciding minigame at DePere, Wis., Beaney
emphasized three things to his players: ``Take care of your
academics because you've missed some class time and we're going on
spring break; prepare for RIT; and let's finish the three-on-three
tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   If it sounds like nonsense, the joke apparently is on the other
65 teams in Division 3. ``What's amazing is that it wasn't the
winning that mattered most,'' says Ryan Goldman, part of the Class
of '98 that graduated with four national titles and a 95-9-6
record. ``It was the fun we had. Beaney always stressed fun.''
</P>
<P>
   It just so happens that the Panthers generally wind up the
celebration with a national championship party.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   College hockey's counterpart to the 1949-54 Yankees, 1956-60
Canadiens, and 1957-69 Celtics, Middlebury is an unlikely dynasty.
On a stately, rustic campus set amid a postcard from heaven, in the
shadow of the Green Mountains, surrounded by dairy farms and ski
lifts, it is also an unorthodox one.
</P>
<P>
   The architect is the owlish Beaney, 47, a former captain and
volunteer assistant at the University of New Hampshire under
Charlie Holt, who was renowned throughout the college ranks for his
graciousness and tactical tinkering. ``He'd win 10 games in a row
and he'd try a new alignment,'' recalls Beaney. ``When someone
would ask him why, he'd say, `We want to see if this way works
better. If it doesn't, we'll just go back to the other way. We
already know that works.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Beaney is an ardent disciple. With two national titles already
in hand, but unhappy with the Panthers' play in 1997, he devised a
new look, pairing right wings with centers and sending out
three-man defensive units, in effect turning the left wing into a
defensive hybrid. In fact, it wasn't so different. ``We'd always
played a center-right wing forecheck,'' says Beaney. ``But this
way, we could interchange more players, give the players a better
frame of reference for the system. We didn't change the system.
What we did was put a different label on it, change the mind-set.
Now we take more pride in defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers promptly reeled off a 29-game unbeaten streak over
a two-year span, annexing national title No. 3 in the process. But
it's not the specifics that make Beaney's fine-tuning instructive;
it's the philosophy behind it. ``I'm always tinkering,'' he says.
``Sure, everybody likes to win. But at the end of the day, I don't
think that's the most important part of the job. I think one reason
we've won is that we never have emphasized winning. To me, it's a
matter of developing a bond. I think success plays a part in that.
But I know you can't have success without the bonding, the hard
work. The exciting part for me is to see the changes each year, to
see the seniors take the freshmen under their wing. We try to give
the players ownership of the team, with the coaches as guides, to
make them responsible for it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The secret lies in the attitude as much as the execution, the
Panthers will tell you. ``That's what we recruit first,'' says
Beaney, who came to Middlebury in 1986 after successful coaching
stints at Bellows Free Academy and New England College, followed by
a three-year hiatus during which he was director of admissions at
Berwick Academy and an aide to Holt. ``Our players are not
necessarily the best, top to bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that they're slouches. Most, like soccer and potential
hockey All-American Giannacopoulos, who's from Needham, Mass., by
way of Belmont Hill, are products of exclusive and highly
successful private schools. Panthers assistant Lou Santini is
legendary for mining the New England preps for talent, and though
athletic scholarships are prohibited at the Division 3 level,
Middlebury, its idyllic Champlain Valley setting, and its national
reputation for academic excellence are not a hard sell. Beaney,
Santini, and Beaney's chief lieutenant for 12 of his 13 years here,
Wes McKee, mold the talent, which has included three of the last
six national Division 3 Players of the Year, a host of
All-Americans, and the near-flawless Class of '98 _ goalies
Francois Bourbeau and Chris Farion, who alternated games; forwards
Mark Spence and Emil Jattne; and defensemen Goldman and Filip
Jirousek.
</P>
<P>
   Talent notwithstanding, certain things won't be compromised.
Beaney remembers recruiting a player for the Class of '98, and
coming off a mediocre 13-10 season, he needed all the help he could
get.
</P>
<P>
   The father of one prospective recruit asked him, ``Can you win
the national championship?''
</P>
<P>
   Beaney responded, ``I don't want your son coming here if that's
why he's coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out the Panthers haven't stopped winning national
championships since. The group Beaney brought in coalesced, and a
tradition was born that transcended the titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't overestimate the power of family,'' says Ryan
Goldman, whose brothers, junior Curt and sophomore Scott, rank 1-3
in scoring on this year's team. ``The sum is greater than the parts
split up. The tradition is the power of the family.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
