u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS &LR;      03-19 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'LL BE BRUINS FROM WHERE TAYLOR'S STANDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- When you sit down with your morning corn flakes and
coffee and peruse the NHL standings, it's hard not to hypothesize
about where the Bruins will finish.
</P>
<P>
   With the standings so tight and Boston having 15 (of 82) games
remaining, it's just as hard for the players to keep from examining
all the possible scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are in sole possession of eighth place, the final
playoff spot in the Eastern Conference, with the Rangers and
Florida still hot on their trail. Montreal and Washington are still
considered contenders but their hopes are fading fast.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe the Bruins are the favorites to gain a postseason
berth while others think the Rangers or Panthers have a more
favorable schedule. Bruins center Tim Taylor likes his team's
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're looking all the time,'' said Taylor. ``When you lose,
you're looking at the teams behind you. When you win, you're
looking at the teams ahead of you to see if you can catch them.
Obviously, we're looking at teams behind us and making sure they
stay behind us. Against Toronto, we win a big game (4-1 Wednesday)
and you know Florida is watching the scoreboard before their game
(in San Jose) and they see we won and now it puts pressure on them.
They lose, now they're 3 points back.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we keep winning, we're in a good situation. It's
really tough for teams who are behind already to see the team
they're trying to catch win a game. Mentally, it's like, `Aw, they
won again.' And they have to win just to stay where they were.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Panthers made the trade with Vancouver to get star wing
Pavel Bure, many thought that might be the kiss of death for the
Bruins, especially considering the way they were playing. Taylor
said he didn't fret about the Bure acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   ``How good is he going to be, rushing him back after a knee
injury?'' said Taylor. ``I've had knee surgery before. He's going
to have to wear a brace, he's going to be slower, he's taking
someone else's ice time. He's going to be pushed to be offensive,
so how much defense is he going to play? A lot of things.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Bure not being 100 percent upon his return,
Taylor said there's also the factor of how his presence affects the
rest of the club.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think with them, they put so much emphasis on Bure
coming back that the rest of the guys psychologically think, `He's
back, he's our savior' and I don't think they play as well,'' said
Taylor. ``No one steps to the forefront to help him out. They
expect him to do it himself. Then when he's out, everyone seems to
rally around and play their solid defensive game and that's how
they're winning hockey games. Look at the Colorado game, Bure
scores three goals and they still lose, 7-5. Would you rather win,
2-1 or 2-0 or lose, 7-5?''
</P>
<P>
   Looking around the rest of the conference, Taylor said there are
some clubs who have not fared as well as he expected (the Rangers
and Montreal to name two), some who have done better, and some
about where he expected. He said it has made for an interesting
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little surprised with the way some teams are playing
right now,'' he said. ``As the season started and as it was
progressing, I don't think anyone could've figured out what was
going to happen at the end because we thought it might take 90
points just to make the playoffs. It still might look that way but
no team is really running away with it. Buffalo is about where I
thought they'd be. Pittsburgh is better than where I thought they'd
be. Toronto is a lot better than I thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone predicted Florida, they have the easiest schedule.
But then I looked at their next three road games and the way
Anaheim, LA, and San Jose have played of late . . . Detroit went
out there and went 0-3 against those teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida started 0-1 Wednesday night, losing a 4-2 decision to
the Sharks, and will face Los Angeles Saturday and Anaheim Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor said the Bruins are trying not to be preoccupied with
other clubs. Instead, they'll concentrate on playing the same style
they did against the Maple Leafs and if they do, their fortunes
will take care of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we did extremely well in keeping the game really
dull,'' said Taylor. ``It was a slow game and that's when we play
the best on the road. That's what we do, we take the crowd out of
it and their crowd wasn't in it. We had some chances early and we
didn't capitalize but we didn't really give them too much. The only
opportunity they had was (Derek) King shorthanded in the second
period but other than that, we held them pretty good.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do best is we wait and when other teams make a
mistake, we seem to capitalize on them. When we were going through
our slump earlier, teams were still making mistakes against us but
we weren't putting the puck in the net. It seemed like we would
make one mistake and the other team would score and it would cost
us a game. Now, that seems to be going back in our favor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
