<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-JOYNER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR AL JOYNER, NO SPEEDY RECOVERY FROM LOSS OF WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are certain days when it is cloudy and misty that Al
Joyner shudders and recoils at the thought of ``the most painful
day of my life.'' It is the type of gloomy day that reminds him of
a gloomier day still, Sept. 21, 1998. That was the day Joyner
discovered his wife, Olympic gold medal sprinter Florence Griffith
Joyner, dead in the master bedroom of their home in Mission Viejo,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still remember how there was no sun and it was misty,''
Joyner said as he sat Thursday in a quiet lounge at the Royal
Sonesta Hotel in Boston during a break from a book signing tour of
his late wife's recently published ``Running for Dummies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a terrible day,'' he added, his voice trailing off into
a whisper. ``A terrible day.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite rampant rumors that Griffith Joyner's death was somehow
related to abuse of performance-enhancing steroids _ rumors that
she, her husband, and her brother-in-law/coach, Bob Kersee,
vehemently denied after she handily won the 100- and 200-meter
events in the 1988 Seoul Olympics _ an autopsy concluded that the
38-year-old former sprinter had asphyxiated during an epileptic
seizure in her sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before the Olympics, I told her that she was probably capable
of doing a 10.5 (in the 100 meters),'' recalled Joyner, a 1984
Olympic gold medal winner in the triple jump. ``She laughed and
said, `If I do, they'll probably want to dissect me.' And in the
end, they did.''
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy also revealed that Griffith Joyner had a congenital
blood vessel abnormality called a ``cavernous angioma'' on the
front-left part of her brain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really want to go around and tell people about my wife, and
then to correct any misinformation that was out there about her for
the last and final time,'' Joyner said, explaining why he agreed to
do the book tour. ``I don't want my daughter growing up, having to
answer those same questions. I just want my wife to be able to rest
in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   As hurtful as those accusations were, Joyner said he was so
grief-stricken following his wife's death that, in the darkest
moments, he comtemplated suicide. But, he says, two things stopped
him. First, there was his belief in God, and then there was the
couple's only child, Mary Ruth, 8, who took time off from school to
accompany her father to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it weren't for those two things, I don't think I'd be here
today,'' he said. ``I thought I would never say that. I always
wondered how people would feel that way; that they would want to
end their life. But in that situation, it was one of the most
helpless moments of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   He felt about as helpless as in the moment he discoverd his
wife's body and tried to awaken her, to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think about that now more than anything else,'' Joyner said,
his eyes glancing down at the glass coffee table. ``I wish I hadn't
fallen asleep downstairs. I will always feel that, maybe, I
could've helped save Florence if I had been there. I came in that
night and said, `Honey, I'm home. I love you.' And she said, `OK, I
love you, too,' and went upstairs to bed. Those were her last words
to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The thought of it, however, has brought Joyner little solace.
``I don't think I'll ever be at peace with it,'' he said. ``It's so
hard, because I miss her so much. This (pain) is something that is
never going to go away. That's the way it is, but you try to go on.
Sometimes the things you miss the most are the small things. Those
are the things you really take for granted. They're things that
only a married couple in a relationship would know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like coming up to you from behind, unexpected, and
having her put her arms around you and saying things like, `Thank
you for putting up with me for all these years.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Again, his voice trailed off. ``It's those little things.''
</P>
<P>
   And though the pain still lingers, Joyner says his daughter, who
carries herself with her mother's aura of confidence, has been a
source of inspiration and consolation. She has served as his ray of
hope on those gloomy days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, she's an inspiration,'' he said. ``She has a lot
of her mother in her. She has her strength. A week after Florence
had passed on, she had to go back to school. We were standing on
the stairway in the house and I started thinking about things and
started crying. Mary was crying and I was like, `Mary, what's
wrong?'
</P>
<P>
   ``She came down, sobbing, `Daddy, I'm going to be a week behind
in school.' I was thinking, `That ain't why I'm crying,' but I
figured things were going to be all right,'' he said, breaking into
a chuckle. ``So, two hours into school, I began thinking about Mary
and thinking how it was going to be just as hard for her, because
it was a brand new school and she didn't have any friends and then
two weeks before school started she lost her mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know how people are going to respond, but the school
was great. So, two hours into her first day at school, her teacher
called me and said, `Mr. Joyner, Mary's in (phys. ed) right now,
but she requested that we call you and tell you that she's doing
all right and hopes that you are, too.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just cried and cried like a baby that day, because it said
so much and it meant so much to the point that I'm up there
thinking about her and she took the initiative to have her teacher
call me. The next day, I cooked her oatmeal like I normally do for
breakfast, and she dropped it. She said, `Dad, I'm sooo sorry.' We
were running late, but it was like she didn't want to do anything
that would bring me any more hurt. It's amazing, but when I look at
her, that adds to my strength and helps to keep me going.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on those gloomiest of days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
