<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE KEY TO REPLAY: EQUAL COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a suggestion to the National Football League on how to
ensure a level playing field for instant replay officiating.
</P>
<P>
   Pay the network carriers to have the same amount of cameras and
playback machines at each game.
</P>
<P>
   As it is now, ESPN, CBS, ABC, and Fox use different amounts of
equipment in their coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Whether a network uses four cameras or 20, every major play _ or
at least those deemed reviewable by the recent NFL owners agreement
_ would be captured on video. Whether its the best angle of the
play is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, for instance, covers as many as eight games on Sundays and
uses 10 cameras and eight playback machines for its national game
and a minimum of four cameras and three playback machines for its
regional contests.
</P>
<P>
   CBS uses 15 cameras and ten replay machines at it two top games,
and a minimum of seven cameras and five replay machines at its
regional games. More cameras translate to more isolation shots of
individual matchups. Individual cameras could be assigned to each
of the skilled positions with another one trained solely on the
offensive line.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer cameras means less isolated shots of those individual
matchups. All the big plays will be shown, but instead of seeing Ty
Law jam Keyshawn Johnson at the line of scrimmage, viewers would
see the matchup later in the play when the ball neared.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can catch all the action with four cameras, but you feel
more comfortable with more,'' said one television analyst. ``That
way, you know every angle is covered.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanket coverage is not an issue on ESPN or ABC. ESPN uses 20
cameras and 10 replay machines for each of its Thursday or Sunday
night games. ABC uses 12-15 cameras and six or eight replay
machines for every Monday Night football game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have every play covered from multi-angles,'' said ABC
spokesman Mark Mandel. ``Whatever happens on the field, it will be
documented.''
</P>
<P>
   That's fine for those speciality games, but the majority of
games don't draw that amount of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   If it is any consolation, at least both teams would suffer
equally in games covered by only four cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Sure.
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to the Buffalo Bills after their game in Foxorough or
the Seattle Seahawks, who lost to the New York Jets when Vinny
Testaverde was given credit for a touchdown he didn't really score.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just the way it is,'' said CBS analyst Phil Simms.
``The good thing is that it can correct some very unjust calls. The
bad thing is that it could become the focus of every single
telecasts, whether a call is reversed or not. Yea, there were some
tough calls last year. But one thing you'll find out is there
weren't a lot of them. I say, get on with the game and not belabor
blown calls.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms said that instat replay still won't settle everything. He
pointed out that the pass interference call at the end of last
year's patriots-Bills game in which Terry Glenn was pushed would
still be ultimately decided on the field. The ruling awarding
Vincent Brisby a catch when he was out-of-bounds could have been
reversed, as would Vinnie Testaverde's last minute touchdown
against the Seattle Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   John Madden doesn't like the system for a completely different
reason. ``No coach wants replay to be tied to timeouts,'' madden
said. ``The head coach has the worst seat in the house, so he's
probably not going to see the play clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Madden said the system forces coaches to deploy an assistant to
monitor the game in the press box. The assistant coach weould then
signal their challenge to the referees.
</P>
<P>
   Given the recent trend of conferencing among officials during
games, Madden suggsted adding a monitor to those meetings and allow
the refree to decide whether further review is warranted. ``They're
taking all that time anyway,'' madden said. ``Then the coaches
would have nothing to do with it. If an official missed something
it would get corrected.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
`Creator' speaks
</P>
<P>
   TNT basketball analyst Kenny Smith grabbed a great interview
with Allen Iverson aired after Tuesday night's Lakers-Timberwolves
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to be known as a point guard or two guard,''
Iverson told Smith. ``I'd rather people label me a creator.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson talked about his once-stormy relationship with coach
Larry Brown. ``It was rocky at first,'' he said. ``But I've
matured. I'm listening to him now. I realize that he was never
trying to hurt me. He was just trying to make me a better player.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown agreed, saying, ``We have a mutual respect now.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson also talked about his off-the-court problems. ``I know
that I will make mistakes,'' he said. ``I also know know that I
learn something every day. I know that I'm not a bad guy just
because of the people that I hang around with or the way I wear my
hair. The credit comes when you start winning. Dennis Rodman became
a genius all of a sudden after the Bulls started winning
championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson said he would love to play with Rodman. ``He plays every
game as if its his last,'' Iverson said. ``I want all my teammates
to know that is how I play the game. I just try to send that
message to them that I may be the highest-paid player on the team
but look at all the burn marks and cherries that I have from diving
on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Holyfield-Lewis No. 8
</P>
<P>
   TVKO, the pay-per-view arm of HBO, generated 1.2 million buys
for the Holyfield-Lewis fight or roughly $60 million. That makes
the fight the eighth highest television gate in history . . . ESPN
has gotten its wish to televise the America's Cup without worrying
about airing a competing network's logos. Fox Sports Net had signed
an agreement allowing the upstart cable network to plaster its logo
on Young America's yachts. It's great marketing, akin to placing
posters of Keith Olbermann behind goalie nets to ensure that Fox
Sports Net gets shown on competiting networks whenever a goal was
scored. ESPN threatened to not carry the race unless Fox Sports Net
wasn't allowed to basically receive free advertising space. It's
understandable, but ESPN's opposition allowed Fox Sports Net to
transform its guerilla marketing strategy to a higher ground.
``When we gave money to help build a winning US entrant, we did it
to bring the Cup back to America, and it was a good marketing
opportunity,'' Fox spokesman Vince Wladika told Associated Press.
``When it became apparent that the televising network was willing
to sacrifice the event along with America's chances of reclaiming
the Cup, we felt it was our duty to put our own interest behind
that of America's reclamation of that Cup.'' Bully for Fox Sports .
. . Former Nets and UMass coach John Calipari debuts on ESPN's
``NBA Matchup'' March 21. The show, hosted by Andre Aldridge and
analyst Fred Carter, airs on ESPN2 at 12:30 a.m. and on ESPN at
8:30 a.m. on Sunday mornings. Calipari replaces analyst Jim Lyman,
the former Philadelphia, Washington, and Clippers' head coach who
was named a Nets assistant Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
