<HEADLINE>
DUKE IS KING, BUT THE COURT IS WIDE OPEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the college basketball season winding down to its final two
weekends, the pecking order this season remains clear. There is
Duke and there is everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   There is also more parity than ever. If there is any doubt about
that, look at the makeup of the Sweet 16, which includes five
double-digit seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Included are representatives from three mid-major conferences:
Gonzaga (West Coast), Miami of Ohio (Mid-American), and Southwest
Missouri State (Missouri Valley).
</P>
<P>
   Gonzaga coach Dan Monson has a theory on why parity _ if you can
call it that _ has arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they reduced the scholarships from 15 to 13, big schools
couldn't take everybody,'' said Monson. ``If there were still 15
scholarships, (Gonzaga guard) Matt (Santangelo) would be at
Stanford today.''
</P>
<P>
   The other factor is the NBA. The bigger programs, especially,
are having trouble keeping their best players for more than a year
or two, which eventually proves costly, unless you are a school
such as Duke or Kentucky that can restock every year.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Duke, if the Devils make the Final Four, they will
have beaten a No. 16 seed (Florida A&AMP;M), a 9 seed (Tulsa), a 12
seed (Southwest Missouri State), and either a 6 seed (Temple) or a
10 seed (Purdue) to make it to St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   That's hardly heavy lifting and would be the easiest route to
the Final Four since 1991, when North Carolina reached the Final
Four by beating No. 16 Northeastern, No. 9 Villanova, No. 12
Eastern Michigan, and No. 10 Temple.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Calipari, Part II? No
</P>
<P>
   OK, let's deal with some rumors (and right now they are just
that) which spawn like tornadoes this time of year. No, deposed
Nets coach John Calipari will not be coaching next season in
Amherst or anywhere in New England in the near future. When
Calipari was at the University of Massachusetts, he had a clause in
his contract that stated he could leave the Minutemen if any one of
a group of selected schools called. UCLA, Kansas, and North
Carolina were on that list.
</P>
<P>
   Will any of those jobs open soon? Perhaps. The speculation about
Bill Guthridge's future remains a prime topic in North Carolina.
The latest is that if Guthridge decides he has had enough, Kansas
coach Roy Williams would replace him. As for UCLA, Steve Lavin has
irked some old-time Bruin loyalists with his Generation X style of
coaching. That, plus the Bruins' early exit (a first-round loser to
Detroit) could make things interesting for Lavin in the next
several months. Would the Bruins switch Lavin for Calipari?
Perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Calipari wants to get back into college coaching, but he can
afford to wait for a high-profile job such as Kansas, Michigan, or
UCLA. Calipari has also checked with the NCAA to see if there are
any ramifications of the Marcus Camby affair that could hurt him in
the future with NCAA schools. No matter what happens, Calipari will
not have to worry about his next paycheck for awhile, since he
reportedly received a payoff of nearly $3 million from the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Irish have options
</P>
<P>
   Here's the latest on the Notre Dame situation. It could get
resolved quickly if the Irish call Utah coach Rick Majerus, who
might bite if he can be convinced the Irish are serious about
upgrading their program as quickly as possible. Majerus is not big
on images, which means putting on three-piece suits and schmoozing
with alumni and high rollers. He is into finding kids who have a
passion to play the game and who will win. But some people at Notre
Dame don't think Majerus would be a good fit, and he also makes
nearly a $1 million a year, which Notre Dame will not match. San
Diego State, which is building a new facility and wants to upgrade
its program, also reportedly is focusing on Majerus. Notre Dame
officials have put together a list of five or six coaches:
Delaware's Mike Brey, Washington's Bob Bender, Siena's Paul Hewitt,
Seton Hall's Tommy Amaker, Princeton's Bill Carmody, and Xavier's
Skip Prosser. The list will then be prioritized and the Irish will
try to have their coach by the end of the NCAA Tournament, at the
latest . . . Brey and Wake Forest coach Dave Odom are reportedly
being considered for the Georgia job, although Oklahoma's Kelvin
Sampson and Tulsa's Bill Self are also supposedly in the mix, while
St. Louis has asked permission to talk to New Mexico's Dave Bliss,
who has also interviewed at Vanderbilt and Baylor . . . Marquette
is asking about former St. John's coach Fran Fraschilla, who also
has his name up for consideration at East Carolina and San Diego
State . . . Trouble is brewing at Minnesota, where Clem Haskins
will have a difficult time recovering from the academic scandal
that was revealed last week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boyages `hot' assistant
</P>
<P>
   One of the hotter assistants is Ohio State associate head coach
Rick Boyages, a longtime protoge of Jim O'Brien. Boyages is ready
to be a head coach. Yale and Brown are already interested, and if
Steve Alford makes the expected move from Southwest Missouri State
(supposedly Iowa), Boyages's name is already on that ready list.
``Ricky is definitely ready,'' said O'Brien. ``I just want him to
get into a position where he has a chance to compete and win.''
Boyages also could wind up in the Ivy League at Yale or Brown, each
of which are searching for new coaches. If Holy Cross upgrades its
pay and increases its scholarship level in the mostly
nonscholarship Patriot League, it could be a decent job. But
athletic director Dick Reagan also wants someone with head coaching
experience and is trying to finalize a deal that would bring former
Pittsburgh coach Ralph Williard to the Cross . . . Former Virginia
coach Jeff Jones wants to get back into the mix and could wind up
at a place like East Carolina.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1419EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
