<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-FRYE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRYE SET TO GIVE IT A TRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ Watch out for Superman. He's coming soon to
your neighorhood ballpark disguised as Red Sox second baseman Jeff
Frye.
</P>
<P>
   Frye will start at second base Saturday against the Pittsburgh
Pirates. He knows there are a lot of people pulling for him to
succeed after missing the entire 1998 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am Superman,'' he said when asked how he would approach his
first big league game in 18 months. ``Just before the game I'm
going to slip into a phone booth and . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to play (in tonight's game) against the Reds. I know
everybody wants me to be out there. But I don't make the final
decisions, and if it takes one more day for me not to get injured,
that is what I've got to do.''
</P>
<P>
   With little more than two weeks left in spring training, it has
suddenly become very important that the Red Sox evaluate Frye. At
the start of spring training he was sidelined by a bruised rib
cage. It was thought he was finally ready to play last week, but a
nagging groin problem kept him on the practice field. Thursday he
was taking ground balls and running the bases, always a good sign.
</P>
<P>
   Moves have to be made if he cannot perform. The trade winds
normally heat up in the last two weeks. The Sox still don't have a
position for newcomer Jose Offerman, who has started 11 of the 16
games at second base this spring. Donnie Sadler (2), Jim Chamblee
(2), and Lou Merloni (1) have started the other games. Sadler and
Merloni could make the club as utility players. But because of his
experience Frye has an edge at second. And his ability to play
several positions has always been a strong point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeff didn't lose his job,'' reminds Sox manager Jimy Williams.
``He just got hurt. If he's going to be with us he's going to go
out there and play. What he does out there will tell us.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams has no problem platooning players. Scott Hatteberg and
Jason Varitek share the catching. Damon Buford, Trot Nixon, Troy
O'Leary, and Darren Lewis constitute the outfield rotation. Reggie
Jefferson and Mike Stanley were supposed to swing with Offerman in
a designated hitter/first base rotation. But this all assumes Frye
can cut the proverbial mustard.
</P>
<P>
   ``First we've got to put him out there and see what happens,''
said Williams. ``Actually, he could play against the Reds in
Sarasota. But I'm being a little cautious. It seems to me that if a
player is coming off an injury, it's not the best thing we can do
to put him in a road game. That's an hour-and-a-half bus ride, the
game and some ice, then an hour-and-a-half bus ride back home.
Better to let him stay here and get in his work. Then he can face
the next day in a better frame of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams says his preference with middle infielders is not to
platoon. But that's not always possible. Nomar Garciaparra started
143 games. But his partners included Mike Benjamin (73), Sadler
(38), Merloni (32), and Mark Lemke (29). Benjamin has since moved
on to Pittsburgh. Frye would undoubtedly get the lion's share of
starts at second. But he has to prove himself in the last couple of
weeks, which is a challenge worthy of Superman.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can play,'' said Williams, ``then 10-12 days should be
enough. But he has to get out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
