<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASLER EASING HIS WAY BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUPITER, Fla. _ Mike Easler says there are no hard feelings.
Even though he was fired by the Red Sox in 1995, and sued for
wrongful dismissal (the suit was settled out of court), Easler says
he'd still like to manage the Boston ball club someday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's ever a winner in Boston, I would love to be a part
of it,'' Easler says. ``I'd love to manage the Red Sox. It would be
different for the city, I'll tell you that. Maybe that would break
the curse.''
</P>
<P>
   Easler has landed. Three years after that zany spring when he
refused to coach replacement players and was shown the door by
general manager Dan Duquette, Easler is hitting coach of the St.
Louis Cardinals. He's teaching Mark McGwire how to hit home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Well, not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mark teaches me,'' says the original `Hit Man.' ``I watch him.
When I got the job, I got tapes of all the hitters. I studied Mark.
I've never seen a man, day after day, so fundamentally sound. He
never makes a mistake. He has a total understand of hitting. He
took all the stuff he learned in Oakland and he looks totally
different now. He used to have big holes in his swing. Basically,
the only thing I try to do with Mark is make him stay back.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cards decided not to bring Dave Parker back after last
season and manager Tony La Russa called Easler, who'd managed
independant Nashua of the Atlantic League in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Easler played 14 seasons of big league ball before becoming a
hitting coach in 1991. He worked with the Blue Jays and Brewers
before taking over as Red Sox hitting coach in 1993. Mo Vaughn
became his prize pupil and Vaughn had trouble letting go when
Easler was dismissed in '95.
</P>
<P>
   What happened between the Sox and Easler has never been entirely
clear. He refused to coach the replacement players in the spring of
'95, claiming the ball club should pay him the then-major league
minimum $115,000. Easler was making $80,000 at the time. Duquette
suspended him and eventually hired Jim Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Easler went to the National Labor Relations Board, which ruled
he had a legitimate case. According to Easler, the Red Sox placed
liens on the beauty salon run by his wife, and a rental property he
owned. After the suit was settled (he received no money, but the
liens were removed and the Sox agreed not to seek back wages), he
coached at National Christian University in San Antonio, then
managed Nashua.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, all the things that happened between Boston and here
were all for a reason, to get my mind and heart back into the
game,'' he says today. ``I had experienced the death of my mother
and the death of my father. It was a combination of so many things.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a matter of the replacement situation. I used that as a
reason not to come back. But I was just burned out. Nothing against
Dan, but with that replacement thing, there was an agreement that
me and Dan had that I don't think he lived up to. It was private.
He knows. It was other things. I was just burned out. And then with
the replacement situation and the way they were paying the coaches,
it just didn't add up.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I talked to Dan last spring and spent a lot of time in his
office. When you go through these things, you might say things and
act a certain way. I knew it was going to hurt my career. But it
took me to go two or three steps backward to get to where I am
now.''
</P>
<P>
   He never stopped coaching Vaughn after he was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the '95 season Mo called me in the winter time after he
struggled so badly against Cleveland,'' Easler said. ``After that I
flew in there about every two weeks and we worked at the cage in
his house. Jimmy knew it. Everybody knew it. Jimmy's a great coach
and I respect him. We just have two different philosophies. But
Mo's similar to me. He hits inside-out, and hits the ball to all
fields. Hit for average and power. But now I haven't talked to him
since August. He's on his own now. He's a big boy now.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mike Easler is back in the Show.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaugnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
