<HEADLINE>
`TRUTH' DOCUMENTARY DETAILS TROUBLED CAREERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WESLEY MORRIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a man whose agenda was breaking the law, comedian Lenny
Bruce spent a lot of time studying it. He hadn't become obsessed
with it in order to further subvert it. Rather, he wanted to
understand why and how it was raping him, forcibly entering his art
and shutting it down.
</P>
<P>
   That's the depressing revelation of director Robert Weide's
sneakily affecting documentary ``Lenny Bruce: Swear to Tell the
Truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The film exists as an incensing time capsule of an era when the
cops would haunt a nightclub's exit doors to lock a guy up for
having a big, critical mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, the documentary branch of the Academy managed to screen
the film and nominate it for an Oscar this year. Perhaps members
were absorbed in Weide's tacit assertion that in an age of Jerry
Springer, Marilyn Manson and the Internet, Lenny Bruce couldn't get
arrested for his brand of cerebral raunch and lightning social
commentary. Or maybe it's that Weide allows the facts and Bruce's
material to speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce was a martyr for his art, driven almost insane by attempts
to censor his act. ``Swear to Tell the Truth'' begins as a sort of
``This Is Your Life'' with the comic's eccentric mother, his wife
and daughter offering biography and doing some psychological
profiling.
</P>
<P>
   Early, Weide shows Bruce doing uncanny impersonations and
innocuous-enough sketch routines. Later, he unearths an unaired
performance on ``The Steve Allen Show,'' in which Bruce seems
addled and distracted with the humorous melancholy and rootless
lifestyle that would eventually force his wife to leave him. The
film grows darker and slightly harrowing, once it's clear that
Weide wants to lay Bruce bare.
</P>
<P>
   Here, Bruce is not merely a troubled family man but a
self-avenger whose stability and judgment (never one of Bruce's
more active traits) went spiraling.
</P>
<P>
   Paranoia unseats Bruce's smooth demeanor, and he's shown in a
collection of still photos, archival footage and home movies as
devolving from a swank lounge cat into a harried, hard-bitten
creature who often looks cornered and weary.
</P>
<P>
   Once speaking his mind became a challenge, Weide suggests that
Bruce decided to contort his image, chilling with Hugh Hefner at
the Playboy mansion. Hefner, his magazine and lifestyle, were the
perfect societal affront to which he could attach himself. But for
the men dogging Bruce, Hef was never the offensive critic Bruce
was. Playboy was a surveillance man's best friend. They couldn't
get into Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   ``You either dug Lenny or you wanted to wash his mouth out with
soap,'' says a friend. What prurient detractors did to Bruce was
worse: They washed him out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
