<SLUG> BC-TEEN-MAYOR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG MAYOR BRINGS MATURE QUALITY TO OFFICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TIM O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALATIE, N.Y. _ Mayor-elect Jason Nastke is not your ordinary
teen-ager.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after graduating from high school, Nastke was elected
the top official in this village of 1,500 Tuesday when he defeated
the 65-year-old incumbent, Charles White Sr., by 182 votes. He
takes office April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Hudson Valley Community College sophomore will work with a
four-member board of trustees that includes his father, Joseph
Nastke, a political novice compared to his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's my boss in politics,'' Joseph Nastke said with a laugh.
``I am the boss at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Nastke, 19, is mature for his age and insists he won't
allow his photograph to be taken if he is not in a suit. He wanted
to run for the village board two years ago, but state law said he
was too young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a complete interest in my community,'' he said.
``It was just a real love for government, history.''
</P>
<P>
   Walk around the quaint village about 20 miles west of
Pittsfield, Mass., and people praise Jason not for his youth but
for his love of his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's going to do great for the village,'' said Fern
Bashford, owner of Fern's Deli on Main Street. ``He is a very smart
young man. He does his homework before he does things.''
</P>
<P>
   She pauses, seemingly aware the word homework could be
misinterpreted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does his research before he opens his mouth,'' she
clarifies.
</P>
<P>
   Michele and Steven Abrams, owners of Abrams Jewelers, are
similarly enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed the change,'' Michele said. ``He is very young, but
he's really on the ball as far as what's going on in the village.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man's disgust over the handling a new water system for
the town and a heated fight at a February board meeting prompted
Jason Nastke to run for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point, I said that was wrong. It was a disgrace,''
Nastke said. ``It was wrong that the mayor couldn't keep control of
the meeting.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Nastke said his son pulled him into politics: It was not
the usual topic of discussion around the family's dinner table as
Jason grew up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason developed that interest on his own,'' his father
recalled. ``I have never been involved in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   His age became an issue in the campaign, with White opining the
village did not need a ``childlike'' mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big issue, a real big issue, but you know I went to
people and said, `I really want to do the job. I told you I could
do the job of trustee and I did. I want to do the job of mayor,'''
Nastke said.
</P>
<P>
   The part-time job, which pays $2,700 a year and carries a
two-year term, will not interrupt his education. Nastke is
completing his studies for an associate's degree in business and
finance, and he plans to transfer to a four-year college. He has
not selected one, but promises it will be close enough to home for
him to commute.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever college I go to would have to be within traveling
distance so I can continue to be mayor,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
