<SLUG> BC-CHAVEZ-AIRPORT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN ANTONIO CONSIDERS NAMING AIRPORT FOR CESAR CHAVEZ 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHRISTOPHER ANDERSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The City Council is considering renaming the San
Antonio International Airport for California labor organizer and
farm activist Cesar Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Councilmen Rick Vasquez and Mario Salas are sponsoring the
latest attempt to name a prominent San Antonio landmark after the
former United Farm Workers president, who died in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Jeff Webster is the only council member who opposes
the proposal, although others expressed some reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Seven council members, one more than necessary to change the
airport name, have endorsed a plan to ``begin the review process''
leading up to an April 22 council vote on whether to name the
airport for Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Renaming the airport would be an appropriate and expedient way
to pay tribute to Chavez, Salas said.
</P>
<P>
   ``An airport has international significance,'' Salas said. ``It
sends an important worldwide message.''
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Ed Garza said changing the name would be a procedural
snap compared with the lengthy process needed in renaming streets,
which some businesses oppose because of the expense of changing
addresses.
</P>
<P>
   If the council agrees, the airport officially would be called
Cesar Chavez San Antonio International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   Councilman Jose Menendez said some voters believe Chavez is long
overdue for a permanent and public honor, while others have said
they would oppose any recognition of Chavez, whose role as an
advocate for farm workers drew opposition from agribusiness groups
and conservative politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Howard Peak was cool to the idea of renaming the airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a process,'' Peak said, citing the practice of
referring all items requested by council members to a scheduling
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Several council members said Peak privately expressed fears of a
public backlash over the issue. The mayor has said he would like to
see a major street named after Chavez.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
