<SLUG> BC-FILM-REVIEW-CRIME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASTWOOD MISSES HIS TARGET IN `TRUE CRIME' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clint Eastwood looks tired. Not old _ this isn't some rant
against 60-plus actors wooing nubile co-stars. Age has nothing to
do with it.
</P>
<P>
   No, Eastwood looks tired in a pooped-to-his-bones,
existentialist kind of way, as though this game he's been playing
is no longer any fun.
</P>
<P>
   It was, once. But in ``True Crime,'' Eastwood's success as an
actor-director-producer is hampered by the maddening suspicion that
he'd rather be doing something else. He seems distracted, bored out
of his wits, bushed. As Everett, a crusading (what else?)
journalist who makes an 11th-hour effort to clear a death-row
prisoner, Eastwood is so low on gas his direction so lackadaisical
that it's a wonder the movie doesn't konk out in the first
half-hour.
</P>
<P>
   That it doesn't is proof of two things: That the ticking-clock
anxiety of a man doomed to die at midnight is a powerful source of
suspense. And that Isaiah Washington, playing the condemned Frank
Beachum, is one of the most quietly dynamic actors working in films
today.
</P>
<P>
   You've seen Washington before in ``Out of Sight,'' ``Bulworth,''
``love jones'' but you've never seen him hoist an ailing film to
his shoulders and carry it to the finish. He has ferocious talent,
a combination of gravity, stillness and short-fuse dynamism that's
rare in a performer so young. If nothing else, Eastwood deserves
credit for giving him elbow room.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, he gives everything elbow room. Odd as it is for
a man of mythically few words, Eastwood seems incapable of making a
tight movie. His last two (``Absolute Power'' and ``Midnight in the
Garden of Good and Evil'') were baggy duds, and even his best
recent films (``Unforgiven,'' ``The Bridges of Madison County'')
mosey along at their own sweet pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``True Crime'' is neither his best nor his worst film, and at
128 minutes it's far from his longest. But it's flatly directed,
awkwardly edited and until a crackerjack crescendo in the final
reel herky-jerky paced. And the end will leave you scratching your
dome in bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, any movie that credits three screenwriters (among them
Stephen Schiff, who adapted ``Lolita'' and ``The Deep End of the
Ocean'') has a right to be confusing. It also has a right to
mix-and-match an assortment of haggard stereotypes, from the cute
but abusive panhandler (``Promise me you will not spend this on
food,'' says Everett in one of the film's funnier bits, handing the
guy some money) to the trash-mouthed, sex-obsessed newspaper
editor. James Woods brings a certain high-wattage loathsomeness to
the editor, and Denis Leary, as a hangdog assignment editor who
mopes a bit when his wife (Frances Fisher) sleeps with Everett,
musters a particle of sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   Eastwood himself musters none, in part because he's not supposed
to: His Everett is a terrible father, a lousy husband, an
obstreperous employee and an altogether unlikable individual. But
rest assured, he's a great reporter this, despite the fact that he
never files a story and the only notes he takes are cryptic
paraphrases on the order of ``Blv. J.C.'' (He scribbles this,
somewhat grudgingly, after Beachum delivers an eloquent soliloquy
on fear, isolation and his faith in Jesus Christ).
</P>
<P>
   All the same, the worst crime committed by the screenplay isn't
its lack of journalistic verisimilitude. It's the absolute failure
to explain why Everett cares about Beachum and what makes him chase
wild geese in an effort to save him. All we're told is that he has
a blazing epiphany involving potato chips (long story), and that he
trusts his ``nose''; his schnozz gets big play, both literally and
figuratively. The rest is as fuzzy as it is forced.
</P>
<P>
   Except Washington. If you see ``True Crime,'' see it for his
performance for his crisp delivery, for his touching goodbye scenes
with his wife and daughter, for his exquisite dignity in the face
of death. In a film short on dramatic tension, he's reason enough
to watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
