<HEADLINE>
SOME DISHES TASTE BETTER WITH AGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RUTH FANTASIA  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Some dishes simply taste better a day or two
after they're made.
</P>
<P>
   Meatloaf, for instance. Or vegetable soup, or chili, or
cheesecake, or spaghetti sauce, or lasagna. Just about anything in
the Italian food family, for that matter. These foods improve with
age because the more time allowed for the flavors to marry, the
better the food tastes. Since flavors seem to meld no matter what
the temperature of the food, these dishes, and others like them,
are particularly suited for weekend cooking and weeknight eating.
</P>
<P>
   Take that meatloaf. Make one on Sunday and serve it up with a
big bowl of mashed potatoes. After dinner, cut the meatloaf into
slices and wrap each slice separately in plastic wrap. Then, place
the slices in a plastic container or wrap them in freezer paper.
Now you have individual portions of meatloaf for whenever you
choose.
</P>
<P>
   And those leftover potatoes, cover and store them in the fridge.
A day or two later, you can take them out, form them into patties
and fry in very hot oil for potato cakes.
</P>
<P>
   And cheesecake: Mix it and bake it but don't put any topping on
it. If you leave the cake plain, topping slices as you serve them,
you can freeze the leftovers for serving another time. Wrap the
cake pieces tightly in plastic wrap and place in a plastic
container. Thaw in the refrigerator before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Soups, sauces and chili can all be made on Saturday or Sunday
and served during the week. There are a few things to remember,
though:
</P>
<P>
   _ Place hot foods in shallow containers for faster cooling and
freeze within two hours of cooking.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leave at least a 1/2-inch of space at the top of the freezer
container when packing; liquids in these recipes will expand as
they freeze.
</P>
<P>
   _ Thaw frozen foods in the refrigerator, in cold water or in the
microwave. Even though they have been cooked, foods may be
hazardous if left at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   _ Reheat foods to an internal temperature of 165 degrees or
until hot and steaming.
</P>
<P>
   _ When microwaving, be sure to cover and rotate the food so it
heats evenly. Allow food to stand for two minutes after heating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1435EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
