<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAR-WARS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' IMITATORS FACE THE LEGAL FORCE OF LUCASFILM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Two months before the release of its
much-anticipated new ``Star Wars'' movie, Lucasfilm Ltd. is sending
a message to companies and individuals who might be thinking of
pirating images from the flick: Don't.
</P>
<P>
   The San Rafael, Calif.-based film production company said
Thursday it received about $1 million in a settlement with unnamed
companies that have made, sold and advertised counterfeit products
bearing the images of Luke Skywalker and Darth Vadar, among other
``Star Wars'' characters.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the companies have been ordered to stop making and
selling the products.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm President Gordan Radley said his company was
``dedicated to its `Star Wars' fans and will go to great lengths to
ensure that the merchandise they purchase is safe and not of the
inferior quality found in unauthorized products. As the new film
(`Episode I: The Phantom Menace') approaches, we are aggressively
dealing with these issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm said it could not release the identities of the
alleged pirates due to a confidentiality agreement. Nor would it
explain what products had been counterfeited.
</P>
<P>
   However, a lawsuit filed by Lucasfilm in December 1997 in San
Francisco federal court alleged that three East Coast postage stamp
manufacturers made stamps flanked with ``Star Wars'' images for use
in various West Indies and African countries without having a
license to produce or sell them.
</P>
<P>
   The businesses named in the lawsuit that sold the stamps were
Volpone Stamp Co. of Hicksville, N.Y.; International Collectors
Society in Owings Mills, Md.; and New York City-based
Inter-Governmental Philatelic Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the stamps, Lucasfilm's suit alleged that the
companies had not been authorized to use ``Star Wars'' images for a
pamphlet they produced titled ``99 Little Known Facts About Star
Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Volpone would not comment on the settlement with Lucasfilm.
Executives from International Collectors Society could not be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Malamud, president of Inter-Governmental Philatelic,
defended his company's business practices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any stamps we ever produced were fully licensed and approved
by Lucasfilm,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm is credited with founding modern movie merchandising
back in 1977, when the first ``Star Wars'' film was released.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the company has racked up an estimated $4.5 billion
in sales from toys, calendars, T-shirts and myriad other
paraphernalia bearing images from the three ``Star Wars'' films.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1437EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
