</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-BOMBAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINDOWS 98 IS WATCHING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I heard somebody say that Microsoft uses
Windows 98 to ``brand'' everything you do with a serial number so
they can tell who created a file in case they need to trace
something. Is that ethical?
</P>
<P>
   _ Big Brother's Keeper
</P>
<P>
   DEAR BIG: Interesting. ``Microsoft'' and ``ethics'' in the same
paragraph. I don't think I've ever seen that before.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I know it all sounds like one of those Internet hoaxes, but
it's true. Windows puts an identifying number on your computer that
is embedded in Office 97 documents. And Microsoft actually admitted
it. Of course, Microsoft called it a minor security flaw and
started churning out lots of reasons why it's really not a bad guy.
According to the Microsoft Ministry of Truth, the number ``was
designed to help third parties work with and reference Office 97
documents.'' Doubleplusgood doublespeak, no?
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't end there. If you used the Registration Wizard to
register Win98 electronically, you should know that Microsoft
probably gathered that number as well as your name and address and
information about your hardware during the process. Thinking about
wiping your hard drive yet?
</P>
<P>
   The boys in Redmond are scrambling to put a good face on this
fiasco by plugging the security holes. They say they've updated
Microsoft.com to stop receiving hardware info during registration,
and they're coming up with a new wizard that won't even look for
it. They're working on a way to remove an existing hardware ID, and
they say they'll purge whatever they've already gathered. Hey, I
know what you're thinking, but Microsoft guys never lie. Well,
almost never.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also promises a patch for Office 97 that prevents
insertion of the identifier and a tool to remove anything that's
already in your documents. Check for those at
officeupdate.microsoft.com soon.
</P>
<P>
   All this makes me wonder what else those weasels are up to that
we haven't found out about. You know, there's this black van that's
been following me for weeks now. Whoops! Somebody's knocking on the
door. Who could it be at this hour?
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: A computer-savvy friend tells me Bill Gates
caused the Y2K problem by his design of DOS. Is that true?
</P>
<P>
   _ Suspicious
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SUSP: I hope you're happy. You've put me in the
uncomfortable and unfamiliar position of defending Big Bill.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, he didn't design DOS. He bought it, slapped his
name on it and made a gazillion dollars off it. Second, the Y2K
problem goes back to when computer memory was so precious that
programmers couldn't waste the two extra bytes it would take to
represent a date with four digits. Now, older programs and systems
will think 2000 is 1900, and civilization as we know it will come
to an end.
</P>
<P>
   But you can't blame Bill. He was busy being born about the same
time the problem was. Hmmmm. Maybe I spoke too fast. I certainly
don't want to add to all those Antichrist rumors, but you do know
his real name is William Henry Gates III, don't you? If you take
all the letters in ``Bill Gates,'' convert them to ASCII codes, add
up the numbers, then add the III it comes out to 666. I'm sure it's
all a simple coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay suggests carrying a
silver crucifix or possibly some wooden stakes at all times for
your protection. He can be reached at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com
or via snail-mail at Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth
76101. Fax: 390-7257. His real name is Michael Gerst, editorial
systems manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
