<P>
   &UR; NONLETHAL ACOUSTIC WEAPONS SEEM TO BE DOOMED &LR;  _ Attempts to
build acoustic weapons are destined to fail, according to a German
physicist. He has found no hard evidence that infrasound,
frequencies too low to hear, can cause any debilitating effects,
and is convinced infrasound weapons will never work. By Jeff Hecht.
500 words. (slugged: BC-ACOUSTIC-WEAPONS-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SUCKLING PIGS ACQUIRE TASTE FOR CORDON BLEU &LR;  _ Farmers could
ease piglets through the trauma of weaning by feeding them garlic.
Researchers in Britain believe that piglets will take to eating
solid food more readily if both the mother's milk and the feed have
the same strong flavor, such as garlic or cumin. By Andy Coghlan.
400 words. (slugged:
BC-WEANING-LIVESTOCK-WITH-GARLIC-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RIVAL STANDARDS ARE BLIGHTING MUSIC'S DIGITAL FUTURE &LR;  _ A
damaging battle is about to break out in the consumer electronics
industry on a scale not seen since the VHS and Betamax standards
for VCRs fought it out in the early 1980s. Rival alliances plan to
launch two incompatible music formats, both likely to include
anti-copying measures. By Barry Fox. 500 words. (slugged:
BC-MUSIC'S-DIGITAL-FUTURE-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW BEETLES COULD HELP PRESERVE YOUR FOOD &LR;  _ Beetles that dine
on dead bodies and flies that nibble rotten fruit could soon help
preserve your food. Researchers in Britain are using the antennae
of such insects to create sensors that warn when food is about to
go rotten. By Andy Coghlan. 400 words. (slugged:
BC-BEETLES-PRESERVE-FOOD-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF) &QL; 
