A6801 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-REVIEW-CASTRO-HN     03-19 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-CASTRO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR TAKES A SWING AT THE OTHER SIDE OF FIDEL CASTRO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When he finished his novel, ``Castro's Curveball,'' Tim Wendel
was probably thinking of Kevin Costner. Costner would be perfect
for the part of Billy Bryan, an aging catcher making a last stab at
baseball with the Havana Lions in 1947, discovering Fidel Castro's
curveball in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The possibilities of ``Castro's Curveball'' (Ballantine Books,
$23.95, 286 pages) being turned into a movie can't be hurt by
baseball's decision to OK a home-and-home series between the
Baltimore Orioles and the Cuban national team this spring _ the
first such exchange between Cuba and the United States since Castro
took power in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the novel came when Wendel read a piece written by
former major leaguer Don Hoak for Sport magazine in 1964. Hoak said
student demonstrators routinely took over ballfields during winter
ballgames in Havana in 1950-'51 and that during one of those
demonstrations he batted against Castro, who had taken the mound _
fouling off two pitches before the police moved in.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel was intrigued by the incident. Add a Cuban old-timers'
claim that Castro had a so-so fastball, a sneaky slider, ``but his
best pitch was his curveball,'' and Wendel had enough to wonder out
loud what would've happened if Castro had been wooed by American
baseball instead of Cuban politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Castro's Curveball'' goes so far as to have Castro volunteer
for tryouts, unleashing his wicked curveball on American sluggers,
before signing a contract with the Washington Senators. But the
book is seriously crippled by Wendel's decision to describe Castro
only from the outside. Because Wendel doesn't enter Castro's
thoughts, there is no way to explain how he could commit himself to
a revolution and playing baseball at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Castro is supposed to sign his contract, he writes a
note to Bryan saying, ``I've gone to Holguin, in the interior, to
train with my university comrades-in-arms to overthrow the corrupt
government of the Dominican Republic. We plan to oust the truant
Trujillo. For now, beisboll must be delayed ...''
</P>
<P>
   Moments like that come close to being laughable, and Wendel
knows enough to keep them to a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel's take on Castro _ a charming, headstrong speaker who had
no problem sacrificing others on his way to power _ is backed by
historical accounts. Castro's early idealism made way for the
bloodbaths at Santiago in 1953 and the suicide landings of 1956,
when he led 82 revolutionaries into a dead-end invasion.
</P>
<P>
   But Wendel is unable to get a real handle on Castro, then or
now.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he turns ``Castro's Curveball'' into a romance novel, a
tale of an over-the-hill catcher and a beautiful revolutionary torn
between ballgames and overthrowing the government.
</P>
<P>
   Wendel, a former sportswriter for the San Francisco Examiner who
also wrote the story of the 1980 U.S. hockey team, ``Going for the
Gold,'' has Bryan returning to Cuba half a century after his
postwar adventures with Malena Fonseca to find Malena's daughter _
his child or Castro's? _ and a completely different Havana.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
