<HEADLINE>
LE CARRE'S NEW NOVEL IS SINGULARLY DISAPPOINTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GINGER BRISTOW  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Le Carre's new novel, ``Single &AMP; Single,'' will be a
welcome sight in bookstores to his many long-term fans.
</P>
<P>
   With the end of the Cold War, the book begins well. Le Carre,
always an excellent writer, will not fail the reader with his
style. The book opens with one of its most interesting characters.
On a hillside in Turkey, a lawyer is on his knees, his hands tied
behind his back, a small gun at his head.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Mr. Winser, consciously chooses denial of the
situation, and his thought process is very interesting. As his life
passes before him, he asks himself why he has to keep marrying
these women through his life to find out he does not like them. By
the time the video and tape recording of the murder are complete,
we know the lawyer very well. I hated to see him die.
</P>
<P>
   It is a story of a venture capital investment house in London,
Single &AMP; Single, setting up off-shore businesses with the Orlov
brothers, who have turned their communist-government-controlled
businesses toward the free market.
</P>
<P>
   The fictional press proclaims the firm of Single &AMP; Single ``as
boldly going where lesser houses dither,'' and ``quartering the
nations of the new-look Communist bloc in search of opportunity.''
This opportunity runs the gamut from new legitimate business to
prostitution and finally illegal drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   When the younger Single is made aware of the immoral, not to
mention illegal, activities of his father and the new partners, he
betrays his father to customs officials.
</P>
<P>
   Single feels like a traitor, but accepts this over being a
criminal. But when the father disappears, the son seeks his
location, introducing us to a host of characters from his personal
and professional life.
</P>
<P>
   The basic promise of the book _ a father and son who through
betrayal and reversal of fortune find their way back to redemption
_ unfortunately does not materialize. It was this promise that kept
me reading.
</P>
<P>
   The writing is interesting for those who can jump from an
interior monologue to a dialogue, all within the same conversation.
This is not a book for lazy readers. It requires focus and
attention to keep up.
</P>
<P>
   With Single the younger, who seeks to redeem himself by
searching for his father who has gone into hiding, we look for the
same personal insight that the lawyer had in his final minutes, but
it never appears. This character never engaged me even though I
struggled to like him and share in his redemption.
</P>
<P>
   The characters seem to have been well thought out, but they just
never quite become real, including Single's mother, who is
something of a caricature. About three-quarters through the book,
we discover that one of the lead characters is gay. This has never
been hinted at, and it becomes relevant when the customs office
tries to strike a deal with him. It seems almost an afterthought
that works to move the plot forward, but meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   The plot and story-line drive the book, and for those who are
interested in the changes taking place in the old Soviet bloc, this
may be a book for them. For those who are looking for well-drawn
interesting characters, the book, is 345 pages of disappointment.
But fans of good writing and John Le Carre will not share in it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
