r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC'S-DIGITAL-FUTUR     03-19 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC'S-DIGITAL-FUTURE-(NEW-SCIENTIST)-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVAL STANDARDS ARE BLIGHTING MUSIC'S DIGITAL FUTURE  
 (FOR RELEASE THE WEEK OF MON., MARCH 22, 1999)
</HEADLINE>
   (This article from the London-based science and technology weekly
NEW SCIENTIST is free for use for New York Times News Service
clients. Please send clippings to the New York Times Syndicate at
122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168 or fax clippings to
212-499-3382.) 
 By BARRY FOX  
 Copyright 1999 New Scientist  
 (Distributed by New York Times Syndicate)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A damaging battle is about to break out in the consumer
electronics industry on a scale not seen since the VHS and Betamax
standards for VCRs fought it out in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Rival alliances plan to launch two incompatible music formats.
Both will come with draconian anti-copying measures that may
discourage potential purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   Standards have already been established for storing video or
computer data on DVDs (DVD-Video and DVD-ROM). Now the DVD Forum,
the industry's standards-setting body, has come up with a sound
format called DVD-Audio. This is backed by the recording company
Warner Brothers as well as electronics manufacturers Toshiba and
Panasonic.
</P>
<P>
   DVD-Audio promises to provide higher-quality sound than audio
CDs. It samples sound 192,000 times per second, compared with
44,000 times per second for CDs. And each sample it records is
stored as a chunk of data 24 bits long, against 16 bits for CD.
This ability to store more information results in improved sound
quality. What's more, DVD-Audio will cram 80 minutes of six-channel
surround sound on one side of a disc.
</P>
<P>
   But Philips and Sony, co-inventors of the CD format that now
dominates the record industry, make royalties from every CD player
and disc sold. They want to promote a high-quality extension to CD
technology so that they can maintain those revenues. They are
planning to launch a format called Super Audio CD. Instead of using
chunks of data of a fixed length, this format codes sound as a
stream of single bits.
</P>
<P>
   DVD-Audio discs require special players. And while Philips and
Sony say their format is compatible with existing CD players, they
have yet to produce mass-market discs to back their claim.
</P>
<P>
   Another drawback from consumers' point of view is that both
formats are likely to include a new copy-control system developed
to satisfy the big record companies.
</P>
<P>
   The sound is encrypted, and a digital ``watermark'' is added.
This still allows the disc to be copied onto analogue tape, but
record companies will have the option of adding extra codes to the
discs to control how many digital copies you can make, and of what
quality. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (This article is excerpted from New Scientist, a weekly science
and technology magazine based in London.) &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1444EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
