<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-COWBOY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRITER SPENDS A BRACING YEAR AS RANCH HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Books where the authors spend a day, a month or a year at
someone else's job are usually dumb. The Plimpton School of Writing
has three variations: Me, me and me, topped by fairy-tale
conversations and veterans giving grudging respect to the rookie.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cowboy Way: Seasons of a Montana Ranch'' by David McCumber
(Avon Books, $24, 338 pages) isn't like that. McCumber, a former
editor at the San Francisco Examiner and Santa Barbara News Press,
has written about a long, sometimes brutal year as a rank-wage
ranch hand living in a trailer on the 6,000-acre Birch Creek Ranch
in central Montana, bringing the reader into the heart of his
adventure, morning to night.
</P>
<P>
   From his first days on the ranch, feeding hay to cattle in
snow-covered fields, McCumber puts the reader right there _ ``Three
hours and seven loads later I was a wreck. The muscles in my arms
and shoulders were cramping constantly ... and the shooting pain in
my back was now a fixture, from shoulder blades to beltline,
grabbing as I moved in any direction, stabbing when I tried to
breathe deeply.''
</P>
<P>
   McCumber puts the reader through the calving process, too,
bringing heifers out of the freezing cold into stalls, reaching up
inside of them to pull a calf out, some mewling healthily, some
never moving. On the last day of a 20-below windstorm, McCumber has
to take 10 dead calves to the dump above the ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Looking down at the carcasses of cows and calves, getting ready
to pitchfork 10 more bodies onto the pile, he writes, ``Some were
little more than hide and bone, others looked as though they had
just stopped for a rest _ except that the birds had without
exception pecked out the eyes. All this was set against the
picture-postcard backdrop of the Crazy Mountains. A light, fine
snow was falling.''
</P>
<P>
   Nature is the one constant in ``The Cowboy Way.'' Not a day goes
by that McCumber doesn't tip a hat to it _ ``One morning as we
headed out of the shop yard to get our first load, I looked back
over my shoulder and saw that the first direct rays of the sun were
touching the stackyard on top of the bar, above the shop.
</P>
<P>
   ``First the top of the haystack, then the whole stack, then, as
we rounded the corner, the hill beneath it glowed gold, with
everything else still in shade. Spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   McCumber draws clean portraits of his co-workers and his
workaholic boss, Bill Galt, as well as the demands of a
contemporary cattle ranch, caught between four-wheel roundups and
horseback nostalgia. What emerges from ``The Cowboy Way'' is the
weight of nature on the land and the men who try to cope with it,
season to season.
</P>
<P>
   McCumber talks about hauling wide loads down a state highway all
morning _ ``We moved the swathers, without blocking any holiday
traffic, and at noon, Bill gave us the rest of the day off. That
brightened the crew's mood considerably. I drove to Livingston for
a Fourth of July barbecue. I tried to be sociable, festive even,
but I kept falling asleep in the middle of conversations. People
who don't work on a ranch have a hard time understanding this.''
</P>
<P>
   McCumber writes of deer and elk and getting away for a rare turn
at fly-fishing. ``I fished until the deepest part of dusk was
turning to night, keeping only the last _ two pounds of dinner with
a yellow belly and wide dark spots across its back. I fried it with
butter and garlic and green onions and fat slices of an enormous
meadow mushroom ... I drank two Miller beers and wished for this
one night to come back to me one more time, perhaps late in my
fifth decade, when I would need it just as much as I had tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   McCumber is able to carry across that joy to the reader time and
again _ the joy of watching a miserable winter turn to spring, the
joy of sitting on a good horse, handling stray steers, the joy of
seeing an elk cross a fence a few feet away, massive, majestic.
McCumber also describes the misery of a mud- soaked autumn and
winter, close calls with angry steers, and the ranch hosting
hunters for money, cutting up carcasses as part of the deal (``More
brain-salad surgery with the chain saw'').
</P>
<P>
   In the end, when McCumber says his goodbyes, unhappy to leave it
all behind, the reader is just as unhappy to see him go. This is
one walk-a-mile-in-my-shoes book that really works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
