<HEADLINE>
BATTLE FOR THE OSCARS PITS BRAVE SOLDIERS AGAINST BAWDY
ELIZABETHANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Try as you might, you cannot run away from the Oscar onslaught.
Every day, a TV spot is telling us that ``Shakespeare in Love'' is
the leading Oscar contender. Let us count the ways. It's nominated
for, among others, Best Picture, Best Actress, Supporting Actress
and Supporting Actor, Screenplay, and, probably, best vowel usage
by an American portraying a Brit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare'' may be the most sheerly enjoyable movie of all
the nominated films this year. It also happens to be very shrewd
about all of the Shakespeare stuff (the women are smarter and more
emotionally evolved, as they are in all Shakespearean comedies);
it's also a period piece, a romantic comedy and a comedy about
romance, all of which give this picture standing that none of the
other nominees has. This must be why it has 13 nominations total _
two more than ``Saving Private Ryan,'' considered to be the most
Oscar-worthy.
</P>
<P>
   A recent GQ piece strained to turn a truism _ you have to be a
gimp to win an Oscar _ into an article. And besides being a little
dated, it missed the point. It almost seems that to get a
nomination you have to set a movie in the past _ the 16th century,
for example, when most of the academy members were born, I think _
to get the Oscar voters to take your movie seriously. Look at this
year's Best Picture nominees: ``Shakespeare, Elizabeth,'' and the
movies that play on more recent nostalgia, the World War II-set
``Saving Private Ryan,'' ``The Thin Red Line'' and ``Life Is
Beautiful.'' Basically, they're all set in one of two eras.
</P>
<P>
   A few of the Oscar-nominated movies, given how square the
subjects are, try shifts of mood to expand their worlds, and
several use a contemporary energy to deal with their subjects.
``Elizabeth'' is staged with colors _ curry oranges, yellows and
greens _ that didn't seem to even exist in the country where it
takes place. ``Saving Private Ryan'' has the narrative shove of a
horror film; Steven Spielberg can't resist the showman's instinct,
even though the characters have been lifted from other World War II
pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Of the pictures nominated for Best Picture, my favorite would
have to be ``Ryan,'' even though the delirious and self-conscious
charms of ``Shakespeare'' are hard to resist. But another movie
that attracted nominal Oscar attention, perhaps because it didn't
fare so well at the box office, deserves more center-stage notice
than it got. That movie is ``Out of Sight,'' Steven Soderbergh's
smart adaptation of Elmore Leonard's crime caper.
</P>
<P>
   In the Best Actor field, ``Sight's'' star, Clooney, gives the
first performance of his career that feels liberated from the TV
box. But he'll undoubtedly get other chances. Tom Hanks is
steady-handed in ``Ryan,'' and his restraint helped as much as his
top-of-the-heap reputation. (He's almost like a champion
prizefighter at this point, a male Meryl Streep who has to go out
of his way to not be nominated.) Ian McKellen's finely etched comic
suffering as director James Whale is a tribute to an actor's love
of work and filigree. Roberto Benigni seems to have been swept
along in the good will for ``Life Is Beautiful.'' And Edward
Norton's fire-eating act in ``American History X'' is the opposite
of the cool tone of the other nominees. (Though it helps that, in
re-editing the picture, he trained a spotlight on his own acting.)
</P>
<P>
   But Nick Nolte _ for his burly, heedless performance as a doomed
abuse victim in the far-too-undernoticed ``Affliction''_ deserves
the Best Actor Oscar for this and a lifetime of work. However,
another actor also gave the turn of his life this year, although in
a deeply flawed movie: I wish that Danny Glover had at least gotten
a nomination for his weary, well-meaning sufferer in the adaptation
of Toni Morrison's ``Beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   I was surprised, too, that ``Beloved'' didn't do better for the
young women who played the daughters: Christine Elise's
clear-headed Denver, and Thandie Newton's risky attempt at the
title apparition were every bit as good as performances by the
other nominees in the Best Supporting Actress category.
(''Beloved'' was set just after the Civil War, which you'd think
might have helped.) And it doesn't matter that the movie wasn't a
box-office champ, because four of the five nominated Supporting
Actress performances were movies that also were underwhelming
moneymakers: Kathy Bates in ``Primary Colors''; ``Little Voice's''
Brenda Blethyn; Rachel Griffiths for ``Hilary and Jackie''; and
Lynn Redgrave's bewildering Col. Klink impression in ``Gods and
Monsters.'' The likely winner, Judi Dench as the imperious
plot-device Queen Elizabeth in ``Shakespeare,'' offered a roaring
good time.
</P>
<P>
   Dench brings to mind a precedent. This must be the only year in
which a Supporting Actress and a Best Actress nominee both got nods
for playing the same character. Cate Blanchett got a Best Actress
berth as a Queen Elizabeth who watches the world hurtle past her.
Meryl Streep (in ``One True Thing,'' her subtlest work in a while)
and Emily Watson (in ``Hilary and Jackie,'' her most commanding
work in a while) probably have their names on the academy's short
list, their nominations just dependent on them actually being in a
movie. And Gwyneth Paltrow (''Shakespeare'') has been raring at the
bit for years, finally getting her shot.
</P>
<P>
   It's too bad she wasn't nominated for her most deeply felt
performance. No, not that great ``Saturday Night Live'' bit where
she mercilessly parodied Sharon Stone's hungry posturing; I mean
for her role as the cold, tortured flirt in ``Great Expectations,''
which was so roundly imagined you expected to see her in the lobby
afterward. Fernanda Montenegro's bullish turn in ``Central
Station'' is better than the sentimentally conceived part written
for her, and were she a bigger star in North America, it's the kind
of thing she could win an Oscar for. But she's not, so she won't.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest surprise _ and for me, disappointment _ came in the
Best Supporting Actor category. Generally, the supporting fields
are the most fun to watch, as they often reward the most blatant
picture-stealing roles. Geoffrey Rush (''Shakespeare''), Billy Bob
Thornton (''A Simple Plan''; he's said to have rewritten his part),
Ed Harris (''The Truman Show''), and Robert Duvall (his shambling,
Columbo-like cakewalk in ``A Civil Action'') do just that. And
James Coburn got the token Hey-He's-Still-Alive-And-Working
nomination for ``Affliction.'' But Bill Murray's canny control in
``Rushmore,'' perhaps the most consistent thing about the movie,
was inexplicably ignored _ a sure thing that was scratched before
the race began. We can only hope that he's got this good a role in
his future _ and that someone will come through with a winner's
speech that will be as much a sassy triumph as his would have been.
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
