<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-SECONDOPINION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SECOND OPINION: HANDICAPPING THE OSCARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Fashion,'' someone once wrote, ``is a despot that the wise
ridicule and obey.'' That about sums up the Oscars: Many people
believe they're ridiculous, but they watch the awards nevertheless,
and participate in the hype by making their own picks. Like these.
</P>
<P>
   BEST PICTURE and DIRECTOR
</P>
<P>
   Will win: ``Saving Private Ryan'' and Steven Spielberg
</P>
<P>
   Should win: ``Saving Private Ryan'' and Steven Spielberg
</P>
<P>
   Don't count out an upset by ``Shakespeare in Love,'' which is
likely to garner steam from all its nominations in technical
categories (it's also a far easier-to-take movie than ``Private
Ryan''). ``Shakespeare'' is terrific, but there's a difference
between good filmmaking and great filmmaking, and from D-Day
sequence to climactic battle, ``Ryan'' is one of the most
masterfully made films of the decade and the best movie of
Spielberg's career.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Nick Nolte, ``Affliction''
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Ian McKellen, ``Gods and Monsters''
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, Nolte's towering-yet-downtrodden portrayal of a born
loser in ``Affliction'' is the performance of his life, and the
academy is likely to honor his veteran status (and make up for his
not winning for 1991's ``Prince of Tides''). But McKellen's crafty,
brittle performance as faded director James Whale in ``Gods and
Monsters'' _ a ``Sunset Boulevard'' for the '90s _ is more subtle
and acutely observed, and was 1998's best performance, period.
</P>
<P>
   BEST ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Gwyneth Paltrow, ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Cate Blanchett, ``Elizabeth''
</P>
<P>
   The Screen Actors Guild Awards, which were filled with
surprises, make the acting categories more interesting than usual
this year. Among the SAG winners, Paltrow is the most likely to
repeat: Her film is better (and more popular) than those of the
other nominees, she has a Hollywood pedigree (parents Blythe Danner
and Bruce Paltrow), and her peers like her _ they really ``like''
her. Blanchett, however, dominated ``Elizabeth,'' taking Queen
Elizabeth I from giddy teen to regal queen. She also kept an overly
busy movie from falling apart.
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTOR
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Ed Harris, ``The Truman Show''
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Geoffrey Rush, ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   This category's up for grabs: For some reason, SAG honored
Robert Duvall for playing a caricature of a lawyer in ``A Civil
Action,'' maybe because the guild was split over the excellence of
the other nominees. Academy voters will probably give this to
Harris as a way of making up for ``The Truman Show's'' not getting
a Best Picture nomination, but Rush's ribald and befuddled
theater-owner in ``Shakespeare'' is the Australian actor's most
entertaining performance to date. (Last year's best supporting
performance, Jeremy Davies' coward in ``Private Ryan,'' was
unaccountably not nominated.)
</P>
<P>
   BEST SUPPORTING ACTRESS
</P>
<P>
   Will win: Lynn Redgrave, ``Gods and Monsters''
</P>
<P>
   Should win: Judi Dench, ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   If Oscar voters waited long enough to cast their ballots, the
disintegration of Redgrave's 32-year marriage (which happened after
the nominations were announced) will earn her the sympathy vote.
Her performance as James Whale's Hungarian housekeeper in ``Gods,''
however, verged perilously close to parody. Dench is in
``Shakespeare'' for six minutes, but you feel her presence as Queen
Elizabeth throughout _ although with the revelation that she had to
wear 5-inch heels to play against the much taller Paltrow, maybe
there should be an award for Best Actress Supporters.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER PICKS
</P>
<P>
   The two absolute locks would appear to be ``Life Is Beautiful''
for Best Foreign Film and ``Shakespeare in Love'' for best original
screenplay. Bet on Scott Frank's ``Out of Sight'' for best adapted
screenplay, although don't count out Bill Condon's script for
``Gods and Monsters'' or Scott B. Smith's sharp adaptation of his
book ``A Simple Plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shakespeare in Love'' will probably ride a wave of wins to
take categories such as Art Direction and Costumes; ``Saving
Private Ryan's'' wave will probably include Sound, Sound Effects
Editing, Dramatic Score, Cinematography and Film Editing. The
selections in the Best Song range from unmemorable to awful, but
Diane Warren's treacly ballad ``I Don't Want to Miss a Thing'' _
file it under ``awful'' _ was the biggest hit, so it will probably
win.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
