</P>
<P>
   TV-EARTHLY (Undated) -- In ``Thelma and Louise,'' Susan Sarandon
was Louise, the more worldly voyager. But in ``Earthy
Possessions,'' Sarandon plays the scatterbrained member of the
T-bird twosome. By Matthew Gilbert.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-RAVENOUS (Undated) _ The trouble with ``Ravenous'' is not
that it's a bad movie. The trouble with ``Ravenous'' is it can't
decide exactly what kind of bad movie it wants to be. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-TRUE (Undated) _ There's a lot of true grit, or at least
convincing grit, in ``True Crime,'' and that's what makes the new
Clint Eastwood movie interesting. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE-FORCES (Undated) _ ``Forces of Nature'' is exactly what
the new romantic comedy starring Sandra Bullock and Ben Affleck is
not. It wants to be a neo-screwball comedy; it at least avoids
formula predictability. By Jay Carr.
</P>
<P>
   MUSIC-ROCK (Undated) _ Ireland's Coors family is poised on the
brink of stardom. By Steve Morse.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-WAR (Undated) _ Mark Bowden's harrowing, authoritative
account of the Somalia debacle, ``Black Hawk Down,'' benefits from
auspicious timing, coming just as Washington debates whether to
intervene in Kosovo. By David Beard.
</P>
