<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6863 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDICARE-$ADV0321-COX     03-19 1417
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-$ADV0321-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDICARE REFORM STILL ALIVE - BARELY
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (a) general news categories
 &HT;    For release Sunday, March 21
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that the blue-ribbon commission named to chart
a course to keep Medicare financially sound into the 21st century
has failed to adopt a plan, what are the chances for reforming the
program in the next few years?
</P>
<P>
   Slim might be an optimistic assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless there is a clear effort by the leaders of the House and
Senate on a bipartisan basis, I think it would be difficult to move
any legislation (to reform Medicare),'' said Martin Corry, federal
affairs director for AARP, the nation's largest association of
older Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds of doing Social Security (reform) in the next two
years are getting longer and longer, and the odds of doing Medicare
are longer still,'' Corry said.
</P>
<P>
   Given their narrow margins of control in both houses of Congress
and a presidential race without an incumbent in 2000, the
Republicans are likely to be cautious about pushing a reform plan
that could be portrayed as detrimental to the popular federal
health program for 39 million elderly and disabled Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Without reform, Medicare's Hospital Insurance Trust Fund --
commonly called Part A -- will be exhausted in 2008. Just a few
years later, the first wave of the 77 million baby boomers will
become eligible for Medicare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't supposed to be this way. Here's what was supposed to
happen:
</P>
<P>
   The blue-ribbon panel of policy experts and key lawmakers was
supposed to have drafted a plan that would keep Medicare sound for
generations. The panel's recommendation was supposed to provide
enough cover for the White House and Congress to implement the
tough choices that might be required, without fear of political
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what happened:
</P>
<P>
   The panel was so deeply divided over policy differences that it
failed to adopt a plan. Both sides ascribed political motives.
Although the only plan considered -- a proposal by the panel's
chairman, Sen. John Breaux (D-La.) -- received 10 out of 17 votes,
it fell one vote short of the 11 required by law for it to make a
recommendation to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what's going to happen:
</P>
<P>
   Breaux will introduce his plan in the Senate Finance Committee,
which has jurisdiction over Medicare. Three of his supporters on
the panel, Sens. Phil Gramm (R-Texas), Bill Frist (R-Tenn.), and
Bob Kerrey (D-Neb.), are also Finance Committee members and said
they will support it.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's vice chairman, Rep. Bill Thomas (R-Calif.),
co-authored the plan with Breaux. Thomas is chairman of the House
Ways and Means health subcommittee, which also has Medicare
jurisdiction. He will introduce the plan in his subcommittee. The
plan also has the support of the full committee chairman, Rep. Bill
Archer (R-Texas).
</P>
<P>
   The Breaux-Thomas plan is given a fairly decent chance of
getting out of either the Finance or the Ways and Means Committee,
or both. Beyond that, its prospects are murky.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' liberal wing in Congress is uniformly skeptical
of the plan and rejoiced in its rejection by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ... proposal would destroy Medicare as we know it,'' said
Rep. Pete Stark (D-Calif.), the ranking Democrat on the Ways and
Means health panel. ``This plan just herds seniors into bare bones,
unattractive HMOs.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the commission had adopted the plan, getting it through
Congress would have been a steep hill to climb, said Gramm. ``I
think you would be deceiving yourself and the public to say that
it's not even steeper,'' in the wake of the panel's failure to
adopt the plan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, President Clinton, who has been loath to present
specific Medicare or Social Security legislation since his major
health reform proposal was summarily rejected in 1994, promised to
offer his own Medicare reform plan in the next month or so.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond politics -- which is a major stumbling block -- there are
deep and profound differences over what the federal government's
role should be in dealing with the health of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Should the government provide the health care coverage or should
it guarantee the coverage? That's the question.
</P>
<P>
   Since its inception in 1965, Medicare has been a government-run
health insurance program in which the government determines what
services will be covered and how much it will pay for them. In
recent years, Medicare also has covered beneficiaries who enrolled
in health maintenance organizations. This year the program is
expanding to include other forms of managed care coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that the program is woefully out of date with
modern health care delivery. It doesn't cover prescription drugs,
it covers only some preventive care and it generally favors
in-patient hospital treatment over alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``And even though Medicare is inadequate in many respects, it is
also going broke,'' Breaux said. (CQ QUOTE)
</P>
<P>
   His plan -- dubbed ``premium support'' would have dramatically
changed the structure of Medicare. Instead of the government
determining coverage and paying for benefits, it would provide
people with money to purchase private insurance -- primarily
through managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Plans would compete for customers based on the services they
provided and the premiums they charged. The government would set
minimum services standards at least equal to those in the current
Medicare program. It would provide premium support by covering the
average cost of the premiums. Beneficiaries who wanted to enroll in
more costly plans would have to pay any excess over the average
cost out of their own pocket.
</P>
<P>
   People who didn't want to go into a managed care plan could
remain in the traditional fee-for-service program, which pays
doctors and hospitals directly.
</P>
<P>
   Critics worried that aggressive managed care plans would enroll
the youngest, healthiest beneficiaries, leaving the rest in the
traditional fee-for-service program.
</P>
<P>
   Because the fee-for-service program would be treated as if it
were a competing insurance plan, critics suggested that its
premiums could be much higher than the average. That would mean
higher out-of-pocket premium costs for those in the fee-for-service
program.
</P>
<P>
   To help the poorest, Breaux's plan would have exempted
beneficiaries with incomes at or below 135 percent of the poverty
level -- about $11,000 for an elderly individual -- from paying
premiums.
</P>
<P>
   His plan also would have extended prescription coverage to the
poorest beneficiaries and given managed care companies an incentive
to provide it to others.
</P>
<P>
   But critics said it did not go far enough because it would not
have provided prescription drug benefits to all Medicare
beneficiaries, at a time when drugs are often replacing surgery as
a medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Breaux would have merged Medicare's two trust funds -- one for
hospital costs, the other to pay doctors and related bills -- into
one fund financed through premiums and general revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of how much money his plan would save varied, but
Breaux said it would have extended the programs' financial
soundness from 2008 to at least 2013 or 2017.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Vladeck, former head of the Health Care Financing
Administration -- the agency that runs Medicare -- was one of the
commission's strongest critics of the Breaux plan.
</P>
<P>
   Vladeck argued that the small amount of savings that might be
produced through competition would not be nearly enough to offset
the fact that twice as many people will be enrolled in the system
in the next few decades. Vladeck said more money would be needed.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has proposed using 15 percent of the projected federal
surplus -- almost $700 billion -- over the next 15 years to shore
up the Medicare program while structural changes are being made.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of Clinton's plan argue that it does nothing to make
Medicare more financially sound because it merely transfers general
revenue to the Medicare trust fund while giving the impression that
it relieves the program's looming insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting surplus dollars into the Part A Trust Fund doesn't fix
Medicare's underlying program,'' Breaux said. ``I've likened it to
putting more gas in an old car -- it still runs like an old car and
doesn't have any of the features of a new car.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
