<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-GUNS-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO TO CHANGE ITS GUN LAWS THIS WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 21)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NUEVO LAREDO, Mexico _ Locked away behind the dingy walls of a
hilltop prison here, a haggard 22-year-old Christopher Colvin looks
like a poster child for Mexican-style gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin, of Monroe, La., has lost about 30 pounds since he was
jailed here in January for crossing the border with a shotgun and a
pistol in his pick-up truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know I was breaking the law,'' said Colvin, as he
stared out from behind a metal screen.
</P>
<P>
   But it remains to be seen how life will change for Colvin and
scores of other Americans as a new and controversial Mexican law
takes effect this week.
</P>
<P>
   The law calls for fines of $800 to $1,000 instead of prison when
a foreign resident is caught with a single shotgun or low-caliber
handgun, but it stiffens the penalties for most handguns and rifles
higher than .22 caliber because they are reserved for use by the
Mexican military.
</P>
<P>
   The law strikes at the heart of a heated debate over border
relations in a region where, on the Texas side of the Rio Grande
firearms are in stock at Wal-Mart and on the Mexican side guns are
kept far from the hands of the people.
</P>
<P>
   Horacio Garza, mayor of Nuevo Laredo, said the law ``is very
strict, but is more favorable to tourists.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison gates won't fly open for some 100 U.S. citizens held in
Mexico on weapons charges, but officials say it could promote
leniency and result in fewer foreigners landing in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface, for people who unwittingly cross to Mexico
with a gun or shell, this may mean a quick fuse for getting out,''
said Jaime Stewart, a Laredo, Texas-based attorney who specializes
in Mexican law.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have disagreed on such basic elements as the exact
date the law will take effect and how it will be implemented.
</P>
<P>
   As a U.S. State Department official, who requested anonymity,
said, ``It may take months to work out exactly what this law
means.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous Americans, like Colvin, have said they were unaware
that possessing firearms or ammunition was illegal here and that
they never intended to break the law.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin, who speaks no Spanish, swears he can not stomach prison
food and survives on cans of tuna fish and sausage sent to him by
his family.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Laredo, Texas, located across the Rio Grande from
here, tries to warn tourists about Mexico's gun laws by passing out
warning handbills to motorists crossing the international bridge to
enter Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Transportation erected signs in several
U.S. border cities warning travelers not to bring guns into Mexico.
A bill mandating such signs is pending before the Texas
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Uriza Lara, the chief federal prosecutor here, said the law
is not retroactive but could still be considered by judges wanting
to impose light sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Among those whose family and colleagues created the greatest
stir over the situation was Tommy Bean, 60, a Vidor, Texas, car
dealer who spent more than seven months behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   Bean was sentenced to five years in prison after he crossed the
border here with a handful of ammunition left in his vehicle from a
gun show, but he was released in October under a U.S.-Mexico
prisoner exchange program.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview from Vidor, Bean said his stint in prison
cost him his business, his retirement fund, and has left him
branded a felon.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was returned to the United States under the treaty, he
said he has had to report once a month to a probation officer and
can no longer dove hunt or vote.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new law, residents of foreign countries, including
Mexicans living in the United States, can pay a fine rather than be
sentenced to prison if they have a clean criminal record and had a
weapon singled out for leniency under the law.
</P>
<P>
   For weapons reserved for use by the military, the penalty has
increased five years for a maximum sentence of 30 years. Those
weapons include handguns above .38 caliber and long-barreled
weapons of calibers.223, 7mm and 7.62 mm; carbines of .30 caliber
or higher as well as automatic and semi-automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Because of street crime, armed insurgencies and an endless wave
of drug-cartel violence, Mexican officials have said they have no
choice but to impose strict gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Mexico's stance on gun control has drawn the ire of
some Texas officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is draconian,'' said state Rep. Ron Wilson, a Houston
Democrat, who is sponsoring a bill mandating that the state erect
and maintain gun warning signs for travelers headed to Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson recalled his own experience dove-hunting in Mexico in the
mid-1980s. He said he was questioned by federal police but allowed
to continue on his way after showing them a government-approved
hunting permit he had secured for use on a local ranch.
</P>
<P>
   As for Colvin, he and a friend, Jason Copes, 19, who is also in
prison here, crossed the international bridge with a 9 mm pistol, a
shotgun, and several shells lying in the bottom of a pair of
fishing waders.
</P>
<P>
   Colvin, a railroad worker, claims he realized he could not bring
a gun into Mexico when he read the warning handed out at Laredo
toll booths, but he said there was no place to turn around on the
bridge.
</P>
<P>
   When he told Mexican customs officials he needed to take his
guns back to the United States, he was arrested on the spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
