<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 16:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6876 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-19 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANIMALS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGS AND LOVERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By VICKI CROKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Choosing a dog is like falling in love.
</P>
<P>
   And whether we're swing dancing at a singles bar or playing
fetch in the park, there are certain looks and personality traits
that make the heart go pitapat.
</P>
<P>
   The characteristics that appeal to us in a dog are often the
exact ones we seek in a mate. Our choice of significant others and
dogs go paw in hand. And it is revealing about how we view both
ourselves and the world around us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, we search for another who makes us complete,'' says
Sarah Wilson, co-author of a number of dog training books,
including the classic ``Good Owners, Great Dogs.'' And what we feel
we are lacking, we seek from our significant others _ qualities
that make us whole. ``I go for smart, protective, and loyal dogs,''
Wilson says, ``and that's what I went for in my man, too!''
</P>
<P>
   If you have both a spouse and a dog right now, count all the
things they have in common (though you shouldn't necessarily share
this information with them). If you have one but not the other, let
one's personality be a guide to what you would seek in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. We love it when people look like their dogs. But
far more often, people look nothing like their dogs. ``The physical
opposite appeals to a lot of people,'' Wilson says.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of odd couples in the world _ some at the altar
(some need to be altered), some in the dog show ring. At any dog
show, the big ladies are often gathered with the tiny toy dogs, or
walking, as Wilson says, ``the nearly two-dimensional greyhounds.''
Short people just adore the giant breeds.
</P>
<P>
   We can't choose our family members, but we sure can pick 'em
when it comes to lovers and dogs.
</P>
<P>
   You love jocks? Get a retriever. Life of the party makes you
swoon? The Jack Russell terrier is your canine. You want athletic
and no-nonsense? Try a bloodhound.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, such an approach could revolutionize the way personals
are written. ``Trystless terrier _ mercurial, compact, smart,
independent, playful _ seeks big, lanky, laid-back blonde wolfhound
for walks in the park, chew-toy tussles, and occasional nips.''
</P>
<P>
   Big and chunky. Tiny and thin. Wired or calm. What we are all
seeking in another is one who can balance us.
</P>
<P>
   We have an internal checklist in the proper selection of a
companion: Are our play levels well-matched? Is she demanding?
Protective? How much does he shed? And best of all _ is this one
trainable?!
</P>
<P>
   But those checklists are different for everyone. ``What makes
one person feel complete drives another up the wall,'' Wilson
points out.
</P>
<P>
   Just ask our mothers, our friends, our dog trainers _ we don't
always choose wisely. Some people are just always getting their
fingers bitten.
</P>
<P>
   And even when we do find the right one, there are drawbacks.
Lots of women, Wilson points out, choose a dog who will make them
feel safe. Wilson says she herself fits this category. Her husband
and her dogs (German shepherds and Australian shepherds) are very
brave and protective of her. ``I pay a price for that preference,
though,'' she says, laughing, ``with occasional bouts of serious
barking. But with positive reinforcement and good socialization,
both groups are coming along nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   As in any romance, appearance counts in the chemistry or sizzle.
Ah! The ruggedness of a Rhodesian ridgeback, the glamour of an
Afghan hound, the piercing blue eyes of a Siberian husky. But in
love or dog shows, there is just no accounting for taste. We have
often experienced the old ``what on earth does she see in him?''
syndrome, whether our friends are trotting out a new beau or a
Boston terrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Through the eyes of love,'' Wilson says, ``anything is
beautiful.'' And we cannot see the flaws that others do in our
spouses or our dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately with any kind of love, it's what's under the skin
that lasts. ``If you're attracted just by the physical alone,''
Wilson says, ``it can be a disaster. Like a mail-order bride, that
gorgeous redheaded chow may be better in the picture than on your
couch.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson has a friend with a Chinese crested _ a nearly hairless
breed. ``At first I thought it looked like a chicken that hasn't
been plucked properly.'' But as Wilson got to know and like the
dog, she came to love the look and feel of it.
</P>
<P>
   Our significant others and our dogs are reflections of our
aesthetic taste. ``That's why a lot of men absolutely hate it when
their wives go out and get toy dogs,'' Wilson says. It seems to
question their masculinity in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, many TV viewers were shocked when a low-slung,
heavy-set breed _ the clumber spaniel _ clobbered an Afghan hound
and took top honors at the prestigious Westminster Kennel Club dog
show. But one aficionado described her breed in the most romantic
terms. What she sees is a thick body made for hugging; the
dreamiest creamy lemon fur; and jowls that just scream sincerity.
In other words, her dreamboat.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like romance. But with dogs, Wilson says, ``it's the
idealized romance of the 18th-century poets. You know, `My love is
like a rosebud.' '' You see your dog running toward you, her hair
blazing with golden light as she gallops joyfully through the ochre
strands of tall grass. ``Your dog will never say . . . `I'm bored
with this relationship.' Or `I hate my life.' Your dog is true
love.''
</P>
<P>
   And truly, dogs do complete something in many of us. They add to
our lives in ways we don't even understand. But with dogs or
dating, we need to be adult enough to distinguish reality from
fantasy and to be happy with it. The perfect dog, as we all know,
was Lassie _ the dog who could pull Timmy from a swollen river and
do it without a lock of that collie fur out of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that perfect scene,'' Wilson says, ``took 15 takes and
four Lassies.'' The same, she says, is true of romance films. We
can't airbrush life the way Hollywood does.
</P>
<P>
   But we really don't need to. ``In a society that is always
sullying intimacy,'' Wilson says, ``dogs glorify it in a completely
innocent way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
