<HEADER>
A6906 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-19 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE TAKES ON NEW YORK CITY FOR HILLARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last Saturday, President Clinton devoted his weekly national
radio address to the issue of police misconduct. On Thursday,
Acting Assistant US Attorney General Bill Lan Lee announced that
the Civil Rights Division of the US Department of Justice would
investigate ``certain patterns and practices'' of the New York City
Police Department. As it is, two US attorneys are already
conducting investigations into the NYPD's Street Crime Unit.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here? Why is the Clinton administration, which
has no jurisdiction over local police and has heretofore exhibited
zero interest in allegations of police brutality in New York City,
suddenly so attentive to possible misconduct by a handful of street
cops in the Bronx?
</P>
<P>
   The official answer is that this flurry of activity is
responsive to the shooting of Amadou Diallo, the unarmed West
African man who was gunned down in a hail of 41 bullets by New York
City police officers. The real story is that Hillary Rodham
Clinton's campaign for the US Senate in New York has unofficially
commenced.
</P>
<P>
   In the words of the president's former chief strategist, Dick
Morris, if you believe all this federal interest in the Diallo case
is coincidental, ``you don't know Bill and you sure don't know
Hillary.'' This is the beginning, Morris says, ``of a carefully
orchestrated effort to use the White House to dirty the mayor so
the First Lady can defeat him for the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's concern about police brutality in New York City
conveniently overlooks reams of statistical data which show that
the NYPD is arguably the most restrained major metropolitan area
police force in the United States. And instances of New York City
police misconduct are declining. As Morris noted in his New York
Post column, ``complaints to the Civilian Complaint Review Board
are down 11 percent over the past two years, even though the size
of the police force has increased. Complaints which relate to the
use of physical force have dropped by almost a quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, by almost any objective measurement, New York City cops
are among the most professional law enforcement officers in the
country. Under Giuliani's leadership, they have waged a war on
crime that has been so persistent and so successful that it has
literally turned the city around.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind about that. The point is that Hillary Clinton is
gearing up to run for the Senate seat being vacated by Daniel
Patrick Moynihan. Toward that end, she and her husband are pulling
every string to ensure that her campaign is successful.
</P>
<P>
   The First Lady's campaign is divided into two parts. Part One
might be called Operation Hillary. Working off a plan prepared for
her by former White House deputy chief of staff (and New Yorker)
Harold Ickes, Mrs. Clinton has been calling up New York State
Democratic Party leaders and entertaining a number of them at the
White House. As well, she has been burning up the phone lines to
major Democratic campaign contributors to get a realistic
assessment of her fund-raising capabilities and needs.
</P>
<P>
   As she works the various constituencies, party leaders have been
busy clearing her path. They have assured Mrs. Clinton that she
will have no primary opposition. That's a huge obstacle removed.
Another obstacle is residence. If you believe the New York
``insiders,'' Mrs. Clinton will solve that problem by moving to
Manhattan before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Part Two of Hillary's campaign deals with the biggest obstacle
in her path: Rudy Giuliani. This effort is being managed by
President Clinton and has all the resources of the federal
government behind it. In his radio address last Saturday, Clinton
announced an $87 million plan to curb police brutality. The federal
investigations into the Diallo shooting will cost at least $2
million and probably more. And this is just the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming months, it is not hard to imagine that the Justice
Department will open an investigation into the New York City prison
system, that the EPA will ``probe'' clean air violations by the
City of New York, and that the Department of Health and Human
Services will ``uncover'' corruption in the New York City hospital
system. Indeed, it seems likely that all but a few branches of the
federal government will be enlisted in the task of destroying
Giuliani's record and reputation as Mayor. And the beauty of it is
that Clinton can commit all these resources at no expense to his
wife's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The tag-team Clinton campaign in New York allows Mrs. Clinton to
separate herself from her husband (by moving to New York) while
continuing to benefit from her marriage to him. She gets the best
of both worlds. He gets to make up to his wife for the
embarrassment he has caused her.
</P>
<P>
   Using the federal government to destroy an opponent is
unethical, of course, but the Clintons have never been especially
keen on ethics. They believe in winning, whatever the cost. Rudy
Giuliani take note.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
