<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOYNIHAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. MOYNIHAN TO UNDERGO BACK SURGERY  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., said Friday
he will undergo surgery later this month aimed at alleviating lower
back pain that has worsened in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan, 71, said he has a condition called spinal stenosis,
which is a narrowing of the passage that surrounds the spinal cord,
a cable of nerve tissue that runs from the base of the brain to the
lower back. The narrowing of the passage puts pressure on the
spinal cord, often causing pain in the lower back and legs.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery will be performed at Johns Hopkins University
Hospital in Baltimore on March 31 and is designed to ease pressure
on the spinal cord. Moynihan said he expects to be in the hospital
for about four days. Congress will be on a two-week recess during
that time.
</P>
<P>
   The senator said he has suffered from lower back pain
intermittently since he fell while on a Navy ship in 1946. But in
January, he added, he began experiencing more severe pain and has
had a difficult time walking. Since then Moynihan has been given
cortisone shots to help alleviate the pain.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said his back pain had nothing to do with his decision
to retire from the Senate when his term ends in 2000. He was first
elected to the Senate in 1976 and announced his retirement last
November.
</P>
<P>
   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and New York Mayor Rudolph
Guiliani, a Republican, are considering running for Moynihan's
seat.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan said he has talked to Clinton about the possibility of
her running but added that he has no inkling of whether she will
decide to enter the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan is the top Democrat on the powerful Senate Finance
Committee, where he has shaped health care, tax and Social Security
policies during the 22 years he has served on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   His Senate colleagues regard him as one of the body's leading
scholars. Moynihan once taught economics, sociology and urban
studies at Harvard. He worked in the Labor Department in the John
Kennedy and Lyndon Johnson administrations in the 1960s. President
Richard Nixon appointed him ambassador to India and later the
United Nations, where he also served under President Gerald Ford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
