</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
Page 1, Saturday, March 20. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken; phone: (888) 346-9867; mail:
hwarnken(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ International monitors were ordered
Friday to pull out of Kosovo, and Western embassies ordered their
nonessential staff to leave Yugoslavia after peace talks here
collapsed and NATO renewed threats to bomb unless President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia accepts a peace plan for Kosovo.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA-MANDELA (United Nations) _ Nelson Mandela, in Libya, says
the Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi has promised in a letter to the
United Nations to hand over the suspects accused of the bombing
over Lockerbie, Scotland, by April 6. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-BOMB (Moscow) _ In one of the most devastating single
acts of violence in Russsia's volatile North Caucasus region, a
powerful bomb ripped through the central pavilion at a downtown
market in the city of Vladikavkaz today, killing 58 people and
wounding more than 100. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   BALLOONISTS (Geneva) _ The Breitling Orbiter 3 balloon was less
than one day's flying time Friday night from achieving what had
thwarted balloonists for two centuries: a nonstop voyage around the
world. By Malcolm W. Browne.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-EDUCATION (Paris) _ Foreign Journal: Trying to change the
education system in a country that fears any sort of change is a
thankless job, says Claude Allegre, the feisty French minister of
education, with some exasperation. Since his old friend Lionel
Jospin, the prime minister, picked Allegre, 62, to run the vast
French education bureaucracy, he has become one of the most
vilified politicians in France. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ News from President Clinton's news
conference Friday afternoon. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MONEY (Washington) _ President Clinton's impeachment
appears to have a silver lining _ or at least a green one. Campaign
donations to Democratic coffers have soared, with much of the
giving inspired by the president himself as he crisscrosses the
country, blaming Republicans for trying to bring him down and
thanking his supporters for sticking by him. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLERS (Orlando, Fla.) _ Jim Larson lost two women he
loved to random killers. First it was his sister, Sonja Larson. She
and a roommate were stabbed to death in 1990 by Danny Rolling, a
serial killer who said demons spoke to him. Then in 1997, Larson's
wife, Carla, was abducted from a supermarket parking lot by a man
on vacation at Disney World. Later this month his wife's killer,
John Huggins, will join Rolling on Florida's death row. By Rick
Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-WOMEN (Long Barn, Calif.) _ The car and two of the
bodies of the three women who have been missing for more than a
month from Yosemite National Park have been found. By Evelyn
Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   AFFIRMATIVE-ACTION (Los Angeles) _ After watching black and
Hispanic enrollment tumble with the end of affirmative action,
University of California regents are expected Friday to officially
retool admissions, guaranteeing a spot for students in the top 4
percent of their high school classes. The switch, heavily promoted
by Gov. Gray Davis, will bring in more rural and poor students, and
supporters hope it will serve as a morale booster for schools that
traditionally send few students to the university. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GUCCI-LVMH (Rome) _ A battle for control of Gucci Group NV
erupted Friday, when a wealthy French takeover investor agreed to
pay $3 billion for a 40 percent stake in the famed Italian fashion
house and rescue it from a hostile takeover bid by the French
luxury goods maker LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis Vuitton. By John
Tagliabue.
</P>
