<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6933 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATAKI-NH-HNS &LR;      03-19 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATAKI-NH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATAKI, ACTING LIKE A CANDIDATE, VISITS KEY PRIMARY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ New York Gov. George Pataki has added his
name to the long list of political luminaries who have trooped
through New Hampshire on their quest for national attention.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the others, the Republican governor didn't specifically
say his mission is to capture a job in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But like the host of winners and losers who have historically
stumped in Manchester, from George McGovern and Richard Nixon to
Lenora B. Fulani and Pat Paulsen, Pataki allowed that he has the
credentials to lead the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you think about,'' said Pataki, 53, adding that
his experience as New York's governor shows he has the goods to be
a presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ``But my focus is on the positive message for my party and the
future of America,'' Pataki said Thursday during a busy night of
fund-raising, speaking and getting acquainted with GOP insiders who
could help him should he decide to run for president or vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   His key appointment for the visit, as keynote speaker at the
annual Lincoln Day Dinner of the city GOP Committee, drew 200
guests who applauded politely as the recently re-elected governor
drew from last fall's campaign speeches to recite his
accomplishments. He talked about drastically reduced welfare rolls,
safer streets, $19 billion in tax cuts, 400,000 new private-sector
jobs and a $1.8 billion budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, he borrowed from addresses he delivered during a tour of
Republican gatherings in Chicago, Missouri and Florida in February,
when he had referred to Ronald Reagan as the positive force of the
20th century and how a similar leader is needed to mark the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our policies of belief in freedom, belief in liberty and the
individual are right not just for the Republican Party,'' he said.
``They unite us. ... Those policies will allow us to look to 2000
... with confidence we can win those elections.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's visit included stops for money and publicity.
Shortly after arriving here aboard the Gulfstream of New York Mets
co-owner Fred Wilpon, Pataki joined a dozen state Republican
big-wigs who tossed $50,000 into the coffers of his political
action committee, the 21st Century Freedom PAC.
</P>
<P>
   He also booked interviews on radio and television to spread his
``positive message'' about the success of Republican governors and
conservative policies. Local broadcasts spread to parts of three
states and a taping for the CNBC cable network got the governor
about 15 minutes before a national audience.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pataki needs the exposure. Even in the politically savvy city of
Manchester, residents can't seem to place him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him. He's the mayor of New York,'' said one of the
three clerks at the Holiday Inn where the governor checked in. Two
other clerks at the front desk of the hotel said they simply didn't
know who he was. One gushed that two other would-be Republican
presidential nominees, Pat Buchanan and Steve Forbes, had just
stayed the night.
</P>
<P>
   Around the New England city, it was easy to find others who
didn't know the governor. At the Merrimack Restaurant, near the
Holiday Inn, co-owner Maria Saitas said many presidential hopefuls
have stopped in for meals over the years, including Vice President
Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know him,'' she said of New York's governor. ``Patakus. He's
Greek. I'm Greek.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who are quite familiar with the governor, such as the
executive board of the state GOP and other Republican loyalists,
spoke highly of the governor, who happens to be of Hungarian
descent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a rising star on the national scene,'' said Stephen
Duprey, chairman of the state Republican Party, who noted that
Pataki comes from a big state with generous political donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the first one to say he's pro-choice,'' said Barbara
Russell, assistant chair of the state GOP committee, referring to
Pataki's position on abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki refused to be pulled into a debate on abortion, despite
published reports in the conservative Manchester Union Leader
newspaper in which Buchanan challenged the governor to enter the
race and debate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he wanted to concentrate on the issues that unify
the Republican Party, not divide it. All the while, he steered away
from directly answering whether he would enter a primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's about a person and I certainly don't think
it's about me,'' he said. ``It's about being in a position where
the policies and ideas that I believe in, and I believe the
Republican Party believes in, will win in 2000 _ and after we win
we'll be able to govern successfully.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
