<HEADER>
A6935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV21-     03-19 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGTIME TREES PUT ON A SHORT, SWEET SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 21)  
 (af)  
 By CASS PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I had traveled in the South, but never during the time when
magnolias were blooming, so I was of a distinctly mature age when I
saw my first magnolia blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   I was living a little farther north, in the nation's capital,
and trudging off to some business, when I spotted the trees in one
of those tiny greenswards that Washingtonians call vest-pocket
parks. They are useless as parks, being crammed into the spaces
left over when streets run out of kilter and intersect at odd
angles, but some wisdom has led the city's landscapers to turn them
into little seasonal showplaces to inspire tourists and
brown-bagging civil servants.
</P>
<P>
   I had passed those trees dozens of times without giving them a
glance. They weren't very imposing and weren't, to a Midwestern eye
trained to elms, horse chestnuts and cottonwoods, all that
attractive. But on this grayish day in late March they were covered
with large dusty-pink blossoms, easily 6 inches across, like wine
goblets strewn among the skeletal branches.
</P>
<P>
   A friend from Virginia called them tulip magnolias, with a
derisive sniff. ``Not real magnolias,'' she said. ``They don't have
any scent.''
</P>
<P>
   One never misses experiences one never had, I suppose, and I was
more than willing to forgive these trees their lack of fragrance
for their ability to produce such impressive blossoms in northerly
climates. When I further identified the trees as a cultivar of
Magnolia soulangeana, a hybrid developed from crosses between more
sweetly scented species, I bought one to plant in my yard.
</P>
<P>
   As a city devoted to spring (possibly because it is unbearable
in the summer), Washington has more than the usual complement of
spring-flowering trees and shrubs. There are the famous Japanese
cherry trees, of course, surrounding the Tidal Basin in pink foam
and scattered everywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   There are braces of Bradford pears nestled into square holes in
the pavement outside the entrances of scores of office buildings,
and every conceivable variety of crab apple and crape myrtle
adorning lawns from Foggy Bottom to the farthest suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The city of Takoma Park, just outside the District of Columbia's
northwest border, calls itself Azalea City for the riotous display
that has, in some yards, entirely displaced the lawn.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is well and good, and it's worth a springtime
sojourn just to bask in the ambiance of dogwoods and redbuds and
flowering peaches and plums. But when it's over, it's over.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of May, the trees are just trees again. A dogwood
may be more attractive when it's out of bloom than, say, a
forsythia, but it's still unremittingly green.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of cherry blossoms, the brevity of the display is
the whole point. In Japan, they are a symbol of fleeting beauty and
courage, because the flowers last but a week and will open, once
bud formation is triggered by warm weather, even in the teeth of a
late-winter blizzard. Of course, in that case, their grand week
will be severely curtailed.
</P>
<P>
   The same kind of transient glory applies to spring-flowering
trees in general. Barely a month passes from the time the first
cherry blossom opens to the time the last dogwood petal flutters to
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, I especially admire those trees that do not
bloom in the early spring: witch hazel, for example, which displays
its yellow flowers in winter, proving itself up to the cherry
blossom's standard in courage, or golden-rain tree, which blooms in
summer with drooping clusters of yellow blossoms.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese pagoda tree blooms in late summer, with purple-tinged
flowers followed by a crop of bean-like fruits. Washington is well
endowed with this tree, sometimes called Chinese scholar tree, but
no one has thought to have a festival for it.
</P>
<P>
   I miss the catalpa trees that used to grace my front yard. Alas,
they grew old and brittle and had to be removed, but their pale
yellow flower clusters, borne upright like candelabra, were
beautiful in early summer, long after the spring blossoms were
gone.
</P>
<P>
   Summer-blooming trees tend to be less showy than spring
bloomers, because the flowers appear when the tree is already
leafed out. In most cases, you have to engage in the activity of
looking at the flowers _ they don't just come out and smack you in
the face.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are a few summer-flowering trees that manage
something close to spring-flowering theatrics. Mimosa, or silk tree
(Albizia julibrissin), is one example. It has eye-catching
plume-like pink flowers at the ends of the branches in summer.
</P>
<P>
   Those who like the looks of mimosa, but don't have the space for
a 45-foot tree, might consider instead the smoke tree (Cotinus
coggygria). It's more of a shrub than a tree, rarely getting over
15 feet in height, and has fuzzy purplish flower spikes in early
summer, like grape cotton candy.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting, too, are those blooming trees that are not of the
lawn-decoration variety. A horse chestnut (native species are
called buckeyes) would be a poor choice for the average suburban
lot, since it will reach 100 feet, but its early-summer blooms are
an impressive white with yellow blotches, borne in footlong
clusters.
</P>
<P>
   If there's a horse chestnut planted in one of Washington's
vest-pocket parks (it would have to be a large one), it was not a
park that I often walked by. If I had, I certainly would have taken
notice of it. I came late to the admiration of magnolias, but I've
loved horse chestnuts all my life.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
