<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLOMBIA-QUAKE-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMOTIONAL AFTERSHOCKS: QUAKE TAKES TOLL ON COLOMBIANS' MENTAL
HEALTH 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, March 21) 
(Eds.: Tilde needed over n in Patino) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARMENIA, Colombia _ The couch in the cramped office of
psychiatrist Roberto Estefan is getting an especially heavy
workout.
</P>
<P>
   By day, Estefan treats a stream of patients suffering from panic
attacks, insomnia and depression provoked by a Jan. 25 earthquake
that devastated this city in western Colombia and killed more than
1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   At night, the patients' couch serves as the doctor's bed,
because Estefan's apartment building collapsed in the quake.
</P>
<P>
   Recovery efforts have focused on clearing the debris and
providing emergency food and shelter. But Estefan and other
psychiatrists are treating victims for the mental aftershocks.
</P>
<P>
   The magnitude 6 earthquake _ the worst to strike Colombia this
century _ was an emotional wringer.
</P>
<P>
   In the first three weeks after the temblor, Estefan and his team
at the mental health unit of San Juan de Dios Hospital in Armenia
treated 450 walk-in patients _ three times the norm.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the hospital reported three suicide attempts
daily. Working door-to-door in a quake-ravaged barrio, one
psychiatrist counseled 65 people in 12 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wherever you go, people are asking for help,'' Estefan said.
``I go out for a hamburger, and most of the people who say hello
seize the moment to tell me about their insomnia and their
sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   A quick tour of Armenia helps explain why.
</P>
<P>
   Half of the city's buildings were shattered. Thousands of
homeless and jobless have crowded into refugee camps, where
tensions run high. Virtually everyone has lost family members or
friends. In just 20 seconds, a way of life was destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Religious sects have added to the turmoil by portraying the
quake as the wrath of God or a prelude to doomsday, Estefan said.
Geologists have registered 3,000 aftershocks, and people fear
another killer earthquake may be looming.
</P>
<P>
   The slightest movement ``leaves you traumatized,'' said Gerardo
Aguirre, a carpenter whose house collapsed. ``It seems like the
world is going to come to an end.''
</P>
<P>
   Luz Stella Toro, a lawyer who volunteered to help construct a
refugee camp called ``January 25,'' said that some people who have
jobs don't even bother going to work, because they believe they
will die soon.
</P>
<P>
   The earthquake was followed by an outbreak of looting and
burglaries by refugees and roving gangs that bankrupted hundreds of
merchants and sowed panic in many neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a permanent fear of a new catastrophe _ or more
looting,'' said Diego Arbelaez, director of Ser Humano, a private
group that counsels dying patients but now focuses on earthquake
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Even medical care-givers are in mourning. Some are too busy
rebuilding homes or helping their families to report to work.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Raul Ossa, a doctor at San Juan de Dios Hospital, said his
father is upstairs in one of the wards, suffering from severe
depression after the death of his wife in the earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some cracked walls, the hospital is structurally sound.
Some health workers, however, refuse to make rounds on the upper
floors, because they fear the building will collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Children are the most vulnerable, because they don't understand
what happened, Arbelaez said. Many have trouble sleeping, refuse to
go to school or won't let their parents out of their sight.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Patino, an official with the National Federation of
Coffee Growers, said his two boys refuse to enter the family's
apartment by themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any sound at night, everyone runs out to the
patio,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Arbelaez said that about 200 psychiatrists and psychologists are
working in Armenia and surrounding towns. He added, however, that
2,000 are needed. Hospitals are running out of sedatives and
anti-depressants.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers have assumed part of the burden. Cuba has dispatched
a team of psychiatrists to Colombia, and the Association of
American Psychiatrists plans to lead seminars for mental health
workers in the earthquake zone.
</P>
<P>
   At the ``January 25'' shantytown, Richard Rusi, a volunteer
psychologist from Bogota, focuses on children. Because fault lines
run through the region, the youngsters may have to deal with
tremors for the rest of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   One woman told Rusi that her 4-year-old daughter no longer
speaks and began wetting her pants and sucking her thumb after the
earthquake. As a first step, Rusi told her to stop spanking the
child for such acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give them back their confidence,'' Rusi said.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-year-old Joan Espinosa can barely pronounce the word
``psychologist,'' but he said that Rusi's counseling has made him
feel braver.
</P>
<P>
   At a park, workers for UNICEF and Save The Children use boiled
eggs and basketballs to demonstrate the Earth's composition. They
stage puppet shows about earthquakes to explain that it is a
natural phenomenon caused by the shifting of the Earth's plates.
</P>
<P>
   Others try to raise people's spirits in writing. A roving poet
has scrawled verses on some of the city's ruins. Banners across
Armenia's main streets provide uplifting messages, such as:
``Houses may fall, but not our dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that most people in Armenia have probably suffered
some degree of post-traumatic stress syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   According to a study on the quake's impact by the mental health
unit of Armenia's San Jose clinic, an earthquake can cause as much
psychological trauma as torture, kidnapping, rape, military combat
or grave car accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Depression and panic are normal responses. At times, Estefan
said he has been unable to contain his own sorrow and has burst out
crying.
</P>
<P>
   But if such symptoms last longer than a few months, Estefan
recommends therapy to avoid long-term problems. He fears that if
too many distraught people go untreated, the rates of crime,
alcoholism and suicide could increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prognosis is good,'' Estefan said. ``There is a huge
possibility to recover. But the earlier they come in, the better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
