<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7034 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KILROY-SPRING-BREAK-$     03-19 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILROY-SPRING-BREAK-$ADV21-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS STILL UNEASY AT 10TH ANNIVERSARY OF SON'S CULT KILLING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, March 21) 
 
By RUTH RENDON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA FE, Texas _ The sensation isn't as strong as it once was,
but this is still a bad time of year for Helen and Jim Kilroy.
</P>
<P>
   Each March, as the winter chill fades, they know that thousands
of high-school and college students are welcoming a break from
classes and heading for Texas beaches or the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, their son, Mark James Kilroy, was among those who
chose South Padre Island in South Texas as a spring break
destination. It started as a typical outing for the 21-year-old
student from the University of Texas at Austin, but it ended in
death after he was abducted off the streets of Matamoros, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a month later, his mutilated body was among 13 discovered
at a ranch outside Matamoros. The killers later were identified as
a gang of occult-obsessed drug traffickers who believed that human
sacrifices would protect them.
</P>
<P>
   Although their son's murderers have been brought to justice, the
Kilroys can't help saying a little prayer for the young people who
flock to the border at this time of year for a week of partying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as intense as it once was,'' Helen Kilroy, 54, said
from the couple's home in the Galveston County town of Santa Fe.
Still, she said, ``It's a bad occasion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a common sight when we see the kids going to the
Matamoros area,'' she said. ``You just wonder if everything has
been worked out or if problems still exist.''
</P>
<P>
   Before her son's disappearance, she said, Mexican and U.S. law
enforcement authorities rarely worked together. Now, she said,
young people on spring break are afforded at least some police
protection if they cross the border.
</P>
<P>
   George Gavito, a former Cameron County sheriff's lieutenant who
worked with the Kilroys in the search for their son, said things
have changed for U.S. spring breakers in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have more security and officers,'' said Gavito, who now
does security work for U.S. companies doing business in Mexico.
``They are aware of what happened 10 years ago and they keep it in
mind. For that reason, they keep a closer eye on the kids. They
kind of baby them a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kilroy disappeared March 14, 1989, while partying in
Matamoros. His mutilated body and those of 12 others were
discovered April 11, buried at Rancho Santa Elena outside
Matamoros.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities described a bloodstained shack where the bodies were
found as a ``human slaughterhouse.'' Two other victims of the same
drug ring were found at a nearby communal farm.
</P>
<P>
   The smugglers had performed human sacrifices, authorities said,
in the belief that they would provide magical protection from
police and rival drug organizations.
</P>
<P>
   The search for the killers ended May 6 that year in a shootout
between the cult members and Mexico City police. Five drug-ring
members had spent weeks eluding police after the mutilated corpses
were found.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Maria Aldrete Villareal, 34, the cult's reputed
``godmother,'' was sentenced in May 1994 to 62 years in prison for
the ritual slayings. Four other cult members received 67-year
sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Another gang member, Alvaro Dario de Leon Valdes, was sentenced
to 30 years for the slaying of gang leader Adolfo de Jesus
Constanzo.
</P>
<P>
   Constanzo reportedly had ordered de Leon to shoot him and his
bodyguard as police surrounded their Mexico City hideout.
Prosecutors said gang members agreed to kill each other if
apprehended by police, ``because their satanic religion prohibited
suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to choosing random victims, authorities said
Constanzo's gang killed and mutilated drug-trafficking rivals and
witnesses to their criminal activity. U.S. officials estimated that
Constanzo smuggled 2,000 pounds of marijuana per week into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Gavito said the Kilroys' strong determination to find their son
helped in stopping the cult. He said he remembers Mark's friends
going to his office in Brownsville, Texas, to report his
disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once Mr. Kilroy showed up, he was there every day for the next
30 days. He wouldn't leave,'' Gavito said. ``In fact, it got to the
point that he was helping the dispatcher answer the phone. He was
at the sheriff's office early in the morning with biscuits and
coffee. It was real hard to tell him that we had other cases and we
needed to move on. I think that's what kept us all going. We kept
the heat on the Mexican authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Kilroys had not been as persistent, Gavito said, he
suspects the cultists would have continued killing for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the sacrifice of Mark Kilroy helped in stopping this
cult,'' he said. ``The cult would have grown. They would have
killed probably 100 more people, if they ever were to be found out.
Since they were dealing in drugs, that means they were paying
bribes to some Mexican officials and they were protected. If it had
not been for Mark, it would have continued.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kilroys are active parishioners at Our Lady of Lourdes
Catholic Church in Hitchcock, near Santa Fe. The family observes
the anniversary of Mark's death by dedicating a Mass to him at the
church.
</P>
<P>
   Their other son, Keith, lives and works in the San Diego,
Calif., area.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, the Kilroys set up the Mark Kilroy Foundation to help
fight drug trafficking and help drug users kick the habit.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the seed money for the foundation came from the proceeds
of the book ``Sacrifice: The Drug Cult Murder of Mark Kilroy at
Matamoros,'' written by Jim Kilroy, 55, a chemical engineer, and
San Antonio writer Bob Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation provided money to start a residential treatment
center for men in Texas City and for women in Kemah.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation also sponsors SAFE _ substance abuse free
environment _ programs in the Hitchcock and Santa Fe school
districts, said Helen Kilroy, who volunteers full time with the
foundation.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation's fourth annual gourmet dinner, dance and auction
drew about 700 people recently and raised $20,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing everything on our own,'' she said. ``Many
people in different organizations have joined together to have all
this happen. We would hate to have anyone get the impression that
we're doing it all.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those is Gavito, who befriended the Kilroys and
communicates with them weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the annual fund-raiser, the foundation raises money
through the sale of Jim Kilroy's book, which is available for
$16.08. The book, a personal account of what the family went
through in the time surrounding Mark's disappearance and the
discovery of his body, is available by contacting the foundation at
P.O. Box 777, Santa Fe, Texas 77517.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
