<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-NITEOUT-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NIGHT OUT WITH BRETT RATNER SNATCHING OSCARS' CANDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 21) 
 (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CHRISTIAN BERTHELSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One car, or two? That's the kind of question that
gets thrown around the week before the Oscars, as nominees,
hotshots, never-beens and sharks zip around town, being seen and
scarfing up whatever goodies studios throw out.
</P>
<P>
   Take Brett Ratner, 28, the hotshot director of ``Rush Hour''
with Jackie Chan, billed as ``the fastest hands in the East'' and
Chris Tucker, ``the biggest mouth in the West'' (no nominations).
Ratner gathered his posse _ Chris Penn, who also appeared in ``Rush
Hour,'' and Joey Krutel, a childhood friend from Miami _ on
Thursday night to attend a party at the Atlantic restaurant. The
party was for New Line, the studio that released ``Rush Hour,'' and
it was being given by Mike DeLuca, the company's president.
</P>
<P>
   Juggling cell phones, Ratner first made sure that Penn would
meet him at the right house _ not his old one, but the new one high
in the Hollywood Hills with the view of the city flats below. Then
he said good night to his fiancee, Rebecca Gayheart, the actress,
as he and his boys headed out into the night.
</P>
<P>
   They decided: one car, Ratner's huge black Range Rover. On the
way, Ratner fielded a few more calls. (Someone was pitching him a
script, a cross between ``Goodfellas'' and ``Godfather II.'')
</P>
<P>
   Penn compared Ratner to a kid in the candy store who suddenly
owned the store. Why?
</P>
<P>
   Because Ratner's $35 million movie, released last year, took in
$141 million at American box offices for New Line. In this
whirlwind week of parties leading up to the Academy Awards, he was
New Line's man of the hour. DeLuca greeted Ratner as effusively as
if he were in the running alongside Steven Spielberg and Roberto
Benigni.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner set up court at a rear table, and a procession began as
people came to greet him: the actresses China Chow and Tara Reid,
and a handful of movie executives. ``This is ground zero Hollywood
right here,'' said Rick Hess, the head of Phoenix Pictures, which
helped produce ``The Thin Red Line.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratner picked at spring rolls and ordered a Coke and a bottle of
water. Penn handed him a phone, to talk to Don ``The Dragon''
Wilson, a kickboxing star. ``Did you know Bruce Lee,'' Ratner
asked, then inquired whether he could beat Lee up. Talk turned to
the best Oscar parties to attend. The Vanity Fair party was the
clear choice. ``Ending the night at the Miramax party is best,''
said Ratner, because lox and hot eggs and potatoes are served.
</P>
<P>
   Later, he greeted Madonna, Marisa Tomei, Tia Carrere, Jennifer
Lopez and Farrah Fawcett. Only Ms. Tomei had ever won an Oscar
(best supporting actress in 1993 for ``My Cousin Vinny''), but
Ratner had had Ms. Fawcett's poster on his wall as a teen-ager, and
that counts for something. Catherine Zeta-Jones, Chris Rock and
Sean ``Puffy'' Combs were on hand, too, as was Hugh Hefner, in an
open-collared shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Ratner circled the club, with a stop (quickly aborted) to try
out a few dance steps with a couple of girls. Just before midnight,
Penn said he was 34 and wanted to go home. There were meetings to
go to the next day, and more parties to attend in the week. And
Hollywood is an early-to-bed town.
</P>
</TEXT>
