<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-FERMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LABEL GIVES A HOME TO SOUL SURVIVORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not often does one record label save an entire genre of music.
</P>
<P>
   Define? Establish? Yes. Sun and Stax down in Memphis, Chess in
Chicago, Motown in Detroit _ all formed our perception of a certain
era or a certain sound, and gave us classic performers such as
Elvis Presley, Muddy Waters, Marvin Gaye or Otis Redding.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but to most listeners, Jackson, Miss.'s Malaco Records
doesn't often get mentioned alongside these other classic labels.
Stop 10 guys wearing Stevie Ray T-shirts and ask them what Malaco
is, or who is on it, and my bet is at least eight of them won't
have a clue.
</P>
<P>
   Their loss. In its 30 years _ profiled by a just-released six-CD
box, ``The Last Soul Company'' _ Malaco has released scads of
classic blues and soul recordings. Among them are King Floyd's
``Groove Me,'' Bobby ``Blue'' Bland's ``Get Your Money Where You
Spend Your Time,'' Z.Z. Hill's ``Someone Else Is Steppin' In'' and
Little Milton's ``The Blues Is Alright.''
</P>
<P>
   But along the way, Malaco actually ``saved'' soul music _ from
extinction and from itself.
</P>
<P>
   This was the early '80s, a horrible time for urban music. The
vapid flashiness of disco and its numbing thump had rendered
old-style soul of the sort Redding and Bland played all but
obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   Too many white listeners who had enjoyed classic '60s soul now
wrongly lumped disco and soul together, and the youth wave of
funk/disco acts swept up urban listeners.
</P>
<P>
   How, really, could a balladeer like Bland compete with the
gaudiness of a K.C. &AMP; the Sunshine Band, or the spectacle of
Parliament-Funkadelic? Simply put, he couldn't, and many '60s soul
stars found themselves dropped from major labels and/or unable to
get airplay.
</P>
<P>
   Malaco's Tommy Couch, a former University of Mississippi frat
boy and a serious music fan, stepped up. Before this, Malaco had
been a fairly successful regional label, doing soul, funk, and
old-style blues.
</P>
<P>
   From 1980 on, though, Malaco consciously gave soul singers a
home, nurtured them, promoted them. Couch saw that the deep soul
market was going untapped by major labels, and Malaco found its
niche _ initially with a journeyman Texas singer named Z.Z. Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Hill had recorded for a number of small labels with middling
success, but when the singles ``Down Home Blues'' and ``Cheating in
the Next Room'' hit in 1981 and 1982, it reopened the floodgates
for classic-sounding soul. Malaco followed up with strong singles
and LPs by Bland, Milton, Latimore, and Denise LaSalle, and along
the way a large Southern audience rediscovered the music it had
always loved.
</P>
<P>
   Of all these artists, Dallasite Johnnie Taylor has reaped the
most benefits. A former Stax artist, he ran through the door Hill
opened and has had hit after hit ever since: His 1996 CD, ``Good
Love!,'' sold more than half a million copies and stayed atop the
blues charts for months.
</P>
<P>
   Considering his huge catalog of hits in the '60s, and his '70s
smash, ``Disco Lady,'' Taylor might have done OK if not for Malaco.
But dozens of other acts wouldn't have _ and soul itself might well
have become ghettoized into the margins of American music. Malaco
has made sure that hasn't happened, and ``The Last Soul Company''
is a fine and thoroughly enjoyable testimony to its legacy _ so
far.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
