r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VAUGHAN-CDS-TEX     03-19 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAUGHAN-CDS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW VAUGHAN CDS ADD LITTLE TO HIS LEGEND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE FERMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nine years after his death, the shadow of Stevie Ray Vaughan
still looms enormously large over the blues.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the most recent issue of Guitar World magazine.
Kenny Wayne Shepherd, a SRV wannabe right down to the weathered
Fender Stratocaster, was named by readers as the best blues
guitarist, beating out Eric Clapton and B.B. King.
</P>
<P>
   This says far more about Vaughan than Shepherd, and what it says
is that we still hunger for Vaughan's style and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   Epic Records obviously understands this: On Tuesday, Vaughan's
label is reissuing all four of the solo studio records he cut
during his lifetime. ``Texas Flood,'' ``Couldn't Stand the
Weather,'' ``Soul to Soul'' and his finest effort, ``In Step,''
arrive in stores remastered and with bonus studio and live tracks.
</P>
<P>
   A second single-disc best-of, ``The Real Deal: Greatest Hits
Vol. 2,'' also will be released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The big question is, is it worth buying all four CDs again, just
for a handful of bonus tracks and some brief comments by Vaughan on
music?
</P>
<P>
   Not in this case _ and I say that as a huge fan who used to see
Stevie in small bars in 1981 and 1982, before he signed to Epic and
released his debut, ``Texas Flood,'' in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   The remastering has beefed up the sound on all four CDs at least
a little, which is nice, if not necessary for enjoyment of the
music. It's not as though the original LPs or the first CD versions
sounded bad or horribly thin; they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, 11 of the 14 bonus musical tracks are just different
versions of songs that were on the original CDs, or 1991's ``The
Sky Is Crying.'' In some cases, such as the poignant ``Life Without
You'' that concludes ``In Step,'' the live version is intense
enough to qualify as a fantastic addition to Vaughan's recorded
legacy. Another worthy _ and truly new _ addition is a funky take
on Hound Dog Taylor's ``Give Me Back My Wig,'' which is on
``Couldn't Stand the Weather.''
</P>
<P>
   But considering the paucity of truly ``new'' songs here, the
reissue series makes me believe that Epic is milking SRV's legacy
without really adding a whole lot to it.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, too, that all of these reissues come after two live
CDs, ``In the Beginning'' (poor) and ``Live at Carnegie Hall''
(good), both of which featured songs not on Vaughan's studio
recordings.
</P>
<P>
   It seems, by now, that Epic is simply parceling out piecemeal
the Vaughan stuff it has in the can, in dribs and drabs, with
little rhyme or reason. If we're going to add ``new'' songs to his
CDs, they should be previously unreleased stuff like ``Wig'' _ and
``Slip Slidin' Slim,'' which is on ``Soul to Soul.'' Another option
would be a two-CD set of live jams with guys like Albert King and
Jeff Beck, which are readily available on bootlegs. What fan
wouldn't love to have that stuff?
</P>
<P>
   Also problematic is the 16-cut ``Deal.'' The songs are fairly
well-chosen, but it's a mystery why there is only one tune _
``Telephone Song'' _ from 1990's ``Family Style,'' Stevie's
collaboration with older brother Jimmie. I guess this just sets us
up for the inevitable third best-of, although at this point it's
hard to imagine what will go on it. I'm sure Epic will find, well,
something.
</P>
<P>
   What would have been nice, in the first few years after
Vaughan's death, would have been a truly complete boxed set, or
perhaps a three-CD set of previously unreleased material such as
``Wig'' and Freddie King's ``Hide Away.'' It's far too late for
that, though, even though Vaughan clearly deserves the same sort of
multidisc treatment paid to artists like Clapton and King.
</P>
<P>
   And considering that Vaughan didn't put out nearly as much
material as either of those artists have, a comprehensive box would
have been far easier to assemble. Ideally, it would have had all
the good stuff, plus some unreleased tracks.
</P>
<P>
   But whether one buys the reissues and/or ``Deal,'' or not, I
would avoid ``Sugar Coated Love,'' a CD with Lou Ann Barton singing
lead and, we're told, Stevie on 10 of the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Cut in 1977 in Austin and released in January, ``Love'' delivers
far less than the sort of white-hot Barton-plus-Vaughan summit
meeting it hints at. The sound is horrible, the recording
information is scant and Vaughan's guitar work isn't unusual enough
to make it stand out. He was, at this point, a sideman, playing
standard blues-band songs.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a true obsessive and just have to have every SRV lick
you can lay your hands on, fine; ``Sugar Coated Love'' is for you.
For anyone else, it's a pass.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong; the Epic reissue program definitely has the
potential to do some good in the blues world. Vaughan inspired
absolute reverence in people, and rightly so. He remains one of THE
great bluesmen, alongside Robert Johnson, Muddy Waters, and all
three Kings (B.B., Albert and Freddie).
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, these reissues may bring some new fans into the
fold _ most likely young kids who are just now discovering the
blues and Vaughan's legacy. And there's nothing wrong with that _
Stevie certainly deserves it.
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman is pop music critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7839, or e-mail:
dfer(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
