<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GONE FOREVER? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, the dream of every cautious young American was
to work for a giant corporation. Better pay, more perks, automatic
advancement, and lifetime security were the entitlements associated
with a really good job: working for the telephone company, for
example, the local electric utility, or a Fortune 500 firm.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years, however, we in newspapers have pounded out a
constant stream of stories about takeovers, mergers, spin-offs,
downsizings, lay-offs, and plant closings. Things have changed, we
have warned in our Sunday editions, citing a variety of
authorities: Giant corporations are in the soup. They cannot be
counted on as stable sources of rising living standards or even
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Now a leading economist has written a concise and authoritative
survey of the economic forces that transformed corporations from
fat and happy institutions into the lean and mean competitors that
they are today.
</P>
<P>
   In ``New World, New Rules'' (Harvard Business School Press,
$29.95) Marina v.N. Whitman says that virtually every aspect of the
``implicit contract'' that once existed between corporations and
their various constituencies has been rewritten by a whirlwind of
economic change.
</P>
<P>
   The good news, she says, is that the forces of globalization,
deregulation, and technological advance have enhanced the dynamism
of the US economy. The bad news is that the same forces ``have torn
many people loose from their traditional mooring of economic
security and widened the income gap between the most succesful and
the least.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't come much more blue-chip these days than the
63-year-old Whitman. She was a member of the President's Council of
Economic Advisers under Richard Nixon. She is a former vice
president and chief economist of General Motors. She teaches at the
University of Michigan and is a director of Chase Manhattan,
Procter &AMP; Gamble, Alcoa, Browning-Ferris Industries, and Unocal.
</P>
<P>
   And the v.N.? It stands for von Neumann. Her father, John von
Neumann, was among the giants of 20th-century social science _ an
architect of the computer, strategic thinker par excellence. As a
child growing up on the leafy campus of the Institute for Advanced
Study in Princeton, N.J., she bicycled in the footsteps of Albert
Einstein, Kurt Godel, and Felix Gilbert _ before heading off to
Radcliffe College and a Columbia University PhD in economics.
</P>
<P>
   It was a mixture of slowdown, volatility, and sharpened global
competition that forced change upon large US corporations, starting
in the early 1970s, Whitman writes. They didn't want to undergo the
metamorphosis; they would have preferred to remain as they were,
``confident engines of growth and prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting with the breakdown of the system of fixed exchange
rates in 1973, followed by the oil shocks, growth slowed in the
industrial nations. The poorer nations, especially in Asia, began
catching up and invading US markets. Alarmed by stagnant incomes
and a drop in long-term productivity, legislators in the United
States especially embraced deregulation as a means to restart the
economic engine.
</P>
<P>
   The result: a sharp diminution in the bonds of trust between
employers and the employed. ``Employment relationships once assumed
to embody a lifetime commitment are more likely to be regarded
today as contingent and probably temporary,'' Whitman writes.
``Loyalty has been redefined to mean mutual respect and support
only for as long as the relationship lasts.''
</P>
<P>
   Accelerating the change was the rise of investor capitalism.
Managerial autonomy long had been touted as the hallmark of the
modern age, but a host of financial innovations in the 1980s _
notably the high-yield instruments known as junk bonds _ created a
``market for corporate control.'' And that meant that boards were
no longer free to pursue diverse goals in defiance of narrow
economic logic.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the increasing tendency of US, Japanese, and European
firms to invest directly in plants and whole companies in each
others' home markets gradually blurred the distinction between
``foreign'' and ``domestic'' and spared much protectionist conflict
in the 1980s and 1990s, but only at the cost of heightening
competition among firms, says Whitman. No more ``us'' and ``them;''
instead a struggle of each against all.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as Wall Street was reining in on corporations,
government was assigning new roles to them, Whitman notes, making
them watchdogs of consumer and workplace safety and equal
opportunity. Companies skinned back from other responsibilities
they previously had shouldered, in managing pension and health care
benefits. Corporate philanthropy has undergone a historic change,
becoming narrower and less dependable. Cross subsidies of all sorts
are out of fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the downsizing of corporations' role in modern
society has impoverished nearly everyone, Whitman writes. One
result of the increased pressure has been a search for scapegoats.
Another, she expects, will be a search for substitute sources of
security _ including perhaps an expanded welfare state.
</P>
<P>
   The one place Whitman doesn't look for an answer is in a
restoration to a central place of corporations themselves. ``It is
not just impossible to resore the comfortable oligopolies that
characterized the United States of the 1950s and 1960s. A few
moments' thought reveals why it is undesirable as well.'' Why
exactly? The experience of Japan, she says, is enough to show how
lifetime employment and other paternalistic practices can put a
nation in a bad way.
</P>
<P>
   I dunno. Readers will have noticed that we in newspapers have
begun to hold out the hint _ the barest whisper _ that an age of
wealth-creating oligopolies might come again. One industry after
another seems headed for the kind of concentration and market power
that characterized the age of ``the good corporation.''
</P>
<P>
   It is probably true that orderly markets may never again afford
the swift elevator to wealth that they provided at the turn of the
20th century, or the completely unself-conscious ride to riches of
the 25 years after World War II. But the 1950s look pretty good
from here.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
---------- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a column last week, I attributed to Frank Fisher a remark
about Zvi Griliches that in fact was spoken by Michael Rothschild.
I regret the error.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
