r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     03-19 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E! ESCALATES OSCARS FRENZY, DESPITE BEING LEFT OFF THE GUEST LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the front-running purveyor of televised Oscars hype, ``E!''
may be a victim of its own overachieving success.
</P>
<P>
   The cable channel built a sizable following for its frenetic
red-carpet coverage of Oscars attendees stepping from limos into a
blaze of flashbulbs and shrieking fans. That apparently gave the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences the bright idea to
throw its own grab-and-gab pre-show party _ and leave E! off the
guest list.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1994, the Rivers tag team, mom Joan and
daughter Melissa, will be shut out, at least for live reports
during the key half-hour leading up to the start of the Academy
Awards telecast.
</P>
<P>
   No other media outlet can broadcast interviews or supply live
footage during the actual Oscars broadcast. And now the academy and
ABC have tacked a 30-minute pre-show onto the official coverage,
called it ``Sunday at the Oscars'' and hired actress Geena Davis to
host it.
</P>
<P>
   Cautious not to bite the hand that allows some feeding at the
academy table, ``E!'' is making low-key public responses to the
obvious freeze-out. Says John Rieber, ``E!'' vice president of
programming and the pre-show executive producer credited with
coming up with the red carpet idea: ``We'll abide by all their
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``E!'' couldn't possibly be happy with the new arrangement,
which basically muscles it out of the celebrity-seeking loop at a
crucial time. Last year's pre-show was the channel's highest-rated
program.
</P>
<P>
   To counter, ``E!'' is planning an 11-hour Oscars frenzy: eight
before the telecast and three after the ceremony. Its coverage will
consist mainly of interviews, party reports and Joan Rivers dissing
celebrity attire, acceptance speeches and general Oscars etiquette.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will still do more (Oscars coverage) than anyone else,''
Rieber said. ``And Joan is the queen of the pre-show. The
celebrities know this. The viewers know this. Everyone wants to
talk to her, and that certainly won't change.''
</P>
<P>
   For all her criticism for being unprepared _ each year she gets
the nominations confused, leaving celebs looking baffled but making
for great comedic TV _ Joan Rivers has amassed quite a following.
That's thanks in part to her shoot-off-at-the-mouth humor, and the
way she yells ``Whaddya wearing?'' to celebs eager to promote their
designers and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   She's usually planted on the red carpet, flagging down attendees
as Melissa moves about elsewhere, giving Oscars facts and analysis
alongside ``expert'' Todd Newton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still very much in the game, a game we invented and have
perfected,'' Rieber said. ``It'll still be great because, while
there is more Oscar coverage out there, the question is, what will
you miss if you're not watching us?''
</P>
<P>
   What a shrewdly designed dig at ``Sunday at the Oscars,'' which,
from the looks of it, probably won't compare to the funky looseness
of ``E!'s'' gushy reporting.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's half-hour is expected to include red-carpet arrival
coverage as well as something ``E!'' has never been allowed to do:
take cameras inside the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion, stake out the
lobby, go backstage, and check the pulse inside the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Producer Gil Gates, at the helm of the awards show for the ninth
consecutive year, insists that they've watched enough pre-shows to
know what they want _ and don't want. Host Davis made that clear
during an interview, proclaiming, ``You certainly won't hear me
yelling to someone, `Who made your dress!?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Gates gushes about the Oscars being ``an all-consuming event,''
but is this a good thing? In a society in which celebrity worship
seems to deepen with each generation, the Oscars easily rival the
Super Bowl in terms of empty media hysteria.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly now that more channels need to fill air time. CNN,
MSNBC, Fox News, Turner, AMC, Bravo and local news stations
handicap the Oscars race with specials and expanded coverage
leading up to the broadcast. Even Davis says, ``It's enough to make
you reassess your priorities.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because much of it merely adds to the clutter _ like
Roseanne's ``Elizabeth'' fashion show and makeover on her talk
show. (Although those sick of Barbara Walters' pre-Oscars
interviews should check out Comedy Central's ``The Beth Littleford
Interview Special,'' a satire of Walters, during which Minnesota
Gov. Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura shows Beth his favorite assault
weapons.)
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the question is which came first _ the demand for this
kind of coverage or the coverage that created the demand?
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, a lot of Oscar preview shows bore me to tears,'' said
Gary Cogill, film critic for WFAA/Channel 8 in Dallas-Fort Wort. He
tried to spice up his own preview show with an in-depth (for TV)
interview with Steven Spielberg and an interesting segment on how
Texas and Texans have been portrayed by Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've overreacted to the Oscars, and the end result is
what you're seeing now in some of these shows. I find (Joan and
Melissa Rivers) insulting. I know people watch, but they're
abrasive and annoying in what they report and how they report it.
I'm more interested in the why and how. And audiences deserve that.
We can't continue to dumb down everything, even when it comes to
film.''
</P>
<P>
   Rieber agrees _ to a point. ``It's certainly become a massive
media event,'' he says. ``But every year we wonder if it's too
much, and every year it comes upon us and we get excited. I mean,
here it is. Can't you feel the excitement?''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
