<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV21-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADERSHIP DILEMMAS IN NEW ENGLAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 21, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What separates real leaders from pretend leaders is the ability
to take the crowd where it doesn't want to go.
</P>
<P>
   And by pure coincidence, three New England governors are caught
in the jaws of political dilemmas of their own making at the same
time, with their reputations for leadership at stake.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Gov. John Rowland enjoyed a wave of popular support
when his long months of backstage negotiations with the New England
Patriots football club paid off with the announcement the NFL
franchise would flee Massachusetts for the $374 million pot of gold
promised by Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   But now the deal is on shaky ground. Taxpayers resentful of the
giveaway, the most famous of whom is Ralph Nader, a scathing critic
of the Patriots' land-and-cash grab, are rising in anger. Rowland's
erector-set configuration of public and private financing is
tottering, because the gas company that owns the current stadium
site is demanding more money to move than Rowland's scheme
envisioned.
</P>
<P>
   In New Hampshire, Gov. Jeanne Shaheen still enjoys a 68 percent
poll approval rating, but her leadership is questioned by the
complicated snarl over what taxes must be raised to comply with
state Supreme Court rulings about how public schools are to be
funded. Pink slips have gone out to some Granite State teachers, as
the state's governmental machinery clanks and groans and stalls and
staggers..
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen won't sign the income tax the Republican-controlled
House approved. She proposed a new statewide property tax, a
business tax, a video slot machine tax, and higher booze and
cigarette taxes. The state Senate wrestled with the unpalatable
options, which carry a $1 billion pricetag, as the state confronts
an April 1 court deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen's political dilemma: she was elected twice vowing to
veto any statewide broadbased tax on income, sales or property.
She's caved on property, is apparently willing to cave on sales,
but refuses to budge on the income tax _ the one tax approved by
the House.
</P>
<P>
   The third politician grappling with a problem of his own making
is Gov. Paul Cellucci. Apparently convinced by in-house polling
data that his popularity rests on a tough-guy image, Cellucci has
been rattling off a series of crack-down-on-crime measures that
garner him a sliver of soundbite on the evening news.
</P>
<P>
   But now it's time to stand and deliver for Cellucci, who used to
oppose the death penalty, but now promotes capital punishment as
the key to his crime containment program. Monday, the friends and
foes of capital punishment will flock to the State House for what
promises to be a long, contentious and bitter hearing on the pros
and cons, with life and death at stake for the prosecutorial pros
who want to slay the convicted cons.
</P>
<P>
   Last time around the House voted down the death penalty by one
vote, and Cellucci made a big deal of this in his campaign. This
time, the vote is still close. But Speaker Tom Finneran is against
it, and Cardinal Bernard Law's opposition is regarded as
significant, and possibly pivotal.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci tried a bit of political legerdemain, appointing a
handful of legislators to higher-paid posts in his administration,
and hoping to replace them with pro-death-penalty sympathizers.
Cellucci has demanded that the Legislature hold off voting on this
year's death penalty bill until, presumably, at least some new
death penalty advocates get elected.
</P>
<P>
   But those who follow the issue closely suggest that the
opposition is well-organized and that recent revelations of
misconduct by police, prosecutors or the justice system in a number
of states reinforce doubts about whether wrongly accused convicted
murderers can be unfairly executed.
</P>
<P>
   What political problem do all three governors confront?
</P>
<P>
   In each case, it was the governor's own initiative that has
resulted in a divided electorate.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland sought a big splashy pro sports deal to be the capstone
on an expensive urban renewal program for Hartford, his ailing
capital city. But Rowland gave away so much money to Bob Kraft, the
clever Patriots owner, that there is not enough left on the table
to pay off the gas company that just happens to own the land where
the stadium will sit. How does Rowland successfully defend the
concept of enriching out-of-state owner Kraft, and stiffing the
local gas utility?
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen painted herself in a corner with the famous antitax
``pledge'' extorted from gubernatorial candidates in New Hampshire
for decades. She seems willing to ride with her decision to buck
the income tax, and play around with all the other pieces on the
tax chessboard. But she has not bowled over anyone with her
leadership as the state vacillates.
</P>
<P>
   She may yet win a Senate seat in 2002, and she may be a dark
horse for vice president, if the Democrats nominate Vice President
Gore, whose New Hampshire operation is run by Shaheen's husband.
Like Rowland, who is mentioned for consideration as a Republican
vice presidential option, she has to make a reputation as a bold
and innovative leader. That has not yet happened in the tax debate,
nor the stadium tussle.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is not mentioned by anyone as a vice presidential
contender, but he is undeniably close to Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
and could conceivably land some kind of federal job in a Bush
regime. Just having been elected as a Republican in a Democratic
state is a calling card in national GOP circles.
</P>
<P>
   But if he can't deliver the death penalty this time around,
fresh off an election victory, on an issue of his own choosing, at
a time of benign economic conditions, over what is most likely the
most favorable political terrain he'll enjoy in the forseeable
future, then he loses stature.
</P>
<P>
   This much can be said of Rowland, Shaheen and Cellucci in their
current struggles: they made their own beds, on issues of their own
choosing, and now they have to figure out how to persuade
majorities of their legislatures to swallow some tough votes. How
they handle that will determine what people think of them. We
measure our leaders by how they handle the tough ones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1740EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
