<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOT-SCULPTURE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FOOT GETS A HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Foot, a proposed sculpture for San Francisco
Bay about which nearly everybody seems to have an opinion, took a
big step when a key committee of the Art Commission here gave it an
enthusiastic hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a perfect piece; it's sexy and beautiful,'' said Stanlee
Gatti, chairman of the commission's visual arts committee, which on
Wednesday unanimously approved Seattle sculptor Buster Simpson's
proposed foot in the Bay just off the end of Market Street.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture is a hollow, 18-foot-high, striated
stainless-steel rendering of a foot with its big toe just touching
the water.
</P>
<P>
   When a sketch of it was presented to the public in 1997, there
was an outpouring of both protest and praise. Critics wanted to
boot it back to Seattle. Fans, such as Gatti, say it's a major art
piece that would add to the city's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those pieces that could be a history marker for
America in art,'' Gatti said, adding that he has received numerous
calls from museum directors around the country who said they envied
San Francisco for having a chance to get The Foot.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture would cost $400,000 if approved, and because of
the controversy over its aesthetics, Simpson was given $25,000 to
come up with a plan.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, he returned with a stainless-steel model of The
Foot along with computer-generated models of it.
</P>
<P>
   Gatti and fellow commissioners Denise Roth, Dugall Stermer and
Ralph Guggenheim seemed impressed. Richard Newirth, director of
cultural affairs, said it was ``stunning artwork'' and was so
impressive that it swayed doubting commissioners.
</P>
<P>
   The sculpture, which would change colors depending on weather
conditions during the day and be lit with pulsating lights at
night, still must wade through deep water before it is approved.
</P>
<P>
   First, a citizens advisory committee must OK it. Then it must go
to the county Transportation Authority, made up of the Board of
Supervisors. The supervisors probably will hold a committee
hearing, then full board hearing. Then it needs a approval from the
Port Commission, which owns the water where the foot would stand.
</P>
<P>
   Newirth said he figures the approval process should take six to
eight weeks, although he agreed with Gatti that ``nothing is ever
easy in this town.'' In fact, one supervisor, Barbara Kaufman, has
delivered her review: ``Yech!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
