   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO _ WASHINGTON _ Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic has rejected and refused to sign the Kosovo peace
agreement, which now puts the ball in the United States' and
President Bill Clinton's court about when to begin NATO air strikes
against Yugoslavia. International observers, diplomats and aid
workers have been put on 24-to-48 hours notice to leave Belgrade.
But Clinton, after being briefed by his national security team
Friday morning, spent the rest of the time trying to convince
members of Congress that the move was in the United States' best
interest. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON _ WASHINGTON _ President Clinton holds his first formal
news conference in nearly a year. Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Press conference is skedded for 4 p.m. EST.
</P>
<P>
   DNC-MONEY _ WASHINGTON _ The Democratic National Committee opens
a three-day meeting Thursday to choose a new leadership team
heading into the 2000 elections. One key question is who can
replace Steve Grossman, the finance chairman who helped revive a
financially flat-lined party. (Shepard, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-ANGKOR _ SIEM REAP, Cambodia _ Talk about a trip to
write home about . . . Back in 1871 Frank Vincent Jr. dropped out
of university somewhere in America. Despite frail health, the
17-year-old embarked on ``a systematic tour of the most interesting
parts of the world.'' Vincent was one of the first American
travelers to see the great temple of Angkor Wat, a monument to the
four-armed Hindu god Vishnu the Preserver. Covering nearly one
square mile and cresting in a central tower taller than the
Cathedral of Notre Dame in Paris, the temple of Angkor Wat is the
largest and one of the most haunting religious edifices in the
world. For the next 98 years, an ever-growing stream of
sophisticated travelers from around the world journeyed to Angkor
Wat and the ruins of the nearby royal city of Angkor Thom.
(Albright-Kunstel, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   Moved in (i) International and (t) Travel categories.
