<P>
   ISRAEL-EMBASSY _ JERUSALEM _ In under two months, the
Congressionally mandated move of the U.S. Embassy from Tel Aviv to
Jerusalem is supposed to begin. The trouble is, the destination
site is still just a vacant lot and that's how administration
officials would like to keep it. President Bill Clinton will likely
exercise a waiver to delay what would be a dangerously
controversial act _ a move that would recognize the disputed city
of Jerusalem as Israel's capital and pre-empt the hottest issue in
the Oslo peace process. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MCI-LAWSUIT _ In a motion filed this week, lawyers for three
banks, including NationsBank, leveled accusations against MCI
Telecommunications in a civil racketeering lawsuit. The allegations
say MCI leased network space to ``resellers'' who have used the
space for telephone credit cards used by organized crime. An
affidavit by an MCI manager, who has pleaded guilty to fraud,
implicates higher level company officials in a conspiracy to
defraud the banks out of more than $30 million. Rankin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
