<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7083 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOLSON-THEATER-REVIEW     03-19 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOLSON-THEATER-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`JOLSON SINGS AGAIN:' THE SOUND OF HANDS CLAPPING, THE CHILL OF
BACKS TURNING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By BEN BRANTLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRUNSWICK, N.J. _ Sunday night, if all goes according to
schedule, the legendary, brilliant director Elia Kazan will appear
on the stage of the Dorothy Chandler Pavilion in Los Angeles. On
Saturday afternoon, another legendary, brilliant director of Greek
heritage, whose name is Andreas, will appear here on the stage of
the George Street Playhouse, where he has been spending much time
recently.
</P>
<P>
   Both men will be wreathed in clouds of moral debate, and a sound
with which both are familiar, that of hands clapping, will assume
unusual significance. Kazan, 89, is being given an Academy Award
for lifetime achievement, an honor that has drawn objections
because of his role as an informer during the witch hunts for
Communists in the 1950s. Protesters have urged those attending the
Oscars to refrain from applauding Kazan.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas will as usual receive lots of applause, oceans of it,
and even before the curtain calls for ``Jolson Sings Again,'' a
play by Arthur Laurents, who, not incidentally, has known and
worked with Kazan. The clapping should not, however, be taken as a
sign of approval.
</P>
<P>
   In the final moments of this brisk, probing and imbalanced drama
about naming names in the age of McCarthy, Andreas stands by
himself in a spotlight, bathed in the taped sounds of noisy ovation
and clearly chilled by the loneliness of it all. As
success-addicted stars always are finding out in Hollywood biopics,
there's no warmth in the adoration of crowds when you've lost your
friends. Yes, it's a hokey show business cliche, but in this
particular context it definitely has some bite.
</P>
<P>
   That scene captures the spirit of ``Jolson Sings Again,'' which
is probably this weekend's most purely topical evening of theater.
The play often feels confiningly shaped by the dramatic conventions
of the period in which it is set, with big, lip-biting
confrontations and bantering dialogue that is too silky to be
credible.
</P>
<P>
   But it also has the authentic heat of a war story told by a
soldier who has known the front lines. Laurents, best known as the
author of the books for the musicals ``Gypsy'' and ``West Side
Story,'' saw firsthand what happened to those who informed and to
those who didn't in postwar Hollywood and the ways in which both
were scarred. (The title, for the record, refers to Larry Parks,
who played Jolson on film and was also an informer.)
</P>
<P>
   At its best ``Jolson Sings Again,'' which has been directed by
David Saint and runs through March 28, pulses with the indignation,
confusion and pain of people trapped in a no-win moral quandary. It
also sustains a sophisticated dramatic argument, finding different
shades of judgments for similar acts of betrayal and arguing that
it is possible to separate the sinner from the sin.
</P>
<P>
   But if the play is about the impossibility of seeing the world
in moral absolutes, it also presents its theme with black-and-white
baldness. While the work has four characters of relatively equal
importance, only one of them feels fully developed in both the
writing and the performance.
</P>
<P>
   That is not, by the way, Andreas, although he is certainly the
center of the evening. Yes, he has unquestionably been inspired by
the career of Kazan. Portrayed by Armand Schultz, he is a sexually
charismatic man of dazzling talent who has made the transition from
Broadway to Hollywood, where he is flourishing as both a director
and a Lothario.
</P>
<P>
   Among those in his thrall are Julian (Robert Petkoff), a young
New York playwright, and Robbie (Betsy Aidem), the agent of both
men and the sometime lover of Andreas. The fourth member of the
quartet is Sidney (Jonathan Hadary), Robbie's husband and a
screenwriter of shaky talent but very firm left-wing principles.
The play examines the consequences of what happens when three of
the characters (all but Julian) are subpoenaed to name names in the
film industry.
</P>
<P>
   Andreas may be the drama's drawing card as a sensational figure
a clef, but he is also its weakest link in that he functions less
as a real character than as a litmus test for those around him.
Unlike Kazan, who famously offered patriotic justification for
informing, Andreas is an unqualified, career-driven opportunist who
makes no bones about saying so. He is also an irresistible seducer,
and Julian is reduced to telling him flatly, ``You are evil.''
</P>
<P>
   The devil is never an easy role, and Schultz seems overwhelmed
by his character's satanic dimensions, going stiff when he should
be temptingly molten. Similarly, Julian, who must come to terms
with his homosexuality as well as Andreas' acts of betrayal, has
been conceived as a blank page of a man on whom the play's lessons
are written, and Petkoff adds little in the way of enlivening
detail.
</P>
<P>
   Laurents introduces an intriguing erotic element to the men's
relationship, yet their scenes together, which should be the play's
most urgent, have a woodenness that is part soap opera, part
debate. Hadary is fine as the wisecracking firebrand. But the
evening's naturalistic fire is mostly generated by Ms. Aidem, who
wears both her character's period affectations and her moral
ambivalence with wonderful flair and sincerity.
</P>
<P>
   Laurents, whose characters have been richly embodied by Shirley
Booth, Katharine Hepburn and Barbra Streisand, is a virtuoso in
creating women's roles, and he doesn't disappoint with Robbie. Here
is a person of solid convictions and very human instincts of
sexuality and survival, and Ms. Aidem does full justice to the
attendant battle within. The real heartbreak in the play comes not
when Andreas and Julian have their showdown but when Robbie says to
her husband: ``You're the good guy. Andreas is the bad guy. Which
am I? I'm both, Sidney darling.''
</P>
<P>
   The production has been handsomely staged, with great-looking
mid-century Hollywood costumes by Theoni V. Aldredge and a clever
revolving multipurpose set by James Youmans. Saint gives crispness
and suspense to the transitions between scenes, though he seems
less adept at helping his actors feel comfortable with Laurents'
epigrammatic dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those lines sound anachronistically self-conscious.
(``Stop pointing the finger, because sooner or later it points
back.'') Others, however, have a winning wit and elegance.
Consider, for example, Julian's dead-on assessment of the film
``Gentleman's Agreement,'' an Oscar winner in 1947: ``The movie
that said you better be nice to a Jew because he might turn out to
be a Gentile.'' It would be nice to hear what Laurents has to say
about ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES: `JOLSON SINGS AGAIN'  &QL; 
By Arthur Laurents; directed by David Saint; sets by James Youmans;
costumes by Theoni V. Aldredge; lighting by Howell Binkley; music
composed by David Van Tieghem; production manager, Vern McKinney;
stage manager, Thomas Clewell. Presented by the George Street
Playhouse, Saint, artistic director; Tom Werder, managing director,
in New Brunswick, N.J. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
With: Robert Petkoff (Julian), Betsy Aidem (Robbie), Jonathan
Hadary (Sidney) and Armand Schultz (Andreas).  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
