<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARCEAU-DANCE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCEL MARCEAU'S SILENT GENIUS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: France)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The great French mime, Marcel Marceau, returned
triumphantly to New York on Thursday night and taught us again that
the best of art is never literal.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying a passenger on an ocean liner, he turns green with
seasickness. Yet his face is painted white. It is a measure of his
silent genius that imagination and illusion still speak so potently
through his artistry. At a time when two generations of younger
mime artists have rebelled against his brand of classical mime,
Marceau remains a model, not a fossil.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has never seen the staples of the repertory with
which Marceau has toured the United States since 1955 should beat a
path to the Kaye Playhouse at Hunter College where two different
programs will be presented through March 28.
</P>
<P>
   Marceau's vociferous fans were already out in force to see the
first program of new and old pieces on Thursday. Schuyler Chapin,
the city's cultural affairs commissioner, opened the evening by
reading Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's proclamation of the day as
``Marcel Marceau Day'' and noted that Marceau was celebrating his
76th birthday on stage.
</P>
<P>
   To ask whether Marceau is still spry is to ask whether the sun
rises in the morning. When he counts invisible money he gives us a
symphony of fluttery fingers. When he ``climbs'' stairs he marches
in place with knees bent and slips his hand lower and lower on a
putative bannister, an exercise in contrasting movement. To analyze
his craft is to deny its poetry. And yet there is no way to avoid
tipping a hat to his gift for distillation, the essential gesture
or movement in constant concert with the mobile face.
</P>
<P>
   Like any major actor he stands between comedy and tragedy and he
oscillates between these two poles in his signature piece, ``The
Maskmaker.'' As his mouth turns up or down, we believe he has
pulled different masks on and off. It is common theatrical wisdom
that a mask imposes a specific character on an actor, that he
becomes the mask. But when Marceau suddenly cannot wipe away his
happy face, we see the opposite: a body limp with despair below a
grinning expression, a metaphor for human existence. Watch also how
Marceau's body shrinks and his beaming face fades into a frozen
peace in ``Youth, Maturity, Old Age and Death.''
</P>
<P>
   In the new ``Soliloquy of Three Poor Souls,'' he is a loser
telling a sob story, mocked by others on a park bench. The same
tale is retold with different emphasis by each character: the image
of a man who says he wanted to shoot himself because he could not
support his brood as a pianist and violinist is turned into a
satire. Whether the three characters are real or aspects of one
person is less important than the picture of rejection and
redemption.
</P>
<P>
   When playing multiple characters as in ``The Little Cafe'' and
``The Trial,'' he moves into a richer dimension. It is a very
French cafe where groggy, tipsy and choosy patrons are served by a
waiter whose day ends with a debonair outing at a music hall. There
is a wonderful scene when a dissatisfied customer is tricked by the
waiter who goes back into the kitchen for a minute and serves him
exactly the same dish. The customer beams. How do we know it is a
kitchen? Because Marceau creates a sense of place, even kicking the
door back with his foot.
</P>
<P>
   Superb is the word for his finger-pointing prosecutor and
defense lawyer in ``The Trial.'' ``The Pickpocket's Nightmare'' is
less satisfying, a generalized joke about hands shooting out from
panels.
</P>
<P>
   Detail comes back in a suite for Bip, Marceau's signature
character, when he looks for a job, travels by sea and is
overwhelmed by too many women from a dating service. Gyongyi Biro
and Alexander Neander were the silent and able announcers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
