<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-WESTSIDE-STYLE-ART     03-19 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WESTSIDE-STYLE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SLEEPY SUBURB THAT IS THE UPPER WEST SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21)  
 (af)  
 By AMANDA HESSER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sandwiched between friends in a booth at Lot 61 West
21st Street, dressed in leather pants and Manolo Blahnik heels,
Tait Chatmon took a moment to appreciate the view. ``In one glance
you have dreads, then you have lawyer types, then you have city
kids, then you have bridge and tunnel,'' she said, dragging her
finger across the room as if swiping icing off a cake. ``I love
it!''
</P>
<P>
   That's what you get on a Monday night downtown, and that's why
Ms. Chatmon and half a dozen of her friends make the trip down here
_ down to ``the city'' _three or four times a week. They come by
car.
</P>
<P>
   But they're not bridge and tunnel. They're from a part of
Manhattan where strollers are more menacing than cab drivers, where
the Gap is never more than a short walk from one's doorstep and an
exciting cultural moment is the opening of a new branch of Gracious
Home. This sleepy, comfortable Westchester of Manhattan is the
Upper West Side.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chatmon and her friends _ like many, many Upper West Siders
in need of a style fix _ shop everywhere but their neighborhood and
do almost all their socializing downtown. The Upper West Side is
their bedroom community, bridged to the city by the Nos. 1 and 9
local subway lines.
</P>
<P>
   The Upper West Side has gone through phases. Once a literary and
artistic haven of creative eccentrics and liberals, it became a
swinging singles scene in the 1980s. But now its trend-setting
appeal has eroded. It has turned from marbled rye to white bread,
as textured as a small city in middle America.
</P>
<P>
   The tone is set on 66th Street, with Tower Records, a
three-level Barnes &AMP; Noble, a Disney Store, a Sony Multiplex, an
Eddie Bauer, a Nine West and the Gap. Further north, it starts all
over again; the five-block stretch between 82nd and 86th Streets
has a Barnes &AMP; Noble, Gap, Banana Republic, Coach, Origins, Nine
West and a Sony Theater. Put a roof over the whole thing, and you
could be in a mall in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   Megastores and Starbucks aren't the only villains. Nearly
everything that once gave the Upper West Side its quirky charm _
from Shakespeare &AMP; Co. books to Charivari, the clothing store _ has
been wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   The triangle of real estate defined by Zabar's, Lincoln Center
and the Museum of Natural History is a style-free zone. In between
the Nine Wests and the Eddie Bauers are countless restaurants,
clubs and shops. And yet, many who live there insist that there's
nowhere to eat or go out to.
</P>
<P>
   The Evelyn, one of the better bars, has the brassy Boston feel
of a Cheers with bad lighting. At Rain, a Vietnamese restaurant,
the droopy fernlike plants seem left over from the 80s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is lame,'' said Saul Adams, a journalist who grew up in the
neighborhood. ``It's slowly become worse and worse. I mean, it was
never party central, but it used to have a little more character.''
</P>
<P>
   People who live on the Upper West Side get their hopes up with
every new flurry of openings, often only to be disappointed. And
mystified. Recently, a dozen or so boutiques and restaurants
designed to make the area more of a style destination have opened.
</P>
<P>
   But already, the outlook is bleak. The most sophisticated
newcomer, Calle Ocho, serves Latin American fare, the cuisine of
the moment, but in an oversize room teeming with Banana Republic
emigres. Balthazar it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why many residents feel shame when confronted by
someone who lives south of the border at Central Park South. When a
young woman was recently at dinner with Adam Rapoport, an editor at
Time Out New York magazine, who lives in the West Village, and
mentioned that she lived on the Upper West Side, his response was
typical. ``I've heard of that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Many 20-somethings like Ms. Chatmon, who live in the
neighborhood, are drawn to its suburban virtues. For grocery
shopping it's unparalleled: Fairway, Citarella, Zabar's. And it has
great gyms; the wet area at Reebok is the city's finest. Ms.
Chatmon likes the feeling of community and the fact that it's far
from the madding subways and midtown crowds. ``It's quieter,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Quiet as a coma. But it wasn't always this way. In the 70s, when
hip spots started to crop up, the scene was an ethnic, intellectual
and swinging mix. There were dairy restaurants like Famous, 50s-era
date palaces like the Tip Toe Inn, art theaters like the Thalia,
chess clubs and Plato's Retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The magician Doug Henning starred in the musical ``The Magic
Show,'' a Broadway hit whose songs celebrated the neighborhood with
lyrics like: ``West End Avenue!'' and ``Right across the street
from Zabar's!''
</P>
<P>
   In the 80s, the Upper West Side got hotter, particularly
Columbus Avenue. Stores like Charivari attracted shoppers from all
over the city. It was one of the first stores in Manhattan to sell
clothing by designers like Anna Sui and Yoji Yamamoto. There was a
thriving singles scene at places like the Surf Club, and the China
Club attracted celebrities. It was never avant-garde like the East
Village, but then it was the 80s and preppies and yuppies were
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Columbus Avenue became so popular that rents began
to climb. Within a few years, they had doubled and tripled. The
individual businesses that gave the avenue its flavor could no
longer afford to be there. That's when the Gap, Banana Republic,
Barnes &AMP; Noble and Sony Theaters moved in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It lost its specialness,'' said Barbara Weiser, whose family
owned Charivari. The store's five locations on the Upper West Side
have all closed in the last few years. ``Most people get altitude
sickness coming above 50th Street,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   In the 90s, downtown culture has edged yuppie culture out of the
mainstream. Four-star restaurants and Louis Vuitton have staked
claims in SoHo and Tribeca; the Upper East Side went downtown and
brought some of the downtown spirit back up with it. The Upper West
Side shares none of that synergy. It's neither ritzy nor hip.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the mallification of Manhattan seems to be
happening rapidly,'' said David Hershkovits, the publisher and
co-editor of Paper Magazine, who couldn't remember the last time he
had been to the Upper West Side. Even SoHo feels more like a
high-end mall these days.
</P>
<P>
   But on the Upper West Side it seems worse, the blandness more
entrenched. Blame the residents. Entrepreneurs secretly complain
that Upper West Side locals just aren't willing to spend on style.
As unfashionable as it may be, they prefer value to vogue.
</P>
<P>
   A restaurateur who is new to the area and who agreed to an
interview only if he were not named, lighted up at the opportunity
to vent about the problem. ``It's almost hard to believe some of
the things people say,'' he said. ``I have had people say, `I eat
my soup to the rim,' or, `I got my salad split, but we want
more.'''
</P>
<P>
   A clientele that demands Carnegie Deli portions is probably not
going to appreciate a shaving of truffle. And so, the restaurateurs
say, they dumb down their dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Kalt, an owner of Spazzia, the Upper West Side
counterpart to Spartina, a chic trattoria in Tribeca, has altered
the menu to fit price-conscious patrons. At Spartina, he offers a
roasted duck breast with figs and a 100-year-old balsamic vinegar;
at Spazzia, he swaps it for a roasted duck breast with Swiss chard
gratin and a chestnut honey sauce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give them the opportunity to spend less money,'' Kalt said.
If Upper West Siders see their homey neighborhood as a place to
nest but not to splurge, that may explain why Ansonia, a three-star
restaurant that was heralded as a breath of fresh air on Columbus
Avenue three years ago, couldn't cut it. The neighborhood rejected
its high-end ambitions and its comprehensive wine list, and the
restaurant wilted in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Many restaurateurs are now trying a new strategy, opening
larger, more moderately priced places like Calle Ocho and Ruby Foo,
a popular Asian restaurant on Broadway that serves giant sushi to
please the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers regard the neighborhood in the same way. Stefani
Greenfield, an owner of Scoop, a trendy clothing store with
locations in SoHo and on the Upper East Side, said she would
consider opening on the Upper West Side, but if she did she would
open a Scoop Street, their lower-priced version.
</P>
<P>
   David Shearer, an owner of Totem, a design store in TriBeCa,
also considers the Upper West Side a viable market. If he opened a
store up there, he said, he would gear the merchandise for smaller
spaces and for families.
</P>
<P>
   Clubs have also been trying. The owners of Life, a popular
downtown club, helped open Cream, a club on Columbus Avenue, last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Lewis, an executive director at Life, describes the uptown
clubs as more sanitized versions of those downtown. They open
earlier and draw a more clean-cut crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Cream, for instance, on a recent evening, looked as if it had
been decorated by a prom committee, had a sound system muffled like
a home stereo, and played three Michael Jackson songs in an hour.
</P>
<P>
   There were people from Staten Island, a bachelorette party from
New Jersey, and scant signs of fashion life. Plaid button-down
shirts. Satin stretch T-shirts from two years ago. One woman was
wearing a business suit. Bouncers were actually turning away people
in sneakers, a pretty regular accessory at a downtown club.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not a destination club,'' Lewis said. ``This club will
do well when it rains.'' He was right. Cream has done well, though
Life backed out after a year. Successful or not, many of the Upper
West Side boites come off as very suburban.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday night _ the big night for Upper West Side clubs
but popularly referred to as ``amateur night'' elsewhere in town _
the clubs were just plain out of touch compared with a place like
the Key Club on East 13th Street.
</P>
<P>
   There was more energy on a Thursday night at the Key Club last
week, when Ms. Chatmon was there with her entourage. On this night,
she was the party's promoter. With it in full swing, the place
swathed in red velvet and smoke seeping among people on the crowded
dance floor, Ms. Chatmon said that she's going to stop promoting
parties on the Upper West Side. ``It's just not bringing in the
crowd I want. It's just not downtown.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1813EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
