<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7129 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DNC-MONEY20-COX     03-19 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-MONEY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NEW DEMOCRATIC CHAIRMAN UNVEILS EXPANSION PLANS
 &HT;    360&AMP;adds.
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The incoming chairman of the Democratic Party on
Friday unveiled a multimillion-dollar expansion of its programs to
recruit and support candidates _ and a savvy team to raise money
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Andrew, who will succeed fund-raising wizard Steve Grossman
as the nuts-and-bolts director of the party, told members of the
Democratic National Committee that his ``America 2000'' plan will
combine the best of high-tech and old-fashioned grassroots
politics.
</P>
<P>
   The DNC will create a Democratic Internet Center, digitized
voter profiles and a $1 million software link between its new
headquarters and those of the state parties. At the same time, it
plans to recruit and train 1 million volunteers for door-to-door
combat with the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future, grassroots politics will have silicon
strands,'' Andrew said in his first formal address to DNC members.
``We will electrify, digitize and personalize the way we do
politics in every election. We will make the party of high hopes
the party of high-tech.''
</P>
<P>
   To pay for it all, and to wipe out the lingering debt from the
1998 congressional election, Andrew has put together a new Finance
Department.
</P>
<P>
   It includes Beth Dozoretz, a Washington hostess and an
experienced fund raiser who brought in more than $2 million to the
party during the 1998 election cycle; Andrew Tobias, the author of
best-selling financial advice books, and Rep. Loretta Sanchez of
California, who has a nationwide fund-raising network in the
Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew, the Indiana party chairman who was handpicked by
Grossman as his successor, credited Grossman with rejuvenating the
Democratic Party amid scandals arising from the party's aggressive
fund-raising during the 1996 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in this country has worked harder and longer than Steve
Grossman to put this party on a sound financial footing and allow
us to go forward,'' Andrew told the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   The party is still nearly $6 million in debt, down from $18
million at the start of the 52-year-old Massachusetts businessman's
two-year term.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, the party's debt was reduced to $960,000, but it
rose again in the months leading up to the 1998 election, in which
the Democratic Party gained five seats and fought the GOP to a draw
in Senate races.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when Grossman arrived to begin a joint chairmanship
with Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, the party not only was heavily in
debt, but its fund-raising on behalf of the Clinton-Gore
re-election campaign was under investigation by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans tried to bankrupt us,'' said Romer, who is
continuing as the party's general chairman, a position that makes
him its national spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   During his 24-month tenure as co-chairman of the party, Grossman
spearheaded a fund-raising effort that grossed more than $90
million. He put on a blitz of fund-raisers featuring President
Clinton, first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, Vice President Al Gore
and his wife, Tipper Gore. He expanded direct-mail and phone
solicitations beyond the party's aging liberal base. And he wooed a
new target: high-tech entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got on the phone and stayed on the phone,'' said David
Worley, chairman of the Georgia Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew's ``America 2000'' plan follows a similar course. But it
also calls for rolling out an on-line fund-raising effort as well
as a beefed up Democratic Business Council, the structure used by
the party to reach out to business leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew has committed his new team to exceeding the amounts
raised by Grossman, but has not specified by how much.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the soft-spoken, behind-the-scenes Grossman,
Andrew used his appearance before the DNC to lambast the Republican
Party as ``the GOP _ Grumpy Old Party,'' and the GOP's presidential
candidates as a ``motley crew.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the current GOP
front-runner, is little known by American voters ``beyond the
monogram on his shirt sleeve.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said former Vice President Dan Quayle is ``more a punch
line than a president,'' Pat Buchanan is ``the most progressive
candidate of '99 _ 1899,'' Lamar Alexander ``gave plaid a bad
name,'' Rep. John Kasich of Ohio is so enthusiastic ``you'd think
he was the one on Viagra,'' and Steve Forbes is the candidate with
``the bank account of Bill Gates and the personality of MS-DOS.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew said the GOP candidates are ``a disaster in the making,''
and some Republicans ``want to call in the Red Cross'' _ a
reference to Elizabeth Dole, the former head of the charity.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
