s l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TAE-BO-EXERCISE-$ADV2     03-19 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAE-BO-EXERCISE-$ADV21-825(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUNCHING AND KICKING ALL THE WAY TO THE BANK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, March 21)  
(lh) 
 By PENELOPE GREEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ I'm not going to say that I never saw the tapes,''
said Rique Uresti, a former male cheerleader wearing a Jim
Carrey-ish smile and slightly flared brown tights. ``But Tae-Bo is
Tae-Bo, and this is Gotham Box.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This'' was certainly something. On a recent frigid Tuesday
night at the Equinox gym on East 85th Street and Third Avenue,
Uresti led 80 women (and one man, a 55-year-old accountant) through
a zingy series of punches and kicks. Eighty-one New Yorkers out at
dinnertime on a chilly evening. Uresti, whose resemblance to Jim
Carrey only deepened as he began to move, seemed to be having a
terrific time. He giggled and swung his head around like a Fosse
dancer. The women looked happy, too. They smiled and jabbed and
panted and counted out loud.
</P>
<P>
   It was very user-friendly, almost idiot-proof _ peppy, boppy,
martial artsy _ this kickboxing to Mariah Carey. A punch is a
wonderful gesture to fake, especially to an eight-count beat. And
there are no opponents in Gotham Box, and no bloody noses.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the women gathered, damply, into little happy-talk
bunches, tiny knots of feel-good testimonials to Uresti's class and
the overall satisfaction of the new way of working out _ which has
swept away last year's fads like so many old sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   The new way is called Tae-Bo (pronounced TIE-BOE), a name that
has been trademarked but has spawned many imitations, including
Uresti's Gotham Box. The real thing, a cocktail of tae kwon do,
boxing and aerobics, is the baby of a 43-year-old martial arts
champion and action-movie actor in Sherman Oaks, Calif., named
Billy Blanks. Blanks is distinguished among his fitness brethren by
both his beauty and his diffidence _ you might say that he is the
inverse of the overgroomed and voluble Denise Austin, of the
Lifetime channel _ and he runs an exercise studio and karate dojo,
which has lately metamorphosed into quite an empire.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy Tae-Bo exercise tapes to use at home; a set of four
costs $59.85. These are the tapes Uresti referred to, which are
sold by an infomercial playing 2,000 times a day on cable
television stations around the country.
</P>
<P>
   You must have seen its fervent testimonials, like ``It gets in
your blood,'' as one woman says. Or, ``It made a difference in my
comeback,'' as Carlos ``King'' Palomino, a welterweight boxer,
says, adding: ``I've had three fights, three knockouts.'' In a
growly voice, Shaquille O'Neal, the basketball star, says, ``Get
off your butt, man.''
</P>
<P>
   And soon Billy Blanks comes on, with his shy smile and his
devastating physique, and tells you he has always wanted to help
people, and you believe him. He tells you other fitness gurus have
lied to you, but that Tae-Bo will work because it is ``the Truth.''
And you believe him. I believe him. I bought the tapes. Why not? If
you've got the will, Billy Blanks says, Tae-Bo is the way. No messy
pills to buy, no unattractive machines, no Psychic Friends. What an
infomercial.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the tapes have reached almost $80 million, according to
an executive in the infomercial industry, and made Blanks a
millionaire many times over since the 30-minute advertisement began
saturation broadcasts last August and Blanks made a weeklong
appearance from the Bahamas on ``Oprah Winfrey.'' He also received
a reported $1.5 million advance for an exercise book from Bantam
Books.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have acquired a book,'' said Stuart Applebaum, a spokesman
for Random House, of which Bantam is a division. ``The price is
speculative.''
</P>
<P>
   Money like this attracts imitators. A lawyer for Blanks, Jan
Yoss, said she sends an average of 60 cease-and-desist letters a
week to gyms and health clubs that are using the name Tae-Bo
without paying a licensing fee. Blanks took out a trademark on the
name in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Legal claims are also flying around Tae-Bo, including a suit
joined by the former boxing champion Sugar Ray Leonard, who says
his name was used without permission in the infomercial. A lawyer
for the advertisement's producer has declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Tae-Bo-ish classes like Tae-Box or Cardio Tai Box or Cardio
Kickbox can be found at a gym near you, although you will have to
fight to get into them. ``I have never seen anything like this,''
Felicia Bessen, group fitness manager at the Equinox gym, said.
``That infomercial really struck some chord. I've got 100 people
showing up for Gotham Box, and I've got every instructor in town
calling to say they can teach Tae-Bo.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Perry, aerobics director of the Newport County YMCA in
Newport, R.I., said: ``The crowds! It's like a Dead concert!'' Ms.
Perry has named her class Tae-Box. She says that people are so
caught up that they show a Pavlovian eagerness at workouts. ``You
count to eight,'' she said, ``and people start sweating right away.
And then you make them count and you're like, `This is a piece of
cake!' We had all this complicated choreography, and now all you
have to do is stand there and count to eight.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A friend of mine says that Tae-Bo is the macarena of exercise:
irresistible moves with a beat that anyone can do and look sort of
OK. Men and women, young and old, all ``get'' Tae-Bo, because a
punch is an instinctive move.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about yoga, by contrast, is instinctive. (You remember
yoga, don't you? The ``inner'' workout?) Yoga is weird and painful
and elitist; it made you feel like you weren't quite a member of
the club. And that awful feeling of being left out meant that you
weren't primed to receive the mystical yummies that yoga was
hawking. Besides, unless you were writhing around with all your
pierced buddies down at Jivamukit on Lafayette Street in Manhattan,
yoga was boring.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps oneness is out. In any case, the mild aggression of
Tae-Bo feels like a welcome palate cleanser.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Billy Blanks' publicity agent, Julieann
Hartman, and manager, Jeffrey Greenfield, were hovering outside a
television studio in Los Angeles while Blanks was inside being
taped for an appearance on the Howie Mandel talk show. They passed
Ms. Hartman's cell phone back and forth as they spoke to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy; I'm getting 60, 80 calls an hour,'' said Ms.
Hartman, who used to work for ``Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenfield said: ``What we are branding is not Tae-Bo, it's
Billy Blanks. And Tae-Bo is the vessel we're using to get his
message across.''
</P>
<P>
   And that message is?
</P>
<P>
   ``That is that you can change yourself from the inside out and
make yourself a better person,'' Greenfield said. ``We've got big
plans: Tae-Bo for kids, Tae-Bo for couples, combat Tae-Bo. And then
there's clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanks has a mawkish and compendious news release _ ``the Billy
Blanks story'' _ that describes his rise from ``abject poverty'' as
one of 15 children in Erie, Pa., to becoming a seven-time world
karate champion. He is married to his childhood sweetheart, Gayle,
and they have two grown children, Shellie and Billy Jr., both of
whom teach in his studio.
</P>
<P>
   He developed Tae-Bo almost 20 years ago and started teaching a
version of it, called Karobics, in 1982. When he found out a decade
later later that someone else had trademarked Karobics, he changed
the name _ a blessing, because Karobics has no euphony.
</P>
<P>
   By telephone from his California dojo, Blanks said that he has
kept his feet on the ground despite the frenzy of the last six
months. As we spoke, he said the line for his next class had
wrapped around the building once or twice and was heading down
Ventura Boulevard in Sherman Oaks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's God's problem,'' he said. ``God got me into this, and He
can get me out. I've got people coming from all over the country to
see if I'm really the guy they see in the videos.
</P>
<P>
   ``Girl, I'm here at the studio,'' he told me. ``I'm the same
person I was yesterday. I'm never going to change because I know I
have a God bigger than anything I do. I've got to go. Have a
blessed day!''
</P>
<P>
   Before hanging up, Blanks said he wanted to build a dome under
which he could teach Tae-Bo to 1,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   I'd show up. Wouldn't you?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
