<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ST JOHN'S HAS A CELTICS LOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ The schedule says the Boston Celtics are in
New York Saturday afternoon. Don't believe it. Those are Pitino's
Impostors. The real Celtics will be on display right here in the
awesome Thompson-Boling Arena Saturday. They'll be playing Ohio
State for the NCAA South Regional championship and a berth in the
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The uniforms say ``St. John's,'' but what that bunch happens to
be are the Celtics. The 1964 Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The coach may be the all-time single-biggest Celtic
worshipper on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   The coach, of course, is Mike Jarvis, whose Celt- _ OK, St.
John's Red Storm _ take on Jim O'Brien's Ohio State Buckeyes. Mike
Jarvis hails from ``The Coast'' in Cambridge, and he grew up
idolizing the Bill Russell Celtics. His ultimate fantasy was to
coach the team, and it still may be. Until then, he will settle for
coaching a miniature Old Celtic team that features five
double-figure scorers, a high-octane fast-break attack, a clever
and selfless half-court offense, and a relentless defense.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't that sound like a team we used to know?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two people I still have to call today,'' Jarvis said
at a news conference Friday. ``The first is my brother Richard, who
would come up with the dollar and a half to take me to the Garden
for a balcony seat to watch the Celtics. The second is Red
Auerbach, who has become a real good friend of mine since my days
at George Washington. Why wouldn't I model my team after the
Celtics? They were the greatest winning institution in the history
of American sport, and the way it was done was with team, team,
team, a focus on defense, running when it was there, and setting up
intelligently when it wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``When God sent me Patrick Ewing, I tried to make him into Bill
Russell, and he was polite enough to wait until he got to college
before he said, `Who was Bill Russell?' But one of these days I
will get another Patrick Ewing at St. John's, and I will do the
same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   The one thing missing from the current St. John's equation is
the Bill Russell sort. The Red Storm have no pure center. Jarvis
goes with a front line of 6-foot-7-inch Ron Artest, 6-7 Tyrone
Grant (the nominal center), and 6-6 Lavor Postell. There is no
dominant center, no eraser, no control tower to trigger the fast
break. That aside, what's left is a T-E-A-M in the finest Old
Celtic tradition, and it just happens to be playing its best
basketball of the season.
</P>
<P>
   After being blown out by the University of Connecticut in the
Big East title game, St. John's has (Red) stormed its way into the
Final Eight, squashing Samford, Indiana, and Maryland by a total of
65 points. The Maryland game included a run of 23 unanswered
points, a figure that speaks to great expertise at both ends. The
only team playing better of late is that Krzyzewski bunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very fortunate and blessed to be in this position,''
acknowledges Jarvis. ``We hope our best is yet to come.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis took over a St. John's team that had underachieved for a
number of years despite the presence of two very high-profile
players in Felipe Lopez and Zendon Hamilton. The returning players
had gotten very tired of Fran Fraschilla. The team needed an
entirely new approach. It didn't take them long to discover that
Mike Jarvis was a very different sort of coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``What impressed me at our first meeting,'' says the thoughtful
Grant, ``was that he actually talked to us like men. Then he came
in with an open mind. He didn't care what had gone on before. He
gave everyone an opportunity to see if they could play.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone couldn't play, but about eight of them can and the
first five is as well-balanced a group as you could imagine. The
scoring totals range from Grant's 10.5 to guard Bootsy Thornton's
14.6. Precocious point guard Eric Barkley, who dazzled Maryland
with 24 points and 9 assists, is the clear floor leader, but
sophomore forward Artest, who blocked six Maryland shots, is only
14 behind Barkley (168-154) in the assist department. The
rebounding is another team effort, with Grant, Artest, and Postell
all averaging between six and eight a game.
</P>
<P>
   But the Old Celtics were never about stats, and neither is this
St. John's team. There are bigger teams and stronger teams, but few
more cohesive teams. They buy into anything the coach is selling,
and that's all any mentor can ask.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Jarvis is in the interesting position of having been
involved in each of the three distinct levels of competition and
expectation an NCAA Tournament team has to handle. He has had a
cannon-fodder team or two at Boston University, where the selection
itself was the reward. He has had a Cinderella hopeful in George
Washington, which won two games in 1993 to provide the school and
its followers with a nice little week and a half March thrill. And
now he has a team that dares dream of winning the national
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is different now,'' he says. ``When you barely get in, you
always dream the Impossible Dream, but you have got to be
realistic. At the next level, you hope you can get to a Sweet 16, a
Final Eight, or even a Final Four, but you start making your
vacation plans. Now you don't think of making your vacation plans
until later. The same schools with solid programs seem to be there
year after year with a chance to win, and St. John's hopes to be
one of those programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The future can wait. In the here and now, these New Celtics of
his are 40 minutes away from the Final Four. If they get there,
maybe Red will send them a piece of the old parquet for good luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
