<HEADLINE>
UNEMPLOYMENT RATE AT 29-YEAR LOW IN BAY STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The number of unemployed Massachusetts workers dropped
to a 29-year low in February in a sign that many more people are
reaping the gains of a robust local economy.
</P>
<P>
   Last month's 2.9 percent jobless rate, down from 3.2 percent in
January, was well below the nation's 4.4 percent rate, resulting in
the widest disparity between the state and national rates since the
two began to diverge four years ago, say analysts.
</P>
<P>
   The February decline was only the third time since March of 1970
that the rate dipped below 3 percent. The last instance was in July
of 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The number of unemployed in Massachusetts fell to 93,600 in
February, from 102,900 in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boom continues,'' commented Nicholas Perna, chief
economist at Fleet Financial Group. ``What a long way we have come
since 1992. The unemployment rate is down in the vicinity of 3
percent, which is remarkably low and well below the national
average. So, this is a great time to be looking for a job, to be
changing jobs, or to be getting back into the market after losing a
job.''
</P>
<P>
   New jobs were added in nearly every sector of the economy except
manufacturing. Massachusetts factories, hit by weaker exports to
Asia and other countries, shed 1,900 jobs in February.
</P>
<P>
   Since February 1998, the service sector has added 26,700 jobs,
or 2.4 percent. Real estate, finance and insurance jobs have
increased by 6,300 or 2.9 percent. Meanwhile, retail trade jobs
were up 10,500 or 1.9 percent over the year, with specialty stores
accounting for 4.2 percent of those gains.
</P>
<P>
   For employers, however, the lower jobless rate means competition
for skilled workers will likely intensify as Massachusetts
companies struggle to fill vacancies. ``We have the jobs, but we
are a high-cost state and housing is high cost, so there is a
serious impediment in terms of attracting people from other
states,'' remarked Fred Breimyer, chief economist at State Street
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   And although workers are having less trouble finding jobs,
analysts say wages have not risen markedly in response to the heavy
demand for labor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically, wages are flexible, and we tend to think they will
rise to meet the demand,'' said Nancy Kimelman, chief economist at
Thompson Financial Services. ``Instead, what we are hearing is that
companies simply cannot find qualified people. In many cases, they
are raising wages for the new people coming in, but not for those
who are already there.''
</P>
<P>
   How long will the economic boom continue? Forecasters are
predicting positive economic growth through 1999, but there are
indications the momentum will begin to lessen by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, companies will continue to face difficulties hiring and
that could put some constraints on their ability to expand,'' noted
Breimeyer. ``Secondly, the Federal Reserve may raise interest rates
as a means of slowing inflation, and third, there could still be
some negative impact from the situation globally.''
</P>
<P>
   The global trade crisis may create problems in coming months
because many Asian countries are facing more serious economic
problems than previously anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, our economy is humming along,'' said Yolanda
Kodrzycki, an economist and assistant vice president at the Federal
Reserve Bank of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a high degree of consumer confidence, which means
people are willing to spend,'' she said. ``Increased spending is
showing up in the retail area, and in housing construction. So, I
would expect the unemployment rate here in Massachusetts to remain
quite low.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1822EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7146 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-POSSESSIONS-REVIEW     03-19 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-POSSESSIONS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`EARTHLY POSSESSIONS': MIDDLE AGE CRAZY, AND READY TO SHOW IT 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are for
New York area. Check local listings.) 
(lh) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Watching Susan Sarandon loosen up is always fun. Her classic
transformation was, of course, eight years ago in ``Thelma and
Louise.'' On the road, she traded hair spray, high-collared blouses
and ladylike repression for jeans, a ponytail and a spree of
feminist retaliation and almost justifiable crime, her windburned
but glowing-with-freedom face to the sun. Ms. Sarandon's
metamorphosis Saturday night on the HBO film ``Earthly
Possessions'' isn't nearly so satisfying, but it has its own charm.
Don't let the fact that she seems to be playing her early scenes as
Edith Bunker throw you; the movie gets much better.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sarandon's character, Charlotte Emory, makes her entrance in
a raincoat and sensible shoes, standing in line at her hometown
bank mumbling to herself that she used to know everyone in town.
Her plan is to withdraw all the money from her account and leave
her husband, a minister of minimal emotions who has been taking her
for granted for years. But Charlotte is not an adventurous woman;
in early middle age, she has yet to have the courage to learn how
to drive a car.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan becomes irrelevant when a bank robber grabs her, holds
a gun to her head and takes her hostage. It's clear that he is not
an accomplished criminal when he takes only the $300 that one
teller had in her hands and makes his getaway in a bus. Luckily for
Charlotte, he is the young, cute and misguided Jake Sims (Stephen
Dorff), and the balance of power in their relationship constantly
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   It begins when Charlotte insists on getting off the parked bus
because she's claustrophobic. She also loses a little respect for
Jake when he admits he doesn't know how to hot-wire a car. But
things really start to get interesting when the romantic attraction
between criminal and hostage speaks its name.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign is the slightly seductive way Charlotte says
about her age: ``Anyway, it doesn't matter. It's just a number. It
doesn't mean anything.'' And the next thing you know, she and Jake
are both drunk on fruity cocktails with funny names, slow dancing
and taking a cheap hotel room for the night. Even then, things
don't take exactly the course you might expect. Later, things are
complicated by Jake's bimboish, pregnant 17-year-old girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte is either inconsistent or complex. ``It's just that
this is my very first time outside of Clarion,'' she tells Jake as
the bus pulls away from the depot in her hometown. But she's
quickly declaring that the town they've traveled to is dirty and
that the photograph of her on the television news programs is
horribly unflattering. And she's not too demure to make flirtatious
comments like, ``Well, you ARE the guy with the gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte is, after all, an Anne Tyler character. And Ms.
Tyler's heroines have been know to make bold moves of independence
when the people around them least expect it. Some have also been
known to go home at the end, happier and wiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earthly Possessions,'' directed by James Lapine and adapted by
Steven Rogers, is full of verbal and physical humor. One of the
finest moments is Charlotte standing beside the table at the dance
hall patiently, waiting for Jake to pull out her chair for her. The
film's strength is that just when the laughs are coming strong, a
character will say something to reverse the tone completely (like
``Don't make me hurt you, Charlotte'' or Charlotte's line to Jake,
spoken somberly, ``I don't want to play anymore''). Are the people
we care about really on our side, or are loyalties always a matter
of changing circumstance? &UR;  &LR; Is life really light comedy or tense
drama? In the world as seen through ``Earthly Possessions,'' it's
never completely clear until the end.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `EARTHLY POSSESSIONS'
</P>
<P>
   8 p.m. ET Saturday on HBO
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greisman and Marykay Powell, executive producers; Tony Mark
and Sue Jett, producers; script by Steven Rogers, based on the
novel by Anne Tyler; James Lapine, director. Produced by Rastar
Productions.
</P>
<P>
   With: Susan Sarandon (Charlotte Emory), Stephen Dorff (Jake
Simms Jr.), Elisabeth Moss (Mindy Calendar), Jay O. Sanders (Zack
Emory), Alan Pottinger (Scotty Jamison) and John Christopher Jones
(Marvel Hodge).
</P>
</TEXT>
