<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Saturday, March 20. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ With NATO air strikes looming,
President Clinton on Friday spelled out the need for risky American
military action in Kosovo if Serbian leaders are bent on
aggression. The allied nations must act, he said, because
``hesitation is a license to kill.'' (Summary wires). By John M.
Broder.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Washington) _ News from President Clinton's news
conference Friday afternoon. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-MONEY (Washington) _ President Clinton's impeachment
appears to have a silver lining _ or at least a green one. Campaign
donations to Democratic coffers have soared, with much of the
giving inspired by the president himself as he crisscrosses the
country, blaming Republicans for trying to bring him down and
thanking his supporters for sticking by him. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   LIBYA-MANDELA (United Nations) _ Nelson Mandela, in Libya, says
the Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi has promised in a letter to the
United Nations to hand over the suspects accused of the bombing
over Lockerbie, Scotland, by April 6. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SAUDI-RECESSION (Jidda, Saudi Arabia) _ Faced with a recession,
soaring unemployment and declining incomes, Saudi Arabia is
undergoing a transformation, and what once seemed inconceivable is
slowly becoming the order of the day. The government, famous for
free health and education programs and lavish military spending,
and for never collecting a nickel's worth of taxes, has announced
deep spending cuts concentrated in defense and security, even
putting on hold a $1.7 billion arms deal. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   CUNY-REPORT (New York) _ Two years ago, Gov. George Pataki gave
the trustees of the chronically troubled City University of New
York a new chairwoman with a mandate to steer the university in a
new direction. Less than five months later, the trustees got a
golden chance to carry out that mandate when Chancellor W. Ann
Reynolds resigned after repeated attacks from the board. But in the
20 months since, the opening the trustees created has turned into a
yawning gulf. Not only has the board failed to find a permanent
chancellor. It is not even interviewing candidates, the search
process having broken down last summer. And other top executives at
the university have drifted away one by one. By Karen W. Arenson.
</P>
</TEXT>
