<HEADER>
A7154 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOBACCO-LAWYER-TEXAS-     03-19 0522
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-LAWYER-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SETS DATE FOR LAWYER SEEKING MILLIONS FROM WORK ON TOBACCO
DEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A Houston lawyer who tentatively was awarded
$260 million for advising the state in its multibillion-dollar
tobacco settlement has been ordered to appear before a federal
judge to defend the fee.
</P>
<P>
   Marc D. Murr this week was instructed to appear May 6 in
Texarkana before U.S. District Judge David Folsom to ``show cause''
why his fee award should not be nullified.
</P>
<P>
   A national arbitration panel had awarded Murr only $1 million,
but &UR;  &LR; Murr has asserted he's due far more under a state arbitration
panel decision that was based on his outside-counsel contracts with
then-Attorney General Dan Morales.
</P>
<P>
   Some state legislators and other attorneys involved in the
tobacco negotiations have argued for months that Murr's role was an
obscure one not worth a quarter of a billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Also fighting that claim is Morales' Republican successor,
Attorney General John Cornyn, who last month asked Folsom to
dismiss Murr's claim.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom indicated that he could negate the larger fee
recommendation because of Murr's ``failure to comply'' with a
January 1998 court ruling in which the judge said the ultimate
award had to be approved by representatives of the state, Murr and
the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``This court has never selected any panel member for such an
arbitration,'' Folsom said in his order, dated Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   By inference, the judge said the fee was worked out only by
representatives of Murr and his longtime friend Morales, who
engineered the $17 billion settlement with tobacco companies to
recoup state expenses for decades of smoking-related health care.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 7, 1998, the state arbitration panel agreed to a fee
equalling 1.5 percent of the settlement, the court said. But if
Murr ``contends such an award is binding against the state of
Texas,'' he'll have to prove he complied with Folsom's order 14
months ago mandating that the court be represented on the panel.
</P>
<P>
   Murr has not formally asked Folsom to enforce the state panel's
decision, but state attorneys have said they want to preclude that
from happening by getting the claim dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   In asking Folsom to dismiss the claim, Cornyn contends that Murr
should petition the Legislature for any award above the $1 million
recommended by the national arbitration panel. That panel reviewed
all attorneys' fees and awarded $3.3 billion to five other private
lawyers who developed the case for Morales and $1 million to Murr.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Cornyn said, ``I am encouraged that Judge Folsom has
ordered Mr. Murr to `show cause' why his claim of $260 million in
taxpayers' money should not be thrown out.''
</P>
<P>
   Murr did not return phone messages left Friday at his Houston
office.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Schenkkan, an attorney for Texas lawmakers who intervened
in the case to fight the higher fee, said the judge ``can throw the
claim completely out, and I assume, in addition, he can order
sanctions.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
