<P>
   KOSOVO-TALKS (Paris) _ International monitors were ordered to
pull out of Kosovo, and Western embassies ordered their
nonessential staff to leave Yugoslavia after peace talks here
collapsed and NATO renewed threats to bomb unless President
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia accepts a peace plan for Kosovo.
By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Washington) _ U.S. officials watch as the military
situation unfolds in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CLINTON (Washington) _ President Clinton urges Congress
to give bipartisan support for NATO air strikes against Yugoslav
Serbs. (Summary from wires.) By John Broder.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES (Srbica, Yugoslavia) _ There are thousands of
refugees on the move in Kosovo. A spokesman for the United Nations
High Commission for Refugees estimated some 20,000 have been
displaced since Sunday, the bulk of them in the mountain range just
northwest of the capital Pristina. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
