<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-watch-PA </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  pennsylvania votechart
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON WATCH VOTE CHART Questions regarding this
transmission should be directed to 202-628-3100, ext. 224.
WASHINGTON, March 19 -- The following chart shows how senators and
representatives voted on key bills and amendments within the last
week. A ``Y'' means the member voted for the measure; an ``N''
means the member voted against the measure; a ``?'' means the
member did not vote; and a ``P'' means the member voted
``present.''
</P>
<P>
   SENATE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: S. MISSILE
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Wednesday approved, 97-3, a bill to deploy an
anti-missile defense system for the United States. Supporters said
that the defense system is important to national security and would
also create jobs. Opponents said that the U.S. should be looking
for ways to stop the spread of existing weapons of mass destruction
rather than spending billions of dollars on unproven defense
systems. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: CHINA
</P>
<P>
   The Senate on Thursday voted 69-30 to table, or set aside, a
proposal that would have required congressional approval before the
United States could support admitting China into the World Trade
Organization. Supporters of the tabled motion said that Congress
needs to be involved in the decision in order to prevent any
``hasty deals'' with China. The bill's opponents said that the U.S.
economy will benefit greatly by China's admittance, and that the
proposal is unnecessary. A ``yes'' vote favors tabling the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2
</P>
<P>
   --- ---
</P>
<P>
   SANTORUM (R-PA) Y N
</P>
<P>
   SPECTER (R-PA) Y N
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE VOTES:
</P>
<P>
   1) BILL NUMBER: PALESTINE
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 380-24, a resolution asking
President Clinton to oppose any Palestinian unilateral declaration
of independence. Supporters said that a declaration of statehood
would be a violation of the Oslo Accords, which outlined a
timetable for a peace settlement between Israel and Palestine.
Opponents said that the resolution is unnecessary since the Clinton
administration has already stated its opposition to a Palestinian
declaration of independence. A ``yes'' vote favors the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   2) BILL NUMBER: STEEL
</P>
<P>
   The House on Wednesday approved, 289-141, a bill to limit the
amount of steel imported into the United States. The bill would
also impose a steel notification and monitoring program on all
steel imports. Supporters said the measure is needed because the
Clinton administration has not taken the proper measures to address
the ``illegal dumping'' of foreign steel into the U.S. Opponents
said the bill is too radical and would interfere with free trade. A
``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   3) BILL NUMBER: H. MISSILE
</P>
<P>
   The House on Thursday approved, 317-105, a bill to deploy an
anti-missile defense system for the United States. Although it does
not appropriate funding, the bill states that the defense system
against ballistic missile attacks should be deployed ``as soon as
technologically possible.'' Supporters said that all Americans
should be protected in case of a ballistic missile attack.
Opponents said that the defense system would not ensure protection
of the U.S., and would negatively affect efforts to remove Russia's
nuclear weapons. A ``yes'' vote favors the bill.
</P>
<P>
   VOTE : 1 2 3
</P>
<P>
   --- --- ---
</P>
<P>
   BORSKI (D-PA) Y Y Y
</P>
