<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, March 20 sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will bubble up near the central Gulf
Coast Saturday as a weakening but still formidable disturbance taps
moisture from the Gulf of Mexico. Moderate to heavy rains are
possible, particularly across southern parts of Louisiana and
Mississippi. Showers and a few storms also will eventually develop
across southern sections of Alabama and Georgia. On the northern
flank of the system, broken areas of generally lighter rains will
spread slowly but inexorably from the lower Mississippi Valley
toward the southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   With Gulf moisture being monopolized by the disturbance, only
broken areas of light rain or light snow will develop over the
upper Middle West in conjunction with a cold front plunging
southeastward from Canada. Meanwhile, milder air will build into
the eastern Great Lakes region ahead of the front, though
northwesterly winds off the chilly waters of Lake Erie and Lake
Ontario will limit any warm-up in lakeshore communities.
</P>
<P>
   Brisk winds from the northwest will average 15 to 25 mph along
the Northeast Seaboard Saturday as the stirring of the lower
atmosphere by abundant sunshine allows momentum from fairly strong
winds aloft to mix toward the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and a few thunderstorms will accompany a cold,
upper-level low pressure system from California into Nevada and
southern Idaho. Small hail could accompany a few of the
thunderstorms as they pivot eastward over central California.
Moderate snows will fall over the Sierra Nevada. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Spring Ahead &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The astronomical beginning of spring occurs Saturday at 8:46
p.m. EST, when the direct noon rays of the sun strike the equator
over the central Pacific. The distinction between the astronomical
and the meteorological start of spring is one of perspective. Many
meteorologists subscribe to March 1 as the beginning of spring,
signifying the three-month transition between the three coldest
months and the three warmest months, on average. Regardless of
which definition is used, winter weather can intrude on spring.
Incorrigible winter never adheres to the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1846EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
