<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7200 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS &LR;      03-19 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MAKES CASE OF ACTION AGAINST SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Friday staunchly defended
preparations for U.S. involvement in the Serbian province of
Kosovo, warning that the killing of women and children had
``crossed the threshold'' for military action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would hate to think that we would have to see any more
little children die before we do what is right,'' Clinton said at
his first full-fledged press conference in nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   The president acknowledged that NATO aerial attacks against
Serbian military positions in and around the Kosovo province would
endanger American pilots, saying, ``U.S. and other NATO pilots will
be put in harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, frustrated international mediators adjourned
the Kosovo peace talks and said they would not resume unless the
Serbs decide to accept the accord, which was signed by ethnic
Albanian leaders but rebuffed by President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia, which is dominated by Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Although Clinton did not impose a signing deadline on the Serbs,
he implied that possible military intervention was near, saying
that ``hesitation leads to death'' in the volatile region of
southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my view, Serbian leaders, who have authorized the killing
of women and children, have already crossed the threshold needed
for NATO action,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting between Serbian forces and ethnic Albanians in Kosovo
has claimed more than 2,000 lives in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Kosovo once enjoyed relative autonomy as a province of Serbia.
But Milosevic has gradually stripped away self rule, triggering a
rebellion in Kosovo last year that has led to violence between
rebels and Serbian forces, including recent mass killings of
civilians that are blamed on Serbians.
</P>
<P>
   About 90 percent of Kosovo's 2.2 million people are ethnic
Albanians, and most favor independence.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton described Kosovo as primarily a ``humanitarian
crisis,'' he said the fighting in the province threatened to engulf
the entire region by igniting ancient animosities in countries such
as Greece and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, the president met with congressional leaders
to lay out his case for possible U.S.-led intervention involving
other members of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from the meeting, Senate Armed Services Committee
Chairman John Warner, R-Va., said, ``I think the meeting added
momentum toward the Senate supporting the president and NATO in
this action.''
</P>
<P>
   Before meeting with Clinton, Senate leaders delayed until Monday
legislation that could block money for any U.S. military
involvement in the Serbian province without prior congressional
approval.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered five
Navy jet fighters to join the American fleet of more 200 warplanes
in the region.
</P>
<P>
   During his press conference, the president also addressed the
mushrooming scandal involving China's alleged theft of nuclear
weapons technology from a federal laboratory and allegations of lax
security measures by the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that we in the White House have done everything
we could have done,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Wen Ho Lee, a Taiwan-born American engineer
working at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico, was
fired after allegations arose that he helped China learn the design
of an advanced nuclear warhead.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a crime was committed, anybody who committed it should be
punished,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   But the president cautioned that his advisers had not yet
determined conclusively that any espionage had occurred. ``Nobody
has reported that to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the president ordered a review of security at U.S.
nuclear labs. The review will be undertaken by the president's
Foreign Intelligence Advisory Board, a bipartisan and independent
panel headed by former Sen. Warren Rudman, R-N.H. The review is
expected to take 60 days.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson has announced
plans for tightened security at the laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., chairman of the
Senate Intelligence Committee, complained that security at Los
Alamos and at other facilities has been ``too loose too long.''
</P>
<P>
   The vice chairman of the committee, Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb.,
also was critical, saying of security measures, ``I no longer have
confidence we are doing it right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
