<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7213 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-600&AMP;     03-19 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTERN PERSONNEL ORDERED OUT OF YUGOSLAVIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Great Britain, France, Germany, Italy)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(Eds: See also KOSOVO-CLINTON, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-REFUGEES) 
(mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ International monitors were ordered Friday to pull out
of Kosovo, and Western embassies ordered their nonessential staff
to leave Yugoslavia after peace talks here collapsed and NATO
renewed threats to bomb unless President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia accepted a peace plan for Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is likely to be as long and as difficult as President
Milosevic wants to make it,'' warned Gen. Wesley Clark, the
alliance's supreme commander, at his headquarters in Belgium on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton called in congressional leaders
for a briefing on the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials in Brussels said that no decision on bombing
would be made until all 1,400 cease-fire monitors were safely out.
They also said it looked unlikely that an order to bomb would come
on Sunday unless events on the ground forced NATO's hand.
</P>
<P>
   France and Britain ended the peace talks here after Serbian
delegates repeated earlier objections to accords providing autonomy
for Kosovo and 28,000 NATO peacekeepers to enforce the agreement.
Representatives of the ethnic Albanian majority in Kosovo signed
the accords, worked out in Rambouillet castle near here last month,
on Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   With the Serbs refusing even to talk about peacekeeping
arrangements, there was no point in continuing the talks, a
statement Friday morning by the French and British foreign
ministers said. They agreed to reconvene negotiations only when the
Serbs had changed their minds and agreed to accept the accords too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rambouillet accords are the only peaceful solution to the
Kosovo problem,'' the statement by the French foreign minister,
Hubert Vedrine, and the British foreign secretary, Robin Cook,
said. ``Far from seizing this opportunity, the Yugoslav delegation
has tried to unravel the Rambouillet accords.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will immediately engage in consultations with our partners
and allies to be ready to act,'' they said. ``We solemnly warn the
authorities in Belgrade against any military offensive on the
ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark told reporters that there were between 14,000 and 16,000
heavily armed Serbian police in Kosovo; 17,000 to 20,000 Yugoslav
army troops, and another 5,000 to 10,000 troops just outside the
borders, all with hundreds of tanks, armored vehicles and artillery
pieces.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian forces could pose a threat not only to the civilians
in Kosovo but also to the monitors there and to the 10,000 NATO
troops gathered in nearby Macedonia to lead the peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   A separate European NATO force under French command is prepared
to go in from Macedonia and pluck out the monitors if the Serbs try
to keep them from leaving. The monitors, part of a cease-fire
mission by the Organization for Security and Co-operation in
Europe, were ordered Friday by the Norwegian foreign minister, the
organization's chairman, to start leaving by road for Macedonia on
Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far the local Yugoslav army and political authorities have
been very cooperative,'' Melissa Fleming, a spokesperson for the
organization in Vienna, Austria, said Friday night. ``If there is
no obstruction, the observers could all be in Macedonia by Saturday
afternoon,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That would leave the decision to bomb in the hands of NATO's
secretary-general, Javier Solana of Spain. The allies gave him
authority at the end of January to bomb Serbian targets and
Yugoslav military installations if that was what it took to get
Milosevic to accept the agreement and the peacekeepers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ten years ago, when he was president of Serbia, Milosevic
abrogated autonomy for Kosovo province, which would remain a part
of Yugoslavia under the accord the Serbs rejected, at least for a
three-year transition period.
</P>
<P>
   Solana has said he would consult with leaders of the United
States, Britain, France, Germany, Italy and Russia, the six
countries that had convened the negotiations here, and with other
allies before he decides what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has always been opposed to any bombing in Serbia, and it
is possible that either Russia or some Western country may want to
try to make one more run at Milosevic in Belgrade before the planes
are launched.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's military authorities have long been planning two
separate waves of air strikes aimed at forcing a change in the
Serbian position.
</P>
<P>
   The first wave, a short, sharp strike that could come within
hours of an order from Solana to Clark, the allied military
commander, would launch warplanes including B-52s and pilotless
cruise missiles from U.S. Navy ships in the Adriatic Sea to strike
selected Serbian military targets.
</P>
<P>
   The second wave, a phased set of attacks against air defense
systems throughout Yugoslav territory in Serbia and Montenegro,
would be aimed at rendering those defenses harmless in case the
allies decide later to continue bombing other targets.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have never wanted, as one French policy-maker put it,
to become the air force of the Kosovo Liberation Army, which wanted
independence for the province but settled for autonomy for the
three-year transition period when they signed the accord.
</P>
<P>
   But Milosevic has changed the situation on the ground in Kosovo
in recent weeks, violating earlier pledges to reduce his police and
military forces in the province and moving in tens of thousands of
soldiers and special police.
</P>
<P>
   A military offensive by those forces now, or an attempt to keep
the unarmed international observers from leaving, would have ``the
gravest consequences,'' Vedrine and Cook warned Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
   William Walker, the American diplomat leading the OSCE observer
missions, said Friday, ``The fact that we pull out does not mean
there are not eyes and ears telling the world what is happening.''
He added, ``The world will know if anyone uses force.''
</P>
<P>
   About 22 percent of the 2 million people of Kosovo, 443,000
people, have been driven from their homes since Milosevic started
attacking the rebels a year ago, the U.N. High Commission for
Refugees said Friday. About 90 percent of the population in Kosovo
is ethnic Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   All the Western allies say they would prefer capitulation by
Milosevic over going ahead with air strikes, but even France,
usually the most reluctant to use force, sounds tough this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Milosevic bears the entire responsibility for the
situation and for its consequences,'' French President Jacques
Chirac said Friday after a meeting with the German chancellor,
Gerhard Schroeder, who agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   But if bombs do start to fall on Kosovo or even on Belgrade in
coming days, one consequence will be the end of the allies'
painstaking efforts to keep Russia with them on getting Milosevic
to come around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
