s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-AR     03-19 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAITING FOR SMALL CAPS? BRING A GOOD BOOK 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21)  
 (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Contemporary investors seem to have condemned to the mists of
time the lessons of ``Small is Beautiful,'' the 1973 book by the
late E.F. Schumacher that extolled the benefits of all things
micro. Based on recent history, big is best is now the philosophy
of choice.
</P>
<P>
   Schumacher had a point. It used to be that earnings at small
companies grew more rapidly than their large-capitalization
cousins. Over time, that meant their stock prices tended to
outperform the behemoths that dwell in averages like the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   But from 1993 through 1998, small-cap stocks didn't do nearly as
well as large caps. And nothing has changed this year: Through
Friday, the Russell 2000 index, a small-stock benchmark, was down 6
percent; the S&AMP;P 500 was up 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These are not favorable developments for those who follow this
asset class. Claudia E. Mott, director of small-cap research at
Prudential Securities, took some time last week to talk about when
small might again be beautiful. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)At the end of last year, you were quite optimistic
about a rally in small-cap stocks. That hasn't happened. What went
wrong?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. During the fourth quarter of last year, I thought we would
have a rally that would last from six months to a year. It lasted
six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Two major things happened. Small-company earnings, which had
been very good relative to big caps earlier in the year, started to
fall apart and are now in a position of weakness vis-a-vis the
large caps.
</P>
<P>
   Second, in the fourth quarter, mutual funds flow data started to
turn negative. That set us back into a tough market, where a lot of
managers had to sell stock to deal with redemptions.
</P>
<P>
   According to my calculations, February may have been a record
redemption month for small-cap funds. So, I feel we are back to
square one again, unfortunately. Right now, there is no convincing
reason to buy small caps. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What is going to turn things around for small caps?
Don't they look like screaming buys compared with big-cap
stocks?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I really don't know what will turn this, and I'm running out
of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the normal things we look at just aren't working:
valuations, good earnings growth, a strong dollar and cuts in the
capital gains rate and the discount rate. All of those things
should tend to generate a fairly substantial rally.
</P>
<P>
   That said, I don't think the case for small-cap stocks is done.
Just when you think they are all washed up is probably the time
when things will turn around. I do know it won't take much money to
get it started. But I don't know what will trigger it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)There a lot of serious folks who believe that a
correction in big-cap valuations is long overdue. If that happens,
will a sharp slide in big-cap stocks bury the small caps?(end
italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. During most correction periods, the small-cap market does not
tend to be a shining star. But in the correction that took place
between 1976 and 1978, when the last Nifty 50 unraveled, the
small-cap market rallied about 25 percent when the large caps were
down about 11.5 percent. If lightning strikes twice, perhaps we
don't have to get totally annihilated if the large-cap market pulls
back. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What sort of tactics are managers of small-cap
mutual funds employing to deal with this downturn?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. They may be moving some money into cash, but using cash as a
defensive mechanism is not a good idea because it is not what these
managers were hired to do. Also, they are moving up into somewhat
bigger stocks with capitalizations of around $1 billion, compared
with a stock with a market cap of $300 million, because the
liquidity is better.
</P>
<P>
   But I haven't seen a lot of funds closing down. That issue is
more applicable to institutions like pension funds. Some have given
up on the sector, but not in a wholesale fashion. If you started to
see that, you would have had a much harder market. But keeping the
temperature of the institutional side of the business is one of the
things we are trying to keep a handle on. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)There must be companies and industries within the
small-cap universe that you like.(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I can't talk about specific companies. But we look at a model
combining valuation with earnings momentum. Based on those
criteria, we like home building, building materials, savings and
loans, computer software and peripherals and trucking companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)At base, what is the case for small caps?(end
italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, history is what history is. Perhaps there are some
seasonal patterns to when small caps do well, but you need them for
diversification. Small caps represent almost 85 percent of the
listed companies on the three major exchanges.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that concerns me is that a lot of people will get left
behind when this group comes back, because they chose to get out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
