<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS IT'S `VERY IMPORTANT' TO TELL THE TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton, confronted with a question at
his news conference Friday on what he thought his legacy on lying
will be, said young people should learn from his experience that
``there are consequences'' when a president doesn't tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   At his first solo press conference in 11 months, Clinton was
asked the question in the context of his many denials last year
that he had had an affair with former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky. ``What do you think your legacy will be about lying?''
asked Jan Smith of Fox News. ``And how important do you think it is
to tell the truth, especially under oath?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, looking solemn, replied, ``I think it's very important.
And I think that what young people will learn from my experience is
that even presidents have to do that, and that there are
consequences when you don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet he defended his record, adding, ``But I also think that
there will be a box score, and there will be that one negative. And
then there will be the hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of times
when the record will show that I did not abuse my authority as
president, that I was truthful with the American people, and scores
and scores of allegations were made against me and widely
publicized without any regard to whether they were true or not.
Most of them have already been actually proved false.''
</P>
<P>
   The president concluded, ``So I would hope that there would be a
higher regard for truth-telling by all people in public life and
all those who report on it.''
</P>
<P>
   His response was the most extensive answer he has given to the
question of what lessons he learned from the year-long impeachment
drama that ended Feb. 12 with his acquittal in the Senate on
charges of perjury and obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   During that time he dropped many of his denials and admitted
that he had given misleading answers as well as responses that were
not helpful to Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr and the legal team
representing Paula Jones in her now-settled sexual harassment
lawsuit. But he insisted he had not lied under oath, even when he
denied having a sexual relationship with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton dodged an opportunity to reflect how he was treated
during the impeachment process and whether he felt any lingering
resentment over it. ``Anything I say or do, or any time I spend ...
on that will detract from my ability to be an effective
president,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he declined to address a question about an allegation
by nursing home owner Juanita Broaddrick of Van Buren, Ark., that
Clinton raped her in a Little Rock hotel room in 1978 when he was
state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   David Kendall, an attorney for Clinton, denied the allegation in
a statement last month. ``He speaks for me,'' Clinton said Friday.
``I think he spoke quite clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about books by former White House aide George
Stephanopoulos and political consultant Dick Morris that are
critical of Clinton, the president evoked some chuckling when he
said he had read neither one. But he did say that ``the
overwhelming majority'' of people working in his administration had
been loyal to him and that an unnamed scholar remarked to him that
his was the most loyal cabinet since the presidency of Thomas
Jefferson.
</P>
<P>
   On the question of whether First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton
will run for the U.S. Senate from New York, Clinton said, ``I
literally don't have a clue.'' He added that he thought she
``really would be a terrific senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said that last year, before Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y., announced he would not seek reelection, the first
lady had talked to Clinton about moving to New York after they
leave the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan's announcement last November set off speculation about
a Hillary Clinton candidacy. Mrs. Clinton was ``just immensely
flattered'' by such talk, Clinton said. ``But I don't have any idea
what she is going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about progress in repairing their relationship in the wake
of the Lewinsky scandal, Clinton said he and Mrs. Clinton are
``working hard, and we love each other very much. And we're working
at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended Vice President Al Gore against criticism
directed at suggestions by Gore that he invented the Internet and
had grown up plowing farm fields in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Gore had fought in Congress for federal funds to
aid development of the Internet and had worked on his family's farm
as a boy. He added that Gore ``is, by nature, a reticent person
when it comes to talking about his life and his background.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said he would ``be happy to toot his (Gore's) horn
in terms of the years that we've worked together,'' praising Gore's
role in ``all the good things that have happened in this
administration.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
