<SLUG> BC-DOW-RECORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW FLIRTS WITH RECORD LEVEL AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After zipping past the 10,000 milestone Friday morning, the
stock market floated down the rest of the day due to disappointing
news about IBM Corp.'s profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It did not happen. It tried desperately'' to remain above the
10,000 level, said James Weiss, deputy head of stock investing for
State Street Research &AMP; Management Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, the Dow Jones industrial stock average
was down 94.07, or less than 1 percent, finishing an historic week
at 9903.55 after breaking the 10,000 barrier on Tuesday for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Investors on Wall Street and at their computers in remote
locations watched the Dow Friday, and analysts said that the
market's inability to get past 10,000 was one measure of the strong
psychological factors driving stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``There either seem to be some gremlins in the closet that chase
the stock market down when it hits 10,000, or there are legitimate
sellers out there that have targeted a certain level as a sell
point,'' said Ned Riley, BankBoston Corp.'s chief investment
officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``These investors are missing the true concept of investing,''
Riley added. The market's level ``shouldn't dictate how people are
investing long-term monies.''
</P>
<P>
   A 9 1/16 plunge in the shares of IBM and dozens of smaller
technology companies deflated the market after Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter reduced its expectations for Big Blue's stock this year to
195, from 210, due to concerns about a slowdown in computer sales.
IBM closed at 168 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq index declined 41.47 points, or 1.68
percent, and finished the day at 2421.49. The broad Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index declined 17.26 points, closing at 1299.29.
</P>
<P>
   Friday also marked the quarterly ``triple witching'' phenomenon.
Triple witching is the quarterly expiration of contracts on stock
options, index options, and index futures. It typically adds to the
market's volatility as portfolio managers rush to buy or sell
stocks to square their positions. Analysts said that managers
seemed to be selling the market short to protect their portfolios,
a move that also dragged the market down.
</P>
<P>
   Following the Dow's lead, stock markets around the world reacted
favorably to a US rally on Thursday, when the US index of 30 stocks
gained 118 points.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's Nikkei index soared 4.2 higher to its best finish since
July 31. Germany's DAX index closed 1.7 percent higher, Britain's
FT-SE 100 rose 0.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 rose 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service material was used to prepare this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
