<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7257 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-BOS &LR;      03-19 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEST GIRDS FOR KOSOVO ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST _ A Western group Friday ordered its 1,400 human rights
monitors out of the troubled province of Kosovo Friday, a move that
will leave the warring Serbs and Albanians unwatched and will
heighten the possibility of a long-threatened NATO strike on Serb
targets.
</P>
<P>
   After the Serbs failed to join the ethnic Albanians in signing a
Western-brokered peace pact, President Clinton met with US
congressional leaders and made his most direct call for action to
stop the yearlong conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake; if we and our allies do not have the will to
act, there will be more massacres,'' Clinton said. ``In dealing
with aggressors in the Balkans, hesitation is a license to kill.
But action and resolve can stop armies and save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   American diplomats scurried out of the Yugoslav capital of
Belgrade Friday to Budapest. The 1,400 monitors for the
Organization on Security and Cooperation in Europe's verification
mission were set to take a convoy early Saturday south to
Macedonia. Belgium, Austria, Germany and Britain also urged their
nationals to leave Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am responsible for the safety of approximately 1,400
verifiers from many different countries in Kosovo,'' OSCE chairman
Knut Vollebaek told reporters in Oslo after announcing the order.
``I have no other choice in the present situation than to withdraw
the OSCE personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslavs, delivering a message through Greek diplomats,
said bluntly that if OSCE left, ``we would not be welcome back,'' a
high-ranking OSCE source said.
</P>
<P>
   OSCE staffers scrambled to pull their belongings together to be
ready to leave at 5 a.m., said Colonel Michael Philips, a military
aide to OSCE mission chief William Walker. ``We worried that our
belonging will be trashed'' at OSCE headquarters, he said. ``A lot
of people here are upset and crying and worried about their
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Western mediators officially dissolved the sputtering peace
talks in Paris Friday, saying the Serbs' unwavering refusal to sign
the pact made it useless to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no purpose in extending the talks any further,'' the
mediators said in a statement. Russia's foreign minister, Igor
Ivanov, said he disagreed with the OSCE pullout. Russia is a
traditional ally of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   A Contact Group of six Western nations has been trying to forge
a pact between the Serb-dominated government of Yugoslavia, inside
whose borders Kosovo lies, and the ethnic Albanians, who make up
about 90 percent of the territory.
</P>
<P>
   The Western-drafted pact, which would give broad autonomy to
Kosovo and severely limit Yugoslav control over its own, southern
province, was signed by Albanian representatives. By refusing to
sign, the Serbs face a punitive air assault by NATO _ a threat made
more acute by Friday's decision to withdraw the monitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will immediately engage in consultations with our partners
and allies to be ready to act,'' the co-chairs of the Paris talks,
British Foreign Minister Robin Cook and French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine, said in their statement.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus is meant to protect monitors from being harmed or
taken hostage should NATO follow through on its bomb threat. But
the pullout also means Kosovo could become a violent free-for-all
between the army of the ruling Serbs and the guerrilla force of the
ethnic Albanians' Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's nobody watching, the Albanians are at the mercy of
the Serbs. And we know what kind of mercy they show,'' said Jason
Miko, an aid worker with Mercy Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're worried,'' said the high-ranking OSCE source. ``We've
got indications that they're absolutely going to wreak havoc. It's
going to be a really ugly scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Foreign observers are also skeptical about the plans of the KLA.
Both sides have violated the October cease-fire, and both sides
have been accused of provoking the other, hoping to lay blame for
peace-breaking on their respective enemies.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 monitors, including Walker, will stay in the
Macedonian capital of Skopje, but all others will head home.
</P>
<P>
   The monitors' voyage is a formidable one. They are unarmed, will
not be escorted, and will have to cross a border where there are
tens of thousands of Serb troops, as well as a bridge to Macedonia
OSCE military sources say is mined.
</P>
<P>
   Vollebaek said he had been assured by the Yugoslav government,
which has never liked having the OSCE in Kosovo, that the monitors
would be allowed to leave without incident. The Serbs have harassed
monitors, and last month detained international observers at the
Kosovo-Macedonian border for 22 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``I choose the believe the promises I have been given,''
Vollebaek said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, as well as
private aid organizations, are also beginning to pull out _ leaving
few people to help the more than 250,000 people displaced during
the yearlong fighting. The United Nations estimates that a fifth of
the Kosovar population has been chased or burned out of their homes
in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 refugees have flooded over the Kosovo-Macedonian
border in the past month, said Fernando del Mundo, spokesman for
the UN group.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of foreign monitors has local Albanians worried that
the Serbs will launch a brutal assault against them, said Ylber
Bajraktari, a journalist with the Albanian-language Koha Ditore.
Serb forces have been burning villages and exchanging fire with
Albanian guerrillas in spite of an October cease-fire pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are afraid, especially of the gap between OSCE leaving
and an air strike taking place,'' Bajraktari said.
</P>
<P>
   Aid workers and monitors said Friday was uncharacteristically
quiet in Kosovo, and speculated that the late winter snow was
discouraging firefights.
</P>
<P>
   Miko said his staff spotted the heavy presence of both KLA
soldiers and Serb military in the hotspots of Vucitrn and Srbice
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the weather gets any better, these places could be the
sites of the first all-out fighting'' between the two sides, Miko
warned.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
