<HEADLINE>
DIFFERENT STANDARD APPLIED TO MUSICAL SCORES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By REED JOHNSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A few years ago, when Hans Zimmer began working on
the score for Terrence Malick's ``The Thin Red Line,'' the
German-born film composer was settled into a comfortable Hollywood
groove.
</P>
<P>
   After launching his career with relatively low-budget art-house
movies such as ``Moonlighting'' and ``My Beautiful Laundrette,''
Zimmer gradually had moved on to epics such as ``The Last Emperor''
and high-tech shoot-'em-ups such as ``The Rock.'' He'd received
Oscar nominations for his scores for ``Rain Man'' and ``The
Preacher's Wife'' and won a Grammy Award for ``Crimson Tide,''
making him one of the industry's most sought-after tunesmiths.
</P>
<P>
   So, when Zimmer and director Malick began discussing ``The Thin
Red Line,'' a decidedly unconventional World War II movie, Zimmer
quickly sensed that the collaboration wouldn't be conventional
either. As it turned out, he was right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was starting to become very much established in a way here
(Hollywood), for better or for worse,'' Zimmer says. ``Terry took
me on this enormous sort of ride, and I learned so much. Because he
never would think of me as a composer, he would think of me as a
filmmaker, which was a lot to live up to, in a way.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Hollywood power ladder, composers tend to occupy the
lower rungs. Usually, they're brought in six or eight weeks before
a film is finished. That seldom allows room for music that is
stylistically experimental or emotionally ambiguous.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, of all the personnel involved in making motion pictures,
perhaps only composers and songwriters are judged by their work
both within and apart from the movie itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music has a certain power, the best of it, to stand on its
own,'' says Andy Trudeau, an executive producer of cultural
programming for National Public Radio and lifelong movie soundtrack
buff.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some scores that fit so perfectly with the
photography and the acting that when you pull it out, it just lays
there like flat root beer. So I apply a `stand alone' standard.''
</P>
<P>
   By ``stand alone,'' Trudeau means that a film score must possess
a certain aesthetic value aside from its ability to illustrate,
underscore or otherwise contextualize the images on screen.
</P>
<P>
   On recent installments of NPR's ``Weekend Edition Sunday''
program (heard locally on KCRW FM-89.9 from 8 to 10 a.m.), Trudeau
and co-host Liane Hansen have been applying that criteria to this
year's five nominees for best achievement in music, original
dramatic score. Besides Zimmer, they are David Hirschfelder for
``Elizabeth,'' Nicola Piovani for ``Life Is Beautiful,'' Randy
Newman for ``Pleasantville'' and John Williams for ``Saving Private
Ryan.'' Oscars also are given for original musical or comedy score
and for best original song.
</P>
<P>
   ``Which of these scores are you going to be listening to with
pleasure 10 years from now?'' Trudeau asks rhetorically.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Hollywood composers seldom have the luxury of writing music
that aspires to a life of its own.
</P>
<P>
   In that respect, says Zimmer, both ``The Thin Red Line'' and
DreamWorks' animated ``Prince of Egypt'' _ for which Zimmer and
Stephen Schwartz received Oscar nominations in the best original
musical score category _ were ``sort of about working outside the
system, or what is thought of as the system.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of working with Terry was very much experimenting,
reinventing myself in a way,'' Zimmer says. ``I've done a lot of
action movies, movies where people are shooting at each other, so
the first thing to do was to rid myself of all the cliches.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Oscars now have separate awards for dramatic and
comedic scores, some composers say there's still a presumption that
dramatic music is more difficult to write. In fact, the opposite
may be true, says composer Matthew Wilder, nominated this year for
Disney's animated musical ``Mulan'' along with lyricist David
Zippel and veteran composer Jerry Goldsmith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music naturally has a tendency to lean toward emotional
depth,'' Wilder says. ``It's easier to be romantic. I think it's
much tougher to find the comedic spin within a score.''
</P>
<P>
   But whichever composers are honored tonight, they'll almost
certainly be upstaged by the Gwyneth Paltrows and Tom Hankses of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is, the average soundtrack sells about 2,000 to
3,000 units,'' says NPR's Trudeau. ``It's mostly a specialty field.
Once in a while you get a `Titanic' that comes along and blows
everybody away. But who remembers the other two scores that
(composer James) Horner wrote that year?''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Trudeau says, they were ``The Mask of Zorro''
and ``Mighty Joe Young.''
</P>
</TEXT>
