<HEADLINE>
INVESTING FOR BEGINNERS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ABBY ELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not all investment clubs are exclusively for small-town
Midwestern women or for people whose income includes, or will soon
include, Social Security checks.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 37,000 such clubs nationwide, according to
the National Association of Investors Corporation, which helps
clubs organize. About 10 percent are run by people under 35, the
association says, and the percentage is growing steadily. And while
their monthly investments may be smaller than their phone bills,
members say the experience is fun, often profitable and great
training for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle Hogan Kennedy, now 26, started what she called a ``wee
investment education club'' when she was a student at American
University in Washington. The impetus: Her father had told her to
invest her tax refund in a mutual fund _ an idea that left her at a
loss. So she and four friends (soon eight) started buying
investment guides and meeting regularly to share advice, though
they never invested as a group.
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1994, Ms. Hogan headed to Chelsea, Vt., to
open a restaurant and founded another investment club. This time,
members contributed $25 a month and the club opened an account at
Charles Schwab. Each member was responsible for researching a stock
and presenting findings. The group would then decide whether to
buy, using criteria like ``potential and current profits, debt,
whether or not it was an up-and-coming field or a longstanding
company with new products,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The club averaged a roughly 15 percent annual return on its
investments, she said, although some investments the members didn't
make, in Internet stocks and the like, did even better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we'd bought into Yahoo and the rest, but back then who
knew? Certainly not nine 20- and 30-somethings trying to figure out
the stock market in east-of-nowhere Vermont,'' Ms. Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   Figuring out the markets from the big city, however, can be
equally challenging. Three years ago, Jeanhee Kim, 30, began an
investment club in Manhattan. It took almost six months for Ms.
Kim, a financial writer, and four pals to figure out the rules,
debating whether they should be a limited partnership (they were),
whether to register as a taxable entity (they did), how much to
contribute monthly and, perhaps most important, where to invest.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, they decided that each person would kick in $2,000 and
then contribute $50 a month. They bought stock in the Gap, Lucent
Technologies, Johnson &AMP; Johnson, as well as First Data, a payment
systems and information management company, and I-Flow, which makes
intravenous feeding and medication equipment. The members met
monthly, studying stocks, snacking on pizza and smiling at their
returns.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't all pizza, beer and dough. Group dynamics are
always tricky, but especially in an investment club, where
decisions have dollars-and-cents consequences.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worse than a book club, because you have to put money
into it, and it can be difficult getting a consensus,'' Ms. Kim
said.
</P>
<P>
   One member was a lawyer who decided ``how to organize, get tax
codes,'' Ms. Kim said, while another, a social worker, created
harmony and contributed a lot of common sense. Another member, she
said, was always thinking of the worst case and asking how they
would cope with disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made every decision slower, sometimes bringing levity
because he could be comical about it but sometimes bringing cries
of frustration from the group,'' Ms. Kim said.
</P>
<P>
   The club recently disbanded, because members had moved, married
or become too busy to attend meetings. Ms. Kim said her share is
now worht almost double her original investment.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their difficulties, investment clubs are worthwhile for
both the learning and the camaraderie, Ms. Kim and Ms. Hogan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They serve as a valuable building block for when a person
moves ahead,'' said Ms. Hogan, who now lives in Green Bay, Wis.,
with her husband, John, and four children. She publishes an on-line
newsletter, ``The Money Maven,'' and hopes to start an on-line
investment club.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can find a club, and for the cost of Internet access or
cable TV, start to build a stock portfolio,'' she added.
``Twenty-somethings who feel they don't have two nickels to rub
together can get involved in the emerging industries and take an
avid interest in the market without needing hundreds or thousands
of dollars.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
