<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-SCREENWRITERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FEW (MORE) WORDS FROM THE NOMINATED WRITERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At the end of Orson Welles' ``Citizen Kane,''
newsreel editor Philip Van Zandt opines: ``I don't think any word
can explain a man's life.'' Of course, he was wrong. (Rosebud.) But
then, Van Zandt wasn't privy to the film's childhood flashback
scenes.
</P>
<P>
   He would probably also get some argument from this year's
Oscar-nominated writers, a talented group of diverse individuals
who have done a pretty fair job of explaining a lot of things _
men's lives, world wars and politicians' misadventures among them.
</P>
<P>
   The nominees: &QL; 
ORIGINAL SCREENPLAY
</P>
<P>
   _ Warren Beatty and Jeremy Pikser, ``Bulworth''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty and Pikser first collaborated on ``Reds'' and reteamed
for ``Bulworth,'' a political film of a much different nature. The
comedy about a suicidal senator on a crazed, truth-telling jag
received critical hosannas, but only one Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hoped for more,'' Pikser says. ``Just as we hoped more
people would see the movie. But I look at it as quality vs.
quantity. The people who did see it, for the most part, loved it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus,'' he adds, ``for a political film, I think it did pretty
well. It got a bigger audience than, say, `The Nation's' subscriber
list.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty doesn't necessarily see it that way. But he's got a
bigger windmill to chase.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe now with the nomination, (20th Century Fox chairman)
Rupert Murdoch will see my (darn) movie,'' Beatty says.
</P>
<P>
   If he has waited this long, probably not.
</P>
<P>
   _ Roberto Benigni and Vincenzo Cerami, ``Life Is Beautiful''
</P>
<P>
   This is certainly the most audacious screenplay in the bunch,
daring to make a comedy set during the Holocaust. Guess what _ it
worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was scared,'' Benigni admits. ``But I was scared like when
you are in love with somebody, because I was honest with myself. I
was not trying to make something violent or bad. A lot of friends
of mine told me that this would lose me a lot of my audience. But
the idea was so simple _ it's a love story, about a man's love for
his family and his son _ and I can't imagine something better than
this. If I could come back, I would remake it 100 times.''
</P>
<P>
   And we would just as likely come back and watch it again, too.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Rodat, ``Saving Private Ryan''
</P>
<P>
   Writing a Steven Spielberg movie is a little like playing on
Michael Jordan's Chicago Bulls. The supporting cast tends to go
unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that's fine,'' says Rodat, whose biggest writing credit
prior to ``Ryan'' was the children's movie ``Fly Away Home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The satisfactions in writing are occasionally public, but more
often they're personal. For me, it's those times when I get inside
a scene and feel the emotions the characters are feeling. There's
nothing like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Spielberg, Rodat has taken great pleasure in the public
dialogue the movie has inspired.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people have realized the sacrifices their parents and
grandparents made, and that's been gratifying,'' Rodat says. ``I
don't think a lot of people had a sense of that before. The world
is far from a perfect place, but it's a much better place because
of these soldiers who died. I'll never be able to forget the
crosses in the cemeteries there in Normandy.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard, ``Shakespeare in Love''
</P>
<P>
   Marc Norman first started writing ``Shakespeare in Love'' in
1991, three years after one of his children suggested he think
about the Bard's early days as a playwright.
</P>
<P>
   ``That speaks for the value of the nuclear family, doesn't it?''
Norman says, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   After a deal with Universal and Julia Roberts fell apart in
1992, the project fell into disfavor with studio executives. ``It
was damaged goods,'' Norman says. That changed when Miramax
chairman Harvey Weinstein rescued it in 1996, and the rest, as they
say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   Norman wrote the screenplay's early drafts. Playwright Tom
Stoppard added his own clever touches and Elizabethan in-jokes in
subsequent rewrites, both when the script was at Universal and,
later, with Miramax.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movie almost died 10 times, but somehow kept coming
back,'' Norman says. ``I'm really in awe of that and it has made
all of the awards and success even more satisfying.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrew Niccol, ``The Truman Show''
</P>
<P>
   A former advertising copywriter in London, Niccol has plenty of
experience with the sort of blatant product placement featured in
``The Truman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being sold something every minute of the day,'' Niccol
says. ``In essence, we're being asked to acquire happiness. (The
film) wants to make you aware that you're being sold something and
that you don't have to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Truman Show'' was Niccol's first screenplay. He directed
his second, ``Gattaca,'' a thoughtful, futuristic tale of genetic
tinkering. Clearly, Niccol enjoys tackling weighty issues with his
work. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
ADAPTED SCREENPLAY
</P>
<P>
   _ Bill Condon, ``Gods and Monsters''
</P>
<P>
   Condon is as surprised as anybody that Oscar has recognized his
little movie, which was adapted from Christopher Bram's novel,
``Father of Frankenstein.'' When he screened the film last year at
Sundance, it received tremendous response, but no distributor
picked it up.
</P>
<P>
   ``If critics didn't get behind it early, I don't think anybody
would have seen it,'' says Condon, who also directed the film.
Lion's Gate ultimately acquired the film in June and released it in
October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made the movie in 24 days,'' Condon says. ``It had to be
that way, financing such as it was. (The movie cost $3 million.) I
knew that when I was writing it, so I structured it in a way that I
could make it quick.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Frank, ``Out of Sight''
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of Sight'' was Frank's second crack at adapting Elmore
Leonard; he had written the screenplay for ``Get Shorty'' three
years earlier. Both scripts won awards from the Writers Guild;
``Out of Sight'' gave Frank his first Oscar nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Box office aside, this was the most satisfying and fun job
I've ever had,'' Frank says. ``It was a gas all the way through.
(Director) Steven Soderbergh was so in sync with my script. He took
what was, on the page, a B movie and elevated into a really good B
movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank says the key to adapting Leonard for the screen is to give
the script structure while maintaining the book's unpredictability.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all happenstance, and that's what makes the books so
delicious,'' Frank says.
</P>
<P>
   _ Elaine May, ``Primary Colors''
</P>
<P>
   May adapted Joe Klein's best seller for the screen, not the
easiest of assignments. The book was long, complex and, as it was
loosely based on the life of everyone's favorite wayward president,
fairly well-known to audiences. While the film was not a big hit,
critics generally praised May's handiwork.
</P>
<P>
   May previously was nominated for her adaption work with Warren
Beatty on ``Heaven Can Wait.'' She was unavailable to comment for
this story.
</P>
<P>
   _ Scott Smith, ``A Simple Plan''
</P>
<P>
   Novelist Smith adapted his own book for the screen and was as
surprised as anyone that he was nominated for an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me doesn't think of myself as a screenwriter,'' Smith
says. ``I feel like a weekend golfer who has been invited to the
Masters.''
</P>
<P>
   In turning his psychological thriller into a movie, Smith seized
the chance to improve on his original work by making it more
detailed and complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``The central question of the film is `What would you do?'''
Smith says. ``That's the attraction, I think. People imagine
themselves in the situation and want to think they'd handle it
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Terrence Malick, ``The Thin Red Line''
</P>
<P>
   The lyrical war film, adapted from James Jones' epic novel, is
Malick's third effort as a writer and director in his sporadic,
25-year career. ``Badlands'' (1973) and ``Days of Heaven'' (1978)
preceded it.
</P>
<P>
   Malick, ever private, declined to comment for this story. As per
his contract, he did no interviews to promote ``The Thin Red
Line.'' Rumor has it that he will attend the Oscars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
