<SLUG> BC-CERVICAL-TEST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TEST PROMISES BETTER PREVENTION OF CERVICAL CANCERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The US Food and Drug Administration approved a detection test
Friday for the virus that causes cervical cancer, an advance that
might help doctors determine more easily which women with
precancerous conditions need more testing and treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Using a sensitive DNA probe, the test, called Hybrid Capture II,
can detect all 13 forms of the human papilloma virus, or HPV, that
cause cervical cancer. A number of other strains of HPV, a sexually
transmitted virus, do not cause cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Although the incidence of invasive cervical cancer has been
declining steadily in recent decades, about 12,800 US women will be
diagnosed with it this year and nearly 5,000 will die, according to
the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   The maker of the new test, Digene in Beltsville, Md., has high
hopes for it. ``Essentially, we envision this test as a primary
screening device,'' Evan Jones, chairman and CEO of Digene, said in
a telephone briefing Friday with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Others are more restrained. No one will really know how useful
the test is until the National Cancer Institute completes a
five-year study of it, perhaps this year, said Dr. Ellen Sheets,
director of the Pap smear evaluation center at Brigham and Women's
Hospital in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of using it as a screening test, she said, the HPV
test will more likely, at least initially, be used primarily on
women who have abnormal or ambiguous results on a Pap test, a
procedure in which a small sample of cells is taken from the cervix
with a swab and examined under the microscope for abnormal cells.
</P>
<P>
   Although the test can spot the presence of HPV, it cannot
determine whether cervical cells have become abnormal, the true red
flag for cancer, she said, adding that this is the reason she feels
it might not be a good screening test. The test is expected to cost
about $50.
</P>
<P>
   But every year, about 2 million women have equivocal Pap smears,
and for them, the test will be ``very helpful,'' said Dr. Sharyn
Lenhart, immediate past president of the American Medical Women's
Association and a psychiatrist in private practice in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The new test is a more sophisticated version of an HPV test that
Digene began marketing two years ago, and is probably more
convenient for use by smaller labs, an FDA spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   The test comes on the heels of a number of other advances in the
detection of cervical cancer, including better ways to do Pap
tests. Two of those advances, AutoPap and PapNet, use computers to
help technicians pick out cervical cells that look abnormal under a
microscope. Also, ThinPrep allows cells to be spread more thinly on
the microscope slide so that they are easier to read. Unlike the
HPV test, these methods detect cells that might be cancerous, not
the presence of the virus that causes cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Better ways to tell which women with abnormal Pap tests need
further testing and treatment is not only a major concern for
patients, but for insurers as well.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors cannot tell which abnormal results truly spell danger;
in fact, most abnormal Pap tests turn out to be nothing serious.
</P>
<P>
   But many women with abnormal Pap tests are sent on for
colposcopy, a test that can cost about $150 in which doctors use a
high-powered microscope to look at the cervix. This is often
followed by freezing, burning or using electrical wires to remove
suspect tissue, at another $500 or more a patient.
</P>
<P>
   This can cure the problem if a woman has cervical dysplasia, the
presence of abnormal cells, or carcinoma in situ, a noninvasive
cancer. But because of the ambiguity of Pap test results, many
women go through colposcopy needlessly.
</P>
<P>
   With the new Digene test, doctors may be able to test women who
have ambiguous Pap tests and see whether they have HPV, and if so,
whether it is one of the strains likely to cause cancer. A 1995
study published in the Journal of the National Cancer Institute
showed that 93 percent of women with invasive cervical cancer had
the high risk form of HPV.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
