<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-NEWCOMERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONTENEGRO, GRIFFITH BOTH EXCITED FIRST-TIMERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Odd how a little event like an Oscar nomination
can do funny things to a person's life. Just ask Fernanda
Montenegro and Rachel Griffiths.
</P>
<P>
   Both are attending their first Academy Awards ceremony tonight,
and they're doing it in style, as nominees for what the irony-prone
Griffiths cheekily calls ``the little gold man,'' the Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro, the 69-year-old queen of Brazilian live theater, is
up for best actress for her role in ``Central Station,'' as a
retired teacher whose hard heart softens as she helps a motherless
youth search for his father. It is only Montenegro's fourth major
film role in half a century of acting.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths, a rangy 32-year-old ``toiler'' from mildly political
middle-class Australian roots, is up for best supporting actress
for her role as the less-successful sister in ``Hilary and
Jackie.'' Despite a lengthy list of Australian and British credits,
her only American film has been ``My Best Friend's Wedding.''
</P>
<P>
   Both carry the weight of their nation's pride into tonight's
ceremonies; both say they are long shots to win. But both profess
to care little about their chances because it's already been one
glorious, if sometimes taxing, ride since the nominations were
announced Feb. 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``You divide your life in three parts,'' Montenegro said. ``I
think for me two parts are past and this moment is the beginning of
my third part. I'll call the third part `The Unexpected.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Like Montenegro, Griffiths said the Oscar nomination surprised
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never chased it; I never wooed it,'' Griffiths said. ``It's
like the Ace of Cups in the tarot (card deck). It's great that life
can give you these things. It comes out of the blue and it's
thrilling.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro found out she'd been nominated while sitting in a New
York hotel with the film's director, Walter Salles, and a group of
Brazilian journalists after attending the National Board of
Review's annual awards ceremony the previous evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got ready, got myself set up, because there was some very
discreet expectation'' that she might get a nomination, Montenegro
said. She had believed only that the movie might get nominated, as
it was, for best foreign film.
</P>
<P>
   Then they read off the nominees for best actress.
</P>
<P>
   ``The second name was mine and I didn't believe it,'' Montenegro
said. ``People started shouting, `You've been nominated,' and then
things happened very quickly. Then the phones started to ring.
Three women (from the studio) came then with a schedule (of
interviews and appearances) and it went all day.''
</P>
<P>
   At 11 p.m. she was still doing work, having an interview over
dinner with a Brazilian journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very impressed with how well-organized this is,''
Montenegro said. ``It's sort of a controlled avalanche, a very
well-organized avalanche.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, her avalanche started months ago. First, there were
film festivals around the world, then the media junkets for the
film's American release, then various awards shows and other
promotional efforts that kept her from her Brazilian home and
family (all in the acting business as well) for all but a few days
at a time in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   She has done days and days of interviews, often from the Beverly
Hills hotel where she was ensconced for the recent Screen Actors
Guild and Golden Globe awards.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were the preparations for the big Oscar night,
helped when the designer Valentino wrote her a note asking if she
would wear his gown to the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite certain I'll be very well-dressed,'' Montenegro
said.
</P>
<P>
   Griffiths, who during an interview shows off the pricey new
Jimmy Choo heels she'd just been given, has had a similar whirlwind
of attention since being nominated.
</P>
<P>
   For her, word came while she was sitting in a Melbourne,
Australia, hotel. She soon was partying with family friends and
repeatedly calling her best friend, just to say, ``I don't believe
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, her entire country had reason to not believe it, because
``Hilary and Jackie'' hadn't even been released there yet, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of Australians were as shocked as I was,''
Griffiths said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there's been an outpouring of support for her and
other Australian nominees such as Cate Blanchett, Geoffrey Rush and
Peter Weir.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of goodwill is extraordinary,'' Griffiths said.
``Anybody who's ever known you feels like they're touching this
little gold man through you. And people are so pleased for me,
people who know how hard I've struggled. People are rooting for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   For much of the past month, Griffiths has been shuttling in and
out of town for a series of awards shows and publicity appearances
for ``Hilary and Jackie'' and two other films that are being
released about now, while doing Oscar preparations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just having a good time,'' Griffiths said. ``I don't
expect to win. I feel like a dark horse who snuck in at the last
moment. I feel like I've already won. This is winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro gives herself little chance of winning either, but
plans to have a great time tonight nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quasi impossible,'' Montenegro said. ``I say quasi
because I never expected to be here, to be nominated, and yet, I'm
here. I'm already quite satisfied with being nominated. I'll be at
a party either way, whether I win it or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in her hotel's elegant parlor, Montenegro shakes her
head at the attention, and the luxurious trappings, that
accompanied her nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden, I have you, an American journalist, and an
interpreter talking with me here in this beautiful hotel,'' she
said. ``It's a magical moment. But I'm not starstruck. It was
written on the stars. It's like a new beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   For both, part of the thrill is meeting actors and others whose
work they've always respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven Spielberg told me I was great'' at the Oscar nominees
luncheon, Griffiths said. ``I could not believe I was standing next
to Steven Spielberg, but there can't be two such sweet people in
the world that look like him. But what was I going to say: `I
really liked ``E.T.''?'''
</P>
<P>
   For Montenegro, the actors she grew up watching in classic
American films inspired her but seemed so remote from her own
existence. Now, she'll be among them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been an actress in Brazil for 50 years, and I never
expected to be here,'' Montenegro said. ``It is like a dream, a
dream, a beautiful dream. I feel like a Cinderella, like a bride,
an old bride. It will be like a fantasy.''
</P>
<P>
   But sweetest of all for the two actresses, the nominations have
been a tremendous validation of their craft.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, I had to take the hard-slog road,'' Griffiths
said. ``The question of `am I good enough?' has never been far
away. But this kind of acknowledgment cemented my position in
Australian cinema. It buys you grace. You don't have to beg to be
gotten in the door.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Grifiths had to hurriedly rearrange her schedule the
afternoon of the nominees luncheon when director Brian De Palma
asked to meet with her.
</P>
<P>
   Montenegro's nomination, the first of a South American actress
since Norma Aliondru in 1987, has changed the way people in Brazil
see her.
</P>
<P>
   ``(They) feel like it's the end of the World Cup,'' Montenegro
said. ``Brazil loves me, and I feel it. I don't want to be
self-indulgent, but when I go to restaurants, people applaud. It is
very, very astonishing.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, that will stop, Montenegro said, but for now, life is
sweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no illusion, but in this moment, I have the respect of
my audience,'' Montenegro said. ``Perhaps they'll stop (applauding)
at the end of March.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
