<HEADLINE>
FULL SENATE TO GET NEW HAMPSHIRE TAX DILEMMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ At the rear of the room where the finance
committee of the New Hampshire Senate meets, there is an enormous
steel vault that once served as the state's treasury, but now sits
empty with its massive door ajar.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the finance committee came up empty, rejecting its last
option to find the nearly $1 billion needed to solve New
Hampshire's school funding crisis by the court-imposed April 1
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the committee said ``No'' to a sales tax, a
statewide property tax, legalization of video slot machine
gambling, increased liquor taxes and a bill calling for interim
funding to buy time and keep the state's schools open past June.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the matter will move to the full Senate. On Monday,
senators will question the sponsors of the plan rejected Friday, an
historic income tax bill that passed the House earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday promises to be chaotic as that proposal, the so-called
Hager-Below plan, and many others resurface for debate. The senate
president, however, has promised that a vote to send a tax proposal
over to the House will be held no later than Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Most senators acknowledged that were it not for Gov. Jeanne
Shaheen's pledge to veto an income tax, the Hager-Below plan would
pass and become law. It calls for a $6 statewide property tax
levied on second homes and business property and a 4 percent income
tax that would exempt the first $28,000 earned by a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   This week, teachers in Claremont, the property-poor town that
lent its name to the lawsuit threatening to topple the state's tax
structure, received pink slips warning them they would be out of a
job by summer.
</P>
<P>
   No one, 15 months after the court ordered the state to find a
constitutional way to fund schools, knows what that plan will be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
