</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCARS-CINEMATOGRAPY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERE'S LOOKING AT YOU, CINEMATOGRAPHERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Lighting, camera movement, frame composition and
lens choice make up the true language of motion pictures.
Cinematographers are the essential artists who design those
pictures. And this year's nominees brought us a treasure trove of
indelible images.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _  &LR; Remi Adefarasin (``Elizabeth''): The British cinematographer
oversaw the mesmerizing, second-unit desert photography for the
Oscar-winning ``The English Patient'' before going on to make this
study of the Virgin Queen's rise to power a dazzling display of
moody shadows, precision illumination and carefully deployed camera
pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rembrandt's paintings really summarized the whole look we were
going for. They have pools of light that fall down and bathe the
main protagonists, but we didn't want it to look theatrical, like a
spotlight was falling on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, the sets were deliberately made dark, so it would be
easier for me to keep the light off. That way, you could see that
you were in a real environment, but the light could be pinpointed
on where the story was without overcooking it. We didn't want it to
be so stylized that you felt like you were being manipulated.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Richard Greatrex (``Shakespeare in Love''): A BBC-trained
cameraman who also shot ``Mrs. Brown'' with director John Madden,
Greatrex tried to create a realistic environment for
``Shakespeare's'' farcical goings-on while providing unobtrusive
illumination for its large cast of declaiming characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``John's shots are always exceedingly elaborate, so you try to
create a lighting style that can cope with that, which often takes
rather a lot of doing. A shot very rarely holds still; it develops
from close-up into wide and back into close-up again, and from one
room into another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The other thing is to give space to the actors that allows
them to feel free. I try not to tie actors up with `you've got to
hit this mark because this light's here.' I think an essential part
of the storytelling is to permit actors to concentrate on being the
characters and not have to think about all these terrible
technicalities all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Conrad Hall (``A Civil Action''): This is veteran director of
photography Hall's eighth Oscar nomination; he won the award for
``Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.'' His brief on ``A Civil
Action'' was to help director Steven Zaillian pare down a highly
technical, complicated and lengthy corporate malfeasance lawsuit to
its dramatic basics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our story involves living rooms, bathrooms, hallways,
kitchens, that kind of thing, which is a lot different than forests
or mountains or oceans or costumes. It was particularly interesting
to try to find a look for the essence of the story, which is about
trying to find the truth about whether polluted well water poisoned
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was like the difference between clear water and
polluted water. I tried to find the clarity of image that would be
representative of a search for the truth. The clear, crisp imagery
we tried to create helped to reinforce the sense of that search.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Janusz Kaminski (``Saving Private Ryan''): Kaminski won an
Oscar for ``Schindler's List,'' his first collaboration with
director Steven Spielberg, and was also nominated for their third
film together, ``Amistad.'' Many feel that his visualization of the
D-Day invasion in ``Saving Private Ryan'' is the most realistic
combat footage ever staged.
</P>
<P>
   ``My aim was to make the viewers feel like they were active
participants in the invasion of Normandy. And I felt I succeeded in
making the camera an active participant as well, rather than just
being an objective observer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read somewhere that the operators were let free and they
just ran around the beach with cameras. That's simply impossible to
do, because you have the whole field prerigged with squibs and
explosives. Since those are going off all through the take, the
actors and cameramen had to rehearse their moves. It may appear
chaotic on the screen, but the operators were following carefully
choreographed action. Nothing happened haphazard; it was very much
calculated.''
</P>
<P>
   _ John Toll (``The Thin Red Line''): Toll earned Oscars for
shooting ``Braveheart'' and ``Legends of the Fall,'' and his ``Red
Line'' work recently won this year's American Society of
Cinematographers' outstanding achievement award. Toll's visuals
have been praised for their beauty and lending a formal coherence
to Terrence Malick's narratively diffuse World War II film.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visual idea of all this violence occurring in such a
beautiful place was really striking. It's really a film about the
tragedy of war, and that really contrasted the horrible nature of
the combat on Guadalcanal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge was to re-create this event and to get inside
the heads of the characters in a way that, cinematically, felt very
natural. We wanted the audience to feel as if they were witnessing
these events and feel the emotions of the characters very close-up
and firsthand. We did it by trying to re-create the natural
circumstances of the war in that environment. You do that by using
the camera to tell the story; in our particular case, we were
really interested in almost putting the camera into the story
somehow.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 1934EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0275 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7278 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-470&AMP;A     03-19 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-470&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLOOD OF REFUGEES TRIES TO GET AWAY FROM SERB OFFENSIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-TALKS, KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-CLINTON.) 
(lh) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRBICA, Yugoslavia _ His house is only half built, and there is
only one room that is habitable and warm, but Afrim Vojvoda, a
young farmer, and his wife, Shyhrete, put up 49 people when
refugees swarmed down the hill from neighboring villages two nights
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``At nine o'clock the first group came,'' Mrs. Vojvoda said,
sitting on the floor hugging her young daughter. ``They knocked on
the door, and I was terrified it was the police. Then another
family came at 10 o'clock, and then another at 2 in the morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading the last group was Fetije Xani, a 40-year-old mother
with six children in tow from the village of Poljance. They had
left home in a hurry, women and children and old people, stumbling
on foot through the dark the five miles to Srbica. ``I could not
see anything, the children were crying,'' Mrs. Xani said, touching
the head of her 6-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   The exodus was set off when word came that Serbian forces were
advancing, she said. ``My brother-in-law came and said take the
children because the Serbs might come,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers had listened all day to shelling higher in the
mountains and when fighters of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
ethnic Albanian guerrilla force, pulled back under heavy shelling,
the villagers decided to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the village left; no one stayed behind,'' Mrs. Xani said.
Her relatives sat crowded into the one room with a stove, along
with their hosts. The other 30 refugees had moved on to find
lodging with relatives or other families in the area.
</P>
<P>
   There are thousands of refugees on the move in Kosovo. A
spokesman for the U.N. High Commission for Refugees estimated that
20,000 have been displaced since Sunday, the bulk of them in the
mountain range just northwest of the capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Bajram Gashi, head of the local Mother Theresa aid office, said
he was struggling to cope with more than 5,000 refugees who have
arrived in Srbica in the last three days. Some 1,300 more were
staying in the village further up the road, and many more had
headed south.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his tiny office, heated by a wood stove, he spoke as
workers carried foam mattresses to waiting cars. ``The biggest
problem is shelter, a roof over their heads,'' he said. ``But there
other difficulties, keeping them warm. They need blankets and
stoves.'' He added that the fighting had knocked out the
electricity and water supplies.
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, a woman started shouting in the corridor. ``She is
asking for a stove and wood,'' he said. ``We might have one truck
of wood coming, but we have 5,000 people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in cellars, in unfinished houses,'' he
continued. ``People who are refugees themselves are giving shelter
to refugees. We have one family giving shelter to 80 people.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The refugees in this region have been fleeing a major military
operation mounted by the Yugoslav Army over the last three weeks.
Combined army and police units have been shelling and burning
villages, steadily clearing the area of villagers and Kosovo
Liberation Army fighters who have tried to resist. The military has
advanced from east to west over the Cicavica mountain range,
traditionally something of a rebel stronghold. The movement, and
the arrival of a new column of forces with T-72 tanks in Srbica at
the beginning of the week, have succeeded in emptying the remaining
villages without any fighting. Poljance was the last village on the
western side of the mountain range.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian forces are now widely thought to be planning an
advance west, into the Drenica region, the heartland of the rebel
resistance and the base of its command headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opinion of the people is that the Serbs will make a push
on the eastern part of Drenica,'' Gashi said. ``They are frightened
of a new massive offensive.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugees in Srbica are stuck in the middle. They have no
guarantee of safety, warned Gani Veseli, who has been organizing
shelter for refugees. The Serbian police are based in their station
in the center of town, and Yugoslav Army troops are in a disused
factory on the hill. Just 100 yards down the road is the first
checkpoint of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   Until Friday the international monitors of the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe have stood in between, their
bright orange vehicles parked along the road in what is essentially
no man's land.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of tension in the area,'' said Col. Lars
Finstad, the chief verifier in the area. ``But while they stay
where they are, things are more or less OK.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke just minutes before the order came for the monitors to
evacuate. Within hours there would be no more orange cars to
separate the two warring sides.
</P>
<P>
   Down the road, rebel fighters were still guarding the entrance
to Poljance and some of the villages deeper in the mountains. They
have mined many of the roads as they have pulled back, but can put
up little resistance in the face of the Yugoslav Army's vastly
superior artillery and tank power.
</P>
<P>
   As the monitors prepared to evacuate Kosovo, William Walker, the
head of the mission, spoke to his local employees and warned them
that the violence could escalate with the departure of the
monitors. ``What comes next could be that the situation gets worse
before it gets better,'' he told them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
