<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're King-Size Issues, Whatever You Call Him &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is a symbol so hallowed that only the person it represents
should determine its use? Can anyone wield such control over how
the print and electronic media refer to him? Such are the issues
raised by the Artist Formerly Known as Prince in a suit filed in
late February in New York against Uptown magazine, a fanzine
devoted to him.
</P>
<P>
   The Artist accuses Uptown of copyright and trademark violations
and piracy of intellectual property for using his symbol without
permission, said one of his lawyers, Michael Elkin of Thelen Reid &AMP;
Priest in Manhattan. He wants to halt publication of Uptown, which
is based in Sweden but has much of its circulation in the United
States, and any associated books in the works about him, as well as
to close down Uptown's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Hahn, a lawyer with Hanify &AMP; King in Boston who describes
himself as a ``major Prince fan,'' is representing Uptown pro bono
and calls the suit a battle over civil liberties. The Artist
himself distributed computerized copies of the symbol, Hahn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The notion that a person can change his name to a symbol, ask
everyone to use that symbol and then sue them for using it is
legally absurd,'' he said. ``This is a story about David and
Goliath. It's about freedom of speech, access to information,
copyright infringement. It's about an uncivil war between a major
pop musician and his fan base.''
</P>
<P>
   By threatening to sue, the Artist has shut down other Web sites
run by his fans, saying they were illegally distributing bootleg
recordings _ an accusation not made against Uptown. His lawyers see
the Uptown case as nothing more than an extension of those efforts.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not interested in shutting down the press or
publications,'' Elkin said. ``He simply would like for the
unauthorized use of his property interests not to be exploited.''
</P>
<P>
   Abby Ellin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Just One Maniac Per Point &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When 10,000 Maniacs played its first show in September 1981, the
Dow Jones industrial average was in the 800s. Before a concert in
Ithaca last week, just a day after the Dow first inched over
10,000, the band talked about what its members called ``the other
10,000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank God, after 18 years, we finally understand what the Dow
is,'' laughed Dennis Drew, the group's keyboard player. ``My dad
handles all of my investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Group members said their popularity and record sales fluctuate
with the stock market. No word, though, on whether they will change
their name to 11,000 Maniacs to stay ahead of the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Ross Sorkin &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From Mud Packs to Millions &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Software and Web shopping sites aren't the only fast routes to
fortune for 30-year-olds. Just ask Marcia Kilgore, founder of Bliss
World, a spa and cosmetics company in New York that she created
just three years ago at age 27 and sold this week to LVMH Moet
Hennessy Louis Vuitton for a sum estimated to be well into eight
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kilgore did not set out to be a massage-and mud-mask mogul.
She was simply fed up with ineffective dermatologists and wanted to
cure her own pimples. Soon she was doing facials for clients she
had cultivated in her other incarnation, as a fitness trainer.
</P>
<P>
   From there grew Bliss Spa in Manhattan's SoHo as well as lines
of skin-care products and cosmetics. Now she will stay on with LVMH
as executive director of Bliss, retaining a minority stake.
</P>
<P>
   Her clients include Jennifer Aniston and Cindy Crawford. The
usual wait for the honor of having her fingers personally massage
less famous facial muscles is 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   After running her own show, Ms. Kilgore sees little difficulty
adjusting to a supporting role in a global corporation. ``The great
part about LVMH's approach to us is I don't have to work really
within a corporate structure,'' she said, adding that she would now
have more time for creative thinking. LVMH said much of the appeal
of Bliss was its young, energetic management.
</P>
<P>
   Women's Wear Daily estimated that LVMH would pay Ms. Kilgore up
to $30 million if Bliss, which it plans to expand worldwide with
more spas and increased cosmetics sales, met certain targets.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Kilgore, who said revenues were ``11 or 12 or 13 million''
last year, did not disclose the sale price but said the $30 million
estimate was high.
</P>
<P>
   Does the change mean she will pay more attention to the pores of
clients like Madonna? Hardly, Ms. Kilgore acknowledged. If a
celebrity insists on her personal touch on short notice, she could
give no guarantees, she said, but ``I would try.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Canedy &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
