<SLUG> BC-MA-DEATH-PENALTY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARDINAL, BISHOPS VOW FIGHT AGAINST DEATH PENALTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIEGO RIBADENEIRA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Cardinal Bernard Law, in thinly veiled reference to
Governor Paul Cellucci, said Friday that ``well-informed''
Catholics who support the deathy penalty are committing a sin.
</P>
<P>
   In an unprecedented joint news conference, Law, the leader of
the Archdiocese of Boston, and the bishops of Massachusetts' three
other Catholic dioceses vowed to fight any attempts by the state
Legislature to restore capital punishment. Law is scheduled to
testify Monday at a state legislative hearing on the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, a Roman Catholic, is a vocal proponent of the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The teachings of the church are very clear,'' Law said. ``For
a well-informed Catholic to support capital punishment, it would be
morally wrong. And if one knowingly rejects the teachings of the
church it is wrong, morally evil and a sin.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to reconcile Cellucci's position on the death penalty with
the governor's faith, Law said: ``It's very difficult for me to
understand how Catholics can come to that position.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci, who graduated from a Catholic high school before going
on to receive two degrees from Boston College, took issue with
Law's statements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I mean that's his opinion,'' Cellucci told reporters at
the State House. ``There's an awful lot of Catholics in
Massachusetts and an awful lot of them support the death penalty.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not the first time Law and Cellucci have tangled over
issues involving Catholic teaching and public policy. In January
1991, Law said Cellucci should not be allowed to speak at Hudson
Catholic High School, Cellucci's alma mater, because the
then-lieutenant governor supported abortion rights.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday's comments represented some of the most pointed
comments the Cardinal has made specifically on the death penalty in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   As religious leaders from several denominations gear up for
battle on Beacon Hill, Cellucci, who was a death penalty opponent
until about a decade ago, said he is trying to make the state safer
for all citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to do what I think is right for Massachusetts,'' he
said. ``I happen to believe that putting the death penalty on the
books will deter a certain amount of horrific violent crime.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Law, Bishop Daniel Reilly of Worcester, Bishop Thomas
Dupre of Springfield, Jerome Somers, chairman of the board of the
Union of American Hebrew Congregations, and several other Jewish
and Christian clergy are scheduled to testify against capital
punishment on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   While the current head count in the Massachusetts house is
close, death penalty opponents believe they have a one-vote margin.
However, there are five vacancies that will be filled by special
elections in the next two months.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the death penalty are urging House Speaker Thomas
M. Finneran to hold a vote while they still have an edge, rather
than risk the uncertainty of five separate elections.
</P>
<P>
   For Cellucci, who made restoring the death penalty a top
priority during his run for governor last year, the upcoming death
penalty debate represents an important political test.
</P>
<P>
   In late 1997, a death penalty bill appeared headed for victory
in the Massachusetts House after the outrage generated by the
sexual violation and murder of 10-year-old Jeffrey Curley of
Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   But a last-minute vote switch by Representative John Slattery, a
Peabody Democrat, killed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   While the Catholic Church has always opposed the death penalty,
the bishops said Friday that after the defeat of the death penalty
bill two years ago, they and other religious leaders wanted to step
up their efforts to stymie any political momentum in favor of
capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not soft on crime,'' Bishop Sean O'Malley of Fall River
told reporters inside Law's Brighton residence. ``At the same time,
there is a growing concern that innocent people have been accused
and convicted of captial crime. It's very likely that we've
executed innocent people.''
</P>
<P>
   Pope John Paul II has written and spoken extensively on his
opposition to capital punishment, as a violation of the church's
responsibility to promote a culture of life. During his recent
visit to St. Louis, John Paul won clemency for a man on death row
in Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   But Cellucci said he believes the death penalty will save lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can save life of one police officer . . . by putting the
death penalty back on the books, then we should do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Catholic bishops argued that the death penalty promotes
a mentality of vengeance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yet no amount of revenge can bring back a loved one,'' the
four bishops said in a statement. ``Capital punishment does not
provide genuine solace to those burdened by the loss of murdered
loved ones.''
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Council of Churches, an ecumencial
organization representing 15 Protestant denominations, released a
statement Friday denouncing the death penalty as a ``contradiction
of both values of our Christian traditions and the principles of
humane government.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement, which has been sent to all state legislators,
also was signed by Bishop Methodios, the Greek Orthodox bishop of
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the capacity to place offenders in custody and keep
them from being a threat to public safety,'' the council of
churches' statement said. ``Thus, the death penalty adds no
protection for our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Samuel Chiel, rabbi emeritus of Temple Emanuel in Newton,
noted that in the Bible the death penalty is mandated for 36
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   But later, as the Jewish religion evolved, Chiel said, rabbis
became convinced that the death penalty could be erroneously
applied. So they came up with enough restrictions to make it
virtually impossible to apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jewish religious law effectively suspended the death penalty
two thousand years ago, the first such legislation in history,''
Chiel said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe writer Frank Phillips contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
