<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-STICKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIGID NEW MOTOR VEHICLE TESTS TO BEGIN IN OCTOBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts motor vehicles will undergo rigorous new
emissions tests starting this October, under a plan to reduce smog,
the state announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the state's 4.2 million motor vehicles would face the
tests every other year, in addition to an annual safety inspection.
Owners would pay $23 for an inspection sticker annually whether
they had the emissions test or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emissions from cars, trucks and buses represent more than 40
percent of all'' smog-causing chemicals, said Environmental Affairs
Secretary Robert Durand. ``The new inspection and maintenance
program represents a giant step forward in reaching the vital goal
of . . . clean air in Massachusetts.''
</P>
<P>
   But service station owners, who had lobbied for the fee to be
increased from the current $15 to at least $35, warned that the
state may have difficulty recruiting the necessary 1,200 to 1,500
service stations into the program unless fees are increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're deeply disappointed,'' said Roger Montbleau, president
of the New England Service Station and Automotive Repair
Association. He said that garages will have to pay $700 per month
to lease testing equipment.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said garage owners may change their minds after
reviewing the program's details, including a $3.16 raise in the
portion of their take-home fee, plus free training and other
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The new testing ends the state's four-year battle with federal
officials to improve its vehicle inspection program. It will become
final after statewide public hearings next month.
</P>
<P>
   The new equipment, called a dynamometer, checks chemical
emissions under simulated road conditions, rather than while idling
as the current tests do. As a result, dynamometers will detect
additional polluting cars that will have to be repaired before
owners obtain new stickers.
</P>
<P>
   However, cars built before 1984 and cars less than two years old
will be excused from the additional emissions tests, which state
officials say take about 12 minutes. State officials also said Gov.
Paul Cellucci would submit a bill next week to reduce safety checks
to every other year as well.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and business groups applauded the new program.
Brian Gilmore of the Associated Industries of Massachusetts called
it ``a low cost and convenient way for Massachusetts residents to
make an important contribution to cleaner air for all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
