<SLUG> BC-SOC-MLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLS BEGINS FOURTH SEASON AMID HIGH EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fourth season of Major League Soccer could go far in
determining whether soccer can become the country's fifth major
sport. MLS, which begins play Saturday and concludes with the Nov.
21 championship game at Foxboro Stadium, has so far exceeded
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   But the era of spectacular gains and breakthrough attendances
seems over. Opening day attendances for five games are expected to
range from 10,000 to 25,000, down from the extraordinary debut
numbers in 1996 (when six different teams averaged 20,000). The
novelty aspect of MLS is ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some would say we have become the fifth major sport already,
and some say we will never be that,'' MLS commissioner Doug Logan
said Friday. ``But that kind of talk is just a way of blowing off
steam. What we are doing is establishing and institutionalizing the
sport of soccer after a number of starts and stops and failures.
And we are well on the path to doing that. We've done a remarkable
job but there is still a long, long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, MLS has proved many doubters wrong. The league has
established a fan base, satisfied most of its sponsors, brought the
US into the global sports realm on a more regular basis, and
provided a basis for the national team, which has regained
credibility under former D.C. United coach Bruce Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, the quality was not there,'' Logan said.
``Four or five weeks into our first season, when play was a little
on the rough side, if you had said our teams would be able to take
on all comers in the Americas and win, it would have been difficult
to believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are into the real world. There is no such thing as a
breakthrough, but there is persistence and modest incremental
gains. I'll be happy if our attendance goes up, since we've made
Saturday nights the heart of our season, the television ratings go
up a little bit, and the play is better. A year ago, I would say we
had two pretty good teams. Now, we have four pretty good teams and
if, at the end of this season, we have six pretty good teams,
that's progress.''
</P>
<P>
   But D.C. United, the MLS champion in 1996 and '97 and runner-up
to Chicago last year, proved itself by defeating Brazil's Vasco da
Gama to win the InterAmericana Cup last year.
</P>
<P>
   United has been the flagship team of MLS, playing an attacking,
skillful style with a blend of US players under the leadership of
Bolivian midfielder Marco Antonio Etcheverry. Arena constructed the
team, guided it through three successful MLS seasons, compiling a
remarkable 14-2 playoff record. Arena is a tough act to follow for
former Revolution coach Thomas Rongen, who will be without John
Harkes (Revolution) and Tony Sanneh (Hertha Berlin).
</P>
<P>
   The United defense appears to be set with Carlos Llamosa and
Eddie Pope inside, flanked by Jeff Agoos on the left and
Argentinian Diego Sonora, acquired from the MetroStars, on the
right. Etcheverry has been MLS's outstanding performer for three
years, supported by role players such as Ben Olsen and Richie
Williams and the occasionally spectacular Jaime Moreno. But
United's lack of depth was costly in the MLS Cup final last year
against the Chicago Fire.
</P>
<P>
   The Fire won the championship and US Open Cup ``double'' in its
first season, emphasizing the lack of quality in MLS and showcasing
the motivational and tactical abilities of coach Bob Bradley,
assistant to Arena in 1996 and '97.
</P>
<P>
   But Chicago also displayed an overdependence on veterans Roman
Kosecki and Peter Nowak, plus defenders Lubos Kubik and Francis
Okaroh.
</P>
<P>
   There will be less foreign influence in MLS, since the league
has unwisely changed the limit on non-US players from five to four.
The idea was to save money and provide more opportunities for US
players, but this also reduces options to add bargain-basement,
diamond-in-the-rough discoveries such as the Sierra Leone striker
Unisa Conteh, who had impressed in training with the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The league has provided a venue for US coaches, but has produced
only two proven winners in Arena and Bradley. Curiously, seven of
the 12 MLS coaches are foreign-born.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
