<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-PICKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACES LOOK LIKE THE CLOSEST IN RECENT MEMORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS AND GLENN  WHIPP 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Daily News film critics Bob Strauss and Glenn
Whipp really have their work cut out for them this year. With most
of the Oscar races as close as they've been in a decade, our
usually confident prognosticators are experiencing a wee crisis of
arroga ... er, crisis of confidence this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Which doesn't mean that Bob and Glenn don't have opinions.
Indeed, there's more to spout off about this year than ever.
</P>
<P>
   STRAUSS: Whatever happens tonight, at least the odds are against
the academy embarrassing itself (that troublesome Elia Kazan life
achievement award excepted, of course). Most of the serious
contenders, at this point, seem pretty worthy. Some more so than
others, obviously, but at least everything won't go to ``Titanic''
again.
</P>
<P>
   WHIPP: And for that we can be thankful, although it really
wreaks havoc with our Oscar pool picks. But suspense is a good
thing. I can't remember the last time all the winners weren't a
foregone conclusion by the time of the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   This year, too, we have the added bonus of watching the show's
control-freak producers attempt to squelch all political
commentary. I can't wait to see the reaction shots they choose to
show when they hand Kazan his award. If there's one person standing
and clapping, you can bet they'll find him.
</P>
<P>
   STRAUSS: Especially if it's Roberto Benigni. I predict that
they're so enamored with the demonstrative Italian cut-up, they'll
zoom in on him after EVERY award is announced.
</P>
<P>
   Which leads to my first real prediction. Benigni wins best actor
for ``Life Is Beautiful,'' like he did at the Screen Actors Guild
Awards. Though the other nominees were just as good if not better,
Nick Nolte and Edward Norton were in films that were just too bleak
for academy sensibilities, Tom Hanks has won enough recently, and
Ian McKellen _ whose emotionally intricate work in ``Gods and
Monsters'' towers above the rest _ might make some radical gay
acceptance speech that, in the year of the Kazan controversy, the
academy just doesn't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   WHIPP: Which is as good a reason to root for him as any, not
that I need any motive other than his memorable, haunting
performance in ``Gods and Monsters.'' But Benigni will win, and
that's fine. Once he finishes kissing presenter Helen Hunt's feet
and twirling her around the stage, his acceptance speech will make
everyone feel that life, indeed, is beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   As for actress, it's probably between the two Elizabethan
performances. Cate Blanchett and Gwyneth Paltrow both won Golden
Globes, but Paltrow took home the SAG honors. She also comes from
the more popular movie and has Miramax's vast and somewhat
oppressive promotional push behind her. If the corset crowd splits
its vote, Fernanda Montenegro could sneak in. But I doubt it.
British accents, not foreign dialects, have always been the choice
here.
</P>
<P>
   STRAUSS: You're probably right, and that's a minor shame. Of all
the performances in the best actress category, ``Central
Station's'' Montenegro's stands out as being the least gimmicky _
no fancy costumes, no terminal diseases _ and the most stirringly
human. But Gwynnie gave a great, mind-bendingly multifaceted
performance in ``Shakespeare,'' and was luminous as all get out in
the bargain. She deserves the Oscar she's gonna get.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the supporting actress category seems a little
undernourished this year. I guess Kathy Bates has pulled ahead of
eight-minute wonder Judi Dench by virtue of being the only American
in the field, and her work in ``Primary Colors'' was quite, well,
colorful. The same can be said for Lynn Redgrave in ``Gods and
Monsters'' (although she channeled a bit too much of Mel Brooks'
black-and-white ``Young Frankenstein'') and Brenda Blethyn of
``Little Voice'' (though her garish performance was the acting
equivalent of an explosion at a paint factory).
</P>
<P>
   I'm going with homegirl Bates, although I'm personally not too
excited by anyone in this race.
</P>
<P>
   WHIPP: Blethyn's blare is still ringing in my ears, and I saw
the movie back in November. Why she's here and not Lisa Kudrow is
something I'll never understand. Maybe the British accent factor
... but it was so grating.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bates winning, yeah, sure, maybe. But I'll go with Dame
Judi and her glorious eight minutes. She didn't win last year for
``Mrs. Brown,'' and my guess is voters will try to remedy that
here.
</P>
<P>
   The supporting actor category might be the evening's biggest
free-for-all. Robert Duvall, like Dench, should have won last year
for ``The Apostle,'' so maybe the academy corrects its oversight
this time around. But then Ed Harris has never won,  &UR; !ital! &LR; period,
which is the ultimate oversight.
</P>
<P>
   A ``Shakespeare'' sweep could carry Geoffrey Rush _ minus those
hideous teeth _ to the podium, and if voters are in a sentimental
mood, maybe James Coburn gets his due. Billy Bob Thornton is the
most deserving of the bunch for his heartbreaking turn in ``A
Simple Plan.'' I'd give it to him, but something tells me that this
is finally Harris' year.
</P>
<P>
   STRAUSS: I feel just the opposite. Loved Billy Bob, and I think
he'll win simply because his was a co-starring, not really
supporting, role that just gave the voters more to like. But I
slightly preferred Harris' portrayal of Hollywood megalomania in
``The Truman Show,'' as precise a piece of acting as any I've seen
_ but probably too close to home for a lot of academy members to
feel comfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, in the director's competition, the only sure also-ran
is ``Truman's'' Peter Weir; if your film doesn't get a best picture
nomination, it's all but impossible to win this category.
</P>
<P>
   As for front-runner Steven Spielberg, his sure thing status
crumbled long ago. But it still seems incomprehensible that one of
the most impressive directing jobs of the decade could be
overlooked, despite the warm feelings many understandably have for
Benigni and ``Shakespeare's'' John Madden, whose movie about the
joys of writing and acting especially appeals to the academy's two
biggest voting blocs.
</P>
<P>
   Either of those two beating Spielberg could, I guess, be
acceptable. But if it turns out to be ``The Thin Red Line's''
insufferably artsy Terrence Malick, I'll organize a protest that'll
make the Kazan complaints look like a quilting bee.
</P>
<P>
   WHIPP: You won't be alone. One nominated writer nearly lost his
lunch when I told him I thought Malick would win in his category.
``That will really annoy me,'' he said. ``Because it's the only
truly awful screenplay in the bunch.'' My hunch is, he didn't like
the movie, either. Most simply found it artfully incomprehensible.
</P>
<P>
   However, many voters revere Malick and will want to give him
something for coming down from the mountain and making his first
movie in 20 years. So I think Frank will be the one doing the
protesting.
</P>
<P>
   As for director, Spielberg  &UR; !ital! &LR; is a sure thing, seeing as he
has the Directors Guild's seal of approval. And even though
``Shakespeare'' bested ``Ryan'' in terms of nominations, I think
the sword is mightier than the pen. ``Shakespeare'' is too light
for the academy to give it its most serious award. And ``Life Is
Beautiful'' will get its due in the foreign language category.
</P>
<P>
   STRAUSS: I wouldn't be entirely confident about that. Remember,
to vote in the foreign language category, a member has to see all
five nominated films, and those who have the time to do that tend
to be elderly and female. They could identify with ``Central
Station'' more readily than ``Life Is Beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, I wouldn't write the late-surging ``Life'' out of any
category _ except writing. Marc Norman and Tom Stoppard have the
original screenplay Oscar deservedly sealed and delivered for their
tirelessly clever ``Shakespeare'' script.
</P>
<P>
   In the other craft categories, I think the undeniably gorgeous
``Red Line'' has a shot at cinematography (though I'm rooting for
``Ryan''). Otherwise, they mostly get split between ``Shakespeare''
(art direction, costume design, musical or comedy score) and
``Ryan'' (film editing, makeup, sound, sound effects editing).
</P>
<P>
   WHIPP: It is a pretty even split. And I think ``Ryan'' will win
the war-film cinematography battle, even though John Toll's
windswept tall grass shots were beautiful, if a bit redundant. The
two films are top contenders for dramatic score, too. I preferred
Hans Zimmer's mesmerizing work on ``The Thin Red Line,'' but on a
hunch, I'm going with that
 &UR; !ital! &LR; other World War II film, ``Life Is Beautiful,'' to win.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Bob, and you know it pains me to say this, I am in
complete agreement with you on your craft category picks.
</P>
<P>
   STRAUSS: I salute your perspicacity. And if we're right, Oscar
math invariably has it that the top prize winner also gets the most
statuettes.
</P>
<P>
   So, despite all the drama and uncertainty of the past several
months, ``Saving Private Ryan'' is, as it has always been, the best
picture of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   If, I emphasize, we're right.
</P>
<P>
   WHIPP: We're right. I think.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
