<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HONG KONG ECONOMY LOSES MORE GROUND IN LAST QUARTER OF 1998 
</HEADLINE>
 (rk) 
 By   MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Confirming a dismal earlier prognosis, Hong Kong
said Friday that its economy shrank an estimated 5.7 percent in the
fourth quarter of 1998 and 5.1 percent over the whole year.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first full-year decline in economic output since Hong
Kong began keeping records in 1961, and it extends Hong Kong's
worst recession since World War II. Such news has become numbingly
familiar in the 17 months since the Asian crisis struck this
once-vibrant commercial center.
</P>
<P>
   What surprised economists was that Hong Kong's economy continued
to lose a lot of ground in the most recent quarter. Despite a
rebound in the stock and property markets, consumer spending
plummeted 9.3 percent. That was nearly as bad as the 10 percent
decline in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fourth quarter was a lot worse than we were expecting,''
said Ian K. Perkin, the chief economist at the Hong Kong General
Chamber of Commerce. ``The domestic spending figures were
dreadful.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the government attributed the weakness in
consumer spending to the unemployment rate of 6 percent _ also a
record high _ and to incomes, which are being frozen or cut by
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Perkin said the weak spending boded ill for this year, because
the government has pinned much of its hopes for an economic revival
on consumer confidence. In its recent budget, Hong Kong forecast
that domestic spending would grow 2.5 percent in 1999, fueling an
overall growth rate of five-tenths of a percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong will need a huge recovery in the second six months
of the year to meet those goals,'' Perkin said. He noted that
retail sales, exports and investment spending were all down so far
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Perkin said he would not revise his forecast that Hong Kong's
economy would contract another 1 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In what has become a pattern, Hong Kong's stock market
disregarded the bleak news _ rising nearly 4 percent, to 11,082.
Analysts said investors were encouraged by strong performances on
Wall Street and in Tokyo. They were also anticipating cuts in local
interest rates, which tend to strengthen the value of stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The government called the stock market's robust performance
proof that the economy was healing, despite the continued weakness
in spending. The spokesman also noted that the contraction in gross
domestic product in the fourth quarter was less steep than in the
third quarter.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In its 1999-2000 budget, Hong Kong hopes to resuscitate local
confidence with several high-profile spending projects. The most
prominent is Cyberport, a $2 billion office park and residential
complex for technology companies. The government is also in
advanced negotiations with Walt Disney Co. to build a theme park on
Hong Kong's Lantau Island.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts warn that the talks with Disney could founder. And
the Cyberport project faces opposition from big property owners,
angry that the government awarded the project to a company
controlled by the son of Hong Kong's most prominent tycoon, Li
Ka-shing.
</P>
<P>
   Some lesser tycoons complained that they were cut out of the
project. A few even charged the government with cronyism _ a rare
accusation in Hong Kong, where all the property developers
benefited more or less equally from the tremendous increase in real
estate values throughout the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Tsang, the financial secretary of Hong Kong, denied that
the government had shown favoritism in awarding the project to the
Pacific Century Group, which is controlled by Richard Li. The
developers are demanding that they be allowed to bid on at least
the residential part of the complex.
</P>
</TEXT>
