<HEADLINE>
&HT;       ONE PHILLY REP. TO ATTEND CIVILITY RETREAT
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;     By Lisa Fine   c. 1999 States News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, MARCH 19 -- There won't be any bipartisan bonding
amongst Philadelphia area lawmakers at this weekend's ``civility''
retreat for U.S. Congress members and their families in Hershey,
Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Only one member of the Philadelphia delegation, Republican
Congress member Jim Greenwood, plans to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Funded by the Philadelphia-based Pew Charitable Trusts, the
retreat was designed to help members of Congress from both parties
understand each other.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Rep. Curt Weldon, and Democratic Reps. Joe Hoeffel,
Chaka Fattah, Bob Borski, and Bob Brady, were not scheduled to show
up for the weekend activities.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer than half of the 435 members of the U.S. House of
Representatives were expected at the retreat, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there is some impeachment-related tension,'' said
Niko Yen, a spokesperson for Greenwood. ``Knowing him (Greenwood),
he probably went to the retreat to help bridge that gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Yen said Greenwood had no reaction to his colleagues' absences.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's up to them,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   So what could keep members of the Philadelphia delegation from a
free weekend of bonding in their home state? Spokespeople for the
Congress members gave the following reasons:
</P>
<P>
   Borski: ``family commitments.''
</P>
<P>
   Brady: ``a number of constituent obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   Fattah: ``scheduling conflicts.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoeffel: ``planned to attend, but came down with the flu.''
</P>
<P>
   Weldon: ``is attending a firefighters conference instead.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers hope the retreat will help Congress members work
together on pending issues like Social Security and Medicare
reform.
</P>
<P>
   But Weldon's spokesman Pete Peterson said some lawmakers don't
need to go to Hershey to learn how to work in the spirit of unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Weldon) typically works in a bipartisan effort anyway,''
Peterson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
