<HEADER>
A7327 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LIBYA-MANDELA-ART-NYT     03-19 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIBYA-MANDELA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIBYA SAYS IT WILL HAND OVER LOCKERBIE SUSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Libya told the United Nations on Friday that it
would hand over the two suspects in the 1988 Lockerbie bombing for
trial in the Netherlands by April 6.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Libya appeared to accept all the other conditions
the United States and Britain have said they wanted met before they
would consider lifting the economic sanctions the Security Council
imposed on Libya in 1992 because of its refusal to surrender the
two men.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter delivered on Friday to the United Nations, Libya's
leader, Col. Moammar Gadhafi, agreed that the suspects would be
tried under Scottish law by Scottish judges sitting in the
Netherlands. Any prison sentences imposed would be served in a
Scottish jail under U.N. supervision. Libya would post a consul to
Scotland who would have free access to the prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The two men are wanted for the bomb that destroyed Pan Am Flight
103, killing 270 people, while it was flying over the Scottish
village of Lockerbie.
</P>
<P>
   The Libyan offer was first disclosed earlier on Friday by
President Nelson Mandela of South Africa, who has acted as a
mediator in the dispute, during a speech in the Libyan capital of
Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
   But it was also conveyed in the letter delivered Friday to the
U.N. secretary-general, Kofi Annan, by Libya's representative,
Abuzed Omar Dorda, who said it contained all the points made by
Mandela.
</P>
<P>
   Dorda confirmed that the two suspects, Libyan intelligence
agents Abdel Basset Ali al-Megrahi and Lamen Khalifa Fhimah, would
be handed over to the secretary-general or his representative.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and British diplomats expressed satisfaction with President
Mandela's account of the Libyan offer but made plain that after so
many years of Libyan evasion, that nothing short of the surrender
of the two men would satisfy them.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration would take a close look at the
letter, a State Department spokesman said, but added that, ``What
we are going to be looking for is the actual turnover of the
suspects.'' Annan welcomed Mandela's announcement in a statement by
his spokesman, saying, ``The secretary-general is greatly
encouraged by this development and the necessary arrangements will
now be initiated by the Secretariat.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan thanked Mandela, as well as Crown Prince Abdullah of Saudi
Arabia, who also served as a mediator with Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Mandela, apparently reading from a copy of the letter
to Annan, said on Libyan television that Gadhafi would ``ensure
that the two suspects would be available for the secretary-general
of the United Nations to take custody of them on or before 6 April
1999.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``we are particularly hopeful that these
undertakings will put the secretary-general in a position to
expedite his report to the Security Council to have sanctions
against Libya finally lifted.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter goes on to say that Libya expects economic sanctions
to be suspended as soon as the two suspects reach the Netherlands.
They are to be lifted permanently 90 days later if Annan has
reported to the Security Council that Libya has complied fully with
all demands.
</P>
<P>
   In the letter, Libya also affirms its opposition to ``all forms
of terrorism'' and pledges ``cooperation with the investigation,
the procedures and trial within the framework of Libyan laws and
legislation.'' And it offers to pay compensation to the victims'
families if the suspects are convicted.
</P>
<P>
   But in return, Libya requested that the Security Council adopt a
resolution making the terms of this agreement binding on all
parties to the dispute _ possibly because it fears that the United
States or Britain, as permanent Security Council members, might
veto the lifting of sanctions after the suspects are surrendered.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear Friday night whether the Security Council would
go along with this request. But Dorda insisted Friday that this was
not a new Libyan condition for surrendering the suspects, but just
something that it favored.
</P>
<P>
   Libya had long resisted handing over the suspects, insisting
they would not get a fair trial in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Britain and the United States agreed to Libyan
proposals for a trial in a third country. Libya said it would be
willing to turn over the men over for a trial by Scottish judges in
the Netherlands, but then sought assurances that sanctions would
actually be lifted, and that the men, if convicted, would not serve
their prison sentences in the West.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Gadhafi told the Libyan Parliament that Libya had
received ``all the guarantees'' it needed through South Africa and
Saudi Arabia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
