<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0297 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7328 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-1stLEDE-0320-     03-19 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-1stLEDE-0320-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ADVISORY:
 &HT;    1STLEDE WRITETHROUGH TO INCLUDE REPUBLICAN COMMMENT
 &HT;    CLINTON TRIES TO SHUT, LOCK DOOR ON SCANDAL YEAR
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington category
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his first full-fledged news conference in nearly
a year, President Clinton on Friday delved with evident relish into
problems in Kosovo and China and skimmed over questions about the
controversy, sex scandal and impeachment that consumed his White
House for 15 months.
</P>
<P>
   Invited to discuss whether he leaves a legacy of lying for
American children, the president gave a tacit admission that he
hadn't told the truth about his affair with former White House
intern Monica Lewinsky. ``I think that what young people will learn
from my experience is that even presidents have to (tell the truth)
and there are consequences when you don't,'' he said in the East
Room.
</P>
<P>
   However, he brushed that failing aside, saying that ``there will
be a box score, and there will be that one negative.'' Emphatically
slicing the air with his hand, he asserted that there will be
``hundreds and hundreds of times when the record will show that I
did not abuse my authority'' and added that ``scores and scores''
of allegations had not been proved.
</P>
<P>
   With a barbed comment for his political foes and the press, he
added, ``I would hope that there would be a higher regard for
truth-telling by all people in public life and all those who report
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that bitter referral, the president declined to
answer questions stemming from the turbulence that nearly cost him
his job. He did not give a direct response to the charges of rape
leveled against him last month by Juanita Broaddrick in a televised
interview, relying on the denial issued by his lawyer, David
Kendall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a statement made by my attorney,'' Clinton said.
``He speaks for me, and I think he spoke quite clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's remarks brought a sharp rejoinder from Republican
National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nothing short of outrageous for Mr. Clinton to suggest
that his perjuries and obstructions of justice don't count because
he claims he's racked up a high 'box score' in other areas,'' said
Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it was disappointing to say the least that the president
refused to take this opportunity to address the charge'' that he
sexually abused Broaddrick in Arkansas 21 years ago, the Republican
chairman said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton deflected the Broaddrick question and
impeachment-related issues with a kind of ``Rose Garden'' defense.
Citing his promise given there last month, he said was turning his
full attention to ``the American people'' now that the Senate has
acquitted him.
</P>
<P>
   In that spirit, Clinton declined to defend his about-face on the
Independent Counsel Act, which he signed in 1994 and which his
administration now opposes. Clinton said that because he was a
target of an independent counsel, he would leave it to others to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he felt betrayed by former aides such as George
Stephanopoulos and Dick Morris, who have both written critical
accounts of his administration, the president ducked the question
by saying he had read neither book, nor any articles about them.
``So I have absorbed no pain, `` Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by press corps gadfly Sarah McClendon to say ``why you
think the people have been so mean to you,'' the president
responded with a joke about a man who fell into the Grand Canyon
and was hanging by a twig whose roots were slipping. Clinton said
the man asked, ``Lord, why me?....And this thunderous voice says:
'Son, there is just something about you I don't like.' ``
</P>
<P>
   However, Clinton was expansive on other subjects:
</P>
<P>
   Defending his administration's record amid charges that the
Chinese stole nuclear secrets from a U.S. weapons lab in the mid
1980s, Clinton said he was unaware of any leaks on his watch. He
dismissed a report by the Fox News Channel that China also obtained
technology for electromagnetic pulse weapons from several nuclear
labs during Clinton's first term.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the best of my knowledge, no one has said anything to me
about any espionage, which occurred by the Chinese against the
labs, during my presidency,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On prospects that first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton will run for
the Senate from New York, he said, ``I really don't have a clue''
on her decision but said she would be a ``magnificent senator.'' He
added that she had always urged that they move to New York after
the presidential term.
</P>
<P>
   On recent ridicule aimed at Vice President Al Gore for claiming
that he had fathered the Internet, Clinton said that his heir
apparent had been ``one of the major architects for America's
progress in technology'' and had been ``integral to the good
things'' of the administration. Clinton added that Gore has, in
fact, been too ``reticent'' to brag about his accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
