<HEADER>
A7342 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOC-GALAXYRESEND-LADN     03-19 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXYRESEND-LADN-(RESENDING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25) 
GALAXY PREVIEW
</HEADLINE>
 STORY ORIG. SENT FOR March(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The pressure will be on again in October _
this time more than before.
</P>
<P>
   For the next eight months, Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano will
prepare his team for the only games that matter _ the Major League
Soccer playoffs. That's when jobs will be on the line, particularly
his.
</P>
<P>
   The season begins Saturday with a game against Colorado at the
Rose Bowl, but the challenge will last long after that.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy has proved to be Major League Soccer's most dominant
franchise during the regular season. It set nearly every team
record imaginable a year ago _ most goals, least goals allowed,
most victories, most points and longest winning streak. In three
years, the Galaxy has captured two Western Conference
regular-season titles and reached the championship game once, in
1996. But that's where the hoopla ends.
</P>
<P>
   There was no championship in 1996, just a 3-2 overtime loss to
D.C. United after the Galaxy blew a 2-0 lead midway through the
second half. In 1997, the Galaxy was swept by Dallas in the first
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   A huge favorite to reach the final in 1998, the Galaxy was swept
by eventual champ Chicago in the Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year we want to win the championship . . . we expect to
win the championship,'' Zambrano said. ``Every year we have come up
short. We will forever be expected to win. If you don't, you have
to pay the consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   To add to the pressure, this may be the Galaxy's least
attractive team yet, at least while it embraces a youth movement.
</P>
<P>
   If disgruntled playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos misses any matches
because of his contract dispute with the league, a mixed group of
young and veteran Americans will hold the team's future in their
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Cienfuegos, 31, a holdout since training began in February,
reported to training camp Monday. However, he will leave town today
if a new contract isn't worked out, said his agent, Corey
Clemetson.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy is already without three other foreigners who were on
the club last season. Guatemala's Martin Machon, apparently at odds
with Zambrano, was loaned to Santos in Mexico in the last year of
his MLS contract, essentially ending his MLS career. Ecuador's
Wellington Sanchez was sold to an Ecuadoran club and Mexican
striker Carlos Hermosillo is expected to miss two months while he
finishes his season in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The expectations were raised under the new ownership of Philip
F. Anschutz, who purchased the club for $26 million in October. The
Galaxy will have to move forward with an inexperienced midfield of
Clint Mathis, Joey Franchino, Daniel Hernandez and veteran Danny
Pena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a competitive disadvantage (not having foreigners),
without a doubt,'' Zambrano said. ``We've already begun playing
with Clint and Daniel. It's not going to be the same Galaxy team,
but it doesn't mean it's going to be a less attractive team.''
</P>
<P>
   Mathis, expected to play a big role this season, has seen
valuable time on the U.S. National team under new coach Bruce
Arena. He said he and the others are ready to show that the Galaxy
can win with a predominantly American lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can play; a lot of people overlook the American players,''
Mathis said. ``This is a huge opportunity to see what kind of
talent we have, especially against other teams with plenty of
foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the only question anyone cares about is, can this
team win a championship?
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to say, can I win with a team that is all
Americans, I tell you a resounding yes,'' Zambrano said. ``Can we
win a championship? That's another question. That's another
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a saying in soccer that young players win games, but
experienced players win championships. I think with very few
exceptions in the history of soccer that has been true. Sometimes a
young team can win because of exuberance and dynamics, but at the
end of the day you need that experience that a bona fide foreign
player can give you to make that difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ecuadoran coach, in his second full season after guiding
L.A. to an MLS-best 24-8 record in 1998, says he isn't conceding
the season by any means. The Galaxy may lack foreign experience
until MLS allocates foreign-born players, but it has a wealth of
American experience.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is led by former U.S. National team defender Paul
Caligiuri and U.S. defender Robin Fraser, coupled with outside
defensive attackers Greg Vanney and Ezra Hendrickson.
</P>
<P>
   Though the midfield is young, U.S. Player of the Year Cobi Jones
is on the front line along with Welton, coming off his finest
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not just a bunch of young kids. We have a proper
balance, which is why I won't say this team can't win a
championship,'' Zambrano said. ``This season will serve as a
gaining of experience for a lot of our young guys who haven't had a
full season. Mathis, Franchino, Hernandez, Jolley, none of these
guys have had a full professional season under their belt.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 2017EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0299 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7343 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-BOMB-ART-500&AMP;A     03-19 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMB-ART-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB IN CAUCASUS KILLS 58, INJURES MORE THAN 100 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In one of the most devastating acts of violence in the
volatile North Caucasus region, a powerful bomb ripped through the
central pavilion at a downtown market in the city of Vladikavkaz on
Friday, killing 58 people and wounding more than 100.
</P>
<P>
   Top law-enforcement officials, who left Moscow to go to the
scene, said the explosion was ``unequivocally a terrorist act.'' A
grim President Boris Yeltsin, offering condolences to the victims'
families in a special television message, vowed to wage a merciless
campaign against those responsible.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing, coming on the heels of yet another brazen
kidnapping in nearby Chechnya and other violent episodes in the
region, was a reminder of how little control Moscow has over its
southern borderlands, which have been exhausted and impoverished by
wars and lawlessness since the breakup of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing was in the capital of northern Ossetia, which was
the scene of ethnic clashes between Ossetians and the Ingush in the
early 1990s that culminated in mass evacuations of Ingush and
lingering bitterness, with the situation exacerbated by criminal
gangs and an easy access to weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   But there was no indication Friday who was responsible for the
explosion, and no group claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   The scenes from the market shown on Russian television Friday
night looked like a massacre, with dismembered bodies strewn across
bloodied rubble. According to reports, 15 people were killed
instantly when the bomb went off at 11:40 a.m., near a stall where
two long lines of shoppers had formed to buy potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just come out of the cellar when a powerful explosion
went off,'' said one resident, interviewed Friday night on
television. ``I sat down, and when I got up again, I saw such a
horrible picture.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities in Vladikavkaz put out an urgent appeal for blood
donations, as the city's hospitals struggled to cope with the
steady flow of victims brought in from the market, most with
shrapnel wounds. Two of the wounded were children, television news
reported Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The timing and location of the bomb suggested that it had been
deliberately set to cause maximum damage and death. It was meant to
be ``intimidating and was aimed at destabilization,'' said
Alexander Zdanovich, spokesman for the Federal Security Services.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses reported seeing two young men running out of the
central pavilion shortly before the bomb went off. Both Sergei
Stepashin, Russia's interior minister, and Federal Security
Services chief Vladimir Putin arrived at the scene Friday afternoon
to start the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Vladikavkaz is near Russia's border with Georgia, and about 30
miles from Chechnya, the breakaway region that has been engulfed by
banditry and kidnappings since its 1996 victory in a war with the
Russian army. The violence in Chechnya has caused international
concern, particularly after kidnappers cut off the heads of four
employees of a British telecommunications firm.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Aslan Maskhadov, president of Chechnya, issued a statement
expressing condolences for those killed in Vladikavkaz, and
offering to assist in the search for the criminals. Maskhadov and
Russian Prime Minister Yevgeni Primakov had been scheduled to meet
soon to discuss cooperation in the region, particularly regarding
kidnapping and other crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Gen. Gennady Spigun, the representative of the Russian
interior ministry in Chechnya, was recently seized by gunmen who
took him off a plane on the runway at Grozny, the Chechen capital,
an act that worsened Moscow's relations in the region. In response
to the kidnapping, Stepashin, the Russian interior minister,
threatened to punish Chechnya's rebel warlords, and to impose
economic sanctions against the region if Spigun was not released.
Two weeks later, the general is still being held, reportedly for a
huge ransom, but Moscow has not followed up on its threats.
</P>
<P>
   Regional leaders have sought increasingly to take power in their
own hands, in some places organizing vigilante groups, in others
sidestepping federal laws. Chechnya itself, which has declared its
independence from Russia, has adopted the Islamic legal system, or
Sharia, and recently staged a public execution, even though Russia
has formally dropped the death penalty to comply with European
human rights standards.
</P>
<P>
   Regional leaders have implored Moscow to come up with a coherent
policy for the region, and to carry it through. ``Does Russia have
any policy in the Caucasus?'' Maskhadov, the Chechen president,
asked in a recent interview in the Moscow newspaper Komsomolskaya
Pravda. ``I have always wanted to find this out from Russian
leaders and never got any coherent answers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
