<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO PLANS THREE-PHASE ATTACK ON YUGOSLAV MILITARY TARGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Will update later with further details.) 
(See also KOSOVO-TALKS, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-CLINTON) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's plans for attacking Yugoslavia include a
series of missile and air strikes, beginning with attacks against
air defenses and escalating to more sustained strikes on tanks and
other heavy weapons, NATO and Clinton administration officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The initial strike, involving mostly cruise missiles, would be
``short and intense,'' in the words of one official.
</P>
<P>
   It would aim to knock out Yugoslavia's network of land-based
missiles and anti-aircraft weapons, which would clear the way for
strikes by U.S. and NATO fighters and bombers. But the initial
attacks are designed to persuade the Yugoslav leader, President
Slobodan Milosevic, to end his crackdown in Kosovo province before
additional strikes begin.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic continues to resist, the officials said the second
and third phases are designed to destroy much of the heavy weaponry
_ tanks, armored personnel carriers and artillery batteries _ that
Yugoslav army and police forces have used to destroy villages and
drive civilians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes would be intended to ``level the playing field''
between the Yugoslav forces and the ethnic Albanian rebels in
Kosovo. ``It would be very difficult for him to continue to do what
he's doing once you've leveled the playing field,'' one NATO
official said of Milosevic. ``If you don't have artillery, it's
really hard to bomb villages.''
</P>
<P>
   Any NATO attack appeared to be at least days away. It was not
clear Friday what would prompt the NATO attacks. At his news
conference Friday, President Clinton said, ``I think that whatever
threshold they need to cross has been crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the officials said they expected at least one last effort at
diplomacy. While many officials described NATO's plans as if
strikes were inevitable, others said there was still a chance that
Milosevic might back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that the history of Milosevic's behavior is
to blink when faced with a real threat,'' one senior Pentagon
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Washington declined to discuss the military
planning in detail, citing the need for operational secrecy. But
their willingness to discuss NATO's plans broadly appeared to be an
effort to demonstrate the administration's resolve in the face of
Milosevic's continued resistance to a peace settlement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
