<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANGEROUS SELECTIVITY ABOUT RULES OF GLOBAL TRADE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In peacetime, Washington starts trade wars. First
there was the Battle of the Bananas, still being slugged out across
the Atlantic. Then came the gleaming edge of steel, a fight that
pits the workers of Weirton, W.Va., against their counterparts in
Brazil, Russia, Japan, Korea and China. For this week, the White
House has scheduled a beef over hormone-treated meat.
</P>
<P>
   Listening to the rhetoric here in recent weeks, it would be easy
to conclude that there is a theme to these epic struggles:
enforcing the rule of law around the globe. All nations, the White
House and Congress proclaim, must learn to live by the trading
guidelines established under international treaties.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes this argument has the ring of sincerity about it. At
other moments, like some last week on Capitol Hill, it smacks of
disingenuousness and even rank political hypocrisy. Usually there's
a little of both.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the issue that has turned NATO allies into economic
enemies: yellow fruit. The Clinton Administration argues that this
only looks like a laughable argument over a product neither grown
in America nor picked by American workers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they acknowledge somewhat sheepishly, Washington is doing
the bidding of Carl H. Lindner, the chairman of Chiquita Brands.
Lots of industries complain about their treatment abroad, but
Lindner, a big contributor to Democrats and Republicans alike, has
been more skilled than most in getting the political establishment
to take up his cause _ no easy task when barely a single American
job is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that Lindner has a legitimate complaint. The World
Trade Organization has consistently ruled that Europe discriminates
against bananas grown in Central America, where Chiquita has long
held sway, and in favor of those grown in Caribbean countries that
were European colonies not long ago. Europe has openly defied the
rulings, tinkering with its banana imports but never solving the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the administration decided to hit Europe where it
hurt, slapping 100 percent tariffs on luxury goods, including _
this is where it really gets nasty _ pecorino cheese. You could
feel the chill in Zabar's.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who has spent far more time on the banana
issue than one might expect of the leader of the free world, says
the real issue is the rule of law. ``If we're going to have a
global trading system and a system for resolving disputes,'' he
said recently, then Europe is going to have to learn to obey WTO
decisions. ``I think most people in Europe believe we shouldn't
have won, but sometimes we lose cases we think we shouldn't have
lost,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He meant to be lecturing the Europeans, but the message hasn't
exactly sunk in on Capitol Hill. American lawmakers, like their
European counterparts, believe it is vital to obey the rules _
except, of course, when they run counter to American economic
interests; then they are an intolerable interference with American
sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   That explains how the House, in an overwhelming 289-141 vote on
Wednesday, passed some of the most protectionist legislation in 60
years. It directed the administration to limit steel imports from
other nations by any means necessary _ quotas, tariffs or
``voluntary'' agreements with other countries. The House bill is
unlikely to become law, but it sent a clear message heard around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone in Congress knows that setting unilateral import
limits violates the treaty that established the WTO four years ago
_ a treaty the Senate ratified. But the logic that won the day
belonged to George Becker, the president of the United Steelworkers
of America, who said a series of White House steps to punish
countries that ``dump'' low-cost steel in the American market was
not enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steelworkers and steel communities hold dear the notion that
America's trade policies should benefit Americans first,'' Becker
said. ``That may be a novel idea in some quarters, but it was a
winning idea today in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   America first is a thrilling campaign line, but Republicans and
Democrats alike recognize the likely reaction: counter-retaliation,
in equal disregard of the WTO's rules. It is one of the rare issues
on which Treasury Secretary Robert E. Rubin and Dick Armey, the
House majority leader, actually agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dangers of drifting _ or in this case, racing _ toward
protectionist policies are very real,'' Armey said. ``Let's not kid
ourselves. It will not make anything better; in fact, it will make
things much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a warning worth remembering this week as American
negotiators try to strike a deal with China on its entry into the
WTO. Why would America want a country that may be stealing weapons
designs, and is certainly imprisoning dissidents, inside the
organization that sets the world's trade rules and judges who is
violating them? Not as an act of charity, but to enmesh China's
leaders in a system that sets some standards of international
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   But which is more powerful, the standard or the example? When
Beijing is faced with deciding whether it must comply with
unpopular rules that may cost its workers jobs, it is likely to
look closely at how Washington handles the same problem.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
