<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7364 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INVEST-ACTIVIST-ART-$     03-19 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-ACTIVIST-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN ACTIVIST SHAREHOLDER TAKES ON THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21)  
 (af)  
 By HILARY ROSENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert A.G. Monks, money manager and shareholder rights
proponent, has long been a sort of Lone Ranger of American
investing, charging in to exhort companies to change their ways in
the name of helping shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Now, profligate managements abroad are starting to pay heed to
Monks, who is 65. The Lens Fund, the institutional investment
vehicle he runs, is being folded into Hermes Pensions Management, a
British concern with 40 billion pounds ($65.3 billion) under
management that is owned by a giant pension fund, BT Pension
Scheme.
</P>
<P>
   He will help oversee investing at Hermes Lens International,
which will be a holding company for the Lens Fund, soon to be
renamed to reflect its new status.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal's closing, which is imminent, the Lens fund will
have a big-name backer. With new asset contributions from Hermes
and extra marketing, the fund's assets under management will likely
rise to about $220 million, from $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, Hermes Lens International will oversee UK Focus, a
joint fund of Hermes and Lens which Monks already helps manage. It
has been active since last October and has about 150 million pounds
in assets. Monks said Hermes Lens International would manage a
family of funds, with new offerings in Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Monks, at an age when others ponder retirement, choose
this new effort? Because it is a mission. ``What I do is make power
accountable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With its extra resources, the United States fund plans to step
up its activities. There is plenty of corporate mismanagement
about, Monks said; he contends that the strong economy has hidden
many sins, which will eventually come to light.
</P>
<P>
   One red flag is executive pay levels. Monks said excessive
compensation signals that a company's board is not truly
independent of its management.
</P>
<P>
   Monks' brand of activism amounts to a kind of value investing.
Lens buys large positions, typically under 5 percent, in a few
underperforming companies and then tries to persuade their
managements to make changes that Monks expects to benefit
shareholders. If they won't, he rallies others with proxy fights or
takes his arguments to the news media.
</P>
<P>
   Lens' investing style pays. In six years of operation, through
Dec. 30, 1998, it returned 25.1 percent a year, on average,
compared with 20.5 percent for the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock
index.
</P>
<P>
   Monks ``is the founder of the modern corporate governance
movement and certainly its most effective advocate,'' said Richard
Schlefer, the director of corporate governance at TIAA-CREF, the
giant retirement fund.
</P>
<P>
   Lens now owns shares in six United States companies, and, this
month, Monks started a campaign for a board seat at Juno Lighting,
a lighting fixtures manufacturer based in Des Plaines, Ill., in
which Lens has a 6.7 percent stake. Lens began buying Juno shares
in October 1997, at just over $18.
</P>
<P>
   There are two problems at Juno, Monks said: Nearly half of its
assets are in cash and only one of its five board members is an
independent outsider. Juno did not return phone calls last week
seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   In an analysis early last year, Lens stated its belief that Juno
stock could rise to $31 a share if it put its cash to work. Juno
shares closed on Friday at $20.875.
</P>
<P>
   One successful investment has been Reader's Digest Association.
Given its declining profits and lack of independent outside
directors, it seemed an ideal stock pick for Lens. Although a pair
of charitable foundations control the company as holders of the
voting class of shares, Monks felt that Lens could influence the
situation, so the fund started buying shares in December 1997 at
just over $23 for each A share.
</P>
<P>
   He has been pleased with the actions of the new chief executive,
Thomas O. Ryder, to add independent directors, sell some noncore
assets and reduce costs. Monks had figured the stock was worth $34
a share when he started buying; it is now at $34.875. Lens has
taken some profits on the position.
</P>
<P>
   In Britain, the UK Focus fund holds eight stocks. One is Mirror
Group, a media conglomerate whose chief executive, David
Montgomery, recently resigned after UK Focus led a campaign seeking
his ouster because shareholders had lost confidence in him.
</P>
<P>
   The fund started buying Mirror shares in October at about 140
pence ($2.28). They closed on Friday at 204 pence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
