<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7365 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-I-VILLAGE-ART-$AD     03-19 0738
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-I-VILLAGE-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)  
 A SHIFTING LANDSCAPE AT THE iVILLAGE OFFERING  
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)   (af)  
 By SANA SIWOLOP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A good deal or not? That is the vexing question investors were
asking last week about the initial public offering of iVillage, the
No. 1 on-line network for women.
</P>
<P>
   As of last Monday, iVillage was set to go public at a price of
$12 to $14 a share. With some 23.2 million shares outstanding, that
would have given it an initial market value of as much as $324.8
million.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, iVillage's lead underwriter, Goldman, Sachs,
raised the expected range to $22 to $24 a share. That would have
given iVillage a value of as much as $556.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, the first trade was at $95.875, valuing the
company at $2.22 billion. (The company sold 3.65 million shares,
and they closed on Friday at $80.125).
</P>
<P>
   Valuing any Internet stock is frustrating. But in iVillage's
case there are a couple of extra worries. First is a lawsuit,
brought in January by a former employee over terms of an employment
contract. Two weeks ago, a former chief financial officer of the
company filed a declaration in the suit in which she accused
iVillage of ``inappropriate'' accounting.
</P>
<P>
   There is also new competition. Since last fall, Microsoft, the
Conde Nast unit of Advance Publications and others have either
entered the women's Internet market or increased their presence.
Most worrisome is a joint venture announced in January by the
Hearst Corp. and Women.com Networks. The two operated the second-
and third-most popular Web sites for women. (Hearst's half was
Homearts.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Given Friday's closing price, Steven Tuen, director for research
at IPO Value Monitor, a research firm in New York, said there would
be profit-taking over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts think iVillage can make it in the long haul. And
that, for those who didn't get in on the initial offering, may be
what matters most.
</P>
<P>
   Gail Bronson, an analyst for IPO Monitor, a research firm based
in Los Angeles, said: ``iVillage was the first to market in the
category. They have a sterling underwriter; they have built some
strong strategic partnerships.''
</P>
<P>
   Though networks for women typically provide access to experts on
topics like cooking and careers, iVillage's strategy has been to
offer women a place to chat among themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, it has worked. According to iVillage's prospectus,
the company had 170,000 registered members at the end of January
1998, but 960,000 by December. And iVillage managed to more than
double its sales last year, to $15 million, from $6 million in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Media Metrix, a New York firm that tracks Internet traffic,
estimated that iVillage had 3.16 million visitors in January,
compared with 2.37 million for Homearts and 1.68 million for
Women.com. And iVillage signed a promotional contract with NBC last
fall that analysts say will give it a huge visibility boost.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many Internet sites, where revenues are generated by
potentially fickle advertising and sponsorships, iVillage finds a
growing percentage of its revenue _ currently 17 percent _ coming
from the sales of products like baby items, books, horoscopes and
chocolates.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to use part of its offering proceeds to expand
its majority ownership position in iBaby Inc., an on-line retailer
of baby items.
</P>
<P>
   Still, iVillage is no widows-and-orphans stock. Losses are
growing, to $43.7 million in 1998 from $21.3 million a year
earlier. And they will continue for the foreseeable future, the
prospectus says.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, competition will probably intensify. According to
Media Metrix, the combined ``reach'' of Women.com and Homearts _
the portion of Web users in the United States that visited their
sites at least once _ was 6.5 percent in January; iVillage's reach
was 5.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Maintaining revenue growth may also turn into a challenge.
Despite healthy prospects for the on-line market for women, Ms.
Bronson thinks it is unlikely that iVillage can keep doubling
revenues annually. So after the stock's initial pop, iVillage
investors had best do the traditional thing and keep a close watch
on the company's competitive position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
