<SLUG> BC-LILLY-MIGRAINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LILLY TO STOP DEVELOPING MIGRAINE DRUG  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Japan)   By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eli Lilly &AMP; Co. announced Friday that it would end development
of an experimental migraine drug that had been billed as a
promising new method to treat the monster headaches.
</P>
<P>
   While analysts applauded the move _ the market for migraine
drugs in the United States is one of the industry's most
competitive _ shares of Lilly extended their slide of the last two
weeks, falling 1.5 percent, or $1.375, to $87.4375.
</P>
<P>
   The recent slump is a sharp reversal from the first two months
of the year, when Lilly's stock was among the biggest gainers in
the pharmaceutical sector. Since reaching a 52-week high on March
5, the shares have fallen 10.2 percent. For the year, Lilly is down
1.62 percent, compared with a 5.7 percent gain for the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's announcement had a greater impact on Synaptic
Pharmaceutical Corp. of Paramus, N.J., which had been developing
the migraine compound with Lilly. Synaptic shares plunged 44.3
percent, or $5.1875, to $6.50. The migraine drug was one of
Synaptic's leading compounds.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Lilly said Friday that the migraine drug was
dropped because of toxicity seen in animal studies. He said,
however, that Lilly and Synaptic Pharmaceutical would continue to
collaborate on other uses for that class of drug.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, Lilly is very strong,'' said Sergio Traversa, an
analyst with Mehta Partners. ``The company is very picky about the
drugs it develops. The company has done nothing wrong. This is just
a bad period.''
</P>
<P>
   The bad period began two weeks ago, when The Wall Street Journal
and other newspapers reported that the Federal Trade Commission had
expanded an inquiry into the trade practices of several drug
companies, Lilly among them.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the inquiry, the commission is looking at Lilly's
licensing arrangement with Sepracor to sell a purified version of
Prozac, Lilly's popular antidepressant, people involved in the
investigation said. The investigation is still in its early stages,
these people said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, S.G. Cowen Securities lowered its 1999 sales
estimates for Prozac to $2.93 billion from $3.05 billion. While
many analysts said it was too early in the year to make such a
projection, Lilly's stock tumbled 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   A Lilly spokesman said Friday that the company did not comment
on the movement of its stock.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent slide in Lilly's stock, most analysts remain
bullish on the company.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when most major pharmaceutical companies are looking
at possible merger opportunities, Lilly does not need such a deal,
many analysts say, because of its strength in drugs in the
pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the most promising drugs are Actos, a diabetes pill made
by Takeda Chemical Industries in Japan, which Lilly will market in
the United States and another drug to treat diabetic macular edema
and retinopathy.
</P>
<P>
   Provided that the diabetic pill is approved by the Food and Drug
Administration, some analysts estimate that the drug's sales may
reach $2 billion. It is unclear what money Lilly will receive for
Actos through its arrangement with Takeda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
