<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PREPARES AMERICAN PEOPLE FOR POSSIBLE AIRSTRIKES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton tried to prepare Congress and the
American people Friday for possible NATO airstrikes against Serbian
forces in Kosovo after peace negotiations collapsed between ethnic
Albanian rebels and the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
   Although he gave no indication of when military action might
occur, his remarks suggested it could be imminent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to put a single American pilot into the air. I do
not want anyone else to die in the Balkans. I do not want a
conflict,'' Clinton said, acknowledging that U.S. planes could be
shot down if they try to penetrate a ``strong air defense system''
maintained by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's military.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Clinton suggested that the loss of U.S. lives would
be justified in order to stop what he said would certainly be
``more massacres'' of innocent civilians if the United States and
its allies fail to act.
</P>
<P>
   ``In dealing with aggressors in the Balkans, hesitation is a
license to kill. But action and resolve can stop armies and save
lives,'' Clinton said during his first extended solo news
conference in 11 months. He warned Milosevic to return to the
negotiating table or he would do ``whatever is possible'' to weaken
his ``ability to massacre'' innocent people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now only President Milosevic stands in the way of peace,''
Clinton said, noting that the ethnic Albanians have signed on to a
peace deal to end the fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Citing the atrocities committed in Bosnia by Serb forces before
NATO took action there, Clinton said he would not wait until ``we
have thousands more people slaughtered and buried in open soccer
fields before we do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the immediate humanitarian concerns, Clinton also sought
to justify military action as necessary to prevent the ethnic
conflict in Kosovo from spilling over into Europe, which he said
would inevitably draw the United States into war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a conflict with no natural boundaries. It threatens
our national interests,'' he said, noting that America's future in
large part depends on a ``stable, humane and secure Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton laid out his justification for action after a two-hour
meeting at the White House with 31 members of the House and Senate,
who urged him to seek congressional approval before ordering
airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the lawmakers, including Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison,
R-Texas, left the meeting convinced NATO is on the verge of acting
because of Milosevic's refusal to sign a peace agreement with
Kosovo Albanian separatists. The agreement would authorize
commitment of up to 28,000 allied ground forces to Kosovo as
peacekeepers. Pentagon officials have said that 4,000 U.S. troops
would be part of that mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what Milosevic is planning ... If Milosevic
starts to take human lives that is going to provoke a very swift
response,'' Hutchison said in a Senate floor speech following the
White House meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is sobering time,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has set a debate Monday and Tuesday on Kosovo,
including an amendment by Hutchison that would prohibit funding of
U.S. involvement in a peacekeeping mission until Clinton presents
Congress with a plan, complete with a deadline for ending it.
</P>
<P>
   Although most lawmakers left the White House meeting still
unconvinced that military action is necessary, they called it a
``positive step'' that the president sought their advice. Emerging
from the meeting, they urged Clinton to do more to inform the
American people of what is at stake in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a high potential of American men and women coming home
in body bags,'' said Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho. ``The American
people don't understand what's going on over there or the magnitude
of our involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., said he could not support military
action unless Milosevic's forces begin ``a very significant
massacre'' of civilians in Kosovo. To act before then, he said,
would amount to an invasion of a sovereign nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us to initiate an action such as bombing Serbia is really
an act of war, and I don't know that it has reached the threshold
where we should be taking that type of military action against
them,'' Nickles said.
</P>
<P>
   In his news conference, Clinton said the Serbs had already
crossed that threshold by continuing to kill innocent civilians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to do what we can to prevent further atrocities,''
the president said.``I hate to think we would have to see a lot of
other little children die before we can do what seems to me to be
clearly the right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   A number of lawmakers did offer conditional support for
airstrikes, contending that the credibility of NATO is on the line.
They asked Clinton to seek congressional support first, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on the brink of a very grave situation,'' said House
Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill. ``Can NATO stop massacres right in
their own back yard? Can NATO ignore some of the tests of history
in ignoring what's going on? I don't think NATO can do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Joe Biden of Delaware, the ranking Democrat on the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee, said, ``The outcome of non-action is
clear: Milosevic will engage in ethnic cleansing, the number of
refugees will be in the magnitude of tens of thousands, the region
will be destabilized, and our interests will be badly hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic continued his massive buildup of military power on the
Kosovo border Friday that Pentagon officials estimate at 40,000
troops. NATO began beefing up its own forces in the region and all
non-essential U.S. Embassy personnel are being evacuated from the
Serbian capital of Belgrade. International observers in Kosovo,
including 126 Americans, also were ordered out in anticipation of
NATO action. A State Department spokesman said evacuations likely
would be completed by the end of Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Defense Secretary William Cohen ordered several
more fighter aircraft and refueling planes to the region to join
200 U.S. aircraft already on standby.
</P>
<P>
   Up until Thursday, Clinton was still hopeful that Milosevic
would sign on to a Washington-brokered peace accord that would give
the Kosovars limited autonomy as part of Serbia and allow NATO
forces to enter Kosovo as peacekeepers. But representatives of the
Belgrade government walked out of the meeting Friday in Paris,
calling the agreement a sham and vowing never to allow foreign
forces on what they consider to be sovereign ground.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Clinton's strong words, most lawmakers said they believe
he may put off action until next week in order to give the
Russians, who have long been allies of the Serbs, and a group of
European diplomats one last chance to convince Milosevic to accept
the peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
