<HEADLINE>
STATUE TO HONOR WOMAN WHO RAN UNDERGROUND RAILROAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Under the cloak of darkness, Harriet Tubman would
arrive on Beacon Hill, a woman with a bounty on her head _ wanted
more dead than alive for spiriting slaves to freedom in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of the Underground Railroad, Tubman spoke here often,
a small woman who commanded the attention of men during a time when
women were supposed to sit and listen. Her fiery words galvanized
abolitionists, both black and white. After Emancipation, she
continued to return, speaking on behalf of women's rights.
</P>
<P>
   When old age kept her from the lecture circuit, her voice fell
silent. Though she is one of a few black historical figures
recognized by most Americans, there are few tributes to her.
</P>
<P>
   But, in Boston's South End, where a statue of her will rise in a
tiny park that bears her name, Tubman is making history again.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-foot-tall bronze sculpture memorializing Tubman will be
the first statue on city property recognizing an African-American
woman. It is also the first on city-owned property honoring a
woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's high time,'' said Mildred Farrell, executive director of
the Boston Art Commission. ``It's a blessed event, not just because
it's a woman but because it's a woman of color in a neighborhood
known for its diversity.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday the city breaks ground on the park, now a fenced grassy
area the size of a half court, with concrete steps that descend to
an empty pit.
</P>
<P>
   At the entrance of the park, the statue of Tubman will beckon
visitors. Clutching a Bible, Tubman stands astride, her eyes toward
heaven. Her outstretched hand summons five adults, including a
mother cradling an infant, all following her on the journey to
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Sculptor Fern Cunningham, an art teacher who lives in the city's
Dorchester neighborhood, spent three years creating the statue,
which is now being bronzed at a Johnston, R.I., foundry.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the park, a 1913 statute called
``Emancipation'' will be installed _ the only monument in America
to freed slaves created by a black artist, Meta Warrick Fuller. It
depicts a freed man and woman emerging from a tree trunk near a
weeping figure which represents humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Fuller described her work this way: ``Humanity (is) weeping over
her suddenly freed children who, beneath the gnarled fingers of
fate, step forth in the world, unafraid. The Negro has been
emancipated from slavery, but not from the curse of race hatred and
prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Though African-Americans have made strides in the decades
following the Civil Rights struggle, taking up issues of
institutional racism that Emancipation left undone, the fact that
it took until 1999 for the city to memorialize a black woman speaks
volumes about what America views as historically significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at African-American heroes, people who have been
important to our history to our development, they have been largely
ignored,'' said Cunningham, who spent months studying Tubman's
legacy. ``The problem with American history is that the history is
founded upon the destruction of the lives of certain people. The
clash is created in how we shall interpret history.''
</P>
<P>
   She said it's difficult for Americans to recognize Tubman as a
hero, because she stands in contrast to leaders like George
Washington and Thomas Jefferson, both of whom owned slaves. In
Jefferson's case DNA testing suggests he fathered children with one
of his slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the American dilemma: Who is a hero?'' Cunningham
said.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial to Tubman, she said, is also overdue in other parts
of the country. Cunningham said there are small statues honoring
Tubman in Auburn, N.Y., where she lived before she died in 1913,
but few elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   When her statue, ``Step on Board,'' is dedicated June 20 it will
be the largest Tubman monument in the country.
</P>
<P>
   While Tubman's statue is the first of an African-American woman,
and the first of a woman on city-owned property, there are two
other statues honoring women in Boston, both, however, are on state
property. Both remember women as victims.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the east wing of the State House, a statue remembers
Mary Dyer, who was hanged in 1660 for being a Quaker. Another
statue, on the south lawn, pays tribute to Anne Hutchinson, who was
banished for her religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Tubman, unlike Dyer and Hutchinson, will be remembered for
winning her battles, said Frieda Garcia, president of the Harriet
Tubman House of United South End Settlements, a community center in
the South End. Garcia said Tubman outfoxed the bounty hunters,
sneaking more than 300 fugitives from slavery in Maryland to
freedom in Canada, and inspiring the abolitionist movement to
continue the struggle. She lived a long life, passing away at 92.
</P>
<P>
   Tubman's tenacity and emboldened spirit is what Cunningham
strived to capture in her sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Intially I thought of having her sitting down, but the more I
read about her, I thought she should be standing, and in motion,
she should be pulling people along,'' Cunningham said. ``I wanted
to convey the emotion and tension of her moving people along.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
HARRIET TUBMAN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Her date of birth is unknown, but 1820 is widely believed to
be the year of her birth. She was born a slave in Maryland on a
Dorchester County plantation.
</P>
<P>
   --Tubman died March 10, 1913 in Auburn, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   --Born Araminta, she changed her name to her mother's name,
Harriet. Her achievement in freeing slaves earned her the names
``Moses'' and ``General Tubman.''
</P>
<P>
   --She has been described as an abolitionist, nurse, preacher,
reformer, and spy.
</P>
<P>
   --In 1844, she married a free man named John Tubman.
</P>
<P>
   --She escaped from slavery to Philadelphia for fear that her
family would be separated after the plantation owner died.
</P>
<P>
   --She returned in 1850 to free those family members she left
behind. Within two years she helped 11 men, women and children to
freedom in the North along the Underground Railroad. Over time she
successfully helped 300 black men and women escape.
</P>
<P>
   --She established The Harriet Tubman Home for the Aged and
Indigent in Auburn, N.Y. after serving as a nurse during the Civil
War.
</P>
<P>
   --In 1869, she was remarried to Nelson Davis, a Civil War
veteran, and continued to devote herself to numerous projects for
black people and the suffrage of women.
</P>
</TEXT>
