<HEADER>
A7375 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-ENTREPRENEURS-ART-     03-19 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ENTREPRENEURS-ART-3TAKES-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GONG SHOW FOR START-UPS, THE BEST BUSINESS PLAN WINS 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Ill., Conn., Calif., N.Y., Mo., Mich., Texas, Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
(af) 
By JAMES SCHEMBARI  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere outside the surreal economic world where 23-year-old
entrepreneurs become $25 million executives lies the economy of
everybody else, where smart people with good ideas struggle for
years and then are never heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   At the junction of those worlds lies the prospect of good
television.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money Hunt,'' a public television program produced in
Connecticut, has figured that out. By aiming a camera at people who
by their very nature can talk endlessly about their ideas and then
pitting them against each other, the producers have created 30
minutes of sometimes corny, yet compelling, television. The program
is now broadcast in most major markets around the country (55
stations over all).
</P>
<P>
   The format is simple. Two entrepreneurs pitch their businesses
to the show's two hosts and a guest executive _ someone like Guy
Kawasaki, a longtime software executive at Apple Computer, or Brian
Maxwell, the founder of Powerbar, maker of food bars marketed to
athletes, who started a $100 million company in his kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneurs are grilled on their business plans, and then
the guest executive picks a winner. The prize is an on-air
presentation of the executive's business card, handed over as if it
were a gold cup, and a promise of an hour of his or her time
whenever the winner wants to ask for advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to wait until I have some crucial question,'' said
Cora G. Yang, of IQ Foods, a company in Downers Grove, Ill.,
moments after winning her match at a recent taping. (Ms. Yang,
whose company makes V.G. Burger vegetarian burgers, defeated Debra
Root of Mrs. Malibu Gourmet Natural Foods, a Malibu, Calif., maker
of low-fat peanut butter.) ``It's like having a fairy godmother,''
Ms. Yang said. ``I'm not going to squander it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Money Hunt'' is riding the explosion of entrepreneurship in
the American economy. For the 26 guest slots in its new season, the
program received about 1,000 applications on its Internet site
(www.moneyhunt.com). Its producers say they are negotiating
agreements that would allow local versions of ``Money Hunt'' to be
made in Japan, Europe and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   All this for a program that had a quiet start. It first appeared
on a public access cable channel in Connecticut in 1996 and moved
to public television a year later. But even though it now has major
sponsors like Pricewaterhousecoopers and Yahoo Finance, ``Money
Hunt'' still has a ``Wayne's World'' feel to it.
</P>
<P>
   The program was created by Cliff Ennico, a lawyer who once
worked on Wall Street, and Miles Spencer, an investment banker,
friends who live near each other in Fairfield County, Conn.; the
headquarters are in an office attached to Spencer's home.
</P>
<P>
   The nautical-themed set was designed by Spencer's wife; his
mother, a former soap opera extra, sometimes operates a camera. And
in keeping with the entrepreneurial theme, Spencer's dog is named
Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   The men in charge made themselves the program's hosts, but it
doesn't take long to observe that television is their second
language. They are often awkward, and their one-liners seem forced.
In acknowledgment of their lack of TV experience, they have hired a
coach to help develop their on-air personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Ennico, 45, who looks like a college English professor, is the
funny one. Spencer, 35, with all the smoothness and confidence of
the guy who sold you your Mercedes, is the serious one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not Louis Rukeyser,'' said Wai Wah Chin, an adviser to
the program and a senior vice president of Charterhouse, an
investment firm in Manhattan. ``In the early stages they were
thinking of doing something with a gong, but I think they were
joking.''
</P>
<P>
   But the attraction of ``Money Hunt'' has nothing to do with its
creators' personalities; it comes in those intense few minutes when
they are peppering an entrepreneur with questions. It is obvious
that the hosts have done their homework, and even though they are
smiling, they can be merciless.
</P>
<P>
   To a clothing designer: ``Your plan calls for $70 million in
sales in 2002. Isn't that a little aggressive?'' and ``How do you
control quality if so much of your production is sourced out?''
</P>
<P>
   To an executive of an Internet company: ``You appear to have a
significant reliance on service revenue versus licensing fees. Do
you see that as a potential inhibitor to the growth of the
company?''
</P>
<P>
   And to the founder of another Internet company: ``What's your
competition on the Internet?'' After an uncomfortable silence and
the answer that there were about 2,000 similar sites, Spencer said
of the man's concept, ``I'm not really buying any of it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Many of the guests seem to enjoy the confrontation, saying it is
similar to making a presentation to venture capitalists, although
it's over much faster. They often parry the questions with answers
that once again explain how great their ideas are.
</P>
<P>
   During a week when ``Money Hunt'' is being taped, entrepreneurs
come in from all over the country, and because three shows are
usually taped at a time, there are six entrepreneurs going in and
out of the Norwalk, Conn., studio all day. These people don't just
nod hello to one another. They gather in the greenroom and talk
about their businesses, bragging about their products and handing
out brochures like grandparents passing around pictures of their
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``You want people to catch your fervor,'' explained Allen
Miller, who was appearing on the program and is the founder of
Corporate Carrier Networks, an Irvine, Calif., company that sells
back-office software to telecommunications companies.
</P>
<P>
   When the guest executive arrives, it's as if Bill Gates had
walked into the room, because here is someone who was once where
they were and is now where they so desperately want to be. Forget
about a vague prospect of an hour of his time later; here's the guy
now.
</P>
<P>
   In a room full of entrepreneurs, nobody's shy. Ms. Yang and her
husband, Mark Barnekow, the chief executive of their natural foods
company, talked to Maxwell of Powerbar about how to instill the
entrepreneurial spirit in employees. The three of them shared
stories of developing their products in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would never get the opportunity to sit with Brian like
this,'' Ms. Yang said. ``It's worth its weight in gold.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Root, who had whispered, ``Don't worry, I'm going to hit him
up,'' shortly after Maxwell arrived, leaned forward in her seat and
told him why her peanut butter would be wonderful in a Powerbar. He
listened politely.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell shrugged off the attention, saying he was happy to offer
advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the other side of the table 12 years ago,'' he
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Scott, a co-founder of Nantucket Nectars and another of the
new season's guest executives, did not mind being pounced on,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how I am when there are people who can be helpful to
me,'' acknowledged Scott, whose venture turned a fruit drink recipe
into a multimillion-dollar company. ``I don't have any incredible
insights. I've just been through the battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The show is almost an extension of the action in the greenroom.
It moves fast and sometimes everybody tries to talk at once. The
questions and answers come so quickly that the guest executive,
whom the show calls a mentor, sometimes has to struggle to get in a
comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we started rolling, I saw that I would have to dive
in,'' Maxwell said of the program on which he appeared. ``There
weren't any gaps. It made for pretty good television.''
</P>
<P>
   After both entrepreneurs have been grilled and have stepped off
camera, but are still well within earshot, the hosts and mentor
discuss the companies as Siskel and Ebert used to discuss movies:
agreeing, disagreeing, sometimes rolling their eyes at each other.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of offering thumbs up or thumbs down, Ennico and
Spencer defer to the mentor for the verdict. Maxwell picked Ms.
Yang. Scott, in his guest appearance, chose Chris Lohring of
Tremont Brewery in Boston, saying he felt he could help Tremont
more, even though the company it was up against, the on-line Kosher
Grocer Inc. of Brooklyn, had more short-term potential.
</P>
<P>
   Deborah Alexander, co-founder of Kosher Grocer, said later that
she didn't think Scott understood her business. Still, she left the
show feeling encouraged and has since received e-mail from Spencer,
offering advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two hosts favored my business plan, but the mentor didn't,
which is a very realistic reaction to anybody's business plan,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Cowsert not only didn't win in his recent appearance on
the program; he had to sit on the set and explain why his company
went bust. Cowsert had been on the program last season and been
beaten by an electricity reseller. Now the hosts had invited him
back for a bit of show and tell, cautioning other entrepreneurs on
what to avoid. (``He was in a train wreck,'' Spencer confided
before the taping.)
</P>
<P>
   Cowsert's company, Newstar Collaborative Technologies in St.
Louis, had developed teleconferencing software and was doing pretty
well until Microsoft and Netscape Communications got into the
business. Now Cowsert is, well, doing something else, but he said
he was happy to go over some do's and don't's.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can always tell the pioneers by the arrows in their
backs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ennico said people have gone on the show with some unusual
ideas. He remembers a man who wanted to set up an Internet site
where people could mix and match existing music to make customized
compact disks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded great; he really had his technology down,'' Ennico
said. ``There was one problem. He didn't have a deal with the major
record companies, and he couldn't understand why they wouldn't be
interested. Our mentor had to explain, in no uncertain terms, why
they wouldn't be.''
</P>
<P>
   The entrepreneurs say they hope their appearance on the program
will attract investors, but that doesn't seem to happen often. CMS
Technologies of Livonia, Mich., which provides tracking and
security systems for computer networks, said that after the
appearance of one of its executives, an order was placed by a
Princeton University official who had been watching the program,
but no investors called.
</P>
<P>
   Investors did contact Doug Monahan, founder of Sunset Direct, a
computer sales and marketing company in Austin, Texas, but he
turned them down. He did, however, hire Pricewaterhousecoopers, a
Money Hunt sponsor, as his accountant after the show.
</P>
<P>
   Lucinda Duncalfe, chief executive of the Destiny Software Corp.,
a Conshohocken, Pa., company that creates Internet systems for the
financial services industry, said she heard from only a few
individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Venture capitalists don't look at TV for deal flow,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Petersen of Rhino Naturals, a company in Los Angeles
that makes liquid dietary supplements, said he did hear from an old
school friend after appearing on the program.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``We've met with a dozen investors since we taped the show, and
I've asked if any of them saw it, and they all said no,'' Petersen
said. ``So I don't know who's watching it except my high school
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Haney, who is on the advisory board of a group in
California that invests in nascent companies, said when asked about
the program: ``I never heard of it.'' One executive at a venture
capital firm in the San Francisco Bay area, who spoke on condition
of anonymity, said he had seen ``Money Hunt'' but dismissed it as
an infomercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you're going to come across an insomniac investor who's
up at one in the morning, but you're not going to attract important
investors,'' he said, referring to the program's midnight Sunday
time slot on KQED, a public television station in San Francisco.
The program is seen in the New York area on WLIW, Channel 21, at
12:30 P.M. Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Bachemin, the program publicist for KQED, said that about
14,000 households tune into the program, although many may be
taping it. The main audience, she figures, is other entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty good for midnight,'' she said of the audience.
``The programmers think it's because the Bay area is such an
entrepreneurial area. They want to see what other entrepreneurs are
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom O'Malia, director of the Greif Entrepreneurship Center at
the Marshall School of Business at the University of Southern
California, said he had seen the program and felt that it provided
a valuable service by spotlighting entrepreneurship.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the focus on money disturbed him. As a prerequisite
for starting a business, he said, money is overrated, and many
entrepreneurs fall into the trap of handing over too much of their
businesses to get it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all read about the heroes that made it, but many try to go
from the minor leagues right to the major leagues,'' O'Malia said.
``They go right into the money business instead of being
entrepreneurs. Of all the myths of entrepreneurship, perhaps the
greatest is that you need a lot of money to start a company. You
don't. I mean, Apple started with $1,600.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Money Hunt,'' of course, is all about money, and the show is
itself an entrepreneurial enterprise. As one mentor said moments
after a taping finished, ``Someone should do a ``Money Hunt'' on
`Money Hunt.' '' Spencer certainly has plans to expand the
television franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will be a puddle of a man if I don't end up with commercial
distribution of this enterprise,'' he said, suggesting that ``Money
Hunt'' could be shown on the Fox network before football, on CNBC
on the weekends or on CNN. ``We're a little public TV show now, but
that's just where we'll be from.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he sees potential beyond television. The two hosts
have written a book about entrepreneurs, still untitled, for Harper
Collins; it is due out in the fall. Spencer also would like to find
a way that he and Ennico might profit from one of the program's
most valuable assets: the information on all those applications
from entrepreneurs that is sitting in their computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are some of the fastest-growing companies in the United
States,'' he said. ``It's a heck of a data base, and the most
attractive option is assigning the deals to pools of capital.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though many entrepreneurs reported little response from
potential investors to their appearances on the show, Spencer said
he was already getting calls from investors about some of his
guests and was using his investment banking skills to match the two
sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``I skim the cream,'' he said. ``Last year I generated six
figures in fees. I'm very opportunistic, but there's always another
bus coming in two minutes. Right now, I have buses lined up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
