<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7378 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-19 1264
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOWER STANDARDS FOR ATHLETES? A NO BRAINER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've got another Proposition for Judge Ronald L. Buckwalter of
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Check out the test scores of these so-called ``deprived''
athletes when they are leaving college.
</P>
<P>
   Buckwalter is the federal judge who threw out the NCAA's
Proposition 16 college entrance requirements for athletes, saying
``African-American and low-income student-athletes have been
disproportionately impacted'' by the standards on classroom grades
and standardized test scores.
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 48, which evolved into Prop. 16, was adopted in 1986
and placed tougher entrance requirements on athletes. The ruling
attempted to limit schools from accepting any athlete as long as he
or she could play.
</P>
<P>
   If the judge has his way (the NCAA is appealing) there would be
no limits as to how low a college could go academically to bring in
an athlete at the Division 1 and 2 levels.
</P>
<P>
   That would be a disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has been using the Wonderlic testing system for years to
mentally evaluate college players eligible for the draft.
</P>
<P>
   The Wonderlic Personnel Testing company has been used by close
to 40,000 businesses around the nation. The average score is a 22.
</P>
<P>
   The average score of an NFL player this year is 15.
</P>
<P>
   The average score for a custodian is 14. A 15 is well below
average intelligence. And these are the results of players who have
been on college campuses for four years, supposedly learning.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those with scores 15 or lower _ even with four years of
college _ cannot read. The Wonderlic test is timed, and you have to
be able to read quickly.
</P>
<P>
   These results seem to dispute the judge's theory that these
students, who are under Prop. 16 standards, would go to college and
do well.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   All lowering the standards will do is make a bigger mockery of
college athletics than already exists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This past week, I went out to dinner with one of the top general
managers in the NFL, a man who has scouted football talent on just
about every college campus in the country. The subject of the
basketball scandal last week at Minnesota came up, where a woman
tutor revealed she had written papers and taken tests for players
for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why does everyone seem so surprised?'' the GM said. ``It
happens in just about every school that plays big-time sports in
America. These kids don't study. They don't do their own papers.
Someone else is taking tests for them. It's a joke. Some of them
come to us and can't read or write. What have they been doing for
four years?''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've coached players,'' said one of the most veteran coaches
in the NFL, ``who couldn't read or write. These are the guys that
have a tough time getting a driver's license, because they can't
read the book. They don't know how to open a bank account or write
a check, or what a mortgage is. It's a shame. Most of them are good
kids. I believe in trying to educate the `D' student, but the
question is how do you do it? They cannot handle the load of a
typical college student. So you have to find something for them
that they can use later in life.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, those are the lucky ones. The ones with a chance to play
pro football, or pro basketball, make some money, and have some
kind of life. What happens to the average players who have nowhere
to go when they are finished?
</P>
<P>
   The players would be better served if the colleges had to
guarantee that they would be able to read, write, and have at least
some minimal nonathletic skills before they leave school. Make them
take a version of the Wonderlic test. If they fail, the number of
scholarships allowed that school would be reduced in subsequent
years.
</P>
<P>
   How about the student who doesn't play sports? Parents are
paying $30,000 per year in some top schools, and these kids have to
earn their way, while the athlete is given the tests ahead of time,
and some secretary or manager in the athletic department writes the
athletes' term papers?
</P>
<P>
   About four years ago a defensive lineman, now playing in the AFC
East, came out of a junior college after two years, played one
season in college, didn't go to class, and was drafted the next
spring. Ditto for an offensive tackle who played at Florida State.
I remember Deion Sanders saying he never attended a single class
his entire final year at Florida State, and yet he played every
game.
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks ago in this space, we reprinted a part of Derrick
Lewis's deposition in the Reggie Lewis lawsuit. Derrick Lewis
played for Northeastern for four years, admitted under oath he
didn't have any life skills, and ``rarely'' went to class. How was
he allowed to stay in college for four years if he rarely went to
class? How did he stay eligible to play basketball?
</P>
<P>
   Big-time college sports, football and basketball, are an
academic joke at many big-time schools. They are continued solely
to make money. Bringing in more kids who are less qualified isn't
going to make things better, either for the school or the athlete.
In almost every case, he won't have an education when he leaves,
either.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Reggie Lewis case: can his lawyers be serious
when they say they are looking for upwards of $100 million in
damages, because that is what Lewis would have made the rest of his
life as a former Celtic captain and a potential coach in the NBA?
Someone should ask former Celtic captains of the past how much
money that title made for them in the future. Zip. And as for
Reggie being a future NBA head coach, that's a laugh. Reggie was
too laid-back and easygoing to ever be a head coach in the NBA or
anywhere else. Lewis died during a workout at age 27 of a heart
attack. The medical reports say his heart condition was
deteriorating. There was no way he was going to play or coach at
the NBA level with a heart condition that was so serious he
couldn't survive a workout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even though Instant Replay passed easily at the NFL meetings in
Phoenix this week and will be reinstated next year, several coaches
are waiting to see what happens to the ``whistle'' call.
</P>
<P>
   When the league was using Instant Replay as an officiating tool
years ago, the ``whistle'' became the popular cop-out for tough
calls on the field. The game officials got out of situations by
claiming ``the whistle blew'' before the play in question
concluded. There was no way to prove it didn't. For example, in
this year's Green Bay-San Francisco playoff game (won by the
49ers), Jerry Rice fumbled in the closing seconds. Green Bay
recovered and should have won. But the officials missed the call.
Instant replay could have overturned the call. However, the
officials later said that the whistle blew before the recovery,
obviously to take some sting out of the bad call. The inadvertent
``whistle'' would have overruled replay in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One small step for man, one costly leap for Max Lane. Word is
the Patriots guard had to come up with $600,000 out of his own
pocket to settle his end of the Paradise Club mosh-pit incident.
That's after-tax money, which means Lane has to make about $1
million to be left with the $600,000 to pay the injured woman . . .
Here's what is wrong with sports today. The NFL owners spent a
total of 27 hours in meetings over 3 1/2 days this past week. Two
of those hours were on football. The rest on money.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
