<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7380 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAFETERIA-NYT &LR;      03-19 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAFETERIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLD-TIME D.C. CAFETERIA THREATENED BY RISING RENT AND CHANGING
TASTES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ How about the liver and onions for $2.25? Or fried
whiting, the most expensive entree on the menu, for $3.95? For
dessert, the pudding will set a diner back only 65 cents, or he can
splurge, with homemade rhubarb pie for $1.65.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see, I had liver and onions, mashed potatoes with gravy,
the pineapple-lettuce salad and lemon meringue pie,'' said John
Kendrick, a retired professor at George Washington University who
has been eating at Sholl's restaurants since he moved to Washington
in 1941. ``For all that, I think I paid $5.45. Maybe it was $5.50
but no more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   For home-style cooking, reasonable prices and a friendly
atmosphere, there is nothing else in the nation's capital quite
like Sholl's Colonial Cafeteria at 20th and K Streets downtown. As
an old-fashioned slide-your-tray-along-and-keep-the-line-moving
kind of place, there may be few like it anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, in a month or two, the last of the Sholl chain of
cafeterias, serving institutional cuisine for 71 years, might
follow the automat and tailfins into cultural oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   As Washington's economic fortunes and downtown rental rates
rise, the owners of the office building where the last Sholl's _
there once were eight of them _ has operated for 20 years are
asking for a 20 percent rent increase above the current $20,000 a
month, by early summer, to bring Sholl's more in line with other
businesses in the neighborhood. Sholl's 10-year lease expired this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The demand has not only forced George Fleishell, 71, the
cafeteria's majority owner and nephew of the founders, Evan and
Gertrude Scholl, to contemplate closing the cafeteria, it also has
brought sadness and defiance among devoted customers, some of whom
have formed a group to fight to keep the cafeteria open.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is totally outrageous,'' said Jim McGrath, a retired
analyst at the Library of Congress and chairman of the Save Our
Sholl's Committee, who describes his mission as ``a labor of love
and a labor of anger.''
</P>
<P>
   McGrath has called for another strategy session on Saturday
morning at the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``The treatment these people are getting is beyond belief,'' he
insisted.
</P>
<P>
   Brian McVay, a senior managing director for the company that
manages the building, Cushman &AMP; Wakefield, said through a
spokeswoman, Sheila Peck, that policy precluded him from discussing
negotiations in progress.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the ambiance and affordability of Sholl's, and
its place in Washington's culinary history _ the Trumans, Nixons
and Carters ate at Sholl's _ few people might care about its
closing. But Fleishell and his predecessors always have
demonstrated a certain civic conscience, keeping prices low enough
for the poorest of residents while attracting high-priced lobbyists
and lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need a place like this in the city,'' said Robert Cutts,
an official with the Federal Communications Commission who was
eating lunch with his wife, Barbara. ``It would be a loss to the
city if it closed, if for no other reason than people of modest
means can come here to get a good meal and be treated with respect,
the same as anybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   The same expectations also have kept Sholl's popular with people
like Ted Barnhill, a professor of finance at George Washington.
Barnhill eats lunch at Sholl's several times a week, drawn by the
simplicity and wholesomeness of the food. ``If you want to eat
hearty,'' he said, ``this is a great place.''
</P>
<P>
   But low prices can only account for so much. Tastes and trends
change. Washington's downtown is rife with ethnic and fast-food
restaurants, and Fleishell said he had noticed a precipitous
decline in the number of meals served over the years. Since the K
Street cafeteria opened 20 years ago, he said, the lunch crowd, for
example, has dropped to 600 people from 1,800.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have raised some prices on occasion,'' Fleishell said.
``One of the most popular things used to be filet of haddock, at
$2.95. Now, it's too expensive to handle. I'd have to charge $7.''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly what anyone can do to save Sholl's remains a question.
Harold Brazil, a member of the City Council, said he might write a
letter to the owners. Sen. Max Cleland, D-Ga., who first visited as
a student at American University, is serving as honorary chairman
of the Save Our Sholl's Committee to call attention to the
situation. McGrath said friendly persuasion might encourage the
building owners to lower the rent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Albert B. Krachman, Fleishell's lawyer, concluded that it might
come to public embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the outflow of support, the landlords should see this
as a chance to get a great public image, contribute to the
community and become a hero,'' Krachman said. ``Or they could close
a public institution that's been around for 71 years, put people
out and be regarded as an oppressive pariah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
