<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-UCONN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-STAKES GAME FOR CONNECTICUT WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ So what if the Iowa State women's basketball team
is the underdog? Don't say the Cyclones have nothing to lose, or
that they should just be happy just to be in the NCAA tournament.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of talk drives Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never understood the theory that you have nothing to lose,''
he said Friday. ``You have a game to lose. I don't understand that
mentality.''
</P>
<P>
   The same goes for University of Connecticut coach Geno Auriemma,
who said, ``I hate it when teams say they have nothing to lose. We
have a national championship to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   So both teams know the stakes are high Saturday when they face
off in the NCAA Mideast Regional.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-seeded Iowa State (24-7) last weekend beat Santa Clara
and Oregon to advance to the game against the University of
Connecticut (29-4). It is only the third time that 19th-ranked Iowa
State has played in the NCAA tournament, and the first time the
Cyclones have made it to the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   The top-seeded Huskies, ranked No. 4 nationally, have been to
the NCAA tournament 11 straight times and have a 6-0 record in
Sweet 16 games. They moved into the regionals with an 86-84 win
over Xavier Sunday, where freshman Tamika Williams scored the final
2 points.
</P>
<P>
   Fennelly, said his team is inspired by that game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Xavier played loose, they played to win,'' he said.
``We've looked at that tape a lot, and that's given our kids some
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   And with no seniors on its roster, confidence is what Iowa state
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Fennelly is banking on the shooting of sophomore guard Stacy
Frese, who leads the team in scoring (17.3 points per game) and
free-throw percentage (.838), and leads the NCAA with 49 percent
3-point shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have great guard play to win at this level,''
Fennelly said, adding that Frese's toughness means as much as her
scoring.
</P>
<P>
   During a game in late November, she severely sprained an ankle
during the first half, but came back to play in the second half
(she missed the next four games). In a Big 12 tournament game two
weeks ago, Frese got knocked in the head, and the trainer told
Fennelly that the guard would be out for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I look down the bench and she put herself back in the
game,'' he said. ``It's like a running back who gets tackled and
lays there you don't think he's going to get up, then he gets up
and runs for 30 yards for a touchdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Frese said she's aware that she'll be the prime target for the
Huskies, who are known for attacking the top scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, teams have been doing that to me all season, but if they
try and take me out, I'll just try and get the ball to the other
people who are out there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fennelly said he's also looking out for UConn's offense, led by
junior Shea Ralph (17.2) and Big East player of the year Svetlana
Abrosimova (16.8 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want our offense to be their offense,'' he said. ``I'm
not worried about length of time to bring the ball up, and the
shots, I'm worried that when we turn the ball over, it's a layup
drill for them.''
</P>
<P>
   If UConn wins, it would be the sixth season in a row that
Auriemma has led his team to at least 30 wins. But he said that's
not a record he cares about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've only been in the Final Four two of the past five
years,'' he said. ``So if we win and it's 30, and we lose Monday,
I'm not going to be a happy camper.''
</P>
<P>
   The second Mideast Regional game pits No. 2 seed and ACC
champion Clemson against No. 3 seed Georgia. Clemson, ranked 10th
nationally, set the school record for wins with a 26-5 record this
season. Georgia, which is making its 16th trip to the NCAA
tournament, is ranked 12th nationally. Its leading point scorers
are sophomore guards _ and twin sisters _ Coco (19.1 points per
game) and Kelly Miller (18.1 points per game).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
