<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7382 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-19 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: IN CREDIBILITY GULCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Over the last year the United States and NATO have repeatedly
warned and threatened Slobodan Milosevic. Stop your assaults on the
people of Kosovo, we have told the Yugoslav president, or we will
carry out air attacks on Serbian forces there and elsewhere in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has treated the threats contemptuously, as bluffs. And
that is what they have been so far. The record is an object lesson
in how not to conduct policy, with heavy costs:
</P>
<P>
   _ The credibility of the United States, in particular that of
President Clinton, has been severely damaged in the world.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO's credibility has also been badly hurt. Its leaders will
gather in Washington a month from now to celebrate its 50th
anniversary; but unless the Kosovo humiliation has somehow been
reversed, it will be a strange celebration.
</P>
<P>
   _ The 90 percent of Kosovars who are of ethnic Albanian origin
have paid a terrible price in human terms. Hundreds of thousands
have been displaced from their homes. Many of their villages have
been destroyed by Serbian forces.
</P>
<P>
   The policy failure is the more remarkable because Clinton
ignored the overwhelming lesson of past dealings with Milosevic.
That is that you must act immediately when he starts killing
people, or things will get worse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991 President Bush and his secretary of state, James Baker,
did nothing when Milosevic's army shelled Croatian cities. Their
empty excuse was that it was a matter ``for the Europeans'' _ who
of course would not act without American leadership. Milosevic went
on to the murderous war in Bosnia, with Bush and then Clinton
dithering until, finally, the Dayton peace conference was convened.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic began his killing in Kosovo one year ago, when Serbian
artillery and tanks pulverized several villages. At that point
action by the United States and NATO _ limited bombing _ would have
stopped him. But there was only empty talk, so he turned the screw
further.
</P>
<P>
   Last June NATO sent its planes over Macedonia and Albania, which
border Kosovo, in a demonstration that was supposed to impress
Milosevic. But again he called the bluff.
</P>
<P>
   In October NATO was ready to use force. But we accepted instead
a promise by Milosevic to observe a cease-fire on terms negotiated
by Richard Holbrooke. Milosevic never complied with the terms.
Starting at Christmas, the Serbs escalated the killing, including a
terrible massacre of civilians. Now they have large additional
forces ready to attack.
</P>
<P>
   By bluffing and delaying, Clinton has greatly increased the cost
of any eventual intervention. A year ago limited bombing would have
been enough. Then the plan became heavy bombing. Now it calls for
NATO ground forces, including 4,000 Americans, to keep the peace if
and when Milosevic agrees to our proposal for Kosovo autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   But suppose he does not agree. Suppose he is prepared to suffer
heavy bombing. Suppose he retaliates with even more savage attacks
on Kosovo Albanian civilians. What do we do then?
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has said that American ground forces
will go into Kosovo only if there is a permissive environment. What
is our plan if the environment is one of Serbian political and
military resistance?
</P>
<P>
   After the folly of the last year, there is no easy option. But
the worst would be to do nothing. That would intensify terror in
Kosovo. It would threaten to destabilize all of the Balkans. And it
would devastate the credibility of NATO and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will have to say more than he did at his press
conference Friday to convince Congress and the American public of
the cost of doing nothing in Kosovo. He will have to convince us,
too, that he has, and will carry through, a serious, long-term
policy directed at the source of evil over many years: Slobodan
Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has responded to our diplomacy in the past only when
we were serious about the use of force. Holbrooke got him to Dayton
because our bombs were falling on the Bosnian Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hesitation is a license to kill,'' Clinton said at his press
conference. It is better for him to learn that late than never.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
