<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NCAA-UCONN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN FACES BIGGEST LITTLE HURDLE TO FINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ You're Jim Calhoun. You're 40 minutes away from taking
your UConn team to its first Final Four appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike previous years when teams such as Duke, North Carolina,
and UCLA had blocked your path, all that is standing in your way is
a small, 4,500-student Jesuit school from Spokane, Wash., that the
tournament committee thought was only the 10th-best team in the
NCAA West Regional.
</P>
<P>
   At every press conference the past two weeks, the question
always centers on what you haven't done _ not what you've
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   You smile when the failures in regional finals are mentioned
rather than all the wins _ an average of 26 a year for the past 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   You smile some more when it is mentioned that this looks like
your best chance to reach the Final Four, since you have the best
team in the region. No one questions that.
</P>
<P>
   You know that no team in the regional can beat you. You've known
that since the bracket was announced two weeks ago. You know that
you will have to lose Saturday's final against Gonzaga rather than
the Bulldogs winning it.
</P>
<P>
   You know that you won your first two tournament games as
expected against Texas-San Antonio and New Mexico, and things
looked even better when you came here last Sunday in what has been
an extended spring break vacation/business trip.
</P>
<P>
   But then you look at the bracket, and you can only shake your
head. Facing you is Iowa, which not only is a very good team but is
on a crusade because its coach, Tom Davis, has been told that he is
no longer needed and has turned into the grand old master of the
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   You hold your breath and get past that game, carving out a tough
78-68 win, you don't see a 10th-seeded team in your future. You see
Cinderella in sneakers. Instead of being the focus of sympathetic
cheers, wishing you well in your bid to overcome this invisible
barrier, you are now Goliath against David.
</P>
<P>
   Someone asks if this is some sort of test that fate has planned
for you.
</P>
<P>
   You sit back, smile, and nod your head. ``Let's put it this
way,'' you say, ``if we get there (to the Final Four), I think I
can skip purgatory.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless Calhoun's No. 1-seeded Huskies take care of business as
expected against Gonzaga, there are places that some people will
want to send Calhoun that Dante himself might fear to tread.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night's victory over Iowa in a game that had World
Wrestling Federation overtones, Calhoun said he got a call from
former assistant Howie Dickerman (now the coach at Central
Connecticut), ``Howie said the entire state was humming,'' said
Calhoun, who also said he was not sure what that actually meant.
</P>
<P>
   All of it, of course, is in anticipation of what most people
think will be UConn's 32d victory in 34 games.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun and the Huskies have had to fight the perception that
they merely have to show up at America West Arena and the coveted
Final Four berth will be handed to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is perceived as a David-and-Goliath game,'' said Calhoun.
``It's perceived, but it is not.''
</P>
<P>
   Said guard Khalid El-Amin, ``We have heard of Gonzaga. We saw
them in the power ratings all year.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn has been ahead in those same ratings all season, which is
why there are such high expectations it can accomplish what it
couldn't do in 1990, when Duke's Christian Laettner made his
game-winning shot; or in 1994, when a pair of missed foul shots by
Donyell Marshall could have won the Sweet 16 game against Florida;
or in 1995m when eventual national champion UCLA beat them in the
West Regional; or last yearm when North Carolina beat them in the
more-than-friendly confines of the Greensboro (N.C.) Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun was asked what he had learned from all of those
experiences, all of those disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned to make sure that Christian Laettner doesn't get
into the game,'' said Calhoun, just warming up. ``I learned to make
your foul shots at the end of the game and don't get involved in
overtime. I learned that you don't get involved in a shootout with
UCLA and don't go to Greensboro if you get a chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides that, I didn't learn anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Satuday afternoon, with the country watching and most of it
rooting against him and his team, Calhoun will learn if he is as
lucky as he is good, and if he is going to finally get to the Final
Four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
