<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN POLICY DOMINATES AT CLINTON PRESS CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the possibility of NATO air strikes grew more
likely Friday, President Clinton began laying out the case for
military action in Kosovo, declaring that ``hesitation is a license
to kill.''
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that US and NATO pilots would be put in
harm's way if such steps are taken, he said, ``Make no mistake, if
we and our allies do not have the will to act, there will be more
massacres.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments came at his first solo news conference with
the White House press corps since April in what was a postscript to
a scandal-ridden year and an example of how the climate in
Washington has changed in the five weeks since his acquittal by the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy matters dominated the hourlong exchange, but
among the few nuggets Clinton offered was that his wife suggested
more than a year ago that they move to New York after his term as
president. And concerning speculation that First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton might run for the Senate from New York, the
president said, ``I literally don't have a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he and Mrs. Clinton were ``working hard'' to repair
their marriage strained by the sex scandal. ``We love each other
very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton fielded about two dozen questions ranging from lessons
he has learned after lying about an affair with Monica S. Lewinsky,
to accusations of Chinese espionage at US nuclear laboratories, to
the ridiculing of Vice President Al Gore over his claims that he
invented the Internet, to his reaction to criticism from former
aides who say they no longer think he is fit to be president.
</P>
<P>
   On Kosovo, Clinton blamed the possibility of military action on
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosovic, who has not signed a peace
agreement accepted this week by Kosovo's Albanian rebels. ``Only
President Milosevic stands in the way of peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have massed their troops. They have continued to take
aggressive action. They have already leveled one village in the
recent past, killed a lot of innocent people. I do not believe that
we ought to have thousands more people slaughtered and buried in
open soccer fields before we do something. I think that would be
unfortunate, if we said we have to have a lot more victims before
we can stop what we know is about to happen,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Expressing his personal distaste for a possible military action
in Kosovo, Clinton said: ``I do not want to put a single American
pilot in the air. I do not want anyone else to die in the Balkans.
I do not want a conflict. I would give anything to be here talking
about something else. But a part of my responsibility is to try to
leave to my successors an environment in Europe that is stable,
humane and secure. It will be a big part of America's future.''
</P>
<P>
   On the impeachment crisis, the president, reminded of the George
Washington allegory on the importance of truth-telling, said he
hoped young people will learn from his experience that even for
presidents ``there are consequences when you don't'' tell the
truth.
</P>
<P>
   He called his lying ``one negative'' in his box score. ``And
there will be the hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of times when
the record will show that I did not abuse my authority as
president, that I was truthful with the American people, and scores
and scores of allegations were made against me and widely
publicized without regard to whether they were true or not. Most of
them have already been actually proved false.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he said, ``I would hope that there would be a higher
regard for truth-telling by all people in public life and all those
who report on it. I think it would be a very good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton refused to go beyond his attorney's previous denial
that he allegedly raped an Arkansas nursing home operator more than
20 years ago when he was the state's attorney general. The woman,
Juanita Brodderick, recently came forward to tell her story.
``There's been a statement made by my attorney,'' the president
said. ``He speaks for me, and I think he spoke quite clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he had ``absorbed no pain'' from highly critical
books written by his former aides, including a recent one by former
senior adviser George Stephanopoulos, because he had not read them
or any articles about the books. However, he said, ``I very much
value the loyalty and service I have received from the overwhelming
majority of the people who have worked here.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended his adminstration's handling of suspected
Chinese espionage at US nuclear labs in the 1980s. On Thursday, he
ordered a review of the security threat in the wake of suspicions
that China stole nuclear weapons technology from Los Alamos
National Laboratory in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Of the FBI investigation, begun in 1996, he said, ``It is my
understanding that the investigation has not yet determined for
sure that espionage occurred. That does not mean that there was not
a faulty security situation at the lab. The security procedures
were too weak for years and years and years.''
</P>
<P>
   He also defended US dealings with China, saying, ``Our
relationship is not perfect, but I think it is the correct
course.'' And he denied that the administration was slow to act or
that its response was influenced by contributions from
Chinese-Americans to his reelection and other Democratic campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   On Gore, Clinton defended his vice president, who has been
taunted for claiming he invented the Internet and opening his
presidential campaign in Iowa without mentioning his priviledged
upbringing in Washington as the son of a senator, but instead
talking about how he slopped hogs, drove mules, built homes and
cleared land by hand with a double-bladed ax.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came a lot closer to inventing the Internet than I did,''
Clinton quipped. ``As far as his boyhood home,'' the president
added, ``I know what you're saying. You're saying, well, he went to
St. Alban's and his daddy was a senator. But it's also true that he
is from East Tennessee and he did learn to do all those things on
the farm.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton passed up the chance to reflect on his feelings about
the impeachment process. ``I think it's best for me not to focus on
that now,'' he said. ``It seems to me that anything I say or do, or
any time I spend ... on that will detract from my ability to be an
effective president.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked why people had ``been so mean'' to him, Clinton
laughed and told a joke about a man who is walking along the Grand
Canyon and falls off, but sees a twig and grabs it, and then sees
the roots of the twig start to come loose. The man asks the Lord
why him, and ``this thunderous voice says, `Son, there is just
something about you I don't like.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Turning more serious, he said, ``Whatever happens, I have been
blessed in my life. Most of us leave this life further ahead than
we would be if all we got was justice...I wouldn't trade anything
for having had the opportunity to be president and do the work I
have done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
