<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARR     03-19 0573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-GARCIAPARRA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GARCIAPARRA TROUBLED BY SORE ARM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ It may be nothing more than a spring-training
sore arm. If this were the regular season, Nomar Garciaparra says,
he would have been playing shortstop Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But because the player in question is The Franchise, Sox camp
was at full alert, awaiting word on Garciaparra's status.
</P>
<P>
   While the Red Sox played the Cincinnati Reds here, Garciaparra
stayed back in Fort Myers, where he received treatment and played
catch. Garciaparra has now gone eight games without playing
shortstop, and while he told the team's medical staff Friday that
he was ``encouraged'' by how he felt after his session of light
throwing, according to club spokesman Kevin Shea, he has an
appointment to see team doctor Arthur Pappas this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We probably won't know anything till (Saturday),'' manager
Jimy Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be all right. In my mind he's going to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra's condition to date has been described as biceps
tendinitis, a not uncommon malady. Garciaparra told reporters
Friday he felt a ``sharp pain'' when he threw.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said Garciaparra may have hurt himself on a relay throw
from left field a week ago Thursday against Toronto. That was the
indication he got from team trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember seeing the relay throw, he had good stuff on it,''
Williams said. ``I don't know if he had a good grip on the ball or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra did not play last weekend, but returned to the
lineup Monday as the team's designated hitter. With the Reds a
National League opponent, no DH was used Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox trainers are not permitted to discuss injuries,
deferring all questions to Pappas. Dr. Tim Kremchek, the Reds'
medical director who is Harvard and Tufts-trained, agreed to speak
about biceps tendinitis in general terms, cautioning that he does
not know the specifics of Garciaparra's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biceps tendinitis in an infielder is not an uncommon
problem,'' Kremchek said. ``And sharp pain would not be
inconsistent with the condition. He could have strained it, then it
got inflamed. Eight days would be a long time to be out with biceps
tendinitis in the regular season, but during spring training it
means nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, if that's the case, and he's hitting and
DHing, I doubt it's very serious. It can't be that bad. I'm sure
Dr. Pappas will take a look at him, and probably with rest and
exercise he'll do well.''
</P>
<P>
   If Garciaparra says he'd be playing if this were the regular
season, that's probably true, Kremchek said. ``But why take that
chance in March?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra said Friday he has given no thought to seeking a
second opinion. Club spokesman Shea said that if Garciaparra feels
the need to do so, the club would be supportive.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Garciaparra missed 16 games with a separated right
shoulder, injured when he dived for a ground ball in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Williams preferred to take an optimistic stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some time yet,'' Williams said. ``Think about the
type of kid he is, who he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We open up two weeks from Monday. We've got time. His legs are
fine, he's been hitting. We'll take care of this. It's not as if he
wasn't throwing in that last game. It's not like he came out of the
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
