<HEADER>
A7390 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GUCCI-LVMH-2TAKES-NYT     03-19 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUCCI-LVMH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLE ERUPTS FOR CONTROL OF GUCCI GROUP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ A battle for the famed Italian fashion house Gucci Group
NV erupted Friday when a wealthy French takeover investor agreed to
pay $3 billion for a 40 percent stake to rescue it from a hostile
bid for control by French luxury goods maker LVMH Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton SA.
</P>
<P>
   But LVMH responded to the deal between Gucci and Francois
Pinault, whose various holdings include France's biggest department
store, Pinault-Printemps-Redoute; Converse sneakers, and Samsonite
luggage, by making an offer for all of Gucci that would value the
company at $7.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The drama that ricocheted in moves and countermoves through the
day pitted two of France's most powerful and most unconventional
capitalists against each other for control of Gucci, the hot item
in the global fashion world. It illustrated the new no-holds-barred
corporate dueling that is overtaking Europe as companies
consolidate to meet the challenges of globalization and a unifying
European market.
</P>
<P>
   The share price of all three companies rose to record levels.
Gucci's share price rose as much as 6.8 percent, to 68.25 euros,
worth $75 at the current exchange rate. LVMH rose as much as 4.2
percent, before settling at 232.10 euros, after it announced a bid
for all of Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   At stake for LVMH and its chairman, Bernard Arnault, was not
only the potential loss of Gucci, which it has been seeking control
of since January, when it announced it had acquired a 34.4 percent
stake. Arnault also faces the possibility of a strong new
French-controlled luxury group competitor built around Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   For Pinault, the deal would not only be a lifeline extended to
Domenico De Sole, the Gucci chief executive, who has been seeking a
defense against LVMH, but would also be the latest move in
Pinault's push beyond the bounds of the businesses of department
stores, books, records and mail order sales. That expansion reached
a new level last year, when Pinault paid $1.2 billion to acquire
Christie's, the venerable London auction house.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The skirmishing began early Friday, when Pinault announced it
would pay $3 billion, or $75 a share, for a 40 percent stake.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Pinault said it had paid $1 billion for the
beauty products units of Sanofi SA, including the Yves Saint
Laurent fashion house and Van Cleef &AMP; Arpels and Oscar de la Renta
perfumes. Pinault plans to sell those brands to Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Serge Weinberg, chief executive of Pinault-Printemps-Redoute,
said the plan was to use Gucci as a platform for the formation of a
big new luxury goods group. The group would be run by Gucci's De
Sole, and its fashion designer, Tom Ford, who would use the $3
billion received for the new Gucci shares to make further
acquisitions, Weinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Gucci, which is based in the Netherlands for tax reasons but has
its operations in Italy, had sought to repel an LVMH takeover by
offering employees stock options that would have diluted LVMH's
share to about 25 percent. LVMH challenged the move in an Amsterdam
court, and the court froze both companies' voting rights pending a
final decision in April.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Gucci and LVMH had agreed to send representatives to
Amsterdam Friday to resolve their differences. De Sole had insisted
that LVMH make a bid for all Gucci shares, but on Thursday Arnault
ruled that out, saying Gucci's earnings results, while excellent
given the weak market for luxury goods, made it too risky. A lawyer
for Gucci presented LVMH representatives with a press release
announcing the Pinault bid.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH officials expressed surprise and anger at Friday's
announcement. In Amsterdam, James Lieber, who was to represent LVMH
at the planned talks with Gucci, reacted angrily. ``Gucci has once
again taken action that has created a hostile environment,'' he
said. He said LVMH was examining its options and would contest
Pinault's offer before a Dutch court.
</P>
<P>
   Then later Friday, LVMH unexpectedly struck back, announcing a
bid for all Gucci shares. LVMH said it was willing to pay a ``full
and fair price,'' and people close to the company said that was
about $85 a share. At such a price, LVMH would pay $4.9 million for
the shares it does not own.
</P>
<P>
   LVMH said, however, that its offer was contingent on the
cancellation of Pinault's offer for 40 percent of Gucci and
Pinault's purchase of Sanofi's beauty brands.
</P>
<P>
   That counteroffer raised the possibility of an all-out battle
for control of Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably, it's war,'' said Jean-Marie L'Home, who follows
luxury goods at BNP Securities in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Pinault in Paris said the company would not
comment.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole, who left Paris Friday evening for London, issued a
statement saying that Gucci's board would evaluate the LVMH offer
at a meeting Sunday, when it was supposed to approve Gucci's
results for the 1999 fiscal year, which will be published Monday.
De Sole, who earlier described himself as ``ecstatic'' over the
Pinault deal, said of the LVMH counteroffer: ``This is a matter for
the board.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the offer by Pinault had pushed Arnault into a
corner, leaving him with no alternative to a full bid, despite the
reservations expressed on Thursday, or face the likelihood that he
would become a noninfluential, minority shareholder in a powerful
rival.
</P>
<P>
   Arnault's counterbid puts the ball back in Gucci's court. People
familiar with Pinault said there was little likelihood Pinault
would make a counteroffer for all of Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   News of Pinault's move sent shivers through the luxury goods
world.
</P>
<P>
   Pinault, 62, is a tough, self-made businessman who enjoys buying
up promising companies and increasing their value. He does not shy
from a good battle and follows his tastes with his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   A connoisseur of wine, he acquired the Chateau Latour domains in
the 1980s. He is also a major buyer of 20th-century art, and has
dotted his summer property in Brittany with contemporary sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   Pinault and Arnault have much in common. Both employed a mix of
savvy and ruthlessness over the last decade to assemble a
conglomerate of companies whose value they have increased by
eliminating overlaps in manufacturing and distribution, rigorously
controlling costs, and spending heavily on advertising.
</P>
<P>
   But while Arnault has vaulted himself into the exalted position
of arbiter of global luxury tastes, putting particular energy into
high-end fashion houses like Dior, Christian Lacroix, Givenchy and
Kenzo, Pinault has made high-profile acquisitions in the world of
distribution.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, he has acquired France's leading
department store group, Au Printemps, and took control of La
Redoute, the big mail-order house, and FNAC, a book and record
store chain.
</P>
<P>
   His holdings in the United States include Converse and
Samsonite. Last year, he sold a stake in Vail Associates Ski Resort
in Colorado to help finance the Christie's acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   De Sole, born in Italy but now a U.S. citizen, was once a
partner in Patton &AMP; Boggs, the Washington law firm, and has worked
with Gucci for 14 years. Ford is an American who left Perry Ellis
to become Gucci's designer. Gucci, under their aegis, has gone from
success to success. Its fourth-quarter profits, released Thursday,
soared 62 percent, to $68.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   French analysts suspected that bad blood between Arnault and De
Sole had reached such levels that LVMH might try to oust De Sole
but make an attractive enough financial offer to keep Ford.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 2055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
