<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7393 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEVORKIAN-PROSECUTE-8     03-19 1076
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEVORKIAN-PROSECUTE-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KEVORKIAN TO FACE MURDER CHARGES IN A TRIAL THAT BEGINS MONDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich)  (js) 
 By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ Four times, prosecutors have tried to prove that Dr.
Jack Kevorkian, the man who says he has presided over more than 130
suicides, committed a crime when he helped seriously ill people
die.
</P>
<P>
   Four times, they have failed. Three juries acquitted Kevorkian.
One case ended in a mistrial.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, prosecutors will try again. It is a trial that people
on both sides of the debate over euthanasia and assisted suicide
see as a potentially defining showdown over whether such acts
should be considered criminal or whether they are the entitlement
of the terminally ill.
</P>
<P>
   And this time, several key things are different.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the previous trials, where Kevorkian was accused of
violating laws prohibiting assisted suicide, this time he is being
charged with first-degree premeditated murder. That makes the
stakes higher for both Kevorkian and the state.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike his previous trials, indeed unlike the vast majority
of murder cases, the jury will actually see Kevorkian doing the act
that prosecutors contend is murder. They will watch a videotape,
already broadcast nationwide on the CBS news program ``60
Minutes,'' that shows Kevorkian injecting a fatal solution of
chemicals into 52-year-old Thomas Youk, who suffered from
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, or Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here they have Kevorkian directly causing the death of Mr.
Youk,'' said Larry Dubin, a law professor at University of Detroit
Mercy, who noted that in previous cases, Kevorkian was essentially
accused of helping people kill themselves, rigging up a device that
would let people pull a string and release the chemicals
themselves. ``The prosecution proving that Kevorkian committed this
act is very easy for them.''
</P>
<P>
   This does not mean it will be easy to persuade a jury to convict
Kevorkian of killing Youk last September at the Youk home in
Waterford Township, a Detroit suburb. Indeed, experts say that in
some ways, the murder charge puts the prosecution at a greater
disadvantage than in previous cases.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, some say, the state may be able to make the case that
what Kevorkian did matches the black letter definition of murder,
intentionally causing someone's death. And in a murder case,
whether the person consented to being killed is legally irrelevant.
</P>
<P>
   But emotionally, will jurors agree that arranging the death of a
desperately ill man who wanted to die is an act that warrants a
murder conviction, one that could result in a sentence of life
without parole?
</P>
<P>
   ``The odds are very high that a jury will say this is just
disproportionate, it's out of all proportion to what he did,'' said
Yale Kamisar, a law professor at the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The initial charges against Kevorkian, brought in November after
60 Minutes broadcast the videotape Kevorkian made of Youk's death,
also included criminal assistance to a suicide, a charge that would
have given a jury a less severe option.
</P>
<P>
   But earlier this month, prosecutors decided to drop the assisted
suicide charge, leaving only the murder charge and a much lesser
charge of delivery of a controlled substance. Kevorkian's license
to practice medicine has been revoked in Michigan and California.)
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' decision followed a ruling by Oakland County
Circuit Court Judge Jessica Cooper that an assisted suicide charge
would allow the defense to present testimony about Kevorkian's role
in ending people's pain and suffering. Such testimony would be
inadmissable with a murder charge, she ruled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a calculated risk, of course,'' said David G. Gorcyca,
the Oakland County prosecutor. ``But that kind of testimony has
proved lethal to our case in the past. In the previous trials, the
defense has entered testimony from physicians and family members
about the condition of the victim, such factors as choking on your
own saliva. What you had is jurors, even male jurors, crying. To
overcome that kind of emotional testimony at trial is almost
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   David Gorosh, one of Kevorkian's lawyers, said precluding such
testimony ``prevents us from presenting a fuller picture to the
jury.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that the jury would have other ways to learn about
Youk's condition, including the videotape, which shows him
struggling to speak and breathe, hardly able to lift his hand.
Gorosh said the defense would argue, as it has in previous trials,
that Kevorkian's intention was not to kill, but to end a person's
suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas Youk, death was inevitable for him,'' Gorosh said.
``But he didn't want to die. He simply asked Dr. Kevorkian to help
him ease his suffering, end his pain if he could. When you ask a
jury is this murder, when you think of what is murder, this is not
it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   One unanswered question that could greatly influence the trial
is whether Kevorkian, 70, will be representing himself or whether
his lawyers will be handling the case. So far it has been a mix of
both.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, for example, Kevorkian filed his own appeal, seeking
to have the murder charge dismissed or delayed based on the Ninth
Amendment to the Constitution, which says that rights not otherwise
addressed by the Constitution are reserved for the people.
Kevorkian contended the amendment means the government cannot force
someone in severe pain to continue to suffer. The appeal was
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Gorosh said that against his advice, Kevorkian has said he
wanted to deliver the closing argument in the case and to
cross-examine one of the key witnesses, the Oakland County medical
examiner, with whom he has had a long-running feud.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, Gorosh said the judge indicated that either
Kevorkian or his lawyers should represent the defense during the
entire trial. Gorosh said he and Kevorkian had not yet reached a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to persuade him that the lawyers should try the
case,'' said Gorosh. ``He's an incredibly charming man, he's as
honest as the day is long, and I think jurors would appreciate
that. That said, a criminal trial is a complicated thing. How to
proceed tactfully with witnesses, with the judge, within the
confines of the rules of evidence. Although Dr. Kevorkian is quite
brilliant, he isn't schooled in the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
