<HEADER>
A7395 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OPEC-VIENNA-HNS &LR;      03-19 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPEC-VIENNA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPEC EXPECTED TO PRESENT UNIFIED FRONT AT ANNUAL MEETING 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sometimes the best way to avoid a family brouhaha
is to spend as little time together as possible.
</P>
<P>
   That's the apparent thinking behind OPEC's series of meetings
where its quarrelsome members have privately agreed in a series of
meetings to reductions cutting output by 2 million barrels a day.
</P>
<P>
   As a result when oil ministers from the OPEC cartel meet in
Vienna next week for their spring meeting, they aren't likely to
have to endure the squabbling between the group's two largest
producers _ Saudi Arabia and Iran _ that has characterized past
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, representatives from the 11-member Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries are expected to rubber-stamp terms
reached between OPEC's largest players and some key, non-OPEC
producing nations that has pulled prices up from the depths.
</P>
<P>
   That expectation has helped propel crude prices 10 percent in
the last 10 days. On Friday, oil for April delivery rose 24 cents
to close at $15.24 on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC's primary task in Vienna, then, will be to shore up support
among the group's smaller members, present a united front to the
world, and get out of town fast. Some analysts are expecting a
meeting that will last only a few hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've already agreed on everything,'' said John Lichtblau,
chairman of the New York-based Petroleum Industry Research
Foundation. ``The less they talk, the (fewer) chances there are for
disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   They have reason to make some painful concessions _ oil prices
have been wallowing at depressed levels since late last year,
causing severe, economic woes for countries dependent on crude
exports.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the oil ministers will be asked to ratify an accord
spearheaded by OPEC heavyweight Saudi Arabia. It includes cuts from
non-affiliated producers Mexico, Norway and Oman.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement, reached at The Hague earlier this month, would
require the OPEC countries _ excluding Iraq, whose exports are
still controlled by United Nations sanctions _ to trim their
production by about 1.7 million barrels a day or about 7 percent
starting April 1.
</P>
<P>
   To further smooth the waters before Vienna, ministers from four
OPEC nations from the Persian Gulf region _ Saudi Arabia, Kuwait,
United Arab Emirates and Qatar _ as well as non-OPEC member Bahrain
are scheduled to meet Saturday in Abu Dhabi, the capital of the
United Arab Emirates, to discuss the proposed cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Few, if any, oil analysts seriously believe the parties will
fully comply with the 2 million goal, which would pare world
supplies by about 2.7 percent. But the markets have been persuaded
the pact will provide for a sizeable cut of at least 1 million
barrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saudi Arabia, U.A.E., Kuwait and Venezuela will deliver a
million barrels, and the others are all varying degrees of
unlikelihood,'' noted one industry source, who asked not to be
named.
</P>
<P>
   A plan to cut 2 million barrels is very ambitious, even
excessive, said Leo Drollas, chief economist for the Centre for
Global Energy Studies in London. If such a plan were fully
implemented ``it would lead to some serious tightening of the
market later this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Rothman, senior energy futures analyst for Merrill Lynch
in New York, said if only 1 million barrels were taken off the
market ``inventories, which are quite excessive, could get worked
down fairly aggressively over the course of the year and be back
down to near-normal levels by the end of '99. This, of course,
means cuts being sustained.''
</P>
<P>
   If the OPEC countries were to comply with, say, 75 percent of
the production cutbacks that would be enough to send oil prices
rising to $18, even $20 a barrel by the fourth quarter, said Nizam
Sharief, director of energy policy for Hornsby &AMP; Co., a
Houston-based energy risk management services firm.
</P>
<P>
   The deal has already pushed up prices at the gasoline pump and
for heating oil in areas of the country where that's the fuel of
choice.
</P>
<P>
   April heating oil rose 0.99 cent to 40.69 cents a gallon; April
unleaded gasoline rose 0.61 cent to 47.64 cents a gallon; April
natural gas rose 1/2 cents to $1.699 per thousand cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, North Sea Brent Blend crude oil for delivery in May
rose 8 cents to $13.45 per barrel on the International Petroleum
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts give considerable credence to the accord because it was
orchestrated by OPEC kingpin Saudi Arabia, at no small sacrifice to
the kingdom. Saudi Arabia is risking losing some market share in
order to reach an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the specter of government revenues plunging by a
third this year if crude prices did not recover _ Saudi Arabia
loses about $2.5 billion for every $1 drop in the price of oil _
the kingdom has agreed to take the biggest cut, a
585,000-barrel-a-day reduction.
</P>
<P>
   That's a dramatic move for Saudi Arabia, since it will push the
kingdom's production below 8 million barrels a day for the first
time since the Persian Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   ``They broke the sacred floor,'' said Raad Alkadiri, country
analyst for the Petroleum Finance Co. in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   To bring OPEC's second largest producer, Iran, on board, the
Saudis accepted a key Iranian demand that Tehran be allowed to cut
back from a starting point of 3.6 million barrels a day, rather
than from 3.3 million barrels a day as the Saudis would have
preferred.
</P>
<P>
   On previous occasions, the Saudis have tried to cut a deal
before an OPEC meeting without rival Iran present.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``they had a lot of squabbling over the starting
point for cuts,'' Drollas said. ``So this time they were astute
enough (to realize) unless they brought Iran on board, they would
not get very far with OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the cost of this, the price they had to pay, is to accept
the Iranian position regarding the cuts last year,'' Drollas said.
</P>
<P>
   These concessions, however, are also an indication of Saudi
Crown Prince Abdullah's commitment to having good relations with
Iran, Alkadiri said.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, debt-laden Iran _ depending on oil exports for
about 85 percent of its hard currency _ has been bludgeoned by the
low crude prices even more severely than the Saudis. Last year,
Iran renegotiated its loans for the second time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Other OPEC members, of course, are struggling as well.
</P>
<P>
   Petroleos de Venezuela, Venezuela's state-owned oil company,
announced plans this week to sell $1 billion worth of bonds. Energy
Minister Ali Rodriguez, in a television interview, said the oil
company ``needs an urgent loan of $900 million because it doesn't
have the money to pay its suppliers,'' Bloomberg reported from
Caracas Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In Nigeria, the government's financial position is stark,
according to Cambridge Energy Research Associates. ``Spending this
year will be only half of that two years ago and by far the lowest
of the entire decade.''
</P>
<P>
   While higher oil prices prompted by production cutbacks will
help the economies of the oil producing nations for a short term,
they will not solve these nations' underlying economic problems,
argues Michel Camdessus, managing director of the International
Monetary Fund, the Washington-based economic bail-out reserve.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to oil producers, wherever they are, is clear: do
not delude yourselves,'' Camdessus said in an interview with the
French newspaper Les Echos. He said they must work to reform their
economies and diversify away from oil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oil prices will perhaps rise but in real terms the increase
will not be significant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
