<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PERSONAL BUSINESS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Please Enter Your 4-Digit Dining PIN &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter wants to keep employees from
practicing arbitrage in the over-the-deli-counter market at its Two
World Trade Center cafeteria in Manhattan. It seems that some
workers would ask for extra sandwich fillings but not always
mention them to the cashier.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would go up to the sandwich maker and say, `Can you add
a little of that? Add a little more?''' said Keith Waters, an
assistant vice president in charge of dining. The cashiers could
only see the sandwiches from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   The company's response: sandwiches by ATM. Since December,
employees have had to enter sandwich orders on a computer
touch-screen. Out come detailed receipts, listing extras like
coleslaw or sun-dried tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   People, not machines, actually make the sandwiches, while
employees get sodas and other items and head to the cash registers.
The cashier charges for all the sandwich ingredients listed on the
receipts, and only then do employees pick up their orders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Waters said, ``we can account for items employees were
ordering but they weren't paying for, like bacon on a turkey
sandwich.'' The computer kiosk was part of an overall redesign of
the cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Far from bristling over the new system, Waters said, employees
are just as happy ordering from a touch screen instead of a person.
``Most of our employees use their computers every day,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shelly Freierman &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Controlling City Limits  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the nation's leading foundations are joining an effort
to manage urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Forty foundations, including Ted Turner's, held an urban-sprawl
conference in Miami in January. And a new nonprofit group, the
Sprawl Watch Clearinghouse (www.sprawlwatch.org), has been formed
to provide information and advice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea behind this is that there has to be a regionally
designed response to metropolitan growth-related issues,'' said
Peter Bahouth, executive director of the Turner Foundation in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Other participating foundations included the Heinz Endowments of
Pittsburgh, the James Irvine Foundation of San Francisco and the
John D. and Catherine T. MacArthur Foundation and the Joyce
Foundation, both of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Cohen
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
