</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-CONFLICT-PAY-ART-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOLDEN HANDCUFFS' THAT TURN TO DROSS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21)  
 (af)  
 By DAVID CAY JOHNSTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   James Moore figured that his career was in great shape. In 1988,
after five years as manager of the Acme Corrugated Box Co. plant in
Philadelphia, he had broken the union while keeping production
humming. Revenues were soaring, as were profits, even as half the
local competitors went out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Acme's owner, Burton Cohen, said he wanted Moore, then 43, to
stay around. To help insure that, he gave Moore an executive
deferred compensation plan, also known as ``golden handcuffs,''
that would pay $50,000 annually for 10 years once Moore turned 65.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1996, when Moore was 51, he was dismissed. And his golden
handcuffs turned to dross. Acme's lawyer, Kenneth D. Kleinman,
explained that to collect, Moore had to be employed at the company
on the day he turned 65.
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge, while sympathetic to Moore's situation, has
ruled that he has no recourse against Acme under the nation's
pension laws. And therein lies an important lesson for managers
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   It is simply this: A 1974 law designed to protect pension
benefits does not cover everyone. Indeed, Labor Department records
show that an exemption intended to apply to sophisticated senior
executives has been stretched to envelop hundreds of thousands of
lower-level managers like Moore, who has a ninth-grade education.
</P>
<P>
   The law, the Employee Retirement Income and Security Act, or
ERISA, was passed after Congress heard horror stories about people
who worked their entire adult lives for companies, only to be let
go just before retirement age so that they could be denied
benefits, or to get nothing because their employers went broke.
People covered by the 1974 law cannot be given the kind of deal
Acme gave Moore.
</P>
<P>
   The law required companies to put money regularly into pension
funds that were protected from creditors if a company failed. At
employers' insistence, though, an exception was made for so-called
top-hat plans.
</P>
<P>
   That allowed owners, executives and some top sales people to
have additional deferred compensation plans that were not funded in
advance _ under the theory that these people did not need
government protection.
</P>
<P>
   Moore said that he signed every form put in front of him,
including one that appears to transfer some of his rights to the
company. And he never consulted a compensation lawyer, who could
have advised him that the handcuffs were worthless unless Moore was
still on the job on a specific day in the year 2010.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was taking care of their factory, and I figured that they
would take care of me,'' Moore said, explaining why he never sought
legal counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The federal district judge who heard the case in Philadelphia
last year, Raymond J. Broderick, said from the bench that he was
deeply troubled by the way Moore was dismissed with nothing but a
handshake after 12 years. Writing later in his formal opinion, the
judge said Moore ``proved himself an effective plant manager at
Acme,'' with glowing performance reviews and only mild criticism.
</P>
<P>
   According to Moore, plant revenues during his tenure grew from
$2 million to $16 million, while the number of workers fell by more
than half, creating bountiful profits. His last written review, in
1993, praised his ``truly outstanding job of running the plant''
and said that under his leadership, ``the plant has become our
major sales tool.''
</P>
<P>
   By then, the plant had also survived a strike by the box
workers' union and moved to new facilities in Bensalem, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   But over the next two years, Broderick found, Acme came to
believe that Moore had reached the limits of his ability. On Feb.
26, 1996, he was dismissed. At the time, Acme offered Moore a
$50,000 settlement, but he rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   In carving out an exemption from the pension law, ``Congress
assumed that top-hat plan participants would be financially
sophisticated enough to negotiate their own `golden parachutes' in
the event of early termination,'' Broderick wrote in his opinion.
Nonetheless, he added, ``Moore, perhaps blinded by his loyalty to
Acme, had no legal entitlement to any monies upon his early
termination.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Moore's lawyer, Robert Freidel of Turnersville, N.J., is
appealing the case to the U.S. 3rd Circuit Court of Appeals,
contending that there was a pattern of deception by Acme in its
dealings with Moore. The appellate court is expected to hear the
case late next month.
</P>
<P>
   Acme's lawyer, Kleinman, of Stevens &AMP; Lee in Reading, Pa., said
Broderick ``is very sympathetic to people he considers the
underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And this is an individual who had worked for the company for
12 years and was terminated,'' Kleinman said. ``But even this judge
found that as a matter of law Moore had no claim.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Salwen, the owner of the Executive Compensation Corp. in
New York, which advises executives on their pay packages, said
cases like Moore's illustrated how little attention workers in
their 40s and even early 50s paid to the full terms of their
retirement plans, whether the details were plain or complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an area that cuts across the whole of Corporate
America and one in which there has been a void of regulation,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Salwen warned that abuses invite more regulation. For now,
though, Labor Department officials said that they have received few
complaints about retirement plans that fall outside the pension
laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
