<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON SURVEYS, STUDIES AND NEW PRODUCTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Not to Mix Deals With Gemutlichkeit &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Headed for Europe to break bread and make deals? Make them over
lunch in most countries, but over breakfast or dinner in Italy. But
in Germany, don't even think about a business breakfast; in fact,
you might want to skip mixing food and business altogether.
</P>
<P>
   That advice emerges from a survey of 1,508 European business
executives; the poll was conducted by Harris Research for United
Parcel Service.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the survey was more serious in theme: European
executives were found to be much less optimistic about their
companies' near-term prospects than they were a year ago, for
example, and most expect to lay off workers in the coming year.
</P>
<P>
   But the study also included a few work-style questions. One
asked respondents to name the settings outside the office where
they were most likely to discuss business with their most valuable
customers.
</P>
<P>
   On that topic, more national quirks were seen: Entertaining
clients at home was popular only in Italy. Belgians were the only
respondents who much favored talking shop at a cultural event. Only
1 in 20 European executives mentioned a round of golf or other
sports, and those who did were mainly British. Dutch executives
shared Germans' aversion to power breakfasts but were happy to do
lunch.
</P>
<P>
   So, if not over a meal, where would German executives rather do
business? Airports, hotels and conference centers were their first
choice. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 2101EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0338 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7411 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      03-19 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A UNIVERSITY EXAMINES THE CRUCIFIX AS ART AND SYMBOL  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind.)   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``To draw, paint or sculpt the crucifixion is a terrifying
experience,'' Charles McCollough says, ``for the artist must feel
some bit of the horrible pain and humiliation of being hung up to
die.''
</P>
<P>
   A crucifix by McCollough is one of the most powerful among the
contemporary renderings of Jesus' crucifixion on exhibit in the
atrium of the Bunn Intercultural Center at Georgetown University in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Their presence there is the outcome of a widely publicized
skirmish at the Roman Catholic university's campus that has been
difficult to fathom, even by a regular visitor, like this writer,
who teaches on the campus two days a week.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, a student noticed that many of Georgetown's
classrooms did not have the crucifixes that were once a familiar
fixture, although in no official way an obligatory one, in Roman
Catholic college and university classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The student expressed her distress in a letter to the
university's president. Not satisfied with his polite but
non-committal response, she wrote a blistering article in a
conservative campus publication, using phrases like ``treacherous
acts of betrayal.''
</P>
<P>
   The crucifix question soon was burdened with issues that went
well beyond whatever purely devotional concerns might have been at
its origin. Did their absence symbolize an abandonment of
Catholicism by the university? Did the demand for their replacement
symbolize a threat to the university's diversity and intellectual
openness? Was the whole tug-of-war over a central Christian image
an offense to authentic religiosity?
</P>
<P>
   The administration insisted that there had never been a policy
against crucifixes. They had never been put in some newer buildings
and never replaced after renovations in others. The student request
would be taken under advisement, the administration said, but
nothing precipitous would occur, especially while the university
was engaged in a number of other discussions of how to reflect its
Catholic identity.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative groups, both religious and political, from outside
the campus began to line up behind the crucifix cause. Jewish and
Muslim leaders on campus said that they welcomed a Catholic
university being rich in Catholic symbols.
</P>
<P>
   For the news media, the story was irresistible. Classroom
crucifixes were as concrete an expression of Catholicism as was not
eating meat on Friday had once been. What hung on the walls of
Georgetown's classrooms was certainly more interesting than what
went on within them.
</P>
<P>
   University officials finally acted. The classrooms would get
their crucifixes, and not the traditional mass-produced models, but
esthetically rich versions from different cultures and Christian
traditions. The campus, moreover, would engage in a serious
examination of the crucifix as a symbol with meaning in both
Christianity and world culture.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit, timed for this season of Lent and ending on Easter,
is a stimulating starting point for that examination. Twenty-five
contemporary artists, from different religious traditions, have
depicted the crucifixion in wood carvings, stone and metal
sculptures, oil paintings, textiles and other materials.
</P>
<P>
   McCollough's body of Jesus, about five feet in height, is a
striking departure from more conventionally naturalistic or
symbolic figures he has executed. In a note accompanying the work,
the sculptor, who also is an ordained United Church of Christ
minister, describes finding a piece of dogwood, a species whose
cross-shaped flowers with blood-red tips have linked it
symbolically with the crucifixion.
</P>
<P>
   This particular piece had roots that, turned upright, have
become carved arms, their knotted elbows wrenched painfully out of
shape and their gnarled and broken fingers curled around the
wrought iron nails pinning them to a rough oak cross. The narrow,
roughly carved body is naked in humiliation. The head is bent
forward but staring more than drooping; the mouth is a gaping hole
of agony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to overemphasize the true brutality of this death
by torture,'' McCullough says. ``It is important, I believe, to
represent the crucifixion as state murder, not an abstract notion
of death in general.''
</P>
<P>
   The examination will go beyond the exhibit. On March 29, the
Monday of Holy Week and two days before Passover, an afternoon
liturgy will be followed by an evening of lectures and discussion
by Chaim Potok and the Rev. James Flanigan.
</P>
<P>
   In 1972, Potok, far better known as the author of novels about
Hasidic Jewry than as a rabbi, published ``My Name Is Asher Lev.''
Asher Lev is an artistic prodigy driven to use the crucifixion as a
symbol of torment but thereby sealing his separation from his
Hasidic upbringing and his observant Jewish family.
</P>
<P>
   Flanigan is a professor of art at the University of Notre Dame
and a member of the Congregation of the Holy Cross, the religious
order that founded the university. A sculptor with several
crucifixes in the Georgetown exhibit, he has been curator of the
collection of works at Notre Dame's Snite Museum of Art by Ivan
Mestrovic, the eminent Croatian sculptor.
</P>
<P>
   The speakers will engage one another and the audience with their
perspectives on the crucifix as art, religious object and cultural
force.
</P>
<P>
   Do the crucifixes hanging in the classrooms of many Catholic
colleges and universities have any impact on the students or the
campus ethos? Will the handsome crucifixes recently installed at
Georgetown be practically invisible by May, paid less notice than
the safety signs on maximum room occupancy and certainly less heed
than those reading no smoking?
</P>
<P>
   That is a natural polling project for campus journalists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
