<SLUG> BC-TRAIN-WRECK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESS'   STORY SHIFTS WITH LANGUAGE, CRASH INVESTIGATORS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ As they wound down their investigation at the scene of
Monday's deadly crash of an Amtrak train and a truck loaded with
steel, federal investigators said Friday that a language barrier
might have caused them to misunderstand the description of the
accident by their first witness.
</P>
<P>
   They now understand the witness to have said that he did not see
the truck drive around a crossing gate before it was struck by the
train.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, federal investigators told reporters that the
witness had said he had seen the truck zigzag around the gates, but
Friday the investigators said the witness was saying that he did
not see the truck go around the gate.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators said the Spanish-speaking witness might not have
changed his story, but might just have been misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven people were killed, and 116 injured, in the accident at a
crossing near Bourbonnais, Ill., about 50 miles south of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   No federal official would explain publicly what caused the
confusion. The National Transportation Safety Board issued only a
brief written statement, saying that ``any characterization of
witness statements up to this point would be one person's
interpretation and not the position of the safety board.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators say they have ``a number of people'' who
have said they saw the accident.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on the condition of anonymity, safety board
investigators said the first witness, a Spanish-speaking restaurant
worker from Chicago, called Amtrak on Wednesday night, saying he
had been two cars behind the truck. In an initial interview, with
questions and answers in English, the investigators understood the
man to say that he saw the truck drive around a crossing gate.
</P>
<P>
   In a later, formal interview on Thursday evening, with questions
and answers translated by a state police officer, investigators
understood the man to say that he did not see the truck drive
around the gates. ``He said it the first time, and not the second
time,'' one investigator said.
</P>
<P>
   The man said he did not know whether the truck went through
flashing lights, which are designed to begin seconds before the
gates come down, and about 25 to 30 seconds before the train
arrives.
</P>
<P>
   The witness said he was in the area because he got lost looking
for an automobile dealer.
</P>
<P>
   The truck driver, John R. Stokes, 58, of Manteno, Ill., has said
he did not drive around the gates and did not see the warning
lights until just before impact. His driving record since 1968,
released Friday by the state, shows nine accidents, six license
suspensions, two tickets for driving with a suspended license, and
two tickets for driving without insurance.
</P>
<P>
   He was driving on Monday with a probationary permit. The state's
attorney has begun a criminal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The engineer of the train has not been interviewed because he
remains sedated.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever those potential witnesses have to say, investigators
said that they rely much more heavily on physical evidence. So far,
the physical evidence suggests that the truck driver zigzagged
around the gates, perhaps because he could not see a train coming.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence cited by investigators: The tips of the crossing
gates are damaged. Damage on the locomotive suggests that the truck
and train were not at right angles. Tire trucks in the mud suggest
that someone drove around the gates, but have yet to be matched to
the truck involved in the accident.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 2112EST &QL; 
