<HEADER>
A7419 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-ART-1STLD-WRI     03-19 1110
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-ART-1STLD-WRITETHRU-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MEETS THE PRESS AND DEFENDS HIS RECORD ON TRUTHFULNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for additions; insert about Gore in graf 3 is new, as is the
entire second half)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(lh) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Friday that when the final
word was written on his legacy, he would have one strike against
him _ for lying _ but ``hundreds and hundreds and hundreds'' of
pluses for the times that he was truthful.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that he did not have ``a clue'' whether his wife,
Hillary Rodham Clinton, would run for the Senate from New York. But
he said publicly for the first time that she had long ago suggested
they move to New York when he left office, although he implied they
would be spending a lot of time apart because he would be in
Arkansas at his presidential library. He said they were ``working''
on their marriage, which has appeared stressed over the last year
in the wake of revelations about his extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   At his first full-dress news conference in nearly a year, held
in the formal East Room of the White House, Clinton ranged over an
array of foreign and domestic issues for an hour. He sprang to the
defense of Vice President Al Gore for Gore's overdrawn references
in his personal biography, and he deflected a question about
whether he felt betrayed by former aides who have criticized his
fitness for the presidency. His tone was generally conversational,
but he became visibly testy when he was asked whether his ``legacy
will be about lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who admitted last year that he had lied when he denied
having an affair with Monica Lewinsky, a White House intern, said
that telling the truth was important. ``And even presidents have to
do that, and there are consequences when you don't,'' he said in an
understated reference to his impeachment on charges of perjury and
obstruction of justice, on which he was acquitted five weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   But then he tensed and his voice rose with anger as he asserted
that on balance, he had a strong record and that reporters needed
to be careful about telling the truth too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a box score, and there will be that one
negative,'' he said, referring to his lying under oath. ``And then
there will be the hundreds and hundreds and hundreds of times when
the record will show that I did not abuse my authority as
president, that I was truthful with the American people, and scores
and scores of allegations were made against me and widely
publicized without any regard to whether they were true or not.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those allegations, he said: ``Most of them have already been
actually proved false. And it's very hard to disprove every false
allegation against you. But we have had more success frankly than I
was afraid we would when we started. So I would hope that there
would be a higher regard for truth-telling by all people in public
life and all those who report on it.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined Friday to discuss one of those allegations _ by an
Arkansas woman, Juanita Broaddrick, that he sexually assaulted her
in 1978 while he was state attorney general. His lawyer has denied
it.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that he wanted to devote all of his time to the
nation's business and would therefore refer all such questions to
his lawyers. Pressed as to whether he could not simply deny the
allegation, Clinton ignored the question and quickly moved on.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been available only briefly to reporters since the
impeachment ordeal began more than a year ago. Friday's news
conference was one in a series of steps the White House has taken
to thaw the icy relations with reporters that have marked his
tenure.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He has held two off-the-record dinners with reporters, and his
spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said the president would now conduct news
conferences on a more regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   His aim Friday was to present himself as back to business, and
he generally avoided being drawn into the past. ``I think it's best
for me not to focus on that now,'' he said when asked for his
reflections on being impeached.
</P>
<P>
   He was more comfortable with the topic of his wife's political
ambitions, though he said he was clueless on what she would decide.
``The people she is talking to must know more than I do, because I
literally don't have a clue,'' he said. ``If you asked me today
whether I thought it was more likely or not that she would run or
not run, I could not give you an answer. I just don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that long before either of them knew that Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, the state's senior Senator, would vacate his seat, she
thought they should move to New York. Friday he seemed to be trying
to pre-empt criticism that Mrs. Clinton was a carpetbagger and had
no ties to the state.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who has given few hints about his
post-presidential plans, said of his wife: ``She thought we should
move to New York when I left the White House, knowing that I would
spend a lot of time at home in my library and with the work there,
but that we would also establish a home in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   He also offered an explanation for why she would be a good
representative for New York, saying: ``She cares so much about the
issues, especially those that have a particular impact on New York,
including the education and economic issues that would be very
important to the people there.''
</P>
<P>
   He defended Gore's recent claim to have created the Internet and
his suggestions that he spent a rustic boyhood as a farm hand in
Tennessee. He actually grew up in Washington, the son of a senator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know exactly what he said or exactly how it has been
characterized, but he has been for 20 years one of the major
architects of America's progress in technology,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as his boyhood home, I think _ I know what you're
saying,'' Clinton said. ``You're saying, well, he went to St.
Alban's and his daddy was a senator. But it's also true that he is
from East Tennessee and he did learn to do all those things he did
on the farm.'' He said Gore was by nature shy but that he needed to
share his life experiences with voters, and it was hard to do this
without seeming to brag too much.
</P>
<P>
   He brushed aside a question about whether he felt betrayed by
books highly critical of him by former advisers George
Stephanopoulos and Dick Morris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have absorbed no pain,'' he said, ``since I haven't read
either one of the books.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
