<HEADER>
A7421 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-ONLINE-POLLS20-C     03-19 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ONLINE-POLLS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's online polls make unlikely links
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush's presidential exploratory
committee on Friday unplugged a Web site link that led from its
home page to one that included photos of aborted fetuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee felt it best not to link our site with that
particular site,'' said committee spokeswoman Mindy Tucker, adding
that Bush officials had been unaware of the ``other items''
contained on the site.
</P>
<P>
   Until its removal, the link was part of a Bush effort to pile up
votes in online presidential polls.
</P>
<P>
   One of those polls shut down temporarily this week after
accusing Bush backers of stuffing the cyber ballot box.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is a quarter-step short of being an official
presidential candidate, is using his exploratory committee's Web
site (www.georgewbush.com) to lead people to online polls run by an
assortment of folks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cast your vote for Bush and encourage your friends to do the
same!'' the Bush site says in urging supporters to participate in
polls at six other Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Tucker said the Bush camp views the online polls as ``another
way to voice support for Governor Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the Bush group was notified Friday by the Austin
American-Statesman, one of the online polls linked to Bush's site
was one run by Linda Clements of Palmetto, Fla., who also used it
to share photos of her family, its pet pigs and a healthy dose of
her political philosophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a Bible-thumpin', pew-jumpin', Jesus-lovin',
devil-shovin', blood-bought, red-hot, soul-redeemin', shoutin',
screemin', overcomin' child of God,'' Clements says on the Web
site.
</P>
<P>
   The photos of aborted fetuses on her site are accessed through a
connection that says: ``Blob of tissue? See real abortions for
yourself and you decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Clements could not be reached for comment Friday after the Bush
committee Web site removed its link to her site. Bush backers were
accused of not playing by the one-visit, one-vote rules set by the
operators of another online poll entitled Elections USA.
</P>
<P>
   ``The amount of cheating that has been going on is simply
unbelievable,'' said a note posted on the site last week when the
poll was suspended. ``Three hundred votes for G. Bush and 200 for
A. Gore within the last eight hours? Who are we kidding? What's
next, 5,000 votes in one hour?''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, voting resumed with this warning:
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends, I've resumed the poll hoping (against hope) that this
time there will be less cheating by those few passionate voters who
made me suspend Vote 2000 a week ago.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
