<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7422 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SXSW-CLUBS20-COX     03-19 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SXSW-CLUBS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SXSW provides annual adrenaline to Austin clubs
 &HT;    By Don McLeese
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When South by Southwest debuted in 1987, the
most common response from skeptical club owners was ``What can the
festival do for me?'' Thirteen years later, many of the
participating clubs now find themselves asking, ``What would we do
without South by Southwest?''
</P>
<P>
   Like kids anticipating Christmas, clubs count on getting
everything they want during these five days in March, enough to
offset the struggles of winter business and the slow months
anticipated through the summer. The enabling relationship between
SXSW and struggling clubs is another sign of how much Austin has
changed through the '90s, as a techno-booming economy has put a
premium on space available for development and turned the local
economy topsy-turvy. For clubs in critical condition, SXSW isn't a
bonus; it's life support.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire club business counts on South by Southwest to get
us through the year,'' said Mike Henry, co-owner of the Electric
Lounge. ``You struggle tooth and claw to break even the rest of the
year, but you can bank on South by Southwest. It's a huge gift, and
you always know exactly when it's coming. We would have closed
years ago if it weren't for South by Southwest, and I know we're
not alone in that.''
</P>
<P>
   Its survival threatened by rising property values on the
development-hungry west side of downtown, the Lounge might not last
through next year's conference. Though business has improved at the
intimate, eclectic showcase room during every year since the club
opened in 1993, costs have skyrocketed along with property values.
Rents have more than tripled, but club attendance hasn't, and cover
charges can't. Competition for top touring acts and a dearth of
local headlining talent that regularly fills a room also have
escalated the price of doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we started, space was not at a premium, and you could
find a good raw space that you could make your own,'' said Henry.
``And now, everything is gobbled up for development. The only
people who are winning the club battle are the people who came into
it with money. Our biggest obstacle is that we have always been
extremely undercapitalized, and that used to be the norm with
Austin clubs. We were all pretty much in the same boat. And now
that's definitely not the case; Stubb's and Direct Events (which
runs La Zona Rosa, the Backyard and the Austin Music Hall) have
changed the face of things around here.''
</P>
<P>
   Whereas the club business is typically a high-stakes gamble,
SXSW is practically risk-free. The festival books the talent, pays
the costs and reaps the benefits from sales of conference badges
and wristbands. Each year, the fest attempts to match attractive
showcase lineups with the venues made available by club owners
interested in participating. Instead of paying high prices for
talent with no guarantee of a return at the door, the clubs see
their bonanza from bars that are busier than at any other time of
the year, swarmed with industry revelers downing Celis and Shiner
as if the local beers were an exotic elixir for an insatiable
thirst. For the Electric Lounge, as for so many participating
venues, March bar revenues were almost as great last year as
February and April combined (February, $42,051; March, $73,339;
April, $36,550).
</P>
<P>
   With the Lounge operating two stages throughout the conference _
its tented Electric Pavilion was introduced in desperation after
the club's fire in '93 and proved so popular it has remained a SXSW
perennial _ South by Southwest is usually sufficient to offset a
significant amount of debt. Yet rumors continue to circulate that
this year's windfall will be too little, too late, and that after
SXSW, the Electric Lounge will pull the plug.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our baby, and we're doing everything we can, but we
can't continue to operate as a nonprofit business,'' said Mark
Shuman, one of the club's founding co-owners, who sees smaller
entertainment businesses victimized by the city's commitment to
``smart growth.'' ``The way that the city is trying to develop
downtown, there is a layer of businesses that is being ignored. The
city of Austin touts itself as the `Live Music Capital of the
World,' but they give tax breaks and incentives to large
corporations without giving anything to the music businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The venerable Liberty Lunch finds itself in a similar crunch,
with development on the verge of devouring city property in what
was considered a marginal space for commercial development. Though
the club has benefited from an affordable city lease and is
receiving city assistance in negotiations for a suitable space,
owner J'Net Ward mourns the fact that this will be its last SXSW at
its current location.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very sad,'' said Ward. ``This whole year, everything has
been `this is the last time.' I get very teary-eyed, maybe
depressed, but then I think maybe the new club will be better. And
if I get the deal I'm working on now, the new building will be
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Across town on Red River Street _ where Liberty Lunch hopes to
move _ Stubb's booms on the east edge of the downtown entertainment
district. As the centerpiece of a strip previously notorious for
drug traffic and street crime, the club has developed into a top
SXSW attraction since it opened for the festival three years ago.
At the time, the venue was little more than an open lot, with a
restaurant and indoor staging that wasn't ready for business until
almost a month later.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it was just a big gravel pit back there, and it was
like we were building a big movie set for the conference,'' said
co-owner Charles Attal with a laugh. ``We were still hammering in
stairs that day, and then we opened the doors, and people rushed in
for the Fugees. It was kind of overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   In the years since, Stubb's has been better prepared. In
addition to nightly showcases, the restaurant's calendar is filled
with industry parties, as many as three each afternoon. Such
parties can be more lucrative than the evening shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties are where the big money is,'' Attal said. ``We're
downtown in the middle of everything, and people from out of town
love to eat barbecue. This is always a great place for all the
(talent and booking) agents to meet and a good chance for me to
hang out with them a little bit. I've been able to make agent
contacts just because of South by Southwest, and this business is
all about getting to know them and working with them. I don't care
if you have a piece of grass with no stage; if you're in with the
agent, you're going to get the show.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time the calendar turns to March 2000, Stubb's likely
still will be flourishing, competing with Direct Events for top
touring attractions. If the Red River negotiations continue to
progress, Liberty Lunch will find new life in partnership with
Stubb's, with the Texas Music Museum and even the Austin Rehearsal
Complex mentioned as part of the package.
</P>
<P>
   And the Electric Lounge?
</P>
<P>
   ``I could not in good conscience say what is going to happen,''
said Henry, ``except that when we close, they'll have to drag us
kicking and screaming out of here.'' &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
