<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas tobacco lawyer ordered to justify $260 million award
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The federal judge supervising Texas' $17.3
billion tobacco lawsuit settlement has ordered Houston attorney
Marc Murr to prove the validity of Murr's $260 million arbitration
award because it apparently violated the judge's order.
</P>
<P>
   Murr's claim for fees in the tobacco case was sharply criticized
by other attorneys involved on both sides and by lawmakers who
helped negotiate disputes over the settlement proceeds and attorney
fees. He has been called the ``stealth lawyer'' because few of the
principals in the case ever saw Murr work the case. Former Attorney
General Dan Morales has said Murr provided valuable
behind-the-scene advise to Morales during the case.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge David Folsom of Texarkana ordered Murr to
prove his case in a hearing May 6. That hearing will follow another
hearing on Attorney General John Cornyn's request to dismiss Murr's
claim. ``The judge on his own raised an issue we did not raise, as
he's entitled to do,'' Cornyn said, ``which we welcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Murr nor his Austin attorney, Roy Minton, could be
reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Bill Ratliff (R-Mount Pleasant), who as Senate
Finance Committee chairman helped negotiate competing claims to the
tobacco settlement last year, said Folsom's order ``bodes well'' if
it means Murr will be tossed out of the federal court case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're going to have to convince a state court and in
that case, I would agree with the attorney general that the
Legislature ought to decide it,'' Ratliff said.
</P>
<P>
   In his order, Folsom pointed to a claim by Minton that Murr's
arbitration had been conducted according to Folsom's order. But the
judge said the three-person panel evaluating Murr's claim did not
bnclude an arbitrator Folsom was supposed to select.
</P>
<P>
   The three arbitrators were chosen by Murr and Morales, who had
hired Murr, a friend, as a behind-the-scenes advisor in the tobacco
suit. When the arbitration award became public in December, Morales
explained that the manner in which arbitrators are chosen could be
changed under the agreement, as long as Murr and Morales approved.
</P>
<P>
   Murr has been a controversial figure in the tobacco case since
his role as Morales' advisor was first publicly disclosed near the
end of negotiations that culminated in the settlement in January
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Morales hired Murr in October 1996, seven months after filing
the lawsuit, for a 3 percent cut of the state's recovery. In
January 1997, a second contract set the fee as ``reasonable'' but
not specifying a percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Folsom's referred to his order of Jan. 22, 1998, that outlined
how arbitrators for Murr's claims would be picked when he wrote:
``This Court has never selected any panel member for such an
arbitration.''
</P>
<P>
   The so-called Murr panel awarded him 1.5 percent of the state's
$17.3 billion recovery, or $260 million over 25 years, in October.
The first public notice of the award came in December when Murr
used it to argue for a share of legal fees the tobacco companies
were paying in a national arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   The national arbitrators awarded him $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Only Murr and Morales presented evidence to support his claim to
the arbitrators they chose.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been concerned about the lack of an adversarial hearing
before the `state' arbitration panel,'' Cornyn said. ``They went in
arm-in-arm and were singing off the same sheet of music.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
