<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CLINTON-1STLD-WRITETHRU-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS `THRESHOLD HAS BEEN CROSSED' IN SERBIA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change ``Milosevic of Serbia'' to ``Milosevic of
Yugoslavia'' in 8th graf. No other changes.) (Eds: See also KOSOVO-U.S., KOSOVO-TALKS, KOSOVO-REFUGEES) 
(mk) 
 By JOHN M. BRODER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Preparing the American public for military action
in the Balkans, President Clinton said Friday that the ``threshold
has been crossed'' for the use of force against Serbia to prevent
further bloodshed in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make no mistake,'' Clinton said at an afternoon news
conference at the White House, ``if we and our allies do not have
the will to act, there will be more massacres. In dealing with
aggressors in the Balkans, hesitation is a license to kill. But
action and resolve can stop armies and save lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spoke as ominous signs spread across Europe that NATO
military strikes against Serbian targets could begin within days.
Peace talks between Serbian officials and Kosovar Albanian
nationalists broke down in Paris as the Serb side refused to sign a
peace accord accepted on Thursday by the ethnic Albanian majority
in Kosovo. Western governments began evacuating monitors and
nonessential personnel from Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced Friday that it was dispatching additional
combat aircraft to the region in anticipation of a series of air
strikes designed to reduce Serbia's ability to move against Kosovar
separatists.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent the bulk of his day Friday making a case for U.S.
participation in NATO-led military strikes in the Balkans, meeting
with a large contingent of members of Congress in the morning and
speaking extensively on the subject with reporters Friday
afternoon. He also met with his senior foreign policy advisers to
review plans for the possible air strikes, including the timing of
action, sequence of strikes and targets involved in the planned
Balkan campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders emerged from the White House meeting still
skeptical about the reasons for U.S. involvement in the
hostilities. Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the majority leader, said
the Senate would debate administration policy in Kosovo early next
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the president now recognizes the need to say
to the American people exactly what's at stake here, why would an
action be taken, what would those actions be and what are the
risks,'' Lott said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Don Nickles, R-Okla., said that he told the president that
the United States should not initiate a bombing campaign against
Serbia unless President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia engages in
a systematic assault on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton argued at the news conference that Milosevic had
already perpetrated numerous massacres and other atrocities, in
Kosovo and earlier in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the threshold has been crossed,'' Clinton said,
citing the mass killing of more than 40 Kosovar Albanian civilians
in the village of Racak in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the troops that have been massed, and what we know
about their plans, and what they have publicly said about them, I
would hate to think that we'd have to see a lot of other little
children die before we could do what seems to be, to me, clearly
the right thing to do to prevent it,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   He added later, ``I do not believe that we ought to have to have
thousands more people slaughtered and buried in open soccer fields
before we do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the rationale for the use of force goes beyond
humanitarian concerns.
</P>
<P>
   He said that a raging conflict in Kosovo could send tens of
thousands of refugees streaming across borders and potentially draw
Albania, Macedonia, Greece and Turkey into the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a conflict with no natural boundaries. It threatens
our national interests,'' Clinton said. ``If we don't act, the war
will spread. If it spreads, we will not be able to contain it
without far greater risk and cost. I believe the real challenge of
our foreign policy today is to deal with problems before they do
permanent harm to our vital interests. That is what we must do in
Kosovo.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Clinton faced pointed questioning on Kosovo Friday, both in his
meeting with congressional leaders and in the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked why Milosevic should take American threats
seriously now, after Clinton and other Western leaders had backed
down from earlier threats and allowed numerous negotiating
deadlines to pass. He was asked why NATO delayed action even though
Milosevic has carried out a continuing campaign of repression
against Albanians, Bosnian Muslims and other minorities in former
Yugoslav provinces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should take this seriously because we were serious
in Bosnia,'' Clinton said. ``My intention would be to do whatever
is possible, first of all, to weaken his ability to massacre them,
to have another Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the peace talks between the Serbians and the ethnic
Albanians were extended at the request of the parties, not because
of American irresolution. And he noted that Russia has consistently
opposed NATO military action against Moscow's allies in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and European leaders have enlisted Russian support for
peace efforts in Kosovo, but Moscow has steadfastly refused to
endorse any threat of force against Belgrade. The issue is certain
to arise when Yevgeny Primakov, the Russian prime minister, visits
Washington beginning next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The House last week narrowly voted to approve Clinton's plan to
send American troops to Kosovo to enforce a peace accord if all
parties reach an agreement. The United States would supply about
4,000 soldiers to a 28,000-person NATO peacekeeping force if a deal
is reached.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans have complained that the administration is
wading into a quagmire with no clear means of exit and without
sufficient public support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are going to be killed,'' Sen. Robert Bennett,
R-Utah, said in a speech on the Senate floor Friday. ``They are
going to come home in body bags, and they will be killed in a war
that Congress has not declared.''
</P>
</TEXT>
