</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GREENSPAN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greenspan gives thumbs up to safer derivatives
 &HT;    By Stephen Pounds
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ It was equivalent to the
win-one-for-the-Gipper speech, only for futures traders.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan gave a pep talk Friday to about 500 traders
attending the International Futures Industry Conference at the Boca
Resort &AMP; Club. An overflow crowd forced hotel staff to hastily add
seats behind breakfast serving tables for everyone to hear the
chairman of the Federal Reserve.
</P>
<P>
   And they weren't disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan endorsed the way futures dealers have reduced the risk
of financial derivatives in response to the Orange County, Calif.,
debacle five years ago. Derivatives derive their value from other
financial instruments. That is, an investor bets on the future
value of another security and if he is right, he makes a profit.
</P>
<P>
   When Orange County filed for bankruptcy protection in 1994,
largely because of poor investments in derivatives, and Procter &AMP;
Gamble surprised Wall Street with huge losses from derivatives that
same year, these investments were decried as too risky.
</P>
<P>
   But like the savings and loan scandal that blew up in the early
1990s, the derivative disaster of the mid-1990s forced the futures
industry to add more protection for investors.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan's speech was something of an industry vindication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Greenspan's appearance showed he is well aware of the
importance of the futures industry . . . and its ability to manage
risk, '' said Thomas Donovan, president of the Chicago Board of
Trade.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan pointed out that derivatives were a major factor in
the rise in the noninterest earnings of large banks in the past
decade, and that banks are applying the same capital reserve
requirements to them as they do to loans and other credit risks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dynamic speech. It was basically aimed at regulators,
and the position of the Fed is that everything is A-OK,'' said
George Gero, a director on the New York Mercantile Exchange board.
``It was a lovely speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
