<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAUDI-FAHD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAUDI ARABIA TO LET IRAQIS CROSS BORDER, MAKE PILGRIMAGE TO MECCA
 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   DOUGLAS JEHL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia _ A dispute between Iraq and the United
Nations that threatened to prevent Iraqis from making the annual
pilgrimage to Mecca was resolved Friday when Saudi Arabia said it
would pay the Iraqis' expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Iraqis were allowed to cross into Saudi Arabia as a
result of the decision and were beginning a 1,200-mile journey to
the holy city of Mecca, birthplace of Mohammed, where hundreds of
thousands of Muslims from around the world gather each year.
</P>
<P>
   The Iraqis had spent days stranded on the border, bused there by
the Iraqi government to dramatize the standoff. And like another
action earlier this week, the move seemed to have succeeded in
using religion as a political lever.
</P>
<P>
   The question of how pilgrimage costs of Iraqi Muslims should be
paid has bedeviled the United Nations throughout the more than
eight years in which it has enforced economic sanctions against
Iraq because of its invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the sanctions committee, composed of the same 15
nations that sit on the U.N. Security Council, agreed that some of
the oil money that Iraq is allowed to spend on imports like food
could also be used to subsidize the pilgrimage. To maintain strict
control over the money, it developed a system that required Iraqi
pilgrims to exchange vouchers for cash once they crossed into Saudi
Arabia. Iraq rejected the plan.
</P>
<P>
   It also rejected a compromise proposed by the Security Council,
in which the Red Cross or another independent agency would
distribute the funds. This resulted in the deadlock broken by Saudi
Arabia Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Iraq, apparently in violation of the U.N.
sanctions against air travel, sent more than 300 elderly pilgrims
to Mecca aboard three aircraft. Saudi Arabia briefly confiscated
two of the planes, but after members of the U.N. sanctions panel
failed to agree on whether the religious journeys were in fact a
violation, the Saudis allowed the pilgrims to stay and the planes
to return to Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   Under a quota system to avoid the dangers of overcrowding, which
in the past has led to deadly stampedes, each Muslim country has
the right to send 1,000 pilgrims per million of population. That
gives Iraq a total of 23,000, and Iraqi authorities along the
border were reported to have said that 18,000 Iraqis crossed into
Saudi Arabia Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between Saudi Arabia and Iraq have been uneasy since
the Persian Gulf War of 1991. But Saudi Arabia has always put its
religious obligations ahead of political differences.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been criticized by Muslims around the world if it
had been perceived as turning pilgrims away. The official Saudi
news agency quoted Prince Nayef, the interior minister, as saying
that King Fahd had decided to pay the pilgrims' costs, which are
expected to amount to about $2,000 per person.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
