<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 21:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7440 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATLANTA-NEWMOTOWN21-C     03-19 1727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATLANTA-NEWMOTOWN21-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta's emerging black celebrity scene
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 21.
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Through the rose-colored glasses sitting low on his
nose, Bunmi Jinadu is looking out for the rich and fabulous. That's
his job.
</P>
<P>
   The bald-headed Nigerian was hired by musical millionaires Sean
``Puffy'' Combs and Antonio ``L.A.'' Reid as VIP coordinator for
Justin's, their newly opened Atlanta restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   When teen heartthrob Usher Raymond drops in from Alpharetta
(Ga.), it's Boomy _ everyone calls him that _ who makes sure
there's a good table in the private dining room. And if the kitchen
is closed when rapper Gip of Goodie Mob and his vocalist-girlfriend
Joi show up, Boomy squares it with the chef so the couple doesn't
drive home to East Point (Ga.) on an empty stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Boomy aims to please every diner on his watch, regardless of
creed, color or Hollywood agent. But the prime objects of his
pampering are metro Atlanta's black glitterati, a growing cast of
African-American celebrities who are putting down roots, hanging
out their shingles and searching for the perfect place to see and
be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is a very who's-who kind of place,'' Jinadu says,
sitting at the restaurant's wood-and-marble bar. ``The people we're
dealing with are important, successful people who want to feel
there's a place for them to feel special.''
</P>
<P>
   Hot spots such as Justin's are cashing in on a little-noticed
facet of metro Atlanta's phenomenal growth. Black VIPs are being
drawn here by, among other things, the city's progressive image and
the handful of high-powered entertainment figures who also have
chosen to put down roots. Celebs have decamped from established
glam capitals such as New York and Los Angeles and joined
home-grown worthies who can afford to live elsewhere but choose to
remain in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Take 1970s musical stars. Metro Atlanta is home to legends
Curtis Mayfield, Jean Carne, Tamiko Jones and Peabo Bryson. The now
Pip-less Gladys Knight no longer lives in her hometown, but she
owns a restaurant downtown.
</P>
<P>
   There's an even longer A-list of fresher faces, including R&AMP;B
artists and hip-hop acts who can correctly use ``jiggy'' in a
sentence (but never would): Monica, Mase, Outkast, EPMD's Erick
Sermon, Chuck D. of Public Enemy, Phife Dog of Tribe Called Quest,
Todd ``Too Short'' Shaw, TLC , Da Brat and 112.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond music, Atlanta's black celebrity elite includes actors
Bill Nunn (``He Got Game''), Raven-Symone (``The Cosby Show''),
Taurean Blacque (``Hill Street Blues''), Tichina Arnold
(``Martin''), Emmanuel Lewis (``Webster''), as well as stand-up
comedians Joe Torry and George Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Poet Maya Angelou is a part-time Gwinnett Countian, while
full-time Atlantan Pearl Cleage insists that she's not a celebrity,
even though her appearance on ``Oprah'' last October propelled her
debut novel to best-sellerdom.
</P>
<P>
   Decatur (Ga.)-born movie star Chris Tucker has a comedy
nightclub in Midtown, and Michael Jackson's brother Marlon has a
gospel music production company near downtown. Crooner Keith Sweat
owns a restaurant/nightclub in Atlanta; basketball great Earvin
``Magic'' Johnson has a multiplex near Greenbriar Mall (metro
Atlanta); and rap impresario Jermaine Dupri's So So Def record
label is based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Boxing champion Evander Holyfield is living extra large at his
$20 million mansion in Fayette County, and he'll become the city's
best-known pugilist-restaurateur next month when he opens a swanky
new eatery in Sandy Springs.
</P>
<P>
   And if any of them need legal advice, they can dial locally to
reach O.J. Simpson lawyer Johnnie Cochran Jr., who opened a law
office in downtown Atlanta last month.
</P>
<P>
   Black celebrities' reasons for relocating to Atlanta are often
similar to those cited by lesser-known transplants: lower housing
costs, better weather and a slower pace than other large cities.
Some also cite the area's role in the civil rights movement and as
a place where blacks have long played major political and social
roles.
</P>
<P>
   Singer Raymond says one of the first stops his parents made when
they moved from Chattanooga was to take the family for a visit to
historic Auburn Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Martin Luther King's home and the museum, because
it was worldly knowledge that was right here in Atlanta, and they
wanted me to know about my history.''
</P>
<P>
   Actor Nunn was born in Pittsburgh but moved to Atlanta to attend
Morehouse College in 1970, when, he says, the city was ``like
Mayberry with a couple of skyscrapers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in school I met (former Mayor) Maynard Jackson, and
one of my instructors was (former Fulton County Commission
Chairman) Michael Lomax,'' Nunn says. ``I didn't think about it
consciously at the time, but I'm sure it had an effect on me,
seeing these people who were doing things in politics for the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Other factors make Atlanta special for celebrities. Bryson, who
moved here from Greenville, S.C., in 1971, says Atlanta has an
intangible advantage that show-biz types consider priceless: a
mostly paparazzi-free culture that's not ga-ga for celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta offers you a high level of anonymity,'' he explains.
``If your truck is dirty, you can go out and wash it without
signing a bunch of autographs. It gives you a sense of normalcy. It
keeps you grounded in a way New York or Los Angeles doesn't
allow.''
</P>
<P>
   Recording artist and producer Perri ``Pebbles'' Reid moved to
the Atlanta area with her husband, producer Antonio Reid, in the
1980s. Despite their divorce and a messy squabble with TLC, the
locally-based, platinum-selling recording act she once managed,
Reid says she's staying put.
</P>
<P>
   ``In L.A. there is no way you can get land like you can get
here, even if you are a celebrity,'' Reid says. ``Celebrities are
buying homes on top of celebrities there, because there's so little
land.''
</P>
<P>
   Reid recently sold her Alpharetta house in the exclusive Country
Club of the South subdivision to Raymond. She has since started a
religious ministry and moved farther north, ``where there are
horses in the back yard and it's peaceful. I can concentrate on
things of God and not things of man.''
</P>
<P>
   Among her friends and nearby neighbors is Morris Day, the
flamboyantly foppish one-time protege of the Artist, formerly known
as Prince. Day left Los Angeles and moved to north Fulton two years
ago with his wife and children because he saw qualities missing
from other large cities he visited.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were looking around for a while, and one of the things we
like was the culture of the city and the number of progressive
blacks who are doing things professionally,'' Day says, adding that
he also hangs out with vocalist Tony Rich, who lives in the area.
``You drive through Atlanta and you see upper-middle-class black
children playing basketball in their yards. You don't find that
kind of environment in too many other cities.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet another attraction for black celebrities: Although Atlanta
may not fixate on VIPs, the fact that so many entertainment movers
and shakers live here has elevated the city's image as a place
where show business dreams can come true. And where a VIP can
mingle with other VIPs.
</P>
<P>
   Singers such as Inoj and Trina Broussard have relocated to make
a creative connection with hit-making producers Dupri, Daryl
Simmons, Dallas Austin and Organized Noize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to further my career, and there were a lot of black
entrepreneurs doing business here,'' says Broussard, who lives in
Stone Mountain (Ga.). ``It was like a gold rush. Atlanta has really
blown up.''
</P>
<P>
   Broussard said she rarely goes out socially, but when she does
it's to restaurants and nightspots such as Justin's, the Shark Bar
in Midtown and Sylvia's near Atlanta City Hall downtown_ popular
haunts for black celebrities and those who like to be near them.
</P>
<P>
   Sacha Jenkins, music editor for Vibe magazine in New York, said
Atlanta is generating an industry buzz that has not gone unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like every other month we're down in Atlanta writing
about some artist,'' said Jenkins, whose magazine is preparing an
article on Dupri, the hip-hop impresario. ``There is a strong black
pop presence down there, with serious artists who are making some
serious dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell beams when discussing the area's
glitzy constellation of black stars, and he says he's personally
rolled out the welcome mat for many of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a phenomenon we're proud of, because in essence these
celebrities are voting with their feet, and their dollars,''
Campbell says. ``People are comparing Atlanta today to the Harlem
Renaissance in the 1920s,'' he continues, perhaps hyperbolically.
``They're also calling it the New Motown.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, cautions author Lawrence Otis Graham. Graham, whose
new book, ``Our Kind of People'' (HarperCollins, $25), explores
America's black upper class, says celebrities can be cultural
carpetbaggers with little long-term connection to the cities they
call home. A celebrity boom can go bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Detroit was a perfect example during Motown's heyday,'' Graham
says. ``Berry Gordy and all his artists were the biggest thing in
the city, but the black establishment couldn't count on them. Sure
enough, they moved to Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the movement is to Atlanta. Or from a small
house in one part of the area to a big one in another, trendier
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Music producer Dupri grew up in Fayette County, across the
street from boxer Holyfield's house and not far from rapper Chuck
D. He lives with his mother in that same house in an
upper-middle-class subdivision, and the only hint that there's
anything different about their home is the fleet of gleaming
Mercedes, Bentleys and Porsches parked neatly in the back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Dupri is moving soon. He recently bought a house in Atlanta,
near the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've just outgrown this place,'' he says. ``In Buckhead it
will be easier if I'm hanging out at Phipps Plaza with Mase or I
want to go to Justin's with Mariah Carey.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyle V. Harris writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Sonia Murray contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
