A7441 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEIRLOOM-SEEDS20-COX     03-19 1466
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEIRLOOM-SEEDS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cultivating seed traditions of yesteryear is growing at a swift
pace
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The seeds of spring are here, spilling out of wire
racks at local gardening centers and hardware stores like
tantalizing promises of a rich and tasty growing season. Fat green
beans bursting at the seams. Flowers so bright they could twirl up
the credits of a technicolor movie. Bright red tomatoes, just like
the ones Granny sliced for that plate that was always in the middle
of the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   But as you reach for those little paper packets, take a second
look at what you're putting in your basket, and ultimately in your
garden. If the seed package looks like an ad out of a 1910 farmer's
almanac with sepia-toned drawings, antique lettering and cozy
colors lifted from the pages of an old Dick and Jane book, you are
taking part in what has become one of the hottest trends in
gardening _ heirloom seeds.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, dozens of independent seed companies have
emerged specializing in heirloom varieties. For the third year in a
row, Burpee's mail-order company is offering an heirloom catalog.
Spokeswoman Eileen Caetano-Isola of the Web site
http://www.garden.com reports that 10 times as many heirloom
seedlings have been sold this year than were sold in 1998 and that
requests for information on seed cultivation have also grown.
</P>
<P>
   Heirloom seeds are vegetable and flower varieties that are at
least 50 to 100 years old, although commercial growers disagree
hotly on the definition. Like fine china or old photos, these are
the horticultural world's version of priceless antiques. They are
not hybrids, i.e., plants such as Big Boy tomatoes or Blue Lake
pole beans, bred for years by growers to resist disease and produce
consistent shapes and sizes. Because heirlooms are open-pollinated,
which means the plant can reproduce itself ``true to type'' through
natural pollination methods, unlike hybrids that are usually
sterile, growers can save and use the seeds from year to year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heirlooms are varieties that are often no longer available in
the commercial seed trade,'' says gardening guru Renee Shepherd,
founder of the California-based Renee's Garden. ``They have been
saved because they usually have stories attached to them, human
connections.''
</P>
<P>
   And perhaps that's the greatest appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Heirlooms often come with a history, a story about where they
originated and what makes them unique in family or folklore (hence
the nostalgic marketing).
</P>
<P>
   For example, the most famous heirloom is the Brandywine tomato,
a seed dating back to 1885 that is grown by an Amish community in
Chester County, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great big, pink beefsteak _ one ugly dude,'' says Lin
Harris, horticultural writer for Ferry-Morse seeds. ``It's not
disease resistant. It (ripens) awfully late, but it's a
conversation piece. And it really has a good flavor.''
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd tells of the ``Mortgage Lifter'' tomato, which
supposedly came down through a family ``who sold so many of the
plants they were able to pay off their mortgage.'' She also sells a
Purple Hyacinth bean vine, said to have been grown in Thomas
Jefferson's garden at Monticello. Ferry-Morse has stumbled upon the
Lazy Wife Bean (let's leave that one to the imagination).
</P>
<P>
   Southern culture, because of our agricultural tradition, is full
of heirlooms, although the seeds might not have ever been called by
that name. Denise Smith, owner of GardenSmith greenhouse and
nurseries in Jefferson, says the perfect example of a Southern
heirloom was ``Mr. Bryant's Tomatoes,'' a heritage variety she
sells.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Bryant was a little man in town who saved his tomato seeds
every year, and we would raise flats and sell them,'' Smith says.
``All the people in the community knew they could come out here and
get Mr. Byant's tomato. It was an old Oxheart, a big lumpy tomato
that looked like an ox heart you get at the meat counter. We had
people call from all over the Southeast because it tasted better
than the stuff at the store. It tasted like a real tomato, not a
big red water balloon, even though a lot of the time the plants
were ugly or had cracks. The seeds had passed from his family from
the late 1800s. He died, but we have still have a version of the
Oxheart.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern cowpeas are another example of vegetables with history
and endangered tradition. Today, only a handful of varieties are
available through commercial catalogs, although Southern tables
were rarely without a big bowl of shelled peas that were as
different from garden to garden as the families who raised them.
Many have been passed down through the generations. (Smith recalls
that in her hometown of Americus, everyone got ``Mr. Easterland's
peas.'') But, sadly, many varieties have also been lost as
Southerners left the farm for the microwaved comfort of suburban
kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Heirloom flowers, perhaps, offer even more variety than
vegetable seeds _ Victorian-era sweet pea, aster, marigold,
hollyhock, nasturtium. Burpee, which has produced perhaps the most
ambitious and widely available heirloom line for 1999, sells these
individually or grouped in a collection called ``Grandmother's
Flower Sampler.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People are starting to want the English look or the cottage
garden look _ short, fat, skinny, floppy,'' Smith says. ``I think
it's a reaction to the commerciality of the greenhouse industry and
long-distance shipping to garden centers where everything was bred
to be 8 to 10 inches tall in the flower bed. Instead of little rows
of soldiers in front of your house, people are wanting sweeps of
color and mixed containers spilling over and climbing _ a garden
that's a little wild. And you can get that with heirlooms.''
</P>
<P>
   However, aesthetic appeal isn't the only force behind the
growing interest in heirlooms. The renaissance of these seeds
actually began back in the 1970s as a result of
environmental/political causes. Most point to Kent Whaley as the
godfather of the movement. In 1975, with a handful of purple
morning glory seeds passed down from his grandfather from Bavaria,
he started Seed Savers Exchange in Decorah, Iowa. Part of the
back-to-nature movement of the time, Whaley and others were
apparently concerned over the eroding genetics of flowers and
vegetables, conglomerate control of food sources and dwindling
diversity in the food supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to find other people who were keeping varieties,
and discovered there was a tremendous heritage out there that was
being lost,'' Whaley says. ``We started networking these people
together to prevent the loss of history and culture.'' Today Whaley
produces a 40-page catalog with more than 297 heirloom varieties,
although he says Seed Savers has researched over 11,000.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, some point to the coming of the millennium as an impetus
in the growing heirloom movement. ``Some people seem to be worrying
about things like food supply more,'' Harris says. There's even a
plan for a Y2K garden on the Internet, although seed expert
Shepherd finds that kind of hysteria ``repugnant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that has a lot to do with why heirlooms are big
this year,'' she says. ``It has more to do with the restaurant chef
movement, which has picked up on putting lots of diversity and
color in what they are serving. Vegetables are moving to the center
of the plate, and so there has been a lot of interest from the food
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with heirlooms can be an adventure, like transplanting
flower bulbs from the family homeplace, or finding a dusty bag of
seeds in your great uncle's garden shed and watching them grow. But
heirlooms can also be a challenge. They are not necessarily as easy
to cultivate as the old standbys, the hybrids. Because different
climates and conditions affect how they grow, heirlooms can also
vary greatly from one part of the country to another _ you may not
necessarily end up with a plant that looks like the one of the
front of the seed package.
</P>
<P>
   Most growers concede that if you're looking for a dependable,
hearty plant, go with a hybrid. But if you like to experiment in
the dirt, or want a unique connection to the past, give heirlooms a
try.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, a lot of it is about nostalgia,'' Smith says. ``I think
what has happened is we have moved from people who grew up in the
Depression and maybe lived their entire lives on the farm, to a
younger generation of plant enthusiasts who remember going to
Grandma's in the summer. Sure, it's a fad. People don't know
exactly what an (heirloom) plant is going to do. But that's part of
the fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Miriam Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
