<HEADER>
A7442 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-HEALTH20-COX     03-19 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-HEALTH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Self-assessment tests on Internet helpful but
limited
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ever felt younger _ or older _ than your actual age in
years?
</P>
<P>
   The Internet offers a quick and simple way to find out whether
you may be right: Online self-tests assess everything from your
medical history to how fast you drive, then determine your overall
health outlook and compute the age you resemble, compared to the
average American.
</P>
<P>
   These health risk assessments provide users with a good general
overview of their health status, as well as an indication of how it
could be improved.
</P>
<P>
   But like the Internet as a whole, these self-tests shouldn't be
taken as gospel. Most health assessment Web sites have a disclaimer
reminding users that the questionnaires aren't diagnostic tools,
and that people should seek a doctor's advice for medical
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Usually, (health assessment tests) are helpful in making
people aware of possible problems they may have,'' said Dr. Kelleen
Fitzgerald, an internist and clinical instructor at Emory
University . ``They should almost always be followed up with a talk
with your physician, so the physician can help the patient put it
in context.''
</P>
<P>
   The tests generally include basic multiple-choice questions
about weight, blood pressure, cholesterol levels, family medical
history and substance use. They may also ask about other lifestyle
behaviors that can affect risk of disease, injury or death, such as
not wearing a seat belt or having multiple sexual partners.
</P>
<P>
   After the user fills out the questionnaire, the answers are run
through a program that calculates overall health status and life
expectancy based on population-based studies of health risk
factors. For instance, a 35-year-old man might find that his health
outlook resembles that of a 32-year-old average American.
</P>
<P>
   But that information isn't necessarily useful _ the average
American may not take optimal care of his health. Study after study
shows Americans don't exercise regularly, and most consume 30
percent or more of their diet in fat. So being better than average
isn't necessarily laudable.
</P>
<P>
   The information also can be inaccurate, Fitzgerald warned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure how they can make that assessment without
actually seeing the patient,'' she said. ``That would not be
something I would feel real comfortable putting much belief in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might placate somebody who is overweight and lives a
sedentary lifestyle,'' Fitzgerald added. ``If (a health assessment
test) tells them they're really 30, then they're not going to go to
the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   She also pointed out that most risk factors are broad
generalizations based on statistics from large medical studies, and
may not be applicable to each individual.
</P>
<P>
   Some health risk tests deliberately err on the side of caution,
to avoid mistakenly inspiring confidence. The risk assessment tests
offered by the American Diabetes Association and the American Heart
Association, for example, each have fewer than 10 questions _ but
they're enough to send up a red flag if the answers merit it.
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what these tests are designed to do: Alert
people to potential problems and educate them about risky
behaviors.
</P>
<P>
   The American Diabetes Association's Diabetes Risk Test is on the
Web at http://www.diabetes
</P>
<P>
   .org/ada/risktest.asp. The American Heart Association's quiz on
cardiac disease risk factors is at http://www.americanheart
</P>
<P>
   .org/risk/quiz.html.
</P>
<P>
   HealthCentral, an online health information service at
http://www.healthcentral.com, gives users the option of performing
a full-length self-assessment that takes roughly 10 minutes, or any
one of several two-minute mini-profiles. The shorter profiles cover
a variety of topics, including fitness, nutrition, stress
management, alcohol and substance use and sexual health.
</P>
<P>
   The health risk assessment provided by Greenstone Healthcare
Solutions, a health-care management database provider, at
http://www.youfirst.com is one of the most detailed and
comprehensive on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   The site creates a lengthy individualized report that warns
users about risky behaviors as well as educates them about the
importance of certain health parameters, such as cholesterol and
blood pressure. The report also reminds people about regular
screenings and immunizations they should receive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had epidemiologists and physicians help create (the
site),'' said Shelly Schabes, project manager at Pharmacia Upjohn,
Greenstone's parent company.
</P>
<P>
   The YouFirst site receives about 15,000 hits a month, and so far
2,500 users have completed the health assessment test, Schabes
said.
</P>
<P>
   A unique aspect of the YouFirst site is that it allows users the
option of anonymously saving their health information under a
password so they can periodically retake the test and gauge their
improvement. The information could prove useful for employers
interested in tracking workers' health behaviors, Schabes said.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
