<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7443 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-OSCARS20-COX     03-19 1856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-OSCARS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Critics offer their opinion regarding spiritual content of
movies nominated for Best Film in this years Oscars
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ THE OSCARS
</P>
<P>
   Five critics from diverse religious backgrounds offer their
thoughts on this year's nominees for Best Picture, focusing on the
moral, ethical and spiritual implications of each movie.
</P>
<P>
   The critics rank the finalists in relation to one another, with
1 being the highest and 5 the lowest, judging each movie's moral
message and how well it is conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Baehr, an ordained Episcopal priest, is chairman of the
Christian Film and Television Commission and publisher of
Movieguide magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Ed McNulty, an ordained Presbyterian minister, publishes Visual
Parables, a film review journal, and has taught theology and film
at Decatur's (Ga.) Columbia Theological Seminary.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Herx is a film reviewer for the United States Catholic
Conference's Office for Film and Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Medved, who attends an Orthodox synagogue, is an author,
movie critic and host of a nationally syndicated radio show.
</P>
<P>
   Holly McClure is the movie critic for The Orange Country
Register and syndicated in 360 newspapers. She is a
nondenominational Christian.
</P>
<P>
   LIFE IS BEAUTIFUL (PG-13)
</P>
<P>
   An Italian Jew shields his son from the horrors of a
concentration camp by pretending their predicament is part of a
big, complicated game.
</P>
<P>
   SAVING PRIVATE RYAN (R)
</P>
<P>
   An American Army captain (Tom Hanks) leads a squad of men behind
enemy lines after D-Day to rescue a private who has lost all of his
brothers in battle. The film is known for its brutal opening D-Day
landing scene.
</P>
<P>
   THE THIN RED LINE (R)
</P>
<P>
   Legendary director Terrence Malick puts his unmistakable stamp
on the drama of an Army division's struggle to capture Guadalcanal
from the Japanese during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE (R)
</P>
<P>
   Poor, overworked Will Shakespeare (Joseph Fiennes) has to finish
his play ``Romeo and Ethel, the Pirate's Daughter'' and try to win
the hand of noblewoman Viola (Gwyneth Paltrow) in this witty
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   ELIZABETH (R)
</P>
<P>
   This opulent period film puts a slight feminist gloss on the
early reign of 16th-century monarch Elizabeth I, showing her
transformation from a radiant, saucy innocent to a polished,
ruthless ruler.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore ``Ted'' Baehr/Life is Beautiful
</P>
<P>
   The movie is extremely morally acceptable. It's an incredible
job at looking at the most difficult topic, which is the Holocaust,
but in a way that can reach a broad range of people. There's no
excessive violence. There's no tricks of the trade _ sex, nudity or
violence. It's incisive, creative film-making that makes it a
classic film on the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan It's probably more redemptive than ``The
Thin Red Line'' in that Capt. Miller (Hanks' character) is willing
to lay down his life for someone he said that he may not even like.
But its violence takes it out of our recommended category.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Red Line It explores psychologically the same issues as
``Saving Private Ryan.'' Certainly some of its conclusions are not
some we'd come up with. But it asks the right questions and it does
have a lot of prayer and soul searching.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare in Love It doesn't fit our standards. Although it
has an extremely witty script, the movie reduces Shakespeare to the
lowest common denominator. I'm not saying the movie isn't clever,
but it removes all of the nobler instincts from Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking. No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth It's our last choice. The real Elizabeth was willing
to go to the gallows for her Protestant faith and was quite a
theologian in her own right. It is far from historically accurate.
There was a tremendous religious dialogue that was going on that
the movie ignored.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking. No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Ed McNulty/Life Is Beautiful The whole element of the use of the
imagination to protect innocence in the face of overwhelming evil
is powerfully portrayed. I think you have to take it like a
spiritual fable or parable. Once you can do it, the whole film just
falls into place. I think the moral message is the power of the
imagination, that it can defeat the power of evil to do harm to our
souls.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan It is a wonderful parable of sacrifice. It's
a fitting tribute to a generation that made the sacrifice of
liberating Europe in their own blood. I linked it to what Paul once
wrote, ``Remember you were bought with a great price.'' Ryan
realizes this when he breaks down near the end in the cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Red Line It raises important questions of morality and
meaning and dares to say that even amid the brutality there is a
spark of the eternal and divine. We weren't given a Sunday school
lesson. Part of Malick's greatness is that he leaves it to viewers
to come to their own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare In Love I think it's wonderful entertainment that
shows the linkage of romance and creativity, that love can unlock
the closed gates of the creative mind. If ``Romeo and Juliet''
wasn't written that way, the film shows that it should have been.
The one moral qualm I had is the fact that Shakespeare was married.
I do have moral reservations that the film didn't even deal with
the adultery.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth It's a wonderful film that shows the progression of an
unsure woman dependent on the advice of others becoming her own
person. But it sheds little light on the terrible religious wars of
that time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Henry Herx/Life Is Beautiful I think it's the most creative of
the films. It uses comedy seriously. It is one of those films where
I doubted whether it was possible to see anything humorous in such
tragic circumstances. And yet (Roberto Benigni) brings life and
hope and a sense of triumph of the spirit in the worst of
circumstances. It's a marvel.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan It's celebrating all of those virtues such
as country, God and family. It doesn't take a look back at World
War II from today. It tries to recapture what the perspective was
like in the 1940s. It didn't have resonance, a longer view of what
it all meant. It's locked within its time and place. It's a
considerable achievement but it's limited because of that.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Red Line This one takes a longer view, which is very
introspective. It has an anti-war stance that ``Private Ryan''
doesn't. It presents an alternative view of sacrifice and the
tragedy of war that's represented by a just war. I think it's
off-putting. There are many people who are not on the same
wavelength as Malick. I don't think it quite works.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare in Love It is very literate. It's very playful but
it is sexually explicit. It's amazing that the film depends on
Joseph Fiennes' performance but he's not up for an Academy Award. I
don't think it's terribly deep but I like it a lot.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Elizabeth is full of flash and fury. I think it misses
what that period was all about. The drama is all in the background
rather than in the people. The people are reduced to stereotypes.
It doesn't get across a sense of the religious dimensions of the
power struggle.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Michael Medved/Life Is Beautiful It makes two important points _
that's why so many people love this film. One is the importance of
childhood innocence and the idea that childhood innocence is
important even in the horrendous circumstances of a death camp. The
second message is that the role of husband and father is the
highest calling to which any man can aspire. That's a particularly
welcome message.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan The moral message of the film has to do with
sacrifice to a larger cause, the importance of brotherhood and
companionship. There are six or seven points in the movie where it
takes a very clear stand for humanity, even in the face of
horrendous killing. It showed tremendous moral complexity.
Sometimes you may do the right thing, and still not be rewarded for
it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Red Line It's ``Private Ryan'' on mushrooms. It does
generate some of the same messages as ``Private Ryan'' _ the
importance of commitment to comrades. But the idea of a commitment
to a higher cause is completely lacking. They could have called it
``The Long Red Line.'' It seemed to go on and on and didn't seem to
know where it was going.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare In Love I liked it enormously as a movie but it
raised no deeper moral questions. Next to ``Private Ryan'', it was
my favorite movie of the year, but when you think about it, the
message it sends is both seductive and destructive, the idea that
nothing really matters other than artistic success.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Its nomination makes absolutely no sense. There were
values, ideas and larger elements that the real Queen Elizabeth
cared about, but this movie reduces her to an ambitious, utterly
selfish and self-absorbed lady who turns her victimizers into
victims. It's a mafia movie transferred to the 16th century .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Holly McClure/Life Is Beautiful Roberto Benigni spins a
slapstick farce about the Holocaust and how an Italian Jew tries to
convince his little boy that the concentration camp they've been
sent to is part of a game. The heart, overcoming spirit and
precious appreciation for the gift of life is a true reflection of
how light will always shine in darkness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 3
</P>
<P>
   Saving Private Ryan The movie gives this country a glimpse of
what the American spirit and patriotism was like back when this
country was unified as ``One Nation Under God.'' This is not only a
movie about war, but about the price of freedom. Its faith message
is woven into the attitudes, behavior sacrifices and decisions
these men made.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 1
</P>
<P>
   The Thin Red Line I equate watching this movie to be about as
exciting as watching paint dry and equally as emotionally stirring.
It blends war, sex and the psychological effects of killing into
one long and boring movie that asks a lot of questions about God
but unfortunately doesn't show the true side of God.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 5
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare In Love This is a well-written, well-acted, romantic
tale about Shakespeare and his inspiration for love. Unfortunately,
the sexual promiscuity prevails over anything spiritual and the
godly Elizabethan morality prevalent at that time is replaced with
love and lust.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 4
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth It's not only about dirty politicians, corrupt
government and sex but it's about the decision to worship God with
freedom. Elizabeth proved that by making personal sacrifices and
putting God first, He elevated her to a place of prominence in
history.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ranking: No. 2
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
