<HEADER>
A7444 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHITECLERIC-BLACKCHUR     03-19 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITECLERIC-BLACKCHURCH20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    White cleric ministers to a black congregation in East Atlanta
 &HT;    By John Blake
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bishop Michael D. Spires, ``the blackest white
minister in Atlanta,'' is about to show his church a miracle.
</P>
<P>
   The choir at the Church of Atlanta Lighthouse has already driven
the congregation to a frenzy when Spires takes the pulpit on a
recent Sunday morning. An elderly deacon does a creaky jig in the
aisle. A plump woman collapses, sobbing in the arms of ushers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people afraid to shout because they don't want to mess up
their dress,'' Spires, 58, barks while pacing the pulpit. ``Some
people don't want to shout because they don't want to mess up their
weave!''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Spires beckons to a woman in the audience to join him.
He tells the congregation that she was once in a coma. He prayed
over her in a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   After the visit, Spires says he received a call on his car phone
from a doctor reporting something strange.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went into the room,'' Spires says, ``she was sitting in
a rocking chair eating food and I said, `Save me some, girl!' ''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd erupts in shouts of joy. The woman, Josephine
Summerlin, 61, buries her head against Spires' chest and cries.
</P>
<P>
   ``God is still in the miracle-working business!'' Spires yells
over the congregation's exaltations.
</P>
<P>
   The church's drummer kicks off a soulful groove. The saxophonist
starts wailing. Spires nods at his co-pastor, and they both execute
a graceful 360-degree dance turn as the choir hits its chorus,
singing, ``So glad I found him, Jesus saves.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene could be the highlight reel of any black Pentecostal
Sunday service in metro Atlanta except for one detail _ Spires is
white and his congregation is virtually all black.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 26 years, Spires has been a pulpit pioneer, leading
this nondenominational black church in a working-class section of
East Atlanta. He has endured death threats, taunts from white and
black people. He's even had to overcome his past, _ being raised in
a segregated Southern town in a family that had ties to the Ku Klux
Klan.
</P>
<P>
   The experience has profoundly changed Spires. Almost all of his
friends are black. People who hear him on his weekday radio show
think he's black. Spires even gets uncomfortable now when he's in
an all-white setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I start looking for black people,'' Spires said. ``The
question comes to my mind. Why am I the only one here? It kind of
makes me think, `How am I going to act around these people?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Spires say, however, that he is no Michael Bolton
of the pulpit _ a black wannabe who thinks the culture of
African-Americans is exotic.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Ross, a black Atlanta political pollster, has watched
Spires interact with black ministers and church members for two
years. He has been so impressed by Spires and his ministry that he
will award the pastor the 18th annual Pioneer Achievement Award
next week for the ``indelible'' mark he has had on Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Spires will be the only white of the 15 honorees at the March 27
event. Other honorees include U.S. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.); and
Robert Benham, the chief justice of Georgia's Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's genuine, consistent and for real,'' Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Spires does not define himself as a racial bridge builder.
``When I stand on the platform and preach Sunday morning, I'm not
looking at black people,'' he said. ``I'm seeing souls.''
</P>
<P>
   `Get your own church'
</P>
<P>
   It's a wonder that Spires even has a church to preach in. The
church was on the verge of closing when he first took over.
</P>
<P>
   When Spires arrived at the Church of Atlanta Lighthouse in 1966
as an assistant pastor, the church was split roughly between
black-- and white-- . Over the next several years it became
predominantly black. By 1972, the white founder of the church, Al
Rowan, decided to move North.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 20 members remained. But Spires volunteered to take
over the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of questions from whites,'' said Doris Spires,
56, the pastor's wife. ``People would ask, `Why would you want to
go and pastor a black church?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Blacks had questions, especially for Spires' co-pastor, Charles
Smith. ``Why are you with this white man? Why don't you get your
own church?'' Smith recalled hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The first service started with a whimper. There were 23 people
in the church, compared to about 500 at its peak during the
mid-'60s. The offering came to $35.
</P>
<P>
   Spires went to work. He invited popular black preachers such as
T.D. Jakes of Dallas to hold revivals at his church. He met with
black pastors to build friendships. Smith's presence also helped
retain black church members who were uncomfortable with a white
pastor.
</P>
<P>
   ``My presence here is to bridge a number of gaps,'' Smith said.
``We still have people who have difficulty with this relationship.
There are a number of cases where people have probably approached
me because they felt more comfortable relating to me because I'm
black.'' In the early years, some of the criticism became personal,
laced with racism. Spires received anonymous letters from white
people who called him a ``n-lover,'' and threatened his wife, and
their two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My own people turned their back on me,'' Spires said.
</P>
<P>
   So Spires turned his ministry toward the African-American
community. His church started taking food and clothes to black
people in nearby housing projects. He preached among blacks in
Jamaica, Nigeria and the Ivory Coast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen him around anybody white except ourselves,''
said the Rev. Teresa Spires, his 36-year-old sister.
</P>
<P>
   The running joke at the Church of Atlanta Lighthouse is that
somewhere along the way Spires actually became black. His sermons
are peppered with black slang. During a recent sermon on adultery,
Spiers used words such as ``tail-shaker'' and ``hootchie-momma'' to
describe a temptress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a lot of of co-workers who listen to him on the radio
who didn't realize he was white,'' said Joyce Jones, a Lighthouse
member for 18 years. ``I've heard some of them say he's the
blackest white minister in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   A stocky man, who wears a goatee and a long, black leather coat,
Spires said he's not trying to act black. ``If you move from one
country to another, after awhile, you start talking in their
dialect or their brogue,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He does admit, however, that he prefers to preach before black
congregations.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a man's got any preach in him, black people can pull it
out,'' Spiers said. ``Their reaction to a sermon inspires a
minister to go on and do more.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is a palpable bond between Spires and his
congregation that seems to have little to do with color. A sermon
can't go by without Spires calling a member from the stage to share
a hug or an inspirational story. The church now has about 1,000
members, but the services feel like a family reunion as people mill
about, exchanging warm greetings and hugs. ``When I go there, I
don't think, `Wow, look at all of these black people,' '' said
Wanda Villafranco, one of about 10 white members who regularly
attend the Church of Atlanta Lighthouse. ``I'm thinking, `Wow, all
of these people love me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Spires knows what it means to be an outcast. He grew up as one
in Clinton, S.C. His father, Grady Spiers, was an alcoholic who
physically abused his mother. An older brother died at 10, and a
younger brother was rendered mildly retarded after a bout with
scurvy. As a boy, Spiers got into constant fights while defending
his younger brother from taunts.
</P>
<P>
   He left school at 14 to work in the town's textile mill, joining
his mother and father who also worked at the plant.
</P>
<P>
   It was his grandmother, Rosa Spires, who gave him faith and
taught him tolerance. Though Clinton was segregated _ Spires had no
black friends in his youth _ his grandmother treated everyone
equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Black people came by our house and she'd give them food,''
Spires said. ``She'd give them clothes. She treated all people
alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Spires' father also shaped him. The older Spires experienced a
conversion when Michael was a teenager. He stopped drinking and
became a preacher at tent revivals. Even though Grady Spires was an
``old Georgia farmer'' who, along with his relatives, supported
groups like the Klan , he said racism never ``made sense'' to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``A human being is a human being,'' said Grady Spiers, now 84.
``We all suffer alike. We're all happy alike.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspired by his father and grandmother, Spires said he knew when
he was six that he wanted to be a preacher. It's a calling that
runs in his family. His sister Teresa runs Rescue Atlanta, a street
ministry for ``pimps, prostitutes, and HIV patients.'' A younger
brother, Reggie, is a Christian songwriter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've come through hardships,'' Teresa Spires said. ``We know
what it's like for people to look down on you. We've been given a
calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Spires' calling was also inspired by something else _ a tent
revival he attended in Columbia, S.C., during his youth. Police
placed a rope in the middle of the tent to keep white and black
worshippers apart, but it collapsed during the climax of the
service.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows why, but the rope fell,'' Spires said. ``God was
moving. People had their hands lifted. All of a sudden, we looked
and everybody had stepped into the other people's section. We were
embracing one another. We were crying. We could feel each others
need, pains and victories. We never put that rope back up again.''
</P>
<P>
   That tent revival was more than an inspirational moment. It was
a prelude to the life he now lives, Spires said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There comes a time when we have to take the ropes out of our
lives and let people in,'' Spires said. ``We got too many barriers.
We hold people back. God wants us to be free. God wants us to love
one another.''
</P>
<P>
   John Blake writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
