<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEEMAY-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A gardener needs to take time out and just sit a spell
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Like ants and bees, gardeners doggedly embrace the
work ethic; tirelessly, we hunt and gather, building spaces fine
and tidy. But unlike the insects, we humans know there comes a time
for what a friend calls ``some serious butt time.'' That's why I
always make sure my garden has plenty of sitting places _ benches,
chairs, rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Year-round sitting is as important to me as year-round blooming.
And with the shank of the sitting season imminent, I pay as much
attention to my seating as I do to my pruning. Will this rotten
wood last another year? Should I scrape and paint that wrought iron
or call it artfully aged?
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, parking on a seat is a necessary counterpoint to all
the hauling and toting and lifting and digging and watering we
gardeners do; enjoying is as important as toiling. At the same
time, I get a lot of work done during those sitdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you can just think better when you're sitting: Umm, an
empty spot here. I must get to the nursery as soon as I'm finished
sitting. And, looking at plants when I'm seated provides a valuable
perspective. Valuable because I want my space to be a sitting
garden as well as a strolling garden. Thus, sitting is checking
whether I'm succeeding. Ahhh, that maple has gotten out of hand and
in my face. I'll prune it as soon as I finish sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Few garden activities are learned overnight; I had gardened for
years before I realized the importance of garden sitting. Too busy
with the traditional work of gardening.
</P>
<P>
   Over time, however, I've come to liken seats to plants,
recalling their origins, enjoying the memories they evoke.
</P>
<P>
   My first garden bench was born in 1990 in Sugar Hill. A retired
postal worker made it with pride and skill in his garage workshop.
Oak, with a back shaped like half a sun, it has served well in its
corner of the brick wall out back, and after almost a decade of
rains and freezes and blazing summers, it wobbles a bit. I will not
banish it until it falls down in a rotted heap.
</P>
<P>
   A bench with a metal back and wooden slats for its seat came a
year or so later, discovered at a Decatur furniture shop. I
replaced the wood about five years ago. Then, last year, in a fit
of whimsy, I sprayed red paint on the oval designs in the bench's
back _ to Lyn's dismay.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, she encouraged my spray cans and me to lively
up two black, wrought-iron chairs and a table on the side porch.
So, for a year now, the small group has stood by the kitchen door
wearing streaks and swirls of red, green, brown, purple, gold. OK,
to appreciate the look, you have to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Out front, a big old oak swing dominates. There's nothing like a
porch swing to encourage and reward viewing a garden. Sit there and
gently move back and forth, looking at the azaleas, listening to
the chain's easy squeak and rattle, and you know this has to be an
essential part of the gardening experience.
</P>
<P>
   These sitting places are in Atlanta. My McCaysville (Ga.) garden
just got its first bench, one with no back, so Lyn and I can sit
facing Fightingtown Creek or swing around and face the garden.
McCaysville won't have nearly as many manmade garden seats as
Atlanta. But those big rocks _ round or flat _ sprouting around the
land sit and fit just right.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
