<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-ARRIVES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Welcoming the first day of spring
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ This is the first day of spring; it officially arrives
at 8:46 p.m. On the first day of spring, also referred to as the
vernal equinox, the sun rises due east and sets due west; day and
night are of essentially equal length. This season, spring will
last 92 days, 18 hours and 3 minutes until summer begins on June
21, say Fernbank Science Center astronomers.
</P>
<P>
   SPRING BREAKS: It may be spring this weekend, but last weekend
it was still winter, cold, gray and dreary.
</P>
<P>
   At the Chattahoochee National Recreation Area, though, wildlife
and wildflowers brightened the overcast weekend, says naturalist
Jerry Hightower. On his ramblings, he spied a grey fox and a
Cooper's hawk in the Island Ford Unit. White-tailed deer, great
blue and green herons, red-shouldered and red-tailed hawks, swamp
rabbits and tracks of mink, raccoon, otter, beaver and muskrat were
seen in the Jones Bridge Unit.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend, the red blush of red maple blooms, the white
blossoms of serviceberry and the purple petals of a few early red
buds can be seen along the river. Yellow-flowered trout lilies and
blue- to lavender-flowered hepatica are still blooming in the West
Palisades Unit.
</P>
<P>
   And all along the Chattahoochee people are seeing the white,
pink or purple flowers of fruit trees, the yellow of daffodils, the
purple of periwinkle and other introduced flowers from the many old
homesteads, some dating to the early 1800s. ``While not native,
their beauty is certainly a part of the river's cultural history,''
Hightower said.
</P>
<P>
   Spring guided walks in the recreation area begin next Saturday
with a floodplain forest hike in the Powers Island Unit. For a
schedule of the free walks send a stamped, self-addressed
legal-size envelope to 8615 Barnwell Road, Alpharetta, GA 30022.
</P>
<P>
   Other wildflower walks are being held at several state parks in
coming weeks. One is scheduled for April 9-11 at Unicoi State Park
near Helen. Visitors may see in bloom foamflower, anemone,
trillium, Indian pink, various violets, buckeye and spring beauty.
For more information, call 706-878-3983.
</P>
<P>
   Another walk is scheduled for April 10 at Panola Mountain State
Park near Stockbridge (Ga.). Panola is a large granite outcropping
similar to Stone Mountain (Ga.). The rock face hosts many unusual
plants, including diamorpha and sandwort. Visitors also may see
alum, atamsco lily, stonecrop, dogwood, bloodroot, toadflax and
yellow hawkweed. Pre-registration is required, and there is a $2
per person fee. For more information, call 770-389-7801.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these flowers are blooming now in Callaway Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   FIELD NOTES: Penelope Malone of Lake Forrest Drive in Atlanta
says the annual invasion of cedar waxwings took place at her home
the other day when a flock of about 25-50 birds landed on her
American holly tree and stripped ``every single red berry'' in 15
minutes. ``Every year for the past 18 years they've come,'' Malone
says.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Georgia Native Plant Society have spent a lot of
time recently rescuing trout lilies from a development site near
Alpharetta (Ga.). ``There must be 10,000 trout lilies there,'' says
Jeane Saylor Reeves of the society, which tries to save plants that
would be destroyed by construction.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE SKY: The moon will be first quarter Wednesday evening in
the south as it gets dark, says Fernbank astronomer David Dundee.
Venus and Saturn are in the west just after dark; Saturn sets in
the west about three hours later. Mars, which is steadily
brightening during March, rises out of the east before midnight.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Seabrook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
