u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-SEX-TAPE-560&AMP;A     03-19 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SEX-TAPE-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER BROADCAST OF PROSECUTOR IN SEX TAPE, YELTSIN FIRES CHIEF OF
STAFF
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Less than two days after his government's television
network shocked pretty much everyone by broadcasting a videotape of
Russia's chief prosecutor in bed with two women, President Boris
Yeltsin dismissed his chief of staff Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The prevailing wisdom was that the dismissed official, Nikolai
Bordyuzha, had become the fall guy for the devastating failure _ so
far, anyway _ of the government's campaign to force the resignation
of the prosecutor general, Yuri Skuratov.
</P>
<P>
   But so much of Russian politics is subterranean that it is
difficult even for seasoned political observers to divine what is
happening. A number of political leaders were quoted Friday night
as saying that Yeltsin tends to fire at will, especially when
emerging from a long illness, and that Bordyuzha was simply in the
wrong place at the wrong time.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, 68, looking puffy and speaking in an especially labored
manner, abruptly left a Moscow clinic on Thursday after weeks of
off-and-on hospitalization for an ulcer.
</P>
<P>
   His early release seems to have been set off by the Skuratov
affair, a bizarre sex-and-videotape scandal that threatens to
weaken whatever slim grip Yeltsin still holds on the reins of
power.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov, a favorite of Communists and ultranationalists who
oppose Yeltsin, has a less than stellar record of rooting out
official corruption. His resignation a month ago, ostensibly for
health reasons, had been seen as a fairly routine Yeltsin
housecleaning.
</P>
<P>
   But it roared back into public view this week, when Skuratov
decided to stay in office and Russia's normally docile upper
legislative house, the Federation Council, voted overwhelmingly to
back him over Yeltsin's objection. Yeltsin is powerless to dismiss
Skuratov without the council's agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov asserted that dark forces in Yeltsin's government had
wielded an incriminating videotape to blackmail him into resigning
because his inquiries into official corruption threatened their
power.
</P>
<P>
   While not naming names, he cited current and former Cabinet
ministers and an industrial magnate who could only be Boris
Berezovsky, a supposed billionaire who is a sometime Yeltsin ally.
Yeltsin dismissed Berezovsky this month as secretary of the
Commonwealth of Independent States, the loose alliance of member
states of the former Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Skuratov has said he is pressing forward with inquiries into
Kremlin misdeeds, as well as into the secret taping of his affair.
But he has carefully refrained from direct attacks on Yeltsin. The
two men met on Thursday, but the substance of their talk has not
been made public.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcast of part of the videotape on the RTR network on
Wednesday night has raised doubts about Skuratov's fitness as
prosecutor, but even graver doubts about the government's motives
in releasing it.
</P>
<P>
   Many here have seen the move as a sign of desperation on the
part of Yeltsin or his allies. The Federation Council, a
comparatively cautious group of regional leaders, has been one of
the last bulwarks of support for Yeltsin's rule.
</P>
<P>
   Its refusal to accede to the resignation of Skuratov could be
read as a near-fatal blow to Yeltsin's presidential power and a
further lift for Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who has emerged
as the country's de facto ruler in recent months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the Byzantine depths of Russian politics, Yeltsin's actions
Friday evening can also been seen as a strike against Primakov's
rising power. For Bordyuzha was seen as a Primakov ally, and the
man who is to replace him _ Alexander Voloshin, a Bordyuzha deputy
_ has been closely tied to Berezovsky in business deals. Berezovsky
and Primakov are political enemies as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems Berezovsky's coming back,'' said Anders Ausland, an
expert on Russia at the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace
in Washington. ``Voloshin is one of the people Berezovsky has been
pushing for prime minister instead of Primakov. And everybody's
ganging up on Primakov now, because he's looking too strong.''
</P>
<P>
   The only clear loser in this dark-of-night battle appears to be
Bordyuzha, a former military official who may or may not have been
responsible for releasing the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   As the crisis grew earlier this winter, Bordyuzha checked into a
Moscow hospital complaining of heart problems, a practice so common
among members of the Russian upper class as to be almost routine.
He left only this week, just before Yeltsin dismissed him.
</P>
<P>
   The English-language newspaper Moscow Times suggested Friday
that Yeltsin had ordered Bordyuzha to leave his sickbed. Under
Russian law, it is illegal to dismiss anyone under hospitalization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
