<HEADLINE>
NATO PLANS THREE-PHASE ATTACK ON YUGOSLAV MILITARY TARGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS lede to change `escalate' to `widen to'; adds 12 grafs to
original text, with comments from Congress, background on attack
plans and details of U.S. weapons to be deployed in case of
airstrikes.) 
(ATTN: Mich., Fla.)  (See also KOSOVO-TALKS, KOSOVO-REFUGEES, KOSOVO-CLINTON) 
(js) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO's plans for attacking Yugoslavia include
missile and air strikes that would begin with attacks against air
defenses and would widen to more sustained strikes on tanks and
other heavy weapons, NATO and Clinton administration officials said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The initial strike, involving mostly cruise missiles, would be
``short and intense,'' in the words of one official.
</P>
<P>
   It would aim to knock out Yugoslavia's network of land-based
missiles and anti-aircraft weapons, which would clear the way for
strikes by U.S. and NATO fighters and bombers. But the initial
attacks are designed to persuade the Yugoslav leader, President
Slobodan Milosevic, to end his crackdown in Kosovo province before
additional strikes begin.
</P>
<P>
   If Milosevic continues to resist, the officials said the second
and third phases are designed to destroy much of the heavy weaponry
_ tanks, armored personnel carriers and artillery batteries _ that
Yugoslav army and police forces have used to destroy villages and
drive civilians from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The strikes would be intended to ``level the playing field''
between the Yugoslav forces and the ethnic Albanian rebels in
Kosovo. ``It would be very difficult for him to continue to do what
he's doing once you've leveled the playing field,'' one NATO
official said of Milosevic. ``If you don't have artillery, it's
really hard to bomb villages.''
</P>
<P>
   Any NATO attack appeared to be at least days away. It was not
clear Friday what would prompt the NATO attacks. At his news
conference Friday, President Clinton said, ``I think that whatever
threshold they need to cross has been crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   But the officials said they expected at least one last effort at
diplomacy. While many officials described NATO's plans as if
strikes were inevitable, others said there was still a chance that
Milosevic might back down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that the history of Milosevic's behavior is
to blink when faced with a real threat,'' one senior Pentagon
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Washington declined to discuss the military
planning in detail, citing the need for operational secrecy. But
their willingness to discuss NATO's plans broadly appeared to be an
effort to demonstrate the administration's resolve in the face of
Milosevic's continued resistance to a peace settlement.
</P>
<P>
   There are still significant diplomatic hurdles to overcome. The
North Atlantic Council, NATO's political authority, has so far only
given Secretary- General Javier Solana the authorization to launch
the first phase of strikes. It must authorize an expanded campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The council's ambassadors met in Brussels, Belgium, Friday, but
stopped short of that, despite pressure from the United States to
clear the way for a speedier escalation of the air and missile
strikes. ``We have to be able to move quickly,'' a senior
administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen. Henry
Shelton, spelled out the military plans in briefings with members
of Congress, on Capitol Hill on Thursday and at the White House
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said Clinton made a strong case for
NATO action during Friday's briefing. ``He laid out the problems
with doing nothing, as well as the risks of doing something,''
Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   There is concern within the Pentagon and among Republicans in
Congress that NATO's plans do not have clear objectives.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you bomb, then what?'' said Rep. Tillie Fowler, R-Fla., who
also attended Friday's briefing. ``They don't know. They are
assuming he will cave in. But they do say they don't know for sure
that he will.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   NATO's plans have evolved since October, when the alliance
threatened the use of force until Milosevic agreed to an interim
cease-fire in Kosovo. The original plan called for a more gradual
escalation of strikes, but with Yugoslav forces pouring into Kosovo
recently, U.S. and NATO commanders pushed for a more aggressive war
plan, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO estimates there are as many as 20,000 Yugoslav army troops
in Kosovo, with thousands more poised just outside the border. The
Yugoslav forces are believed to have 200 to 300 tanks, as well as
armored combat vehicles and artillery pieces.
</P>
<P>
   While an initial strike against air defenses would be relatively
short, a Pentagon official said it could take ``many, many days''
to destroy the heavy Yugoslav forces. Another senior administration
official said that even the later attacks would be limited to
military targets and would not include broader attacks on
Yugoslavia's civilian infrastructure like bridges or communications
lines.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has pledged to contribute 260 of about 430
aircraft to a NATO campaign against Yugoslavia, including a dozen
F-117 ``stealth'' fighters designed to evade radar, seven B-52
bombers equipped with air-launched cruise missiles and even two B-2
``stealth'' bombers, which have never before been used in combat.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Secretary of Defense William Cohen ordered the return
of seven aircraft that had been dispatched to the region last month
and then withdrawn, including three EA-6B radar-jamming jets that
would be used to overcome Yugoslav defenses.
</P>
<P>
   The aircraft carrier Enterprise, with roughly 50 combat
aircraft, left the Mediterranean for the Persian Gulf earlier this
month, cutting short the American contribution of aircraft. But the
Navy still has four warships and two attack submarines in or near
the Adriatic Sea that, the officials said, would fire the bulk of
the cruise missiles in the first wave of strikes. Britain also has
a submarine in the region, newly equipped with U.S. cruise
missiles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
