<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   India: Halting Caste Violence
</P>
<P>
   The Bihar state government said it would convene an all-party
meeting to try to stop caste feuds after an attack on Wednesday in
the Jehanabad District that police officials said left at least 33
upper-caste villagers dead. Police said the attack, by a radical
Maoist group, was in revenge for the killing of untouchables last
month. Some villagers say at least 70 were slain.
</P>
<P>
   India, Pakistan: Pledge to Improve Relations
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Ministers Jaswant Singh of India and Sartaj Aziz of
Pakistan agreed to speed up talks to reduce the risk of nuclear
conflict and to resolve the dispute over Kashmir. A new round of
talks is to begin in May and continue for six weeks, they said in a
joint statement issued in Sri Lanka, where they were taking part in
a South Asian regional meeting.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   France: Corruption Case Reopens
</P>
<P>
   Judges reopened an investigation of the former Foreign Minister
Roland Dumas and his ex-mistress, Christine Deviers-Joncours, after
she charged that he knew that the oil group ELF-Aquitaine had
intended to give him an apartment in Paris. Dumas denied her
accusations, including the charge that as foreign minister he got
the company, then state-owned, to hire her and pay her $10 million
between 1989 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Attack on Poverty
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair said the tax and benefit changes in
his welfare-to-work reform program would raise 700,000 children out
of ``frightening deprivation'' and put Britain on the course to
eliminating child poverty in 20 years. In a lecture to social
policy experts on his government's principal domestic goal, Blair
said that ``poverty should not be a birthright.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Labor MP Is Ousted
</P>
<P>
   A Labor member of Parliament lost her seat when she was
convicted of fraud for having understated her campaign expenditures
in the 1997 election. The MP, Fiona Jones, 42, was given a sentence
of 100 hours of community service by Nottingham Crown Court.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Argentina: Menem Candidacy Is Opposed
</P>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES _ The city legislature voted to set a nonbinding
plebiscite for March 28 on whether President Carlos Saul Menem may
run for a third consecutive term. Menem's supporters have
criticized the plebiscite, in part because the wording that will
appear on the ballot states that any run by the president is
against the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Bolivia: Drug Tests for Officials
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Banzer announced that all government officials
would be obliged to take a drug test and that any officials who
test positive would be replaced. Banzer said the measure is ``an
act of good faith to combat drugs at all levels.'' Opposition
leaders countered that the move would be expensive and would
accomplish little.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Opposition Feuding
</P>
<P>
   Feuding in one of Mexico's main opposition parties, the Party of
the Democratic Revolution, is becoming evident in the party's
failure, six days after the vote, to declare an official winner in
the contest for party president. Party officials say the count
could drag out until April 10. Sen. Amalia Garcia, who was ahead by
fewer than two points, has declared herself the winner but received
no endorsement from top party officials.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: State Oil Company Losses
</P>
<P>
   Pemex reported 1998 losses of nearly $1.1 billion due to falling
oil prices and high taxation. The government's dependence on oil
earnings for about one-third of its revenue forced three budget
cuts last year. The head of the oil company, Adrian Lajous, said
that Pemex faced weakening competitiveness without reinvestment in
oil production.
</P>
</TEXT>
