<SLUG> BC-BKW-BECKY-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE-WOMAN SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It all started on a South Dakota driveway that
really wasn't a driveway at all. Turns out it was just a slab of
concrete.
</P>
<P>
   This was Becky Hammon's basketball court. She shared it with her
older brother Martin and the two would play for hours. No other
kids played because there weren't any around. Rapid City was 10
miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Who would have thought the little girl who spent those days on
that anonymous piece of concrete would go on to capture the
attention of a city, then a state?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel famous now, a little bit,'' said Hammon, an
All-American senior guard at Colorado State. ``I'm getting a little
taste of it. I can't go through a day without five or six people
stopping me somewhere and saying, `Good job.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Hammon, whose second-seeded Rams (33-2) play UCLA tonight at the
Sports Arena in the Round of 16 in the women's NCAA Tournament,
arrives in Los Angeles as the toast of Colorado. She was named the
state's Sportswoman of the Year on March 7 and the Denver Post
declared her ``Everybody's All-American'' in a feature story the
next day.
</P>
<P>
   Hammon leads Colorado State in most categories, including
scoring average (22.9), assists (4.8) and steals (2.8). With 2,719
career points, she is the Western Athletic Conference's all-time
leading scorer, male or female.
</P>
<P>
   ``Becky runs the show for (the Rams),'' UCLA head coach Kathy
Olivier said.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, Hammon IS the show.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State had never been in the women's Top 25 before
Hammon. The Rams rose to No. 4 this season.
</P>
<P>
   The average attendance for Colorado State's home games four
years ago was 741. Now, Moby Arena draws a little more than 4,200
for each game. A good percentage of the crowd is usually girls,
whose ages range from 7 to 13 and who universally idolize Hammon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fan base is really family-oriented,'' she said. ``But
we're pulling all sorts of crowds now.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammon's height _ 5-foot-6 _ has something to do with her
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's short . . . she doesn't look like a basketball player,''
said teammate Katie Cronin, a senior forward.
</P>
<P>
   Hammon is undersized, but she is the focus of every defense.
UCLA is no different.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's their spark,'' UCLA guard Erica Gomez said. ``In order
to win, you have to play her very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Hammon was a little off her game in the Rams' first-round win
over Cal State Northridge; she was just 4 of 13 from the field but
made 16 free throws to score 27 points.
</P>
<P>
   But she came out against Southwest Missouri State in the second
round and put on a show. Hammon scored 30 points, had eight assists
and put on a dribbling display that would have made Curly Neal
proud.
</P>
<P>
   Before the tournament, Colorado State coach Tom Collen said
Hammon must be seen in person. Her performance just doesn't have
the same impact on videotape. Cronin, Hammon's roommate for two
years, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have tried and tried to stop her and obviously they
can't,'' Cronin said. ``That's why a lot of people root for her.
You really can't stop her. She's just amazing at what she does.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a ride Hammon has enjoyed for four years. She cherishes
every accolade, every standing ovation, every kid seeking an
autograph. After all, she's come a long way from Rapid City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just living a dream,'' Hammon said. ``If you believe in
yourself, have faith in God and follow your dreams and follow your
heart, dreams can come true. I'm living mine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an awesome feeling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
