<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7458 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      03-19 1318
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Street Smarts Extra (column)
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; The Precocious Prognosticator &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
By Mark Veverka
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(c) 1999, The San Francisco Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Carson Levit was a Dow watcher before watching the Dow was cool.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years ago, before his crackling soprano changed to its
current baritone, the precocious 13-year-old was going long on
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a popular investment strategy. Inflation was out of
control. Jimmy Carter was president. The Rust Belt was foundering.
And the Dow Jones industrial average was sputtering at 800.
</P>
<P>
   The market has come a long way since then. After hitting the
10,000 mark during Tuesday's trading, the Dow has nervously flirted
with the arbitrary benchmark. Yesterday, it soared as high as
10,085 before closing at 9,903.55, down 94.07 for the day.
</P>
<P>
   Levit knows something about soaring Dows and milestones. Unfazed
by the prevailing pessimism of the late 1970s, he believed that the
stock market was poised for a bullish romp. And he backed his
conviction by wagering precious proceeds from his paper route to
buy and sell stocks in between math and English classes at Corte
Madera's Marin Country Day School.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in the eighth grade, I would try to use the
telephones in the principal's office to call my broker and make
trades,'' Levit recalls. ``(And) teachers would then ask me for
stock tips.''
</P>
<P>
   Word of the adolescent stock picker quickly spread from the
schoolyard to the pages of The Chronicle and beyond. From the
beginning, Levit had a knack for picking stocks that would go up.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, the sneaker-clad kid was a national talk-show
commodity, pontificating about the rising prospects of the Dow
Jones industrial average with the likes of Merv Griffin and David
Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be sitting on the couch on the set and my feet
wouldn't even hit the floor,'' says Levit, who now stands 6-foot-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was all pretty exciting for a 13-year-old kid,'' he
remembers.
</P>
<P>
   You bet it was. Sharing &UR;  &LR; television green rooms with such pinups
as Bo &LR;   &LR; Derek and Brooke Shields made the affable teen the envy of
the eighth grade.
</P>
<P>
   But where the boy-trader really made his mark was by predicting
that the Dow would scale once-unthinkable heights. After Chronicle
staff writer Steve Rubenstein spotlighted him in a profile article,
Levit was asked to pen an article for the paper.
</P>
<P>
   That's when he went out on a limb to forecast that the Dow could
more than triple.
</P>
<P>
   In a bylined column published on Nov. 1, 1982, Levit wrote:
``The stock market has finally broken out of its three-year holding
pattern and is heading on a course that wouldn't make the Dow 3,000
seem unreasonable.''
</P>
<P>
   Little did Levit know it would take 11 years for his vision to
come true. But ultimately, the Dow cracked 3,000. The kid was
right.
</P>
<P>
   Today, to the surprise of hardly anyone, Levit, now 33, oversees
investment portfolios worth billions. Since 1993, he has worked at
San Francisco's Dresdner RCM Global Investors LLC _ first as an
analyst and now as a portfolio manager.
</P>
<P>
   His primary responsibility is to oversee about $5 billion of the
$16 billion that RCM has invested in large capitalization stocks.
Much of the money that he manages belongs to pension plans and
endowments of big labor and corporate America. His clients include
Boeing, the Getty Foundation and the University of California at
San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Levit co-manages one of RCM's fledgling mutual
funds, a $12 million large-cap growth fund that was launched and
seeded by RCM just two years ago. The young fund racked up a 44
percent return in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   John Leland, Levit's co-manager of the fund, a 27-year veteran
of RCM and a director of the firm, says Levit still seems to
possess some of that investing intuition that he demonstrated as a
youngster.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much more intuitive than most people in _ or out _ of the
stock market,'' Leland says. ``And most of the great investors are
intuitive.''
</P>
<P>
   It's too early to tell whether Levit is a great investor because
he hasn't been tested in bad markets, Leland says, ``but I would
bet on him. In fact, I have bet on him,'' he adds, referring to the
billions the conservative firm has placed under Levit's control.
</P>
<P>
   One of the other things that impressed Leland and his RCM senior
brethren about Levit was that he used stock proceeds that he began
to mount as a teen to pay his way through Stanford University and
graduate school at the Wharton School of Business.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his experience was hands-on. During high school, he
fudged about his age to land a job at the Pacific Stock Exchange,
where he worked before going to school.
</P>
<P>
   What possessed such a young kid to get engrossed in the stock
market in the first place?
</P>
<P>
   During an unseasonably cool family vacation at Florida's Disney
World, the youngster caught pneumonia and was sentenced to recover
in his hotel room. On top of that, an ear infection prevented him
from flying back to California for days. When he went to the gift
shop to buy a book, there were only two choices: a tome on child
psychology and a primer on how to invest in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   You can guess which one he chose.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, in what now seems eerily prescient, the stock
market book he ultimately chose was authored by none other than
Claude Rosenberg, a founder of RCM _ the firm where he now works.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long after reading the book that Levit was looking for
a broker. In 1976, he took a $1,000 nest egg from his paper route
and plunked it down on the National Exhibition Corp. of Canada, a
company that nearly bought the San Francisco Giants. The investment
proved to be a home run.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by his early success, Levit then diversified his
holdings. ``It was very simplistic. I'd be throwing a football
around and realized that it was made by AMF. So I would invest in
AMF,'' Levit recalls.
</P>
<P>
   As fate would have it, the stock was a winner. As were many of
his other early picks: Teledyne, Perrier and Texas Instruments.
Each of those companies was selling products that were riding huge
waves of popularity at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Levit's legend began to grow. He no longer relied solely on
instinct and began to bolster his stock picking with economic
research.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he was 15, Levit was espousing free-market theories
in articles written for The Chronicle and forecasting that the Dow
Jones industrial average would smash 3,000. Which, at the time, was
like saying gold would hit $2,000 an ounce today, he says. (Gold
currently is worth less than $300 an ounce.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What gave me optimism was that Silicon Valley was just getting
going, and I just felt that our economy was going to start growing
fueled by the growth of technology,'' Levit says.
</P>
<P>
   Also, as a diligent student of politics and economics, he
thought tax rates were destined to fall and that investments
pouring into 401(k) plans and defined contribution plans would
prime the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a lot of research and went to the library. It helped me
see through the bad economic times,'' Levit says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a real believer in Reaganomics,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Levit is two decades wiser, and he has been riding the bull
market since his first stock purchase in the eighth grade. The Dow
has climbed nearly 7,000 points further than his infamous
prediction. Does the Industrial index's flirtation with 10,000
really mean anything to him?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dow has become a dinosaur,'' Levit says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think the 10,000 mark will become a barrier or
impediment to additional growth in the market. And I don't think
we'll sit at this level for very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday in the
Business section. Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415)
777-8444 or by e-mail at mveverka(AT-SIGN)sfgate.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
