<HEADER>
A7461 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NETSCAPE-SFCHRON &LR;      03-19 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETSCAPE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
Netscape Braces for Layoffs
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
( &LR; c &LR; ) 1999, The San Francisco &LR;   &LR; Chronicle &QL; 
America Online _ which completed its $10 billion buyout of Netscape
Communications this week _ is expected to lay off up to a third of
the Internet pioneer's 2,500 employees next week, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The online giant reportedly will cut back Netscape divisions
that overlap with AOL's, such as sales and marketing. Netscape also
could endure losses in departments that develop software also made
by Sun Microsystems, another partner in the merger. Sun will
co-develop future versions of Netscape's browser.
</P>
<P>
   Layoffs at the Mountain View software company will number in the
hundreds, sources said. On Thursday night, TheStreet.com, an online
financial news service, reported a workforce reduction of 700,
citing unnamed sources close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   AOL spokesman Jim Whitney declined to comment, but said the
Dulles, Va., online service will ``make an announcement next week
on how the two companies will operate together.''
</P>
<P>
   A Netscape spokeswoman declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   But one former Netscape employee, speaking anonymously, said it
was ``no surprise'' that AOL would wield the ax. ``That was a given
once they announced their intention to buy us,'' he said. ``Too
much overlap between the companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The impending cutbacks mark an unceremonious end to Netscape's
fairy-tale rise from scrappy startup to Internet icon _ as well as
an affirmation of AOL's growing clout.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape, founded in 1994 by Silicon Valley entrepreneur Jim
Clark and Web golden boy Marc Andreessen, created the first Web
browser for navigating the Internet. But for the past two years,
the company steadily lost market share and was badly battered by
software giant Microsoft, which distributed its browser for free.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Netscape needed a major partner to pull out of its
tailspin, and it struck a deal with AOL last fall.
</P>
<P>
   With its acquisition of Netscape, AOL will reach a staggering 70
percent of all Net users. The company already is the largest
provider of Internet access, with 16 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   AOL Interactive Services President Barry Schuler has been
melding the operations of AOL and Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Netscape CEO Jim Barksdale has joined AOL's board of directors
but will not have any day-to-day responsibilities. Andreessen has
been named AOL's chief technology officer.
</P>
<P>
   Although both companies trace their origins to the Internet,
their cultures are very different.
</P>
<P>
   While AOL developed a reputation for savvy marketing and covered
its corporate walls with posters touting ``Valued Work Behaviors,''
Netscape was a freewheeling group of renegade programmers who named
their conference rooms after cartoon characters and stressed
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   About the only thing AOL and Netscape duplicated were similar
jobs in several departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I surprised by the layoffs? No. There is a lot of overlap
in marketing and sales positions between the two companies,'' said
analyst Jim Balderston of Zona Research in Redwood City. ``The
buyer makes the call _ and in this case, AOL decided to make the
cuts.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
