<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sosa ready for Round 2
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MESA, Ariz. _ The squeals from memorabilia hounds patrolling the
other side of the wall confirmed that a batting-practice ball hit
by Sammy Sosa had reached the parking lot. It was a simple
acknowledgement that Sosa, whose 66 home runs in 1998 made him the
most revered runner-up in the history of the game, has his spring
swing in midseason form.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It's) like I picked up right where I left off last year,''
said Sosa, right fielder for the Chicago Cubs and the reigning
National League Most Valuable Player. ``No one can say what will
happen this time around, but if I can (maintain) this groove into
the season, things will be pretty interesting again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has maintained his optimism for 1999 despite the
season-ending elbow injury to pitcher Kerry Wood and the bulging
disk that sidelined closer Rod Beck for two weeks. He insists the
Cubs will contend for a postseason berth again this year.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa also predicted another six-month home run derby with St.
Louis first baseman Mark McGwire, his newest best friend, whose 70
home runs won the record chase. Unlike McGwire, with his legendary
uppercut, Sosa is not a natural slugger. But he has, even at this
advanced stage of his career, finally mastered the art of
selectivity and made it his advantage.
</P>
<P>
   His strikeouts are down, his average is up, and his profile is
still rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of players who waste much of the natural
ability they possess,'' Cubs manager Jim Riggleman said. ``Sammy
finally harnessed his. Sometimes it takes a while to realize how
good you really are, you know? Now Sammy knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has been plenty good this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Despite playing only two-thirds of the Cubs' games, he has eight
home runs, including two each in his last two appearances.
Diamondbacks pitcher Todd Stottlemyre came so undone on Wednesday
after giving up his second long homer to Sosa that he cursed the
Chicago slugger between innings and was ejected.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of frustration might be epidemic for National League
pitchers in '99. Once a brooding player, who felt underappreciated
in the field and undervalued in the paycheck, Sosa has changed his
outlook, and opponents have been forced to look out ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I respected myself more than ever,'' he said.
``That has to come first. Maybe I carried a chip (on my shoulder)
too long. But when it came off, I was a better player and a better
person, and other people respected me then, too.''
</P>
<P>
   While last season's home-run chase mesmerized the nation, it
took a mental toll, Sosa said, but not enough to have kept him from
tours of Japan and Central America and a ton of banquets. The
rubber-chicken circuit has made him a little cheekier, but his body
is in good shape, and his mind is sharp.
</P>
<P>
   Riggleman knows last season was special and that Sosa isn't
likely to duplicate it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not looking for any particular numbers,'' Riggleman
said. ``It's such a game of statistics that I know the fans will
be, and the rotisserie leagues will be, so it will be an issue
externally. Internally, I don't think it will be. If you told me
Sammy will have an average Sammy Sosa year, I'd take it right now.
Whatever those numbers are, I'd take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Sosa joined the Cubs in '93, he has averaged 39 homers and
110 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully he'll have an injury-free year again,'' Riggleman
said, ``and when you look up at the end of September it's going to
have been a real good year. His physical talent will take care of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa is excited by some lineup experiments that have sandwiched
him between Mark Grace and Henry Rodriguez _ Sosa has predicted the
latter will hit 40-45 homers this year.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he wasn't in the lineup when Chicago traveled to
face the Milwaukee Brewers, and the fans at Maryvale Baseball Park
in Phoenix jeered when they realized Sosa hadn't made the trip.
That's one reason Sosa can't wait for the regular season to begin.
</P>
<P>
   That's when everything is right in Sammy's world.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
