<SLUG> BC-BKC-MILLERTWINS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller twins getting a grip on emotions
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Kelly and Coco Miller bring an obvious zeal to
basketball, and the flip side of their openly displayed emotions
attracts virtually the same jaw-dropping notice.
</P>
<P>
   The talented All-SEC sophomore twins lead Georgia in scoring and
already are playing their way into the school'srecord books. But
when they push beyond the competitive edge coach Andy Landers loves
so much, it threatens to disrupt his carefully woven but fragile
team unity.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia, which plays Clemson this afternoon in the Sweet 16 in
Cincinnati, clearly wouldn't be where it is without the Millers,
both of whom reached the 1,000-point plateau in exactly 57 games.
Coco leads the team with 19.1 points a game; Kelly is second at
18.1. Although they have matured considerably since their freshman
year, they still are prone to cry or grimace during games and
practices and at times argue heatedly with the equally
demonstrative Landers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing with Kelly and Coco is an experience,'' sophomore
guard Kiesha Brown said. ``They're almost to the point of wanting
to be perfectionists, of wanting everything to be right. It leads
to frustration, and everybody knows what that's like.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Landers dismissed Coco from a practice session after
she talked back to him when he made her run laps. She had been
upset after being taken out of a scrimmage. And during a workout
earlier this week, Kelly attracted his wrath after making a mistake
on a fast-break drill and conveying her dismay with her sister.
After Landers yelled at her, he took Kelly aside and spoke to her
quietly during a water break.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life with the 5-10 guards from Rochester, Minn., who
carried a heavy burden last year when Georgia had only eight
scholarship players. The Millers, who play with a ferocious,
full-throttle style, admit that some of their problems stem from
being extremely hard on themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate missing shots; I hate not doing things well,'' said
Coco, who after a practice incident was benched for the first half
of the Alabama game in January. ``I have to learn how to calm down
and keep things under control. I think I've done better with that
this year, but it has been tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said, ``I think I've done a better job of not letting
those things get to me. And I'm trying not to take personally what
the coaches are saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Landers sees some progress. ``They recognize that they're
growing,'' he said. ``Enthusiasm is a great thing. But emotion
isn't always positive. You want the enthusiasm your players to feed
off of to be positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Their teammates say they understand the special nature of the
twins, who last year didn't interact much with other players,
either on or off the court. They still keep to themselves for the
most part, but they're starting to come out of their shell a little
bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've made a tremendous improvement since last year,''
senior guard Pam Irwin-Osbolt said. ``Everybody has bad days. If
you're really hard on yourself, and the coach is on you, that makes
it even more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   With teammates picking them up and coaches working behind the
scenes to help them channel their drive the right way, the Millers
say they believe they're well on their way to putting their growing
pains behind them.
</P>
<P>
   Coco said, ``They know that I know what needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
