<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Penn, Barkley are on guards
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE _ Great guards almighty! That's the surest path to the
salvation of the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   Come March, no one goes to hoop heaven without great guard play.
No one knows this better than Mike Jarvis, who, like his
counterpart Jim O'Brien, has reason for guarded optimism of the
most confident kind.
</P>
<P>
   Those reasons? Point guards Erick Barkley of St. John's and Ohio
State's Scoonie Penn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither team would be here without them,'' said Jarvis, who'll
watch his freshman Barkley lead the Johnnies against Ohio State
tonight in the NCAA South Regional final. ``In Scoonie and Erick,
you have two of the best point guards in the country. The main
thing that makes them great is the fact that team and winning comes
first, and the belief they have that they can win every game they
play.''
</P>
<P>
   That belief was doubly reinforced Thursday. In dismantling
Maryland 76-62, St. John's again relied on its newfound 2-3 zone,
its unselfish ball movement and Barkley. He led the Red Storm with
24 points and nine assists. While committing an uncharacteristic
six turnovers (the freshman has just 76 in 1,191 minutes and 36
games all season), Barkley played like anything but a freshman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's doing a great job as a freshman, running that
team,'' said Penn.
</P>
<P>
   As a junior transfer who sat out last season after following
O'Brien from Boston College, Penn is doing a great job of
confirming his preseason prediction that Ohio State would return to
the NCAA's after last year's 8-22 bummer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scoonie Penn's a great floor leader,'' said St. John's forward
Lavor Postell. ``He keeps everybody under control.''
</P>
<P>
   And takes control when necessary. Like Thursday, when Penn
picked up his fourth personal with 13:23 left and sat down for more
than three minutes. When he returned, Auburn led 52-46 with 10:14
still to play. But Penn promptly hit a 3-pointer and a baseline
floater. He scored 13 of his 19 second-half points in the last 10
minutes to take Ohio State to a 72-64 triumph.
</P>
<P>
   In the Buckeyes' first two tournament wins, Penn shot just
7-for-27 from the floor. He was still hampered by a bruised
buttocks suffered in the last regular-season game. But after
starting out 1-for-6 against Auburn, Penn finished 9-for-14 and got
untracked when he knocked down a 3-pointer just before halftime.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great dribbler, he shoots well and he's a floor
leader,'' Barkley said of Penn, the Big Ten Player of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
