 &HT;    Cup regulars dominate Busch
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Winston Cup drivers continued to dominate the
Busch Series on Friday, taking four of the top five qualifying
spots for today's Diamond Hill Plywood 200 at Darlington Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Martin, who has won five of the last 11 Busch races here,
won the pole, covering the 1.366-mile oval in 29.523 seconds, an
average speed of 166.568 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Roush Racing teammate Jeff Burton briefly held the outside
pole, but he was relegated to the 42nd spot after wrecking his car
in the afternoon practice session.
</P>
<P>
   Cup regulars Dick Trickle and Geoffrey Bodine will start third
and fourth, respectively, with Kevin Lepage sixth.
</P>
<P>
   All 11 Cup drivers who attempted to qualify made the field.
Owner Joe Gibbs withdrew his entry after driver Bobby Labonte was
injured in practice. Nine Busch regulars, including Kerry
Earnhardt, failed to make the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an awful lot of cars at the Busch and Winston Cup
races,'' Martin said. ``It's a tragedy whenever a regular has to go
home. My heart ached for some Busch guys, as well as guys like
Robert Pressley or Kyle Petty,'' who didn't qualify for a Cup event
at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Martin posted his qualifying speed in the first of two laps,
then his Ford hit the outside wall coming out of turn 4 in the
second. ``I knew I couldn't run faster, but I tried to anyway,'' he
said. ``So I wrecked the car. I just refuse to go a long period of
time without doing something stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   PIT STOPS
</P>
<P>
   Five Craftsman truck drivers will be eligible to win a $100,000
bonus in the NAPACARD 200 at Evergreen Speedway in Monroe, Wash.,
on April 3, the 100th race in the five-year history of the series.
The eligible drivers are Ron Hornaday, Jack Sprague, Rick Carelli,
Butch Miller and Joe Ruttman, who have competed in every date.
</P>
<P>
   Cup regular Joe Nemechek was 18th in Busch qualifying in the No.
83 Chevy, which usually is driven by Wayne Grubb, who suffered a
broken shoulder blade at Atlanta last week. Grubb's brother, Kevin,
will replace Nemechek in today's race and will start last. ...
Jimmy Spencer was 24th in Cup qualifying, which was quite an
accomplishment after his No. 23 Ford caught on fire during the
morning practice session. Spencer was forced to use a backup car.
... Rick Bickle also went to a second car after wrecking in
practice, but he was 45th in qualifying and will try again in
today's second round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
