<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon tames track to win pole
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Jeff Gordon escaped the bite of Darlington
Raceway on Friday, sweeping the field in qualifying for Sunday's
TranSouth 400.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, who has won five of the last seven Winston Cup races
here, took the pole with an average speed of 173.167 mph. It was
only Gordon's second pole at Darlington, even though he's tied for
third with four other drivers for overall victories at the track.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bobby Labonte, who broke his right shoulder blade during
a morning practice session, Gordon was able to stay away from the
high-banked walls of the 1.366-mile oval, which is loathed by many
drivers for its narrow straightaways and abrasive asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   ``People try to scare you when you come here the first couple of
times,'' Gordon said. ``They told me that (this) place is fast,
it's high-banked and it's scary. They told me I was going to get a
`Darlington stripe.' I think I've respected it from the start.''
</P>
<P>
   Multicar-owner Jack Roush, who has four cars in the first nine
spots, might have been the only one at the track happier than
Gordon. Roush drivers Johnny Benson and Mark Martin will start
second and third. They will be followed by points leader Mike
Skinner and John Andretti.
</P>
<P>
   Roush's other drivers, Kevin Lepage, Jeff Burton and Chad
Little, will start seventh, ninth and 22nd.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have an owner have five teams is an accomplishment in its
own,'' Benson said. ``But to have them all run fast is hard,
there's no doubt.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson, winless in 98 career starts, was the biggest surprise.
He hadn't started higher than 26th in four races this year, and his
best finish was 16th at North Carolina Speedway on Feb. 21. At last
week's Cracker Barrel Old Country Stores 500 at Atlanta, there was
speculation Benson soon would be without a ride.
</P>
<P>
   He silenced his critics for now, claiming the outside pole with
an average speed of 172.541 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``That all started because of somebody else saying something,''
Benson said. ``We didn't really think it was a huge issue at the
time until they kept writing about it. We all know what we're doing
and that we're sitting in good shape. We just don't care about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rick Mast and Bill Elliott earned their highest starting
positions of the season and will start sixth and eighth,
respectively. Rookie Tony Stewart earned his third top-10 position
at No. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
