<SLUG> BC-NCAASWIM20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feeling `hunted,' Kowal defends title
 &HT;    By Plott Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia took another giant step toward a national
championship, and All-American Kristy Kowal likes the feeling.
</P>
<P>
   The Lady Bulldogs held off a strong challenge from Stanford to
retain first place Friday at the NCAA women's swimming and diving
championships. Stanford fought past SMU for second place entering
today's finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a big day for us. We swam well in the prelims and
everyone swarm hard tonight,'' said Kowal.
</P>
<P>
   Kowal emerged from her 100-yard breaststroke final with the
second-best NCAA time ever. She had tears, but not because she
didn't beat the record _ she actually holds the record that was set
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just incredibly happy. Somebody said it was tears of
sadness, but it wasn't,'' Kowal said. ``I was very nervous. Last
year, nobody knew who I was and there was no pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``But when I came out tonight, I knew I was the hunted and I
just wanted to defend my title.''
</P>
<P>
   Defend it she did, and she'll try to defend her title in the
200-yard breaststroke tonight. She likes her chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think being in our pool helps us,'' Kowal said. ``I know
every inch of this pool and I am used to the (starting) blocks. So
it's an advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Kowal's voice was scratchy and hoarse, she said, from yelling
encouragement to her teammates. Asked if swimmers could really hear
the crowd, she said, ``definitely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially in the breaststroke,'' she laughed. She imitated
herself bobbing up and down under the water.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real loud, and then it gets quiet, and then it gets
loud.''
</P>
<P>
   SMU's Martina Moravcova, who picked up three first places
Thursday night, came back Friday night with another All-America
performance.
</P>
<P>
   The senior Lady Mustang from Slovakia blistered the field with a
1:43.84 in the 200-yard freestyle for her fourth consecutive title
in that event.
</P>
<P>
   She also swam a leg on the Lady Mustangs' fourth-place finish in
the 200-yard medley relay. She has had a huge hand in SMU's 225.5
points.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
