<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7470 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MIDWEST-HUMMER20-     03-19 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MIDWEST-HUMMER20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Waiting for normalcy to return
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Wonder why your NCAA basketball bracket is a cruel
joke? Just come here to the land of the double-digit seed, where
there exist more feel-good stories than in a convention hall full
of vitamin salesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where Oklahoma and Miami University ended up so
unexpectedly, practically uninvited guests to Friday's Midwest
Regional semifinals. Oklahoma is but the third seed this high
(13th) to get this far, attempting to become the only one to go
farther. And 10th-seeded Miami is simply the wrong one, there being
no acceptable beach and little local knowledge about making a
decent rum drink.
</P>
<P>
   There is something to be said for overachieving _ in moderation.
We can handle just about one Gonzaga per Sweet 16. But what to do
when you can't throw a rock without getting sued by at least two
teams that shouldn't be there?
</P>
<P>
   Friday was to be comeuppance time in the Midwest, but there were
no guarantees. You can state nothing with certainty, other than the
fact that a couple of pesky programs would happily get in the way
of a much-anticipated Kentucky-Michigan State showdown.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, at this stage of the tournament, I'm just about
Cinderella-ed out. The term, already flogged into a coma, has lost
all meaning. When so many upsets happen so routinely, isn't it
about time to admit that there are a bunch of teams out there that
can win an important Division I college basketball game? With the
exception, of course, of any located in the state of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   When the surprise becomes the expected, then it is only a matter
of moments before up becomes down and John Tesh does rap.
</P>
<P>
   The spate of upsets in this tournament is the best argument yet
for moving the collegiate 3-point line back a foot or so, at least
to international distance. At 19 feet, 9 inches, the arc is just
too close. It is the equalizer, allowing more flukes, more
victories by ambush.
</P>
<P>
   Miami already has been around long enough to be a real danger.
The Y2K problem looms, but there is a more pressing concern _ that
of subjecting computer spell-checks to repeated doses of
``Szczerbiak.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm worried that if Miami's Wally Szczerbiak gets any more
exposure, both Tiger Beat and Playgirl are going to be asking for
courtside credentials in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, these teams make good stories. Miami coach Charlie
Coles went through 34 years of coaching and one heart attack _ in
last year's Mid-American Conference Tournament _ to win as many as
two NCAA games.
</P>
<P>
   And Oklahoma hadn't won a tournament game in the five years of
coach Kelvin Sampson until this go-round.
</P>
<P>
   And it is kinda cool to hear the player introduction go
something like, ``At 6-8, from Chihuahua, Mexico, Eduardo Najera!''
The Sooners star proves that basketball has no permanent address.
</P>
<P>
   These stories have had their proper airing. Seemed to be about
time for other more irresistible forces to take over. For example,
there is one theory I've always held to in judging a basketball
matchup _ always go with the team with the most tattoos. And the
Sooners' opponent Friday, No. 1 seed Michigan State, had a roster
that looked like a battleship crew on leave.
</P>
<P>
   You keep waiting for normalcy to get a foothold on this little
tournament. Surely it must make itself known soon, just too late to
do anyone's brackets any good.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
