</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WESTCAPSULE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How Connecticut stacks up against Gonzaga
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   When; where: 3:40 p.m. today; America West Arena in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   TV: CBS
</P>
<P>
   Records: Connecticut 31-2, Gonzaga 28-6.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches: Jim Calhoun is 301-120 in 13 seasons at Connecticut,
551-257 overall. Dan Monson is 52-16 in two seasons at Gonzaga.
</P>
<P>
   How they got here: The top-seeded Huskies routed Texas-San
Antonio in the first round 91-66. They defeated New Mexico 78-56 in
the second round and Iowa, 78-68, in the third round. Gonzaga, a
No. 10 seed, upset seventh-seed Minnesota 75-63 in the first round
and second-seed Stanford, 82-74, in the second. They defeated
Florida 73-72 in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   Starting lineups: Connecticut _ guards, Khalid El-Amin (5-11,
so., 13.5 ppg) and Ricky Moore (6-2, sr., 6.5 ppg); center, Jake
Voskuhl (6-11, jr., 5.8 ppg); forwards, Kevin Freeman (6-7, jr.,
12.8 ppg) and Richard Hamilton (6-6, jr., 21.2 ppg); Gonzaga _
guards, Quentin Hall (5-8, sr., 11.4 ppg) and Matt Santangelo (6-1,
jr., 12.7 ppg); center, Jeremy Eaton (6-11, sr., 12.1 ppg);
forwards, Richie Frahm (6-5, jr., 14.2 ppg) and Casey Calvary (6-8,
so., 9.4 ppg).
</P>
<P>
   Outlook: It has been an inspiring ride for upstart Gonzaga, but
this is where the string of upsets ends. Iowa hung in against
Connecticut by outmuscling the Huskies. While Gonzaga is scrappy,
the Bulldogs rely too much on their perimeter shooting. UConn
defends the 3-pointer well. More important, the Huskies love to
push the pace.
</P>
<P>
   Prediction: Connecticut, 84-67.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
