<HEADER>
A7475 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TECH-THEFTS-$ADV21-NY     03-19 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-THEFTS-$ADV21-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A GROWING MARKET IN HOT TECHNOLOGY  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 21) 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: This is an added story)  
 (af)  
 By REBECCA FAIRLEY RANEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Criminals following the Willie Sutton rule _ go where the money
is _ are not knocking over banks, as Sutton did. They are raiding
shipments of computers, microchips and cell phones.
</P>
<P>
   The direct losses that technology companies attribute to theft
are $250 million a year, according to a new study, and the industry
is spending a further $750 million a year on insurance and security
measures.
</P>
<P>
   The problems of truck hijackings, armed takeovers, burglaries
and trucks that mysteriously turn up empty at their destinations
have plagued Silicon Valley for years.
</P>
<P>
   Police in San Jose, Calif., estimate that in recent years,
robbers have hit an electronics company once every five days, said
John O'Loughlin, director of security at Sun Microsystems. Such
thefts often involve goods worth $100,000 or more, while the
typical bank robbery nets only about $2,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A number of crimes in the mid-1990s prompted two industry
groups, the American Electronics Association and the International
Electronics Security Group, to hire the Rand Corp. to perform the
study, said to be the first attempt to quantify the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-five companies were surveyed, representing 40 percent of
industry sales; they reported 1,700 incidents of theft in a
nine-month period in 1997 and 1998. Industrywide estimates were
extrapolated from the results.
</P>
<P>
   Losses to distributors, retailers and customers were not
measured, but the researchers guessed that they might run up to
four times what manufacturers lose, putting the total cost of
technology hardware theft as high as $5 billion a year in an
industry that shipped about $235 billion of hardware in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The Rand researchers found that insurance covered only about 25
percent of manufacturers' losses because of high deductibles and
widespread self-insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Thefts of computers and components from trucks were by far the
most common crimes, usually occurring in transit. Some involved
hijackings; in others, goods were replaced with boxes of rocks
without the driver knowing. Fewer than 1 in 10 thefts occurred on
manufacturers' premises.
</P>
<P>
   Companies that stepped up security spending during the study
period saw their losses decline, the researchers found. One useful
measure: removing the company logo from trucks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
