<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0384 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7477 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BASS-PRO-SHOPS-2TAKES     03-19 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BASS-PRO-SHOPS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STORE WITH THE SECRET TO LURING ANGLERS AND HUNTERS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mo., Maine, Calif., Texas, N.C., Fla., Ill., Va.,
Tenn. and Zimbabwe)   By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPRINGFIELD, Mo. _ On their way to a fishing tournament in
Oklahoma last June, the 12 members of Zimbabwe's national fishing
team stopped at this city of 150,000 on the edge of the Ozarks. The
reason? To visit Bass Pro Shops Outdoor World, a sportsman's
paradise whose inventory of fishing and hunting equipment is as
wide as all outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, more than 4 million people _ Americans and foreigners
alike _ passed through the store's turnstiles, just beyond its log
cabin-like entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Many are dedicated to hunting and fishing, as are a good number
of the store's 350 employees. But many probably would not know a
spinning reel from spinner bait. They are drawn by the chance to
see for themselves the blend of unrivaled inventory and
showmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Now the privately owned Bass Pro Shops Inc. is branching out,
betting that this store's success can be cloned.
</P>
<P>
   After 24 years with just one store, there are now Bass Pro Shops
in the suburbs of Atlanta and Chicago and in Fort Lauderdale and
the Florida Keys. Six more _ including one opening on March 25 in
Grapevine, Texas, near the Dallas-Fort Worth airport _ will open in
five states in the next 18 months. State development and tourism
agencies are begging for even more.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why. While the company has sold some of its
products at outdoors retailers around the country, Bass Pro's
300,000-square-foot flagship store _ the size of six football
fields _ has long been in a class by itself. It includes a
four-story waterfall, rifle and archery ranges, four aquariums, an
indoor driving range, a putting green and a 17,000-square-foot
Wildlife Museum with a world-class collection of stuffed animals.
</P>
<P>
   On the third floor, past the live snake exhibit, visitors can
have their hair cut at the four-chair barbershop and arrange to
have a fishing lure made out of the clippings. Or they can eat at
McDonald's or dine at Hemingway's Blue Water Cafe, which boasts a
30,000-gallon saltwater aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The store's incredible, it's so huge,'' said Jacque McClure of
Marina del Ray, Calif., who visited recently with her fiance. ``I
could easily have spent another day.'' As it was, she spent just
over $1,000 on fishing equipment and outdoor clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Larry and Karen Montoya drove two days from their home in
Lakeside, Ariz., spent $750 over four days at the store and then
drove back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen so much fishing equipment,'' said Montoya, who
owns Rock CD Music Warehouse in Lakeside. ``We want to go back this
summer,'' with their three children.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of never allowing a dull moment is designed to
create what John L. Morris, the company's 50-year-old founder,
refers to as ``excitement and entertainment.'' The store's design
developed from trips that he, his sister Susie Hunt, now executive
vice president, and other employees took to different stores years
ago to try to pinpoint their appeal. Their most memorable visit was
to L.L. Bean in Freeport, Maine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, heck, if they can draw all those people to the middle
of nowhere,'' Morris said, ``we can do that in Springfield.'' They
now attract even more. L.L. Bean said its Maine store draws just
over 3.5 million visitors a year.
</P>
<P>
   Bass Pro's 4 million annual visitors explain why officials from
many cities and states have beaten a path to Morris' door, seeking
a Bass Pro Shops _ usually to no avail. ``Each store is a
significant investment,'' Morris said. ``We can't afford to make
many mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   But when the site looks right, Morris is ready. He was impressed
from the start not only by the profit potential in Grapevine, just
off Highway 114 a short distance from Dallas-Fort Worth
International Airport, but by the welcoming attitude of Grapevine's
mayor and City Council. So welcoming, in fact, that the road to
Grapevine has been renamed Bass Pro Drive.
</P>
<P>
   When Concord, N.C., landed its Bass Pro Shops last summer, Gov.
Jim Hunt predicted that it would create 300 jobs, attract millions
of visitors and generate revenues of more than $300 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the store is what attracts fishing fans from as far
away as Zimbabwe: Row after row of rods, reels, guns, decoys,
tents, campers and outerwear, as well as plastic bait for as little
as 27 cents and motor homes for up to $45,000. One floor rivals a
boat show, with speed boats, house boats, pontoon boats, fiberglass
boats and aluminum boats. Those last two, made by the Tracker
Marine Co., also owned by Morris, are the world's biggest sellers
in their class.
</P>
<P>
   While none of the new stores are as big as the original here,
the others are still huge, complete with waterfalls and aquariums.
</P>
<P>
   In slowly expanding, Bass is moving beyond the model of L.L.
Bean, built around its huge mail-order operation and one big store
in Maine. It is trying to make a bigger splash than its rivals,
like Cabela's and Orvis, which have added smaller retail stores to
supplement catalog sales.
</P>
<P>
   Morris was born and raised in Springfield, still a region of
lakes and woods _ and, naturally, hunting and fishing. He opened
the original store in a small corner of his father's liquor store.
But the other sites were chosen with a discerning eye for location
and partners with deep pockets and reputations for accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   The following are among those partners:
</P>
<P>
   _ The Mills &UR;  &LR; Corp., the Arlington, Va., mall developer. Bass Pro
is allied with Mills at Gurnee Mills near Chicago, in Grapevine
Mills, at Opry Mills in Nashville, Tenn., scheduled to open next
year and Katy Mills near Houston scheduled to open later this year.
</P>
<P>
   _ John Q. Hammons, the Springfield-based hotel operator. His
329-room Embassy Suites hotel in Grapevine will carry Bass Pro's
Outdoor World name in its title, as will his 250-room Embassy
Suites at Concord Mills in North Carolina scheduled to open this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Gaylord Entertainment &UR;  &LR; Co. of Nashville. Gaylord, the
owner of Grand Ole Opry and the Opryland Hotel in Nashville, will
build a $300 million Opryland Hotel next to Grapevine Mills, and
Morris will build a Bass Pro Shops at Nashville's Opry Mills. In
1993, Bass Pro and Gaylord formed a partnership, one Morris said
``positions us well for long-term growth.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the flagship store, Tracker Marine, and the
mail-order operation, which distributes 34 million catalogs a year,
his empire includes Big Cedar Lodge, a wilderness resort an hour
from Springfield, and American Rod and Gun, Bass' wholesale
division, which sells to some 7,500 dealers in more than 50
countries.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Fishing and hunting, in short, are big business. According to
the Fish and Wildlife Service, anglers spent $703 million in
Missouri in 1996, hunters $683 million. The 35.2 million Americans
who fish (27 percent of them women) spent $38 billion on
fishing-related expenses in 1996; the 13 million hunters (only 9
percent women) spent $20.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Bass Pro Shops has a 24-hour toll-free number for customers to
buy hunting licenses and freshwater or saltwater fishing licenses.
</P>
<P>
   When its prize mascot, Ethel, the biggest largemouth bass in
captivity, died in Bass' 64,000-gallon aquarium in 1994, it held a
memorial service that attracted so many people that the crowd
spilled beyond the store's 300-seat auditorium onto the sales
floor. The service was broadcast on cable television and many
commercial stations carried accounts of Ethel's demise.
</P>
<P>
   ``To this day,'' said Martin MacDonald, Bass' director of
corporate relations, who presided over the service, ``visitors to
the store still call me Brother Martin.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris also donated a parcel of land next to his store for a $40
million American National Fish and Wildlife Living Museum and
Aquarium, scheduled to open in two years. The museum is projected
to attract almost 1.5 million visitors annually, 69 percent from
out of state.
</P>
<P>
   To forestall conflict-of-interest accusations, the project has
been incorporated as a nonprofit corporation. While Morris is on
its 15-member board, so are current and former officials of the
Audubon Society and other conservation groups.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Morris continues to look for opportunities. ``I'd be
happy to add two or three stores a year, if we can resist the
temptation to grow faster than our ability to maintain our
quality,'' he said. Acknowledging that further expansion could
require taking the company public, he described that possibility as
``very tempting and maybe necessary,'' adding that ``the downside
is having to be responsible to others.''
</P>
<P>
   Another downside for Bass Pro Shops could be if hunting really
is falling out of favor, as is often said. That may be more
illusion than reality, since the number of hunters stayed roughly
level from 1991 to 1996. But hunters went afield 21 million more
days last year, according to the Fish and Wildlife Service, and, in
real dollars, spent 43 percent more for trips and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Still, whatever the future of hunting, Morris said, ``fishing is
our heritage, and it's still the main thrust of our business.''
</P>
<P>
   Morris is not worried. ``I've been as lucky as you can get,'' he
said, ``being able to turn my hobby into a business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
