<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0395 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7495 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BUCKEYES20-COX     03-19 0556
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BUCKEYES20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Buckeye's looking for confidence from the line
 &HT;    By Susan Vinella
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Jim O'Brien has tried twice-weekly, 7 a.m.
foul shooting sessions. He's tried sports psychologists. He's tried
pep talks. And still, the Buckeyes foul shooting, well, stinks.
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State is shooting just 61 percent from the foul line.
Against Auburn, they shot a dismal 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what it is,'' O'Brien said. ``In practice,
our percentages are really high, which makes me think it's not
mechanical. For the most part, I think it's between the ears.''
</P>
<P>
   OSU center Ken Johnson acknowledges that doubt creeps in when
players step to the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we even need practice,'' he said. ``I think it's
just confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   He chuckled when asked if the school's sports psychologist has
helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can talk to us seven hours per day but if we don't go out
there with confidence, then we won't make our free throws,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Scoonie Penn is the only Buckeye starter shooting better than 70
percent from the line (74 percent). Michael Redd is next, having
made 62 percent of his shots. Johnson is the worst free throw
shooter among the starters, with a 48.6 percent success rate from
the line.
</P>
<P>
   OSU guard Brian Brown will see several familiar faces when he
steps on the court against St. John's today. Red Storm reserve
foward Reggie Jessie was a teammate of Brown's at Bishop Loughlin
High School in New York City. Starting forward Ron Artest played at
nearby La Salle Academy and freshman guard Erick cq Barkley played
on the same CYO team as Brown in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said initially he didn't understand why Brown chose to
attend Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when Ohio State was going bad,'' Barkley said,
referring to the Buckeyes' losing records and off-the-court
problems in recent years. And I said, `Why you going there?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `Just watch.'''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley will get to do that in person today.
</P>
<P>
   A Columbus native, Redd was asked what it was like to live in
the city during the recent down times of OSU basketball. Redd said
the team was so bad, the locals coined an unflattering nickname for
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to be called the 'Suckeyes' all the time instead of
the Buckeyes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, sitting a few seats away, shifted uncomfortably in his
seat and blushed a bit.
</P>
<P>
   After his 26-point performance in OSU's victory against Auburn,
Penn was the center of the media's attention Friday. At one point,
a reporter asked four of Penn's teammates who were sitting next him
during an interview session to describe one particular Penn shot or
moment that made them go ``Wow, how did he do that?''
</P>
<P>
   Redd recalled getting a great no-look pass from Penn during a
home win over Iowa. Brown recalled a shot Penn threw up against
Indiana that bounced off the backboard and went in. Jason Singleton
and Johnson said Penn has made so many remarkable plays, they
couldn't highlight just one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's routine for him to make plays like that,'' Redd said.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat embarrassed by the praise, Penn bowed his head, buried
it in his hands and turned a light shade of red. He had nothing to
add to the discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
