<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Huskies hyped for game against Iowa
 &HT;    By Bucky Albers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ As if Tamika Williams didn't already have enough
motivation to play well this afternoon when her Connecticut team
faces Iowa State in the NCAA Midwest Regional basketball
tournament, she has gotten some extra incentive.
</P>
<P>
   The former Chaminade-Julienne High School star has been told
that she will be able to spend the night at home in Dayton if the
Huskies (29-4) defeat Iowa State (24-7) in the 12 noon game at the
Shoemaker Center.
</P>
<P>
   That may not sound like much to the average person, but Tamika
hasn't been home since Christmas. She is eager to spend some time
with her parents, George and Jo Williams, and with her 12-year-old
sister, Tiffany, who is already 6-feet tall and a budding
basketball star.
</P>
<P>
   Tamika's older brother, Mike, just became a father, and she
wants to see her new nephew.
</P>
<P>
   When you are playing college basketball, especially for a
high-profile team like Connecticut, there isn't much time for
family in the middle of March Madness.
</P>
<P>
   After watching C-J play in the state tournament at Columbus
Thursday, Tamika's parents drove down to Cincinnati on Friday to
see their daughter after the Huskies practiced. They didn't get
much time with her.
</P>
<P>
   So many reporters wanted to talk to Tamika that UConn officials
took her aside and set up interviews separate from the usual
session with coaches and players. ESPN did a private interview.
Earline Brown, a family friend, and her daughter-in-law, former UD
player Tobette Pleasant Brown, managed to have their picture taken
with the 18-year-old phenom, but there wasn't much time for
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Before they knew it, Tamika was being swept off toward the team
bus without the pound cake that Mrs. Brown had baked for the team.
The cake was hustled to the bus just in time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You lose control,'' Tamika's mother said. ``You have to sit
back and wait. I probably won't get to see her until after the game
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Tamika didn't forget about the family. Some of her teammates
gave her their complimentary tickets for today's game, so she was
able to round up two dozen for family, relatives and friends.
</P>
<P>
   When George and Jo drove back to Dayton, they brought with them
Tamika's latest trophy. She was named Freshman of the Year by The
Sporting News .
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the UConn-Iowa State game meets the winner of the
Georgia-Clemson game Monday evening for a ticket to the Final Four
in San Jose, Calif., next weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
