<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke juggernaut rolls on
 &HT;    By Leo Willingham
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Duke moved another step closer to the Final Four
Friday, but it wasn't easy.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils (35-1) advanced to the East Regional final with
a 78-61 victory over Southwest Missouri State, which might have
played its last game under coach Steve Alford. Unlike its two
previous tournament games, top seed Duke found itself in a battle
against the Bears (22-11), the 12th seed, which trailed 39-30 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Duke used a 14-4 run in a four-minute span of the second half to
pull away for its 30th straight victory and a spot in Sunday's
regional final. The Blue Devils failed to reach 80 points for the
just the fourth time this season and the first since Dec. 22, a
71-60 victory over Kentucky at the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The loss ended the tournament run for Alford, the former Indiana
All-American who is one of eight candidates for the vacant Georgia
job and has been mentioned as a possible successor to Tom Davis at
Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   _ Top seed Michigan State (32-4) advanced to the Midwest final
with a 54-46 victory over Oklahoma (22-11). The game was delayed
for 10 minutes in the second half as Oklahoma's Eduardo Najera, the
team's leading scorer and rebounder, lay motionless on the court
after colliding with Michigan State's Mateen Cleaves. Najera
suffered a concussion and a lacerated chin, but returned to the
game.
</P>
<P>
   _ Connecticut (31-2) hopes to secure its first-ever Final Four
berth today when it faces Gonzaga (28-6) in the West final in
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
