<HEADER>
A7500 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-DUKE20-COX     03-19 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duke handles SW Missouri, wins 30th in row
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It wasn't devastation, but it was still
domination for No. 1 Duke as the No. 1 Blue Devils got 24 points
from senior guard Trajan Langdon to beat Southwest Missouri State
78-61 in Friday night's NCAA East Regional semifinals at the
Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Duke (35-1) extended its winning streak to 30 games and will
play the winner of Friday's late game between Purdue and Temple on
Sunday for the regional championship and a spot in next week's
Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   After Duke won its first two NCAA Tournament games by 41 points
each, the 12th-seeded Bears were expected to offer just token
resistance to the Blue Devils, who appear to be on a collision
course with their third national championship in this decade.
</P>
<P>
   But to its credit, Steve Alford's team made Duke work for the
victory. Not until the final 10 minutes were the Blue Devils able
to put away the pesky Bears from the Missouri Valley Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Duke came into Friday night's contest having won its last 11
games by an average of 30.8 points.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri (22-11) reached is first Sweet 16 by
upsetting Wisconsin and Tennessee in last week's first and second
round in Charlotte. In those games, Southwest Missouri held its
opponents to 29 percent shooting.
</P>
<P>
   No such luck against the Blue Devils, who shot 55.6 in first
half and were hot for most of the night from the outside.
</P>
<P>
   If Duke can win Sunday's game, it will advance to the Final Four
from this arena for the fifth time in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Up by nine at halftime (39-30), Duke jumped out to its biggest
lead of the game, 47-34, on a long 3-point shot by William Avery
with 16:48 left. But Southwest Missouri came back with its own
3-pointer by Allen Phillips. The Bears were still in the hunt,
trailing 50-39.
</P>
<P>
   Then Duke got four straight points from Langdon and a 3-pointer
from Nate Games to put the Blue Devils ahead 57-42 with 12:23 left.
Alford called a timeout, feeling the game was about to slip away.
</P>
<P>
   His instincts were right as three minutes later the Duke lead
was 18 and the Bears simply did not have enough energy to make a
final run to get back into the game.
</P>
<P>
   In Duke's two previous tournament games, the Blue Devils led by
39 and 30 at halftime. Against Southwest Missouri State, Duke led
39-30 at the intermission but had to fight for every single point.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Devils jumped out to a quick 15-6 lead on Avery's
3-point shot at the 13:17 mark and appeared to be headed towards
one of its withering runs. But Southwest Missouri would not succumb
to the pressure and quickly regrouped, getting a pair of 3-pointers
from Phillips and Kevin Ault to move to within three at 15-12.
</P>
<P>
   Every time Duke seemed ready to apply the knockout punch, as it
had done to so many opponents in the first half this season,
Southwest Missouri found a way to score and stay within striking
distance.
</P>
<P>
   The Bears still trailed 23-20 when Duke's Elton Brand scored
inside and Langdon hit a long 3-pointer to put the Blue Devils up
by eight with 5:51 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Missouri would get the deficit back to five, but then
Langdon hit a three with 50.8 seconds left to give Duke its
halftime margin. Langdon scored 10 points in the last 5:51.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
