<HEADLINE>
LINE CHANGES AND OSCAR TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Several UCLA football players will have new
positions when spring practice begins April 6, with each change
involving the defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have moved 300-pound guard Steve Morgan to defensive
tackle, where he'll join Ken Kocher, Sean Phillips and Anthony
Fletcher to form a young (two redshirt freshmen, two true
sophomores) but massive tackle rotation in the 4-3 alignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Morgan's a load and we want guys who will clog it up,'' coach
Bob Toledo said. ``He's hard to move. Guys couldn't block him in
one-on-one drills.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, freshman tight end Saia Makakaufaki (260 pounds)
will play defensive end, defensive tackle Micah Webb will move to
offense when he recovers from knee surgery, and redshirt freshman
and defensive lineman Doug Whiting will miss the 1999 season
because of back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   __ Recruiting update: The Bruins have received an oral
commitment from Pat Norton, a junior fullback from Newhall Hart
High School. UCLA has two scholarship fullbacks on the roster,
seniors-to-be Durell Price and Mark Verti. Norton's commitment is
not binding until he signs a letter of intent next February. He is
the second junior to commit, behind Vista (Calif.) linebacker Tim
Warfield. UCLA's allotment of approximately 18 scholarships for
next season is going fast.
</P>
<P>
   __ The winners are: Former UCLA offensive lineman Kris Farris
reviewed movies for the Daily News last season. Farris took time
out from preparing for the NFL Draft to proffer his predictions for
Sunday's Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Best actor: Tom Hanks (``Saving Private Ryan'') is an Academy
favorite but won't get his third statue of the '90s. Ian McKellan
(``Gods and Monsters'') and Nick Nolte (``Affliction'') are very
deserving but will cancel each other out.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Edward Norton (``American History X'').
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Roberto Benigni (``Life is Beautiful'').
</P>
<P>
   ++ Best actress: The voters feel Meryl Streep (``One True
Thing'') has already been adequately compensated. Unfortunately for
Fernanda Montenegro (``Central Station'') and Emily Watson
(``Hilary and Jackie``), not enough people have seen their work.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Cate Blanchett (``Elizabeth``).
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Gwyneth Paltrow (``Shakespeare in Love'').
</P>
<P>
   ++ Best supporting actor: This is the most exciting and
talent-filled category. It seems to be a tight race between Billy
Bob Thornton (``A Simple Plan'') and Geoffrey Rush (``Shakespeare
in Love''), the edge going to Thornton for his dim-witted, morally
challenged Jacob.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Thornton.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Best supporting actress: Judi Dench (``Shakespeare in Love'')
is the only nominated actress with a pivotal role in a legitimate
Best Picture contender. Kathy Bates' performance was powerful, but
``Primary Colors'' was released more than a year ago, and the
voters can't remember anything before December.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Dench.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Dench.
</P>
<P>
   ++ Best Picture: For me, there is a clear-cut champ, ``Saving
Private Ryan.'' ``Life is Beautiful'' will win the Best Foreign
Language Oscar, leaving ``Shakespeare in Love'' as the only serious
contender.
</P>
<P>
   What should win: ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
<P>
   What will win: ``Saving Private Ryan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
