<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DOW JONES INDUSTRIALS FAIL TO CLOSE ABOVE 10,000
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average made its biggest move yet past
10,000, but fell back once again, unable to make its first close
above that milestone. The Dow made it to 10,085.31 in early
trading, and spent more than half the session trading above five
digits. But the robust opening turned around when IBM and dozens of
smaller technology stocks began to decline. The Dow closed at
9,903.55, down 94.07 points.
</P>
<P>
   Other stock market gauges also ended lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell 17.26, or 1.31 percent, to 1,299.29.
And the Nasdaq composite index decreased 41.69, or 1.7 percent, to
2,421.27.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury prices slumped on speculation that AT&AMP;T would increase
its bond sale from the $6 billion or more already planned. The
yield on the 30-year Treasury rose to 5.55 percent, from 5.48
percent on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST UNION PLANS TO CUT 5,850 JOBS
</P>
<P>
   First Union said it would cut 5,850 jobs, or 7 percent of its
work force. The job cuts come in the wake of First Union's $16.1
billion merger with Corestates Financial. The actual cuts were
lower than the 7,150 jobs the banking company said it might make.
</P>
<P>
   LEHMAN EARNINGS INCREASE 13 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Lehman Brothers Holdings said first-quarter earnings rose 13
percent, to $211 million, or $1.57 a fully diluted share. Analysts
had expected a profit of $1.45 a share.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG ECONOMY SHRINKS 5.7 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   The economy of Hong Kong shrank an estimated 5.7 percent in the
fourth quarter of 1998 and 5.1 percent in all of 1998. It was the
first full-year decline in economic output since Hong Kong began
keeping records in 1961. And, despite a rebound in the stock and
property markets, consumer spending plummeted 9.3 percent in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   GREENSPAN HINTS AT LESS REGULATION
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the Federal Reserve, Alan Greenspan, said the
success of derivatives traded outside of exchanges suggested that
futures markets could operate with less government oversight.
Futures industry leaders praised the speech and said they hoped it
would influence Congress when it begins rewriting futures trading
laws later this year.
</P>
<P>
   PAN-EUROPEAN TV NETWORK PLANNED
</P>
<P>
   Mediaset of Italy and Germany's Kirch Group said they would pool
$1.1 billion in assets to create a pan-European television network.
The two companies already control broadcast outlets in
German-language nations, Italy and Spain.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN TELECOM DEAL REPORTED NEAR
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and British Telecommunications are close to buying a stake
in Japan Telecom, adding a third partner to their $10 billion
alliance and speeding their entry in the Japanese market, a senior
official at the Japanese company said.
</P>
<P>
   NISSAN-RENAULT DEAL ADVANCES
</P>
<P>
   The board of Nissan Motor expects to meet March 27 to discuss
Renault's bid to buy a 35 percent stake in the company. Nissan has
been seeking a foreign investor to help it return to profitability.
DaimlerChrysler quit talks with Nissan earlier.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS OF RECOVERY IN BRAZIL
</P>
<P>
   General Motors and Volkswagen plan to increase production in
Brazilian factories, providing signs of life in the country's
struggling auto industry. The moves suggest price-cutting and
government efforts to help sales by suspending some car taxes for
90 days are paying off. Car sales in Sao Paulo, Brazil's largest
city, tripled last weekend, according to automakers, as consumers
took advantage of discounts of up to 20 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 2226EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0402 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 22:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7504 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-NUHN-COLUMN20-COX     03-19 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-NUHN-COLUMN20-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Scoodini does it again
</P>
<P>
   By Gary Nuhn
</P>
<P>
   Dayton Daily News
</P>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ He was a breech-birth baby.
</P>
<P>
   Scoonie Penn came into the world with the umbilical cord wrapped
around his neck. According to his mother, Allegra, he didn't take a
breath for four or five minutes.
</P>
<P>
   I think Houdini was able to do that; a good match since now, 22
years later, Scoonie is a basketball Houdini.
</P>
<P>
   Scoodini did it again Thursday night while most of Ohio slept.
Ohio State was about to put away the jerseys when Scoonie came back
on the floor against Auburn in the NCAA South Regional semifinals
and took over as if he were Steven Spielberg walking on the set of
a movie.
</P>
<P>
   He made, by conservative count, somewhere between 17 and 47
marvelous plays in the last 10 minutes to resuscitate the Buckeyes,
dismiss Auburn and set up tonight's Regional final match with St.
John's.
</P>
<P>
   He is his mother's child, Scoonie Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Allegra grew up a great athlete in West Chester County, N.Y. It
didn't hurt that she had seven brothers, who, naturally, nicknamed
her ``Legs.''
</P>
<P>
   Legs was taking her first-born son, then known as Oonie, to the
playground by the time he was 3 or 4 to shoot around, and drilled
into his head that he could do anything he wanted if he tried hard
enough. Later, after high school games, Scoonie would come back to
the gym after taking his shower and find his mother on the floor
shooting baskets.
</P>
<P>
   Scoonie grew up fast. Without a father at home, he was the
eldest male and as such took on more responsibility than any
11-12-year-old should have.
</P>
<P>
   Allegra worked on the assembly line at a General Electric
aircraft plant and when there was overtime to be had, she couldn't
turn it down. That left Scoonie in a conflict _ he wanted to spend
all his time playing ball, yet he had a younger brother and sister
to look after.
</P>
<P>
   ``There might have been times I missed some games because of
it,'' he said. ``And I might have been mad at times. But I knew
what was best.''
</P>
<P>
   He was a two-sport star at Salem, Mass., High _ a
tailback/cornerback in football and a 30-point scorer in
basketball. ``I always liked football better,'' he said. ``But
after my sophomore year, I let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   He chose basketball because he didn't have to find a dozen other
kids to play with him.
</P>
<P>
   After two years at Boston College, he followed his coach, Jim
O'Brien, to Ohio State, and now has propelled the Buckeyes back
from basketball's graveyard.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise. Last season, as a transfer, Scoonie was allowed to
practice with the team, but not play in games. It was like teasing
a lion by pulling raw meat along outside his cage.
</P>
<P>
   Scoonie's release was playing scrimmages, and no matter how
O'Brien mixed and matched the players, Scoonie's team usually beat
the Buckeye regulars.
</P>
<P>
   For all of his on-court contributions, Scoonie said he'd rather
be remembered in another way. ``Everybody talks about the plays,''
he said, ``but the way these guys respect me as a teammate and as a
friend is more important to me. If they look back and say that that
kid Scoonie was a great kid to play with and a great kid to be
around, that will make me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   I set up a scene for him for tonight: ``Ten seconds to go; St.
John's up by a point; you've got the ball; no timeouts. What
happens next?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shootin' it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But what's the play?'' I asked. ``Where will you be?''
</P>
<P>
   He looked at me and laughed at my naivete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm shootin' it,'' he said again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
