<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0406 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7516 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-19 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES JOHNSON HAVE BEST JOB AROUND?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VERO BEACH, Fla. _ If power were muscle, Davey Johnson's biceps
would rip apart his Dodgers shirtsleeves.
</P>
<P>
   If power were money, he'd need a blue-and-white money belt for
his walking-around cash.
</P>
<P>
   If power really were the ultimate aphrodisiac, he'd have to
fight 'em off with a Louisville Slugger.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. Davey Johnson, beginning his fourth major-league
managing job, might be the most powerful man in a baseball uniform
anywhere this spring.
</P>
<P>
   He has a track record _ managing division champions in six of 10
full seasons _ that commands respect from his bosses, his players
and the press.
</P>
<P>
   He has a ``high-maintenance'' reputation _ the result of
contentious stints with the Mets, Reds and Orioles _ that could
intimidate his employers and staff.
</P>
<P>
   He has the security of a contract that guarantees him $1.5
million for each of three Dodgers seasons. He has the likelihood of
a one-year honeymoon while Dodgers critics focus on big-spending,
bold-talking general manager Kevin Malone.
</P>
<P>
   And he has all that in Los Angeles, where there's a chance to
put the National League's highest-profile franchise in the playoff
win column for the first time in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the Dodgers' front office, there's a feeling that if the
club's baseball power structure is a pyramid, in any practical
sense it's Johnson who stands at the top. Malone figures it's more
like him and Johnson side by side at the top _ but that sounds like
a concession in itself, seeing that the GM is first among the
baseball men on the Dodgers masthead, while the manager isn't
actually listed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a marriage,'' is how Malone described the
semi-equal partnership. Will it be a happy marriage?
</P>
<P>
   Malone wonders why the question keeps coming up, maintaining
that the men got along fine in the two seasons they both worked for
the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to me to make the final decisions most of the time. I
have to make the decisions because of my position,'' Malone said.
``But I learned a long time ago that I'm only as good as the people
who surround me. I want my people opinionated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the `No Fear' thing that if you don't live on the
edge, you're taking up space. You have to take risks. You have to
take chances. If you surround yourself with people with strong
opinions, you're going to have differences of opinion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always have to look at the big picture. I've got one eye on
the present and one eye on the future. He's (the manager) got both
eyes on the present. That's his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We both are opinionated, but we'll try to do what it takes to
win. We might have differences of opinion, but we'll figure out the
right thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   When their opinions clash, it will be Johnson who gets the first
chance to sway the public. He's the one with the postgame quotes,
the one with the winner's credentials. Malone, less familiar to
most reporters and fans, is still establishing his credibility in
Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson learned to use the media when he managed the Mets for
seven seasons in New York, where it's use or get used. He seemed to
learn something when he managed the Orioles for three seasons in
the shadow of Washington, D.C., where the White House staff crafts
a Message of the Day.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, however subtly, often delivers a Message of the Day to
the Dodgers beat writers.
</P>
<P>
   Monday in Kissimmee, Fla., the message was that 21-year-old Onan
Masaoka had pitched himself into contention for a left-handed
relief job even though ``the organization wants him to start in
Double-A.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday it was about the value of infielder Jose Vizcaino,
whose future with the team is the subject of front-office
discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday it was about the mound ``presence'' of pitcher Ismael
Valdes, whose intangible qualities are frequently questioned and
who is often rumored to be trade bait.
</P>
<P>
   And when Johnson talks baseball, who wouldn't listen? His new
players know he's a 43-home-run second baseman who's been there _
and there and there _ as a manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``In New York, they had a ballclub with a lot of talent that
couldn't get to the next level. Boom _ he came in and got them
there (winning the 1986 World Series),'' said Dodgers first baseman
Eric Karros. ``In Cincinnati, they had a good ballclub, a good
bunch of guys, but couldn't get over the hump. He came in and they
won (two division titles). Same in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done it three times in situations very similar to this.''
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson does it again with the Dodgers, who open the season
April 5, of course Malone will deserve half the credit, at least
half. But Malone's huge payroll and only half-joking prediction of
a World Series have made him the target of Dodgers-haters. That
means if the team falls short, the question will be, ``Malone spent
$86 million for !ital!this?''
</P>
<P>
   As for Johnson, either he wins or it's the GM's fault. That's a
nice spot to be in. That's power.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 2247EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
