<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7517 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PRESS-HNS &LR;      03-19 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SEES SEX SCANDAL AS A FOOTNOTE IN HISTORY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to shake any pall left from his impeachment,
President Clinton predicted Friday that lies he told in the
sex-and-perjury scandal would be a minor notation in the box score
of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference dominated by tensions in the Balkans,
Clinton acknowledged ``working hard'' on his marriage, sidestepped
a sexual abuse allegation from 21 years ago and defended his policy
of engagement with China.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton denied looking the other way on allegations that China
stole weapons secrets from the United States or that his
administration was slow to deal with security lapses at the
nation's nuclear laboratories.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am confident that we in the White House have done what we
could to be aggressive about this,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   In his first full-scale White House news conference since April
30, Clinton responded to most inquiries from reporters whose
questions for the past year have centered on his affair with Monica
Lewinsky and efforts to conceal it.
</P>
<P>
   The president declined to discuss his personal thoughts about
the bitterly partisan impeachment trial that ended five weeks ago
with his acquittal in the Senate on perjury and obstruction of
justice charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's best for me not to focus on that now,'' says Clinton,
pointing out that he has two years left before his presidency ends.
``Any time I spend worrying about that will detract from by ability
to be an effective president.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what lesson children would learn from his admitted lies
about trysts with the former White House intern, Clinton said the
lesson is that ``even presidents'' have to tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he suggested history will judge his
administration kindly despite the affair and his cover-up effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a box score, and there will be that one
negative,'' Clinton said, his voice rising as he gripped the podium
more tightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then there will be the hundreds and hundreds and hundreds
of times when the record will show that I did not abuse my
authority as president, that I was truthful with the American
people, and scores and scores of allegations were made against me
and widely publicized without any regard to whether they were true
or not.''
</P>
<P>
   In a slap at journalists, Clinton added: ``So I would hope that
there would be a higher regard for truth-telling by all people in
public life, and all those who report on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how his relationship was faring with first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton in the wake of the affair, the president said:
``We're working hard, and we love each other very much. And we're
working at it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton said he has ``no clue'' if his wife will
run for the Senate in 2000, but pointedly added that more than a
year ago she said they should move to New York when his presidency
is over.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton declined once again to discuss, or even deny,
allegations by a businesswoman that he raped her in 1978 while he
was running for attorney general in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   When Arkansas nursing home operator Juanita Broaddrick first
publicly accused Clinton of sexually assaulting her in a Little
Rock, Ark., motel room, the president referred inquiries to his
attorney, David Kendall, who called the charge ``absolutely
false.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a statement made by my attorney,'' Clinton said
when asked again why he would not at least deny the charge. ``He
speaks for me, and I think he spoke quite clearly.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also dealt with questions about spying at U.S. nuclear
installations, a controversy fueled by the dismissal of a
Chinese-American working at Los Alamos National Laboratory in New
Mexico. He was fired last week after allegations arose that nuclear
weapons secrets were given to the Chinese military some time in the
mid-1980s. China has denied any spying at the nuclear labs.
</P>
<P>
   The president denied that the administration reacted too slowly,
but at the same time acknowledged that security at the New Mexico
lab and other facilities was too weak for ``years and years and
years.''
</P>
<P>
   He denied that donations to the Democratic National Committee
from Chinese-related sources prompted a delay in investigations.
Asked if information was suppressed for political reasons, he said:
``The ... charge is simply untrue.''
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress have called for a re-evaluation of U.S.
relations with the Chinese government. Clinton said U.S. ties to
China have brought about some positive developments, such as
Chinese cooperation during the Asian economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The president characterized the U.S. relationship with China as
''profoundly important, very large, and inherently frustrating,
because it has many different elements, some of which we like, some
of which we don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who next week is to meet with Russian Prime Minister
Yevgeny Primakov, said he hopes an agreement can be reached for the
International Monetary Fund to extend Russia's credit.
</P>
<P>
   The president added that new lending to Russia will achieve its
goal only if laws are changed there to reform financial
institutions and stop money flooding out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF approved a $22.6 billion loan package to Russia in
midsummer but suspended most of the aid after the ruble was
devalued in mid-August, a move that plunged the country into a
financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping we can reach an agreement that will permit the IMF
program to go forward, because I think that is important,'' Clinton
said. ``But it will only work if the money does not turn around and
leave the country as soon as it is put in.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he felt betrayed by former aides George
Stephanopoulos and Dick Morris, who recently published books that
included critical accounts of his administration, the president did
not rise to the bait. Clinton said he has read neither book.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding recent ridicule aimed at Vice President Al Gore for
padding his resume with the claim he had fathered the Internet,
Clinton said that the vice president had been ``one of the major
architects for America's progress in technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said Gore has been ``integral to the good things'' of
the administration, adding that he has been too ``reticent'' to
brag about his accomplishments. ``I'll be happy to toot his horn,''
the president said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton praised Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin and
expressed hope that he would remain in the Cabinet, despite rumors
that the former Wall Street investment banker is eager to leave
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin has not issued a direct denial when asked about the
rumors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
