<DOCNO> NYT19990319.0409 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7519 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-MONEY-1STLEDE     03-19 1231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MONEY-1STLEDE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S CONSOLATION: DONATIONS TO PARTY SURGE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
 - WRITETHRU-NYT  
 (Eds.: Subs grafs 5, 6 and 11 with additional reporting)   
 (ATTN: Colo., N.J., Texas, Ark., Calif., Fla., Ohio, Nev., N.H. )  By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's impeachment appears to have a
silver lining, or at least a green one.
</P>
<P>
   Republican efforts to remove the president from office have
prompted a spurt in campaign donations to Democratic coffers, with
much of the giving inspired by the president himself as he
crisscrosses the country, blames Republicans for trying to bring
him down and thanks his supporters for standing by him.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who was impeached by the House on Dec. 19 by the House
and acquitted by the Senate on Feb. 12, single-handedly has raised
more than $9 million since mid-January. He has attended more
fund-raising events this year (13) than he has held Cabinet
meetings (1) or met with foreign heads of state (7).
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a very big draw, probably our biggest ever,'' said Roy
Romer of Colorado, general chairman of the Democratic National
Committee. ``When they see him being attacked in a partisan way as
he was all last year, people rise up and say, `I'm coming to the
table with twice what I gave before.' Receipts are double what we
anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic fund-raiser agreed. ``The impeachment,'' he said,
``has energized donors.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, aides to Romer said that by this time in 1998, an
election year, the president had raised $4 million for the national
committee alone through his attendance at 11 events, nearly double
the six DNC fund-raisers he has had to attend this year to raise
the same amount.
</P>
<P>
   Romer said that Democrats were in ``Alamo syndrome,'' which he
described as fighting back against attacks on the president. As a
recent direct-mail letter from the committee to prospective donors
put it: ``Now is the time for key Democrats to rally around the
president and our party. Otherwise, nothing stands in the way of
the GOP's slash-and-burn tactics. The last Congress focused almost
entirely on investigating instead of legislating.''
</P>
<P>
   In the last eight weeks, Clinton has raised money for all three
Democratic campaign committees, those of the national party, the
Senate committee and the House committee. He has helped raise money
for two state parties, in New Hampshire and Arkansas, and for two
members of Congress. In one evening earlier this month he brought
in $2 million for Sen. Robert G. Torricelli, the New Jersey
Democrat, who prominently defended him during the impeachment
process. Torricelli is not up for re-election until 2002.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, two Democratic fundraisers said that the president
raised ``very little'' money in the first few months of 1997,
estimating that the first quarter's total was less than $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The president's calendar is chock-a-block with more events, and
aides say it will only become more crowded as the 2000 campaign
draws closer. He is scheduled to attend Democratic National
Committee fundraisers next week in Cincinnati, Las Vegas and Los
Angeles. Two weeks later he heads for lunch in Detroit and dinner
in Boston to raise money for a joint committee promoting Senate and
House candidates in 2000. That committee alone is scheduling
Clinton for about eight more events this year, with a goal of his
personally bringing in $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans typically raise more than Democrats, and Jim
Nicholson, chairman of the Republican National Committee, said this
committee alone had raised about the same amount this year as the
president had for all Democratic committees. By other gauges,
though, the president's collection of cash has been extraordinary.
Two Democratic fund-raisers estimated Friday that in the first
quarter of 1997, the last non-election year, Clinton raised less
than $2 million, not even one-fourth of what he has amassed in the
last nine weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Such a frenzy of fundraising is unusual for a lame-duck
president. ``He's out raising money like he's running for another
term,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president of Democracy 21, a public
policy group. ``With all the fundraising the president keeps doing,
it may well be that Clinton's legacy is going to be as the greatest
big-money fundraiser in American history.''
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton speaks at these events, usually for 10 or 15
minutes after dinner, he frequently strays to topics like his
political survival. At the Torricelli dinner, where singer Gloria
Gaynor entertained the crowd, Clinton joked that he was trying to
decide which of her anthems to take as his theme song: ``I Will
Survive,'' or ``Never Can Say Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   His purpose, aides say, is to thank supporters for sticking by
him, to repay what aides describe as his personal debt to members
of Congress who defended him, and, increasingly, to make a point of
what he perceives as his persecution by Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday night, he pulled in half a million dollars for the
Democratic National Committee at a fundraising dinner in Stuart,
Fla.. After the Drifters sang their paean to loyalty, ``Stand By
Me,'' the president said: ``I thought about how the American people
have stood by me through thick and thin. This country has got to
get over believing that our political life is about beating each
other up and hurting people instead of lifting people up and
bringing them together.''
</P>
<P>
   When he spoke Tuesday in Florida, he took with him two
Democratic congressmen from the area, Reps. Peter Deutsch, who may
run for the Senate seat being vacated by Republican Connie Mack,
and Alcee L. Hastings, a former federal judge who, Clinton pointed
out, had been impeached in 1988 and removed from the bench. Unbowed
by his impeachment, Hastings went on to run for public office and
win a seat in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Gary, a Florida trial lawyer who was the host for the
event, said that the donors, many of them African-American, found
the president an inspiration. ``He has refused to be denied, he has
been down but not out, he has been a fighter, and has had, as we
say in the church, to climb the rough side of the mountain,'' Gary
said. ``When you see all he's been through and that he never
considered throwing the towel in, that's inspiration for a lot of
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spent the previous weekend in his hometown of Little
Rock, Ark., where he helped raise money at a state party dinner
featuring former Sen. Dale Bumpers, who gave the closing speech
last month in Clinton's impeachment trial. He also visited
Texarkana, Texas, where he raised $500,000 for Rep. Max Sandlin,
who served as a deputy whip during Clinton's impeachment in the
House in December and helped hold the Democrats together.
</P>
<P>
   At these events and others, the word ``impeachment'' did not
pass from the president's lips. Instead, he used the word
``Constitution'' as code to convey his argument that his lying
about his affair with a White House intern did not rise to an
impeachable offense as described in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``At a time in the last year when a lot of people just worried
which way the political winds were blowing,'' Clinton said at the
$1,000-per-person dinner for Sandlin, ``that guy was telling people
to read the Constitution of the United States of America.'' The
audience responded with a big applause.
</P>
</TEXT>
