<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7526 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOFFA-RULING-NYT &LR;      03-19 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOFFA-RULING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOFFA CLEARED TO TAKE HELM OF TEAMSTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas)  (mk) 
 By STEVEN GREENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal judge cleared the way Friday for James
Hoffa to be sworn in as president of the International Brotherhood
of Teamsters, 32 years after his famous father took the helm of the
powerful truckers' union.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Judge David Edelstein of U.S. District Court in
Manhattan rejected the remaining appeals that had delayed
certification of Hoffa's election in December.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling cleared the way for a federal election monitor,
Michael Cherkasky, to certify the election. On Friday night, just
hours after Edelstein's ruling, Cherkasky telephoned Hoffa's lawyer
with the official certification, clearing the way for Hoffa to take
the union oath of office in the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hoffa had won an overwhelming victory on Dec. 7, he was
unable to take the helm of the 1.4 million-member union, delayed by
numerous challenges to the election. For more than a month, several
of Hoffa's top aides have been working to put policies and
procedures in place so that Hoffa can start running the union as
soon as he is sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   In his ruling, Edelstein rejected an appeal by Hoffa's main
challenger, Tom Leedham, that the certification of Hoffa's election
be delayed indefinitely while a court-appointed oversight board
weighed charges filed against three of the 19 vice presidential
candidates elected on the Hoffa slate.
</P>
<P>
   One Hoffa vice president was charged with violating campaign
gift rules, another with filing false campaign finance reports and
a third with financial improprieties.
</P>
<P>
   Leedham, who received 39 percent of the vote to Hoffa's 55
percent, also asserted that certification of Hoffa should wait
until the review board issued a report on its investigation of
Hoffa, who has not been charged with any wrongdoing by the board.
</P>
<P>
   With Leedham arguing that the election monitor should screen
Hoffa's character _ and those of his running mates _ before
deciding whether to certify him, Edelstein ruled that Cherkasky
could rule only on election violations.
</P>
<P>
   The Teamsters are subject to a complex system of federal
oversight as part of a consent decree that the union signed in 1989
to settle a federal civil racketeering case, in which the union was
accused of having a ``devil's pact'' with the mob.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Edelstein upheld a decision ordering a new election
for a Teamsters vice president, J.D. Potter of Texas, whom
Cherkasky had barred from running.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
