<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-DARLINGTON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON ON POLE, BUT BENSON OFF HOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARLINGTON, S.C. _ Jeff Gordon says he won the pole for the
TranSouth Financial 400 with ``an unbelievable lap'' at 173.167 mph
at Darlington Raceway yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Then what can be said about the lap rung up by Johnny Benson?
</P>
<P>
   Mired in a season kindly described as mediocre, Benson toured
the treacherous 1.366-mile oval at 172.541 mph to claim the outside
starting position in the two-car front row.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's more like it,'' said Benson, who came into this event
having qualified 39th, 37th, 26th and 36th in 1999. Those starts
produced finishes of 17th, 16th, 38th and 22nd in the No. 26
Cheerios Ford Taurus owned by Jack Roush.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Benson's job security has become fodder for
the early season NASCAR Winston Cup rumor mill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been trying as hard as we can, and there's no doubt
we've struggled,'' said Benson, who is winless in 98 career Cup
starts. ``We need some good runs. I thought last week we were gonna
qualify good \Rat Atlanta Motor Speedway\S and I went for it and
ended up bad. This week Jack said, `What are you gonna do?' And I
said, `Well, maybe we'll just go for a good, solid run.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He kind of looked at me and I thought, `Well, I might change
my mind on pit road.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Good thinking. Benson ultimately posted his best qualifying
effort since starting second at Rockingham, N.C., in November. His
hot lap also marked the first time he has qualified in the first
round during 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good, solid run for us,'' said Benson, who is in his
second season with Roush Racing. ``We needed it, and hopefully, we
can just get it race-ready and race good this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Benson's run was only the start of the headline news for Team
Roush, as four of its five drivers earned top-10 positions. Mark
Martin qualified third at 171.878 mph in the repainted No. 6 Zerex
Ford; Kevin Lepage (171.764) will start seventh in the No. 16
Primestar Ford; and Jeff Burton (171.638) earned the ninth position
in the No. 99 Exide Batteries Taurus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just super,'' said Roush, who added that Benson and
Lepage needed good runs ``real bad.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, Mark was real steady,'' Roush said of his ace. ``We
thought we had a shot at the pole, but that 24 car \RGordon\S is
just incredible right now. It's awful hard to do anything with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, winner of the Cracker Barrel 500 at AMS on Sunday,
bagged his 25th career pole and second in 13 races at the track
``Too Tough to Tame.'' Gordon, who also won the pole for the
Daytona 500 (and the race), is the first two-time pole winner of
1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the prettiest lap, but when you're running that fast
you want to be able to keep it on the edge,'' said Gordon, driver
of the No. 24 DuPont Automotive Finishes Chevrolet Monte Carlo.
``These guys \Rat Hendrick Motorsports\S hit the chassis and engine
combination just right, and I hit all my marks on the track.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if a lap can ever be perfect, but the car was
unbelievably good. It did everything I wanted it to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, meanwhile, authored his sixth consecutive top-10
qualifying effort at Darlington, which is NASCAR's oldest
superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   Series points leader Mike Skinner maintained his impressive pace
by qualifying fourth at 171.890 mph in the No. 31 Lowe's Chevy. It
was the fourth consecutive top-10 qualifying effort of 1999 for
Skinner, who leads injured runner-up Bobby Labonte by 32 points.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth starting spot was claimed by John Andretti at 171.782
mph in the No. 43 STP Pontiac Grand Prix. It was Andretti's best
effort since he started fourth in the Pepsi Southern 500 here last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The top 25 positions were locked in yesterday, with the
remainder of the 43-car field to be determined today.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
