</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-STJOHN-590&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JARVIS SURPRISED BY SPEED OF ST. JOHN'S SUCCESS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Who is this team in the St. John's uniforms
that is on the verge of going to the Final Four, and where has it
hidden the group that stumbled through the end of the regular
season just two weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   St. John's run to the South Regional final of the NCAA
tournament against Ohio State on Saturday night seemed unlikely
back in October, when the walls in coach Mike Jarvis' office were
still bare. It seemed even more improbable when the Red Storm
limped into Orlando, Fla., last week, reeling from a 21-point
beating by Connecticut in the Big East tournament final.
</P>
<P>
   With just one more victory, St. John's will go to the Final Four
for the first time since 1985, when it was propelled by Chris
Mullin, Walter Berry and Bill Wennington.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jarvis conceded last week that when players asked him on
the first day of practice if he thought they could go all the way,
it was a bit of wishful thinking when he replied that certainly,
yes, they could win it all.
</P>
<P>
   Only a group as confident as this one could have believed that a
team that lost its two leading scorers _ one of whom was a
first-round draft pick in the NBA _ had a freshman point guard, a
new coach and a new offensive system could perform so well that it
would hand Indiana its worst tournament loss and dismantle a
Maryland team that many thought could have received a No. 1
seeding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honestly, I would have said a minimum of a year away,'' Jarvis
said, ``probably three or four players away providing the majority
of players stayed. I would say it would have taken another year for
them to become more comfortable with what I would like them to do.
For us to be talking here, 40 minutes away. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Jarvis was proven wrong because his team raised the quality of
its game several notches during the NCAA tournament. Since that
loss to Connecticut, the Red Storm (28-8) has played intelligent,
cohesive basketball, slowly, methodically squeezing the life out of
its opponents with nearly flawless play. The players have bought
into Jarvis' demand that they be open to adjustments, and their
defense, in all its incarnations, has been superb, limiting three
opponents to 33.9 percent shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   The offense has been smooth and efficient, with no one player
dominating, except perhaps Erick Barkley, with his stellar passing
skills and unflappability in the face of pressure. St. John's has
shot 48.7 percent in the tournament and has had 77 assists on 158
field goals.
</P>
<P>
   The victory over Samford, with its Princeton-style offense,
required discipline and patience. The victory over Indiana required
the willingness to believe Jarvis when he said that the unfamiliar,
distasteful zone defense would work. And the victory over Maryland
required the confidence that St. John's had the ball handlers to
neutralize the Terrapins' press and that the same aggressive zone
defense would work again. St. John's won the three games by an
average of 21 points.
</P>
<P>
   What has happened to change the tenor of this season _ from
multiple near misses against top five teams to the total domination
of Maryland _ the players say is rooted in late-season losses to
Villanova and Connecticut. After those games, Jarvis said, his
players discovered what was needed to advance.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing for 40 minutes instead of 20 minutes here and
there,'' center Tyrone Grant said. ``In the post-season, teams play
for 40 minutes. That taught us a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also taught us that we've got to continue to attack the way
we were early in the season, and it would wear our opponents
down.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The last three opponents have been worn down so early in the
games that, in the space of a week, St. John's has gone from shaky
to superlative. Against fourth-seeded Ohio State _ a team that is
using one of the nation's best backcourts to fashion its own
meteoric rise from the basement of the Big Ten _ the Red Storm is
favored.
</P>
<P>
   After winning just one game in the Big Ten last season and
enduring a 17-game losing streak along the way, second-year coach
Jim O'Brien _ who left Boston College two years ago after a
disagreement with the school's admissions officials _ has crafted a
remarkable recovery. Ohio State (26-8) finished second in the Big
Ten to Michigan State largely on the strength of its two
spectacular guards, Scoonie Penn and Michael Redd, who combined for
48 of Ohio State's 72 points in a victory over Auburn on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   But the perception of the Buckeyes is that while Penn (16.9
points) and Redd (19.6 points) are superb, the rest of the team is
no bigger than St. John's and is not as gifted as the Red Storm,
allowing St. John's to key on the backcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been concerned about it all year,'' O'Brien said.
``Teams have attempted to take Scoonie and Michael out all year.
We've been fortunate that there hasn't been one guy who has stepped
up to be the third or fourth scorer but several guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if I had my druthers, I'd rather have five guys in double
figures than two guys averaging 20.''
</P>
<P>
   Surely, Penn and Redd have slight edges at their positions over
Barkley and Bootsy Thornton. But those advantages are not as great
as the ones Lavor Postell should have over Brian Brown, a guard
from Brooklyn who has been in the starting lineup at forward for
the first time all season, and that Ron Artest should have over
Jason Singleton, a 6-foot-6-inch, 190-pound forward.
</P>
<P>
   Even at center, the 6-7, 240-pound Grant has been able to handle
bigger players, like the slight 6-11, 225-pound Ken Johnson, who
averages just 6.3 points per game for Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   ``These two teams are much more similar than Maryland was,''
Jarvis said. ``They're both team oriented. They're both undersized,
but don't tell them that. And the kids believe. It's going to be a
matter of will more than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   And St. John's has already shown plenty of that in this
tournament. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
