<HEADLINE>
TEXAS LAW STUDENT TAKES HER SCHOOL TO COURT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RON NISSIMOV 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Wendy Anderson moved from Austin to Houston in 1997 to
enroll at the South Texas College of Law, but she is now getting a
legal education she never bargained for.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson is representing herself in a lawsuit she recently filed
against the school over its academic policy. She claims the school
deceived her about how much time she would have to bring her grade
point average up to 2.0 if she experienced academic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was temporarily kicked out of the school in June 1997
because she failed to maintain a C average, according to her state
district court suit. Anderson, who could not be reached for
comment, did not flunk any classes, the suit said.
</P>
<P>
   School spokeswoman Sheila Hansel said Friday that Anderson has
been readmitted to the school and is currently doing ``very well
academically.'' School officials denied Anderson has been treated
unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson claimed in the lawsuit that one reason she chose South
Texas College of Law, which is affiliated with Texas A&AMP;M
University, was because school literature assured her she would
have at least two semesters to bring her GPA up to 2.0.
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks after she enrolled in January 1997, the lawsuit
said, Anderson was told for the first time that the school's policy
was to dismiss students after the first semester for failing to
maintain a 2.0 GPA. She was dismissed before completing two
semesters.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said the one-semester policy had been in effect
beginning October 1996, but the school's admissions bulletin and
policy handbook had failed to disclose the policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an older student, it had been some time since I had been in
school,'' Anderson said in court papers. ``I knew that I would
potentially require a couple of semesters to familiarize myself
with analytical thinking and writing.''
</P>
<P>
   She said that if she had been told of the policy she would not
have chosen the South Texas College of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson filed suit in January seeking at least $50,000 in
actual damages as well as unspecified exemplary damages. She also
wants a court order ``expunging any evidence of previously
attending law school and their corresponding grades.''
</P>
<P>
   She claims that as a result of being temporarily kicked out of
school, she ``suffered intense feelings of humiliation and
belittlement, an abnormal sense of inferiority and accompanying
panic attacks, and loss of sleep and appetite.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit said most U.S. law schools allow students two
semesters to bring their GPAs up to a minimum level.
</P>
<P>
   School spokeswoman Hansel said she did not have information
Friday on what type of school literature prospective students
received at the time Anderson applied.
</P>
<P>
   A letter written to Anderson by the school's general counsel
Jerry Thorn in December 1997 that was included in court records
said Anderson's legal claims were ``not applicable.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The College wishes you to understand that it values you as a
student,'' Thorn wrote to Anderson. ``It appreciates the efforts
that you have put forth to this date in getting yourself ready for
law school and then attending and hopes that you continue on this
course.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
