<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA MUST STOP HAMMON TO WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ They sat at a table on an elevated podium inside
the Sports Arena and said all the right things: how they're happy
to be here at the NCAA West Regional, how they respect their
opponent, how it will be a great game.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, the UCLA and Colorado State women's basketball
teams tipped their hands. The teams' focus is clear as they prepare
for tonight's 9:30 p.m. game.
</P>
<P>
   During UCLA's 30 minutes on the dais, nearly all the talk was
about Colorado State All-American point guard Becky Hammon, what
she can do and how to stop her.
</P>
<P>
   When someone finally asked about the rest of the 33-2 Rams, UCLA
coach Kathy Olivier had to think about the question for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hope I don't screw up the name,'' she began before mentioning
forward Katie Cronin by last name. ``Cronin, she's very talented.
She can shoot well. You can tell she's the other leader on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State followed the Bruins in the press conference and
the dominant talk was about the Rams' size disadvantage, and how to
stop UCLA's post duo of Maylana Martin and Janae Hubbard, who
helped the Bruins (25-7) win their first Pac-10 title.
</P>
<P>
   When coach Tom Collen was asked how his team will defend, he
said the players prefer to press and create an up-tempo offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be to our advantage to go up-tempo,'' he said. ``It's
not to their disadvantage, but we don't want to play a halfcourt
game with them.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, it appears UCLA has the advantage. Martin, a
6-foot-3, third-team All-American, and the 6-4 Hubbard combine for
31 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado State doesn't have anyone taller than 6-3, and Marsha
Tate doesn't even play in every game. Plus, the Western Athletic
Conference team with the best post game, Collen said, is Southern
Methodist _ the same Mustangs who shocked the Rams 65-49 to win the
WAC tournament. Previously, the Rams had won by seven and 17
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're big, but we're small,'' Cronin said of UCLA. ``We can
bring them out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rams like to shoot from the outside, led by the 5-6 Hammon,
who averages 23 points and shoots 42 percent (111 of 265) from
3-point range. As a team, Colorado State has attempted 759 treys.
</P>
<P>
   But here again is a UCLA advantage. Point guard Erica Gomez
played with Hammon on the U.S. Jones Cup team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being that size, you have to find some ways to score,'' Gomez
said. ``She played against people who were a lot taller, so she
knows how to get her shot up.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Bruins have a plan to stop her: Continue to rotate
defenders on her.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the best help defense I've seen,'' Gomez said. ``A
couple of teams have good 3-point shooters in our conference.
Washington State puts up an incredible amount. Our team has gotten
better, as far as rotation goes.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the location of the game: 10 miles from UCLA.
Although the Bruins haven't drawn well in the postseason (the 9
p.m. starts have limited the attendance of UCLA's target group _
pre-teen girls), it's much easier and cheaper to drive to the
Sports Arena than fly from Fort Collins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
