<HEADER>
A7623 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPRINGSTEEN-ART-2TAKE     03-19 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINGSTEEN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINGSTEEN INFUSES ASBURY PARK WITH A BIT OF ITS PAST ENERGY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Texas)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   JACQUES STEINBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASBURY PARK, N.J. _ When Ed Gubitosa and his wife, Grace,
learned that Bruce Springsteen and the E Street Band would be
providing a sneak preview of their first concert tour together in
more than a decade, they dropped everything.
</P>
<P>
   The Gubitosas, who live in Houston, would not be discouraged
simply because the two concerts, which are technically rehearsals
for a world tour, were being staged on less than three days'
notice, more than 1,600 miles away, here in the punch-drunk
seashore city where Springsteen began his career in the early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   And they weren't dissuaded when Gubitosa, a 45-year-old airline
executive, called Ticketmaster from Texas and learned that all
3,000 tickets to the performances Thursday night and Friday night
had been sold in little more than an hour.
</P>
<P>
   All that mattered to the Gubitosas, both natives of the Jersey
Shore, was that the concerts were a way to turn back the clock and
relive a chapter of ancient history _ theirs, ``Bruce's,'' and
Asbury Park's _ with their children, Andrew, 12, and Gina, 16.
</P>
<P>
   And so, as a freezing wind from the ocean lashed the boardwalk
outside Convention Hall on Thursday night, the family celebrated
spring break by huddling together like Dust Bowl refugees in a line
of perhaps 300 others who were ticket-deprived, hoping a few extra
tickets would be made available at the box office just before show
time, as is often the case at Springsteen concerts.
</P>
<P>
   That the Gubitosas were not among the lucky 53 people shepherded
inside the hall as the concert began did not seem to diminish their
experience. ``I'm having a blast,'' Gubitosa said this afternoon,
as he weighed joining the line again for a second night.
</P>
<P>
   It has been that kind of week in Asbury Park.
</P>
<P>
   For a small resort city that has had very little to smile about
for decades _ its once-thriving colony of 200 hotels has dwindled,
famously, to just one _ the fleeting reappearance of Springsteen
has generated a frenzy reminiscent of the days when Billie Holiday,
the Marx Brothers and Frank Sinatra came here to play, followed
generations later by The Doors, The Who and the Rolling Stones.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was lightened all the more this week by Springsteen's
decision to donate the proceeds from the two shows, which grossed
about $100,000, to four local charities.
</P>
<P>
   ''When someone like Bruce Springsteen, who has an emotional
attachment here, makes a physical investment, that's powerful,''
said Susan Maynard, the executive director of the West Side
Community Center on Dewitt Avenue, who learned from a radio report
that her social service agency had been selected to get some of the
money. ``It's a sign that good things are coming.''
</P>
<P>
   For Springsteen, who last toured the country three years ago
with a dour, acoustic set that left many fans wondering if he had
lost the desire to play rock-and-roll, the performances here
suggested that he, too, seemed eager to go back in time.
</P>
<P>
   Stretching Thursday's night show to 2 hours and 35 minutes with
no intermission, Springsteen, seemed as gleeful as a child who had
rediscovered a long-lost toy, stomping across the stage with his
guitar hoisted over his shoulder and smiling giddily at his eight
bandmates as they tuned up for an international tour that begins
next month in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   With saxophonist Clarence `Big Man' Clemons to his right and
guitarist Little Steven Van Zandt to his left, Springsteen ignored
most of the material he had recorded after 1984, the year the album
``Born in the U.S.A.'' made him a pop icon.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he played chestnuts that were once known only within
the clubs of New Jersey, rockers like ``Spirit in the Night. ''
Rounding out a week in which he was inducted into the Rock 'n' Roll
Hall of Fame, he also unveiled a new song, ``Land of Hope and
Dreams,'' which fuses gospel and rock to a piano line simulating
the roll of a train.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a special night for us,'' he told those standing in
the audience, many of them waving cellular phones with open lines
to friends, who, like them, probably had slimmer stomachs and
fuller hairlines when they first discovered Springsteen as a
scraggly teen-ager from nearby Freehold.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a rededication of our band.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know what to say,'' he added, ``except that I'm real
happy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Standing within arm's reach of the stage, in a venue no bigger
than a high school gym, Jeff Gimbal, 47, turned to his brother,
Jim, 42, and shouted ``He's not the only one!''
</P>
<P>
   The Gimbals, who own an educational recording company in Ocean
Township, cheered even louder when Springsteen pointed near them
and recalled where he stood as a fan when an unknown Pete Townshend
came to Convention Hall and smashed his guitars in the late 1960s;
the brothers had been there that night, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wore me out,'' Jeff Gimbal said to his brother . ``My legs
are shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it will take a lot more than a Bruce Springsteen
concert to solve Asbury Park's problems. But officials in this city
of one square mile, which owns the 69-year-old red-brick hall where
Springsteen performed, hope that the enthusiasm he generated this
week is contagious.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when he should be thinking about little other than how
to jump-start a long-stalled $800 million plan to rebuild the
shuttered waterfront, the city manager, Wilbert Russell, confessed
that he had been reduced this week to the role of a full-time
ticket broker.
</P>
<P>
   Allotted only enough tickets to sprinkle among a handful of
elected city officials, Russell said that he had turned down offers
of upward of $1,000 per ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``The city has been beaten down,'' Russell said. ``Asbury really
has a tainted name, with people saying `Asbury isn't what it used
to be.' I think Bruce is giving hope that a change is coming about
in the city.''
</P>
<P>
   In one sign that Springsteen may well have begun to prime the
pump, however slowly, Chico Rouse, the general manager of the
Convention Hall and adjoining Paramount Theater, said that within
hours of Springsteen's announcement of his shows, the city had
received serious inquiries from two ``significant'' rock and pop
acts about playing Asbury Park. Rouse, whose father, Charlie,
played saxophone with Thelonious Monk, said it was too early to
name them.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted that they would be a departure from some recent
billings at the hall. One was billed as March Metal Meltdown, an
extravaganza that blends professional wrestling and heavy metal
music. Another was an evening with the man who was the subject of
Robert Redford's movie ``The Horse Whisperer,'' who filled the hall
with clay six-feet deep and who demonstrated his gift by talking to
several local mounts.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd spilled out of the hall Thursday night and onto the
splintered boardwalk, the happiest man may have been George Panas.
</P>
<P>
   Panas, an immigrant from Greece, bought the circular Howard
Johnson's on the boardwalk in 1961, at a time when the line spilled
out the door all day, every day, during the summer. Now, Panas only
opens his restaurant when there is an event at the hall, but even
then, he, his wife and their daughter don't see the crowd that they
saw last night: nearly 1,000 people passed through their doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, this will again be one of the great towns,''
Panas, 67, said from behind the bustling counter. ``Like
Disneyland.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
