<HEADER>
A7632 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-NYT &LR;      03-19 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNEE INJURY MAY KNOCK BONILLA OUT OF OPENER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. _ A magnetic resonance imaging test of
Bobby Bonilla's right knee Friday revealed that his posterior
cruciate ligament has a 15 percent tear, an injury that will keep
the Mets' starting right fielder out of the lineup for the next 10
days to two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the Mets' final exhibition game this spring is
two weeks from Saturday, the chances are good that Mets manager
Bobby Valentine will have had just one opportunity all spring to
see his projected starting lineup on the field together. And that
came on Thursday night, when Bonilla reinjured his knee.
</P>
<P>
   And what are the chances that the 36-year-old Bonilla will
actually be ready for opening day, on April 5 in Miami?
</P>
<P>
   ``Questionable, right now,'' General Manager Steve Phillips
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla missed opening day last season, when he was a member of
the Florida Marlins, after undergoing off-season surgery on both
his left shoulder and his left Achilles' tendon. By the time the
season was through, Bonilla had not only been traded to Los
Angeles, but had also gone through three stays on the disabled
list, not to mention in-season surgery to have a noncancerous
growth removed near his colon and an episode of tendinitis that
caused him to miss the last six games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   So even though Bonilla _ who hit .249 last season with just 11
homers and 45 runs batted in _ seemed dejected by Friday's news, he
realized it could have been worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was going to have to have surgery, which meant
here we go again,'' said Bonilla, who was fitted with a brace
instead. ``That's why I was really nervous going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla first injured his knee in a collision with the Expos
pitcher Dustin Hermanson on March 8. Fred Hina, the Mets' trainer,
said Friday that Bonilla's knee had been gradually improving until
the first inning Thursday night, when he banged it while bending
down to field a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla remained in the game and belted his first homer of the
spring (even though the ball appeared to be well foul of the
left-field pole). But as a precaution, the Mets' team physician,
Dr. David Altchek, recommended that Bonilla undergo an MRI this
morning, and that is when the tear was found.
</P>
<P>
   When the Mets traded Mel Rojas for Bonilla on Nov. 11, they were
just going for a little stability in their outfield. Aside from
center fielder Brian McRae, the Mets' rotating set of outfielders
proved particularly unproductive last season. By acquiring Bonilla
and signing Rickey Henderson, Phillips was making an effort to
improve the situation _ offensively, if not defensively.
</P>
<P>
   But considering that Bonilla is 36, and carries a lot of weight
on his frame, and Henderson is 40, Phillips' solution also posed
some risk. And not just health-wise. Although Henderson's left knee
has been sore, it has not kept him from playing. But after going 0
for 3 Friday, Henderson is 0 for his last 24 since opening the
spring with a single and is hitting his age (.040).
</P>
<P>
   At least Henderson _ who never cared much for spring training _
has been able to get some at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   As Bonilla lamented Friday, ``I needed to get at-bats this
spring, because I didn't want what happened to me last year happen
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
