<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 23:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7635 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-EDUCATION-NYT &LR;      03-19 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-EDUCATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: REALISTIC SCHOOL STANDARDS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, March 20:
</P>
<P>
   The school standards movement is being undermined by a failure
of political will. In state after state, politicians pander to the
public with tough new standards and tests _ while failing to
provide qualified teachers or the rudimentary labs necessary to
prepare students adequately. When students fail the new tests,
parents explode in outrage and the standards are eased, feeding the
impression that public schooling is worthless and that some
children can never learn.
</P>
<P>
   New York state has embarked on a similar course. Anyone who
doubts this should look at the 27 percent failure rate on a new
English test prescribed by the state Board of Regents, one of five
such Regents tests that students will eventually have to pass to
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   In the near term, the state must take an active role in helping
high school students who face a test for which their districts have
failed to prepare them. In the long term, the state will need to
embrace the broad preparation plan that the State Board of Regents
recommended when it created the new standards. To do any less is
courting civic disaster.
</P>
<P>
   For most of its history, New York had a two-tiered testing
system that led to two classes of diplomas. About 38 percent of
high school students took the more challenging courses that led to
the Regents High School Examinations, and for those who passed, the
Regents diploma. But most students took less demanding courses and
the Regents Competency Tests, leading to a local diploma.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Regents has scrapped the less challenging courses
and tests and now wants virtually every student to take the math,
science and English courses that lead to the Regents examination.
The exam initially will have two passing grades, one for the
Regents diploma and a lower one for the local diploma _ which will
soon be phased out, making everyone reach for the Regents' mark.
</P>
<P>
   The new standards do not kick in until next year. But a dry run
in an English exam among current high school seniors whose results
were released this week found that 27 percent across the state and
37 percent in New York City failed to achieve even the lower grade
required for a local diploma. By contrast, under the old system,
virtually everyone who took the weaker competency test got a local
diploma. Given that next year's English test is longer and more
difficult and that science and other subjects will be tested in
subsequent years, the failure rates could soar much higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Regents hoped to avoid high failure rates by
spending almost $900 million to bring all students up to speed
while concentrating the bulk of that money on poor districts that
have the least-qualified teachers and the worst facilities. But
after welcoming the new standards and pledging to support them,
Gov. George Pataki submitted a budget proposing only about $270
million and redirected much of the money toward affluent districts.
</P>
<P>
   Students who do not get better preparation will fail the new
tests in ever greater numbers. Those who repeat the 12th grade will
make the current overcrowding problems worse. As more students drop
out and fail to get jobs, they will deaden an economy that already
lags behind the nation's.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, the state should commit to furnishing all of
its students with the instruction and tools they need to succeed.
But doing that will require money, planning and vigorous leadership
from the governor and the Legislature.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-19-99 2337EST &QL; 
