<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LAD     03-19 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-WILNER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN'S CALHOUN DEALS WITH PRESSURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pressure is not two free throws with the game on the line or a
3-point shot at the buzzer. Pressure is the weight of a state,
especially when the state is Connecticut and the coach is Jim
Calhoun.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have averaged 25.4 wins per season in the '90s. They
have won 30 games four times. They have won the Big East
regular-season title six times. They have won the Big East
tournament four times. They've made the Sweet 16 seven times and
the Elite Eight four times.
</P>
<P>
   But they've never reached the Final Four, and for that reason
Calhoun is under hydraulic pressure to defeat Gonzaga today and win
the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone has made so much of us getting to the Final Four,''
Calhoun said. ``But I know I'm not going to change. If we win
(today), I'm not going to be a better coach. If we lose, I'm not
going to be a worse coach.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nutmeg State might disagree, since his success and its
self-respect are forever intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   UConn basketball is unique. What other elite program has a
history that begins in 1986? That's when Calhoun arrived from
Northeastern, where he coached the late Reggie Lewis. Until then,
the Huskies had won a total of four NCAA Tournament games, and none
since 1976. The All-American section in Connecticut's media guide
shows three players; all are Calhoun's.
</P>
<P>
   The school is located in Storrs, a small town 20 miles east of
Hartford. It has no movie theater and no McDonald's but a
passionate alumni following. (Approximately 90,000 reside
in-state.) The football team is Division I-AA and the Hartford
Whalers bolted for North Carolina two years ago, leaving
Connecticut without pro sports. Boston teams are popular in the
north and New York teams in the south, but the Huskies are all that
binds the state. Fourteen newspapers cover UConn regularly,
compared to the six that follow UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't North Carolina or Kansas or Kentucky. There is no
athletic history and not much reason to spend four years in Storrs,
except someone forgot to tell the UConn faithful. Each time he
misses the Final Four, Calhoun is swallowed by the expectations he
alone created.
</P>
<P>
   ``If over the next 10 years we average 26 wins and not make the
Final Four, I'll be a very happy coach,'' he said, appearing
genuine. Later, this: ``We haven't been to the Final Four and I
guess that's how you judge (coaches). I've accepted that.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun's critics either miss the point or ignore the facts. For
all its regular-season wins and Big East titles, Connecticut has
produced little NBA talent. Of the nine players drafted during the
Calhoun era, only two (Cliff Robinson and Ray Allen) are impact
players. Scott Burrell, Tate George, Travis Knight, Donny Marshall,
Donyell Marshall and Chris Smith are role players or castoffs.
UConn's talent hasn't been commensurate with its success. Calhoun
must be doing something right.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies have three Elite Eight losses under Calhoun, all to
better teams: Duke in 1990, when Christian Laettner hit a jumper at
the buzzer; UCLA in 1995, and North Carolina last year, in
Greensboro.
</P>
<P>
   The '94 Huskies lost to Florida in the Sweet 16 when Donyell
Marshall missed the game-winning free throws with three seconds
left. They lost to eventual-champ Duke in 1991 and to No. 1 seed
Ohio State in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Really, the only bad loss _ the only loss you can pin on Calhoun
_ came in 1996, when the No. 1 Huskies crumbled in the Sweet 16
against No. 5 Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how to avoid another piercing defeat, Calhoun cracked:
``One, make sure Christian Laettner isn't in the game. Two, make
your foul shots at the end. Three, don't get into overtime. Four,
don't get into a shootout with UCLA. And don't go to Greensboro, if
you have the chance.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, Calhoun has avoided it all _ the higher seeds and
home-court advantages, the late-game fades and last-second shots.
He's one No. 10 seed away from pacifying a state and corralling his
White Whale.
</P>
<P>
   If not now, when?
</P>
<P>
   __ Ready and relaxed: Gonzaga showed no signs of nerves at its
press conference Friday afternoon, less than 24 hours before the
most important sporting event in school history.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Quentin Hall, a Bahamas native, on the adjustment to
living in eastern Washington: ``I had to buy more clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Forward Casey Calvary, on whether the Bulldogs have adopted
coach Dan Monson's personality: ``Our coach does a lot better with
the women than we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Monson, who is engaged: ``Casey's suspended.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall, on guard Richie Frahm kissing Calvary after his
game-winning shot against Florida: ``I would have hugged him. I
wouldn't kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: Maryland lost in the Sweet 16 with its most
talented roster in the post-Len Bias era. Wouldn't want to be coach
Gary Williams' dog.
</P>
<P>
   The Pac-10: Conference of (NIT) Champions?
</P>
<P>
   Duke was favored by 27 points over Southwest Missouri _ an
astonishing spread for the Sweet 16.
</P>
<P>
   Think Temple's nonconference schedule prepared it for the
tournament? The Owls played Mississippi, Michigan State,
Pennsylvania, Indiana, Wisconsin, Stann State, Florida State,
Fresno State and Rutgers.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' dream Final Four: Connecticut, St. John's, Duke and
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' nightmare Final Four: Oklahoma, Ohio State, Gonzaga and
Purdue.
</P>
<P>
   And finally: On Selection Sunday, Gonzaga was 5,000-to-1 to win
the NCAA title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
