<HEADER>
A7639 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-NCAA-380&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      03-19 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-NCAA-380&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONNECTICUT COACH ONLY CARES ABOUT WIN THAT WILL PUT HIM IN FINAL
FOUR 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JERRY BREWER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Geno Auriemma has had a lot of success during his
14 years as the women's basketball coach at Connecticut. He has a
.793 winning percentage and a 6-0 record in the round of 16. His
1995 national championship team finished at 35-0.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, his team has a chance to make it six straight seasons
with at least 30 victories when the top-seeded Huskies play
fourth-seeded Iowa State at noon in the NCAA Mideast Regional
semifinals at the Shoemaker Center.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference Friday, Auriemma scoffed at the mention
of the possibility of another 30-victory season. ``We've won 30
games five years in a row, but we've been to two Final Fours,''
Auriemma said. ``And I think if you asked me if I would trade in a
couple of 30-win seasons for a couple of Final Fours, I'd say yeah.
If we win and don't win Monday, I'm not going to be a happy man.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies (29-4) have lost in the regional championship three
times in the last five years _ in 1994, 1997 and 1998. Last season,
they were beaten by a surprising North Carolina State team. But the
Huskies are favored to stop that trend this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what I love,'' Auriemma said, balking at the notion
that Iowa State has an advantage as an underdog. ``I love when
teams come in and say, `We have nothing to lose.' I love when teams
say that; you're not going to play as hard as we are. We've got a
national championship to lose. That's what we're playing for.''
</P>
<P>
   In the second game here Saturday, second-seeded Clemson (26-5)
plays third-seeded Georgia (25-6).
</P>
<P>
   In the East Region, top-seeded Tennessee, vying to become the
first women's team to win four consecutive national titles, faces
fourth-seeded Virginia Tech this afternoon in Greensboro, N.C. That
game follows the contest which pits third-seeded Duke against
second-seeded Old Dominion.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue, seeded No. 1 in the Midwest Region and ranked No. 1 in
the nation, plays fourth-seeded North Carolina Saturday night in
Normal, Ill., followed by third-seeded Rutgers against
second-seeded Texas Tech.
</P>
<P>
   In the West Regional in Los Angeles, top-seeded Louisiana Tech
meets fourth-seeded Louisiana State Saturday night, followed by the
game between third-seeded UCLA and second-seeded Colorado State.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Iowa State (24-7), ranked No. 19 in The Associated Press poll,
is relishing the opportunity presented by its first round of 16
game. Watching UConn barely defeat Xavier by 86-84 in the second
round has the Cyclones believing they can win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of all the No. 1 seeds, they were the team we thought we
could play with,'' said Iowa State guard Megan Taylor, who averages
15.7 points.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State's style is similar to Xavier's. The Cyclones have a
deft touch from the perimeter, shooting 39 percent from 3-point
range. Xavier was the only team in the nation that shot better from
long range.
</P>
<P>
   Iowa State has a star point guard to deal with the Huskies' full
court pressure. Stacey Frese, a junior, averages 17.3 points and
led the nation in 3-point field goal percentage, hitting 48.3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a scrawny little thing that people don't think much
about when they first look at her,'' Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly
said. ``But she's a great player, a real leader on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   UConn players say they are more focused this week and are intent
on getting back to the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The past two years were disappointing,'' said Amy Duran, the
Huskies' captain. ``You look back, and those were games we could
have and should have won. Maybe we were a little too worried about
losing. I don't know. I don't think we're going to make that
mistake again.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
