<HEADER>
A7643 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-BAYHILL-370&AMP;ADD-N     03-19 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-BAYHILL-370&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER ATTACKING A SPRINKLER, LOVE TIES FOR LEAD AT BAY HILL
INVITATIONAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ It was a successful day for Davis Love III, but
an embarrassing one as well.
</P>
<P>
   Angry about seeing his ball buried in a bunker on the 17th hole,
Love banged a sprinkler head with his club. The sprinkler head
broke, releasing a steady stream of water that poured into the
bunker, making a large portion of it unplayable.
</P>
<P>
   Love said he expected to be fined by the PGA Tour. But after
this weekend, he may have a $450,000 winner's check that will
easily cover his debt.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a six-under-par 66 and putting himself in position to
win a tournament that has eluded him in the past, Love was tied
with Tim Herron at 135, nine-under-par Friday after the second
round of the Bay Hill Invitational. Andrew Magee was one stroke
back in third place, while Tom Lehman was alone in fourth place at
137, two shots behind and well within striking distance.
</P>
<P>
   While Love was happy with his position, he was troubled by his
outburst, particularly because he has great respect for Arnold
Palmer, the tournament's host. It was too late for Love to mend
what he had done. But he did apologize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure those maintenance guys aren't real happy with me,''
said Love, whose round included five birdies, an eagle and only one
bogey. ``Hopefully, Arnold will send me a bill for it when he gets
it at the end of the month. I have done a lot of things that I'm
not proud of: kicked water coolers and hurt your foot, bashed your
toe with your club. Suffice to say, I am embarrassed. But it's good
for you to get embarrassed every once in a while. Takes you down a
notch.''
</P>
<P>
   While Love's composure left something to be desired, his play
was superb as he used his power and steady putting to tie Herron,
the first-round leader who shot a 69 Friday after an opening-round
66.
</P>
<P>
   The highlights of Love's round included an eagle at the par-5,
530-yard fourth hole, when Love reached the green in two shots, a
drive followed by a mammoth 3-wood shot that landed just four feet
from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Even the sprinkler head incident did not break Love's
concentration. After hitting his buried bunker shot onto the green,
Love made a 45-foot putt to save par, then ended his day with a
12-foot putt for birdie at No. 18.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Love finished second at Bay Hill in 1989 and 1993, and last year
he was tied for first place after two rounds only to finish 75-76,
which dropped him into a tie for 17th place. This year, Love hopes
for a happier ending.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to win this tournament, just because it's Arnold's
tournament,'' said Love, who has 13 victories on tour, including
the 1997 PGA Championship. ``It's a good golf course and a good
field. I have been very close here a couple of times and I'm off to
a good start again. If this weather continues, scores are going to
be pretty good. You have to try to keep up.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Tiger Woods barely made the cut of two over par as
one of the top 70 professionals. Woods was actually tied for 71st
place, but Matt Kuchar, an amateur who finished at two under par
(142), did not count against the cut.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's even-par 72, Woods silently cleaned out his
locker at Bay Hill Club &AMP; Lodge, figuring he was off for the
weekend. But a few moments later, Woods was informed that he had
made the cut. Now, if he could only fix his swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``To shoot 72 was kind of a mini-miracle, because I hit it so
bad,'' said Woods, who has missed only one cut during his career,
at the 1997 Bell Canadian Open. ``I wish I could see a pattern. The
only pattern I could see was that I was consistently
inconsistent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Love already has four top 10 finishes this year, but
no victories. He hoped to change that this weekend. And he would
also try to hold his temper.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hit a lot of sprinkler heads and nobody sees it,'' Love
said. ``I have a feeling that somebody saw that one.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
