<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-DUKE-SWMISSOURI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWEST MISSOURI STATE PUTS UP A FIGHT, BUT DUKE PREVAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ No. 1-ranked Duke came into the East
Regional like a bullet train in a stagecoach race, beating its last
11 opponents by an average of 31 points.
</P>
<P>
   Big-name opponents, like North Carolina and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   But little-known Southwest Missouri State proved Friday night
that the Blue Devil Express could be slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Overmatched, but never outhustled, the No. 12-seeded Bears went
floor burn for floor burn, 3-pointer for 3-pointer, with the
tournament heavyweight for nearly 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But Southwest Missouri State ran out of horsepower in the second
half and lost, 78-61, in a scrappy performance that gave the mighty
Blue Devils their first test in the tournament that they are
expected to win.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Southwest Missouri State coach Steve Alford
finally removed his starters with 59.5 seconds left and down by 20
points, the crowd at the Continental Arena _ Duke fans included _
gave them a standing ovation. It was only the fourth time this
season that the Blue Devils were held to 80 points or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   This was the Blue Devils' house. They are 14-1 in regional
semifinal games at the Meadowlands. Four times they left as East
Regional champions with a ticket punched to the Final Four _ in
1986, 1988, 1989 and 1990.
</P>
<P>
   This was Duke's 16th round-of-16 appearance and was Southwest
Missouri State's first. Alford's post-season record consisted of a
Division III title game loss while coaching tiny Manchester
College.
</P>
<P>
   Alford, an all-American at Indiana as a player, and his Bears
ignored the Blue Devils' daunting record. Southwest Missouri State
came out to play as if it were just another Missouri Valley
Conference game.
</P>
<P>
   It began as if it were taking on Drake, not Duke. The Bears ran
with the more athletic Blue Devils, and they banged inside with
Duke's nine high school all-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard, poised and unafraid display led by Keven Ault,
one of four Hoosiers in Southwest Missouri's starting lineup. He
opened the game by going right at, and over, Elton Brand. The
6-foot-3-inch junior guard showed why he was named Indiana's Mr.
Basketball in 1996 in a fearless first half when he lifted his
teammates every time the Blue Devils threatened to make it a
blowout.
</P>
<P>
   When Duke charged to 15-4 lead, Ault stripped William Avery and
got the ball to Allen Phillips for a 3-pointer. Then he nailed one
himself. Another Ault steal _ one of his three in the first half _
and the Bears were back to within three. Another Indiana product,
6-11 Danny Moore, never backed down from Brand, a consensus
all-American. Moore had six first-half points, including a dazzling
reverse layup around his higher-profile opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Moore even slapped Brand's point-blank dunk attempt, holding him
to nine first-half points. The Bears seemed to have an answer for
everybody, except for Trajan Langdon. The Blue Devils' fifth-year
senior is still nursing a sprained fifth metatarsal in his left
foot, but he uncorked 15 first-half points, mostly from way out as
he was 3 of 4 from behind the 3-point line.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Duke shot 55 percent in the first half while the
Bears made only 40 percent, Southwest Missouri State managed to go
into halftime down by only 39-30. The Bears' stingy first-half
defense forced seven Duke turnovers for eight fast-break points. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
