<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-19 23:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7647 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-MICHST-OKLAHOMA-N     03-19 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-MICHST-OKLAHOMA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUTALLY, SPARTANS SLOG PAST OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Michigan State survived Friday night, barely and
brutally.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartans slogged past Oklahoma, 54-46, in a game that
featured rugged defense and less offense than an elementary school
clash. Two players wound up dazed and on the floor after a nasty
collision, and every other player looked weary and bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   Do not search for the videotape of this contest in the NCAA film
archives. Not unless you love watching teams struggle to get open
shots, struggle even when they got the shots and simply struggle
all night. Sure, the defense was feisty, but pick a player on
either team and he probably had a subpar performance on what was
the biggest evening of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the obvious difference for the top-seeded Spartans is
that they survived in the semifinals of the Midwest Regional at the
Trans World Dome to scamper into the round of eight, where they
will play Kentucky or Miami. Meanwhile, the Sooners, who were
trying to become the first 13th-seeded squad to be among the final
eight teams left in the tournament, stumbled mightily.
</P>
<P>
   Michigan State (32-4) walked to a 36-29 lead with 10 minutes
left in the second half by allowing Oklahoma (22-11) just four
points for 10 minutes. Or did the Sooners stop themselves? In one
five-possession spurt, the Sooners, who were 17 of 51 (33 percent)
from the field, hit the rim once. Even though Mateen Cleaves,
Michigan State's star, was only 3 for 14 shooting and had nine
points, the Spartans received 12 from Andre Hutson and 11 from
Morris Peterson to survive.
</P>
<P>
   With 9 minutes 34 seconds left in the second half, there was a
frightening collision after Oklahoma inbounded the ball. As Cleaves
pursued a dribbling Michael Johnson, he ran into Eduardo Najera,
who was setting a pick. Cleaves' head banged into Najera's chin and
both players collapsed on the hardwood.
</P>
<P>
   There was silence throughout the dome when neither player
budged. Cleaves finally moved and was helped to his feet after
being on the floor for almost five minutes. It took Najera a lot
longer. There was blood on the floor near Najera and he needed
medical attention on his chin. He rose 11 minutes after the
collision, with a bandage on his chin, his face pale, and he needed
to be helped to the sidelines. Both players returned later, but
Najera, whose nine points were well below his 15.7 average, was
wobbly.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma managed to stifle Cleaves early. He was restless and
frustrated when the first half was almost over and he had not
scored. So when he took possession of the ball with less than 10
seconds remaining in the half, he dribbled ahead like a sprinter,
glided around the Sooners, slid inside and made a nifty left-handed
layup with one second remaining. It gave Michigan State a
precarious 26-25 lead, and it gave Cleaves a little relief.
</P>
<P>
   Magic Johnson, who guided the Spartans to the national
championship as a player in 1979, was perched behind their bench
and broke into a big smile.
</P>
<P>
   The way to possibly throttle Michigan State is to negate
Cleaves. The muscular point guard loves to push the ball up the
court, loves to explode to the hoop, loves to toss up jumpers and
loves to play defense. If Cleaves is unable to do those things, the
Spartans become an ordinary team.
</P>
<P>
   So coach Kelvin Sampson of Oklahoma tried to confuse Cleaves by
using different defenses throughout the half, and the strategy
worked. The Sooners trudged to a 23-19 lead, the largest of the
half, and Cleaves, unnerved and uncomfortable, missed all eight of
his shots from the field before the coast-to-coast layup.
</P>
<P>
   The Sooners used a 2-3 zone and dared Michigan State to shoot
from the outside. They used a 2-1-2 zone and packed it in tight
around the basket. Most unusual of all, the Sooners used a matchup
zone with the 6-foot-8-inch Najera hounding Cleaves, who is 6-2,
above the free-throw line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
