<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DREAMS NO MONEY CAN BUY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Mo.)  (mk) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The coach's son discovered at a tender
age that the country was a vast playground of wondrous talent
beyond the scope of even an Indiana boy who could really play. In
New Castle, Ind., Brandon Miller had learned from his father that
basketball was like religion, something in the blood. But from his
boyhood idol came the message that fame and fortune are not
necessarily part of the same basketball equation.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Alford had filled what supposedly is the largest high
school arena in the country, seating 9,300, in a place so
basketball crazed that they built the State Basketball Hall of Fame
right next door. Alford eventually left New Castle's Chrysler High
for Indiana University, where he became a central character in a
best-selling book about a volatile coach. Alford also won the 1987
national championship, Indiana defeating Syracuse as 7-year-old
Brandon Miller watched with his father, Roger, at his grandparents'
home, on a Monday night he will never forget.
</P>
<P>
   The hometown hero was drafted by the Indiana Pacers but he never
did become a big-time money player. Like his father, Sam, and Roger
Miller, too, Steve Alford became a coach, which meant there was one
player he never had to recruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I committed to Southwest Missouri my sophomore year of high
school,'' Brandon Miller said Friday night before Southwest
Missouri State was a stubborn sacrifice, losing its East Regional
game, 78-61.
</P>
<P>
   The Alfords and the Millers found out what it was once like to
be a mosquito trying to knock off New Castle in the Indiana state
sectional. Sam Alford, who coached his son in high school, was in
the assistant's seat next to Steve, now the head coach, on the
Southwest Missouri bench. Roger Miller, the assistant to Sam for
the one season he coached Brandon at New Castle, was in the stands,
waiting for his son to jump off the bench and man the point.
</P>
<P>
   This photo opportunity of a lifetime came late in the first
half, the Bears still not quite pitch-forked by the Blue Devils.
Miller threw away an entry pass but baited William Avery into a
charge. Then he was matched against an all-American, Trajan
Langdon, and didn't hustle back fast enough from a double team.
Langdon nailed a 3-pointer. Miller came out a game that would be
with him forever, like Indiana-Syracuse in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, there would be additions to the Miller family
album. When Roger played high school ball in Vincennes, Ind, he
made the state Final Four. ``He's got me there,'' said Brandon
Miller, a 6-foot freshman with short, cropped hair and a boxer's
flattened nose.
</P>
<P>
   The farthest he went at Chrysler was the final eight, his
freshman year, which was Sam Alford's 20th, and last. In Indiana,
these tournaments advancements are badges of honor, a lifetime
defined by one shot, one night, one game when a town from nowhere
is suddenly a star on the state basketball map.
</P>
<P>
   ``The year we went to the Final Four with Steve, we had 26 buses
from New Castle following ours into Indianapolis,'' Sam Alford
said.
</P>
<P>
   There was always a level to climb, an opponent to behold. That
was the beauty of the Indiana tournament until some bureaucrats got
together and changed the one-classification format against the
lifers' wishes.
</P>
<P>
   New Castle Chrysler was never the biggest school, with 800 or so
students, but it had tradition and commitment. It had Sam Alford.
``I tell the coaches in Missouri, `Our coaches and players are no
better than yours,''' he said. ``But Indiana basketball is just
something you have to witness.''
</P>
<P>
   A coach there starts low, aims high. Sam Alford's first job was
at Monroe City, a 100-student school with seven senior boys. From
there it was on to South Knox and Martinsville, and then it was
time to put down roots, make his stand. His last victory in New
Castle was his 300th, but there were also 188 defeats, one of them
in the tournament to little Knightstown. He didn't campaign to have
the system junked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no ... no,'' he said. ``The coaches didn't want that
system changed. All of us had been at the lower end.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach who wins with the little guys invariably moves up. In
big-time college basketball, these associations often end clumsily.
Steve Alford is already on the short list at Iowa, meaning the
Bears may not get out of the first round again. Miller won't be
going with Alford, but he at least got this far, all the way from
New Castle, to the Round of 16, against the best team of all.
</P>
<P>
   It was all an Indiana kid could want, the opportunity to dream,
which money can't buy.
</P>
</TEXT>
