<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN:   LETTING BYGONES BE BYGONES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   WILLIAM C. RHODEN  
 &HT;     
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KNOXVILLE, Tenn. _ Last week Lou Carnesecca, Brian Mahoney and
Ron Rutledge sat together in Orlando, Fla., and watched St. John's
whip Samford and tear apart Indiana. On Thursday, they watched St.
John's play a near-perfect first half on the way to a romp over
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   As the clock wound down, with St. John's one victory away from
the Final Four, the three stood, applauded and shook hands. Connie
Jarvis, the wife of the St. John's coach, Mike Jarvis, the players
and parents hugged and celebrated one more unlikely step in an
unlikely season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's every coach's dream to have a team play that way,''
Carnesecca said in his raspy voice. ``To play with great
discipline, great passing and great intelligence. They remind me of
the 1964 UCLA team. They play that way, with great passing. They
perform surgery on you and you don't even know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the three held a significance you might miss if
you didn't know the history.
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen years ago, in March 1985, Carnesecca, Rutledge and
Mahoney were on the bench coaching together in Denver as St. John's
reached the Final Four with victories over Kentucky and North
Carolina State. St. John's, with Chris Mullin, Bill Wennington,
Mark Jackson and Walter Berry, met Big East rival Georgetown in one
national semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a little different, we were supposed to go,''
Carnesecca said. Mahoney added: ``That's what makes this so
special. There were no expectations for this group. Now you look at
the way they're coming together, the way they are playing together,
everything is really coming together nicely.''
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Carnesecca, Mahoney and Rutledge indicates a
more subtle adhesion: the coming back together of a program, a
self-styled mom-and-pop operation that had, by its standards, been
stood on its ear.
</P>
<P>
   After Carnesecca's retirement in 1993, Mahoney, who had served
as his assistant for nearly 20 years, was given the job out of
loyalty and a desire for continuity. Four seasons later, Mahoney
was dismissed by Ed Manetta, who had replaced Jack Kaiser, the
longtime athletic director.
</P>
<P>
   After a clumsy search process, the university hired its third
choice, Fran Fraschilla from Manhattan. That selection set in
motion two seasons of turmoil, but it also produced two marvelous
players: Ron Artest, the sophomore forward, and Erick Barkley, this
season's outstanding freshman point guard.
</P>
<P>
   After a well-documented feud that centered around personal
conduct and Fraschilla's interest in another job, Fraschilla was
fired. Jarvis was hired from George Washington, and the program has
regained its balance. The presence of Carnesecca, Mahoney and
Rutledge underlines how steady the ship is.
</P>
<P>
   Mahoney, who was wounded by his dismissal nearly five years ago,
returned to St. John's last fall to work in the university's
development office with Carnesecca and Rutledge. ``We wanted to
show our support,'' Mahoney said. ``We thought it was a nice
gesture. I think Mike appreciates it. I think the kids notice it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they do. On Friday, Tyrone Grant, the senior center who
was recruited by Mahoney and played one season for him, two for
Fraschilla and one for Jarvis, said it was nice to see a bond
forming.
</P>
<P>
   ``When coach Jarvis came it brought that togetherness back to
the program,'' he said. ``I haven't seen all my coaches together at
a game in a long time. Since the first game, they have been there,
they have supported us. Those are coaches who recruited me. So, I'm
just happy that we're together and we're a big family again,
because for two years we weren't really a family. Everybody was
spread apart.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminders of that 1985 St. John's glory year abound: Mullin and
Jackson are teammates on the Indiana Pacers; Berry has enjoyed a
long, profitable career in Greece. The former coach and his two
assistants are a bridge from St. John's past to a promising future.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, Carnesecca, Mahoney and Rutledge will take their
assigned seats near the St. John's bench and watch the Red Storm
battle Ohio State for the right to go to the Final Four. Mahoney
said that he was happy to be back in the fold. It's almost as if he
never left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've put a lot of years in the school,'' Mahoney said. ``I
spoke to Father Harrington'' _ Donald J. Harrington, the university
president _ ``and one of the things he said was: `You don't realize
it, but people still have strong feelings about you. You don't know
how many people still admire you.' He told me, `Remember you're
part of this.' That made me feel good.''
</P>
<P>
   All the Red Storm needs Saturday night is a victory for a happy
ending.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
