<HEADER>
A7660 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-PURDUE-TEMPLE20-C     03-19 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PURDUE-TEMPLE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Temple rolls to date with Devils
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ In what has been an unconventional
career, Temple coach John Chaney invoked some unconventional wisdom
after Friday night's NCAA East Regional semifinals. For his Owls,
Chaney hopes the fourth time is the charm.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney's sixth-seeded team from Philadelphia used relentless
defense and timely technical fouls by Purdue to turn what was
supposed to a tough game into a laugher, routing the Boilermakers
77-55 at the Continental Airlines Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Temple (24-10), in the Sweet 16 for the first time since 1993,
advances to Sunday's championship game to play No. 1 Duke where a
win would put Chaney into his first Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   The odds of beating Duke are very much against Temple, but
history says the Owls are due to win a regional championship. In
1988 they reached the East championship game and lost to No. 2
Duke. In 1991 they lost in the East finals to North Carolina. In
1993 they fell in the West championship game to Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Now all the Owls have to do is beat a 35-1 team on a 30-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   As the final minutes wound down, the Temple fans began yelling:
``We want Duke! We want Duke!''
</P>
<P>
   Temple will get Duke on Sunday at 2:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   It was the most points Temple had scored since an 85-78 win over
St. Joseph's on Feb. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue (21-13), the No. 10 seed in this regional, didn't have to
look far to find where it let the game slip away.
</P>
<P>
   The Boilermakers were up 11-7 at the 14-minute mark of the first
half when they were hit with two technical fouls in the span of 19
seconds. The first came against Jaraan Cornell, who was nailed
after throwing an elbow. Then coach Gene Keady was given a
technical by official John Clougherty for protesting a little too
strongly.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the smoke had cleared, Temple had made five of six
free throws and had put together a 13-0 run to lead 20-11.
</P>
<P>
   Consecutive three-pointers by Mark Karcher gave the Owls a 30-18
lead with 8:18 left in the first half. The Temple lead would grow
to as many as 19 before the Owls settled for a 47-32 advantage at
the intermission.
</P>
<P>
   It was Temple's highest point total at halftime all season. The
Owls are averaging only 66.4 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue never made even a token gesture of getting back in the
game in the second half as Temple opened the period with a 14-4 run
that expanded the lead to 25, 61-36, at the 13:24 mark.
</P>
<P>
   Then it simply became a matter of how bad the beating would be.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue had lost five of its six games coming into the NCAA
Tournament, but upset seventh-seeded Texas and second-seeded Miami
to reach the round of 16 for the fourth time this decade.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
